<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-U.S. (Washington) _ The chemical that the United States
cited to justify its bombing of a Sudanese factory last week could
be used for commercial products, the agency overseeing the treaty
barring chemical weapons said on Wednesday. By Steven Lee Myers and
Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-CAMPS (Manshera, Pakistan) _ At the camps hit by the U.S.
missile attack on Afghanistan last week, tens of thousands of men
have received military training in the last few years and then gone
off to fight in wars around the world, from nearby Kashmir to
faraway Bosnia and Chechnya. By Raymond Bonner and Steve LeVine.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ The inside story of backroom
intrigues that led to the most recent upheaval in Russia's
government: Boris Berezovsky and other tycoons exploited the
financial crisis to install a more pliant government. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   BRUNEI (Bandar Seri Begawan, Brunei) _ Oil-rich Brunei is
experiencing something utterly new in its well-lubricated history:
a cash-flow crunch. And on top of that, a bitter feud has broken
out in the royal family since the Sultan stripped his younger
brother of his posts as head of Brunei's state investment agency
and one of its largest conglomerates. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-ROY (New Delhi) _ With their pride still measured in
megatons, and a strut still in their step after showing they can
explode nuclear bombs with the best of them, most of India's elite
did not want one of their own telling them, ``The air is thick with
ugliness and there's an unmistakable stench of fascism in the
air.'' This assessment came from Arundhati Roy, who ascended into
international literary stardom last year with her first novel,
``The God of Small Things'' (Random House), In a haunting
8,000-word essay by Ms. Roy, ``The End of Imagination.'' Deeply
personal, poetically penned, unsparingly harsh, it lambastes the
nation's main political parties and calls the bomb a ``final act of
betrayal by a ruling class that has failed its people.'' By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
