<P>
   RUSSIA-SOROS _ George Soros' group, the Quantum Fund, has lost
$2 billion in Russia in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-ECON (Mexico City) _ Russia's effective devaluation of the
ruble last week has sent panic throughout the world's emerging
markets, with the Latin American economies likely to be among those
that suffer the most. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DERIVATIVES (Undated) _ Trading in the rapidly devaluing ruble
came to a screeching halt Wednesday, renewing concerns about
Russia's ability to manage $40 billion in ruble-denominated debt,
roughly 10 percent of which is held by foreign investors. But
Western investors and banks could face greater losses from the
complex financial instruments known as derivatives. Indeed, the
amount of Russian derivatives at risk for foreign investors may be
sharply higher than that of bonds and loans. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   EMERGING-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The collapse of the last year
in emerging stock markets _ the Thailands, Polands and Russias of
the world _ has been breathtaking. Not since they began to attract
strong investor interest at the end of the 1980s have these markets
had such a sharp decline that wiped out so many years of gains. By
Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
