   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST-PILOTS (Undated) _ If the pilots at Northwest Airlines
make good on their threat to strike this weekend, it will be the
first time a major airline has been shut down in the age of
so-called fortress hubs _ the big metropolitan airports that are
dominated by a single carrier. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Television advertisers today, more
than ever, are seeking to make their commercials music to the ear _
building brand identity with replays of classic rock tunes and with
original scores that they have commissioned. By Andrea Adelson.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ A panel of three federal judges
delivered a blow to Democrats this week when it ruled that sampling
techniques planned for the 2000 census violated federal law. The
issue is far from dead, though, as the administration now plans to
appeal to the Supreme Court. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
