   &UR; HOME (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRADEMARK-SKYLINE (New York) _ For years, Bobby Short has been
singing at the Cafe Carlyle that he feels New York is really ``my
personal property, right down Broadway to City Hall.'' Careful,
Bobby. That slice of New York skyline you think is yours may in
fact be trademarked. The Art Deco spire of the Chrysler Building is
a registered trademark (No. 1126888). So is the neo-classical
facade of the New York Stock Exchange (No. 1761655). Even the
Manhattan White Pages needed permission to depict ``Patience,'' one
of the marble lions guarding the New York Public Library on Fifth
Avenue (Trademark No. 1838167). By David Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT14,15) have been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   DEWEY-NICKS-FUN (Los Angeles) _ Dewey Nicks' ebullient fashion
photography reminds you that people have forgotten how to have fun
in fashion. Dewey and Stephanie Nicks' ebullient lifestyle reminds
you that people have forgotten how to have fun in life. By Amy
Spindler.
</P>
<P>
   SCIARC-STUDENTS (Los Angels) _ Back to school, the time of
notebooks and protractors and sales circulars, has become one of
the basic seasons of American marketing. Even adults decades out of
the classroom can succumb to the pitch; it evokes certain primal
school-day sights and smells and textures. At the Southern
California Institute of Architecture (SciArc), the once-renegade
school whose influence has shaped the look of design in Los
Angeles, back-to-school means something different. There,
first-year students don't buy stuff; they build their own desks. By
Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-RENOVATION (Undated) _ We didn't start with the idea of
renovating our house in Pleasantville, N.Y., a 3,000-square-foot
Cotswold cottage on steroids. The house, built in 1907, has what
the folks in real estate like to call character, which means that
it takes a lot of character to live there, because nothing works
properly. No, we started with the idea of moving. By Ben Cheever.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-ARCHITECTURE (Undated) _ Last week Phyllis Lambert, the
formidable doyenne of architecture, whose youthful rebellion
against her father, liquor tycoon Samuel Bronfman, resulted in the
construction of the Seagram Building in 1958, announced that she
had chosen her successor as director of the Canadian Center for
Architecture in Montreal. Kurt W. Forster, founding director of the
Getty Center for the History of Art and the Humanities at the Getty
Center in Los Angeles and, currently, chairman of the Department of
Art and Architecture at the Federal Institute of Technology in
Zurich will assume the directorship of the center on March 1, 1999.
The Swiss-born scholar, 63, is expected to bring a considerable
measure of international cache and academic integrity to the center
that Ms. Lambert founded, using her own inheritance money, in 1979.
By Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-ARTS-CARPET (Newark, N.J.) _ Usually it's a bronze statue, an
old schoolhouse or a stately home that becomes the symbol of a
town. But the new contender in Newark is a colorful 12- by 92-foot
carpet, an addition to the New Jersey Performing Arts Center,
installed last Thursday in the entrance foyer. ``It's
Afrocentric,'' observed Lynne Falanga, of Watchung, N.J., who
attended a concert at the center on Sunday. ``They're incorporating
the neighborhood into the arts center, and that's the best part
about it.'' By Joseph Giovannini.
</P>
