<SLUG> BC-SCANDAL-DEMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC CANDIDATES STAY CLEAR OF PRESIDENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Democratic candidates are distancing themselves
from President Clinton, fearing that independent counsel Kenneth
Starr's report on the investigation of the president may somehow
cost them votes in this year's midterm elections.
</P>
<P>
   During a three-day campaign swing aimed at highlighting some of
the Democrats' best chances for taking back control of the House,
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., has been forced to walk the
line between supporting the president's policies and appearing to
defend Clinton personally as he battles to overcome the Monica
Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the president. I've worked well with him, and I trust
him. But I'm as disappointed as anybody at what happened,''
Gephardt told reporters who questioned him about the matter at
every stop in Kentucky, Iowa, Wisconsin and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's admission of an ``inappropriate relationship'' with
Lewinsky and accusations of perjury and cover-up have made him an
unwelcome figure on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   None of the hopefuls Gephardt campaigned for appeared willing to
have Clinton in their districts, and a few said that a visit from
the president, given his ``personal problem,'' would distract from
their efforts to focus on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd end up talking more about his problems than the issues,''
said Democrat Rob Tully of Dubuque, Iowa, who's trying to unseat
Republican incumbent Jim Nussle. But Tully was quick to add that he
does support the president on many issues.
</P>
<P>
   A few candidates, however, said they would like to have first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton make an appearance on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Lydia Spotswood of Kenosha, Wis., who said she would
welcome the first lady's help in her fight to defeat incumbent
Republican Mark Neumann in the 1st Congressional District, believes
most voters are tired of hearing about the affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time to stop the Jerry Springer show in
Washington,'' she said. She acknowledged that the scandal is ``a
serious matter'' but said it was time ``to move on to issues that
affect people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt has called Clinton's relationship with Lewinsky
``reprehensible'' and raised the prospect that Starr's report could
prompt impeachment hearings. But he has also said it was best to
take a ``wait and see'' approach and suggested that Starr in the
end may not even deliver a report outlining any impeachable
offenses.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of interviews as he flew across the Midwest,
Gephardt also cautioned reporters not to ``ever count Bill Clinton
out'' and suggested that if Republicans tried to push for
impeachment without clear grounds, ``this thing could backfire on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he added, ``the president deserves the
presumption that there's nothing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Clinton's Aug. 17 admission of his relationship with the
former White House intern, his aides have been trying to shore up
support among Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt acknowledged Wednesday that he had been called by White
House chief of staff Erskine Bowles after his ``reprehensible''
remark appeared in the morning papers. But he insisted that Bowles
did not pressure him to be more supportive.
</P>
<P>
   He said their conversation focused on the fall's legislative
agenda, except when Bowles said, ``the president was really sorry
about all this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I know he is,'' Gephardt added.
</P>
<P>
   As he campaigned on behalf of Democratic candidates, speaking
about health care reform, Social Security and education, the
minority leader insisted that the Democrats' hopes this fall of
picking up the 11 seats they need to retake the House would not
rise or fall on the presidential scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are worried more than anything about the effect
scandal could have on voter turnout. A low turnout could prove
disastrous for Democrats since the Republicans have always been
good at turning out their core supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said he hopes that Clinton's apology to the country,
which he called ``a courageous'' and ``forthright'' statement, will
help ease voter concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he can still be an effective leader. People give him a
high rating because he's done a good job, and I think he'll
continue to do that,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
