<SLUG> BC-STARWOOD-REIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARWOOD EXPECTED TO SHIFT TO BASIC CORPORATE STATUS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ADAM BRYANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide, the world's largest
lodging company, is expected to announce Thursday that it will
convert to a standard corporate structure from an unusual real
estate investment trust and make the trust a subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in White Plains, N.Y., is also expected to
announce that it will buy back about $1 billion worth of its stock.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of its change in status will answer a question
mark that has been hanging over Starwood for months. Starwood
recently lost a battle with Congress and the White House to extend
the tax advantages of its unusual corporate structure as a ``paired
share'' real estate investment trust, or REIT.
</P>
<P>
   The pending change has raised questions among many investors
about how it will affect Starwood's performance despite assurances
from Starwood executives that its assets, rather than its corporate
structure, are the company's real strength.
</P>
<P>
   Such doubts have dragged down Starwood shares, although many
lodging stocks have also slumped as investors have feared that
hotel companies might be overbuilding. Investors in Starwood, which
has acquired Westin Hotels and ITT in the last year, are also
watching each quarterly report carefully to see whether Starwood
executives can wring both savings and additional revenue from all
its acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mueller, an analyst at Nationsbanc Montgomery
Securities, said the change to a more typical corporate structure
would most likely generate interest in Starwood among a broader
range of shareholders, particularly with the expected stock
buyback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conceptually, it sounds like a structure that makes a lot of
sense for the company and is good for the shareholder,'' Mueller
said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Starwood rose 50 cents Wednesday, to $42.50. The
company's stock is down 31 percent since its most recent high of
$61.50 last October.
</P>
<P>
   Most real estate investment trusts pass on much of their income
to investors through dividends and therefore pay little or no
federal tax. But in the early 1980s, many trusts managed to
affiliate themselves with active real estate managers, giving them
greater flexibility and creating situations in which the REIT can
effectively lease property back to itself. In such cases, the
management company, which is considered a separate entity and is
subject to federal taxes, is paired with the REIT. Together, the
two trade as one stock. In 1984, Congress disallowed the creation
of any additional paired-share REIT's, but allowed some, including
Starwood and its predecessor, to continue to operate in this
fashion until this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
