A4407 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-ASSESS-NY     08-27 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: EVEN YANKEES HAVE POSTSEASON CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four consecutive losses probably won't prevent the
Yankees from challenging the American League and Major League
single-season records for victories, because the depth of their
lineup and starting rotation and their collective drive will allow
them to build new winning streaks.
</P>
<P>
   But they have problems, some apparent, some small but festering,
that could easily derail them in the postseason, when the caliber
of competition improves dramatically, when small weaknesses become
the difference between winning and losing.
</P>
<P>
   _ The veteran reliever Mike Stanton claimed responsibility for
two of the Yankees' first three losses in their slump, accepting
the blame and the hurricane of boos aimed in his direction. But
Stanton, who pitched two solid innings in Wednesday afternoon's 6-4
loss in the first game of a double-header with the Angels (the
Yankees won the second game, 7-6), is only part of a larger
problem. The Yankees' middle relief is in almost total disarray,
and must be fixed before the playoffs begin.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees possess excellent starting pitching and a superb
closer in Mariano Rivera. But in the postseason, at-bats are longer
and starting pitchers generally throw more pitches and last fewer
innings; a bridge of relief between the starter and the closer is
needed. The Yankees won the pivotal fourth game of the World Series
in 1996 because the Atlanta Braves lacked middle relief, because
the bullpen wasn't deep enough to get three or four crucial outs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had the personnel for a good middle relief corps in
April. Since then, the right-hander Jeff Nelson, an important
element of the bullpen, suffered a disk injury in his lower back;
he is rehabilitating and some within the organization believe
there's a 50-50 chance he'll come back _ to what degree of
effectiveness after three months of inactivity, nobody knows.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton had been terrible until Wednesday, with an 8.55 earned
run average since the beginning of June, and he appears caught in a
spiral of anxiousness. The worse he throws, the harder he tries,
and the harder he tries, the worse he throws. Torre believes
Stanton will rebound, and Wednesday might be a step in that
direction. Stanton is healthy, he has good stuff, opponents were
batting just .239 against him before Wednesday's games and he
understands he has a problem, the first step to repair.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying a suitable right-handed middle reliever is a far
more complex question. If Nelson is lost for the season or doesn't
regain his effectiveness, Torre has several alternatives. Ramiro
Mendoza has pitched effectively, but he doesn't generate strikeouts
and recently, he came down with a case of tendinitis after pitching
in three consecutive games. Mike Buddie, hit hard Monday and
Tuesday, is too inexperienced for the role, and like his fellow
sinker-baller Mendoza, he gets ground balls, not strikeouts and
pop-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Torre's best option to replace Nelson appears to be shifting
Orlando Hernandez from the rotation to the bullpen. Like Nelson,
Hernandez dominates right-handed batters with his sidearm slider
(they are hitting .149 against him); he struck out Juan Gonzalez in
three consecutive at-bats recently.
</P>
<P>
   But Hernandez has never pitched in relief, nobody knows if he
could pitch effectively on consecutive days, and he usually
requires an inning or two to find his bearings. Opponents are
hitting .282 against him in the first 30 pitches of his starts this
season, .215 afterward. As a middle reliever, he would not have
that luxury. Torre cannot simply wait until the playoffs begin to
switch Hernandez. He needs to experiment, to test Hernandez in
relief. There's no time like the present.
</P>
<P>
   _ It's a baseball cliche: A singles hitter bangs a couple of
home runs and then stops hitting singles as he tries to hit home
runs. But the cliche applies to Chuck Knoblauch, the Yankees
lead-off hitter. Knoblauch has a staggering 13 home runs since the
All-Star break, and in the process his swing has, in the jargon of
the day, become very big. He has stopped doing many of the things
that have made him a great leadoff hitter in his career.
</P>
<P>
   In five seasons leading up to this year, Knoblauch averaged 1.41
ground balls for every fly ball, a ratio that reflects the approach
of a hitter spraying line drives all over the field. In the last
two months, he has averaged 0.68 ground balls for every fly ball.
He had a .385 on-base percentage before the All-Star break, .309
since, going into Wednesday's games. He came to the Yankees with a
reputation as an excellent bunter, but almost never bunts. Over the
last few days, Knoblauch appears almost to be leaping at the ball
with a vicious uppercut.
</P>
<P>
   Torre has said time and again he wants Knoblauch to think about
line drives, not home runs. When the Yankees traded for Knoblauch,
they wanted him for his ability to get on base and drive the
offense. With his current approach, he would be a liability in the
postseason, when the pitchers are better and smarter and more
careful.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Yankees ran the bases aggressively and smartly in the
first months, leading the league in stolen bases. At least two
opposing managers, Oakland's Art Howe and the Royals' Tony Muser,
suggested the Yankees' base running was the most underrated aspect
of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Torre expected opponents to watch his team more carefully and
keep them from stealing bases, because with the exception of
perhaps Derek Jeter and Knoblauch, they don't have great
base-stealing talents, just good, smart base-runners.
</P>
<P>
   For one reason or another _ maybe the team's recent reliance on
home runs _ the Yankees have stopped running, and temporarily lost
that mind-set. They have just nine stolen bases in their last 17
games, but much more important than that is the sudden increase in
base-running mistakes. Jeter and O'Neill forgot the number of outs
just innings apart two weeks ago, Joe Girardi once failed to follow
the direction of the third-base coach, Willie Randolph, and Jeter
made a crucial mistake Tuesday. Teams win in the postseason because
they capitalize on mistakes, not commit them.
</P>
<P>
   More than a month remains before the playoffs and the Yankees
are a great team and will finish the year with a great record. But
like every team, they have problems.
</P>
<P>
   The 1906 Chicago Cubs won 116 games and lost the World Series,
the 1954 Cleveland Indians won 111 games and set the American
League record for victories, and they lost the World Series. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
