</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERCK-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCK ACCEPTS POLICY ON CARE UNIT PROCEDURES 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Merck &AMP; Co. and its Merck-Medco Managed Care LLC unit have
agreed with the Federal Trade Commission to bar Medco from
discriminating against drugs made by Merck's competitors or
exploiting private marketing information about other drug makers
that Medco receives.
</P>
<P>
   Merck said Wednesday that the agreement formalized policies and
practices that it voluntarily adopted more than three years ago.
Merck bought Medco for $6.6 billion in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Managed care drug units like Medco and similar units of Eli
Lilly (Eli) &AMP; Co. and SmithKline Beecham PLC buy drugs at discounts
from an array of manufacturers in return for delivering high-volume
sales through employer drug plans and health maintenance
organizations. The managed care unit helps Merck win the business
of the HMOs and other drug plans.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement with the FTC staff, Merck-Medco must offer
customers a wide-ranging choice of drugs called an ``open
formulary,'' which are selected by an independent committee of
physicians and other experts. Merck has to operate Medco as an
independent unit, separated from the parent company by procedural
barriers called a firewall.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly has a similar formal agreement with the commission, and
SmithKline observes similar rules under an informal understanding,
a SmithKline spokeswoman said
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will be sent to the commission for review and
formal approval.
</P>
<P>
   Per G.H. Lofberg, president of Merck-Medco, said the unit
realized from the start that it had to be independent to compete
with the other managed care drug units. To do so, it had to keep
the confidence of other drug makers that are the sole suppliers of
popular products.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said it was hard to judge the effectiveness
of the managed care drug units for companies that own them. Lilly
has acknowledged that it paid far too much when it bought PCS
Health Systems from the McKesson Corp. for $4.1 billion. It took a
$2.4 billion charge last year, reflecting second thoughts about the
value of PCS.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Sweig, a pharmaceutical analyst with Southeast Research
Partners, said that Merck regularly announced that it was satisfied
with the ability of Medco to increase the Merck share of U.S. drug
sales, now approaching 15 percent. But he said that a surge in
recent years in advertising to consumers of prescription drugs like
Merck's Propecia for male baldness and Lilly's Prozac had had a big
role in sales growth.
</P>
<P>
   Sweig said that Medco profits were slim in comparison with Merck
profits, so the success of Medco, which had been increasing the
number of its members by 20 percent to 30 percent annually, had led
to ``a dilution of Merck's gross profit margins.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, companies like Merck and Lilly hope to lock in
sales to managed care consumers through disease-management
programs, which supply them with educational materials about
illnesses like diabetes, asthma and arthritis. The aim is to have
patients faithfully take their medicine, enhancing drug sales,
while saving on potential hospital and doctor costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
