A4412 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-LADN     08-27 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAJOR CONCERN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the year's major championships recorded history, Phil
Mickelson again finds himself with the title ``Best Player on Tour
Never to Have Won a Major.''
</P>
<P>
   Others got the glory that comes with winning a major while
Mickelson, one of the game's most talented players, waits. He's 0
for 26 in the game's major championships.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson has already strung together a fine season, winning the
Mercedes Championship and the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro Am.
He's earned $1.5 million to rank sixth on the PGA Tour's money
list.
</P>
<P>
   He possesses one of the game's best swings, is Hollywood
handsome and a Houdini with an L-wedge in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   He's a member of an elite fraternity of golfers you'd buy a
ticket to watch, players like Tiger Woods, Fred Couples, Ernie Els,
Tom Lehman, Greg Norman, Mark O'Meara and Justin Leonard. But these
guys have all crossed the major threshold.
</P>
<P>
   Now no one else on tour is close to being in Mickelson's class
when it comes to promise unfulfilled. For proof you only have to
consult the legacy that trails him from tournament to tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson won the 1991 Northern Telecom Open while an amateur.
He turned professional the next year. He has won 13 tournaments
worldwide since then. He is the fourth youngest player to reach the
10-win mark, which puts him in the company of Horton Smith, Jack
Nicklaus and Gene Sarazen, golfers who are legends. And only
Nicklaus, Woods and Mickelson won NCAA and U.S. Amateur titles in
the same year.
</P>
<P>
   So in the record books he is keeping good company. For most of
the players on tour this would be a great career.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson's resume does include what's considered a significant
victory, the 1996 NEC World Series of Golf, a tournament being
played this week and with a field a cut above other events. The
NEC's stature grows next year when it gets an image transplant,
becoming the NEC Invitational, and a field made up mostly of the
most recent members of the Ryder Cup and President's Cup teams. It
will be one of four new World Golf Championship events put together
for the America, Europe, Japan, South Africa and Australasia tours.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson's win in 1996 gave him a 10-year exemption onto the
PGA tour, so he does not have to worry about retaining his playing
privileges while pursuing his elusive goal. It proves he can win a
big event.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, during the week of the PGA Championship, ``Golf
World'' magazine pondered in a cover story whether Mickelson is
tough enough to win a major. After reading it, Mickelson said the
reporting was fair. Then he shot himself out of contention with a
78 on Saturday, again rendering a major Sunday insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   His response to a shattered dream was that golf is just a game
and Saturday's round was not the end of the world. He shot a 67 on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, in the final round of the rain-delayed AT&AMP;T Pebble
Beach National Pro-Am, he recorded another 67 to win that title.
</P>
<P>
   Then last weekend he shot a plus 41 under the Modified
Stableford system to finish high on the leader board at the Sprint
International.
</P>
<P>
   In an eight-day run, Mickelson banked $740,250, almost half his
year's winnings. He's fast becoming the richest golfer on the
planet not to have won a major and he wears that title with grace.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Masters is just eight months away. For Phil
Mickelson, that doesn't seem like such a long time to wait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
