<HEADER>
A4413 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-COMETS-MERCURY-HN     08-27 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-MERCURY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
PHOENIX _ A playwright could have a field day with the WNBA
championship series.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are enough plots and subplots to keep a word processor
whirring for quite a while.
</P>
<P>
   First, of course, there's what figures to be a heated
best-of-three series for the 1998 title.
</P>
<P>
   Game 1 is tonight at 7, when the defending champion Comets face
the Phoenix Mercury at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the continuation of one of the hottest rivalries to
develop over the first two years of the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll guarantee you, I'd rather be in Cleveland right now,''
Comets coach Van Chancellor said Wednesday of the team the Mercury
beat Tuesday night to advance to the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the two best teams (in the WNBA) are in the
championships at this time of year,'' said Chancellor. ``What has
Phoenix done lately? Won eight out of 10? Nine out of 11 or
something like that? They're playing great basketball right now.
They had a little lull near the middle of the summer, but nobody
cares about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a dream matchup, if you want my honest
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   The curtain is ready to rise on the first clash between two-time
Most Valuable Player Cynthia Cooper and Phoenix center and MVP
runner-up Jennifer Gillom since the results were announced earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about Cynthia Cooper vs. Jennifer Gillom,'' Cooper
said. ``This is about the Houston Comets against the Phoenix
Mercury.''
</P>
<P>
   Another subplot is the antics of Mercury coach Cheryl Miller.
The postgame soliloquy she delivered to fans at America West in
July following a 65-62 loss to the Comets still seems to echo off
the walls of the Mercury's home building.
</P>
<P>
   The Basketball Hall of Famer guaranteed a championship victory
over the Comets that night.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a late-season streak during which the Mercury lost five
straight games and seven of nine immediately after Miller's speech,
she at least marshaled the troops enough to get them to the
championship round.
</P>
<P>
   Has there been any point since that night that Miller has
regretted her words?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never regret anything I've said. If you're going to say
something or do something, do it with conviction,'' Miller said,
bristling. ``Every now and then, you roll the dice. You might come
up lucky. We're happy to be here. We're just going to give it our
best shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller sees no link between the speech and the Mercury's
subsequent slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens to any team when they go into a skid?'' Miller
said. ``What happened to New York when they opened the season by
losing the first five?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team goes through that. There's no need of sitting up
here rehashing what happened, coulda, shoulda, woulda. We're here
at the finals and ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she thought her words may come back to haunt the
Mercury now, if the Comets might not still gain motivation from
them, Miller delivered a placid answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think,'' she said, ``that if you're the defending
world champions, defending that crown should be first and foremost.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it doesn't matter what Cheryl Miller thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   In four games during the regular season, the Mercury beat the
Comets once, 69-66 at America West on June 24.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets avenged that loss July 21 and ignited Miller's
postgame tirade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it ironic that we find ourselves back here on the scene
where she said that to the crowd?'' said Cooper, a former teammate
of Miller's at Southern Cal. ``I think that's great for women's
basketball. It will bring another 3,000 to 5,000 fans to the arena
to see the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, as I've said before, Cheryl doesn't get a chance to
come out on the court and play. She thinks she does. But I think
what she did served her team well. It motivated the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Phoenix is such a wonderful place to play. It's wonderful
because of the fan support, because of all the motivation Cheryl
brings to her team and also to the Mercury fans. It's going to be a
tough game; it's going to be a physical game. We'll see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   So the stage is set. The ESPN and Lifetime cameras and lights
are in place. On with the show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
