<HEADER>
A4415 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USWEST-AZR &LR;      08-27 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WEST ADS GALVANIZE STRIKERS 
</HEADLINE>
 WEST-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAX JARMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Midway through their second week, striking US West workers are
piping hot, but not from the sweltering Arizona heat.
</P>
<P>
   Strikers are steamed by an advertising campaign they say is
misleading and makes them more determined than ever to outlast the
company in a bid for a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Gosiger, president of the Communication Workers of America
Local 7019, said the strikers get rejuvenated every time the
company runs an ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we are under attack from the leaders of this
company, but they are underestimating workers. (Workers) are
getting more charged up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, representatives of US West and the Communication
Workers of America met with federal mediator Jim Mahan for a fourth
consecutive day. No major progress was reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems like we're kind of in a shouting match right
now,'' said Carla West, a union representative in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The disputed issues remain mandatory overtime, health-care
benefits and a performance-pay proposal. Both sides have agreed not
to discuss their specific proposals publicly while talks are under
way.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, strikers say what they perceive as attempts by the
company to undermine the solidarity of the union have only
galvanized them further.
</P>
<P>
   Those include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A series of full-page newspaper ads that union officials say
are misleading and full of half-truths.
</P>
<P>
   _A decision by the company to cancel strikers' medical benefits
effective Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   _ The employment of private detectives to videotape and
photograph strikers.
</P>
<P>
   _Intimating that the strikers in US West's 14-state region may
be responsible for about 121 acts of reputed vandalism since the
strike began Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   _ Obtaining a court order preventing union members from
threatening or intimidating US West managers and others working
during the strike.
</P>
<P>
   To Patrick Obermeyer, a Phoenix cable repairman picketing
Wednesday at Third Street and Earll Drive, the company's decision
to cancel the striking workers' medical benefits starting Monday
was a contemptuous act and a slap in the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I'd rather find another job than cross that picket
line,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Union representative Peggy Dewey said she used to be proud to
work for US West, but the company's actions during the strike have
changed that opinion.
</P>
<P>
   She is particularly angry over a series of newspaper ads run by
US West that she says distort the issues over which the workers are
striking.
</P>
<P>
   ``One ad made it look like they proposed to cap forced overtime
at 12 hours a week,'' she said. ``But it didn't say that was after
five years.''
</P>
<P>
   The overtime proposal would include unlimited forced overtime
this year, 25 hours per week in 1999, 20 in 2000, 15 in 2001 and 12
in 2002. Forced overtime, which for some employees is now more than
30 hours a week, is one of the key issues over which the company
and the union disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Dewey pointed to another statement in the ad that claimed the
company was offering free health insurance to all employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't say that to continue with the coverage we now get
for free, employees will have pay about $70 per month out of their
own pocket,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gosiger called a court order the company received against the
union Tuesday a public-relations stunt and another example of the
company's attempt to undermine the union and sway public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The order, issued by Maricopa County Superior Court Judge John
R. Sticht of Phoenix, prohibits the union and its members from
engaging in acts or threats of force, violence, bodily harm,
property damage or vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   US West spokesman Jim Roof said the court order was obtained to
curb rising acts of vandalism against the company and the
harassment by strikers of managers and other employees still on the
job. Vandalism in the Phoenix area primarily involves cut wires in
service boxes where several hundred individual lines connect to
larger cables.
</P>
<P>
   Roof said that since the strike began Aug. 15, there have been
about 25 instances of such vandalism in Phoenix. The rate is
substantially higher than before the strike, he said. Although he
acknowledged that no one has actually witnessed any vandalism, he
said, ``Coincidence can only go so far.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the harassment of US West managers attempting to fill in
for the strikers, he said the acts are well documented. They
include barring service vehicles from leaving maintenance yards;
surrounding service vehicles in the field, thus disrupting repairs;
and surrounding and harassing workers in manholes.
</P>
<P>
   As for the service boxes, Gosiger said he suspects that service
personnel unfamiliar with their jobs are confusing the generally
poor condition of much of US West's system with vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the boxes they claimed were vandalized and they
looked like they always do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this week the union will begin running its own ads.
The television commercials will focus on the issue of forced
overtime, the one to which the union feels the public will be most
sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Dewey nor Gosiger sees the strike ending soon, although
Roof said he was encouraged by the fact that both sides were
talking for the fourth day in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, strikers are beginning to look for temporary jobs to
tide them over. With the tight labor market in Phoenix, most don't
think they'll have trouble finding work.
</P>
<P>
   At the CWA union hall in Phoenix, strikers peruse listings of
part-time jobs and pick up fliers from St Mary's Food Bank and
other community agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can make $70 a day as a substitute teacher in Mesa,'' said
Warren Cole, a customer-service employee also picketing at Third
and Earll. ``With that and my strike pay, I can hold on
indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Monday, 3,761 strikers will be entitled to $200 per
week in strike pay. The payments will come out of the CWA's $176
million strike fund. To qualify, members have to spend at least six
hours a week on the picket line. &QL; 
 &UR; Max Jarman can be reached at 444-7351 or at max.jarman &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
