<HEADLINE>
NEW TYPE OF ROCKET TO CARRY SATELLITES EXPLODES IN LIFTOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ An unmanned rocket carrying an advanced
communications satellite exploded here on Wednesday night less than
90 seconds after liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the accident was not immediately clear.
</P>
<P>
   The launching, at 9:17 p.m., was the maiden flight for a new
version of the Delta rocket, which had been designed by the Boeing
Co. to carry twice the payload of the old version.
</P>
<P>
   The accident came only two weeks after a government spy
satellite exploded here shortly after takeoff, dealing a blow to
the nation's space reconnaissance program.
</P>
<P>
   The Delta family of rockets has been in use for decades. The new
version, called Delta III, was designed to carry a payload of about
8,400 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's payload was a Galaxy X communications
satellite built by the Hughes electronics unit of the General
Motors Corp. The satellite had been built for use by the Panamsat
Corp., based in Greenwich, Conn., which intended to sell use of the
satellite to cable television carriers and telecommunications
companies.
</P>
<P>
   A similar satellite, Galaxy IV failed this spring, cutting off
the use of pagers to many of the nation's millions of paging
customers. The Galaxy X was not meant as a direct replacement for
the Galaxy IV.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes and Boeing would not immediately comment about the
failure on Wednesday night, but Daniel Marcus, a spokesman for
Panamsat, said: ``While the launch is a disappointment, it has
always been part of our comprehensive plan to cover events like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus said that the satellite was fully insured and that the
company planned to proceed with a launching in three weeks in
French Guiana by the European space agency, Ariane.
</P>
<P>
   Panamsat officials said the cost of building, launching and
insuring the rocket and satellite was $200 million to $250 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
