<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCLINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSPOKEN CLARIDGE LEADS USC DOGGED LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ When USC offensive lineman Travis Claridge
looks to his left, he sees someone who has never played in a
college football game. When he looks to his right, there are three
lineman whose combined college experience equals less time than
Claridge played in an average quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This is the world in which Claridge resides these days as the
only veteran of an untested line. Despite being younger than all
but one of the other four starters, Claridge is considered the
star, leader and emotional barometer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to be my rock out there,'' offensive line coach Steve
Greatwood said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a role Claridge shies away from. Actually, there isn't
much the junior is afraid to tackle _ on or off the field. His
brutal honesty might rankle some, but his opinions can rarely be
challenged for their accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   When discussing USC's often inept running game during the
previous two seasons, Claridge said, ``People are always saying the
offensive line (messed) up. Let's be honest, some of our backs were
blind.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the time, it was because the running back would put
his head down and get to the hole and he would get smacked. They
couldn't find the holes. The only true runner was LaVale (Woods).''
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of USC's line has been linked to many of the Trojans'
recent offensive woes, and those comments remain fresh to Claridge.
He believes the line has been unduly singled out ever since he
arrived at USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go out and play my butt off for two years, but if you
lose games, the linemen get blamed,'' he said. ``If the defense
gets shredded, would you say Daylon McCutcheon was awful?''
</P>
<P>
   It's this attitude that makes him a natural leader, and USC has
little choice but to depend greatly upon him. The right tackle,
Matt Welch, is a junior college transfer who has not played
Division I football.
</P>
<P>
   The left tackle, Brent McCaffrey, barely made appearances in two
games last season. The center, Eric Denmon, made appearances in
four games two years ago and missed last season. Left guard Jason
Grain appeared in 10 games, but that was only on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Claridge has started 23 games. An impressive feat considering he
started as a true freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the other guys will look at me to see how I react,''
Claridge said. ``I feel like I'm responsible because, when we line
up, I'm the only one who's been in a college game.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Claridge is USC's top lineman, the new coaching
staff believes he still needs to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been extremely pleased with Travis,'' USC coach Paul
Hackett said. ``But frankly, there are some techniques he's had the
past two years that we need to fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Greatwood said he's trying to keep Claridge's emotions from
taking over during a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't let himself get frustrated,'' Greatwood said. ``He
used to get real mad if a guy blew an assignment. Everyone's going
to have to perform. He can only do what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   For a time, it looked like Claridge was going to be doing his
thing somewhere else. He was close to former assistant Mike Barry
and considered transferring when John Robinson was fired last
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to, but I didn't,'' Claridge said. ``I stuck it
out. You can't run from your problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the coaching change, there has been turmoil in his
personal life. His father, Bill, was diagnosed with cancer this
summer and a tumor was removed from his throat. ``It's been real
stressful for me,'' Claridge said.
</P>
<P>
   He also misses his little brother, Ryan, a fullback who lives in
Michigan and is being recruited by Big Ten schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother lives in another state and I can't always be there
for him,'' Claridge said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tough situation, but as Claridge has learned, it's always
a rough job to be a USC lineman.
</P>
<P>
   CLARIDGE FILE &QL; 
College: USC &QL; 
Year: Junior &QL; 
Major: History &QL; 
Position: Offensive lineman &QL; 
Height/weight: 6-foot-6, 310 &QL; 
Career highlights: 1995 Parade All-American, Super Prep
All-American and rated the nation's No. 1 offensive lineman as a
senior two-way tackle at Fort Vancouver High in Vancouver, Wash.
Has started at right guard for the Trojans since his freshman
year. &QL; 
Did you know?: Claridge was born in Detroit, Mich., and also lived
in El Toro. As a youngster, he worked out with some athletic
trainers, including former Trojan and NFL lineman Marv Marinovich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
