<HEADER>
A4427 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     08-27 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELVIN ARMS TEAM, BUT ONE BULLET A DUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Unless he saved one for himself, Rangers
general manager Doug Melvin fired his last bullet yesterday. Now,
it's up to the Rangers to save his ``executive of the year''
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least his job.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month ago, Melvin was being praised throughout
baseball for the astute deadline deals that, according to scouts,
league executives and media pundits, resulted in major upgrades in
starting pitching, at shortstop and at third base.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Todd Stottlemyre is single-handedly threatening to make a
liar out of all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin added much-needed veteran left-hander Greg Cadaret to the
Rangers' bullpen yesterday. It will likely be the GM's final move
before postseason rosters must be set by midnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to us to do something now,'' Rangers manager Johnny
Oates said before the Rangers closed out their homestand with a
critical 8-6 victory against the Tigers. ``Doug's done all he can
do. The people in uniform have to do the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have what it takes here to win the division. We just have
to go out and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The message to his players is clear: No more excuses. No more
alibis. No more lapses of concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talent-wise, \Rthe Rangers\S are better than the Angels,''
Tigers dugout coach Larry Parrish said.
</P>
<P>
   It's way past time to start playing like it.
</P>
<P>
   Considering almost five weeks remain in the season, a
gut-wrenching tension pervaded The Ballpark in Arlington last
night.
</P>
<P>
   When the Tigers' Frank Catalanotto, the game's second batter,
drove an Esteban Loaiza offering over the right-field fence for a
quick 1-0 Detroit lead, Rangers fans gulped.
</P>
<P>
   The out-of-town scoreboard already showed that the Angels had
beaten the Yankees, 4-1, in the first game of a doubleheader at
Yankee Stadium, their third consecutive victory in New York. And
Anaheim led 1-0 early in the nightcap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look like the guy who couldn't open the pickle jar,'' mused
a frustrated Rangers official, remembering that this team had just
lost five of seven to the Yanks, ``and the next guy makes it look
easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, in a worst-case scenario that seemed well on its
way to becoming reality, were in danger of waking up five games
behind Anaheim in the American League West race this morning.
</P>
<P>
   And ``5'' is their magic number. That's how many games they have
left head-to-head with the Angels. Fall further back than that and
they'll be in the uncomfortable position of needing help from other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side _ a Yanks win in the nightcap and a Rangers
victory against the Tigers _ meant slicing a half-game off
Anaheim's lead.
</P>
<P>
   An aborted Angels comeback in the ninth, the Rangers holding off
the Tigers almost in spite of themselves and a round of
Alka-Seltzer for the house left the Rangers three games back as
they embark on a seven-game road trip to Chicago and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   It would be patently unfair to lay all the Rangers' problems off
on Stottlemyre, but the veteran right-hander's glaring 7.03
earned-run average since he arrived has left Texas no better off
than before he arrived to replace struggling Darren Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin is worried and it shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think \RStottlemyre\S is concerned about it, too,'' Melvin
said. ``But he's just got to keep going out there. Our scouts say
the stuff's still there. I told him the other day that we didn't
get him to come over here and be the savior. A lot of guys have to
pull their weight for us to be a successful team.''
</P>
<P>
   Guys like third baseman Todd Zeile, who made his ninth error
since being acquired in Melvin's July 31 blitzkrieg. And guys like
Gold Glove catcher Pudge Rodriguez, whose seventh throwing error on
a pickoff attempt at second base put the potential tying run in
scoring position with nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Only some clutch relief work by Xavier Hernandez prevented the
Rangers' defensive lapses from costing them the game this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's trying hard,'' said outfielder Juan Gonzalez, who
drove in four more runs, ``but we need more concentration inside
the lines. We need something extra from everybody this last
month.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the Rangers need for Stottlemyre to become the
veteran leader of the rotation that they believed they were getting
when they traded for him.
</P>
<P>
   Some reputations _ and maybe the entire season _ are riding on
it. \Ntagtop:Jim Reeves, (817) 390-7972
\Ntagbottom:''revo\Nstar-telegram.com''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
