<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-HUNDLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY EXPERIMENT IN LEFT FIELD GOES UP IN FLAMES
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Last June, in the sweltering humidity of Port
St. Lucie, Fla., Todd Hundley said there might come a day when he
would tell New York Mets General Manager Steve Phillips to ``take
that catching gear and burn it.''
</P>
<P>
   The grand experiment of turning Hundley into an outfielder had
just begun. On Wednesday, after 34 starts in left field _ some of
which were painful to watch _ the experiment is officially over.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Mets have a $4.8 million pinch-hitter sitting in the
dugout as they chase a wild-card berth and questions to answer
about their catcher position.
</P>
<P>
   When asked on Wednesday what he was going to do with his
outfielder's glove, Hundley said, ``Burn it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to catch again next year,'' Hundley said, although
he was unsure where. ``But we've got to deal with this year
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley made his impromptu announcement with Manager Bobby
Valentine standing nearby (almost like a chaperon) before Hideo
Nomo's 4-1 complete-game victory over San Francisco. While the Mets
lead the Cubs by one game and the Giants by two in the wild-card
race, it has been a year to forget for Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make a career change at age 29 just doesn't work right
now,'' said Hundley, who is hitting .164 with 2 home runs and 11
runs batted in with 49 strikeouts in 110 at-bats. ``This is better
for the organization. It's been decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, without a hit in his last 15 at-bats, was 0 for 3 and
struggled in the field during Tuesday night's 7-3 loss to the
Giants. When asked what he was going to do about his left-field
situation, Valentine said: ``Let's face it, left field hasn't been
a good situation for most of this year. I would say right now it
has to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine stopped short of saying he was going to bench Hundley,
but Hundley was not pleased when he was told of Valentine's
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   He telephoned Valentine late Tuesday night at the team hotel to
discuss the situation. Hundley chose not to reveal what was said.
``It's not worth getting into,'' Hundley said.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, meanwhile, refused to speculate on whether he might
have made the same decision had Hundley not phoned him first. When
asked if he had planned on abandoning the experiment on Wednesday
anyway, Valentine said: ``I planned on him getting more batting
practice. That's the only plan I had.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he intended to or not, however, Valentine opened the
door for the possibility of Hundley going to the bench. And there
was no question the experiment was not working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both because of offense and defense,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley was asked if his reconstructed right elbow was bothering
him. ``It's good enough,'' was the reply.
</P>
<P>
   How about playing left field, then? ``It's so boring, it's
unbelievable,'' Hundley said, before walking away.
</P>
<P>
   Since July 11, the day Hundley made his major league outfield
debut, Hundley had improved his defense considerably from the
tragicomedy of his first couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But opposing teams were running at will on Hundley's tentative
defensive approach.
</P>
<P>
   And Hundley was not hitting enough behind Mike Piazza _ the man
who had taken his place behind the plate _ to justify an experiment
that at least one player said was unfair to the rest of his
teammates, what with the Mets in the middle of the wild-card chase.
</P>
<P>
   The same player had also said the situation was unfair to
Hundley, who was trying to shake off the rust of not facing major
league pitching for almost a year. But neither Hundley nor the
Mets' front office was willing to say they had made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than not playing at all,'' Hundley said, when
asked if he would have been better not trying to come back this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said: ``I don't regret it. We would have had regrets if
we didn't try.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet one cannot help feeling sorry for Hundley, who hit 71
home runs the last two seasons before having to undergo serious
surgery last September, a May trade for Piazza a few days after he
was assured one would not be made, and a damaging leak in the
organization that was critical of Hundley's work and drinking
habits.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all Hundley can hope for is that he will be able to catch
again before the season is over _ and that the Mets will include
him on the post-season roster should they qualify for the playoffs
for the first time in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he was now worried that he would be left off,
Hundley, who has repeatedly said his only goal left is to play in
the playoffs, said: ``Yeah. I guess. That's part of it. But what
are you going to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve and I talked about it. I could come in, in a backup
catcher role and pinch-hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, who met with Hundley on Wednesday morning, said:
``There's no assurance for anybody. When we get to that point,
we'll make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, Phillips said: ``I'm not going to get into a
catcher controversy. One guy's a free agent and we don't know if
he's coming back. The other guy's a catcher who can't catch right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with his outfield experiment behind him, it is clear
Hundley wants to get back behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the New York Mets, I don't know,'' he said. ``I'm not in
control of that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
