A4431 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMWEST-FINE-AZR &LR;      08-27 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-FINE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA: SAFETY WAS SECOND PRIORITY AT AMERICA WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although America West executives say their record fine last
month was the result of procedural oversights, federal
investigators found that the company's maintenance problems stemmed
from a corporate culture that valued uninterrupted flights over
passenger safety.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration documents say the airline
``grossly mismanaged'' its maintenance operations before being hit
with the $5 million fine in July.
</P>
<P>
   America West President and Chief Executive Officer Richard
Goodmanson said he has not seen the reports but said the FAA's
conclusions were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   He said the reports were written by ``apparently junior FAA
investigators'' and said he was amazed that their tone did not
match the FAA's pronouncement last month that the airline was
operating safely.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors' records, obtained through a Freedom of
Information Act request, document 11 cases that formed the basis
for the fine and settlement agreement with the Tempe-based airline.
</P>
<P>
   The cases suggest that the violations cited were not isolated
incidents, but instead resulted from a bottom-line corporate
focus. &QL; 
``The attitude of this carrier's management (is) that safety and
regulatory requirements are secondary to the continued movement of
aircraft within the carrier's route system,'' one inspector
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This culture, which permeates the carrier, lends credence to
the employees who conduct the day to day operations of the carrier
that it is OK to continue an operation even when there may be a
significant factor that could impede safety. This fact alone could
lead to a significant event resulting in a loss of life or
property.'' &QL; 
REPORT IS `OLD NEWS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Goodmanson said that the company never urged employees to skirt
maintenance duties. Although the company had some rough going after
its controversial December 1995 decision to lay off its mechanics
and send heavy maintenance work to outside contractors, Goodmanson
said things had improved markedly by mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
   An FAA spokesman who called ``The Republic'' after being alerted
to the story by America West, called the inspectors' reports ``old
news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The FAA's position about America West is reflected in our
press release on July 14,'' Tim Pile said Thursday. ``And as of
today, they're in compliance with the settlement agreement, they've
met all of the requirements to date, and I hope your article
reflects that.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, the FAA and America West agreed to a settlement that
calls for the airline to follow an even stricter maintenance regime
than contained in federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The airline also agreed to immediately pay half of the $5
million fine. At $2.5 million, the fine is the largest ever for an
air carrier. The remaining $2.5 million is waived if America West
sticks to specific maintenance requirements over the next year. &QL; 
SOURCE OF CONTENTION &QL; 
America West has never had an accident, and the airline has the
second-best safety record in the industry, after Southwest
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   But its maintenance history has been a source of contention,
especially since the 1995 layoffs and outsourcing.
</P>
<P>
   According to a June 22 memo, FAA attorney Naomi Tsuda briefed
her supervisors on the airline's maintenance history to ``prevent
the FAA from being taken for a ride by (America West) management.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the FAA and the airline were holding settlement
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Tsuda said the FAA had launched a ``progressive enforcement
program'' to get the airline to follow maintenance regulations. The
program included a 1996 fine of $205,000 to settle six maintenance
cases, and a $49,000 fine to end the FAA's gripe about an Airbus
A-320 that flew 144 times without meeting all of its
heavy-maintenance require ments.
</P>
<P>
   The last fine was drastically reduced _ from a proposed $154,000
_ to allow America West to buy a computer to better track its
maintenance requirements, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe a strong arm is appropriate in dealing with AWXA
(America West), and any claims that they do not understand the
rules/regs or were unaware of the extent of the problems is less
than sincere,'' she wrote in the memo to her supervisors in the
FAA's Western Pacific legal division. &QL; 
COMPLAINTS BACKED UP &QL; 
Tsuda recapped America West's history because the FAA had recently
put a new attorney and new maintenance inspector on the case. A
month after she circulated her memo, the FAA assessed the record
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Tsuda's complaints were backed up by an FAA inspector. In a
report this spring, he wrote that he warned company officials that
outsourcing was creating problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fell on deaf ears,'' he wrote. ``In fact, when apprised
of a violation and potential violations AWXA (America West) senior
management seemed to take the role of a large bird which is known
for sticking its head in the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodmanson acknowledged that the outsourcing has been a
particular problem between the FAA and the airline, but said it
remains a prudent move. Because America West has a comparatively
small fleet of planes (104), there is not enough heavy maintenance
work to keep a staff busy year round, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did that purely for economic reasons,'' he said. ``If you
looked at it today, it's exactly the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA, he said, has never liked the move to outsourcing
because it requires their inspectors to travel outside their home
territory. For example, America West now has its heavy maintenance
done by Air Canada in Winnipeg, Manitoba.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the FAA's complaints are technical, but generally minor,
Goodmanson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are `taillights out' kind of stuff,'' he said, citing
the FAA's gripe that nine airplanes were found in March to be
flying without cargo netting properly in place.
</P>
<P>
   The most critical item in the FAA's report _ the operation of 17
Airbus planes without a required inspection of the skin around
their cargo doors _ was the result of a miscommunication,
Goodmanson said.
</P>
<P>
   After the inspections were completed this spring, the airline
found all 17 Airbuses in top shape, he said.
</P>
<P>
   FAA inspectors viewed the incident differently, criticizing the
airline for initially arguing that the inspection did not have to
be done. This fueled the inspectors' belief that America West was
inattentive to maintenance duties. &QL; 
`NOBODY WATCHING STORE' &QL; 
Their complaints intensified after they realized that one of the
Airbuses flew an additional 185 times before being inspected for
cracks _ even after being notified by FAA investigators this April
that inspections had been missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is watching the store!'' an FAA inspector wrote in his
report on the Airbus inspections.
</P>
<P>
   The documents show that the FAA initially proposed an $11.2
million fine for 11 cases. The penalty could have been more, if the
FAA had added up the fines for an additional 24 outstanding cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd used up the maximum fine for all the violations, it
would have been $11 million to $15 million,'' said Monroe Balton,
deputy regional counsel for the FAA's Western Pacific division.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its settlement with America West, the FAA dropped its
investigation of an additional two dozen cases, some dating back to
the last decade and six as recent as this year. Most involved
security procedures, such as bags not being properly monitored.
</P>
<P>
   Balton said fines generally are a matter of ``prosecutorial
discretion.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Mary Jo Pitzl can be reached at 271-8963 or at maryjo.pitzl &LR; pni.com
via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
