r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-TIGERS-TE     08-27 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TIGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ PUTS HOLD ON TIGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Right on cue, Rangers public address
announcer Chuck Morgan played the theme to ``The X-Files'' as
reliever Xavier Hernandez emerged from the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Clever idea. ``X-Files''. X-man.
</P>
<P>
   The theme, though, is somewhat out of place. There's nothing
mysterious or otherworldly about Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers defeated the Tigers, 8-6, last night at The Ballpark
in Arlington because Hernandez simply made the pitches in the most
important part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   He entered the game with the bases loaded and nobody out in the
seventh inning with the Rangers holding a two-run lead, and allowed
just one of the runs to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``X-man came in and did a fantastic job for us, and I felt that
was the key,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``To get out of that with
the guys he had to face there, that's a pretty good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez didn't figure into the decision. Starter Esteban
Loaiza (2-3) got the victory that moved the Rangers to within three
games of the Anaheim Angels in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't earn the save. That went to John Wetteland, who worked
the ninth for No. 36.
</P>
<P>
   He probably didn't appear on the ESPN highlights. Those belonged
to Juan Gonzalez, who drove in four runs with a two-run double in
the first off Tigers starter Bryce Florie (6-8), a run-scoring
double in the second and a single in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   But without Hernandez, there likely wouldn't have been a victory
for Loaiza or a save for Wetteland, and Gonzalez's heroics would be
wasted.
</P>
<P>
   The theme song sounded when Hernandez entered the game in the
seventh with the heart of the Tigers' batting order due up.
</P>
<P>
   First was Damion Easley, second on the team with 81 runs batted
in. He popped out to second baseman Mark McLemore on what Hernandez
called a fastball down the middle, a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Next was Tony Clark, Detroit's leader with 27 homers and 82 RBI.
He hit a weak grounder to first baseman Will Clark, although it
scored a run. Hernandez threw six consecutive forkballs, the last
on a 3-2 count even though Clark took the previous two for balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to throw him a fastball and have him pop it out
of the ballpark,'' Hernandez said. ``I figure he saw the ducks on
and wanted to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez intentionally walked Luis Gonzalez, and got out of the
inning when Juan Encarnacion lined out to shortstop Royce Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed reliever then worked a 1-2-3 eighth before
yielding to Wetteland in the ninth. Wetteland retired all three
batters he faced, but he knew who the real hero was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any bases-loaded situation with no outs is pretty much the
ballgame,'' Wetteland said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who has allowed one earned run in his last 13
appearances and has a 1.41 ERA in his last 25 games, did it by
staying calm and throwing strikes, even if they weren't perfect
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think he's playing catch with his son in the back yard,''
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing mysterious about it, but it's a concept the
Rangers sometimes find hard to grasp. Good pitching, with a helping
of good defense, equals victories.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's game was headed in the direction of being one of
those where the formula falls apart.
</P>
<P>
   Deivi Cruz led off the seventh with a one-hopper to third
baseman Todd Zeile, who dropped it for an error. Tim Crabtree then
walked Brian Hunter, and catcher Ivan Rodriguez threw the ball away
on a pickoff attempt to put runners at second and third.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Eric Gunderson came in to face Frank Catalanotto, but
hit him with a 1-2 pitch to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   But just when it looked like another of those ``pitching and
defense let Rangers down'' games, Hernandez bailed out his team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
