r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     08-27 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS NEARLY SWEEP DOUBLEHEADER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If ever a split felt like a sweep, this was it.
</P>
<P>
   After beating the New York Yankees 6-4 in the first game of
Wednesday's day-night doubleheader at Yankee Stadium, the Anaheim
Angels pulled off an incredible rally in the late innings of the
second game only to lose 7-6 on Derek Jeter's RBI single off
Shigetoshi Hasegawa with two outs in the bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   With the split and Texas' victory over Detroit, the Angels' lead
in the AL West was reduced to three games.
</P>
<P>
   Though the second-game loss ended the Angels' winning streak at
five games, winning game one gave them the first three of the
five-game set. Having won six of 10 against the Yankees with only
one more to play, the Angels have clinched the season series.
</P>
<P>
   The second-game loss allowed the Yankees to end a season-worst
losing streak of four games, but Angels manager Terry Collins was
impressed with his club even in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet there's consolation,'' Collins said. ``That's a
tremendous effort. They battled their butts off against a guy like
(Yankees starter) David Wells. There's nothing to be ashamed about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like (Yankees manager) Joe (Torre) said the other day, the
Yankees don't like losing. They come at you as hard as they can,
and we took 'em down to the wire.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels trailed in the second game, 5-1 and 6-3, but refused
to quit. The Angels scored two in the seventh inning on Jim
Edmonds' second homer of the game, added two more in the eighth,
but trailed 6-5 in the ninth against Yankees closer Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs and nobody on, Paco Martin singled. Darin Erstad
fell behind in the count 0-2 but fouled off five pitches with two
strikes and worked the count full.
</P>
<P>
   Martin broke for second on a 3-2 pitch and Erstad lined the ball
into the right-field corner. Martin beat the relay with a
head-first slide and the Angels dugout erupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in and won the first three games and could easily have
said `Let's conserve energy for tomorrow, we've got Chuck (Finley)
tomorrow,''' Collins said. ``But they said `Let's come back and get
the game.' In the fifth inning, they were saying `We're right where
we want to be _ four runs down.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We can leave the ballpark tonight feeling great, with our
heads held high.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera (3-0) got the win over Mike Fetters (2-7).
</P>
<P>
   The Angels fell behind early. Angels starter Steve Sparks had
won five decisions in a row and sailed through 41/3 innings. But
after the knuckeballer struck out Darryl Strawberry to start the
fifth, the Yankees put together five consecutive hits, including a
three-run home run by Homer Bush, and scored five runs in the
inning. It was Bush's first career major-league homer.
</P>
<P>
   Just the prospect of playing the Yankees in a five-game series _
in New York _ seemed like a daunting task. But the Angels have been
up to the challenge by winning three of four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the battle is not to be intimidated by them,'' shortstop
Gary DiSarcina said. ``They smell blood, they can crush you. As a
team, we understand we have to play this kind of baseball to
compete against the best teams. We understand as a group, a unit,
that's how you go about your business.''
</P>
<P>
   However, DiSarcina seemed perturbed at the surprise many have
expressed regarding the Angels' success against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you can categorize it as special when you take the
season series from the team of the century,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how pretty much all you hear about is how the
Yankees are not doing the job, their bullpen is struggling, they're
hitting a tough time,'' DiSarcina added. ``But we're playing good
baseball. It seems like we're playing in the shadows. But sometimes
that's good to put the focus on the other team. We give ourselves
credit. I've never been on a team that battles like this one, that
doesn't give a damn what the score is. It's something to be proud
of.''
</P>
<P>
   As they did in the first two games of the series, the Angels
fell behind in the first game Wednesday. And as in the first two
games of the series, they came back.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Jeff Juden struggled with his command in the
early innings, walking four, allowing a solo homer to Tino Martinez
and an RBI double to Paul O'Neill as the Yankees took a 2-0 lead.
But Juden (1-2) settled down after that, allowing the Angels
offense a chance to figure out Yankees starter Ryan Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina doubled home Edmonds with two outs in the fifth to
score the Angels' first run, and Reggie Williams followed with a
two-run homer for a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels began the sixth with three consecutive hits for two
more runs and knocked Bradley (1-1) out of the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
