<HEADER>
A4457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT &LR;      08-27 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES SPLIT DOUBLE-HEADER WITH ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A long day and a long night of baseball had a chance
to be a lost day and lost night for the New York Yankees. They
looked like a mortal team for a week and looked even worse against
the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The team with the finest record in the major leagues desperately
needed to win on Wednesday. For their sanity, for their confidence
and for halting an irksome losing streak. But they lost the first
game of the day-night doubleheader, 6-4, and then Mariano Rivera
mishandled a save chance in the second game that enabled the Angels
to tie the score in the ninth inning. It was happening again.
</P>
<P>
   So when Derek Jeter batted against Shigetoshi Hasegawa with two
outs and with Jorge Posada on third in the bottom of the ninth, he
was staring at an opportunity to be a savior.
</P>
<P>
   To save the Yankees from possibly being swept, to save the
Yankees from being hexed by the Angels and to save Rivera on a
night when the closer was not impenetrable.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter did all of the above. Jeter squirted a single past a
diving Darrin Erstad at first base on a 3-2 fastball to score
Posada and catapult the Yankees to a dramatic 7-6 triumph that
terminated their four-game losing streak and caused Joe Torre to
sigh so loudly in his office that it could be heard 30 feet away in
the clubhouse. The manager was relieved and so were the Yankees
(95-36) after not frittering away a game they had once led by 5-1
behind a sloppy David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want anything to spiral,'' Torre said. ``Any time
you lose two, three, four games in a row, a little piece of your
confidence gets chopped off. It was a big win for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Very big. It took almost five months to happen, but the
record-chasing Yankees performed like an ordinary team in dropping
six of eight games before Jeter's crucial hit. The Angels, who have
now stopped them in 6 of the 10 games between the two teams, had
handled them better than any team in the American League. But Jeter
insisted that he was not thinking about Anaheim's dominance. He was
thinking about making the last out during the last two losses to
the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to like those situations,'' Jeter said. ``I like those
situations. Sometimes you're going to fail and sometimes you're
going to succeed. It was one of the situations that are fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Homer Bush clubbed a three-run homer, the first of his career,
to spark a five-run fifth against Steve Sparks and give the Yankees
confidence and a 5-1 lead. After Jim Edmonds ripped the second of
his two homers off Wells to make it Scott Brosius scored on Mike
Fetter's costly throwing error to make it 6-3. But the Angels
nicked Wells for a run in the eighth on Tim Salmon's single and
scored another after Rivera replaced Wells to make it 6-5. Wells
yielded five earned runs in seven innings and failed to record his
career-best 17th victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we win, that's all that matters,'' Wells said. ``I
wasn't pleased with my performance because we could have lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera recorded the first two outs in the ninth before Norberto
Martin smacked a single to center field. The Yankees were still
confident. Or were they? Erstad engaged in a classic 11-pitch
at-bat with Rivera that ended with him stroking a 3-2 pitch to
right field. Since Martin was running on the pitch, he managed to
score on the single as Posada failed to properly block the plate
and Martin dived across head first. The Yanks were stunned as
Rivera botched only his fifth save in 38 chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called on him to do a little more than he normally does,''
said Torre, referring to Rivera's attempt to notch a two-inning
save for only the second time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees emerged with their 95th victory as Posada walked
to initiate the ninth, advanced to second on Scott Brosius's
sacrifice bunt and smartly scooted to third on Bush's roller up the
third-base line. Even though Jeter had the game-winning hit, Bush
had as many reporters around his locker because of his important
homer. He has spoken to the fan who has the baseball and plans to
make a deal to get it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young man wants a bat, but I'm probably going to get him a
Derek Jeter or Bernie Williams bat to make it really worth his
while,'' Bush said modestly and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were not smiling after losing the opener. Ryan
Bradley started the game because Ramiro Mendoza had a cyst removed
from his buttocks, and the 22-year-old rookie cruised for the first
four innings and had a 2-0 bulge. But the Angels scored three in
the fifth on Gary DiSarcina's two-out double and Reggie Williams's
first major league homer, a two-run shot, and scored three more in
the sixth to end Bradley's first major league start in untidy
fashion. Bradley, who gave up five earned runs and whiffed eight in
five innings, was optioned to Class AAA Columbus after the game as
the Yanks recalled Jay Tessmer, a reliever and a fresh arm, from
Columbus. The loss to the hardly imposing Jeff Juden and the
post-game queries caused Torre to realize the perception of his
team had changed, even if it is only temporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, all of a sudden, the questions aren't about who we're
going to play in the World Series,'' Torre said. ``Now we're
concerned about getting there. It's funny what a week does.
W-e-a-k, weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's locker was empty by the time Bush, a 25-year-old
rookie, and Jeter, a 24-year-old who was the rookie of the year in
1996, helped the Yankees exhale deeply and win the second game.
Things changed a little for the Yankees in the last week. They have
enjoyed such a superb season that everyone has expected storybook
endings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still human,'' Mike Stanton said. ``There's still only
one who walked on water who wasn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
