<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4469 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN     08-27 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KID'S GREAT CATCH SPOILED BY THIEVING JERK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``k'' editorial column file.) 
(EDITORS: Dennis McCarthy is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily
News) 
By DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It should have been the kid's proudest moment. The
kind you take to bed with you and dream about over and over again
for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The catch. The glorious catch.
</P>
<P>
   A long foul ball hit by one of the Atlanta Braves during batting
practice at Dodger Stadium a few weeks ago, hurtling toward you
like it has your name written all over it.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of adults, teen-agers and small kids jockeying for
position along the foul line to make the catch, but the ball seems
to have eyes only for you.
</P>
<P>
   It flies by all the outstretched hands and lands smack-dab in
the middle of your glove. Ken Griffey Jr. never made a better
pressure catch.
</P>
<P>
   Your mom, who has been watching the whole scene from her seat,
jumps up and starts to cheer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great catch, Travis!'' Lisa Martin yells. ``Great catch,
son!''
</P>
<P>
   And you stand there beaming, like only a 12-year-old kid in love
with baseball can beam _ trying to pick your mom out of the crowd,
anxious to show her the ball you just caught at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   DODGER STADIUM! Not the neighborhood Little League or Pony
League field. Not the school yard or back yard. DODGER STADIUM!
</P>
<P>
   Your mom sees it first; then you feel it. The hand. The hand of
an adult reaching into your glove and yanking out the ball.
</P>
<P>
   You look up and see this big guy standing there smiling and
holding the ball up like he caught it, when he didn't. You did. But
you're only a kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, mister, that's my ball!'' you yell at him. ``I caught it
in my glove!''
</P>
<P>
   The guy looks at you and shrugs his shoulders. Tough luck, kid,
the look in his eyes says. You can't do anything about it. You're
only a kid.
</P>
<P>
   You couldn't see it, son, but your mom was sitting there stunned
at what she was witnessing, trying to figure out what to do.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing you know, she's standing there down by the foul
pole yelling something to you. What is it she's saying? You strain
to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, buddy, great catch!'' Lisa yells. ``I'm proud of you! I
saw you catch that ball!''
</P>
<P>
   And then turning and looking directly at the guy holding your
baseball, your mom yells out: ``Don't worry, son! The jerk who took
it from you will have to go home tonight and try to get to sleep
knowing he stole a baseball from a little boy!''
</P>
<P>
   The guy just looked at her and shrugged his shoulders again. The
best retort the jerk could come up with _ a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched the game, and a good game it was. But Travis just
wasn't himself,'' Lisa said. `` `Disappointed' sums it up.''
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be a big night for the kid.
</P>
<P>
   This game, these tickets, were a present from his mom for
graduating from sixth grade at his Simi Valley school in
neighboring Ventura County with good grades. He's been waiting for
this night for months.
</P>
<P>
   And along comes some jerk to steal his ball, his moment. When
his head hit the pillow later, the kid wouldn't be dreaming about
the catch _ he'd be dreaming about the jerk who stole the ball
right out of his glove.
</P>
<P>
   The kid took one more shot at salvaging the night, standing
vigil after the game by the fence where the Dodgers come out to
their cars _ hoping a few of them would sign the Dodger trading
cards he had in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   But again, the smaller kids were no match for the bigger jerks
who waited by the same fence when Dodger players Matt Luke, Eric
Karros and Eric Young stopped to sign autographs.
</P>
<P>
   Travis almost got close enough to get Young's signature on a
card, but the crush of people was just too much.
</P>
<P>
   One good push was all it took, Lisa says, and Young's trading
card flew out of her son's hand and landed on the ground, trampled
by dozens of feet.
</P>
<P>
   By the time a Dodger security guard retrieved the card on the
other side of the fence for the kid, Young was already in his car,
trying to get by a crush of older teens blocking his way out of the
parking lot _ almost demanding that he stop to sign more
autographs.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa had seen enough. ``Let's go,'' she finally said to her son,
telling him it was this kind of fan behavior that was the reason
more Dodger players didn't stop after a game to sign autographs _
the reason they needed security guards walking them to their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Tears welled up in her son's eyes, and he was angry as they
walked to their own car, Lisa says. Not at the Dodgers, who were
great, but at the adult bully who took his ball.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Dodgers and other ballclubs should think about having
a reserved section during batting practice strictly for kids
bringing their gloves to the park to catch fly balls _ no adults or
older teen-agers allowed.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, remember this, kid: The jerk stole your ball,
but he didn't steal the truth.
</P>
<P>
   You made the catch, kid. And a great catch it was.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 0132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0027 </DOCNO>
