<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINIELLA OUTBURST CAPS MARINERS' 71ST LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The most memorable moment of Wednesday's game
occurred just before Jeff Fassero's seventh complete game of the
season and sixth route-going defeat became official.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Piniella stole the show one out from the finish of a 5-3
Seattle loss to the Cleveland Indians before 43,091 fans who
witnessed one of the most animated displays of Piniella's
managerial career.
</P>
<P>
   Already angry because Russ Davis had been called out by second
base umpire Larry Barnett for running out of the basepath between
first and second bases in the ninth inning, Piniella returned to
the dugout unaware that he had been ejected.
</P>
<P>
   When he found out, Piniella returned to the field and didn't go
nearly as quietly as he had in his first visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my money's worth the second time,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella threw his cap on the ground, kicked at it and missed,
argued some more and finally, on his way back to the dugout, kicked
the hat five more times. He then picked it up and tossed it into
the stands.
</P>
<P>
   A fan tossed it back.
</P>
<P>
   And the Jacobs Field sellout crowd roared again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how anyone can find that many things to say,''
opposing manager Mike Hargrove said. ``It was a long (argument).''
</P>
<P>
   Long and entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hat looks good, but I'm not in the mood for fun,'' said
Piniella after the Mariners' ninth loss in 10 games against the
Indians this season. ``I respect the umpires and realize they have
a tough job to do. But at the same time, I have to defend my
team.''
</P>
<P>
   He defended Davis' right to elude a tag attempt by Indians
second baseman Enrique Wilson, who had fielded pinch-hitter Raul
Ibanez's grounder. Wilson missed Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it when (Barnett) told me I was out for
running out of the basepath,'' Davis said. ``It would have been
different if he had said I had been tagged, which I wasn't. I
didn't run out of the basepath, either. You could see my
footprints.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella saw them. And tried to show Barnett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran (Piniella) when he was pointing at the ground,'' Barnett
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was I supposed to do, point at the sky?'' Piniella
countered. ``My baserunner was running on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' footprints showed that he never left the infield dirt and
the rule says a runner has a 6-foot (3 feet on each side of the
imaginary baseline) leeway to avoid a tag.
</P>
<P>
   Davis thought he was within that boundary.
</P>
<P>
   Said Piniella, ``I wasn't trying to show up the umpire. I was
just showing him the footprints. You can't even talk to (the
umpires) anymore without getting ejected.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero can't do enough to get a victory.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander is winless since July 25 despite tossing three
complete games in his last six starts. He remains stuck on 10 wins,
to go with his 10 losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been pitching awfully well without much run support,''
pitching coach Stan Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have scored 15 runs in Fassero's six complete-game
losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you do?'' Fassero asked. ``I guess the only thing you
can do is have the lead in the eighth inning so we don't face the
other team's closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero had one-run leads in the second and third innings
Wednesday, but fell behind for good in the fifth when Manny Ramirez
continued his season-long assault on Seattle pitchers with a
two-run homer to left field, putting the Indians ahead, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's 32nd homer of the season, and seventh against the
Mariners, came immediately after Fassero botched a potential
inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   With one out and Kenny Lofton on first base, Omar Vizquel hit a
one-hopper back to Fassero. He clutched once and threw slightly
off-target to shorstop Alex Rodriguez, covering the base. The best
Rodriguez could do was come off the bag, make the catch and then
touch the base to force Lofton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I double-clutched and then tried to make a perfect throw,''
Fassero said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he tried to get a fastball in on Ramirez's hands. But the
ball got too much of the strike zone and the Indians right fielder
sent it high and deep.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second Cleveland homer of the game. First baseman
Richie Sexson, subbing for injured Jim Thome, hit a one-out homer
in the second inning, the first of his career-high four hits. He
also doubled twice and singled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit every kind of pitch I throw,'' Fassero said. ``But all
of them were down (in the strike zone). I told Jamie (Moyer) to
pitch him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer starts Thursday's series finale.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Piniella was ejected for the third time this season. ...
Winning pitcher Dave Burba ended a three-game losing streak and
improved to 2-0 against his former team. Mike Jackson, another
former Mariner, picked up his 33rd save. ... Six of the Mariners'
nine losses to the Indians have been by one or two runs. ... Edgar
Martinez had two hits, including his 25th homer. ... Second baseman
Joey Cora extended his hitting streak to 12 games with a
third-inning double. Rodriguez also doubled in the inning, but was
thrown out attempting to steal his 39th base. ... Pro golfer Mark
O'Meara, Ken Griffey Jr.'s friend and Florida neighbor, was among
the clubhouse visitors. He threw out the ceremonial first pitch,
wearing an Indians cap. ``Yeah,'' said Griffey, ``but he took it
off quickly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
