<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON TIGHT END LEADING BY EXAMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Reggie Davis came out of Southern California destined
to be a great rover back at the University of Washington. Then he
was going to be a great inside linebacker. Then a great outside
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was going to get it done at defensive end, and outside
linebacker again, and then at H-back.
</P>
<P>
   Now, facing his last season as a Husky, he is their starting
tight end, and it becomes clearer how his teammates voted the honor
of co-captain to a guy who had two receptions last season.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has made more whistlestops than a politician stumping for
the Iowa primary. Everywhere he's been, he's collected a few more
votes. There's no veteran among the Huskies who can say he doesn't
know Reggie Davis pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie Davis is one of the most responsible people I know,''
wide receiver Gerald Harris said. ``He does things the right way.
People on defense respect him. People on offense respect him.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' parents were in town for the first two-a-day workouts,
regular visitors to each practice. Those jaded by Davis' eclectic
history at Washington might have concluded they were here just to
make sure their son wasn't switched again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hoping he'd be on the defensive side,'' said his
mother, Pearlie, referring to his early UW days. ``But he's always
been someone who has tried to make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it will all come together for Davis, now in his fifth
season at Washington, a player who received eight votes among 10
possible in Best of the West voting when he came out of a small
high school in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Besides pleasing Davis no end, that would please at least one
woman on the UW campus who has seen Mark Bruener, Ernie Conwell and
Cam Cleeland pass through the program in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting my books at the bookstore,'' said Brock Huard,
the UW quarterback. ``One of the older gals in there said, `Why
aren't you guys throwing the ball to the tight end?'''
</P>
<P>
   Bruener had 34 catches his senior year. Conwell had 24 as a
senior, Cleeland 19 last season.
</P>
<P>
   Davis might surpass all of them. At 6-foot-3 and 230 pounds, he
will be a different kind of tight end than the
block-first-catch-later players who lately have been demanded at
Washington. He may be symbolic of an evolving offensive philosophy
at the UW: Set up the run with the pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see that happening,'' Davis said. ``Just from the way
things have been going (in practice), I think that's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For the longest time, it appeared it was never going to happen
for Davis. Players usually emerge because of practice repetitions,
and Davis was never anywhere long enough to do much other than say
sayonara. He even got a fleeting look at quarterback, one of his
high school positions.
</P>
<P>
   A devout Christian, he was tested more than once. So when he was
approached about filling Cleeland's role before spring practice _
albeit with the chance of putting a positive finish on a
peripatetic career _ he was less than wowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say I was happy with the decision, that would be a lie,''
Davis says. ``But I'd been taught to respect authority. The coaches
were put there by God and they know what they're doing. I do my
best to bite my tongue and do what they ask for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Tongue-biting wasn't always so easy, while the Husky coaches
fretted over what they saw as Davis' lack of instinct on defense.
Clarence Davis, his dad, says the weight of the whole parish at
Grace Brethren Church in Long Beach has been behind Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had all the people of our congregation praying for him,''
the senior Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis needed all of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the position changes, I thought, well, maybe they're
trying to tell me something,'' he said. ``I almost left a few
times. I started inquiring about other schools. My mom filled out
an application for another school.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when we did a whole lot of praying.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis concluded it was just another test of his faith. Maybe,
finally, it will be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's give him a chance to go out and prove what we think we
already know about this guy,'' offensive coordinator Scott Linehan
said. ``The best thing is, he runs. He's a 4.5 type of runner, and
for his size, that's moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might see us recruiting that kind of guy more. We wouldn't
ever turn down the Brueners and Conwells, but you can make a lot of
hay with guys who can stretch the field. Once you do that, you have
ways of getting the ball short.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll have that Shannon Sharpe-type ability,'' Huard
said. ``You put him one-on-one against a linebacker, and he's going
to win 10 out of 10 times.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis has sharpened his leadership skills as president of
Washington's 50-person student-athlete advisory council, a body
that voices athlete concerns to the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is asked whether athletes should be paid. The usually
flat-broke side of him says yes. The quixotic side says no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would taint the game,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   There remains some nobility to the game, he seemed to be saying.
No matter how it sometimes exasperates.
</P>
</TEXT>
