<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4491 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      08-27 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
There are some things you just don't count on happening twice in a
relatively short period of time.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chances are, lightning won't strike twice in the same place. You
won't win the lottery again. And good luck trying to run roughshod
over Braves pitcher John Smoltz twice in a three-month span.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had their way with the 1996 Cy Young Award winner
earlier this season, but Smoltz cleared his name Wednesday by
pitching the Atlanta Braves to a 6-2 victory before 32,651 at the
Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people forget that those guys (the heralded Braves
starters) are human, too,'' Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell said.
``You don't get to them very often, so when you do, you'd better
enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, you're not going to get very many
opportunities against Smoltz, and that was the case tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The setback snapped the Astros' five-game winning streak and
kept their magic number at 19.
</P>
<P>
   Their National League Central Division lead over the Cubs was
trimmed to 10{ games, and the Astros fell 3{ games behind San Diego
for the second-best record in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   The top record belongs to the Braves, and the reason was clear
Wednesday: pitching, pitching and more pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz held the Astros to one run in seven innings, and
relievers Rudy Seanez and Kerry Ligtenberg held the Astros in check
over the final two innings to secure the Braves' 88th victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an important game for me,'' said Smoltz, who improved
to 13-2. ``More so because I have to face them again Monday (in
Atlanta), and then again in the playoffs. This is the best I've
felt in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   There's something about the Astrodome that brings out the best
in Smoltz. He is 10-5 with a 2.94 career ERA in the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could take this place on the road with me,'' said
Smoltz, who allowed eight runs in four innings the last time he
faced the Astros. ``I don't know why, but I've always had success
here. They're a very good hitting team, but this is a pitcher's
park.''
</P>
<P>
   For a couple of innings, it appeared Wednesday's game might be a
pitchers' duel. Smoltz and the Astros' Sean Bergman retired the
side in order on their first two trips to the mound, and Bergman
got an out in the third before the Braves finally got a baserunner
_ with some help.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Graffanino reached on an error by shortstop Tim Bogar,
whose throw sailed over Bagwell's head at first base. Graffanino
scored on a single by Walt Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing,'' said Bogar, whose strength is his
fielding. ``That's all I can say. It's an easy play, and I have to
make that play every time. Everything snowballed from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make mistakes like that against good pitchers like
Smoltz. Bergy didn't pitch that badly. We didn't help him at all.
If we catch the ball and make the plays, things might have been
different.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros committed three errors and weren't alert on the bases
as they allowed the Braves to tie the season series at three wins
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tomorrow off, and it looked like we took today off,''
Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``This wasn't one of our better
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Braves were dazzling in the field _ particularly
center fielder Andruw Jones, who made one highlight-reel catch
after another in the two-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made more great catches in one year than I've seen in
probably 10 years,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said. ``He's the best
in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' run in the third was unearned, but Bergman had only
himself to blame for Atlanta's three-run fourth.
</P>
<P>
   After notching two quick outs, Bergman gave up a single to Ryan
Klesko and a two-run homer to Javy Lopez on a 1-0 pitch that caught
way too much of the strike zone. Graffanino singled home Jones to
give the Braves a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to go outside with a fastball, and it came right down
the middle,'' catcher Tony Eusebio said of the home-run pitch. ``If
you make a mistake to Javy Lopez, you're going to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored on Carl Everett's two-out RBI triple in the
fourth, but the Braves took aim at Bergman again in the sixth on
Jones' RBI double.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman, who was replaced by Doug Henry in the sixth, allowed
five runs (four earned) on eight hits and a walk. It was the most
runs he has allowed in his last six starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wasn't hitting his spots,'' Eusebio said.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie righthander Scott Elarton worked the final two innings
for the Astros, allowing a run in the ninth on a double by Ozzie
Guillen. The Astros made their usual ninth-inning stand, scoring
once, but it wasn't nearly enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
