<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-A'S-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS UNLOADS ON A'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ One of the things you have to like about the Red Sox is
that they know how to win. They know the value of good pitching,
defense, and timely hitting. They may stagger but they seldom beat
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's 7-4 victory over the Oakland Athletics before
26,379 at Fenway Park is a good example. The Sox blew a 4-1 lead
but pulled together the right combination to hand the West Coast
visitors their ninth defeat in 10 meetings this year. The Sox made
two costly errors, one by Nomar Garciaparra and the other by Jim
Corsi, along with a passed ball by Scott Hatteberg. Yet, it didn't
cost them a game.
</P>
<P>
   Boston collected 10 hits, the most important a single with the
bases loaded in the eighth inning by Darren Lewis that broke a 4-4
tie. It gave the Red Sox their third straight win as they protect
their lead in the American League wild-card race. They remained
nine games ahead of Texas and moved 10 in front of Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis earned the spotlight with his second game-winner in as
many nights. In Tuesday's series opener, he hit a solo home run in
the seventh inning to give the Sox a 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a team victory. Bret Saberhagen had his seventh
no-decision in nine games, but he contributed to the victory, as
did Dennis Eckersley, Corsi, John Wasdin, and closer Tom Gordon.
Gordon got his league-leading 38th save.
</P>
<P>
   Corsi, however, suffered a groin pull in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams used 14 of his 15 available players; only
Orlando Merced did not play. And the last three runs were scored by
pinch runners Damon Buford and Donnie Sadler and pinch hitter Jason
Varitek, illustrating the Sox' philosophy of staying close and
using whoever is needed to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to be aggressive,'' Lewis said regarding his
eighth-inning single with one out. Boston had filled the bases
against losing pitcher Tim Worrell (2-7) on a single by Mike
Stanley, a sacrifice by Darren Bragg, and back-to-back walks to
Hatteberg and Varitek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up and saw that the infield was in,'' said Lewis.
``So I looked for a good pitch to hit and I got one. I love playing
in Fenway Park. For me it's such a good place to hit. There is
plenty of room in right field, and that's really where I like to
hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a team that doesn't make a lot of mistakes, and really
that's the key to our season. You keep mistakes to a minimum. You
help your pitchers out so that they don't have to throw a lot of
extra pitches. All of this makes it easier for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It should have been an easier night for Saberhagen, who threw
only 62 pitches in the first five innings and seemed to be on a
roll. It took an error on a grounder by Rickey Henderson, a double
by Bip Roberts, and a ground out to put him in a 1-0 hole in the
first. But all seemed well when Boston rallied for three runs in
the second inning and made it a 4-1 game in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   It changed in the sixth inning, so quickly the Sox bullpen could
not get there fast enough. Saberhagen dug a hole for himself. With
one out, he gave up consecutive singles to Matt Stairs and Ben
Grieve and a walk to second baseman Scott Spiezio. Two runs scored
on a funky ground-rule double by Miguel Tejada, making it 4-3. The
ball traveled only 150 feet down the line before being fielded by a
fan, but it was enough to send Saberhagen to the showers after only
85 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement was Eckersley, who had the misfortune of a
passed ball by Hatteberg on an 0-2 pitch. Saberhagen had pitched
well but had nothing to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that gets under my skin is that I fell behind
on Tejada and had to come in with fastballs,'' said Saberhagen. ``I
got the ball in under his hands, but he hits the carom for a
double. They didn't hit the ball great. But they did what they had
to do to stay in the game. So did we.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen (11-6) says he's not down on himself, even if the
victories are getting harder to come by. ``I'd like to be getting
some wins,'' he said. ``But I'm happy the way I'm throwing the
ball. The team is winning and you look at the scoreboard and
Baltimore is getting beat. You're feeling good. The bottom line is
that if the team wins and you have contributed, you feel like
you're a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a team game, reminds Mo Vaughn. ``First and foremost,'' he
said, ``Bret threw well and deserved to get a win tonight. Any time
we get good pitching like that and have good offense and defense,
the main thing you have to do is play your game. I've become a
believer of this. That's what happened tonight in Darren Lewis. If
we keep ourselves in it, we got a chance to win the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
