u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-GORDON-BOS     08-27 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GORDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON HAS BEEN ONE TRUE CONSTANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tom Gordon says his intent and focus have always been
the same. It's never wavered once this season. Whether it was his
first save opportunity or, as was the case in Wednesday night's 7-4
victory over the Oakland A's, his American League-leading 38th
save.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox closer has always delivered with the same
single-minded determination. Gordon was a model of efficiency when
he started the ninth in relief of eventual winner John Wasdin (6-4)
and got his 38th save (out of 39 opportunities) by throwing just 10
pitches, eight for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Three up. Three out. End of inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I gave, I had. And everything I had, I gave,'' said
Gordon, who had no use, really, for the bulky ice pack bandaged on
his right shoulder after he recorded his 35th consecutive save, the
longest current streak in the major leagues. ``I try to take that
focus into every game. That's my approach, and it's the same for me
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   How can he so blithely dismiss the impressive numbers he is
putting up in this All-Star season? Does he not realize he needs
just three more saves to pass Jeff Reardon (40 saves, 1991) as
Boston's saves leader?
</P>
<P>
   ``I see (the numbers), but I haven't really set any goals,''
Gordon said. ``The only thing I've tried to focus on, like I said
earlier in spring training, was to stay healthy and be able to go
out there and help my team win, regardless the situation.
Fortunately for me, there's been a lot of good situations and I've
been able to execute well.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't try to do anything different from what I've done
all year. I take the same approach that I took in spring training
and that's just to be me. And a lot of good things are happening.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gordon intimated there was one goal he did want to achieve
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only real personal thing I've thought about is the World
Series,'' he said. ``I've really thought about it and tried to
picture myself in that game, but that's about it. I don't try to
get too ahead of myself. I try to stay on an even keel and do what
I can to help this team win.''
</P>
<P>
   When Darren Lewis broke a 4-4 tie in the eighth by driving a
ball up the middle to score a pair of runs, it appeared to be all
Gordon needed to close the door on the A's, the same team he faced
when he first moved to the bullpen last Aug. 20, recording a save
in a 5-4 decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Flash has an opportunity to come in and close ballgames,
it doesn't matter if we have one run or two runs, we have the
confidence in him that he's going to get the job done,'' said
Lewis. ``He's been doing it all year. Tonight, he was outstanding
and got ahead right away and threw strikes. Actually, we got him a
little cushion so he could relax a little bit and not have to be on
pins and needles.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon didn't seem to have any anxiety, judging from the
workmanlike manner in which he retired the top of Oakland's lineup.
He got Rickey Henderson to line to second, Bip Roberts to fly to
left, and Jason Giambi to strike out swinging on a game-ending 1-2
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to do whatever I can to help this team be a winning
team,'' Gordon said. ``I'm not going to change anything, but I'm
going to take every game _ from the first game to the very last
game of the season, it doesn't matter _ and do everything I can to
stay consistent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
