<HEADER>
A4538 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     08-27 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG BAILS OUT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers wanted to change their
look. Into a winner they hoped.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly their most reliable pitcher, closer Jeff Shaw is
looking a lot like Todd Worrell.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, who gave up two ninth-inning home runs in Atlanta to end
the road trip, allowed two ninth-inning runs Wednesday night. But
it was Eric Young who picked up the save with a game-winning home
run in the bottom of the ninth that gave the Dodgers a 4-3 victory
over the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the ninth, Young hit a 1-2 pitch into the
right-field stands off left-hander Steve Kline. It was Young's
fifth homer of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' Young said. ``Bottom line is we need wins
right now. And it is great that we were able to pick up Jeff
tonight. He has been doing that for us since he got here. That's
what teams do. That's what we need to do.''The Dodgers had juggled
their lineup, puttng Eric Karros into the cleanup spot, and he
responded with a sixth-inning homer. Raul Mondesi, dropped from
third to fifth, appeared to add an insurance run when he singled
home Trenidad Hubbard in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   But a couple of Valley products had other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Fullmer of Montclair Prep in Van Nuys opened the ninth with
double off Karros' glove and scored on a single by Shane Andrews.
Shaw took over and gave up an RBI single to Ryan McGuire, who
attended El Camino Real High School and UCLA, that tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   Despite blowing his eighth save opportunity of the season, Shaw
(3-6) wound up the winning pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw some pitches I thought were strikes that should have
gotten us out of the game,'' Shaw said. ``(Home plate umpire) Joe
West is a veteran and he wasn't givng the inside pitch. But I'm not
frustrated with the way I threw.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' victory hardly spoiled a homecoming for Fullmer,
the Expos' first baseman who also homered in the fourth against
Park.
</P>
<P>
   But it was ninth that the Expos will remember.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw took over after the single by Andrews. Terry Jones pinch
ran and raced to second on Shaw's wild pick off throw.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Widger popped out to first with Jones running from second,
and the Dodgers nearly got an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   They had to settle for Shaw putting away pinch hitter Bob
Henley. On a 1-2 count, Shaw threw a fastball down and in and the
crowd of 34,039 thought the game was over. Henley fouled off four
more pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Another close call by home-plate umpire Joe West made the count
3-2, and Henley walked on a breaking ball in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up pinch hitter McGuire, who delivered.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was Park's second straight and 10th in his last 11
decisions. It also kept the Dodgers seven games back in the
wild-card race to the New York Mets, who play a four-game series
here this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were coming off a 4-3 victory Tuesday night, and
with a big four-game series this weekend with Mike Piazza and the
wild-card-leading New York Mets, they wanted to establish some
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Expos right-hander Carl Pavano, who defeated the Dodgers 5-1 on
Aug. 5, wasn't as sharp this time and immediately got into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Young opened with an infield single, stole second and moved
to third on an infield out. Sheffield followed with a sharp single
to right to give the Dodgers a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Pavano settled down until Karros' homer in the sixth. But his
young infield made it difficult, committing two throwing errors.
One belonged to former Dodgers second baseman Wilton Guerrero, who
threw away Trenidad Hubbard's potential inning-ending double play
grounder in the third.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheffield popped to third to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos did little against Park, who was coming off a 5-1
victory last Friday in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Fullmer was 2 for 19 on the Expos' last home stand but came in
with a solid .279 average, 10 homers and 60 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Park threw him a fastball on 2-1 and Fullmer drove into the
stands in left-center.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd went silent, except for cheering from the seats
beneath the press box. Fullmer's parents, Judy and Marv, his grand
parents and an aunt were at the game.
</P>
<P>
   They had come to a lot of games here, but never one so special.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is excitng but very nerve racking ,'' said Fullmer's
mother. ``It is really kind of neat, because we have been
season-ticket holders here since he was two. He's grown upcoming to
this ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   The family has seen Fullmer play a lot this season, traveling
twice to San Francisco and once in Montreal, Boston, Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time since he's been playing ball, he's here,''
Judy said after the home run. ``It's nice to see him play here.
When he was in the minor leagues, he played all his games on the
East Coast, never once making it West of the Mississippi.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 0234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 05:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4653 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEVIUS-NEVIUS-SFCHRON     08-27 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEVIUS-NEVIUS-SFCHRON-BASEBALL&AMP;DRUGS </SLUG>
  
 `JUST SAY NO' NOT ENOUGH FOR BASEBALL  &HT;     By C.W. NEVIUS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Well, you'd have to think this is not the kind of national news
story Major League Baseball was hoping to get out of Mark McGwire.
In response to reports that McGwire is taking _ and making no
secret of it _ the testosterone-producing pill androstenedione,
officials in baseball and the players' union are calling on doctors
to ``gather information'' on performance-enhancing pills.
<P>
   Let's hope they realize what they are doing, because this is
going to open a major-league can of worms.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, baseball's drug testing procedure could use some
revamping. It is a relic from the days of widespread, embarrassing
recreational drug use. The official drug policy says the league is
testing for ``the following controlled substances: cocaine,
marijuana, amphetamines, opiates and phencyclidine (PCP).''
</P>
<P>
   There is a vague reference to a ``prohibition ... to all illegal
drugs and controlled substances, including steroids,'' but the
reality is that, as the drug policy states later, ``Major League
players are not subject to unannounced testing for illegal drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gary Wadler, who co-wrote the book ``Drug and the Athlete,''
and is a clinical associate professor of medicine at Cornell
University, says baseball is not the only sport with its head in
the sand regarding muscle-building drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the NBA,'' he says. ``There is no testing for anabolic
steroids at all. I can't believe that. The thing about steroids is
that they keep the body from breaking down. With the NBA's
demanding schedule, steroids would be obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   But in almost every case in which a drug-testing program is put
into place, it is in reaction to a large public outcry _ hello Mr.
McGwire. And that's where the fun begins.
</P>
<P>
   First, as Dr. Wadler says, ``the stark reality of this is that
(a drug policy) is a negotiated thing.'' The policy is an agreement
between the leagues and the players' unions. The NBA doesn't even
test for marijuana, which has become one of the sticking points in
the lockout. Issues of privacy, and the prying into what someone
does in his private life _ legal or not _ are open for debate.
</P>
<P>
   But drugs that help players become stronger and faster change
the game. If Ben Johnson lost his 1988 Olympic gold medal because
he was using steroids, should McGwire at least have an asterisk
next to his name in the record book if it can be proved that he was
using performance drugs if he breaks the home run record?
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Dr. Wadler puts it, ``(Former world record-holding shot
putter) Randy Barnes has to be wondering, `How come (McGwire) is a
national hero, and I'm banned for life?'''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wadler then answers his own question. The reason is that
Barnes was caught using drugs that were clearly forbidden by track
and field. McGwire is simply taking advantage of a loophole large
enough for a 260-pound slugger to walk through.
</P>
<P>
   Understand, despite denials from the McGwire camp, Dr. Wadler
has no doubts McGwire's use of androstenedione is
performance-enhancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Androstenedione is testosterone waiting to happen,'' Dr.
Wadler says. ``It is itself a steroid by becoming testosterone,
which is a banned substance, in the body.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's where we enter a gray area. Everyone has testosterone
in his or her body. The question is how much? And what about
players who use ``andro'' or other supplements to ``mask'' strength
gains from actual anabolic steroids. Clearly, this is not an exact
science.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the testing itself. A good example is the NFL's first
attempt at a testing program years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The league announced that it would test football players each
year at training camp. In the first year, they were delighted to
hear that they only caught half a dozen players with drugs in their
system. Meanwhile, those who knew that it only takes 28 days for
the drugs to vanish from the body were barely able to contain their
snickers.
</P>
<P>
   As Dr. Wadler said on The Today Show at the time, ``That wasn't
a drug test, it was an IQ test.'' And those six flunked.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agrees that the only way to catch offenders is, as Dr.
Wadler says ``out of competition, random testing.'' After all, if
baseball players are bulking up with steroids, they aren't doing it
during the season, it is happening during their workouts over the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   But does baseball want to get involved in that sort of hassle?
First, you have to locate players in the off-season, get them to a
testing site, and create an enforcement team that would supervise
the tests. These tests would have to be ``observed samples,'' of
course, meaning that someone would have to stand there and watch
while these sports superstars fill up the urine cup.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the really bad news. What if you actually
start catching people? Consider the sports that have done the most
to crack down on performance drugs _ swimming and track and field.
Each has a comprehensive drug program, iron-clad punishment and
wide-ranging powers.
</P>
<P>
   And what have they gained for their efforts? A perception from
the public that these sports are filled with cheaters, that almost
everyone is using drugs, and that the best in the sport aren't
getting caught.
</P>
<P>
   It may be better to be blissfully ignorant, watching the soaring
home runs, rather than worrying about how the muscles that
propelled them were created. Up until now baseball's
muscle-building drug policy was simple: don't ask, don't tell.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball should change its performance drug policy. But
remember, if it does, the days of the easy answers are finished.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
