<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4884 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DENTIST-RC28-COX     08-27 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENTIST-RC28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dentist's hobby takes flight - spans 25 years
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Dr. Steven Harris' hands aren't
earning him a living in his West Palm Beach dentistry practice,
they're usually involved with his hobby du jour _ including but not
limited to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Rallying his Miata with his wife, Karen
</P>
<P>
   _ Target shooting with his grown daughters, April and Jennifer
</P>
<P>
   _ Banjoing by himself (he notes a distinction between his
banjoing and actual music)
</P>
<P>
   Harris' hobbies come and go _ the computer, the cameras and,
lately, the golf obsession. But these amusements, the family
agrees, are mere dalliances beside the sustaining passions of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   One of those passions sidles up to him on the sofa and says,
``You can tell him about your other love.'' The speaker would be
Karen, 45, his wife and colleague at the office. As she snuggles
under his arm, he leans into her, an old dating trick to maximize
body contact. They luxuriate in the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's confession time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an RC modeler,'' Harris, 52, declares without remorse. ``I
build and fly radio-control aircraft. I'm a member of the Palm
Beach Aero Club. We fly them at the fairgrounds and at a field in
Stuart.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen explains: ``We came into his life 25 years ago in Phoenix,
when he was in the Air Force. I was a dental assistant in town. We
met on the base when I came to the clinic.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve happened to pass through her office. Then he happened to
pass three or four more times. After about the fifth
reconnaissance, Karen decided that her future husband was pretty
cute for a mentally deficient mute, and asked ``What are you doing
tonight?''
</P>
<P>
   Improvising brilliantly, the Air Force captain replied: ``Taking
you out to dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, in the final months of his service
commitment, when Harris was planning a move to South Florida to
open a practice near family members, he was smitten with his other
love.
</P>
<P>
   ``A patient asked to borrow one of my dental burrs,'' he said.
``He needed it for detail work on one of his radio-control
models.''
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued, Steve visited the base RC aero club and fell hard for
his mistress, remote-control planes.
</P>
<P>
   As a youngster, in the days before radio-controlled free flight,
Steve had built gasoline-powered models, when the airplane was
flown in a tight circle by wire.
</P>
<P>
   But here was pure flight, a pilot with a stick with radio
controls commanding ailerons, elevators, rudders, throttles, even
landing gear.
</P>
<P>
   And something more: These models were the devil to build _
exquisite in detail, breathtaking in finish and ruinously
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The radio itself cost $450, a princely sum in the 1970s. A scale
model of a fighter or a biplane with scaled-down but comparable
performance abilities could cost hundreds more and require 500
hours to build.
</P>
<P>
   And consider: a single mistake at the controls could reduce a
model to smoldering kindling.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about your high-maintenance mistresses. How could he
resist?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been very good with my hands,'' says Steve,
recalling how he built his first plane _ a trainer _ for $26, and
got a radio at half-price by building it himself. ``And,'' he adds,
``I had always wanted to fly.''
</P>
<P>
   And these airplanes fly _ taxiing, taking off, climbing,
rolling, looping, diving and landing _ all at the command of a
pilot who must orchestrate throttle, ailerons and elevator input
from the ground.
</P>
<P>
   That plane, he understood at once, is not balsa and paint up
there. It is you. If it crashes, you crash. Le petite mort
flambeau. The small death, flames included.
</P>
<P>
   Since building and learning to fly that first model, he has
built dozens of ever more elaborate models, each of astonishing
fidelity to their full-scale counterparts. They dangle from his
garage ceiling and grace his dentistry office, frozen in flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are toys,'' he admits, ``but toys that you can play with
after you've built them.''
</P>
<P>
   He has also dabbled in radio-controlled cars, boats and
motorcycles but quickly tired of them. After all, RC cars and
boats, when you get down to it, scoot. Model airplanes fly, and
they fly spectacularly.
</P>
<P>
   The visitor asks the obvious question: ``Don't you want to
graduate to airplanes you can fly from the inside?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, of course, he admits. He has logged stick time co-piloting
friends' airplanes, and the truth? No big thrill.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, RC piloting skills translate nicely to big airplanes.
Smiling now, he notes that the reverse is not true. But for RC
pilots, who learn flight control standing in a field with a radio
control box in his hands, remote control eventually becomes innate
control, an unconscious melding of mind and model.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized there came a time that I was no longer thinking
`left' or `right,' '' he says. ``I was just willing the airplane to
do what I wanted it to do. I was one with the airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   And his wife understands this and does not begrudge the Saturday
and Sunday mornings spent at airfields, the untold hours working in
his garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work side by side in the office,'' she explains. ``Every
morning, we get up at 5 and go to the spa and work out. We have the
Miata Club, and I have my church activities and my crafts.''
</P>
<P>
   They exchange smiles, and I recall a line from a movie in which
a father counsels his daughter on the eve of her marriage not to
smother her husband but to ``let there be spaces in your
togetherness.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Karen repeats a story they like to tell about the RC
modeler who insisted that his wife come out to the airfield to
watch him fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `OK, I'll spend an afternoon watching you fly toy
airplanes if you'll spend an afternoon watching me sew.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
