<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Whipping politicians naked down the street
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At one of those Renaissance Weekends later famous because an
obscure governor of Arkansas had been a regular, I found myself on
a panel with Bill Clinton discussing the increasing intrusions into
the personal lives of politicians. Was the ventilation a good or a
bad thing or just, well, you know: a thing?
</P>
<P>
   Did this transparency of political lives scare off good
candidates (while not deterring scalawags, who are as a class
undeterrable) or did it produce honest and open candidates, and if
a bit of both results, which way was the lean?
</P>
<P>
   The political scientists and politicians hemmed and hawed in the
manner of those disciplines, finding strengths and weaknesses in
the evolving change, assets and liabilities, yin and yang, and
generally nudged one another toward the thunderous conclusion that
the situation would bear watching.
</P>
<P>
   I, with the subtle balance and reticent wisdom for which I am
known, held that as far as I was concerned, so the electorate might
at least have one chance in a thousand of not being scammed,
politicians _ I believe my exact words were, ``Politicians should
be whipped naked down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   I wish to change my testimony.
</P>
<P>
   We have now watched Clinton himself whipped naked down the
street. It is not a pretty sight and we, the electorate, are no
better off for it, nor is it likely the effect will be anything but
repulsive to class candidates, thus opening exciting new
opportunities for a career in politics to the sociopaths who figure
they can always get away with it, whatever ``it'' is.
</P>
<P>
   And, worse, if current leaks from the operations of Kenneth
``The Sieve'' Starr can be credited, the Torquemada of the Tidal
Basin means to treat us to details of the president's sexual
misadventures that are none of our business, or of Starr's, for
that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, yes, I know: Only folks with something to hide should fear
having a special prosecutor reach down their throats and jerk them
inside out. But the truth is that those few among us who have
nothing to hide are better candidates for canonization than for
rough-and-ready politics.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I should know about politicians:
</P>
<P>
   _ The source of every penny contributed to their campaigns.
Congressional Republicans pushing for faster reporting of that have
a good idea, though not as the substitute for broad
campaign-funding reform they mean it to be.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether they carry any debilitating or mortal disease. Their
physician's witness will do. I don't need to muck about in their
medical records.
</P>
<P>
   _ The major sources, but not the details, of their outside
income or accumulated wealth. I don't need to second-guess their
tax returns. If they've been up to something, IRS will have them in
court for all to see.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest, I don't know how to end the Internet- and
cable-driven scramble into politicians' personal lives, except to
say that if voters become sufficiently repelled or simply jaded,
the market for gratuitous tattling will dry up. Until then, the
least we can do is begin to recognize that our democracy can't
function if politicians can last no longer than it takes for
ruthless malevolence and giddy iconoclasm to tear them down.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: Teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
