<HEADER>
A4891 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LISCENSE-TAGS27-COX     08-27 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LISCENSE-TAGS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Car owners use license plates to ID themselves
 &HT;    By Kevin Tankersley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Mary Lou Janke's first grandchild, Brent Sykora, was
learning to talk, he just couldn't pronounce Granny, which is what
Janke wanted him to call her. He could say Grammy, and that evolved
into Gween. When Sykora was about 4, he started calling his
grandmother Dween.
</P>
<P>
   That name stuck, and Janke applied for a personalized, or
vanity, license plate that read DWEEN. That was about 20 years ago.
Sykora is now 23 and has two siblings: Blake, 19; and Shelley, 14.
Today, in honor of the three grandchildren, Janke's plate says
DWEEN 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why this one called me Dween Dween,'' Janke said,
lightly tapping Brent with her cane. ``This one came along'' _
pointing at Blake _ ``and made it Dween 2.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's 'Hey Dween,' or 'Dweenster.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The plate began its life on an orange pickup truck, moved to a
gray Ford LTD, and then to its current home on the bumpers of a
blue Ford Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   The plate has brought Janke luck on at least three occasions.
Several years back, the radio station formerly known as KJNE, at
the 102.5 position on the dial, held a contest where listeners
would send in their license plate numbers and then listen to the
station, hoping to hear their plate number announced. Dween won
$1,025 in that contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked to have fainted'' when she won, Janke said. Later on
she also won $102.50 and then $10.25, all from the same station. n
n n
</P>
<P>
   Like Mary Lou Janke, Morris and Lucy Mebane have grandchildren
to thank for their license plate, at least partially.
</P>
<P>
   When Morris, who owned Tri-Cities Pharmacy in Woodway for 18
years, and his son John were in business together, they had to
decide what the son would call the father during working hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want to call his dad `Daddy' when working, so he
just referred to him as Mo,'' Lucy Mebane said. John's children
picked up on that.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Mebane said several of her friends call her Luce, so when
they decided, in 1985 or '86, to apply for a vanity license plate
for their 1984 Honda Accord, MOLUCE was a natural. The plate is
still on an Accord, though it's now a 1998 model they recently
purchased.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of fun with the plate,'' Lucy Mebane said.
``We had no trouble getting it.'' n n n
</P>
<P>
   Vickie McCrary claims she helped finance the construction of the
Waco Police Department station at Fourth Street and Waco Drive. It
seems she was issued more than her share of speeding tickets while
driving a series of cars, each with the license plate GET ME. The
plate has been on every car she has owned, since 1972. It's
currently on a Chevrolet Iroc Z28 Camaro. n n n
</P>
<P>
   Rick Wegwerth has been asked over the years what the S in his
license plate S SKIER stands for? Snow? Super? Sorry?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the S is for slalom, the act of skiing with only one
ski. Using a single ski, instead of the usual two-ski setup, allows
a skier to make sharper cuts, almost in a zigzag fashion, which
makes for a more intense skiing experience.
</P>
<P>
   S SKIER is attached to a red Jeep Cherokee that Wegwerth's wife,
Arlene, drives. They usually tote their boat, a Ski Supreme, to
Tradinghouse Lake, where the family does its skiing.
</P>
<P>
   Wegwerth has taught his two daughters _ Casidy, 8, and Emory, 6
_ to ski. While Emory has been skiing for about a year, Casidy
learned when she was 3. Arlene Wegwerth learned to ski after she
met Rick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't play golf'' or have other hobbies, Wegwerth said.
``All four of us like to ski.''
</P>
<P>
   Wegwerth has had the S SKIER plate for 20 years. It cost an
extra $10 annually in 1978 to register the plates. The price
gradually rose until it cost close to $100 a year for vanity
plates. That's when Wegwerth came close to giving up his set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost dropped it,'' he said, but, like Mary Lou Janke, he
won $120 in a radio contest. The plates paid for themselves that
year, so Wegwerth held on to them.
</P>
<P>
   If Eb Morrow ever forgets his dog's name, he can just look at
the license plate on his Mercury Sable station wagon. The plate
reads GAZEBO. He didn't get the plate for the dog however; he named
the dog after the plate.
</P>
<P>
   In the yard of Morrow's North Waco home stands a large gazebo.
Atop the gazebo is a turret from the old Lyons-Adelman house, which
stood on the land where Standard Hat Works now exists. The house
was designed by W.W. Lamour, an early Waco architect who also
designed the Cameron House ``and any number of old, old homes that
were in town,'' Morrow said.
</P>
<P>
   Morrow moved into his home, which was built in 1903, in 1964,
and added the gazebo when he remodeled.
</P>
<P>
   After Morrow obtained the plate, he purchased his dog, a Vizsla,
a Hungarian pointer retriever breed, and named him Gazebo, as well.
</P>
<P>
   If one were to pull up behind Steve McClain's red Chevrolet van,
the license plate might suggest the driver has divided loyalties.
The plate reads ARK HOG; obviously an Arkansas Razorback fan is
aboard. However, in the middle of the plate is an orange silhouette
of a Longhorn, as in a University of Texas Longhorn. In the days of
the old Southwest Conference, 'Horns and Hogs did not coexist
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother, my aunt and uncles, they all hated the
University of Texas with a passion,'' said McClain, who was the
first person on either side of his family not born in Arkansas. ``I
was raised properly, to call the Hogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite McClain's love for the Razorbacks, a football
scholarship lured him to Blinn Junior College and then to Stephen
F. Austin State University.
</P>
<P>
   But what about that Longhorn sticker?
</P>
<P>
   McClain's older daughter Kacie is on her way to Austin to become
a freshman member of the Longhorn band. It was the band, in fact,
that attracted her to the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where she's always wanted to go,'' her father said.
</P>
<P>
   McClain, manager of Barry's Coffee Company, first had the ARK
HOG plate on a Pontiac Bonneville about 20 years ago. Since then
it's been on a GMC Jimmy and a Jeep Cherokee before finding a home
on the bright red van. Red just happens to be one of the school
colors of the University of Arkansas. Was that a factor in picking
out this particular van?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' McClain admits. ``It was just the mood of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
