<HEADER>
A4892 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PSYCHOLOGY-COLUMN27-C     08-27 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHOLOGY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Some aims of psychotherapy
 &HT;    By Hap LeCrone
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Psychotherapy is generally thought of as a verbal rather than
medicinal approach to helping individuals with psychological
difficulties. In clinical practice, psychotherapy and medication
are often used together to help treat individuals with emotional
difficulties, such as depression and anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the aims of psychotherapy include assisting individuals
with:
</P>
<P>
   n Gaining insight into the reasons behind their unhappiness.
</P>
<P>
   n Changing self-destructive behaviors, including substance
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   n Difficulties in relationships.
</P>
<P>
   n Communication problems.
</P>
<P>
   n How the individual's past relates to his or her current
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   n Unresolved conflicts with parents and/or siblings.
</P>
<P>
   n Distortions in perceptual and cognitive processes resulting in
faulty thought patterns.
</P>
<P>
   n Adjustments due to disabilities or handicaps.
</P>
<P>
   n Health-related issues caused by psychological problems.
</P>
<P>
   There are many types of psychotherapy employed in clinical
practice. Following are some examples:
</P>
<P>
   Family therapy _ A form of therapy treating the whole family.
This approach views the individual as part of a system, and
counseling is focused on the entire system, which includes the
members of the family and the family's environment.
</P>
<P>
   Cognitive-behavior therapy _ The focus of this approach is to
help individuals identify and change distorted perceptions of
themselves and the world around them. Focus includes past, present
and future and helps individuals challenge their unrealistic,
irrational and erroneous beliefs about their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Client-centered therapy _ Often referred to as non-directive
therapy, this type of therapy removes the helping person from the
role of giving much direction and advice and instead lets their
empathi-- and non-judgmental understanding assist in the process of
healthy change.
</P>
<P>
   Psychoanalysis _ A form of therapy in which the psychotherapist
encourages the exploration of deeper, unconscious thoughts and
experiences from childhood. This form of therapy often extends over
months or even years.
</P>
<P>
   Couple's therapy _ Focuses on the relationship and communication
patterns between partners.
</P>
<P>
   Mental health care providers trained to provide psychotherapy
include psychiatrists, psycholog hiatric nurses, psychiatric social
workers and pastoral counselors. Referrals to a psychotherapist
often come from physicians, ministers and educators.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling comfortable with the therapist is essential. An open and
trusting relationship is one of the most important elements in the
psychotherapeutic process.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hap LeCrone is a Waco clinical psychologist. His column
appears Sunday in the Tribune-Herald. If you have questions or
topics you would like Dr. LeCrone to discuss, write him at P.O. Box
7845, Waco, Texas 76714 or e-mail him at hlecronejuno. com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
