<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yearwood's latest slick, smart
 &HT;    By Carl Hoover
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service Waco Tribune-Herald
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Where Your Road Leads, Trisha Yearwood sticks to what's made
her one of Nashville's top female performers: upbeat songs and slow
ballads that showcase her satin-smooth alto.
</P>
<P>
   Her latest album shows one of the perks of success: slick, smart
production values, with songs from top-drawer writers like Jamie
O'Hara, Don Schlitz, Gordon Kennedy, Diane Warren, even Carole
King.
</P>
<P>
   It's listenable, as all of Yearwood's seven albums have been,
but mainstream and safe, with enough country flourishes like an
occasional accent, steel guitar twang or mandolin/fiddle lick to
keep critics from labeling it a pure pop-rock album.
</P>
<P>
   Where Your Road Leads finds its energy in foot-tappers like
``Powerful Thing,'' ``That Ain't The Way I Heard It'' and ``There
Goes My Baby.'' What's missing are the knock-dead ballads from
earlier albums, haunting songs like ``A Bus To St. Paul'' or ``The
Song Remains The Same'' that lingered with the listener long after
the CD finished spinning.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing in Where Your Road Leads with that staying power
or quicksilver magic. Sure, ``There Goes My Baby'' has a catchy
hook, ``That Ain't the Way I Heard It'' offers an insistent
backbeat and the dark, dreamy ``Love Wouldn't Lie To Me'' has a
barbed surprise in its chorus.
</P>
<P>
   But one wishes Yearwood would have been a little more
adventurous in her song selection, with something more daring or
different than the predictable here.
</P>
<P>
   The album's biggest misstep, and probably its most successful
single, is her duet with Garth Brooks, ``Where Your Road Leads.''
</P>
<P>
   She knocks it out like a power ballad, showing the muscle behind
her voice, but the backing arrangement suffers from overkill:
strings and a choir. All this for _ a love song?
</P>
<P>
   One wishes Yearwood enough success from this album to try
something new next time, maybe a pairing with someone from this
summer's Lilith Tour, even a country Lilith Tour of her own. Or
something closer to pure rock, as Emmylou Harris' Wrecking Ball, or
pure pop, the direction k.d. lang has chosen.
</P>
<P>
   This is wishful thinking, I know: Country audiences too often
punish their stars for stepping beyond the familiar. So perhaps the
more realistic request is a broader search for those haunting
ballads, the ones that showed Yearwood much more than country's
blonde cotton candy of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Hoover writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
