<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't save your children from 'Saving Private Ryan'
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I took all of my children to see ``Saving Private Ryan.'' I took
them though I had heard all about the intensity of the first 20
minutes. I knew about the blood and the gore. I had heard the
stories of grown men crying in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is I took them because of all of those things. I took
them because, try as I might to prevent it, they relish in seeing
Arnold Schwarzenegger blast people away with glee. To be sure,
there is plenty of blood in a Schwarzenegger film, but it is almost
always the blood of ``bad guys.''
</P>
<P>
   I took my children knowing full well that some in the audience
would criticize the move and perhaps some of you do, too. I'll
admit that a few years ago I came within seconds of taking them all
-- two years younger -- to see ``Schindler's List.''
</P>
<P>
   There is something wrong in our thinking when make-believe is
more acceptable than a decent rendering of what actually happened.
Network TV has shown endless streams of Schwarzenegger films but
how will it show ``Saving Private Ryan'' without leaving most of it
on the cutting room floor? I cannot imagine.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean to pick only on Schwarzenegger, there are half a
dozen others. Pick Bruce Willis if you like.
</P>
<P>
   In ``action'' films, people die easily, almost effortlessly and
with great creativity (only the leader of the bad guys has a long
road to death). What's more, everyone is happy to see them die.
It's great fun. But death is no holiday in ``Saving Private Ryan''
and it is clear that this is just what Stephen Speilberg intended.
Every time you watch a person die in this film -- every single time
-- it is a painful experience. Before the first 20 minutes is done
you just want it all to stop. Please stop. Yet, this is just a
film. Merely images on acetate. And it was only 20 minutes. The
real D-Day invasion battle lasted hours, not minutes. There were no
real bullets penetrating the stadium-seating theater.
</P>
<P>
   Some have argued that this film allows those who weren't there
to know what it felt like to have experienced D-Day. Baloney. I
knew full well that I could leave at any time. I knew that, at
movie's end, I would most certainly do so. Not one man who waded
ashore at Omaha Beach had that guarantee. Not one.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, I'm willing to call Speilberg's film a masterpiece of the
first order because he provided us a vision of the hell, if not the
hell itself. That alone is a remarkable achievement.
</P>
<P>
   There is a scene early on in ``Saving Private Ryan'' where the
camera's point of view turns from that of the invading forces to
that of the German army. The camera is positioned just behind one
of those murderous ``88s'' responsible for killing so many men.
</P>
<P>
   The view will send chills up your spine. The 88s had a clear
shot. When the doors opened men were mowed down before they could
take a step. I found myself wondering how anyone got out alive.
Those who landed first paid a dear price.
</P>
<P>
   I had intentionally sat next to my youngest daughter just in
case it was too much, too difficult for her 9-year-old eyes to see.
It was not; an indication of just how desensitized our culture has
left our children.
</P>
<P>
   Some have called this an anti-war film, but I don't believe
that, either. After all, Speilberg, who is a major contributor to
the U.S. Holocaust Museum in Washington, D.C., must see World War
II as utterly necessary. But even the most justified war is not
glamorous. As is shown by one character, even the smallest of
actions requires bravery. War is basic survival, trying to kill the
enemy before he kills you and you rarely get a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us adults who have never been in that situation,
``Saving Private Ryan'' gives us more admiration for the sacrifice
of the common soldier. For children, perhaps the movie is enough to
make them think twice about cheering so loudly for Rambo.
</P>
<P>
   (Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall ( TX) News
Messenger)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
