<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Worse than watergate
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Along time ago I sat in an audience of newspaper editors at
Disney World, which some would say is an appropriate place for
newspaper editors to meet. Richard Nixon was the speaker. He was
president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It was there, against the backdrop of Watergate, that he made
his memorable statement: ``I am not a crook.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure he was. Paranoid maybe, but not a crook. Anyway,
Richard Nixon is looking better all the time, by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   The way those editor conventions work is they get somebody like
the president or the secretary of state to come and make a talk.
They have microphones set up in the aisles, and after the speaker
finishes speaking editors who want to impress their colleagues go
to the microphones and ask tricky questions they've been crafting
for three or four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the questions are very dramatic and show how
intellectual and informed the questioner is. You might have noticed
something similar from the White House press corps and the
Sunday-morning ego eruptions on TV programs hosted by Cokie and
Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Nixon had barely finished his talk when one of the editors
strode to an aisle microphone and, in a voice that would do credit
to Ted Koppel, popped his question: ``Mr. President, will the
Republic stand?''
</P>
<P>
   I thought it was a foolish thing to bring up. Of course the
Republic would stand. It stood through a civil war. It stood
through the Great Depression, two world wars and Prohibition. It
would surely stand through Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   If somebody stood up today and asked the same question, I
wouldn't be so quick to brush it off. It seems to me the Republic
is in a lot more trouble now than it was when Nixon was forced to
resign.
</P>
<P>
   A better question might be: How long can the Republic stand, as
we know it?
</P>
<P>
   If you don't think the situation we have in Washington and in
the country today is beyond ridiculous, think back 20 years, even
10, and see if you could have, in your wildest imagination,
conjured up the scenario that today is dominating the news, and the
country. You'd have sworn we had all lost our minds. Maybe we have.
</P>
<P>
   New technology and new morality have taken over and are running
well ahead of common sense.
</P>
<P>
   Watergate was just Nixon and a few of his buddies playing dirty
politics and trying to cover their tracks. Right now, I'd be happy
to settle for something simple like Watergate. We fixed that, maybe
too well.
</P>
<P>
   Three New Age inventions have arrived simultaneously in the
nation's capital. Put together, they scare the daylights out of
anyone hoping for another 200 or so good years for the country. The
problem we have in 1998 is multiple:
</P>
<P>
   1. A president from the ``if it feels good it must be good''
generation, who has never grown up.
</P>
<P>
   2. A special prosecutor more powerful than elected officials,
who doesn't know when to leave well enough alone.
</P>
<P>
   3. A literal army of news reporters and editors, mixed in with
gossip-mongers and other charlatans, working for more TV channels,
stations, networks, newspapers, magazines, and information highway
addresses than a Georgia Tech Phi Beta Kappa can count.
</P>
<P>
   What worries me the most, as one who has come more and more to
appreciate the need to tell the news as it is when it happens, is
that maybe for the first time in the history of the Republic we are
developing a serious First Amendment problem. Can government as we
have known it function with 506 media trucks parked outside the
door while hundreds, even thousands, of reporters clamor for a
instant scoop? What if something like a war comes up?
</P>
<P>
   No, the media didn't cause Bill Clinton to behave like a 1960s
teenager. He's what we get for electing a juvenile delinquent
president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It's also true we wouldn't have this mess if Washington
reporters and editors had covered up for Clinton like they did for
John Kennedy when he was making the White House into a facsimile of
a formerly famous Athens institution known as Effie's House of Ill
Repute. However, it's usually best to report the news, even when
the news is bad.
</P>
<P>
   From down here on the farm, with 600 channels floating into our
back yard 24 hours a day and grocery store tabloids helping set the
agenda, it looks as if the problem isn't simply reporting the news,
but rather over-reporting.
</P>
<P>
   All juveniles aren't in the White House. The news business
suffers more than its share.
</P>
<P>
   We get more news than we want, need, or can absorb. Pretty soon
we won't be able to recognize what's news and what isn't. For
example, while we know what kind of drawers the president wears, we
almost forgot to check his tie.
</P>
<P>
   Considering we have a free country, and a public curiosity on
the trashy side, I don't know what can be done to get us back into
a sane zone, short of passing laws we don't want.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
