<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another longing look
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anniversaries are a convenient way of marking our lives, not to
mention reminding us of how nimble time really is. It's been a year
since Diana, Princess of Wales, was killed in a car crash in Paris,
and the event is being marked with a spate of tie-in books.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these are what the trade calls clip jobs, on-the-run
snapshots from a variety of sources, and they hold little interest
beyond their scrapbook nature.
</P>
<P>
   But a few of them have some claim on the readers' attention.
``Diana, Her Life in Fashion'' (Rizzoli, $40) offers a splendid
selection of photographs of the late princess in various gorgeous
outfits, along with behind-the-scenes detail about their design,
etc.
</P>
<P>
   The Rizzoli book also offers an appendix with bare-bones bios of
the designers _ Conran, Galliano, Valentino and Versace, among
others _ indicating that the book is for the general public rather
than the rag trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diana, Portrait of a Princess'' (Simon and Schuster, $35)
takes a broader view, but, read in conjunction with the Rizzoli
book, it's clear that Diana started out dressing as if she was born
to fit in with the reliably dowdy Windsors but unaccountably
developed a superb eye for clothes. Could a sense of style, in and
of itself, contribute to marital estrangement?
</P>
<P>
   Jayne Fincher, the photographer and author of ``Portrait of a
Princess,'' was an official royal photographer, but despite her
access, many of her photos are not appreciably better than those
taken by newspapermen who had to take what they could get.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Anderson's ``The Day Diana Died'' (Morrow, $27.50) _
a hilarious title with echoes of the portentous, fly-on-the-wall
tomes that used to be written by Fulton Oursler and Jim Bishop _
relates, in minute by minute detail, what Anderson somehow neglects
to refer to as her date with a tragic destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is a breathless writer of the sort usually to be found
writing for Rupert Murdoch. Breathless, but not hysterical _ no
conspiracies, no pregnancies, just a sad, stupid accident. Like
real life.
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-26-98 1612E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
