<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4904 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD28-COX     08-27 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It takes the right kind of glue
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The voice of inexperience is always refreshing, especially when
uttered by someone bright enough to ask questions before plundering
headlong into disaster.
</P>
<P>
   From the Internet comes this one: ``I have a set of beechwood
train tracks that I'd like to adhere together in a semi-permanent
fashion. The FAQ for woodworking states that hot glue is probably
not a good adhesive except for `building forms or jigs.' Since I'm
a non-woodworker, I'm not exactly sure what that means. Basically,
I'm looking for an adhesive that will keep the pieces `stable,' but
will be fairly easy to remove when I want to add to the set in a
few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told that rubber cement might work, but I'm worried
about marring the finish or damaging the wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is more of a `toy' question, but in reading
through this group's FAQ and recent posts, you obviously know a
heck of a lot more about wood adhesives, so I figured I'd take a
shot here.''
</P>
<P>
   For those of you not up to your hips in the Internet, FAQ means
a list of answers to Frequently Asked Questions. It's little wonder
this gentlemen didn't get any satisfaction there; his is scarcely a
frequently asked question. And for those of you who, like this
inquirer, aren't woodworkers, ``forms and jigs'' are shopmade
devices used to speed or otherwise aid in construction.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, the rec.woodworking FAQ is referring to the kind
of hot glue you squeeze out of little electric glue guns, and it's
right. This stuff generally is going to come apart on its own; only
in the rarest instance would I use hot glue for these purposes,
unless I needed the thing to cure immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Hide glue, which is applied hot, is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Hide glue has been used for centuries to make furniture, and
obviously it works quite well. In fact, enough furniture-makers
still use hide glue to keep it in production. You can buy hide glue
pellets, and the purpose-made double boilers used to heat it, at
any woodworking supply house.
</P>
<P>
   For all those centuries, of course, there wasn't any other glue.
In terms of general ease of use and durability, hide glue was
supplanted by today's modern synthetic glues, aliphatic resin
(Titebond) plastic resin and polyurethane. The thing that keeps
hide glue going is the fact that joints secured with it can be
taken apart with the application of moist heat. This is why
antiques can be restored _ failing joints can be taken apart
without damage, cleaned up, repaired and put back together again.
You can't do that with modern glue.
</P>
<P>
   The use of hide glue is not something for amateurs. You can
stink up a shop big time if you burn it, and it has to be just the
right consistency to work properly.
</P>
<P>
   However, I'm not sure that any kind of glue is going to do what
this gentleman requires. Now I have never seen wooden train tracks
that had a finish on them. Obviously, if there is any kind of
finish on the wood, glue won't work. Glue will not adhere
successfully to a finish. Even if it would adhere well enough to
meet the specification here, it would make a mess when removed.
</P>
<P>
   If used on bare wood, any kind of semi-permanent glue is going
to leave some residue which would have to be cleaned off before
regluing.
</P>
<P>
   So, why use glue at all?
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure how these pieces of track connect, nor am I sure to
what degree stress will be applied to them. But if their problem
was mine, I'd try taping them together. There are all kinds of
excellent tapes on the market, single and double sided. For
starters, there's that great old standby, duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   We want to hear from you but are unable to acknowledge every
message.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
