A4905 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WONDERLAND-PALMBEACH2     08-27 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONDERLAND-PALMBEACH28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Low-budget love story amiable, predictable
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Erin Castleton doesn't ask for much. She just wants a guy who
isn't a jerk and who maybe, just maybe, knows that it was Ralph
Waldo Emerson who observed that ``consistency is the hobgoblin of
little minds.''
</P>
<P>
   We don't ask for much, either. We just want a romantic comedy
with characters worth caring about for a couple of hours, written
with enough skill and filmed with enough style to set it apart from
the crowded field.
</P>
<P>
   Since that seems too much to ask, we might as well settle for
``Next Stop Wonderland,'' a pleasant enough low-budget love story
that travels all too familiar ground. Co-written, directed and
edited by Brad Anderson and discovered by Miramax at this year's
Sundance Festival, it follows two made-for-each-other contemporary
Bostonians who remain apart by barely one degree of separation
until the film's final moments. No wonder it is touted as an East
Coast ``Sleepless in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Erin (Hope Davis of ``The Daytrippers,'' looking an awful lot
like a young Hillary Clinton) is a night-shift nurse whose flaky
boyfriend walks out on her, leaving behind a videocassette of his
grievances. Her high-powered mother (Holland Taylor) throws her
back into the dating pool by taking out a personals ad for Erin.
This triggers a montage of date-from-hell encounters with geeks,
nerds, liars and the Emerson-impaired. It's funny stuff, but such
well-trodden territory.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, just blocks away is Alan Monteiro (Alan Gelfant), a
plumber who yearns to be a marine biologist. While going to school,
he works at the Boston Aquarium, but they are more interested in
his mastery of a monkey wrench than his fascination with all
creatures scaled and finned.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing a definite wrench into the movie is a hard-to-swallow
subplot about Alan taking a college loan from mobsters. He falls
behind in payments and gets pressured to cause mayhem with the
tropical fish so an evil developer (Robert Klein, no less) can halt
an aquarium addition. Romantic comedies require some suspension of
disbelief, but this pushes the limits.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Davis and Gelfant float above such flaws, and we do find
ourselves rooting for them. She is surprisingly likable,
considering that she has to play a character going through life
with a wary, sullen disposition. His character is a little too good
to be true, but Gelfant manages to make him credible. The built-in
problem with the movie, as with ``Sleepless in Seattle,'' is that
we want to see more of them together.
</P>
<P>
   It may take a while to get used to Anderson's jittery
camerawork, as if he were underlining that this was all done on the
cheap. But he eventually relaxes into the story, as we do.
``Wonderland'' must surely be a Lewis Carroll allusion, but it's
also a Boston subway stop. Anderson lovingly shows off some of the
lesser-known sights of Beantown, doing for the city what Woody
Allen repeatedly does for New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next Stop Wonderland'' wants to say something profound about
fate, destiny and star-crossed lovers. Of course, it doesn't, but
chances are that most moviegoers will settle instead for its
feel-good position on romance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
