<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4906 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUESO28-COX     08-27 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUESO28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fiery Queso gives 'em the heat
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Tom and Pam Stanley make queso, they pump
the peppers to it: jalapeno, habanero, chipotle, fingerhot and
serranos. Their Fiery Queso singes.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but the heat brought enough pleasure that five judges
declared it the grand prize winner of the Quest for Queso at the
Texas Fiery Foods Show recently at Palmer Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a hot fan, and I liked its texture and flavor,'' said
Jennifer Grissom of Birmingham, a food service consultant for
Southern Living and one of the judges. ``But it's too hot for the
general public, `` she conceded. ``I would serve the Tres Chiles
con Queso at my home for a party.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tres Chiles con Queso, made with only three peppers, was one
of the four finalists, along with a queso dotted with shrimp and a
two-ingredient queso of salsa and Velveeta. However, in a very
close contest, with nearly every judge having a distinct
preference, the Fiery Queso edged out the competition when the
numbers were tallied, winning a gift basket of hundreds of dollars
of fiery food products.
</P>
<P>
   For newcomers to Texas, queso is short for the Spanish words
chile con queso (kohn KAY soh), which translates to chile with
cheese. Texans claim it as their own. But Diana Kennedy in ``The
Cuisines of Mexico'' says, ``I had always thought of chile con
queso as a Texas dish until I went to Chihuahua. It is eaten there
as a vegetable with broiled meats, and it is also served as an
appetizer with hot tortillas.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, queso, which is usually more cheese than chiles, is
scooped up by the chipful at parties and ball games galore. It is
poured on baked potatoes, french fries, broccoli and burgers. It is
comfort food. It is good. It is contest worthy. And it comes in
many variations, some mild, some hot.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Stanley, an electrical project manager and the family chef,
was a little surprised that his Fiery Queso won. ``We weren't real
proud of this batch, `` he said of the 20-year-old, ever-evolving
recipe. Peppers vary so much, he explained. But that was Tom
talking. Pam thought the queso was perfect. However, both
acknowledge that it is hot.
</P>
<P>
   When Pam , an accounts examiner for the State Comptroller's
Office, takes a gallon batch to work, half the people tell her it's
too hot. ``But it's gone before lunch,'' she says with a smile. And
one of those colleagues told her about the queso contest and talked
her into entering.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by the TexasFiery Foods Show and Central Market, the
contest failed to attract a large number of entries. Perhaps it was
because it was the first year of the contest and the word did not
get out to queso cooks, or because there was no big-bucks prize.
Then, again, maybe the contest got lost in all the end-of-summer,
back-to-school activities. Whatever the reasons, fewer than 10
Austinites were willing to divulge their queso recipes for the
competition, a low response in a city where queso is one of four
main dips.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the sponsors elected to go forth with the
competition because the entries they received were so diverse and
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Mozzarella, cream cheese, American white cheese, Velveeta,
asadero _ all found their way into the final preparations, some of
which were smooth and some stringy because of the nature of the
specific cheeses. ``It's hard to compare the various quesos because
of the differences in the cheeses,'' observed judge Michael Flores,
a chef from San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The Queso con Camerones (shrimp), for instance, would be great
in a tortilla, like a queso fundido, said Flores, referring to a
popular appetizer frequently seen in Mexican restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The shrimp queso was a favorite of judge Sam Higgins, Ro-Tel
spokesman, cooking teacher and author of ``I'm Glad I Ate When I
Did 'Cause I'm Not Hungry Now'' and ``Snake, Rattle &AMP; Ro-Tel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was going to eat a whole bowl, Queso con Camerones is the
only one I would touch,'' said Higgins, cleansing his palate with a
Dr Pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the traditional Ro-Tel/Velveeta queso, a mainstay in
Central Texas, most of these quesos were made with white cheeses
and various chiles. Only one, the entry of 12-year old Kevin Neal
Lewis, blended a convenience product with a block of cheese in the
Texas two-step style. And this savvy young cook's convenience
product was not the Ro-Tel combo of tomatoes and green chiles but
salsa, specifically Austin Slow Burn, manufactured by his parents
Kevin and Jill Lewis. Simple and different enough to get him in the
finals.
</P>
<P>
   But are their quesos the best in Lone Star land?
</P>
<P>
   Well, you will have to be the judge of that. Make one and see if
it's better than yours. Fiery Queso
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds white American cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 small white onions, chopped and rinsed
</P>
<P>
   2 small bell peppers, chopped and rinsed
</P>
<P>
   1 small jar pimento
</P>
<P>
   6 large serrano peppers
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   4 habanero peppers
</P>
<P>
   1 fingerhot chile pepper
</P>
<P>
   5 jalapenos
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried and crushed chipotle pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon celery salt
</P>
<P>
   1 dash cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 dash red pepper
</P>
<P>
   Chop all veggies to desired size in a food processor.
</P>
<P>
   In top of double boiler, place all ingredients and cook on
medium heat for 45 minutes after the cheese is melted. Add water
for desired consistency. Cook another 30-60 minutes. Serve with
chips, soft tortillas, taquitos or tamales.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Stanleys use Boar's Head cheese and got all their
peppers at H-E-B. To tame the queso for their grandkids, they
eliminate the habaneros, fingerhot, serrano and jalapeno peppers. _
Tom and Pam Stanley, Quest for Queso grand prize winner Kevin's
Queso
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound Velveeta
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Austin Slow Burn Salsa con Habanero
</P>
<P>
   Add all ingredients to a small Crock-Pot. Stir occasionally
until melted. Dip with favorite chips. _ Kevin Neal Lewis Queso
Blanco con Camarones
</P>
<P>
   1 pound mozzarella cheese, shredded
</P>
<P>
   1 pound cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped fresh tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup chopped white onion
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons roasted garlic
</P>
<P>
   4 chopped peperoncini peppers
</P>
<P>
   4 medium pickled jalapenos, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 thinly sliced green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 cup water, as needed, to thin queso
</P>
<P>
   1 pound cooked, shelled salad shrimp
</P>
<P>
   Melt cheese in top of double boiler or on low in microwave oven,
adding water as needed to desired consistency. Add rest of
ingredients individually and in order listed. Heat on low for 5 to
10 minutes only to keep vegetables slightly crisp. Let sit 10
minutes before serving. _ Cinde Barbeau Tres Chiles con Queso
</P>
<P>
   3 poblano peppers
</P>
<P>
   3 Anaheim peppers
</P>
<P>
   3 jalapeno peppers
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium yellow onion (1 cup)
</P>
<P>
   1 green onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 pound Mexican asadero cheese
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sour cream
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Roast chiles on open flame or under broiler until blackened.
Place in paper bag, close and steam for 15 minutes. Rub off skin
and remove seeds and veins and coarsely chop.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in saucepan over medium heat. Add onions and garlic and
cook until translucent. Add chopped chiles and cook another 10
minutes. Lower heat and add asadero cheese and cook, stirring
constantly, until cheese melts, about 5 minutes. Stir in sour cream
and heavy cream. Add salt to taste. Serve immediately with tortilla
chips.
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Crider is the food editor for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
