<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Community bonds over whale's survival
 &HT;    By Sally D. Swartz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEWALL'S POINT, Fla. _ An off-duty Martin County sheriff's
deputy, boaters and teenagers came to the aid of a sick pygmy sperm
whale that beached itself on the south side of the Stuart Causeway
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a whale strand in the Indian River before,''
said Erik Martin of Ecological Associates, head of the local marine
mammal stranding network. ``It's a freak thing. The whale must have
come in the (Stuart) inlet.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin contacted the National Marine Fisheries Service in Miami,
which planned to send a team to pick up the whale and take it to a
rehabilitation facility in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Glenn Foss, who works at the sheriff's boot camp for
juvenile offenders, said he was eating lunch at the causeway about
2 p.m. when he saw the 10-foot whale, a female, thrashing in the
shallow water. Sharp rocks left cuts all over her body.
</P>
<P>
   Foss wrestled with the whale, pulling it into deeper water so he
could hold it upright, and waved down Pat McCafferty and Tom
Santori of Port St. Lucie, who were planning to launch their boat.
The three held the 800- to 1,000-pound whale steady, and soon were
joined by Krista Mendes and Rachel Sumner, both 14, and Rachel's
dad, John, all of Palm City.
</P>
<P>
   The crew held the whale for nearly three hours. Other passersby
waded out to relieve them. The deputy wouldn't leave his position
near the whale's head, holding her blowhole out of the water and
dodging the spray when she breathed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be a commercial diver in Louisiana,'' Foss said. ``I
love whales _ and any sea creature.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin was not hopeful the whale would survive. ``Usually those
that strand are in bad shape to begin with,'' he said. ``Most don't
even make it to the rehabilitation facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Foss continually stroked and patted the whale's scarred head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sorta feel responsible for her,'' he said. ``I don't want to
leave her. It's amazing how you get attached to something.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
