</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLPHINS-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miami rookies take orders, not abuse, they say
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ If you go by the Webster's definition _ ``to
harass with silly, disagreeable or demeaning tasks'' _ then, yes,
the Miami Dolphins' rookies have experienced hazing during training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   They have to bring buckets of chicken for the veterans to eat on
plane flights. They have to get used to being called ``Rook.'' And
they have to be prepared to treat their teammates to music _ and
we're not necessarily talking about standing up and singing during
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``See that,'' first-round pick John Avery said, pointing out a
stack of new stereo equipment sitting in an empty locker. ``I had
to buy that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Dolphins' rookies insist they do not have to do anything
resembling what happened in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Cam Cleeland, a rookie tight end for the Saints, was injured in
a hazing incident. He and four other draft picks reportedly were
forced to put pillowcases over their heads and run a gantlet of
veterans. According to Cleeland's agent, the veterans hit the
rookies with bags of coins. Cleeland suffered damage to his left
eye and may have had his nose broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's ridiculous,'' Avery said. ``When it gets to the point
when you're actually inflicting pain on another player, I think it
has more to do with jealousy. That's wrong. I don't understand
that. . . . Calling you rookie, making you bring chicken, that's
all in good fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins cornerback Patrick Surtain, the team's second-round
pick, has paid close attention to the Saints' incident. He grew up
in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shocked me because that's a bunch of adults,'' he said. ``
. . . There's nothing like that here.''
</P>
<P>
   The rookies say the most serious threat is a dunking in the
``cold tank'' _ a whirlpool of 45-degree water.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't done it, because, well, I'm obedient,'' Avery
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to the airport for last weekend's trip to San
Francisco, Avery had to swing through a drive-through and order 500
chicken wings.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Avery's wallet has taken the biggest hit, although after
signing a five-year, $5.5 million deal he should be able to afford
it.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone dreads hazing. When Dolphins receiver Lamar Thomas
was a Tampa Bay rookie, he and another former Hurricane, Horace
Copeland, were told to sing to the crowd assembled for a practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We loved it,'' Thomas said. ``They had to take the microphones
away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Latest additions: The Dolphins claimed three players off
waivers Wednesday: wide receivers Nate Jacquet and Phil Savoy, and
tight end Hendrick Lusk.
</P>
<P>
   Jacquet, a former San Diego State player, was the highest draft
pick of the three. Indianapolis made him a fifth-round pick in
1997. He spent the first nine games of the 1997 season on the
practice squad, was inactive for two games, then saw limited action
in the final five games.
</P>
<P>
   Savoy, who was released by Arizona, was a seventh-round draft
pick out of Colorado this season. He finished his college career
ranked second on the school's all-time list for receptions (152).
</P>
<P>
   For Lusk, this will be his fifth NFL stop in less than three
years. He started his career in New Orleans in 1986 as a
seventh-round draft pick out of Utah. He caught 27 passes for 210
yards that season, but was released the following summer. The Jets
claimed him off waivers, then traded him to Green Bay. Before he
played a game with the Packers, they released him. He had signed
with Washington on Dec. 31, 1997, but was released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The addition increased the Dolphins' roster to 61 players. They
are allowed to go over the 60-player limit because of two
exemptions _ defensive tackle Tim Bowens, who held out the first 27
days, and Damon Huard, who spent the summer in the World League.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
