<HEADER>
A4909 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLPHINS-WILMSMEYER28     08-27 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLPHINS-WILMSMEYER28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Out of garage, into NFL for punter Wilmsmeyer
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ The top line of Klaus Wilmsmeyer's bio is simple
and to the point.
</P>
<P>
   1997 _ Was out of football.
</P>
<P>
   And while that technically is correct _ for the first time since
he was a young boy in Mississauga, Ontario, Wilmsmeyer was indeed
out of the game _ it doesn't tell you what he was in.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, we offer a revised bio.
</P>
<P>
   1997 _ Was in the garage.
</P>
<P>
   Wilmsmeyer, who officially won the Miami Dolphins' punting job
when John Kidd was cut, did his kicking in 1997 in the garage of
his Louisville home.
</P>
<P>
   To explain how he ended up there, standing on a patch of carpet
set down on concrete, booting ball after ball into a net, you have
to go back to this time last year and the day a doctor told him,
``You can't play football; the risk is too high.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilmsmeyer had been gearing up to start what he hoped would be
his sixth NFL season and his third with the New Orleans Saints. He
had competition in camp, but his primary concern was his own body,
specifically his back.
</P>
<P>
   It had been bothering him since he arrived in New Orleans in
1995. And it had gotten worse during a busy 1996 _ a career-high 87
punts, including 10 in one game against the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   He showed up for camp in 1997 without a contract and with hopes
that his back would get better. It didn't. So he decided to have an
MRI done. And that is when the doctor gave him the news: He had a
herniated disc in his back that made playing football inadvisable.
</P>
<P>
   He returned home to Louisville, where he and his wife, Deborah,
had settled following his college career as a punter and
place-kicker for the University of Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I waited a couple months before making a decision,'' he said.
``Finally, I said, `I'm going to try and play again.'''
</P>
<P>
   He found a surgeon in Louisville who specialized in back
surgery, had an operation he hoped would solve the problem, then,
three months later, began kicking again.
</P>
<P>
   In his garage.
</P>
<P>
   It was winter in Kentucky, so he couldn't do it outside.
Instead, he spent $350 and bought a kicking net to set up.
</P>
<P>
   In his garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a 14-foot ceiling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it wasn't exactly a comfortable setting. The air was cold
and, even with the carpeting, the footing was slippery. In other
words, it was a little like Soldier Field in late November.
</P>
<P>
   But his back felt better. And if that wasn't enough incentive,
there was the statistic he kept hearing when he turned on the TV on
Sunday and sat there watching NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept saying that half the punters in the league were over
30,'' he said. ``Teams were having a hard time finding young
kickers who could directional punt or pooch punt.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilmsmeyer could point to what he did in 1995. He began that
year in Pro Player Stadium, punting in Super Bowl XXIX for the San
Francisco 49ers. Then, after the 49ers decided not to tender him a
minimum qualifying offer, he became a free agent and signed with
New Orleans. And in his first season with the Saints, he put 21
kicks inside the 20-yard line and only five in the end zone _ an
NFC-best ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when he signed with Miami on Feb. 23, he seemed like a
long shot to make the team. Kidd had held the job for four years,
establishing himself as the team's all-time punting leader (a
44.2-yard average).
</P>
<P>
   Then training camp brought an ironic twist. A bad back. Only it
wasn't his bad back.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd missed the first three season games with back pain, and the
battle for the job came down to a trip to 3Com Park _ the place
where Wilmsmeyer spent three seasons battling the swirling winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to get back,'' Wilmsmeyer said, ``but nobody likes
kicking at Candlestick. It's a tough place to keep a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but it is where Wilmsmeyer won his new job.
</P>
<P>
   His four kicks averaged 49.5 yards. Kidd's four kicks averaged
41.5 yards. Tuesday, the Dolphins made the decision to keep the guy
whose family tree starts in Europe _ his parents are from Germany _
but has traces of Canada and Kentucky in his accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things went into the decision,'' special teams coach
Mike Westhoff said. ``But Klaus just kicked John.''
</P>
<P>
   So maybe now Wilmsmeyer can take his life out of the holding
pattern it has been stuck in for the past six months.
</P>
<P>
   They had kept the house in Louisville. His wife, a high school
teacher, hadn't told her school whether she would be back this
fall. And Wilmsmeyer was holding on to his season tickets for
University of Louisville football games, hoping that he wouldn't be
able to use them.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, there was some added incentive to make it back to the NFL
_ a baby girl named Kasey Nicole Wilmsmeyer born on March 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big motivation,'' he said, glancing at her picture
in his locker and explaining that the goal was to be able to afford
to have Deborah stay home and take care of Kasey.
</P>
<P>
   Although the NFL is a fickle anything-can-happen business, it
looks like that will be possible.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like when this year is finished, it will be time to add
a new line to his bio.
</P>
<P>
   1998 _ Out of the garage ... back in football.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
