<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-COLONIAS28-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Colonias hit by flood
</P>
<P>
   By Ben Wear
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As floodwaters threatened to wash away hundreds
of modest homes in Rio Bravo and El Cenizo, about 800 women and
children headed to the safety of nearby shelters.
</P>
<P>
   But many of their husbands and fathers remained behind, to guard
what few possessions they own against looters _ efforts that might
be futile in light of the rising Rio Grande. Aurora Gonzales, 44,
waited pensively at the United D.D. Hachar Elementary School gym,
praying that her husband's efforts wouldn't be in vain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lost everything, I don't know what we'd do,'' Gonzales
said through an interpreter. ``We've lived there 12 years, and the
house took that long to build.'' Rio Bravo and El Cenizo are
colonias _ substandard developments built about 20 years ago, when
inadequate regulations and poor enforcement allowed developers to
carve up parcels for poor people eager to buy a piece of the
American dream but unable to afford better.
</P>
<P>
   These homes, in a remote area of mesquite trees and prickly pear
cactus about 15 miles south of Laredo, are simple structures of
wood and stucco. They could not be built legally today because they
lie in the Rio Grande's 100-year flood plain. Fortunately for the
homeowners, they can still be legally refurbished if floodwaters
cause severe damage, Webb County planning director Rhonda Tiffin
said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Still, rebuilding is not an easy option for most residents. The
reason: They cannot afford it. A 1997 state survey of El Cenizo
found that the average household income was $10,800 a year. What is
more, no one has federal flood insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners could be barred from rebuilding at the same location
only if the flood carries a home away or destroys it completely.
Then, Tiffin said, a 1997 agreement between a federal agency and
Webb County _ which owns and runs the systems for the colonias _
would prevent hooking new or reconstructed homes to the systems.
The systems are inadequate, and county officials are planning to
apply to the Texas Water Development Board for about $20 million to
upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffin said the county would be unlikely to approve subdivision
plats with homes in the 100-year flood plain _ an area that has a 1
percent chance of being flooded in any given year.
</P>
<P>
   State law has changed since the colonias' early days as well,
making it impossible to build a sewage-treatment plant in the flood
plain. El Cenizo's sewage goes to a small plant that lies about a
hundred yards from the Rio Grande. Webb County utilities director
Tomas M. Rodriguez Jr., whose department inherited the ill-sited
plant some years ago, said it is unlikely that this flood will get
high enough to cause a spill or shutdown at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   When the colonias were established, the land was in an
unincorporated section of Webb County. The developer who sold the
lots was not bound by city subdivision requirements that might have
banned building in the flood plain.
</P>
<P>
   Rio Bravo, which has about 5,000 residents, and El Cenizo, with
about 3,000, incorporated in 1989. Tiffin said the developer
encouraged incorporation because Laredo had moved far enough south
that the colonias fell within its extraterritorial jurisdiction,
meaning Laredo could have exercised some control over building.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the river was rising more slowly than expected,
and it was not certain whether the colonias would be flooded at
all. That didn't quell the fears of many residents.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales said her husband, who works as an aide in a nursing
home in Laredo, could not afford to replace their home if it is
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   San Juana Castorena, 24, who lives with her two young daughters
in El Cenizo, said she and her extended family _ including her
parents and sister and brother _ all live within blocks of each
other, and the river. If floodwaters destroy one house, it's likely
all will be affected. And none of her family, she said, could
afford to rebuild from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would all be homeless,'' she said. ``That's exactly what
would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Some relief could be available, though. A proposed settlement in
federal bankruptcy court calls for the Texas Department of Housing
and Community Affairs to earmark nearly $2 million for housing
improvements in El Cenizo. That commitment would stand regardless
of flooding, said Heather Tindall, a spokeswoman for the agency.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the housing agency often provides grants to
communities damaged by natural disasters, and the two colonias
would be no exception, provided that a state or federal disaster
were declared, said Homero Cabello, director of colonia initiatives
for the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The news that they could fix flood-damaged homes likely will be
small comfort to Rio Bravo and El Cenizo homeowners. None have
flood insurance because neither the colonias or Webb County
participate in the national flood insurance program run by the
Federal Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Unless an area's government participates, homeowners can't get
flood insurance. And without insurance, money for large-scale
repairs will be difficult to scrape up for the mostly poor
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Rio Bravo Mayor Feliciano Garcia said the city might be able to
help, using unspecified and so far uncommitted state or federal
money.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffin said FEMA has money for relocation, but only to
participating cities.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Judith Zaffirini, D-Laredo, said help from several
federal programs would be available if the governor declares Laredo
a major disaster area.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Ralph K.M. Haurwitz contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
