<SLUG> BC-GRAPEFRUIT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Price for grapefruit groves plunges 25%
 &HT;    By Julie Waresh
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. While the value of land used to grow
citrus continues to fall statewide, grapefruit growers have been
hardest hit, according to a survey by the University of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The value of grapefruit groves in the southern part of the state
fell 25 percent to $3,035 an acre this year, while the value for
orange groves fell less than 6 percent to $6,882 an acre.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been particularly rough for the grapefruit people,'' said
Clayton Hutcheson, director of the university's Cooperative
Extension Service in Palm Beach County. ``Nobody wants to buy a
grapefruit grove,'' he said, ``because nobody can get returns from
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Prices growers get for grapefruit have fallen sharply since the
early 1990s, primarily because growers over-planted grapefruit
trees after freezes in the late 1980s cut into supplies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, an 85-pound box of grapefruit that brought an
average of $6.62 in 1992 went for an average of $1.23 last year.
</P>
<P>
   There are 95,735 acres of oranges and 61,622 acres of grapefruit
grown in Palm Beach, Martin and St. Lucie counties.
</P>
<P>
   While this is the seventh consecutive year citrus land values
have declined, the value of farmland easily converted to
nonagricultural use remains high in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The annual survey, scheduled to be released next week, divides
the state into south, central, northeast and northwest regions. It
breaks out southeast Florida _ Palm Beach, Broward and Miami-Dade
counties _ to measure transitional land values.
</P>
<P>
   The value of the southeast region's ``transitional'' farmland _
acreage likely to be converted to home sites or commercial
development _ is triple what it is in other parts of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the value of transitional land within 5 miles of a
major town in the southeast region was $28,000 an acre as of May
1998, compared with $9,213 an acre in the northwest region.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's due to the higher intensity of development and the higher
population density,'' said John Reynolds, the professor of food and
resource economics who conducts the study.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds' Florida Land Value Survey has estimated the market
value for different types of rural land since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Survey respondents include property appraisers, farm managers,
real estate investors, county extension agents and others who
gather information about rural land values.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
