<HEADER>
A4912 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAREDO-UPDATE28-COX     08-27 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAREDO-UPDATE28-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Laredo hit hard by flooding
</P>
<P>
   By Cara Tanamachi and Ben Wear
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Fear turned into skeptism among residents here
as the forecasted raging floodwaters of the Rio Grande arrived in
Laredo as a sluggish rise, seeping close to, but not into, nearby
homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, August 26, river levels at International Bridge
No. 1 near downtown Laredo were about 31.5 feet, and officials
predicted the waters would peak near 35 feet between 9 p.m. and
midnight and hold that level for 12 hours. Flooding begins at 8
feet.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of deaths or injuries in the Laredo area
from the river's rise, a result of heavy rains upstream spawned by
Tropical Storm Charley. The death toll from Charley's remnants in
southwest Texas and northern Mexico stood at 13 _ six in Del Rio,
four in Real County and three in Ciudad Acun(tilde)a, across the
border from Del Rio. A man who died of a heart attack in Uvalde
County while being evacuated from rising water was not officially
listed as a flood victim because his death was not caused directly
by floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service predicted widely scattered showers
and thunderstorms across the Rio Grande, San Antonio, Guadalupe and
Nueces river basins through the rest of the week. However, no major
rainfall that would cause renewed flooding are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials advised residents of Del Rio and other
flood-stricken areas to wash hands carefully, to avoid food that
might have been contaminated and to drink water only if it was
bottled or served by a shelter. There have been no reports of
cholera, hepatitis A, gastrointestinal illness and other disorders,
said Chip Riggins, a physician with the Texas Department of Health
who was dispatched to Del Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Eagle Pass, between Del Rio and Laredo, some
downtown businesses and about 10 homes _ including the home of
Mayor Pepe Aranda _ were flooded, but there were no fatalities or
injuries. City officials weren't aware of any other property
damage.
</P>
<P>
   In the predawn hours Wednesday in Laredo, the water rose as
quickly as 3 inches a minute. But by mid-morning, it slowed to less
than 1 inch per minute, or just under a foot an hour. By noon, the
river had crested near 45 feet _ more than 5 feet higher than
expected _ at the Colombia-Solidarity Bridge, about 30 miles
upstream from downtown. That sent panic through some neighborhoods
downstream.
</P>
<P>
   Officials worried that the river could crest in Laredo much
sooner than expected, even by morning. But by late Wedneday, as the
Rio Grande continued its slow rise, officials estimated the river
would not peak until sometime overnight, and no higher than 35
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents, fearing looters, insisted on staying with their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have everything packed up, but I'm not leaving until I see
water at my porch,'' said Ruth Gonzalez, 46, who lives less than a
block from Zacate Creek, one of two tributaries of the Rio Grande
in Laredo and an area officials advised residents to leave Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   She sat on her porch late Wednesday afternoon, in view of the
creek. Gonzalez and her husband, Javier Sanchez Gonzalez, packed
most of their wordly belongings into the back of a pickup truck,
which sat on the street in front of their home, facing higher
ground and ready to go if water threatens.
</P>
<P>
   In Rio Bravo and El Cenizo, two colonias south of Laredo, where
officials Tuesday had predicted the floodwaters would hit hardest,
the river early Wednesday evening was still 25 feet from the first
row of houses.
</P>
<P>
   Shelters for the colonias' residents filled Wednesday with more
than 800 people _ mainly women and children _ who fled homes during
the night as emergency officials went door to door advising them to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   On either side of the river, spectators gathered to watch the
rising tide. And despite the best efforts of police, many crept
close enough to the water's edge to fling fishing nets. Some walked
away with large fish _ a dinner best not eaten, said officials,
since the water is heavily polluted with debris ranging from snakes
and tree limbs to dead livestock, including goats and pigs.
</P>
<P>
   In central Laredo, at the command center for fire and rescue
teams, emergency workers coordinated evacuation efforts and a
specially trained rapid water rescue team stood by.
</P>
<P>
   At lunchtime Wednesday, a man was spotted attempting to swim in
the river, and the rescue team went out into the swift-moving,
debris-filled river on a hovercraft, according to officials. The
man, however, made it safely on his own to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Laredo Fire Captain Alfonso Perez, Jr., who led the water rescue
effort, said navigating the waters overnight, when the waters are
expected to crest, will be far more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to maneuver around trees, dead cattle, furniture,
whatever might be out there,'' he said. ``We have lights, but you
can only see so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Emergency officials hoped most residents would leave long before
nightfall Wednesday. Evacuations, most but not all of them
voluntary, began early Wednesday in Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the Howard Johnsons 15-story tower, with a
million-dollar view of the river west of downtown, were roused from
bed about 6:30 a.m. and told to find other lodgings. Police visited
the Santa Rita neighborhood in southeast Laredo, a low-lying area
downstream of downtown, and made a non-binding request for
residents on Pamplona Loop, the street closest to the river, to
evacuate. Most did.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Salazar, whose family lives in a two-story on Pamplona,
spent most of the night on his roof with binoculars looking at the
rising water. He was still here around 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to wait to leave until it reaches the street,''
Salazar, 29, said through a translator.
</P>
<P>
   Later that morning, the Laredo Food Bank, which sits about a
block and a half from the Rio Grande, moved out supplies of food as
a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   Given the lack of flooding in Laredo, the relief center at the
Laredo Civic Center was not seeing much business.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Cisneros, Jr., a city health department employee
stationed there, said he had posted about 150 visitors since the
center opened Tuesday at 7 p.m., but that some of the names were
repeat visitors who had left to retrieve belongings when the flood
didn't arrive on schedule and then returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``And a lot of these were from Nuevo Laredo,'' Cisneros said.
``They got stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   In the colonias south of Laredo, Department of Public Safety
patrol officiers controlled traffic to areas nearest the river and
refused to let people return to evacuated neighborhoods until after
the floodwaters pass.
</P>
<P>
   All three bridges connecting Laredo and Mexcio remained closed
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Garza, director of the U.S. Customs office in Laredo, said
the city of Laredo already had inspectors checking the
Columbia-Solidarity Bridge upstream and might open it either late
Wednesday or early today. About half of the 6,000 trucks that cross
at Laredo each day typically use the Columbia-Solidarity Bridge in
normal circumstances, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   City of Laredo spokesman Marco Alvarado said there's no way to
predict when the two downtown bridges might reopen. He said the
company had hired Brown &AMP; Root, an engineering company from
Houston, to study the structural integrity of the bridges after the
water ebbs.
</P>
<P>
   Customs spokeswoman Judy Turner said cross-border shippers in
some cases may opt to take their loads across at McAllen or Eagle
Pass, given the uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   As evening neared, the water's edge likewise approached River
Drive Mall. At 31 feet, the river would begin to seep under the
mall's doors fronting the appropriately named Water Street.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
