r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCR-HISTORY28-COX     08-27 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCR-HISTORY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCR donates product archive to history museum
 &HT;    By Benjamin Kline
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Industrialist John H. Patterson liked to boast that wherever men
traded, a National cash register was tracking the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   A photographer on the NCR payroll often was not far behind,
making images of the famous, Dayton-made machinery in remote places
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Those images _ 400,000 photographic negatives on glass from 1895
forward _ are among the treasures NCR announced that it will lend
to the Montgomery County Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hackett, executive director of the historical society,
called the NCR archive ``an exceptionally rare and valuable piece
of our history. The NCR archive, better than any other single
collection in the Miami Valley, is the keeper of who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The cooperative move, described by NCR and historical society
officials as a partnership that will improve community access to
the company's archive, should assure that the priceless collection
of photographs, slides, drawings, corporate papers, machinery and
furniture will remain in the Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Merz, an historical society trustee, said it also could
encourage other Miami Valley corporations to turn over their
archives to a more public venue.
</P>
<P>
   Lars Nyberg, chairman and CEO of NCR Corp., and Hackett
announced the agreement on a two-year loan that would be followed
by a renewable, 10-year agreement for historical society management
of the archive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This partnership will keep our archive intact and make it more
broadly available to the community for display and research,''
Nyberg said in prepared remarks.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for the historical society to prepare an
inventory, develop a management plan and arrange a public exhibit
of archive items sometime next year. The society also must conduct
a fund-raising campaign to find a permanent location for the
archive and set up a digital library of the negatives and slides.
</P>
<P>
   NCR may invest up to $2 million in the project over 12 years,
Nyberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he was not prepared to announce details of the
fund-raiser. The society has long been overcrowded in its principal
location, the Old Court House at Third and Main streets.
</P>
<P>
   The NCR archive, stored at 1529 Brown St., is not a secret.
Images from it have appeared in local histories and television
programs. Limited use has been allowed to graduate students and
other researchers. But it has remained invisible to the general
public. An NCR spokesman said the agreement does not mean the
archive will be immediately open to the public on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
