<HEADER>
A4915 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALSY-COMPUTER28-COX     08-27 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALSY-COMPUTER28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computer realizes dream of man with palsey
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For maybe 20 years, Scott Meece imagined a wondrous day when he
could write by talking to a computer and read by listening to it
speak. Cerebral palsy, limiting his vision and dexterity, had
trapped his intelligence in a world where books and pencils were
not adequate for communicating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept saying, 'Wouldn't it be neat to have something you
could talk to and it would write down what you tell it?' '' Meece
says. ``I never thought it would really be available.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Meece has a computer setup that talks and listens. It still
costs $5,000, and the voice-recognition software has more bugs than
a windshield after a day on the highway, but the system is much
better than $25,000 would have bought just four years ago, says
Randy Tompkins, who trains people to use these adaptive technology
tools at the Technology Resource Center.
</P>
<P>
   The device enables Meece to work as a consultant for the RTA,
where he trains bus drivers in accommodating handicapped
passengers. ``He's getting paid, and he's paying taxes,'' says Pat
Cashdollar, TRC's program director.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changed my life dramatically,'' says Meece, who is
expressing his gratitude by rounding up corporate sponsors for
TRC's only major fund raiser. The Trek for Tech Run/Walk on
Saturday morning is still looking for sponsors and participants.
</P>
<P>
   Cashdollar and Terry Traske founded TRC 14 years ago in search
of synthetic voices for their disabled children who were unable to
talk. The organization is dedicated to enabling people with
disabilities, especially those that inhibit visual or vocal
communication.
</P>
<P>
   It serves as a lending library of adaptive technology so people
can try out the expensive gadgets before spending hundreds or
thousands of dollars on them.
</P>
<P>
   TRC is best known for its joint venture with the Dayton
Microcomputer Association to refurbish donated computers and
recycle them to people with disabilities, students at risk and the
economically disadvantaged. But the core of its mission is the more
than 1,500 people a year it helps with ways to overcome paralysis,
blindness, muteness and learning disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   It fits donated toys with toggle switches and pedals so, for
example, a child can turn an elephant's trunk into a squirt-gun
nozzle without moving his fingers. It has on-screen keyboards for
people who can't type but can move a trackball or use a pointer
attached to the forehead.
</P>
<P>
   For those with even more limited ability, computers scan the
alphabet or other choices on a monitor until a person clicks on
one. People can use them to turn the lights on or the heat down.
</P>
<P>
   TRC's clients are split evenly between children and adults,
birth defects and injuries or illnesses, Cashdollar says. Among the
most enthusiastic are those who are losing the use of their eyes or
their limbs.
</P>
<P>
   Now products for the disabled are the proving ground for the
voice-recognition technology coveted in many industries. ``It's
still highly overrated,'' Cashdollar says. When Meece says ``This
is a test'' into a new headset, the computer displays ``This is a
death.''
</P>
<P>
   But Meece can override those garbles with his keyboard or mouse,
and his own software actually has learned some of his pronunciation
patterns. He says he was overcome with joy the first time he was
able to write a letter to a friend and read the response.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being married to the computer,'' Meece says. ``I
turn to it when I'm frustrated, when I'm happy, when I'm sad. It
really is my partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
