<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Davis glad to put away other hats
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Finally, Butch Davis feels like a
football coach and nothing but a football coach.
</P>
<P>
   Just more than a week away from beginning his fourth season at
the University of Miami and less than an hour before his Hurricanes
scrimmaged against themselves in Lockhart Stadium, Davis sat on an
aluminum bench several rows up in the stands and . . . exhaled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most enjoyable time since we've been here has been the
last six months, because it's the first time all our energies are
devoted to the development of the team,'' Davis said. ``There's an
anticipation that something good is going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, the first three years what we were doing was a
Band-Aid effect. You asked yourself, `What did you have to do to
stop the bleeding this day, this game, on and off the field.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The abridged version of the ugly history is Davis, upon taking
the job in 1995, found himself saddled with NCAA sanctions as a
result of earlier Miami transgressions. The Hurricanes, as a result
of residual talent, escaped with 8-3 and 9-3 records during Davis'
first two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But last year's 5-6 record was Miami's first losing mark since
1979.
</P>
<P>
   A shadow of what they were
</P>
<P>
   All of which, by circuitous route, brought Davis and the
Hurricanes up I-95 from their digs in Coral Gables for Wednesday
night's activity. The first day of classes allowed Davis to take
practice on the road, so he did.
</P>
<P>
   The stated reason? Miami wanted to show off its team for fans in
Broward Country and perhaps draw a few from Palm Beach County as
well. A PR exercise, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   The unspoken reason? The Hurricanes need to do a sales job on
themselves because their Orange Bowl home has looked too empty too
often lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't the motivating factor,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is that Miami, which once cast a monstrous shadow
itself (remember all those national championships?), now lives in
the shadows of in-state bullies Florida and Florida State while
aftershocks of the NCAA sanctions still rumble beneath the
Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, for example, doesn't expect to reach the full complement
of 85 scholarship players until next season. He does, however, feel
better equipped to deal with the team's Big East schedule and a
non-conference slate highlighted by games against UCLA and
aforementioned Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes, for example, will not feature 29 true or
redshirt freshmen among the 44 players on their two-deep offensive
and defensive charts as they did last season.
</P>
<P>
   But they will, by Davis' own estimate, have only five seniors
who contribute in any significant manner.
</P>
<P>
   In for the long haul
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've tremendously improved,'' Davis said. ``The
reality is that the last year has been a healing process, and
that's going to help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that there hasn't been an assortment of misbehavior by
various Hurricanes during Davis' tenure, but the faith and feeling
is the NCAA and/or police blotters no longer will be primary
concerns. So it was that Miami, listed just ahead of Wake Forest in
the others-receiving-votes category of one pre-season poll and just
behind Oklahoma State in another, took its act up the South Florida
coast for an evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got loyalty to the kids I've sold my commitment to,''
Davis said. ``When you put your heart and soul into trying to make
a change, it's difficult to walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   He's feeling like a football coach again. Finally.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
