<P>
   TEXAS FLOODS (Moving on A wire)
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-COLONIAS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As floodwaters threatened to
wash away hundreds of modest homes in Rio Bravo and El Cenizo,
about 800 women and children headed to the safety of nearby
shelters. But many of their husbands and fathers remained behind,
to guard what few possessions they own against looters. (Wear,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LAREDO-UPDATE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Fear turned into skeptism among
residents as the forecasted raging floodwaters of the Rio Grande
arrived in Laredo as a sluggish rise, seeping close to, but not
into, nearby homes and businesses. There were no reports of deaths
or injuries in the Laredo area from the river's rise, a result of
heavy rains upstream spawned by Tropical Storm Charley.
(Tanamachi/Wear, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Highlights of tomorrow's TV viewing.
ETA: 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   CABLE _ A look at cable's successes, from imaginative new series
like ``South Park'' and ``Celebrity Death Match'' to increased
ratings and impressive industry awards for miniseries such as HBO's
``From the Earth to the Moon.'' Why are creative giants like Jodie
Foster and Tom Hanks heading for cable instead of network? Freedom
-- creative freedom and freedom from commercial interruption. And
viewers, especially younger viewers who don't remember a TV
universe without cable, are responding. (Holloway, Austin
American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   JENKINS _ Profile of Tamara Jenkins, writer/director of the
movie ``Slums of Beverly Hills,'' opening this weekend. Her movie
is unique in its frank, affectionate and funny look at an
underplayed movie subject, a teenage girl. She not only
``worships'' Tim McDonough and Vinnie Murphy (and it was under
McDonough's mentorship that she first began to write) but they
remember her as well. (StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA
8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WITH BOXES detailing ``Slums'' plot, Jenkins bio and other
movies opening this week. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   TV-JESSE _ They're back! Christina Applegate of ``Married . . .
With Children'' has her own Thursday night sticom on NBC called
``Jesse.'' It's a very different role. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   YEARWOOD _ In Where Your Road Leads, Trisha Yearwood sticks to
what's made her one of Nashville's top female performers: upbeat
songs and slow ballads that showcase her satin-smooth alto. It's
listenable, as all of Yearwood's seven albums have been, but
mainstream and safe, with enough country flourishes like an
occasional accent, steel guitar twang or mandolin/fiddle lick to
keep critics from labeling it a pure pop-rock album. (Hoover, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   DIANA _ Anniversaries are a convenient way of marking our lives,
not to mention reminding us of how nimble time really is. On the
aniversary of Diana's death, ``Diana, Her Life in Fashion''
(Rizzoli, $40) offers a splendid selection of photographs of the
late princess in various gorgeous outfits, along with
behind-the-scenes detail about their design, etc. (Eyman, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
