<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4935 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     08-27 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BY my count, six Astros are on track to have career years. Two of
them, Moises Alou and Craig Biggio, are bona fide Most Valuable
Player candidates. Prorated over an entire season, Randy Johnson's
Houston numbers are Cy Young-sized. And Larry Dierker is a
garlic-strong contender for Manager of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not exactly a shock that they've already won one fewer
game than they did all last season with 27 still to play. If they
stay their current course _ not an impossibility if they can avoid
lapsing into too many more brain-dead efforts like the one
Wednesday that produced a loopy 6-2 loss to the Braves _ they'll
finish 100-62 with a player payroll only modestly in excess of what
Atlanta spends on its starting pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are a jerry-rigged team, to be sure. Make that Gerry
with a G.
</P>
<P>
   Credit must be given where credit is due. As glorious a season
as it has been for a slew of guys with stars on their caps,
nobody's having a better year than the guy with stars in his eyes,
general manager Gerry Hunsicker.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker could be National League Executive of the Year on the
strength of the Alou and Johnson deals alone. Throw in the lopsided
trades for Carl Everett (.315) and Sean Bergman (11-7), and he's in
a league of his own. Gerry really should win the title by a
unanimous vote.
</P>
<P>
   No joke _ Dierker can manage
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, he deserves retroactive points for the
unabashedly brilliant move of putting Dierker in the dugout.
Although club president Tal Smith suggested it and the first words
out of Hunsicker's agape mouth were, ``You must be joking,'' he
warmed to the idea quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Larry for 20 years,'' he said. ``I knew that he
knew baseball, and I thought he would create a comfortable
environment in the clubhouse for the players.''
</P>
<P>
   And Dierker has.
</P>
<P>
   True, Hunsicker didn't re-sign Darryl Kile over the offseason, a
failure he calls ``easily my biggest disappointment.'' But if he
had kept Kile, Johnson wouldn't be here today and chances are
neither would Derek Bell (.304, 92 RBIs). With all due respect to
D.K., I'll take R.J. straight up, hands down. So what if he's most
likely just passing through.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker could be batting 1.000 if free-agent acquisition Dave
Clark weren't batting .200. But Clark has been more effective as a
pinch hitter of late _ 9-for-20 since July 18 _ and Hunsicker,
feeling lucky with good reason, predicts: ``Dave's going to win
some games for us before the season's over.''
</P>
<P>
   The way things have been breaking for Gerry, which is to say
smashingly well, Clark will probably sock the winning home run in
the bottom of the ninth inning in the seventh game of the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker has a creative mind and keen baseball instincts, and
the Astros' fine-line, ``small-market'' circumstances demand both.
Their margin for error is minuscule. They can't throw money at
their shortcomings. They must outthink the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Change of scenery works
</P>
<P>
   Bringing in Everett could have been a public-relations fiasco.
Cripes, his kids had been taken away from him for reasons of abuse,
a red-flag charge. But Hunsicker, who had been around Everett as a
Met and remembered him to be ``always smiling a good teammate,''
gambled that the situation wasn't as bad as was being reported in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't. As an Astro, Everett's conduct has been exemplary. So
has his switch hitting, and fielding. The Carl Everett that
Hunsicker remembered couldn't finance, much less buy, a hit batting
righthanded. The Carl Everett he wound up with in Houston is just a
shade under .300 from the right side of the plate and a sound
center fielder to boot.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman had a lousy night against the Braves, getting yanked
from a lost effort in the sixth inning. Remember, however, that he
came to Houston a career 18-27 pitcher who wasn't assured of a
roster spot when spring training began. That Bergman would be
attempting to notch a 12th victory before September says at least
as much about the roll Hunsicker has been on as Alou's 38 home runs
_ 15 more than he had ever hit before _ and the four ahh-inspiring
W's in five starts Johnson has recorded since his acrimonious
parting with the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Both of them could be construed as gambles, their respective
superstar credentials notwithstanding. Although Alou brought with
him a deserved reputation for producing in the clutch, he can be
difficult to handle. In a word, moody. And Johnson had been
behaving badly in Seattle, with statistics to match.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker thoroughly researched both, though, and concluded
their through-the-roof-good risk-reward ratios made adding them to
the Astros' roster imperative.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, this team, his team, is the best baseball team Houston
has ever had. Even if it didn't show up Wednesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
