<HEADER>
A4953 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-54-COX     08-27 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-54-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movie turns hot Studio 54 into a big bore
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Studio 54 hadn't existed, we would have invented it in our
dreams. Or our movies.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan nightclub was a late-1970s blast of neo-Roman
decadence where everyone could be fabulous ... if only they could
get inside. It was a place of contradictions: the hottest spangled
venue for the disco beat and a swan song for that wave of music;
the greatest place to party and the final incentive to book a suite
at Betty Ford; a hotbed for sexual whatever-you-feel-like and an
early way station for the AIDS virus, which stopped the dancing for
many in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   So what sort of movie do you make about a place like that?
Comedy? Tragedy? Satire? Or a tired, creaky fable about a
small-town stud who gets seduced by the limelight, almost loses
himself, but gets saved by the right girl?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the latter is what writer-director Mark
Christopher gives us in ``54.'' Our hero is Shane (Ryan Phillippe),
a sweet but dim New Jersey boy dreaming of a better life on the
Manhattan dance floor. (Hmmm, he must have seen ``Saturday Night
Fever.'')
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a movie relies heavily on voice-overs, you know
something's wrong. ``54'' is wallpapered with Shane's dull updates,
explaining things the movie should be showing instead of telling
us.
</P>
<P>
   Shane gets inside the club and lands a bartending job. He
becomes famous the Andy Warhol way, counting toward 15 one empty
minute at a time. But the movie doesn't get its biggest joke. Shane
lands a photo in Interview magazine and becomes the boy toy for an
older singer, Sela Ward. But he bristles when people treat him like
a piece of meat. And that's all Shane amounts to. The script
doesn't give him any perceivable traits or talents besides a tight
body and a knack for doing splits on a crowded dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``54'' is hypocritical (in other words, very Hollywood). It
wants to offer a cautionary tale while giving you a contact high.
Reportedly, the film was the victim of tampering and reshoots, and
it shows. It is squeamish about showing its main characters
(including Salma Hayek and Breckin Meyer as Shane's married club
pals) getting ahead the 54 way _ by schmoozing, hustling, doing
whatever it takes. It even makes Shane's dream girl Julie (Neve
Campbell), an actress willing to do anything to get ahead, do a 180
and become a saint. The movie is as meek as Studio 54 was
outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   The only person who seems in on the multilayered joke of the
club, with its ground-zero encapsulation of everything wonderful
and tragic about the late 1970s and early '80s, is Mike Myers. His
Steve Rubell, the Studio 54 owner, is a muzzy, smiling, perpetually
stoned troll working out his own childhood traumas in the
cocaine-piled playground he created. Squinting myopically at the
glorious debacle of his own life, he's the only reason to see the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``54''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ryan Phillippe, Salma Hayek and Mike Myers. Written and
directed by Mark Christopher. Rated R for sexuality, profanity and
drug use. 1 hour, 33 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Kills disco a second time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
