<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4954 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-SLUMS-COX     08-27 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-SLUMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Slums': A biting take on teendom
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' begins on a note of exquisite
embarrassment that epitomizes the entire movie: Squirming while a
saleslady fits her with a new bra, Vivian Abramowitz (Natasha
Lyonne) listens in horror as her father, Murray (Alan Arkin),
casually says, ``Overnight she got stacked, just like her mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Post-divorce, Vivian's mother is no longer in the picture. The
sole female in a family that includes brothers Ben (David
Krumholtz) and Rickey (Eli Marienthal), Vivian is the odd girl out
in a clan of Peter Pans who like nothing better than elbowing up to
a steak breakfast at the Sizzler.
</P>
<P>
   It's the summer of 1976. Every three months or so, Dad rouses
them in the middle of the night, skipping out on rent and moving
them into a new fleabag on the edge of town. It's the only way
Murray can afford to stay inside the ZIP code; he wants his
children to have a Beverly Hills education.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think the kids' grown cousin Rita (Marisa Tomei) would be
a good influence on Vivian. But Rita is on the lam from a rehab
clinic; while she makes a fun big-sister figure for Vivian, she's
not exactly an icon of responsibility. Meanwhile, Vivian is being
romanced by the guy across the hall, a pot-selling fellow named
Eliot (Kevin Corrigan) who always wears a Charles Manson T-shirt.
And Murray is courting an upper-middle-class widow (Jessica
Walter), who's looking for companionship instead of another
husband.
</P>
<P>
   What happens isn't as important as how it happens in
writer-director Tamara Jenkins' irresistible feature debut. She
re-creates the daily humiliations of adolescence with
wince-inducing accuracy. What's unusual is to see this territory
covered from a distinctly female perspective, with a sexual
freshness that's bracing (and sometimes blunt). Vivian obsesses
over her breasts, transforming them into the symbol for all the
chaos in her life. Lyonne brings to her sexual fumblings with Eliot
the aura of a detached young scholar trying to understand a very
perplexing subject.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins' dead-accurate eye for '70s detail includes halter tops,
the horrific, gilt-edged apartment the Abramowitzes move into, and
Ben's ceiling-high bong. Almost every scene has a lovely,
off-kilter detail, whether it's the sight of Ben singing ``Luck Be
a Lady Tonight'' (he's angling to play Sky Masterson in the school
production of ``Guys and Dolls'') or anecdotes about Lucille Ball's
stingy Halloween habits.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is on the director's fresh, unpredictable wavelength,
pulling off scenes that switch on a dime from hilarious to
heartbreaking. Lyonne is terrific, navigating the waters of teen
angst, trying to decide whether she should love or loathe her
family. Tomei is her usual lively self, as is indie regular
Corrigan. And Arkin is wonderful as the most complex of the
characters. His Murray is someone with whom we have to come to
terms, just as Vivian does; he's sometimes charming, sometimes
scary, and when we least expect it, deeply vulnerable. In other
words, human.
</P>
<P>
   A meditation on love, forgiveness and the double-edged facts of
family life, ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' is ultimately slight. It's
a series of moments and small, piercing insights. But it's so
beautifully realized that it renews your faith in film as a medium
that can show you new worlds. Or old worlds that you forgot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slums of Beverly Hills''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Natasha Lyonne, Alan Arkin and Marisa Tomei. Written
and directed by Tamara Jenkins. Rated R for nudity, profanity and
sexual situations. 1 hour, 31 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A vivid, original, very funny look at coming of age
on the fringes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
