<HEADER>
A4955 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-THIEF-COX     08-27 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-THIEF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A light-fingered tale of false love
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Thief'' was robbed at last spring's Academy Awards. While
``Character,'' the winner as best foreign-language film, has
considerable merit, this Russian entry is a far more evocative and
affecting work.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Character,'' ``The Thief''' is a tale of fathers and
sons. In this case, it's about fathers symbolic or surrogate,
idealized or unworthy.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, set in 1952 when Josef Stalin was inflicting his
brand of paternalism on the Soviet Union, is told from the point of
view of 6-year-old Sanya (Misha Philipchuk). He and his mother,
Katya (Ekaterina Rednikova), a creamily pretty young widow, are
traveling by train when a studly soldier, Tolyan (Vladimir
Mashkov), crosses their path. He easily seduces Katya, and the next
thing Sanya knows, he's got a new daddy.
</P>
<P>
   Not in the legal sense, but the three form a nice little family
unit _ a convenient front, it turns out, for Tolyan's true
occupation. He's a thief whose modus operandi is to charm his
victims, then rob them. It's pretty much the approach he uses on
Katya and Sanya. But what he takes from them can't be bought or
sold: her heart and her son's childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Still, little Sanya is so eager for a father _ he's haunted by
visions of his real dad, who died before he was born _ that he
eventually falls for the macho yet protective false father provided
by Tolyan.
</P>
<P>
   As allegories go, this one is pretty transparent. Tolyan even
has a tattoo of ``Papa'' Stalin on his chest. The film's strength,
however, lies not in its symbolism but in its telling visual
details, its almost poetic vignettes and the three wonderful
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Misha Philipchuk is one of those effortlessly natural and
appealing child actors whose every emotion registers. Rednikova's
role is less complex, but she has the face of a Russian icon and a
subtle way of tracing Katya's descent from innocence to alcoholic
bitterness. Mashkov, who is a major star in his homeland, suggests
a Soviet Stanley Kowalski with his confounding yet irresistible
mixture of sensuality and brutishness.
</P>
<P>
   One further father-son note: Director Pavel Chukhrai is the son
of Grigori Chukhrai, whose World War II drama ``Ballad of a
Soldier'' (1959) was the first Soviet movie accepted at an American
film festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thief''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Vladimir Mashkov. Directed by Pavel Chukhrai. Rated R
for sex, nudity and language. Subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A Russian fable of father and son that'll steal
into your heart.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
