<HEADER>
A4956 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-WONDERLAND-COX     08-27 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-WONDERLAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Next Stop' serves wry, with a side of reality
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like ``A Streetcar Named Desire,'' the title of the charming new
romantic comedy ``Next Stop, Wonderland'' has both a
transportational and a symbolic meaning. There really is a Boston
subway stop named Wonderland (it's a dog track). But Wonderland,
where everything gets curiouser and curiouser, is also an apt
description for the world this movie's heroine inhabits.
</P>
<P>
   A nurse who's dumped by her jerk of a boyfriend in the first
scene, Erin (Hope Davis from ``The Daytrippers'') is further
burdened by her jerk of a mother. Without Erin's knowledge or
approval, Mom places a personal ad on her behalf in a Boston paper.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an absolutely attractive and inexplicably unattached
guy named Alan (Alan Gelfant) keeps crossing Erin's path without
the two ever quite connecting. It's a spin on the old
boy-meets-girl plot: Boy just misses girl. (Last year's ``Till
There Was You'' tried the same thing with less success.)
</P>
<P>
   Director Brad Anderson, who co-wrote the script with Lyn Vaus,
is stronger on character nuance than he is on narrative. In fact,
he needlessly overloads his picture with subplots. In one, Alan, an
aspiring marine biologist, is caught up in a struggle between a
corrupt developer (Robert Klein), to whom he owes money, and the
local aquarium, where he volunteers. In another, Erin becomes the
target of a milder version of an ``In the Company of Men'' bet,
thanks to her mother's ad.
</P>
<P>
   The parade of unsuitable suitors is familiar but still amusing.
More to the point is the way Erin suffers these various fools _ not
gladly like a fluffy, romantic-comedy heroine, but wryly and
warily, like a real human being.
</P>
<P>
   She even reads books. I can't remember the last time a female
who wasn't meant to be a dog, a nag or some other kind of too-smart
loser read a book in a movie.
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty much the key to this film's appeal. It applies a
naturalistic, stripped-down, independent-film sensibility to a
vintage glossy Hollywood predicament. Erin and Alan are honest and
adult, in both their solitude and their need for connection.
They're also clever, lively and good company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next Stop, Wonderland'' exists in its own little zone, a place
where John Cassavetes shares pillow talk with Doris Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next Stop, Wonderland''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Hope Davis and Alan Gelfant. Directed by Brad Anderson.
Rated R for vulgar language and sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 36 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A small wonder in its own modest way.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
