<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4957 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WONDERLAND-GELFANT-CO     08-27 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONDERLAND-GELFANT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Fate and destiny' played a role in making of the movie, actor
says
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When actor Alan Gelfant's independent film ``The Destiny of
Marty Fine'' took second prize at last year's Slamdance Film
Festival, the first-prize winner was a movie called ``The
Daytrippers,'' starring Hope Davis. At the better-known Sundance
Film Festival, taking place the same time in Park City, Utah, a
first-time director named Brad Anderson was screening his feature
``The Darien Gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it good timing: The actors and director got to know each
other's work that January and came together for Anderson's second
film, ``Next Stop, Wonderland,'' which opens in metro theaters
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense of synchronicity and fate and destiny with
the whole making of this movie,'' says Gelfant. Which is fitting,
because ``Wonderland'' flirts with that notion of unseen forces
moving our lives.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Davis plays a nurse going through a series of
terrible dates looking for Mr. Right. That happens to be Gelfant's
character, a Boston plumber studying to be a marine biologist. But
in the movie, the two just keep missing each other.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Gelfant spent most of his time on the set not
acting with Davis. ``We had a cordial but distant interaction,'' he
says. ``I would have been happy to spend more time with her, which
we eventually did. But as an actress, she wanted to keep her
distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most romantic comedies, ``Wonderland'' balances its humor
with a fluid, intelligent sense of melancholy, underscored by its
bossa nova soundtrack. Gelfant liked the tone of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The title `romantic comedy' suggests something that's insipid
and unbelievable,'' he says. ``You know, you meet a woman, and the
next day you're flying together to Europe. If that really happened
in real life, my friends would say, `That's insane. Do you think
you're in a romantic comedy?' But I liked the melancholy and
realism in this script.''
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of synchronicity, he had a few things in common
with his character. Not only was Gelfant's father a marine
biologist, but Gelfant went to school in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It's there that he worked with director Vincent Murphy, who
happens to be on the faculty at Emory University these days. ``Are
you serious?'' Gelfant asks when he learns this. ``Vinnie Murphy
was my senior acting teacher. Him and a guy called Tim McDonough.
They inspired me more than anything.'' Time out for more goose
bumps when Gelfant learns that McDonough is also an Atlanta
resident now.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there's something to this fate thing.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles resident for eight years, Gelfant, 41, is still
carving out the life of an almost-known actor; on top of acting
gigs, he manages the apartment building he lives in. After ``Marty
Fine'' was honored at Slamdance, he received recognition from an
unexpected quarter. ``When I got back home, most of the cards I'd
gotten were from entertainment lawyers and tax lawyers,'' he says
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't expect ``Wonderland'' to make him a star. But he's
hoping it gets enough recognition (and makes enough money) that his
name could help other good independent films down the road get
made.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and just so you know. Yes, he settled on an entertainment
lawyer. ``He hasn't really had to do anything for me yet,'' Gelfant
says. ``But he's a nice guy.''
</P>
<P>
   THE GELFANT FILE
</P>
<P>
   -- Age: 41
</P>
<P>
   -- Parents: Mother was the first female professor at
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth College(NH); father, now deceased, was a marine
biologist who lived in Augusta, Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   -- Other work: Movies _ ``The Crow: City of Angels,'' ``The
</P>
<P>
   Destiny of Marty Fine.'' Television _ ``In Living Color,'' ``The
Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Upcoming: The independent films ``Life Drawings'' and ``Men
in Scoring Position.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
