<P>
   RUSSIA IN CRISIS: GORBACHEV SPEAKS
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   As Russia's economic and governmental crisis deepens, Mikhail
Gorbachev, former leader of the Soviet Union and Nobel Peace Prize
winner, has offered clear and often clairvoyant perspective in his
most recent column from The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev wrote of President Boris Yeltsin: ``If the president
and his ever-changing entourage continue to insist on a flawed and
unworkable economic program, it could ignite mass protest.
Currently, 90 percent of those polled think that a social upheaval
could erupt in Russia in the near future. It is quite ominous and
the events could go out of control. This is an unacceptable
scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Given the turmoil in Russia, and the shifting alignments of
Russian politics, Gorbachev's opinions become all the more
influential. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev's column is illustrated by the internationally famous
cartoonist Ranan Lurie.
</P>
<P>
   For samples of Gorbachev's column on world affairs, call (888)
2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796), and you'll automatically be connected to a
New York Times Syndicate salesperson in your territory.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
