<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, Aug. 27, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DEBATE (Hollywood, Calif.) _ During the hour-long debate
between incumbent U.S. Sen. Barbara Boxer and her Republican
challenger, the first three questions from panelists centered on
Clinton's troubles with Monica Lewinsky, and Boxer's connections to
the issue. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT-ENDS (San Antonio) _ The silver lining in the rain
downpour in South Texas is that the recent drought appears to be
ending. Water use restrictions across the Edwards Aquifer region
were relaxed but officials urged continued efforts to conserve. By
JERRY NEEDHAM.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CLINTON (San Francisco) _ In his first public appearance
since President Clinton admitted to an ``inappropriate''
relationship with White House intern Monica Lewinsky, Vice
President Al Gore voiced strong support for his boss during a
campaign stop in San Francisco. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   SHARK-ATTACK (San Francisco) _ A 16-year-old boy from San
Rafael, Calif., boy was recovering in the hospital after being
attacked by a shark while he was enjoying one of the last days of
summer boogie-boarding with friends at Stinson Beach. By TYCHE
HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-SCAM (San Francisco) _ Think twice before transferring
that call. It could cost your company hundreds of dollars under a
perennial phone scam. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   911-TECHNOLOGY (San Francisco) _ Consumers have been
unpleasantly surprised after dialing 911 from cell phones and
getting slower assistance than they would if the call had been
placed from a regular phone. As a result, the Federal
Communications Commission has ordered wireless carriers to install
emergency 911, or E-911, location-finding technology by October
2001. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FALL-FILMS (Undated) _ So, the traditionalists tell us, the time
of frivolity and carefree film-going comes to an end as summer
ebbs, and serious viewing begins as the days grow shorter. Yeah,
which is why there are two cartoons this fall about ants and one
about a guy who dies, comes back as a snowman and learns what it
means to be a real father. By BARBARA SHULGASSER.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-REVIEWS-MYSTERIES (Undated) _ September is a big month for
publishers of mysteries and thrillers. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TUXEDOS (San Francisco) _ No two ways about it. Men look great
in tuxedos. The graphic white of a freshly laundered formal shirt
frames the face and sets off the slimming silhouette of the
shapely, satin-lapeled jacket. By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   MAYOR-AIDE (San Francisco) _ Esther Hwang has become the most
ogled scheduling secretary in municipal history. The 23-year-old
UC-Berkeley graduate and former Miss Asian America runs San
Francisco Mayor Willie Brown's bustling scheduling department,
booking roughly two dozen meetings and events a day, fending off
stacks of invitations, calibrating Brown's days and evenings down
to driving and ``cushion'' time. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MATTHEWS-COLUMN (Washington) _ George Stephanopoulos says he's
still burning from the first time Bill Clinton got him to lie. It
was in 1992 when the then-Arkansas governor was being grilled about
his Vietnam draft record. By CHRISTOPHER MATTHEWS.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Why is it so hard to believe
that Hillary Clinton actually bought his lies? Because she's a
lawyer? Because she's got a high IQ? Because she's ambitious?
Because her husband is a politician? Because she's a feminist?
Because she knew he'd cheated before? By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-DRESS (San Francisco) _ Green hair doesn't bother me.
Neither do dog collars, multiple earrings, or three-inch
fingernails painted black. As a teacher, I just don't want to see
anyone's underwear. By CHARLA LA FAVE.
</P>
</TEXT>
