<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-CHURCHES-HOMOSEXUALITY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERAL CHURCHES MOVE TOWARD ORTHODOX STAND ON HOMOSEXUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    For a generation, United Methodists, Presbyterians and
Episcopalians have been debating whether to approve same-sex
marriages and the ordaining of homosexuals. The pattern was the
same in each church. Gay activists gained the support of national
church staff and of many female clergy who put forth resolutions at
every national convention. But they lost nearly every vote.
 &HT;    As the battle wore on, it turned off so many church members that
all three denominations have seen their membership shrink by about
a third since 1965.
 &HT;    However, in recent months leaders all three old-line Protestant
denominations have gotten fed up and said ``No'' to the pressures
of gay activists.
 &HT;    On August 11, the Judicial Council of the United Methodist
Church, which serves as the denomination's ``Supreme Court,'' ruled
unanimously that the following language placed in the 1996 Book of
Discipline had the force of law, and violators can be punished:
``Ceremonies that celebrate homosexual unions shall not be
conducted by our ministers and shall not be conducted in our
churches.''
 &HT;    The Rev. John Ed Mathison, pastor of the 6,000-member Frazier
United Methodist Church in Montgomery, Ala., is delighted: ``The
Judicial Council makes it concrete and clear what the church stand
is. Any pastor performing a same-sex marriage will be brought to
trial and lose his credentials.''
 &HT;    What prompted the council ruling was the case of Rev. Jimmy
Creech, pastor of First United Methodist Church in Omaha, Neb., who
performed a covenanting service for two lesbians in 1997. He was
suspended by Nebraska Bishop Joel Martinez and charged with a
violation.
 &HT;    At a trial he argued that Book of Discipline language was only
``advisory,'' and he was acquitted by one vote. That moved
Southwest UM bishops to ask the Judicial Council for a definitive
ruling, and it came this month. (Creech was reinstated for a few
months, but was not reappointed in June.)
 &HT;    The strategy of conservatives within the Presbyterian Church,
U.S.A. was similar. In their 1996 General Assembly they voted to
place language into the Constitution calling for all church
officers to practice ``fidelity within the covenant of marriage and
chastity in singleness.''
 &HT;    The language was crafted so that it was as critical of adultery
or cohabitation by clergy, elders and deacons as it was of
homosexual conduct.
 &HT;    ``We don't have an organized group of Presbyterian adulterers,
but we do have organized Presbyterian homosexuals'' who fought the
measure, said Parker Williamson, editor of the influential
newspaper, ``The Presbyterian Layman.''
 &HT;    After losing the General Assembly fight, gay activists took the
battle to the church's 172 presbyteries who had to vote for the
measure before it was ratified. Nearly half of the presbyteries (43
percent) voted with the gays, but constitutional change was adopted
as 57 percent of the presbyteries endorsed it.
 &HT;    Gays persuaded the 1997 General Assembly to soften the language
to simply call for ``fidelity and integrity in all relationships.''
This spring, an even wider 66 percent of presbyteries rejected the
watering down, leaving the tougher language intact.
 &HT;    Interestingly, Williamson reports the presbyteries that voted
for the tougher language had membership growth from 1990-1996,
while those voting with gays came from churches that lost 11
percent of their membership.
 &HT;    Most recently, Anglican Bishops meeting at the Lambeth
Conference voted by a stunningly wide margin, 526-70, against ``the
legitimizing or blessing of same sex unions'' and ``the ordination
of those involved in such unions.''
 &HT;    Bishops from the fast-growing churches of Africa overwhelmed the
liberals, all of whom were from North America, Europe and
Australia, all of which are suffering from shrinking church
attendance. In fact, there are more Anglicans worshiping on Sunday
in Nigeria alone than in all the West. No wonder Africans embrace
Biblical orthodoxy.
 &HT;    The impact of Lambeth vote's on the Episcopal Church in the U.S.
is unclear, since it is merely advisory. Newark Bishop John Spong
grumbled, ``If the Anglican Church becomes dedicated to preserving
prejudices, our followers may well vote with their feet.''
 &HT;    Is the man blind? Under his pro-gay leadership, 28 percent of
his church members walked away in a decade.
 &HT;    ``This vote clearly shows that the present leadership of the
American church is out of step with the wider Anglican communion,''
said Peter Moore, president of the conservative Trinity Episcopal
School for Ministry. ``It puts the liberal American church leaders
in a quandary. Do they listen to the rest of the communion, and
rejoin the church catholic, or do they begin to act like a cult
with their own sources of authority and doctrines?''
 &HT;    If the Episcopal Church wants to grow again, it too will return
to Scriptural standards.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1998 Mike McManus
