<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BICKLEY_MCGWIRE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANDRO' USAGE A BAD MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not about asterisks or an unfair advantage. It's not about
one man's quest, the products in his locker and their link to the
steroid tree.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it's all about the message. About kids who marvel at
Mark McGwire bulging out of his uniform, blasting baseballs into
orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Kids who are now flocking to stores, pumping their bodies full
of Androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, the advocates of the latest
performance-enhancing craze better be right.
</P>
<P>
   ``By itself, it is not an anabolic steroid,'' said Dr. Scott
Connelly, a leading pioneer in the development of Androstenedione
and its bulging family. ``But no one can sit here and tell you they
have data in their possession that these compounds, over the long
term, won't have significant negative side effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is precisely the problem. No one knows for sure whether
Androstenedione is harmless in moderation or destined to produce
the next Lyle Alzado. For every doctor who calls it a well-dressed
steroid, another expert claims it's much ado about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the product is flying off the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   A gym in Phoenix posted an advertisement on its locker room
wall. A fitness store in Scottsdale carries 100 different varieties
of the stuff. At a well-known nutritional chain in Tempe, more than
100 people have walked through the doors in the past week searching
for Andro.
</P>
<P>
   ``A constant request,'' said Michele Hernandez, a GNC franchise
owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its popularity is extraordinary, especially since the McGwire
thing,'' said Mark Bozza, owner of the House of Fitness in
Scottsdale. ``And I have to be honest. I do get a lot of young kids
in here, although I get a lot more college students.''
</P>
<P>
   As the debate focusing on McGwire and his use of Andro rages out
of control, there are some distinctions to make.
</P>
<P>
   If there's anyone to blame for the mess, it's Major League
Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL, the NCAA and the IOC have banned Androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has no clear-cut drug policy in place, largely because
it hasn't had a commissioner for the past six years. It knows all
about the perils of chewing tobacco, but largely is clueless to
everything else and completely impotent when it comes to
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   As for the lack of knowledge, you can pinpoint a 1994
Congressional act that removed supplements like Andro from the
strict control of the FDA, which requires years of research and
testing before a product hits the market.
</P>
<P>
   So McGwire is absolved. It's not illegal. While it may increase
his strength and aid his recovery, it won't be responsible if
McGwire shatters Roger Maris' home run record.
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire was a rookie _ and 60 pounds lighter _ he bashed 49
homers. End of story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger Maris was a chain smoker,'' Connelly said. ``He'd smoke
himself into a coma after every game. Who's to say his ability
wasn't enhanced by having a nicotine level that was 10 times
higher? If you want to get ludicrous, let's get crazy with
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, just because it's legal doesn't make it safe. And it
doesn't make it right.
</P>
<P>
   So baseball needs to wake up and implement a sophisticated drug
policy. It needs to identify the drugs and performance-enhancing
supplements it won't tolerate. Instead, there is an abundance of
Creatine commercials during the Little League World Series.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire needs to send a message, too. He should make it clear
that there are uncertainties surrounding his supplement of choice.
He should insist that any copycats do so under proper supervision,
and that anyone who emulates his diet could be in for a nasty
surprise down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it have abuse potential?'' Connelly said. ``Of course it
has abuse potential. Aspirin has abuse potential.''
</P>
<P>
   But aspirin doesn't build muscle. It doesn't make you look like
Popeye.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly says there is evidence that Androstenedione, under
normal dosages, carries no toxicity in the short term. Unlike
steroids, it is not pure testosterone bombarding the system.
Rather, it simply allows your body to produce testosterone, though
his opponents claim there is little difference.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he is quick to say that young males, particularly high
school kids, should avoid Andro. That interfering with their own
hormonal tidal waves is a big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Well, guess who's buying the stuff?
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has cried over abused children. He donates huge amounts
of money every year because of abused children. That alone should
shake his sense of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, he will leave an indelible mark on the game
before the season is history. In 20 years, let's hope the legacy
doesn't have a dark side. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
