<HEADER>
A5043 &Cx1f; tad-z
s w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLMONEY-SENATE-$ADV2     08-27 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLMONEY-SENATE-$ADV29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAMPAIGN FINANCE BILL'S BACKERS SEEK 8 MORE GOP SENATORS
 &HT;    430&AMP;add. With POLMONEY-DATA for release Saturday, Aug. 29.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate returns Monday from its summer vacation
with most Republican members holding firm against a bipartisan
campaign finance bill.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Russell Feingold,
D-Wis., insist that the five legislative weeks left before the
Congress's scheduled adjournment on Oct. 9 might give them enough
time to overcome that.
</P>
<P>
   To help them, a coalition of national groups favoring tighter
restrictions on the unregulated, unlimited ``soft money'' at the
heart of the campaign scandals of 1996 is trying to convince at
least eight GOP senators to switch sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``If two or three move by mid-September, others will move to the
reform side,'' predicted Steve Weissman of Public Citizen, one of
the pro-reform groups.
</P>
<P>
   The House on Aug. 6 voted by a convincing margin of 252-179 for
a bipartisan bill similar to legislation cosponsored by McCain and
Feingold that was blocked in the Senate last October and again this
March. Both versions would ban ``soft money'' _ contributions to
parties by people giving more than $25,000 a year or by
corporations or unions giving any amount _ and would regulate
pre-election ``issue ads'' that mention candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version had the support of seven Republicans and all
45 Democrats. But 48 Republicans voted in March to filibuster the
bill. Because a filibuster by 40 senators can block further action
on any bill, the House-passed bill can't get through the Senate
unless at least eight Republicans change their stand.
</P>
<P>
   None announced a change of heart during August. Sen. Mitch
McConnell, R-Ky., predicted he and Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., could keep GOP defections below eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're more likely to see Elvis again than to see this bill
pass the Senate,'' said McConnell, under whose chairmanship the
National Republican Senate Committee has raised nearly five times
as much soft money as it did under Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he's really saying is, 'Oh my God, here it comes
again!''' Feingold said Wednesday. ``It's down to a small group of
filibustering senators trying to resist the will of the majority of
the entire Congress, and they will lose his battle ultimately _
either in September or early next year.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, McCain said he and Feingold would need at
least a week to feel out other senators and agree on a floor
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my intention to raise the issue, but I have to wait and
see what the parliamentary situation is,'' said McCain.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``They have some added momentum, because the House passed a
bipartisan bill with 61 Republicans _ that's more than one-fourth
of the Republican House members,'' said political scientist Michael
Malbin of the State University of New York at Albany. ``But the
people who oppose it benefit from the timing, because it would take
several legislative steps in the Senate, the House and a conference
committee to make it law.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show most people, regardless of party, favor passage of
campaign finance reforms, though few think they will pass.
</P>
<P>
   But any Republican senators who do vote for reforms will be
defying their party establishment, as was made clear in 30-second
ads telecast last week by Republican National Chairman Jim
Nicholson, who called for another investigation of fund-raising
abuses by Democrats in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear a lot of talk about campaign reform. The truth is new
laws won't mean a thing to people who broke the old laws,'' said
Nicholson, whose party has raised $70 million in soft money,
compared to $46 million by the Democrats, since January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain-Feingold bill has the support of Senate Democratic
Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota, who said, ``All 45 Senate
Democrats continue to stand behind this effort.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Presumably, the seven Republicans can also be counted on,''
said Don Simon, executive vice president of Common Cause. Recently,
his group, Public Citizen and the League of Women Voters expanded
their pro-reform coalition to include new grassroots allies with
broader concerns _ the American Association of Retired Persons, the
Environmental Defense Fund and some national Protestant and Jewish
social-action groups.
</P>
<P>
   State chapters of those national groups have started staging
news events targeted at 15 of the 48 GOP holdouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senators in tough re-election fights in places like Colorado
and New York and Missouri have to feel uncomfortable at the
prospect of voting against a bipartisan campaign finance reform
package,'' Feingold said. Republican Sens. Ben Nighthorse Campbell
of Colorado, Al D'Amato of New York and Christopher (Kit) Bond of
Missouri are seeking re-election in November.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 other Republicans targeted by the expanded coalition have
indicated support in the past for at least some reforms. They are
Sens. Tim Hutchinson, Ark.; William Roth, Del.; Dan Coats and Dick
Lugar, Ind.; Charles Grassley, Iowa; Sam Brownback, Kan.; Spencer
Abraham, Mich.; Chuck Hagel, Neb.; Judd Gregg, N.H., Mike DeWine,
Ohio; Robert Smith, Ore., and Bill Frist, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   But McConnell scoffs at the idea that election-year pressure
would work. In his Senate office, he often shows visitors his
framed copy of a newspaper front page reporting on a successful
GOP-led filibuster he led against a campaign finance reform bill.
</P>
<P>
   The paper is dated Oct. 1, 1994. As he delights in pointing out,
elections held five weeks later gave Republicans control of both
the Senate and the House for the first time in four decades.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
