<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GOMEZ-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIRATES' FORMULA SPELLS SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hottest club in baseball was in town the last two nights.
The Pittsburgh Pirates may be a few years away from competing on a
serious basis, but this is a club that has caught the eye of many
executives in the baseball community.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates have budding stars at several positions. Headlining
their list is third baseman Aramis Ramirez, catcher Jason Kendall,
right fielder Jose Guillen, center fielder Adrian Brown, second
baseman Tony Womack and possibly the best of all in first baseman
Kevin Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's some ballclub over there,'' Arizona Manager Buck
Showalter raved before the start of the series. ``They could have
quite a future on their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates, a small-market club with limited financial
abilities, decided several years ago to use the June draft a bit
differently than other clubs. Pittsburgh knew it couldn't pay out
the huge bonuses many other top picks were receiving. So the
Pirates decided to choose the best available athletes, even if it
meant picking players with limited baseball talent, and mold them
into players. It's a formula other clubs have started emulating in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it all starts with pitching and the Pirates aren't
short in this department, either. Jason Christensen, Jason Schmidt,
Jose Silva, Rich Loiselle and Ricardo Rincon headline a staff that
is awaiting the arrival of Kris Benson, the overall first pick in
the 1995 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Problems did arise earlier this season when several of the
Pirates' hot-shot prospects began acting as though they were
established major leaguers, forgetting what it takes to take the
next step and compete with the big boys in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game does a good enough job of humbling you,'' Young
said. ``You don't need to go out and try to humble anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Another potential problem facing these Pirates is what it will
take to keep this collection of potential All-Stars together. If
these players reach their potential, they will surely command the
kind of salaries the current state of the Pirates simply cannot
afford. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Oh Henry waits &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Sammy Sosa enjoying his finest season ever, the Chicago
Cubs may want to try to protect Sosa in the batting order.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Henry Rodriguez, who has 31 home runs and 84 RBI,
will be a free agent after the season. Rodriguez has teamed with
Sosa to smack 83 home runs. Rodriguez would love to remain on
Chicago's north side, but said he will not seek an extension while
the Cubs remain in the playoff hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might distract from the wild card,'' Rodriguez said. ``I
don't want it to get in the way. But I'd love to come back, knowing
Sammy Sosa is here and having gotten to know all the guys. I'll
look at the Cubs first before anyone else. Maybe they'll come to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs should not discount the importance Rodriguez's presence
has played on Sosa's success in 1999. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dude, you're kidding &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the Atlanta Braves were in Los Angeles last week, a film
crew from FOX wanted to take Braves outfielder Ryan Klesko to the
LA beaches he roamed as a teenager. The crew wanted to film Klesko
surfing on the same waves he hung 10 on as a kid.
</P>
<P>
   The crew, and Klesko, was disappointed to learn that Klesko is
forbidden to partake in such endeavors as part of his current
long-term contract. Nevertheless, Klesko went along to Huntington
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought my surfboard,'' Klesko said. ``It was awfully
tempting. So I sat on the beach and moped. I watched a surf
contest, ate a bagel and read the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, another of Klesko's hobbies that was taken away by the
contract: He's no longer allowed to accompany police on drug
raids. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Very welcome news &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tentative 1999 schedule has very few two-game series, which
players hate. The National League schedule alone, which includes
more than 100 two-game series this year, will likely have a few
more than a dozen next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a major concern for players that it was too much travel
and the competition level was being hindered,'' said San Francisco
Giants player representative Jeff Kent. ``Players and owners have
addressed that, and we're trying to get it right.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
An explanation &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When St. Louis' game against Pittsburgh was called because of
rain in the seventh inning last week, it brought out several
questions pertaining to why games that are called are played over
in their entirety while suspended games are picked up where they
left off.
</P>
<P>
   The division in terminology began in the 1930s and '40s, before
lights were installed in the majority of ballparks. As most anyone
knows, a game is official once the losing club bats at least five
innings.
</P>
<P>
   A game is declared a tie, such as last week's Cardinals-Pirates
game, if the score is tied after five full innings and the visiting
club did not score in the previous half inning. The rule was
instituted to prevent a club from stalling.
</P>
<P>
   It was not uncommon to see the visiting club, which had just
taken a lead, start substituting pitchers between batters if rain
had started falling in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   A game is considered suspended if the visiting club tied or took
the lead in the top of an inning without the home club having
finished its at-bat in the bottom of the inning. Such games are
resumed where they left off. For those interested, check rules 4:10
and 4:12 in the official baseball rule book. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
