<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5062 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERROR-MAGNIFIED-THRE     08-27 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-MAGNIFIED-THREAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WAR ON TERRORISM' CAN DRIVE YOU BONKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    MIAMI _ In what has become the manner of the times, the newly
proclaimed ``war on terrorism'' is taking on a shrill,
hyper-menacing tone that cannot help the U.S. deal with the
problem. Some commentators seem almost gleeful at finding a
dangerous new enemy to take the place of the Cold War threat.
 &HT;    There is an astonishing intensity in the way news is being
presented to maximize the drama. The TV reports _ and most people
get their news from TV now _ go on hour after hour, with
interruptions only for commercials, the weather and sports, whether
or not they have any information to offer.
 &HT;    It is as though nothing else is going on in the world except
Monica Lewinsky and terrorism. Journalists and ``consultants''
interview each other endlessly on what they think about the facts
they admittedly don't know. They spend so much time on camera that
they can't do much reporting beyond offering themselves as the
audience for ``spin control'' briefings, so they aren't prepared to
ask probing questions.
 &HT;    Even the sober, serious ones, such as Ted Koppel, discuss at
length the Armageddon that the terrorists may be preparing for the
United States. There is some official deliberation behind this. The
government feels a need to arouse people so as to have full support
for future action not yet thought through. Gone is the moderating,
skeptical tone of a Walter Cronkite searching for some perspective
and a basis for independent judgment. The more they talk, the less
they say.
 &HT;    It reminded me of the time when President Kennedy, seeking to
mobilize people for the nuclear-arms race, announced a program to
have everybody build a family atomic-bomb shelter in the back yard.
Fortunately, the idea was soon abandoned. A combination of dismay
and ridicule, and a gradual understanding that terrorizing the
country wasn't a good or sound way to strengthen it, shot the
program down.
 &HT;    The Saudi dissident Osama bin Laden, who has been around
promoting his nefarious plots for a long time but was unknown
except to Middle East experts, has suddenly provided a face to pin
on the murky image of terrorism. It's as though he could be held to
account for all of it.
 &HT;    Nobody asks for some clarification of just whom the new war is
to be fought against. Only Arabs, or are the Irish, the militant
Israelis, the Japanese cultists, the Colombian and Peruvian and
Algerian guerrillas to be included? Is terrorist some kind of
special breed to be identified by the color of skin, the length of
nose, facial hair, a headdress? Or is it only somebody who hates
Americans?
 &HT;    There is little explanation of the background of bin Laden and
the ``Afghanis,'' the people from many countries recruited to fight
the Soviet invasion in Afghanistan with Pakistani sponsorship and
American supplies and finance. The European press has made the
point.
 &HT;    The Financial Times called bin Laden ``America's Frankenstein,
``a reminder that dirty tricks and covert action spawn more dirty
tricks.''
 &HT;    Even the dangerous implications of the cruise-missile attacks on
Afghanistan and Sudan are brushed aside in the effort to appear
faultlessly resolute. It has only just come out that the deputy
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Joseph Ralston, was
sent to be in Pakistan when the missiles hit the neighborhood, so
he could convince the Pakistani military that the sudden strike was
not an attack from India.
 &HT;    A misinterpretation of who was targeting whom could have led to
a nuclear exchange between the two subcontinental enemies. That is
an extreme but factual example of why it's bad to stir up
exaggerated fears with worst-case terrorist scenarios.
 &HT;    For myself, I feel obliged to reserve judgment on the missile
strikes. I favor doing whatever is possible to deter terrorism and
punish its practitioners, but we don't know enough yet to tell if
this was a good way and what chances it had of being effective. A
sheer display of destructive power can serve the terrorists'
purposes by heightening tension and hostility.
 &HT;    It was shocking to hear some congressmen and commentators jump
to the assumption that President Clinton decided on the spectacular
retaliation for the bombings in Kenya and Tanzania to change the
subject from the round-the-clock Monica Lewinsky coverage. In
itself, it showed how much the scandal has damaged America.
 &HT;    There is a problem of credibility, having nothing to do with the
president's sex life but with the way important news is handled and
opinion manipulated. Maybe the American public, having been exposed
to this kind of infodrama since the O.J. Simpson show boosted
ratings, is inured to its insidious effect.
 &HT;    But it isn't reassuring. ``War on terrorism'' can become a war
on sanity.
 &HT;     (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1998 Flora Lewis 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------------ &QC;
</P>
