r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERROR-AIR-STRIKES-NY     08-27 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-AIR-STRIKES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MYSTIQUE OF U.S. AIR POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By ELIOT A. COHEN  
 c.1998 Foreign Affairs Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Reliance on air power has set the American way of war apart from
all others for well over half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Other countries might field infantry, submariners or scientific
artillerists comparable in skill and numbers to America's.
</P>
<P>
   Only the United States, however, has engaged in a single-minded
and successful quest for air superiority in every conflict it has
fought since World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Air warfare remains distinctively American _ high-tech, cheap in
lives and, at least in theory, quick. To America's enemies _ past,
current and potential _ it is the distinctively American form of
military intimidation. Air warfare plays to the machine-mindedness
of American civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Aircraft can direct massive and accurate destructive force at
key points without having to maneuver cumbersome organizations on
land or sea.
</P>
<P>
   When American presidents use air power, they should either hurl
it with devastating lethality against a few targets _ say, a
full-scale meeting of an enemy war cabinet or senior military staff
_ or extensively enough to cause sharp and lasting pain to a
military and a society.
</P>
<P>
   The sprinkling of air strikes over an enemy will harden him
without hurting him and deprive the United States of an intangible
strategic asset.
</P>
<P>
   American leaders at the end of this century indeed have been
vouchsafed with a military instrument of a potency rarely known in
the history of war. But glib talk of revolutionary change obscures
the complexity of truly radical change in the conduct of war and,
worse, its inherent messiness and brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, air power is an unusually seductive form of military
strength, in part because, like modern courtship, it appears to
offer gratification without commitment.
</P>
<P>
   More than one commentator who had reservations about aerial
bombardment in the Persian Gulf War expressed a newfound belief in
its utility as a tool of U.S. foreign policy in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Lewis of The New York Times wrote during the gulf
conflict in disgust at the ruin wrought by aerial bombardment: ``We
should never again tolerate anyone who talks about `surgical
strikes.''' After that, however, he developed a keener appreciation
of air power, asserting, for example, that ``a few air strikes in
Dubrovnik'' would have stopped the Yugoslav horrors in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   It remains that many individuals came away from the gulf war
with a far healthier respect for air power, believing it had made
all the difference. Indeed it had. Some 52,000 air-to-surface
sorties delivered approximately 210,000 unguided bombs, 9,300
guided bombs, 5,400 guided air-to-surface missiles and 2,000
anti-radar missiles. American forces also hurled more than 300
cruise missiles at the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   To what effect?
</P>
<P>
   Of its 700 aircraft, the Iraqi air force lost 33 in the air;
approximately 140 perished in hardened aircraft shelters and more
than 120 were flown to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi air-defense system succumbed within days _ really,
hours _ to an extremely sophisticated attack. It managed to shoot
down only a tiny fraction of the attacking aircraft. Moreover, air
power had completely disrupted Iraqi logistics and immobilized the
Iraqi army.
</P>
<P>
   Although ground action necessarily consummated the final victory
for coalition forces, air power had made the final assault as
effortless as a wartime operation can be.
</P>
<P>
   If the claims of air power advocates are correct, the United
States, after the gulf war, acquired a military edge over
conventional opponents comparable to that exercised in 1898 by the
soldiers of Lord Kitchener against the sword-wielding dervishes of
the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after all that, the way to a U.S.-policed world order
might look remarkably smooth. Was the Persian Gulf war a major
departure in the history of warfare and does it point the way to
unshakable American military preeminence?
</P>
<P>
   The war saw the first extensive use of some new technologies.
The F-117 stealth fighter penetrated Iraqi radar safely and
secretly. The Joint Surveillance Target Attack Radar System
detected Iraqi trucks and tanks along highways in Kuwait. An array
of satellites gave unparalleled support to military commanders for
intelligence gathering, map-making, communication, navigation,
meteorology and missile-launch detection.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bulk of the work came from much older systems and
mundane technologies such as air refueling.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the weapons used in the Persian Gulf dated back two
decades or more. Air Force B-52 and Navy A-6 bombers had seen at
least 20 years of active service, although they employed newer
electronics. Guided bombs first appeared in the Vietnam War, when
U.S. aircraft dropped 4,000 or so on the Vietnamese communists.
</P>
<P>
   Even modern, first-line fighters such as the F-16 have been in
use for almost a decade.
</P>
<P>
   So the ``military-technical revolution'' sparkled in new
systems, but it drew as much on considerably more mature
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   And the respect it created for unbeatable American power has
not, in nearly a decade, faltered a bit.
</P>
<P>
   (Eliot A. Cohen is professor of strategic studies at the Paul H.
Nitze School of Advanced International Studies, The Johns Hopkins
University. From 1991 to 1993 he was director of the Gulf War Air
Power Survey, an independent study commissioned by the Secretary of
the Air Force. This article is adapted from a longer version in
Foreign Affairs.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5070 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVIL-DEFENSE-TERROR-     08-27 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVIL-DEFENSE-TERROR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IF THERE IS AN URBAN NIGHTMARE? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JOHN G. ROOS  
 c.1998 Armed Forces Journal International Inc.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   If a terrorist were to strike a U.S. city with a chemical or
biological agent, the Federal Bureau of Investigation would be
responsible for coordinating the response to the attack.
</P>
<P>
   A host of federal, state and local agencies would be mobilized
for the remediation effort, including the U.S. Army's Technical
Escort Unit (TEU). Part of the Army's Chemical and Biological
Defense Command (CBDCOM), the Aberdeen Proving Ground,
Maryland-based TEU has expertise and equipment found nowhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we're organized and equipped to deal with either a
chemical or biological device,'' said Lt. Col. Doug Norton, TEU
commander.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the capability to mitigate the effects of a device if
it has already functioned, or to render it safe if it hasn't
functioned. ... We also have the capability to search for a device,
take samples to determine if chemical or biological agents have
been released and, if we locate a device, we have the capability to
remove and transport it to the appropriate lab for
identification.''
</P>
<P>
   At any time, Norton said, a basic chemical and
biological-response team is ready to respond within four hours to
any incident anywhere in the United States. In all, the TEU has 83
military members and 99 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the U.S. Domestic Preparedness Program, under which
``emergency responders'' from 120 U.S. cities are receiving
training in how to respond to an attack involving chemical,
biological or nuclear elements, is the most visible aspect of the
government's efforts to prepare for an urban nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   The training program is an interagency effort heavily supported
by the Defense Department through the Army Chemical and Biological
Defense Command. Essentially a ``train the trainer'' program, the
effort is aimed at policemen, firemen, hazardous materials
handlers, medical personnel and others who would be called upon to
respond to a so-called ``domestic WMD attack.'' It introduces them
to what they need to know and do _ beyond the actions they would
normally take _ to protect themselves while saving others' lives.
</P>
<P>
   The training program, as well as the rapid-response team,
springs from requirements in the 1997 Defense Authorization Act to
develop capabilities to aid in the event of a chemical or
biological incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, the Army's Technical Escort Unit brings a great
deal to the table. Its members have years of expertise in crisis
management,'' said Jim Warrington, program director for domestic
preparedness at the CBDCOM. ``There's also the Marine Corps'
Chemical Biological Incident Response Force.''
</P>
<P>
   This year $43 million is being spent on the Pentagon's Domestic
Preparedness Program; next year $49 million is set aside for the
effort. ``We anticipate completing the training for all 120 cities
by fiscal year 2001,'' Warrington said.
</P>
<P>
   After an initial course of instruction in Denver in May 1997,
the original training concept was refined, and by mid-April, 23
sessions had been conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we've gone into a city, we've fine-tuned the
training,'' Warrington said. ``Usually the training lasts for one
week.'' The instructors include active-duty military and
non-military emergency personnel and Army Reserve teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at precautions in Israel, where recent scares from Iraq
placed the public in a fearful dilemma, a wide range of
countermeasures are either available or under development to
confront even the most horrifying chemical or biological threat.
</P>
<P>
   These include a highly capable passive defense organization
reaching to all levels, with shelters, personal equipment in the
hands of all the population and a highly professional medical
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Further, an experienced pharmaceutical industry can quickly
produce sufficient antidotes on short notice and distribute these
to the population within days. This was done during the most recent
crisis, together with an all-out effort by global purchasing agents
who obtained additional items abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The danger from a terrorist suicide attack is also well known in
Israel. Not much can be done to prevent these attacks other than
constant vigilance and the political resolve to move quickly
against known threats.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of such future attacks using chemical or
biological agents cannot be neglected, and effective measures to
give early warning or to initiate countermeasures must be
considered.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's early-warning defense system is geared to detect
suicide flyers, remote-controlled drones and converted
crop-spraying aircraft trying to sneak through, but these threats
are considered less likely.
</P>
<P>
   While Israel is a highly organized nation constantly on alert
for mass terror attacks, it has large squatter regions surrounding
already densely populated cities, increasing any risk.
</P>
<P>
   One can only hope that reason will continue to prevail _ not
only in the region known as the cradle of civilization _ but
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (John G. Roos is editor of Armed Forces Journal
International.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
