<HEADER>
A5072 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BINLADEN-TERROR-COMMA     08-27 1557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BINLADEN-TERROR-COMMANDOS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO COMBAT TERRORISTS, U.S. RAIDS REQUIRE COMMANDO UNITS, NOT CRUISE
MISSILES, RANAN LURIE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By CAROLEE B. MORRISON  
 c.1998 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Ranan Lurie, who is now known internationally as a political
cartoonist and analyst, was a celebrated Israeli army combat major
in the Six Day War.
</P>
<P>
   To him it takes hand-to-hand, gutsy commando action to bring
down terrorists, and the idea of firing Tomahawk missiles at a
training camp buried in the mountains is an expensive way of
``saying something you don't really mean.''
</P>
<P>
   In this interview, Lurie addresses the strategy chosen by the
United States to enter into what President Clinton is now calling
``a long, ongoing struggle between freedom and fanaticism, between
the rule of law and terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -0-
</P>
<P>
   CAROLEE B. MORRISON: How would you assess the U.S. missile
attacks in Afghanistan and Sudan in retaliation for the embassy
bombings in Africa?
</P>
<P>
   RANAN LURIE: I believe these cruise missiles were the most
anticipated guests of Osama bin Laden. He is hiding in the
mountains, well prepared for cruise missiles; he is not impressed
by them. President Clinton forgot that the cruise missile is by now
a very known quantity. We have also the problem here of preparing
for the last war _ we shot scores of these missiles in the Persian
Gulf War. Generals always plan the next war on the criteria of the
last war. What I am trying to say is that every terrorist
organization today knows the chances are that 80 percent of U.S.
retaliation will be committed by cruise missiles. The United States
has established itself as a fighting force that wants to rely as
much as possible on technology, while sacrificing nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In terms of lives?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, we don't want to report about casualties. The missiles
cost a lot of money, and nothing in American lives. They are
ineffective against terrorism unless all the bad guys, and all
their weapons, are in known, extensive, above-ground headquarters
or camps.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What should we be doing? How can we surprise them? Can we
surprise them?
</P>
<P>
   A: The only way to surprise them would be by helicopter attacks,
landing Delta Force-type units, special commando forces that also
are enjoying superb intelligence _ this is where the CIA comes in
very strongly. And they actually clear the area.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, I could envision an attack, with the aid of
Pakistan, of America's very superior helicopters, on that specific
spot, protected by air power, and a unit of about two companies
coming down, knocking on the door and demolishing the whole place,
and hopefully capturing its high command.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It sounds as if you're saying we have the capability of doing
this.
</P>
<P>
   A: I think we have, but we don't have the stomach for it. We
don't want to take a chance of losing lives. Let us remember when
President Carter was trying to save the hostages in Iran in 1980.
He sent the helicopters, and there were equipment failures and a
crash in a sandstorm, and men killed, and the mission was aborted.
It caused tremendous damage to Carter, who came out looking like a
very incompetent leader.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, while he approved it, he didn't know the details, so
technically he wasn't responsible, but he was responsible as the
commander in chief. Now, basically, other commanders in chief don't
care to accidentally tread in those footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So when you speak of the stomach to fight, you are referring
to the politicians, not the warriors?
</P>
<P>
   A: Absolutely, yes. You know, a platoon of Navy SEALS has so
much fire power ... and as for the men, once you volunteer to the
Green Berets or the Delta Force or the Navy SEALS, you make a
commitment, a declaration. No one forces them to do it. They go
because of love of country _ or maybe for action and adventure, or
to impress a girlfriend, or to be higher paid. They would like to
serve, because that is what made them a Delta Force.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think we have the adequate intelligence capabilities
for such a mission?
</P>
<P>
   A: Let us take, for instance, the Entebbe raid by the Israelis.
(In 1976, Israeli commandos attacked the airport in Entebbe, Uganda
and freed a hijacked Air France plane full of French tourists
returning from Israel.) At first, the Israelis knew very little
about the whole situation in Entebbe because the hijacking and
hostage-taking happened out of thin air. So there was a tremendous
disadvantage, intelligence-wise, in comparison to the U.S.
advantage, intelligence-wise, appropos Osama bin Laden. We have
known for years that bin Laden is organizing something massive for
terrorist attacks. He has boasted of it on many occasions. So I
should assume this would make him one of the prime intelligence
targets the United States has in the world today. A person like
this is an easy target for a powerful intelligence operation: the
CIA and so forth. It's also in the Pakistani interest to know what
is happening with him, so their agencies are probably working on
it. And all this intelligence would certainly serve our special
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But you don't feel the U.S. counterstrike will be an
effective deterrent?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm afraid the cruise missiles were the equivalent of a
military lip service. It was an operation that really could not
solve a problem. On the contrary, that was almost a knee-jerk
reaction because the military is shouting from here to Timbuktu, so
that all the world can hear, `We can't afford losing people.'
</P>
<P>
   And the moment you say you can't afford losing people, the
terrorists gain a tremendous edge because they know they are not
going to suffer direct contact with American forces. They know they
would lose in any kind of contact with our elite troops. No one is
trained as well.
</P>
<P>
   I believe the goal had to be destroying the people who send the
terrorists, and that didn't happen. It re-exposed our superior
technology, which is fine, but it also affirmed our fear of doing
the right thing and investing the right units, the only ones that
can do the job.
</P>
<P>
   I might add that this is exactly why we failed miserably in the
Persian Gulf War. We invested so many troops, I believe about
600,000, on a thing that 150,000 could have handled easily, and in
the end achieved almost nothing. We did free Kuwait, which is
correct, but it was like taking candy from a baby, and we did it
with such drama, and such pompous superiority. Once we realized we
had to bring down Saddam Hussein, we proved to be nothing. And why,
I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you believe in the concept that the terrorist is not
afraid to die?
</P>
<P>
   A: Absolutely. This is the classic Iranian concept, that for the
terrorists who blow themselves up in buses driving toward embassies
or marketplaces in Israel, it is a tremendous honor. It is the
beginning of a new life. For them, losing lives is a way of life.
The fallen terrorists are `shahids,' the Arab word for martyr. As
martyrs they are going to a fantastic world where they are given
dozens of virgins, gorgeous ones, and they will have a life of
terrific riches, a Donald Trump-style life.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Apparently his followers view bin Laden as a spiritual
leader, a very principled man, with a belief system that is
unwavering, unflinching ...
</P>
<P>
   A: It's as if you would say that also Hitler was a principled
man. What does it mean? That his principles are that other races
are inferior. Therefore they are execution-prone, and should be
burned in the gas chambers. This is more or less what bin Laden
also thinks: that America is Satan, and therefore we are condemned.
He speaks openly of a fatwah on Americans, and jeers at our
soldiers as `paper tigers.' I believe he would sponsor terrorism on
American soil, without any moral hesitation, and establish himself
as a hero for the next 1,000 years in the extremist world. We have
to compare the stomach of facing a terrible loss of 20 or 30 very
good young warriors to the stomach we'd need to face the loss of
millions in a city of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ranan Lurie is a senior adjunct fellow of the Center for
Strategic International Studies. He trained with the elite forces
of the United States, France, Great Britain and Israel. In June
1967, Life magazine published an article, ``A Major's Long Ride to
a Short War,'' about his exploits in the Six Day War. In 1968 they
invited him to the United States as an editorial cartoonist, and
later sponsored his U.S. citizenship. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Carolee B. Morrison is international editor at The New York
Times Syndicate.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
