<HEADER>
A5077 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-FANTASY_BASEBALL-     08-27 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FANTASY_BASEBALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALL-UPS ONLY MEAN TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF CADE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For fantasy league leaders, the final stage of dread is upon you
_ the September call-ups; the minor league prospects the parent
clubs bring up to take a good look at.
</P>
<P>
   But what it really means is that the Geronimo Beroas of the game
go to the bench and are glued there until the end of the season.
And as much as you have learned to despise him, you really need
Beroa's dwindling number of at-bats each week.
</P>
<P>
   What also happens this time of year is that when your player
(Brady Anderson, for instance) gets hurt, the team doesn't bother
to place him on the disabled list, robbing you of a chance to
replace him with some phenom du jour the Expos, Pirates, Reds or
Tigers are trying out.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are contract issues, such as for Wil Cordero and the
White Sox, the sweetest hearts in baseball. The White Sox have
indicated that Cordero, who has an option for next season if he
gets 400 plate appearances, won't get there _ not that he deserves
it. Before you know it, you are down to about eight full-time
players. Your only hope is that the same thing is happening to the
competition. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The killers &QL; 
 &QL; 
For the rest of you owners, especially those destined for fifth,
let's take a warm look at the season's busts by position. For bust
of the year, let's go with Mark Wohlers.
</P>
<P>
   American League &QC;
</P>
<P>
   DH _ Geronimo Beroa.
</P>
<P>
   C _ Sandy Alomar Jr. UGH!
</P>
<P>
   1B _ Frank Thomas - The big Zilch.
</P>
<P>
   2B _ Bip Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   SS _ Kevin Stocker.
</P>
<P>
   3B _ Ed Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   OF _ Mike Cameron, Jay Buhner, Jose Cruz, Brian Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   SP _ Jamie Navarro, John Burkett, Wilson Alvarez, Allen Watson,
LaTroy Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   RP _ Pick a Mariner. Any Mariner.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Morris and Paul Sorrento win dishonorable mention.
</P>
<P>
   National League &QC;
</P>
<P>
   C _ Jorge Fabregas.
</P>
<P>
   1B _ John Jaha.
</P>
<P>
   2B _ Tony Graffanino.
</P>
<P>
   SS _ Manny Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   3B _ Kevin Orie, Matt Williams.
</P>
<P>
   OF _ Lance Johnson, Marquis Grissom, Paul Konerko, Steve Finley,
Karim Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   SP _ Darryl Kile, Willie Blair, Danny Darwin, Bobby Jones.
</P>
<P>
   RP _ Mark Wohlers.
</P>
<P>
   That's a pretty impressive list of players having bad years,
especially Thomas and Jaha. In the year of the three-inch strike
zone, juiced baseball and juiced baseball players, when nearly
every big bopper is having a great year, these guys decide to play
possum. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A miracle &QL; 
 &QL; 
Imagine stumbling into Paul Byrd in time to get his two
complete-game victories last week. What a find, especially at this
time of the season, when such miracles are so hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   Similar miracles are being delivered by the Diamondbacks with
the emergence of Omar Daal and Amaury Telemaco. Who'd a thunk? &QL; 
 &QL; 
The call-ups &QL; 
 &QL; 
Prospects who could play a lot in September include Marlon Anderson
(Phillies); Emil Brown (Pirates); Edgard Clemente and Derrick
Gibson (Rockies); J.D. Drew and Adam Kennedy (Cardinals); Carlos
Guillen (Mariners); Tom Evans and Robert Person (Blue Jays); Mario
Valdez (White Sox); Enrique Wilson (Indians) and Preston Wilson
(Marlins). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
