A5088 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-DEBATE-HNS &LR;      08-27 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S PROBLEMS LOOM IN CALIFORNIA SENATE DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, Calif. _ The first campaign debate between Sen.
Barbara Boxer and Republican challenger Matt Fong saw the first
three questions from panelists centered on President Clinton's
troubles with Monica Lewinsky and Boxer's connections to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In a post-debate news conference, Boxer faced a half-dozen more
questions on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer was a vocal critic of now-Supreme Court Justice Clarence
Thomas and then-Republican Sen. Bob Packwood of Oregon when they
faced accusations of sexual harassment. In addition, Boxer's
daughter is married to Hillary Rodham Clinton's brother.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer has said several times she thinks Clinton's behavior was
wrong, that he should have come forward much sooner. She also has
said Californians should be discussing more substantive issues,
such as her record in the Senate and Fong's positions on issues,
and should let the process decide Clinton's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Fong, the California state treasurer, wasted little time
Wednesday accusing her of using a double standard with her
Democratic president. He called Clinton's behavior embarrassing and
disgusting and claimed he didn't like his children watching TV news
because of the saturation coverage of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps fittingly, the debate was televised live in Los Angeles
on KCAL _ between the ``Jerry Springer Show'' and ``The People's
Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Boxer went out of her way to say she has a
``zero-tolerance'' policy for sexual harassment in her office, she
said it was up to Lewinsky to decide whether Clinton had engaged in
sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been painful, but I think it's been painful for the
American people,'' Boxer said afterward, when asked how the scandal
had affected her personally. ``When a president is under this
cloud, has made a horrible mistake like this, we all feel sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Two recent polls show Boxer and Fong in a dead heat, but Boxer
had at least one great advantage during the debate: Fong's miscues
and occasional vague answers. Fong skipped over phrases, slurred
words and jettisoned his concentration several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara, you're not soft on crime,'' Fong said at one point,
then caught himself and laughed with the audience. He referred to
notes throughout the debate and tried to ridicule Boxer for saying
she had voted against the death penalty 100 times. In fact, she
said exactly the opposite just moments before.
</P>
<P>
   He had trouble explaining some things:
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent has nominated judges, uh, has nominated lawyers,
who for a career sue cops and not only sue cops but make their
life, uh uh, earnings giving seminars on how to sue the police. ...
One judge, for example, took a look at a case where a tourist was
shot in the back of the head in Florida and for $4.05 the Florida
Supreme Court gave a death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Fong's poor performance, the Clinton-Lewinsky problem
dominated the debate, which was held just one day after more bad
news for Boxer: A Field Poll showed her and Fong each with 45
percent support among those surveyed, and only 10 percent
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   For an incumbent with six years in the U.S. Senate, those
numbers aren't encouraging. Even her support from women voters
appeared low in the Field Poll, with the 13 percent advantage among
women she had enjoyed in 1992 now cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's challenged, let's put it that way,'' said
Barbara O'Connor with the Center for the Study of Politics and the
Media at Cal State University at Sacramento. ``So for someone like
Matt, who is kind of steady and not radical and is positioning
himself in the middle of the road, I think he has a very good shot
at the race.''
</P>
<P>
   However, as Boxer pointed out Wednesday, she has yet to place
any ads on TV, the primary source of information for most
Californians. She hasn't sent any mail, and most newspapers and TV
news stations have given the race scant coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer was first elected in 1992 after a brutal campaign against
Republican Bruce Herschensohn, who self-destructed in the final
days after Democrats said he frequented a strip joint and bought
pornography. Boxer has long predicted her 1998 re-election campaign
would be close. She said again Wednesday, ``This will be the
toughest race of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   After the debate, Boxer campaign strategist Roy Behr said that
he didn't know when the Clinton-Lewinsky questions would stop but
that he thought voters didn't care anyway and wouldn't make a link
to Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   The senator did her best to sell that message to the assembled
political reporters and TV audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can stand under a cloud and get nothing done,'' Boxer said,
``or we can do what we have to do for the American people. ... I'm
not going to stand under a cloud.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
