<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5100 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      08-27 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE REITERATES HIS SUPPORT FOR HIS BOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Vice President Al Gore offered an unqualified
defense of President Clinton at a campaign stop Wednesday night,
saying he was ``honored to serve him'' despite discomfort in the
Democratic Party over the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   During a campaign stop in San Francisco, Gore did not
specifically mention the Lewinsky matter or comment on the
president's difficulties. Instead, he took the opportunity in the
middle of a stump speech for the Democratic candidate for
California secretary of state, Michela Alioto, to praise the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud of the leadership that President Bill Clinton has
brought to the United States of America,'' Gore said, coming off a
two-week family vacation in Hawaii. ``I am honored to serve him and
call him a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's comments nearly mirrored a written
statement he issued from Hawaii after Clinton's Aug. 17 address to
the nation in which he admitted having an inappropriate
relationship with Lewinsky while she was a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, Clinton's would-be successor in 2000, is facing problems
of his own. On Wednesday, Attorney General Janet Reno ordered a new
review into whether Gore lied to Justice Department investigators
about his fund-raising activities leading up to the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   At the Alioto fund-raiser, Gore said he had no comment about
Reno's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no formal decision made as I understand it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The highly partisan crowd at the Alioto event, which raised an
estimated $250,000 for her quest to unseat Republican Bill Jones,
stood by the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything there,'' Rep. Nancy Pelosi,
D-Calif., said of the fund-raising allegations. She said the
Justice Department's investigation should clear up questions once
and for all and ``satisfy everyone's concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that Gore remains an important fund-raiser for
Democratic candidates. His appearance in San Francisco, with his
wife, Tipper by his side, was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore will continue to be a big draw. That's not going to be a
problem,'' said Marion Goodman, California president of the
National Women's Political Caucus. ``Gore is a man of high ethics
and I think all this will blow over.''
</P>
<P>
   She had mixed feelings, however, about the president. She said
he was done a great job in promoting the interests of women. But
when it comes to his personal conduct, she said, ``There's
obviously great disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Sen. Alan Cranston, a longtime Democratic
representative from California, also lauded Clinton and Gore's
fund-raising abilities. Both, he said, have star power that is hard
to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still a lot of candidates who want to be seen with
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Democrats are concerned about whether a tainted
Clinton will help or hurt them. Several Democratic congressional
leaders have sharply criticized his conduct in the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0127 </DOCNO>
