<HEADER>
A5105 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-27 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE LOVE, STUPID 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Why is it so hard to believe she actually bought
his lies?
</P>
<P>
   Because she's a lawyer? Because she's got a high IQ? Because
she's ambitious? Because her husband is a politician? Because she's
a feminist? Because she knew he'd cheated before?
</P>
<P>
   What match are those realities against a denial that is fueled
by love and the commitment to a bigger-than-life, multifaceted
marriage?
</P>
<P>
   Those of us out here in the cheap seats may never know
absolutely, positively when Hillary Rodham Clinton learned that her
husband of nearly 22 years had indeed conducted a long-running
sexual affair with a much younger woman. In the White House. Right
under her nose.
</P>
<P>
   According to Newsweek, the president confessed the awful truth
to his wife only a few days before the United States of America got
to hear about it _ on Aug. 13, after an Andrews Air Force Base
ceremony to honor Americans who had been killed in the Nairobi
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting ``knowledgeable sources,'' Newsweek said the first lady
felt ``wounded and betrayed'' and was ``furious.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, many Americans don't believe this. In public-opinion
polls and on the nation's talk shows, they fairly hoot at the idea
that a woman as savvy, sophisticated and political as Hillary
Clinton didn't know all along.
</P>
<P>
   How could she not have known, they say, when two-thirds of the
country hasn't believed Bill Clinton since the whole sordid story
broke in January?
</P>
<P>
   In a USA Today-Gallup poll, some 34 percent of respondents even
theorized that Hillary Clinton has hung in there with her
philandering husband because she ``likes being first lady.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it woman's intuition (or 48 years of living), but
everything I see in HRC's post-confession body language and infer
from her near-silence leads me to believe that she was _ as the
cliche goes _ the last to know. Each time I watch a rerun of her
now-famous ``Today'' show appearance, I'm more convinced.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who looked Matt Lauer straight in the eye and
confidently defended her husband against the vast right-wing
conspiracy's latest dirty trick likely drew her conviction from but
one source: Her beloved spouse had looked her straight in the eye
and sworn he was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   And because she has been crazy in love with him since they met
at Yale Law School, because she has invested more than 25 years of
her life in the ``us'' that they became _ because to allow herself
to doubt would have been to start down a path fraught with danger
and the possible destruction of ``us'' _ she chose to believe him.
</P>
<P>
   Women in love with their husbands often do that. Sometimes women
who aren't in love with their husbands do that, too, because the
``us'' they co-created dwarfs individuals and supersedes all else
in importance.
</P>
<P>
   As therapists and couples counselors will attest, lots of women
with high IQs set doubt aside and choose to believe. Ambitious,
successful women who make more money than their husbands choose to
believe. Women with law degrees believe. Even women who fight for
equal pay and opportunity and keep their own names after they marry
choose to believe.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be logical or conform to our one-dimensional ideas
about how ``smart'' women should behave. But the phenomenon is too
common to ignore as an explanation for the first lady's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1992 presidential campaign, I have kept a semi-candid
picture of Bill and Hillary Clinton tacked up in my office. It was
taken by the celebrity photographer Harry Benson for a People
magazine article that appeared a while after Gennifer Flowers'
notorious revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton is lying in a hammock with his eyes nearly closed
and his lips slightly parted. His wife's face is perhaps two inches
from his. Her own eyes are cast down and her open mouth _ with the
hint of a smile _ is about to deliver a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   I kept the photo because it was one of the sexiest, most
powerfully intimate portraits of two people in love that I'd ever
seen. I look at it today and think: Oh, sure. She stays just
because she likes being first lady.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
