<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5210 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAKISTAN-US-BOS &LR;      08-27 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSILE STRIKE STRAINS FRAGILE US-PAKISTAN TIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.  R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ When US cruise missiles traveled through Pakistani
air space last Thursday to hit suspected Afghan terrorist camps
with links to Pakistani Islamic militants, yet another stress point
emerged in the long, strange relationship between the Washington
and Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
   For half a century, Pakistan has been America's most loyal
friend in one of the world's scariest neighborhoods. At
Washington's request and with American aid, Pakistan served as a
bulwark against communism during the Cold War and a counterweight
to India's dominance of South Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But the last three decades have also been punctuated by
conflict. Pakistan felt abandoned by Washington during two wars
with India. Starting in the 1970s, Washington imposed sanctions on
Islamabad for its development of a nuclear program and added new
sanctions three months ago after Islamabad conducted nuclear
testing.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the two nations have maintained over the years a
delicate partnership that often has been beneficial to both sides.
Particularly important to the US have been joint anti-terrorism
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But today, relations with Islamabad seem once again in peril.
The Pakistani public exploded in rage last week at the US strike.
One missile reportedly landed in southern Pakistan, although it did
not explode. The Pakistani government filed a complaint this week
to the UN Security Council over US violation of its airspace.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistanis claiming to be students at religious schools in
Afghanistan were among those injured in the US strike on the
neighboring country. Some of them were reportedly accompanied to
hospitals by Pakistani intelligence agents. Observers believe that
the presence of those agents exposes Islamabad's covert support for
Islamic militants training in the neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the sanctions imposed after Pakistan conducted
nuclear tests last May have further damaged an already crippled
economy, and they have emboldened radicals bent on discrediting the
current government and fueling anti-United States sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   As the US adopts an uncompromising stand against terrorism,
often without consulting its allies, it risks alienating Pakistan.
If the current strains imperil its government, Islamabad may think
twice about cooperating with Washington in turning over suspected
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is trying damage control, but it is under
tremendous pressure to outright denounce American actions,'' said
Rifaat Hussain, an international relations professor at
Quaid-i-Azam University in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pakistan feels we have been there every time the US needed
us,'' he continued, ``in 1979, with the Soviet invasion of
Afghanistan, during the Cold War.'' Also, he said, Pakistan has
captured and handed over to American authorities major terrorism
suspects _ including the mastermind of the World Trade Center
bombing and the killer of two CIA agents in a rampage at CIA
headquarters in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's US missile attack into Afghanistan _ launched
apparently without notifying Islamabad _ occurred just days after
Pakistani authorities detained and transferred to Kenya Mohammed
Sadik Howaida, a suspect in the Aug. 7 attacks on two US embassies
in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The underlying sentiment is, `why should we cooperate?''' said
Hussain. ``We cooperate and we get kicked back in the teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a roller-coaster relationship, it's true,'' concedes an
Islamabad-based Western diplomat, ``but even during rough patches,
the two countries have always been able to conduct business. At the
same time, there is reason to be concerned about Taliban-style
schools in Pakistan, training Pakistanis.''
</P>
<P>
   Just two days ago (Aug. 25), top US and Pakistani officials met
in London for the fourth round of talks since May focusing on
another delicate subject: Islamabad's recent nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement released Wednesday in Islamabad, both sides
called for resumption of talks between India and Pakistan, and for
the International Monetary Fund to provide a $3 billion financing
package to avert a $30 billion loan default.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Pakistani official who spoke on condition of anonymity
downplayed the current tensions, saying there are ``ups and downs
like any other relationship.'' He added, ``We have not seen the
results that we've expected at times, and they have not seen the
results that they have always wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   But that diplomatic language masks an underlying distrust of
Washington by Islamabad that is three decades old.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bombing and the repeated taking of Pakistan for granted
has sent people into absolute outrage,'' said Agha Murtaza Pooya,
editor of a national newspaper, The Muslim. Much of the anger is
directed at Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's government, which is
perceived to have ``capitulated to US demands.''
</P>
<P>
   The first casualty of popular rage, he said, could be Sharif's
moderate administration. But the long-term victim would be the
bilateral relationship, especially if a radical regime were to
assume power.
</P>
<P>
   Pooya called the 51 year-old US-Pakistani relationship ``an
engaged standoff'' in which the two countries have ``never broken
off, but never really had a consensus.'' He said, ``We have been in
the same bed, but having different dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Nesim Zehra, a foreign affairs columnist for two Pakistan
dailies, The News and The Nation, explained: ``All along they were
essentially pursuing different objectives.'' The US was worried
first about communism, and later about Muslim fundamentalism.
Pakistan, meanwhile, has worried mainly about arch-rival India.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Pakistan has tried to achieve a delicate balance
in its relations with the United States, the Soviet Union, China
and Islamic nations, but it has not satisfied any of them.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1950s, the United States considered Pakistan a buffer
against Soviet domination in Asia. India, a more powerful player in
the region, refused to take sides in the superpower conflict.
Pakistan agreed to host US military bases, and in 1954 and 1959,
signed two military agreements with the US committing Washington to
to aid Pakistan in time of war.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, a US spy plane launched from a base in Pakistan was
shot down in Soviet airspace. The USSR vowed to launch a nuclear
strike against Pakistan if a superpower war erupted. This threat
put Pakistan at great risk because of its alliance with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in 1965, when Pakistan and India fought a war over Kashmir,
the United States cut off supplies to Pakistan. In 1971, when the
two countries fought again over the secession of East Pakistan,
which became the country of Bangladesh, the United States did
little to help Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, the United States needed Pakistan and its military
support when the USSR invaded Afghanistan. Throughout the 1980s,
the US funnelled billions of dollars through Pakistan to Afghan
rebels and temporarily lifted sanctions against Islamabad. Some of
those fighters later joined the Taliban militia and various
terrorist organizations. After the war ended, the United States
reimposed sactions and refused even to deliver the $1.2 billion in
military equipment for which Pakistan had already paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the womb of that war, parented by the US and Pakistan,
you have the likes of Osama bin Laden,'' Zehra said. In the
long-standing US-Pakistan ``marriage of convenience, were the seeds
of the Afghan `jihad' (holy war).''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she added, for practical reasons, neither Pakistan
nor the United States can walk away from the union. ``The US
controls the IMF, the World Bank, all the lending agencies from
which Pakistan desperately needs support.''
</P>
<P>
   The only solution, she said, is for there to be ``a maturing in
each country pursuing its own national interest _ interests that
have rarely coincided.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
