<HEADLINE>
BACHRACH'S LIBERAL LABEL QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As a candidate for the 8th Congressional District,
former state senator George Bachrach promotes himself as the
``unabashed, unapologetic, unreconstructed liberal'' in the race _
a smart message in an overwhelmingly liberal district.
</P>
<P>
   But in his years in the private sector as an attorney and
lobbyist, Bachrach has worked to gain access to government
decision-makers on behalf of corporate clients and
special-interests groups on both sides of the ideological fence.
And he represented businesses in causes that were not entirely
progressive: helping dry cleaners water down a state toxic
materials law; aiding a trash-burning operator with a history of
environmental problems; and advising a developer who went afoul of
public bidding laws and eventually built the ``sick building'' for
the Registry of Motor Vehicles in Roxbury.
</P>
<P>
   Bachrach defends his private-sector work and says efforts to
portray him as something other than liberal is a sign that his
opponents are getting desperate and have begun waging a smear
campaign against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sleep well at night. Just because you call yourself an
unabashed liberal doesn't mean you don't work for a living,''
Bachrach said this week. ``I represented hundreds of clients, and
it's easy to single a few out and distort what happened with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Others in the 10-way 8th District race in the Democratic primary
say there's nothing wrong with Bachrach's work in the private
sector, but that he has opened himself up to criticism because he
has been touting his liberalism as so pure. It might be more
accurate, some suggest, for Bachrach to say he's an unabashed
liberal on schools or health care for seniors, but has also fought
for business interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're out on the trail with George, sometimes you feel
like you just have to bite your tongue. It goes to candor and
honesty,'' said former state representative Marjorie Clapprood. ``I
don't mind when he speaks to his background, but it's very
frustrating and disingenuous to say you're the champion when you're
not. I guess some of his hyberbole has caught up with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bachrach did indeed have hundreds of clients as a partner in the
law firm of Brown, Rudnick, Freed and Gresmer from 1987 to 1995. A
look at some of them suggests that at least during that period of
his career he sometimes set aside his liberal leanings on behalf of
his client.
</P>
<P>
   _In 1989, Bachrach was paid $5,000 to lobby on behalf of
Northeast Fabricare, a dry-cleaners group, and was successful in
excluding a chemical from the draft of the state's toxic use
reduction law. Bachrach said the chemical was not proven to be
harmful and was critical for ``mostly mom-and-pop businesses'' to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   _Bachrach represented the New Jersey-based firm Odgen Martin in
locating a trash-burning facility in Haverhill, arguing against
efforts by the Haverhill Board of Public Health for tighter
emissions standards. The company has had a troubled history,
receiving violation notices from the Environmental Protection
Agency concerning emissions, for example. Questions have also been
raised about the kinds of trash allowed to be burned at the
Haverhill facility and whether dioxin emissions there exceeded
federal standards. Bachrach said the company jumped through all the
required environmental hoops and that he had no knowledge of any
problems.
</P>
<P>
   _Starting in 1989, Bachrach helped Metropolitan
Structures/Columbia Plaza Ventures in its quest to locate
Massachusetts Water and Sewer Commission headquarters on Parcel 18
in Roxbury. The effort was derailed in part after state officials
said the company failed to adhere to public bidding requirements.
The same company later built the Registry of Motor Vehicles
building on the site, which had to be vacated _ at a cost of over
$14 million _ because of ventilation-related health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bachrach said that he was fighting for economic development for
Roxbury, had nothing to do with the public-bidding aspect of the
project, and stopped working for the company before the Registry
debacle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
