<HEADLINE>
_NEW APPROACH SEEN FOR CLOGGED ARTERIES   
 _FOR IN VITRO METHOD, 2 EMBRYOS COULD DO   
 _CALCIUM SAID TO CURB THE SYMPTOMS OF PMS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 New approach seen for clogged arteries
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years, scientists have suspected that atherosclerosis, the
buildup of fatty plaque inside blood vessel walls that can
eventually cause a heart attack or stroke, involves not just
cholesterol but also a condition called inflammation _ an influx of
white blood cells that eat the cholesterol, then hang around,
creating clumps of debris that block arteries.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, it has not been clear what chemical signals cause
white blood cells to rush in, or how to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   This week, two teams of scientists, one writing in the journal
Nature and the other in Molecular Cell, report on ways to block the
white cells, opening the way for a new class of drugs that would
act differently from the current ``statin'' medications that simply
lower cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams studied a chemokine, or signal molecule, called
MCP-1, whose job is to call white cells to the scene of tissue
injury or damage, like that caused by cholesterol on artery walls.
</P>
<P>
   At Dana-Farber Cancer Institute in Boston, Dr. Barrett Rollins,
a medical oncologist, studied a strain of mice bred to have high
cholesterol and also to lack the gene that makes MCP-1.
</P>
<P>
   His team fed a high cholesterol diet to these mice and to a
control group that had the MCP-1 gene. After 25 weeks, the arteries
in the control mice ``looked terrible, like those of people who'd
been smoking and eating cheeseburgers for years,'' said Rollins. By
contrast, the mice missing the MCP-1 gene were healthy and had 80
percent less atherosclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   The other team, led by Dr. Israel F. Charo, associate director
of the Gladstone Institute of Cardiovascular Disease at the
University of San Francisco, and colleagues Landin Boring and
Jennifa Gosling, also studied atherosclerotic mice.
</P>
<P>
   They studied mice that had the gene for the signaling molecule
but lacked the gene for the receptor on white blood cells that
reacts to MCP-1. On a high cholesterol diet, the mice without the
MCP-1 receptor got only half as much atherosclerosis as mice in the
control group that had the receptor, Charo said.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the studies suggest that drugs to block MCP-1 or
its receptor could be a promising way to treat patients with high
cholesterol. Several companies are working on such drugs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; For in vitro method, 2 embryos could do
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For women hoping to bear a child by in vitro fertilization,
implantation of two embryos may work as well as implanting more,
and it carries a lower risk of multiple births, a new study of more
than 25,000 women shows.
</P>
<P>
   British researchers, writing in the current New England Journal
of Medicine, found that implantation of two embryos yielded the
same birth rate as implantation of three or more, provided the
fertilization process _ done outside the body in test tubes _
yielded at least four fertilized eggs. Having many such eggs boosts
the odds because doctors have more to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David R. Meldrum, scientific director of Reproductive
Partners Medical Group in Redondo Beach, Calif., criticized the
study's design, but said that if doctors let embryos grow for five
days, not merely three, then implanting only two embryos does make
sense. The key is that it is easier to select good embryos when
they are five days old, said Meldrum, who co-authored an editorial
accompanying the research.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Calcium said to curb the symptoms of PMS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A study led by researchers at St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital in
New York suggests that calcium may reduce symptoms of premenstrual
syndrome, including mood swings, water retention, food cravings and
pain.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Susan Thys-Jacobs, an endocrinologist, reported this week in
the American Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology that she studied
466 women aged 18 to 45 who had documented symptoms of PMS. Half
the women were randomly assigned to take 1,200 milligrams a day of
calcium carbonate, in the form of Tums, for three months, and half,
a placebo. Neither researchers nor patients knew who was getting
the calcium. SmithKline Beecham, Inc., the maker of Tums, helped
fund the study.
</P>
<P>
   By the third cycle, calcium appeared to reduce symptoms by 48
percent, although symptoms were also reduced by 30 percent in the
control group. It's unclear why calcium would help with PMS, but it
may restore an underlying physiological imbalance.
</P>
</TEXT>
