<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5223 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIMBERLAND-HYBRID-BOS     08-27 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMBERLAND-HYBRID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TIMBERLAND, BEIGE MAY HELP ERASE THE RED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Timberland Co. calls them ``beige shoes,'' a hybrid between
sneakers and hiking boots. Others refer to them as ``cross trainers
for the new millenium'' or ``SUVs for the feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Want to compete in a triathalon or drive your Jeep Cherokee deep
into the wilderness? Then beige shoes may be for you.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after it took an apparent fashion hit from Nike Inc.
and recorded the only annual loss of its 45-year history,
Timberland hopes that its turnaround story will continue to be
driven by new products such as this year's beige shoe.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the entire footwear industry could use a lift.
Sales for most companies are ``flat,'' notes new chief executive
Jeffrey B. Swartz, the third generation of his family to run the
Stratham, N.H.-based company now known as Timberland.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of the reason we have the beige initiative,'' says
Swartz, adding that new products are crucial to success.
</P>
<P>
   In the curious world of leisure footwear, shoes are sometimes
broadly grouped into two categories that have more to do with
styles and market segmentation than they do with color.
</P>
<P>
   There are white shoes, known by the laity as sneakers. Then
there are brown shoes, a cobbler's euphemism for just about
everything from hiking boots to Doc Martens.
</P>
<P>
   Given their popularity with young folks, these categories are
subject to the whims of fashion and wild sales swings.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the 1990s, white shoes were king, and Nike ruled.
But over the last year or so, sneaker sales have cooled off.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, purveyors of brown shoes ``see a window of
opportunity,'' notes editor Bob McGee in a recent edition of
Sporting Goods Intelligence, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Timberland isn't the only one to see a window of opportunity for
beige shoes, which combine the best elements of white shoes and
brown shoes. (Blend white and brown and get beige.)
</P>
<P>
   For the last few years, Nike has been toying with versions of a
beige shoe. The goal is to create a shoe as comfortable and
lightweight as a sneaker but sturdy enough for rugged terrain.
</P>
<P>
   According to Timberland, its fascination with beige shoes was an
outgrowth of two trends: America's love affair with the
sport-utility vehicle and a growing boredom among exercise
enthusiasts with working out at the gym.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, most SUV owners were content to cruise
suburban byways, but as the decade wore on many began to use these
vehicles for the purpose for which they were intended. And when
these off-road explorers finally arrived in the wilderness, they
found they wanted something on their feet other than jogging shoes
designed for treadmills and running tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, something similar was going on at the health club.
Unable to cope with the tedium of the Stairmaster, fitness buffs
were fleeing the gym to jog and bike on mountain trails.
</P>
<P>
   It was for these hearty breeds that Timberland designed the
Gorge MPO, the formal name it has given to its beige shoe line.
(MPO stands for multi-purpose outdoor.)
</P>
<P>
   Combining the leather of a hiking boot with the synthetic
materials used to make sneakers, Gorge MPO shoes are expected to
reach retailers this fall. Depending on the model, the shoes will
have a suggested retail price of $75 to $90.
</P>
<P>
   Price could be a problem, notes McGee of Sporting Goods
Intelligence. Stores are so glutted with sneakers that some
retailers are offering discounts. Will consumers pay 90 bucks for
beige shoes when bargain Nikes abound?
</P>
<P>
   When Swartz's grandfather Nathan bought the Abington (Mass.)
Shoe Co. in the early 1950s, the world of white and brown shoes
wasn't so complex. In a small Boston factory, a Russian immigrant
was content to make shoes for retailers such as Thom McAn.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, Nathan Swartz left Boston after buying a shoe factory
in Newmarket, N.H. Along with the plant, Swartz and his two sons,
Sidney and Herman, inherited some of the factory's old customers,
including a contract to make boots for L.L. Bean.
</P>
<P>
   The plant's custodian, a guy named Joe Butler, wasn't overly
impressed with the Swartzes' first effort at making boots. Why
couldn't these big city hotshots make boots that could keep feet
warm and dry through a New Hampshire winter?, Butler demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a real Newmarket guy,'' Jeffrey Swartz says of Butler.
``First wave Guadalcanal, a steel plate in his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Stung, the Swartzes rose to Butler's challenge. Nathan Swartz
invented a stitch pattern that stopped leaks. The result was the
Timberland Yellow Boot. Walk five miles in a river, and your feet
would stay dry in Timberlands, the Swartzes boasted.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced in 1973, the boot became so popular that Abington
changed its name to Timberland a few years later, and a boot that
found favor with both college students and construction workers
propelled sales for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   As it branched out into boat shoes and casual-shoe lines,
Timberland had another hit in the late 1980s with a boot called the
Euro Hiker.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid 1990s, though, no one model could carry a company. In
some ways, shoe companies had become like record companies _ every
few months they need a new hit, and in 1995, Timberland didn't have
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our new product failed us,'' Jeffrey Swartz says of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   And so the company was overhauled to churn out new shoe models.
At first glance, those efforts appear to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, new products accounted for about 50 percent of
Timberland's revenues of $797 million, Swartz says. In the early
1990s, new products generated only about 15 percent of sales.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, 1997 profits more than doubled to $47.3 million. For
Timberland's most recent quarter, profits were $1.9 million, up
from $600,000 a year ago. Revenues rose nearly 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Wall Street has blown hot and cold on Timberland.
After trading above 85 in May, the stock hit a 52-week low
Wednesday of 47 5/8. On the New York Stock Exchange, Timberland
shares fell 3 1/16 to close at 49 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   According to Buckingham Research Group analyst Lee F. Backus,
the entire shoe industry is in disfavor with investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing fine,'' he says of Timberland. ``They're a very
strong brand.''
</P>
<P>
   That strong brand has just been entrusted to Jeffrey Swartz, 38,
who recently inherited the titles of president and chief executive
from his father, Sidney Swartz, Timberland's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Swartz's challenge is to preserve Timberland's heritage
as it develops new products for a changing market.
</P>
<P>
   A company that once made boots for men now sells boots, shoes,
and clothing for men, women, and children.
</P>
<P>
   A company once known for expensive leather footwear is now
offering cheaper lines made with some synthetic materials.
</P>
<P>
   A company that once sponsored the Iditarod dogsled race now
appeals to consumers' social conscience. ``Pull up your boots and
make a difference'' is one theme of a new ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the current environment, it's hard to rely on just one style.
This fall, Timberland is offering about 200 shoe models.
</P>
<P>
   But while Timberland won't rise and fall on the fate of the
beige shoe, it still has high hopes for its Gorge MPO.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the world demands a beige shoe,'' Jeffrey Swartz says,
``we'll show you what the boot guy can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
