<HEADLINE>
IBM SWIMS AGAINST THE TIDE WITH HIGH-END APTIVA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that we're all comfortable with the idea of buying really
cheap home computers, IBM Corp. is stepping out with a bold new
strategy _ selling really expensive home computers.
</P>
<P>
   The Aptiva SE7, nicknamed Cobra, is the hottest box IBM has ever
built for home users. It features a 450-megahertz Intel Pentium II
processor, a DVD-ROM drive that can show razor-sharp digital
movies, and a hulking 16.8 gigabyte hard drive, all in a sleek
black case that IBM executives compare to the look of an Air Force
Stealth fighter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Either you want the fastest thing or you want the best
style,'' said Ellen Reid Smith, vice president of worldwide
marketing for IBM's consumer products division. ``The stealth
series we're bringing out has both.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cobra will come to market after Labor Day and carry a list
price of $2,399, enough to pay for a couple of lesser machines.
Computer buffs with money to burn can also invest in a matching
15-inch flat-panel monitor for $999, available in October.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can buy an entire computer for $999 these days.
But Smith says there's a hunger for high-end hardware. She says
that despite all the hoopla over cheap computers, only about 20
percent of PCs purchased this year will cost less than $1,000, not
including monitor. Meanwhile, machines priced above $2,000 will get
nearly as big a slice &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; about 18 percent of the market. Right
now, said Smith, most of that high-end business is going to the big
direct marketers like Dell Computer Corp. and Gateway 2000 Inc. Now
IBM is determined to get its share.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a bad move, according to Aaron Goldberg, executive vice
president of industry research firm Ziff-Davis Market Intelligence.
``What IBM is saying is, there's a person out there who wants to
buy the Cadillac,'' said Goldberg. Indeed, a better example might
be the Dodge Viper, the radical high-end sports car produced in
small numbers by Chrysler Corp. Just adding the Viper to its
product line helped Chrysler sell its lesser models as well.
Goldberg said the Cobra could do the same for IBM's line of PCs.
``There's a certain halo effect that having something really cool
gives them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
