<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5233 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-27 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PROBLEM WITH CELLUCCI'S `ELECTABILITY'  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF JACOBY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can Joe Malone win?
</P>
<P>
   In mid-April, anyone but the state treasurer's diehard loyalists
would have answered that question with a snort of amusement.
Surveys of likely Republican primary voters showed him getting
creamed nearly 3-to-1 by acting Governor Paul Cellucci. Party
leaders were urging Malone to drop his challenge. Their urgings
were punctuated at the party convention in Worcester, where a
crushing majority of the delegates endorsed Cellucci. It seemed
clear that Malone would be looking for work before the year was
out.
</P>
<P>
   That, as they say, was then. Now, less than three weeks out, the
outcome of this battle isn't clear at all.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's political momentum is gone. It began leaking soon
after the convention, when polls showed him edging Attorney General
Scott Harshbarger, the leading Democratic candidate, with only 40
percent support. By early August, Harshbarger was edging him. If
Cellucci's stock is falling among voters overall, it is probably
falling among Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to forget that Cellucci has never run for statewide
office in his own right. Unlike Malone, who won commanding
victories in 1990 and 1994, and William Weld, who stormed to
reelection four years ago with the widest margin of any
Massachusetts governor in a century, Cellucci's status is unearned.
When Weld up and quit, Cellucci inherited his constitutional powers
and Corner Office keys. But Weld's popularity was never part of the
package.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion to acting governor gave Cellucci a year's head
start on his long-anticipated contest with Malone, a natural born
campaigner. Yet instead of using those 12 months to earn the trust
and affection of his party's rank-and-file, he immediately went to
work ingratiating himself with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The new governor showed up at a Teamsters picket line to endorse
the union's strike against UPS. He showed up at a Democratic
gathering in Lowell to endorse Hillary Clinton's $21 billion
day-care scheme. Yet he didn't show up when The Boston Globe
invited him to a forum for Republican candidates. For a while he
even balked at promising to show up for the traditional Republican
Unity Breakfast on the day after the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Like Elliot Richardson in 1984, Cellucci is running as a
don't-hold-my-party-against-me Republican. When Paul Tsongas
retired from the Senate, Richardson _ the former US secretary of
everything, the hero of the Saturday Night Massacre _ was the
choice of the Republican establishment to run for the open seat.
Early polls and conventional wisdom had him soundly defeating the
more conservative Ray Shamie, who had been in the race even before
Tsongas's announcement. Foolishly, Richardson believed the hype.
Presuming that he had the primary locked up, he campaigned openly
for Democratic votes. GOP voters didn't appreciate being taken for
granted. Shamie won in a 25-point landslide.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between Cellucci and Malone is not as stark as
Richardson-Shamie. Malone is not nearly as conservative as Shamie,
and Cellucci is no Richardsonian liberal. Moreover, while the
candidates in 1984 were campaigning for an open seat, the fight
this time is between an incumbent and a challenger. Massachusetts
voters are loath to turn out incumbents; Massachusetts Republicans,
who have so few incumbents to begin with, especially so.
</P>
<P>
   But as in '84, one candidate is going out of his way to make
ideology the issue, while the other stresses electability. Cellucci
says, in effect: I'm the better candidate. Malone says: I'm the
better Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The Cellucci camp is betting that what Republican voters want
most is to hang on to the governor's office. Their strategy has
been to attack Malone as a spoiler, a hopeless candidate whose
selfishness is jeopardizing his party's chances in November. Stick
with Cellucci, the acting governor's ads imply, or big-spending
Dukakoids will once again be running the show.
</P>
<P>
   That's a good pitch, especially to moderates whose Republicanism
turns on party loyalty, not philosophy. But it only works if
Cellucci radiates strength. When polls showed him ahead of every
other candidate, the electability argument was hard to rebut. When
they show him losing traction and slipping behind Democrats, it
becomes hard to sustain.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson Malone learned in 1984 _ he ran Shamie's campaign _
is that Republicans thrive when they sharply distinguish themselves
from Democrats and fight hard over principles. For 7 1/2 years, the
Weld-Cellucci record has been one of muting ideological
differences, cutting deals with Democrats, refusing to draw lines
in the sand. The result is that big-spending Dukakoids are already
running the show _ and that Republicans, despite holding the
governor's office, are all but irrelevant in crafting state policy.
</P>
<P>
   Malone calls himself ``the conservative for governor''; his ads
say of Cellucci, ``He really is a liberal.'' But his strategy is
less about labels than about meaning. I'm a Republican who stands
for something, he is telling primary voters. Don't base your vote
on sterile calculations about winnability, base it on your gut
beliefs _ on the reason you're a Republican in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, Malone is right: Great parties are built on
philosophy, not pragmatism. But elections are waged in the short
run. Malone has three weeks left to set GOP hearts aflame. It's not
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Jacoby is a Globe columnist. His e-mail address is
jacoby(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5234 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-DIVERSITY-BOS     08-27 1326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-DIVERSITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE PROGRAMS STRIVE TO BE LABORATORIES OF DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WALTHAM, Mass. _ This summer, Julius Wilder spent most of his
waking hours, often seven days a week, conducting painstaking DNA
immunology research that would cause most college students to flee
for the beach. The 20-year-old junior wasn't intimidated or bored
by his experience, however; he was juiced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has made me excited to enter this world,'' Wilder said
recently between experiments at a Brandeis University lab. ``But I
have to admit it's kind of daunting, at times, to look and see that
there's almost nobody in this world who looks like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Decades after other disciplines diversified their ranks, or at
least began drawing upward trend lines for women and minorities,
the sciences remain starkly white and male.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks, along with Hispanics and Native Americans, accounted for
just 6.5 percent of the job market in science and engineering in
1995, according to statistics compiled by the National Science
Foundation. The comparable figure for women, whose participation in
most careers approaches or equals that of men, was 22.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of these continuing disparities _ perhaps the
largest gender and racial gaps in any profession today _ American
colleges and universities are aggressively pursuing an array of
initiatives directed at ``underrepresented minorities'' and women.
They are doing so despite the assault on affirmative-action and
set-aside programs nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the public generally understands the problem,
and it goes beyond just wanting to make the sciences representative
for reasons of principle,'' said Freeman Hrabowski III, president
of the University of Maryland-Baltimore County. That institution's
Meyerhoff Scholarship program is considered one of the most
ambitious, successful efforts in the country to move blacks into
the sciences.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a national priority to eliminate the gap in the health
status between minorities and the white population,'' Hrabowski
added. ``To reach that goal, the country needs ... scientists who
understand the social and environmental backgrounds of the
populations involved. The sciences need everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The diversity efforts aimed at women and other minorities, some
involving small amounts of money and others entailing millions of
dollars, all have the same goals: to lure their targets into
science education, to maintain their interest in subjects that can
be dry and rigorous, and to lead them into related careers.
</P>
<P>
   Boston University, for instance, has a half-million-dollar piece
of a $65 million US government endeavor to develop prototypes for
21st century high-tech computing. About $500,000 of the national
total is aimed specifically at promoting participation by women,
blacks, Hispanics, and Native Americans. Roscoe Giles, deputy
director of BU's Center for Computational Sciences, said there is
an ``overall emphasis'' throughout the project to include members
of those groups.
</P>
<P>
   Asians are not considered ``underrepresented minorities''
because their percentages among students and workers in
science-related fields consistently exceed their proportion (3
percent) of the general American population.
</P>
<P>
   Brandeis administers a fellowship project in which 25 of its own
students are joined each summer by six high-achieving minorities _
three black undergraduates from the University of
Maryland-Baltimore County and three Hispanics from the University
of Puerto Rico. The idea, funded with a total of $775,000 in
renewable grants since 1993, is to show off the best of the
sciences by paying the expenses of students who otherwise might not
get exposed to a prestigious institution, and letting them work
with some of the country's top academics and scientists.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of hands-on, one-student-at-a-time approach is typical
of programs throughout the United States. And, although statistics
show only small progress, participants insist their projects are
steadily chipping away at a historic problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not 100 percent but the success rate, ... based on
hearing from past students who now work in the sciences, is really
good,'' said Joan Press, a biology professor who runs the Brandeis
program. ``We're making headway, no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, National Research Council reports show that, from 1977
to 1995, the proportion of all master's degrees in the natural
sciences and engineering earned by blacks rose from 3.9 percent to
5.3 percent; from 3.1 to 5.8 percent for Hispanics; and from 0.4 to
0.5 percent for Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   While only nibbling at the edges of the problem in the short
run, the long-range intent of these targeted programs is to change
the image of and atmosphere within the sciences. Most try to do
that at institutions of higher education, thereby creating more
role models, but many initiatives also are designed to reshape the
perceptions of younger females and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   A few examples:
</P>
<P>
   _Eighty urban teenagers in eighth to 10th grade nationwide,
including three from the Boston area, attended a weeklong camp at
the University of Minnesota earlier this month sponsored by the
Association of Science and Technology Centers and the National
Association of Biology Teachers. The students studied bugs and
plants, but they were also part of a bigger effort to get
youngsters interested in science careers.
</P>
<P>
   _The National Science Foundation, which directs tens of millions
of dollars into initiatives nationwide to attract women and
minorities, began the Black Churches Initiative six years ago. In
that project, adults who run day-care centers and other children's
programs in 5,000 US churches are trained to teach young people
about various sciences.
</P>
<P>
   _The public school system in Hartford, which is 94 percent
minority and is the second-largest in New England, is in the middle
of a five-year, multimillion-dollar project _ funded by the
National Science Foundation _ aimed at tripling the number of its
black and Hispanic students who enter science, math, and
engineering tracks when they go on to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way we can change the current situation, which badly
needs changing ... is to expose people to the sciences earlier, and
in a positive, appealing way,'' said Steven Zottoli, a biology
professor at Williams College who administers a $900,000 grant
directed toward women and minorities at his school, as well as two
other projects with the same targets.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the public National Science Foundation, which was
established by Congress, the most vigorous advocate for women and
minorities is the Howard Hughes Medical Institute. ``We very much
have taken on as one of our goals to get a full cross-section of
American society into the sciences,'' said David Jarmul, a
spokesman for the Maryland-based institute, which is primarily a
research facility with a $500 million budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Hughes Institute spends about $90 million a year on
educational efforts outside its walls, much of it intended directly
or indirectly to diversify the sciences. The Brandeis and Williams
College programs are both funded by Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the others are a $300,000 project called CityLab, run out
of Boston University's School of Medicine and designed to expose
high school students to scientific research; a $2.25 million
program at the College of the Holy Cross in Worcester, which seeks
to better train that city's teachers in science-teaching skills;
and $2.6 million in subsidies to the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology for summer programs for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may disagree about the remedy, but there's no question
that it's an insane situation,'' said Giles of Boston University,
referring to the racial and gender gulf in the sciences. ``It's so
big that you have to do something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
