<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OK, SO I WASN'T EXACTLY RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)``Now comes the iMac _ clean, elegant, floppy-free _ and
doomed.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   HIAWATHA BRAY, MAY 14, 1998 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many fans of Apple Computer Inc.'s Macintosh machines wanted to
carve these words on my tombstone after reading my skeptical view
of the new iMac. But they let me live, and so I shall treat them to
a minute's gloating at my expense.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac doomed? Faugh! They're selling faster than Powerball
tickets. And some early surveys suggest that many buyers are people
who have never owned a computer before, or people who have had it
with Microsoft Windows and crave the simplicity of the Mac OS
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   And check this out _ despite the iMac craze, Apple is producing
enough machines to meet demand. This may be the best news of all.
Apple's huge losses of recent years were  &UR;  &LR; in large part due to the
firm's inability to ship enough merchandise to stores during the
holidays. The iMac story suggests that Apple's new management team
is on its way to licking that problem.
</P>
<P>
   So the iMac is selling well, and Apple is off the critical list.
Cigars all around.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I've been playing with a loaner iMac for the past week,
and I find the experience as underwhelming as I &UR;  &LR; had expected. I
plan on giving the machine a more thorough test _ in fact, I've
persuaded my bosses at the Globe to buy me one for use in the
newsroom. But If I was spending my own $1,300, I'd still opt for a
PC and leave the cute little Mac on a shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Well, there's still the matter of that missing floppy disk
drive, and the absence of serial and parallel ports. Apple
partisans are ready with a litany of excuses _ nobody uses floppy
disks anymore, and the iMac has universal serial bus ports in place
of the old serial and parallel ports.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact remains that the iMac lacks useful features
available on the cheapest PC. Apple forces its customers to spend
hundreds more on external floppy drives and USB printer adapters,
then expects them to be thankful for the extra expense. Everybody
would howl if Microsoft pulled such a stunt. But Apple can spit on
its faithful customers and convince them it's raining.
</P>
<P>
   I've got a few other hardware gripes. The iMac mouse, for
instance, is the worst ever. It's a small cylindrical gadget that
looks like half a yo-yo. Most mice have an oblong shape, and a few
minutes with the iMac mouse reminds you why _ more support for the
hand and wrist. The iMac mouse offers almost no support at all.
Thank heaven that you can easily replace it. To its credit, the
iMac worked perfectly with a USB mouse from Logitech that was
designed for use with PCs.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac's built-in speakers are nearly as bad as the mouse,
though in fairness, most PCs also come with lousy speakers, and you
can always upgrade. The iMac also uses the same kind of flimsy
CD-ROM drive found on laptops, not the big, heavy kind found on
desktop PCs and the more costly Macs. Will the drive survive years
of heavy use? I have my doubts.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, the keyboard, though thin and light, has an
excellent feel. And the built-in 15-inch monitor is as sharp as any
I've seen.
</P>
<P>
   Apple is talking up the brute speed of the iMac's Power PC
processor, claiming it's faster than any Pentium II. I haven't
benchmarked the iMac, but CMP Media Inc. has run tests on a variety
of Apple systems using Power PC chips. The results won't thrill
Apple execs. CMP Media found that Power PCs are indeed faster than
comparable Pentium II chips. As a result, Macs tend to be faster on
programs like Photoshop, which require massive amounts of raw
processing power. But the &UR;  &LR; Macs were actually slower on mundane
tasks like word processing and spreadsheets _ the kinds of things
most people do with computers.
</P>
<P>
   So am I warning readers away from the iMac? Not at all.
Certainly not after setting it up, and going from box to Internet
in a matter of minutes. Ease of use counts for a lot in my book,
and the iMac has it in spades. If you want a simple, high-quality
machine, and you don't mind spending a few hundred bucks on extras,
you'll do fine with an iMac. It's clean, elegant, floppy-free _ and
definitely not doomed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
