<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NUMEROLOGIST'S PREDICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 18 months ago my husband was in a mellow frame of mind. In
his early 60s, he was ready to take the long view. Though he might
not have reached his full potential, he felt he had much to be
proud of. He was satisfied to have reached the stage of life when
his career and personal ambition were winding down. He'd begun to
feel he could use a lot more golf in his life.
</P>
<P>
   For his birthday in April, however, his friend Rick gave him
what I thought was a rather odd gift, a visit with a numerologist
named Louisa Poole. That name conjured up in my mind images of a
little old lady from a child's story, someone bent and wrinkled who
pretends to read tea leaves or crystal balls, a figment of
someone's imagination. I thought Jack felt the same until he
reached for the phone to make an appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack, you don't believe in that stuff,'' I said. ``Don't call
her. No one can read the future.'' He ignored me. ``Hon, you know
it's only a combination of guesswork and flattery. You're too grown
up for this kind of foolishness.'' He began rifling through his
date book. ``OK, go,'' I said, ``but don't expect me to take one
word of what she says seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack returned from his reading in a pensive mood. Poole had
informed him, among other things, that it was too soon to think of
resting on his laurels. She'd said that he had important work still
to accomplish on this earth, that his greatest challenge was before
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did she say what it was?'' I asked. No, she hadn't. ``Do you
have any idea what it might be?'' No, he didn't. So for months Jack
tried asking friends and family what they thought his great
undertaking might be. No one had a clue. I was convinced that Jack
would eventually forget all about his mysterious unfulfilled
destiny.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not how this story ends.
</P>
<P>
   You have to understand that for years Jack has worked as a
psychiatrist one afternoon a week at the Lynn Community Health
Center, treating folks with few resources, many of whom are recent
immigrants. Clinic patients, with little in the way of emergency
backup, have a poor record of keeping appointments, but after
Poole's reading, Jack came up with the idea of setting up a weekly
walk-in clinic where parents and children could receive immediate
care. As the walk-in clinic gained in popularity, the focus of
Jack's life shifted.
</P>
<P>
   He set up more mental health walk-in clinics. This fall, he'll
cut back his private practice to spend a second afternoon in Lynn,
supervising an in-house training program for psychiatric nurse
clinical specialists. It's now almost impossible to get his
attention in the evening. He's thinking of ways to integrate newly
hired personnel, planning training sessions, and working on clinic
problems in all his waking hours. Whenever Jack falls silent, I
know he's revisiting the clinic in his head, brooding, worrying,
and obsessing over every snafu.
</P>
<P>
   This is what I've been wondering.
</P>
<P>
   Did Poole truly foresee that Jack would catch fire about meeting
the needs of the people he serves, or did her words actually create
the readiness in him to seize an available opportunity? That's a
question you have to answer according to your own beliefs, but if
Nelson Mandela is right and our deepest fear is not that we are
inadequate but that we are powerful beyond measure, if he is
correct that it is our light not our darkness that most frightens
us, many of us need someone else's encouragement to let that light
shine.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela says, ``We ask ourselves, who am I to be brilliant,
gorgeous, talented, and fabulous? Actually, who are you not to be?
You are a child of God. Your playing small doesn't serve the world.
There's nothing enlightened about shrinking so that other people
won't feel insecure around you. We are born to make manifest the
glory of God that is within us. It's not just in some of us, it's
in everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   In my own life, others have looked into my future and seen me in
roles I could not envision myself. ``You are a wonderful writer,''
my grandfather said to me when I was still small enough to sit on
his knee. A swimming coach, a teacher, my mother, all predicted
without a shred of evidence that I would compete in the Nationals,
go to Wellesley, and find a man who would appreciate me. They were
only guessing, I think. And they were all right.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is all it takes to see into the future:
</P>
<P>
   Faith in one another's greatness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
