<HEADLINE>
DEAR STUDENTS: KEEP YOUR GOODS IN YOUR PANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLA LA FAVE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Green hair doesn't bother me.
</P>
<P>
   Neither do dog collars, multiple earrings, or three-inch
fingernails painted black. When schools starts in my district, 150
students will come through my classroom and I will see all that and
a few new accessories. Most of them are expressions of rebellion _
ways of saying, ``Hey, I'm different. Look at me.'' They're largely
harmless.
</P>
<P>
   I just don't want to see anyone's underwear.
</P>
<P>
   The only trend that really bothers me is the one that dictates
guys wearing jeans four sizes too big and low around the hips in
order to expose a couple inches of boxer shorts, or girls wearing
low-cut tops that show a fair amount of bra.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that I'm shocked, or that the underwear in question is
shabby. On the contrary, it's usually brand new and purchased for
an audience. What bothers me is that this is not an expression of
rebellion, but a mere fad.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose in some ways it's no worse than a lot of past fads _
chest hair-exposing leisure suits or mood rings or false eyelashes
_ but since it's not intended to shock, it places me in an awkward
position. I don't mind disciplining a student for unruly behavior,
but I'm uncomfortable taking a kid out in the hall in order to tell
him to pull up his pants up or to ask her to put a jacket on so I
can't see her bra.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing conversations are ridiculous:
</P>
<P>
   Me: John, please pull your pants up. I don't want to see your
underwear.
</P>
<P>
   John: Why? They're new.
</P>
<P>
   Me: That doesn't matter. It's not appropriate for them to show
in class.
</P>
<P>
   John: My mom bought these for me. She doesn't care. Why should
you?
</P>
<P>
   Because I'm not his mother, that's why. I teach math, not
fashion sense, and while he may not have any trouble concentrating
on plane geometry while his Fruit of the Looms are showing, I do.
</P>
<P>
   The line between public and private behavior has been blurring
for a long time now. The media get most of the attention in this
area, as the evening news looks increasingly like a tabloid show,
but the more subtle problem is that a lot of our kids don't have a
sense of audience. They think that if it's OK to do something at
home, it's OK to do the same thing at school. They think that just
because their mother is willing to look at their underwear, I ought
to be willing to look at it too. And that's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   So students, when you're back in school, your green hair is just
fine. Wear dog collars if you like; paint your nails in yellow and
orange stripes. Dress all in black or mix flowered shirts with
plaid pants. None of that will faze me a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Just make sure I don't see your underwear.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Charla La Fave teaches high school in the Mount Diablo Unified
School District in California.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
