<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-SUCCESSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS OF A HILLSIDE MEADOW LEARNED _ BUT NOW, THE MOWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When we bought our home nine years ago, I saw opportunity in the
small hill out back.
</P>
<P>
   Waves of tall grass rose to a stand of young white pines. To one
side was a copse of saplings and shrubs, including high-bush
blueberries, maples and birches. I envisioned paths winding up and
into the forest beyond. I wouldn't even try mowing the grass. A
hillside meadow. Just the thing.
</P>
<P>
   And for several years, that's what we had. Oh, I never blazed
paths, and the birds ate most of the berries. But I did whack out
oak and white pine saplings and sumac in the copse, where we now
have a lovely and growing stand of birches.
</P>
<P>
   The hilly meadow filled with grasses blowing in the wind and
wild flowers, with an especially nice late show of goldenrod.
</P>
<P>
   Then a few briars cropped up, and a few more. A couple of small
junipers emerged. Some white pines arose. Wild white roses were
welcome at first, then turned into a rampaging thug that, with some
other viney things, have taken over the hillside. Alders and
cherries joined the assault.
</P>
<P>
   Whoa! What is going on here?
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're looking at there are the initial stages of
succession,'' Richard Doherty, a horticulturist and educator, told
me recently.
</P>
<P>
   Succession happens when cleared land is let go. First grasses
take over, then herbaceous perennials, then shrubs, and then trees.
And not just any trees, Doherty said, but conifers. In our area,
that means primarily white pines. Conifers germinate best in
sunlight, while hardwoods will come up in some shade. So later,
hardwoods such as maples and beeches and oaks take over, producing
a so-called climax forest that is a mix of species.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your climax stage really depends upon your area and the
species you have in that area,'' said Doherty, who heads the JCC
Horticultural Therapy Program, which provides horticultural therapy
for people with HIV and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   South of Boston, it is likely to be the oak-pine complex. On
Cape Cod, Doherty suggested, the climax stage seems to be housing
complexes, but perhaps he was joking.
</P>
<P>
   Change has always characterized the New England landscape,
according to Richard Stomberg, who is manager of the Organismic and
Evolutionary Biology Glasshouses at Harvard University. Be it
glaciers or Pilgrims, things have not stayed put, certainly not the
vast white pine forests that greeted the colonists. Inexorably, the
forests were felled for shipbuilding, other lumber uses, firewood,
and to make way for farms.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 19th century, Stomberg said, people began leaving
for the Midwest. Farmers in particular left the stony, bony fields
of New England for greener pastures. ``And at that point, the
farmland began reverting to forest,'' Stomberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out that white pine is a particularly good colonizer
of open ground,'' he said. By the turn of the century, ``there was
almost a monoculture, just a huge carpet of white pines.'' That
triggered a new wave of logging, from 1900 to 1920. When the white
pines were cut, they didn't replace themselves, while hardwoods
were quick to take advantage of the clearings. This produced mixed
forests, ``and that's sort of where we are now,'' Stomberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Stomberg said, ``when you fly over New England, what you
see is trees.'' It is not static, though. Development continues,
especially housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our landscape in New England is constantly being disturbed,''
Stomberg said, ``and that's why our landscape is such an
interesting patchwork.''
</P>
<P>
   It tells stories, too. Sight down a stone wall in the woods, he
said, and you may well see two distinctly different forests on
either side. That is because the stone wall was probably part of a
farm, separating different uses. A woodlot and a pasture would have
different succession stages a century on. So-called pasture
junipers generally spring up in fields, so if you find some hanging
on in the woods, it means that forest may be a succession to a
pasture, Stomberg said.
</P>
<P>
   And my hillside? Yes, it is going through succession stages, and
unless I want trees, I'll be mowing it soon. Well, I sort of knew
that. Thinking that something would come easy was just a stage I
have now outgrown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
