<HEADLINE>
A GRAPE PERGOLA HOLDS UP HISTORY _ AND A PROFUSION OF VINES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vines are climbing in popularity these days, and so are garden
structures, with clematis, wisteria, and roses spreading up and
over trellises, arbors, and pergolas. When my husband and I bought
our farmhouse, we inherited a vine hardly in vogue but whose roots
go deep in New England soil. Parallel to the garage were a row of
hoary Concord grapevines planted 8 feet apart.
</P>
<P>
   When we think of grape arbors today, the images that come to
mind range from boutique wineries with French varietals to
neighborhood back yards that yield grapes for grandfather's wine
and leaves for dolmas. But grapevines are also part of the
indigenous old New England landscape. When Leif Ericson arrived, he
found so many wild grapes growing in the New World that he
christened it Vinland. And the name Martha's Vineyard is another
testament to the vigor of wild American grapes.
</P>
<P>
   The climate here was too harsh for the grapes of Europe, so they
became status symbols. The wealthy erected greenhouses, the first
being at the Lyman Estate in Waltham, Mass., where vines planted in
1804 are still maintained by the Society for the Preservation of
New England Antiquities.
</P>
<P>
   The search for a tasty, cold-hardy grape became an amateur
pastime in the mid-1800s. In 1843 Ephraim Wales Bull, a neighbor of
the Concord, Mass. transcendentalists, planted seeds from a wild
grape that had probably naturally cross-pollinated with a nearby
Catawba grapevine hybridized by a Maryland woman.
</P>
<P>
   When the seedlings bore fruit after six years, Bull named the
tastiest one after his hometown. He unveiled it at a Massachusetts
Horticultural Society exhibition in 1852 as ``a grape for the
millions,'' meaning people who couldn't afford a glass house. The
Concord grape became an instant sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Hovey &AMP; Co., a famous Boston nursery, offered it commercially
two years later and soon the Concord grape was heading west into
Missouri as a tough, hardy, almost foolproof grape for homesteaders
who wanted an all-purpose table and jelly grape, said Christie
White, program coordinator for horticulture at Old Sturbridge
Village, which maintains a Concord grape arbor.
</P>
<P>
   While most antique New England-bred fruits are now mere
curiosities, the Concord grape is almost unique in holding space on
modern supermarket shelves. That's thanks to a New Jersey dentist
named Thomas Welch, who used Concord grapes and Louis Pasteur's
pasteurization process to invent grape juice that wouldn't ferment
(Welch didn't think much of the use of wine at communion
ceremonies). Today we have Welch's Concord Grape Juice and Concord
Grape Jelly. Though the grapes are mostly produced in upstate New
York, Michigan, and Washington state, the Welch Foods Inc.
headquarters are in Concord.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know when my grapevines were planted. Obviously they
went in after 1854, but maybe not long after. Grapevines can live
hundreds of years, and if there's any variety that can withstand
neglect, it's the Concord grape.
</P>
<P>
   When I first met them, my vines were brazenly sprawling on the
ground amid the ruins of the latest in perhaps a long line of
trellises. Their stubby trunks were 3 inches thick, their canes
reaching out in all directions like the tentacles of inquisitive
octopi. The supports had probably just collapsed under the vines'
combined weight, but the sinewy brown canes looked almost capable
of pulling them down.
</P>
<P>
   Flush with pride of new ownership, my husband immediately built
a new trellis of boards nailed to cedar poles. We also did some
restorative pruning, but not consistently enough.
</P>
<P>
   The vines yielded some gallons of grape juice and lots of food
for birds. The perfectly round, deep-purple grapes would develop a
glaucous sheen and turn from sour to sweet if left on the vine
until after first frost. But each bunch of grapes consisted of only
about a few perfect orbs, each full of seeds and mostly hidden by
beautiful leaves. Our grapevines were mainly a vertical bird
sanctuary, favored particularly by nesting catbirds.
</P>
<P>
   Within a decade, the resurgent vines were twisting and
dismantling the 2-by-4 crossbeams. I came up with what I thought of
as the $1,500 Solution.
</P>
<P>
   This was the initial estimate from Glenn H. Johnson of South
Shore Improvements in Hingham, Mass. on what it would cost to build
a modest new arbor that would give our exuberant grapevines
something substantial to tackle and would create a sheltered spot
under which to sit.
</P>
<P>
   I was inspired by my next-door neighbor's Concord grape arbor, a
low but sturdy cedar structure that framed the view of their front
porch and the lightning-splitter dormers of their gothic 1814
farmhouse. It was the most beautiful scene on the street in winter
when the vines became a leafless sculpture piled high with snow.
</P>
<P>
   Before we began building, we hired horticulturist Michael Talbot
of Boston to prune our vines. He whacked them back with a
decisiveness we had never mustered. They looked like dead tree
trunks, except they were bleeding sap.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't want to use concrete footings for the new arbor, so
Johnson dug 3-foot-deep post holes and filled the bottom with large
rocks. After the sturdy 6-by-6 posts of Southern yellow pine were
erected, he filled in around them with gravel and small stones so
they had drainage and didn't come in contact with soil that could
rot them. The crossbeams are 2-by-6s.
</P>
<P>
   Five thousand dollars (actually $4,835) and many decorative
modifications later, Johnson had created an impressive structure 8
feet high, 10 feet wide, and 43 feet long spanning the northeast
length of our perennial garden. It was the Titanic of grape arbors,
or in Johnson's words, ``a monster.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
