<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWARD A NEW UNDERSTANDING BETWEEN THE SEXES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD HIGGINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
WE HAVE TO TALK 
Healing Dialogues Between Women and Men 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Samuel Shem and Janet Surrey &QL; 
Basic Books, 225 pp. $23 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You are washing the dinner dishes, and your wife is drying. She
asks you why you are silent. It is debatable (to you) that you are
being silent, but you concede the point and say that you don't
know. She says, ``Let's talk about it.'' At that point you: a) ask
her about her mother; b) talk with her about what you are feeling
and listen to what she may be feeling; c) excuse yourself to put
out the garbage.
</P>
<P>
   If you answered b), you may not need to read this book. If you
tried a), reading this book could save your marriage. If you
answered c), you have to sit down, read it, and summarize the main
points to your spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Not that ``We Have to Talk'' is simply a how-to book. The
authors, Samuel Shem and Janet Surrey, thoughtfully examine the
different relational styles of men and women and how they got that
way. They look at the inevitable disconnections that occur between
the sexes and argue that, with effort and creativity, those
differences can be used to move into deeper intimacy. Indeed,
working through the impasses to achieve and nurture connection,
they find, is both healing and the core of healthy relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Have to Talk'' builds on work done at the Stone Center at
Wellesley College, where Shem, a psychiatrist, and Surrey, a
clinical psychologist, are faculty members. The writers, who are
married, lecture together and for 12 years have led workshops, or
gender dialogues, around the country. Shem is also the author of
three novels, ``The House of God,'' ``Fine,'' and ``Mount Misery.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a crowded marketplace of books on this subject, and the
authors thus strive to claim new ground. The result is some
repackaging of the basic realities of a committed relationship _
e.g., that there is a ``we'' in addition to an ``I'' and a ``you''
_ in the latest discourse of feminist psychology. That discourse is
so much in the assumed foreground, that, for example, there are
almost no references to the women's movement, while the reaction to
it, the men's movement, is cuttingly analyzed and repeatedly
fingered for the blame. Older theories of self, the authors write,
represent a status quo that is ``hierarchical, violent, fragmented,
disconnected, and isolated.''
</P>
<P>
   I also have trouble with the stereotype of men. The men whose
voices we hear are, by and large, clueless dummies who would rather
``be in their caves,'' e.g., fixing things, changing the oil in
their trucks, or sitting in sullen silence rather than relating,
men who are puzzled and stung by the anger of their spouses. The
description of women's ways is more alert to stereotyping, on the
other hand. A half-dozen times, for example, women object to being
perceived as the ``experts'' at maintaining relationships.
</P>
<P>
   That gender jeremiad expressed, ``We Have to Talk'' is a useful
book. Shem and Surrey's jumping-off point is research done by Jean
Baker Miller and others at the Stone Center, and by Deborah Tannen
and Carol Gilligan, which found that women's psychological growth
is oriented not toward individual autonomy but toward human
connection, toward the building of mutual and growth-fostering
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Gender differences are hardly unknown, as John Gray showed with
the popular success of his 1994 bestseller, ``Men Are From Mars,
Women Are From Venus.'' But Shem and Surrey move in a new
direction. Rather than reifying these differences and inviting
people to exploit them to manipulate the other gender, the authors
propose ``holding'' them in a empathetic effort to understand the
other as a way to foster connection.
</P>
<P>
   The book identifies three obstacles that affect everything from
choosing a restaurant to having sex. They are: male relational
dread, which is contrasted with women's yearning for connection,
the male focus on product against the female focus on process, and
power over versus power with. Building on much current research,
they find that these inclinations are rooted in early development
of boys and girls.
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly, Shem and Surrey show their couples ways of stepping
back from these impasses, of hearing out the other not from the
defensive posture of self or gender identity but from the ``we.''
When they succeed in doing this, things begin to happen, and the
value of their approach, and this book, is clear. Shem and Surrey
describe it as a kind of yoga stretch: ``Every moment presents an
opportunity to stay in connection and grow, or disconnect and
retreat into old patterns of unresolved or avoided conflict. ...
(Doing so) is not easy, not always graceful, and not always
possible in any given moment. But staying with it eventually gives
birth to something new.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
