<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND RATE? CERTAINLY NOT THESE RIDERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They called him Second Place Jesse.
</P>
<P>
   His name was Jesse Stahl, a bronc-bustin' African-American
cowboy from California whose life span straddled the waning years
of the past century and the first third of the current one.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl, in the estimation of some old hands, was the best in his
day at the business of riding uncooperative horses _ even better
than the legendary ``Booger Red'' Privett. But that is a matter of
opinion. Suffice it to say that Second Place Jesse was in the same
league with Booger Red.
</P>
<P>
   Now the truth was that he bested the whole field most of time,
but he had to agree ahead of time to take second-place money or not
be allowed to compete at all. On one of those occasions, Stahl is
said to have ridden his next bronc turned backward in the saddle to
display his disgust.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of rodeos, very few black cowboys were
permitted to show their stuff in contests with white cowboys. Stahl
and the legendary bulldogger Bill Pickett were among the few
exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Pickett was the first African-American cowboy inducted into the
Cowboy Hall of Fame in Oklahoma City. Stahl was (what else?) the
second.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, African-American cowboys confined themselves
to smaller, black-only rodeos, although there were many more who
would have ranked among the best at the sport. Black cowboys, after
all, figured prominently in the cattle culture of the 1870s and
1880s.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, about a fourth of the men who drove the
millions of longhorns up the Western Trail, the Chisholm Trail, the
Goodnight-Loving Trail and other routes to the railhead markets in
the central Plains states were African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   That is a part of American history that was obscured until
recently by western movies and novels that for the most part left
African-Americans and Hispanics out of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two decades, major strides have been made in
correcting those sins of historical omission, both in terms of
academic representations and in the realm of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Professional rodeo has opened its chutes to African-Americans,
and many have done well in Professional Rodeo Cowboy Association
events. The list includes all-around cowboy Marvel Rogers; bull
riders Myrtis Dightman, Charles Sampson and Ervin Williams;
bullfighters (also known as rodeo clowns) Dwayne Hargo and Leon
Coffee; and calf roper Fred Whitfield.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Sampson became the first black cowboy to win a national
championship. In 1990, Whitfield became the first of his race to
achieve the distinction of national calf-roping champion.
</P>
<P>
   Although black cowboys constitute a relatively small percentage
of the card-carrying PRCA membership, their numbers are growing.
Many are earning their spurs in local and regional rodeos as well
as touring competitions such as the Bill Pickett Rodeo and Cleo
Hearns' Cowboys of Color Invitational Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   The Pickett Rodeo, which has visited Fort Worth several times,
is an exclusively African-American rodeo that features the
traditional rodeo events of roping, bronc-bustin', bull riding,
steer wrestling and barrel racing, as well as other exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it even has a steer wrestler attempt to demonstrate
Pickett's famous feat of biting a steer in the upper lip and
throwing it to the ground using only his teeth and his body weight.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys of Color Rodeo, which will play the Will Rogers
Coliseum at 7 p.m. Sept. 5, is a tri-ethnic show. It will present
more than 300 African-American, Hispanic and Native American
cowboys and cowgirls in competition and exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has seen previous editions of that rodeo here, at the
State Fair in Dallas or other venues can tell you that it offers
thrill-a-minute, exhilarating entertainment that ranks with the
best of its kind. There is nothing second place about it.
</P>
<P>
   But more than that, Cowboys of Color is a living history lesson,
a spectacular exhibition of pageantry and action that celebrates
the diversity of the American West of yesterday and today.
</P>
<P>
   To find out how to participate in this entertaining historical
tribute, call the Renaissance Cultural Center at (817) 922-9999.
They'll be more than happy there to tell you where to get tickets
in advance, because the center will be one of the main
beneficiaries of the event.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
