<HEADLINE>
STORY OF NETSCAPE'S RISE ADDS PERSPECTIVE ON MICROSOFT ANTITRUST
CASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. may face its biggest challenge when it squares
off in court next month against Justice Department attorneys who
charge that the software giant illegally leveraged its monopoly
position to extend its dominance.
</P>
<P>
   The seeds for the government's antitrust case against the maker
of the Windows computer operating system were planted more than
four years ago, when Silicon Valley start-up Netscape
Communications Corp. launched its efforts to make the Internet
appealing to mainstream computer users.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Netscape, its role in pioneering the development of
browser software used to surf the World Wide Web and the threat it
presented to Microsoft's stranglehold on the computer market is
chronicled in ``Speeding the Net: The Inside Story of Netscape and
How It Challenged Microsoft'' (Atlantic Monthly Press. $25, 323
pages.) Authors Joshua Quittner and Michelle Slatalla have written
four other technology business books, including ``Masters of
Deception: The Gang that Ruled Cyberspace.'' This time, they have
produced a compelling account of Netscape's early days and how it
ushered in a new era in personal computing.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape is best known for developing the first commercial
software that simplified accessing Internet data. The company
initially comprised Silicon Graphics founder Jim Clark and a team
of programmers who had helped develop an academic version of the
so-called browser software at the National Center for
Supercomputing Applications at the University of Illinois in
Urbana-Champaign.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape had the commercial success in developing Internet
software. Previously, the Internet had been little more than a
network connecting academics and computer experts who knew the
arcane computer commands needed to send, receive and access remote
information.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape served up software that made it easy for mainstream
computer users to tap the wealth of information available on the
World Wide Web. Accessing information became as easy as pointing to
an on-screen text link and clicking on it.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was simple, but it shook the computing world that
Microsoft ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Some thought the browser software could ultimately become the
single window that personal computer users needed to the outside
world, potentially ending the need for Microsoft's pre-eminent and
highly lucrative Windows operating system, used on more than 80
percent of all personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advent of any new technology represented a threat to
hegemony,'' Quittner and Slatalla write. ``The new battle for the
control over the software industry would be fought on the Net, not
on the desktop.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the stakes for computer industry dominance rise through
the time line of this book, the story stumbles. The rich, thorough
storytelling that characterized the first two-thirds of the book
describing Netscape's formation and launch quickly devolves into
elongated explanations of the meaning behind news releases that
Netscape and its chief rival issued.
</P>
<P>
   What starts as a spellbinding, nearly first-person account of a
perilous start-up shifts in later chapters to a dry recounting of
the corporate warfare between Netscape and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Quittner and Slatalla still deliver a package that
offers significant perspectives to those trying to understand the
government's antitrust case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BLURBS
</P>
<P>
   ``Succeeding in Business Without Selling Your Soul''
</P>
<P>
   By John D. Beckett
</P>
<P>
   InterVarsity Press, $15.99
</P>
<P>
   Using the Bible as a guide for business is a small trend
highlighted by companies such as Ohio-based manufacturer R.W.
Beckett. The president of that company, John Beckett, has been
vocal on the subject and has written a book on combining faith and
principles with business. He focuses strictly on applying Christian
principles to business practices, so don't expect other religions
to be acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Presentation Jazz: How to Make Your Sales Presentations
$ing!''
</P>
<P>
   By Anne Miller
</P>
<P>
   AMACOM, $17.95
</P>
<P>
   Anne Miller, president of a New York City sales and
communications company, uses music as a metaphor for creating
better sales presentations. Now she has incorporated that idea into
a book. It contains two parts, one a structuring tool to help
readers organize their presentations, the other an assessment tool
to measure the selling power of the presentation. Miller offers
good ideas for the increasingly competitive business of selling.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ultimate Book of Business Quotations''
</P>
<P>
   By Stuart Crainer
</P>
<P>
   AMACOM, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   For those looking to spruce up a speech, memo or newsletter,
this book holds some gems. Stuart Crainer has spanned the bulk of
business and nonbusiness text to find the most poignant and
profound business quotes by everyone from Groucho Marx and Abraham
Lincoln to Michael Hammer and Tom Peters. Everyone has something to
say about business, Crainer concludes, because business ultimately
touches everyone. The quotes are short and easy to access from
several categories.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
