<HEADLINE>
LITTLE WAYS THAT ANGER CAN KILL YOU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beware the hostile heart.
</P>
<P>
   OK, OK, I admit that I sometimes get impatient in the express
checkout line at my favorite grocery and count the items in the
cart of the customer ahead of me _ especially if two or three more
customers are in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   And, I may get annoyed and huff and puff a little when I get
stuck in traffic; but I'm not cynical, much less hostile.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, maybe not, says a researcher affiliated with Duke
University's Behavioral Medicine Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Redford Williams has been warning for years that cynicism is
part and parcel of a hostile personality and that a hostile
personality can kill us _ most often by heart disease but also by
injuries and accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Williams has come up with a short self-test, published in
the August issue of Consumer Reports on Health, to help us
determine whether we are too hostile for our own good. He says if
we find five or more of these statements to be true, it's
definitely time to mellow out:
</P>
<P>
   _ I often get annoyed at checkout cashiers or the people in
front of me when I'm waiting in line.
</P>
<P>
   _ I usually keep an eye on the people I work or live with to
make sure they do what they should.
</P>
<P>
   _ I often wonder how homeless people can have so little respect
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   _ I believe that most people will take advantage of you, if you
let them.
</P>
<P>
   _ The habits of friends or family members often annoy me.
</P>
<P>
   _ When I'm stuck in traffic, I often start breathing faster and
my heart pounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ When I'm annoyed with people, I really want to let them know
it.
</P>
<P>
   _ If someone does me wrong, I really want to get even.
</P>
<P>
   _ I'd like to have the last word in any argument.
</P>
<P>
   _ At least once a week, I have the urge to yell or even hit
someone.
</P>
<P>
   Most researchers believe that the more often we get angry, the
greater our risk of heart attack _ no matter how we handle that
anger.
</P>
<P>
   Anger can kill by speeding up the heart rate and making blood
pressure soar in such a way that deposits on coronary arteries are
disrupted or clots are formed. Anger can narrow the coronary
arteries just when the heart muscle needs extra blood, and even
inhibit certain nerve signals that help maintain normal heart
rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   COX-2 LOOKING GOOD: Remember COX-2 inhibitors, the new class of
anti-inflammatory drugs under development for long-term treatment
of arthritis without the gastrointestinal side effects of the
nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs we have now?
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say the drugs may also prove important to the
treatment and prevention of Alzheimer's disease, colon cancer,
kidney disease, osteoporosis and other major health concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Top medical researchers reported promising studies on a broad
range of medical conditions at a recent international workshop on
COX-2, organized by Dr. Peter Lipsky, director of the Harold C.
Simmons Arthritis Research Center at the University of Texas
Southwestern Medical Center at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call her at (817) 390-7687. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
