<HEADLINE>
SEEKING THE UNUSUAL IN THE MONOTONOUS WORLD OF TUXEDOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ No two ways about it. Men look great in tuxedos.
The graphic white of a freshly laundered formal shirt frames the
face and sets off the slimming silhouette of the shapely,
satin-lapeled jacket.
</P>
<P>
   However: Have you ever seen a roomful of guys in tuxedos? Do
they remind you of one of those National Geographic photo spreads
of Antarctica?
</P>
<P>
   Sharam Sharei, proprietor of the six Barcelino stores in the San
Francisco area, calls it ``The Penguin Syndrome,'' all these guys
dressed identically with such subtle variations they look like
cookie-cutter figures. Very few men actually vary the look. Either
they like it, or ... they are afraid to be different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most men who wear tuxedos wear a white shirt, black bow tie
and a black tux. That is the standard,'' notes Sharei, explaining
that ``the tuxedo was first introduced to the United States in
Tuxedo Park in upstate New York. The first time it was worn was in
the fall of 1886 when one of the residents of ritzy Tuxedo Park
went to England and was the guest of Edward, the Prince of Wales.
He preferred to wear this new concept instead of tails, which was
the dominant formal wear of the time. He decided it was too formal
for his country estate.''
</P>
<P>
   The tuxedo was a modification of the formal white tie and tails.
``They went back probably to the 17th century,'' says clothier
Wilkes Bashford. ``They were always worn with a stiff white shirt.
And they were always black. Tuxedos, in essence, were the
relaxation of tails. The gentry in Tuxedo Park felt they weren't in
the city but these were very affluent, proper types who still
wanted to be formal even though they were in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   And thus it has been with men.
</P>
<P>
   Man, it seems, is the only member of the animal kingdom who does
not outshine his mate.
</P>
<P>
   With other species, the male is the plumagerian. He struts or
growls, preens or howls, fluffing his ruff or mane or tail feathers
while the dowdy female sits on her nest and hides. Not so the
upright mammal called man. It's the woman who gets the finery these
days. And for black-tie, formal events, it can be fairly expensive
couture frills and flounces. The guy in the tux: He provides the
stark backdrop on which she gets to show off.
</P>
<P>
   Hey guys, it doesn't have to be that way. It's just getting a
guy into something different, while still appropriate and formal,
that is the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many options in formal wear if you want to set
yourself apart from the rest of the penguins,'' suggests Sharei.
``The word is: Accessorize. You can do it with a beautiful
cummerbund set or with a woven-silk vest or with woven-silk formal
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men, however, are usually not daring,'' he continues. ``In the
fashion business, we have a huge hurdle to get over this situation.
How do we get men to become more comfortable in things that are not
of their standard? Are they daring to try color? The bridge, then,
is accessories.''
</P>
<P>
   He notes, however, that the white dinner jacket isn't too big of
a first step.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be worn in the winter _ that is nothing new,'' Sharei
says. ``It prevailed in the '30s, '40s and '50s over the black
dinner jacket. Humphrey Bogart wore a white dinner jacket in
`Casablanca.'''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, men, Sharei concludes, ``are basically conservative. They
always look a little dull. When you go to the trouble to dress up
for the opera, you also want a bit of pizazz and show you're a
breed apart.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is: Men are very resistant to change. And they think
that if they break tradition and stand away from the Penguin Pack,
people will point a finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing a guy thinks about when you suggest something
a little different is: `It's only for real young guys,''' Bashford
says. And it is definitely the younger man who will play with the
tuxedo concept and vary the standard, perhaps not wanting to fogey
up so soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get something new on a guy,'' Bashford says, ``and
he can see how good he looks in it, then maybe you can make a man
change his mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
