<SLUG> BC-FILM-WHY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FOOLS' CAN BE COMMENDED FOR TRYING SOMETHING DIFFERENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gregory Nava's ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love?'' is an appropriate
film to end the Hollywood summer of '98. It's the final salvo of a
barrage of movies during the last three months _ from ``Bulworth''
to ``Snake Eyes'' _ that have genuinely tried to be something
different.
</P>
<P>
   This one is a biography of Frankie Lymon, an obscure,
one-hit-wonder of the early rock era who died a tragic, forgotten
figure at age 25, and is remembered today mostly for being a martyr
to the greed of white record producers of his era.
</P>
<P>
   But the film omits virtually all of cliche scenes of the rock
biopic, it can find nothing especially redeeming to relate about
Lymon (Larenz Tate) and it tells his story from three angles,
through the eyes of the three wronged women he managed to marry in
his short life.
</P>
<P>
   It opens in the late '80s, long after Lymon's overdose death, as
his big hit _ ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love?'' _ has becomes a cover
hit for Diana Ross. A court has ruled that Lymon's estate is due a
small fortune in back royalties, and the three wives turn up to
claim it.
</P>
<P>
   The wives are Zola (Halle Berry), a singer with the Platters and
a one-time star herself; Elizabeth (Vivica A. Fox), an ex-con and
incorrigible shoplifter; and Emira (Lela Rochon), a highly educated
Southern school-teacher Lymon met while serving in the Army in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The script follows the trial that is held to determine which is
the real Mrs. Frankie Lymon (none, for various reasons, seem to
have a clear claim) and the film flashes back and forth in time
through several rock eras, giving us a ``Rashomon''-like view of
its subject.
</P>
<P>
   As a biography, the movie isn't much. It's littered with
anachronisms, it vastly exaggerates Lymon's standing in the rock
pile of the late '50s, and is so cavalier about the truth of his
life that it manages to omit the fact that he was only 13 years old
(and looked even younger) when he hit it big with the title song!
</P>
<P>
   And the film's single moral point _ that Lymon, like many black
performers of the early rock era, was robbed by his white producer
_ becomes emotionally moot, since we are left with no doubt that he
would have shot those lost royalties right up his arm.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, director Nava _ whose last film was the
ultra-respectful and candy-coated musical biopic ``Selena'' _ is
almost too disrespectful and too ruthless in painting Lymon as a
baby-faced monster, and too intent on turning his wives into the
cast of ``Waiting to Exhale.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the film is an original piece of storytelling and it has
its own cheeky style and sensibility. The performance scenes _
mostly with actors lip- syncing the original recordings _ are
particularly dynamic, and capture some of the energy and excitement
of rock at its beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its morbid subject matter, ``Why Do Fools'' actually
works best as a bold farce: a wry comment on the fickle finger of
fame, the emptiness of celebrity, and the absurdity of all human
endeavor _ a point perfectly delivered in a closing shot of the
harlequin face of rock star, Little Richard, telling us that life
is a cabaret.
</P>
<P>
   Why Do Fools Fall in Love. Directed by Gregory Nava. Written by
Tina Andrews. Cast: Halle Berry, Vivica A. Fox, Lela Rochon, Larenz
Tate, Little Richard. Warner Bros. 116 minutes. Rated R for sex and
drug scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
