</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NIGHTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR'S CUT OF `CABIRIA' WORTH SEEING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The phenomenon of re-releasing old movies with added footage _
the so-called ``director's cut'' _ is mostly a marketing gimmick,
and an overused one at that. Most films worthy enough to be
remembered simply do not benefit by reattaching scenes that were
cut as part of the normal editing process.
</P>
<P>
   But the seven minutes added to Federico Fellini's 1957
Oscar-winning masterpiece, ``The Nights of Cabiria,'' actually make
it a slightly better film. It's nothing monumental, but the
sequence helps fill out the heroine's character and it serves as
the natural link to the next sequence.
</P>
<P>
   The restored, slightly expanded and re-subtitled ``Cabiria'' had
its American debut at the last Seattle International Film Festival,
where a post-festival poll voted it the audience-favorite film.
</P>
<P>
   Fellini's story deals with a short period in the life of Cabiria
(Giulietta Masina, Fellini's wife), a
streetwalker-with-a-heart-of-gold, who, as the film opens, is being
rescued from the Tiber after being robbed and nearly drowned by her
unappreciative pimp.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the film follows her through a series of episodes _
a night with a movie star (Amedeo Nazzari), a pilgrimage to a
famous religious shrine, an evening as the subject of a hypnotist _
ending with a promising romance that seems to be her one big chance
for a decent life.
</P>
<P>
   It may not sound like much on paper, but ``Cabiria'' is an
utterly magical movie that pulls us into its spell and sweeps us
along to a tragic but miraculously satisfying and optimistic
ending. Most critics now regard it as Fellini's best film, and cite
Masina's exquisitely vulnerable performance as one of the most
perfect in the 100-year history of cinema.
</P>
<P>
   The added, seven-minute, ``the man with the sack'' sequence,
comes after the episode with the world-weary movie star, as
Cabiria, wandering alone at night near the via Appia Antica, meets
a man handing out food from a sack to the legions of poor that live
in the pits and caves around the old Roman quarries.
</P>
<P>
   It was the last scene written for the film (after Fellini had
met a real-life counterpart to the character), and it was excised
after the film's Cannes debut and the director's preview of the
film for a Roman Catholic cardinal, whose approval was necessary to
get an Italian censorship certificate.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit of a mystery exactly why the cut was made. The
long-accepted story has been that the church was offended at the
insinuation it was not properly feeding the poor itself. Fellini
biographer John Baxter believes this story may have been the
invention of the film's producer, Dino de Laurentiis, who ``with or
without Fellini's collusion, shortened the film for purely
commercial reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the film definitely plays better with the
sequence than it does without it. It's the natural emotional
transition from the comic night of hiding in a movie star's
bathroom (because his girlfriend has unexpectedly returned) to the
sequence at the religious pilgrimage, in which Cabiria _ inspired
by the man with a sack _ asks the virgin to help her change her
life.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, this may be a minor point in the context of the
whole movie, and Cabiria's religious awakening is short-lived, to
say the least. But it's surprising to see just how those seven
minutes broaden our understanding of Cabiria and sweeten her
perspective. Fellini's original instinct was the right one. This is
one ``director's cut'' addition that makes a great film a little
bit greater.
</P>
<P>
   Nights of Cabiria (1957). Directed by Federico Fellini. Written
by Fellini, Ennio Flaiano and Tullio Pinelli. Cast: Giulietta
Masina, Francois Perier, Amedeo Nazzari, Franca Marzi. Rialto
Pictures. 117 minutes. In Italian with English subtitles. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
