<SLUG> BC-FILM-54-SPI </SLUG>
  
 `54' CONTINUES THE '70s MYTH  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest Hollywood disco-nostalgia movie, ``54,'' makes a
trilogy of sorts with those other two recent film portrayals of the
late '70s as the century's high-point in happy decadence: ``Boogie
Nights'' and ``The Last Days of Disco.''
</P>
<P>
   All three films see the era more in terms of myth than reality,
all wildly exaggerate the hedonism of the time, all were made by
directors too young to have any real memory or personal knowledge
of the subject, and all communicate a distinct envy that the party
was missed.
</P>
<P>
   This one is the weakest of the three, partly because its basic
story has already been told by ``Last Days,'' partly because the
casting is lackluster, and partly because first-time
director-writer Mark Christopher just can't quite get a handle on
his milieu.
</P>
<P>
   The film tells the story of Studio 54, the infamous Manhattan
night club, celebrity hangout and den-of-iniquity from the point of
view of a handsome, 19-year-old New Jersey lad named Shane (Ryan
Phillippe), who's desperate to escape his boring,
lower-middle-class existence and sees the disco as glamor
incarnate.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the crowd of celebrity gawkers one night, he catches
the eye of the disco's owner, Steve Rubell (Mike Myers), who gives
him a job as bus boy, and, thus, entree into paradise. In no time,
he works his way up to bartender and resident stud: a position he
holds until the IRS makes its first raid on the place.
</P>
<P>
   Like its predecessors, the film sees the late '70s in terms of
visual spectacle, and outdoes them in portraying the era as a Roman
orgy of sexual excess and pharmaceutical indulgence, inexorably
working its way to that early '80s climax which would spoil the
party forever (but is curiously unmentioned in any of the films):
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   When the music is playing, ``54'' thumps along nicely. But when
the music stops, it bogs down in cliche and soap opera situations.
All the choices here seem wrong:
</P>
<P>
   _ The cast of Gen X exploitation stars _ Philippe, Salma Hyack
and Neve Campbell _ is uniformly dull.
</P>
<P>
   _ Christopher's script seems a pale rip-off of both ``Last
Days'' (without its humor) and 1979's ``Saturday Night Fever.''
</P>
<P>
   _ His direction is unimaginative throughout, and his ``big''
climactic scene _ the overdose of an 80-something granny on the
dance floor (so help me) _ rings embarrassingly false.
</P>
<P>
   The film does have a more than credible performance from
comedian Mike Myers as the ill-fated Rubell. Unrecognizable in
heavy facial makeup, he's just right as the Brooklyn geek turned
power-mad celebrity hustler. But his part is not much more than an
extended cameo: the script doesn't even try to get under the man's
skin.
</P>
<P>
   54. Directed and written by Mark Christopher. Cast: Ryan
Phillippe, Salma Hayek, Mike Myers, Neve Campbell, Sela Ward.
Miramax. 93 minutes. Rated R for sex and drug-taking scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
