<HEADLINE>
BLAZING PADDLES: INSIDE PASSAGE EXPEDITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first day, they wore perfume and aftershave, eyeliner and
creased pants. The last day, they reeked of sweat and salt. Nails
had ridges of black. Hair was matted to heads.
</P>
<P>
   The first day, many questioned their physical abilities. The
last day, they felt strong and powerful, sea warriors capable of
propelling themselves long distances across water through sheer,
brute muscle power.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation took only six days, three guides, nine kayaks
and a stretch of uninhabited wilderness on British Columbia's
Inside Passage so breathtaking it seemed a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's like a time warp _ you're taken back to Indian
times. It's all nature, left undisturbed,'' said Frank McKeown, a
recent retiree from Houston, Texas, and one of the novice kayakers
who signed up for a six-day camp-out with Northern Lights
Expeditions, a Bellingham, Wash.-based outfitter that advertises
``No experience necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll go from being a novice to feeling comfortable in a very
short amount of time,'' said the trip's lead guide, Jacki Kofoed.
</P>
<P>
   But that first day, some looked like they might be up a creek
without a paddle.
</P>
<P>
   Anxieties played beneath polite chitchat at a pretrip session in
Vancouver Island's Port McNeil, the departure point. The group was
13 strong _ or weak. Who knew? And how lucky a number was 13?
</P>
<P>
   Ages hovered around 45, with one 23-year-old and one high-energy
66-year-old marking the extremes. Home ports were Michigan,
Illinois, Texas, California, Washington. Only a few had previous
kayaking experience. ``We saw kayaks out back of the hotel and we
were, like, `These are really a lot smaller than the ones we saw in
the pictures,' '' said a California woman.
</P>
<P>
   Kofoed assured us those were the boats, that they were fast and
stable, and that only five boats had capsized in 15 years of
operation. But she warned that the hypothermia-inducing water is 48
degrees Fahrenheit _ ``It makes me see stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Kofoed had some suggestions. One was to leave watches on dry
land. ``This is one week of your life when you don't need to know
what time it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Time not only flew by, it flew away as the group began mastering
basic strokes over the next few days, camping in dome tents and
venturing out from tiny Compton Island on Whitefish Passage.
</P>
<P>
   The brightly colored kayaks, seven 21-foot doubles and two
17-foot singles made by Northwest Kayaks in Redmond, felt tippy the
first day. Novices working the rudders with foot pedals cut some
creative Z's across the silky water and paddles flailed above the
surface in tentative, unsynchronized strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Old muscles that yelled during the day screamed at night,
calling for ibuprofen. One camper wasn't sure she could make it.
But the learning curve, as Kofoed had predicted, was high. Soon
even the most cautious found their balance and their stroke. The
trick was not to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   Muscles toughened. Smiles broadened. Bonds formed. During an
evening gathering, the sky turned from peach to apricot, washing
faces in gold as paddlers told why they had come.
</P>
<P>
   ``To challenge myself,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see if I could do it,'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of awe took over the increasingly raggedy group. Day
after day, they watched bald eagles swooping out of trees to
scatter gulls on a herring ball, or schools of porpoises and
Pacific white-sided dolphins splish-splashing across the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   An expedition to Village Island, inhabited for thousands of
years by the Kwagyulth tribe, revealed both anthropological and
biological wonders. Elegant totem poles lay decomposing where they
had fallen, and the dense beach midden yielded shards of old
crockery, weathered glass and an occasional trade bead. A talk
about ancient tribal ways was interrupted by a black bear crashing
up an apple tree, unperturbed by the two-legged invaders below.
</P>
<P>
   After two days, most of the kayakers had stopped glancing at the
browning spot where their watches had once been. Baths were
strictly saltwater, and hair began to take on Lyle Lovett
dimensions. Instead of an alarm clock, campers awoke to the sound
of eagles whistling, ravens squawking _ or guide Scott Wilson
singing, ``Can you imagine how much I love you-moo-moo-moo.''
</P>
<P>
   At sea, the guides had an unblinking eye to safety, constantly
clumping stray kayakers and monitoring two-way marine radios for
weather updates. On land, they had an eye to fun, devising goofy
beach games and whipping up sumptuous vegetarian meals _ sushi,
pasta, pumpkin pancakes.
</P>
<P>
   By midweek, the novices were beginning to feel like able-bodied
kayakers. But the biggest challenge still awaited: crossing
Johnstone Strait.
</P>
<P>
   Gale-force winds can kick up quickly in this 270-fathom-deep
channel off Vancouver Island, turning a placid paddle into a
high-seas struggle. Wakes from the four-tiered cruise ships,
gillnetters and purse seiners add to the watery confusion.
</P>
<P>
   The crew headed out singing rowing chants _ ``Or-eee-o,'' after
a favorite snack _ and dug into foot-high chop with newfound
muscles. White caps slapping the boats' bows elicited yelps of
delight.
</P>
<P>
   Could this be the same group of novices that set out just three
days ago?
</P>
<P>
   When the paddlers reached the other side, they knew they had
arrived _ in every sense of the word. But there were more surprises
in store. Immense surprises.
</P>
<P>
   The first killer whales appeared in the late afternoon, hugging
the rocks near the shore by camp, bull kelp rolling off their backs
as they cavorted. Susan Matthews burst into tears. ``I've seen
orcas in captivity, but they are so beautiful, so happy playing
here in the wild,'' she said. ``It will stay in my mind forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The second sighting was midchannel: a pod of 10 to 15 orcas.
Kayakers hopped in their boats, snapped on spray skirts and
super-paddled to the orca playground for a seal's-eye view of the
pod. The expedition group _ which over the week had turned into a
noisy, intimate rabble _ was suddenly silenced as a 6-foot dorsal
fin rose out of the sea directly in front of the flotilla. ``I had
goose bumps,'' said Gail Botwin, from Chicago. ``They're so much
bigger than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   The last night was a little sad. Everyone had become friends,
playing baseball with driftwood bats, telling secrets under
red-streaked skies, watching one another grow dirtier and stronger.
But the sky was filling with stars, and greenish bands of light
began to reach up from the horizon: The Northern Lights were doing
a ghostly jig in a long finale on a starlit stage.
</P>
<P>
   At midnight, a few night owls in camp paddled out into the thick
of night to see bioluminescence, explosions of light emitted by
tiny organisms in the water. Each dip of the paddle caused an
explosion of glitter, and fingers trailed in the water left a
string of diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   The last day, as on the first day, the kayakers took measure of
themselves. What a difference six days had made.
</P>
<P>
   The stench of success was all over them. ``This is the dirtiest
I've ever been in my life,'' said Marian Sta-Ana, a nurse from Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Sta-Ana, who had given herself the trip as a 45th birthday
present, had never even camped before. ``A week ago, I was, like,
`What can I do? Can I really paddle a kayak?' '' she said, staring
across the whitecapped water she'd navigated the day before. ``But
after crossing Johnstone Strait, I knew I could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sta-Ana smiled a slow, satisfied smile. ``I've learned about my
strengths on this trip,'' she said quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Paddling the Passage
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of outfitters offering guided expeditions in
the Inside Passage. Prices do not include transportation to
Vancouver Island. Costs are in U.S. dollars, which will fluctuate
with currency exchange rate. Trips vary from three to eight days.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Lights Expeditions (Bellingham, Wash.)
</P>
<P>
