<HEADLINE>
ACTRESS' PERFORMANCE MAKES `WONDERLAND' WORTH SEEING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The reason to see ``Next Stop, Wonderland'' is for its lovely,
grave central performance by Hope Davis.
</P>
<P>
   This New York actress has done terrific work in the past in
films like ``The Daytrippers'' and ``The Myth Of Fingerprints,''
but as Erin Castleton, a Boston nurse looking for ``quietness
without loneliness'' after her activist boyfriend leaves her, she's
reflective and very nearly still, yet makes a big impression in her
understatement.
</P>
<P>
   Erin is devastated. All her ex has left behind is his cat. He's
cited his ``eight reasons for going'' on a video tape, but she
can't even watch it because he's taken the VCR. Erin's mother,
played with rollicking ``joie de vivre'' by Holland Taylor, places
a personals ad in the paper for Erin because she's tired of seeing
her daughter mope around her apartment all the time.
</P>
<P>
   In a serio-comic montage, Erin suffers the humiliation of
sifting through the candidates who have replied to the ad. The
experience exasperates and horrifies her and she figures she'd
rather be alone than deal with such misery.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of town, plumber-turned-diver Alan Monteiro
(Alan Gelfant) is whittling away at his marine biology thesis and
is supporting himself by working at the aquarium. He's
over-extended with the local bookie because he's trying to pay off
his dad's gambling debts so he's working overtime while living with
his brother. Erin and Alan just miss meeting each other in scene
after scene full of coincidence and fleeting possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Erin finds her real soulmate when she least expects
it, but the road is full of pitfalls and emotional craters. The
premise that two people pass by each other in fateful ways and
finally meet when they're ready for love isn't new to the movies.
Just recently, ``Til There Was You'' covered the same turf, but
``Next Stop, Wonderland'' is a lot more intriguing and
well-designed.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brad Anderson, who signed a 7-figure, multi-picture
deal with Miramax based upon the response at this year's Sundance
Film Festival, the movie is terrifically edited (by Anderson) and
is full of the incidental life signs that are significant and true.
</P>
<P>
   And Davis and Alan Gelfant _ are likeable, no-nonsense,
unfettered actors who keep the journey toward their fateful meeting
low-key and appealing.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is all the supporting ``noise'' going on around
them. Anderson clutters his movie with too much peripheral
``stuff'' and against an actor like Davis, who we can't take out
eyes off anyway, it becomes a nuisance instead of an amusement.
</P>
<P>
   Next Stop, Wonderland. Directed by Brad Anderson. Written by
Anderson, Lyn Vaus. Cast: Hope Davis, Alan Gelfant, Holland Taylor.
Miramax Films. 97 minutes. Rated R for language, sexual themes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
