<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Aug. 28:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIA &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans three pages of coverage on the
deteriorating economic and political situation in Russia and its
impact around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Here is an early list of stories:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RDP (Moscow) _ Developments in Russia: Acting premier
Viktor Chernomyrdin holds intense political consultations with key
figures as the political crisis deepens; the Central Bank halts
dollar sales for the second straight day in an effort to save its
dwindling hard currency reserves, while opposition lawmakers call
for a return to Soviet-style fixed prices and state ownership. By
Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BANKS (Moscow) _ Banking developments in Russia. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-COALITION (Moscow) _ Chernomyrdin sends signals that he
wants to form a coalition that embraces tycoons and Communists
alike. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-EUROPE (Paris) _ European reaction to developments in
Russia: Is there any possibility Europe will ever give any more
money to Russia? By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S. (Washington) _ Where is Washington on the mess in
Russia? By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on the U.S.
role in the Russian economic and political situation. By R.W. Apple
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Washington) _ What is IMF doing? What did
Chernomydin and Camdessus, the IMF chief, say to each other at
their Crimea meeting?. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these stories from the Foreign Desk of The Times,
we plan these from The Financial Desk:
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks fall sharply; the long bond's yield
sets another record low. At 12:55 p.m., the industrial average was
off 264 points, the Nasdaq index was down 79 points. The long bond
was up 25/32 point, with the yield at 5.38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS (New York) _ Republic New York will take a
$110 million charge in the third quarter for losses on Russian
government bonds, ``substantially'' eliminating earnings for the
period. And bank stocks get clobbered again. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ATTACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-ARRAIGN (New York) _ One of the suspects in the bombing
of the U.S. Embassy in Kenya is brought to New York to face U.S.
charges in the blast; an indictment is expected that may include
others tied to the explosion. By Christopher Drew.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-U.S. (Washington) _ FBI Director Freeh, Attorney General
Reno and Secretary of State Albright hold news conference to
discuss developments in the embassy bombings. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-CAPETOWN (Capetown, South Africa) _ Developments in the
aftermath of the Planet Hollywood bombing. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BOMB (Tel Aviv) _ A bomb packed with nails exploded in a
garbage can during morning rush hour today at a busy Tel Aviv
intersection, injuring several people, including two children.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ The Kenneth Starr grand jury meets
for the only time this week; developments in the investigation of
the president.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SPEECH (Worcester, Mass.) _ The president speaks on
crime. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   FAA-AIR-SAFETY (Washington) _ The NTSB says that the FAA may be
responsible for some crashes because its bureaucracy loses track of
manufacturers' safety recommendations. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-BONNIE (Wilmington, N.C.) _ Hurricane Bonnie lost
punch as it sloshed across North Carolina Thursday, but the storm's
heavy rain and slow movement threatened severe flooding on the
state's coastal plain. The storm came ashore with 115-mph winds on
Wednesday but quickly slowed to a crawl and gradually lost
strength. There were no reports of widespread damage, injuries or
deaths, though nearly a half-million people had been ordered to
evacuate in North and South Carolina. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-DISAPPEAR (Undated) _ So you're charged with a crime
in New Jersey and facing a court date in mid-September. And it just
so happens that a huge hurricane is churning in the Atlantic. An
opportunity in the making? Seems like it. The Police in Point
Pleasant, N.J. believe that Antonio Mandarino, earlier reported
drowned in ocean riptides, actually faked his disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   CT-GIRL-SLAIN (Willimantic, Conn.) _ Police here have arrested a
convicted sex offender in the death of an 11-year-old girl who
lived in the same apartment complex as him. This is just the sort
of thing that lawmakers hoped to prevent when the state passed its
version of Megan's Law.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The MARKET story, listed above, will also be filed on the
Financial wire.
</P>
<P>
   CBS-SPINOFF (New York) _ CBS will sell 20 percent of its radio
and outdoor-advertising businesses in an initial public offering,
forming a new company called Infinity Broadcasting. It will take a
restructuring charge in the third quarter of between $50 million
and $70 million. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   CENDANT (Undated) _ Cendant's board hears the audit committee's
report. Cendant also says it will delay filing its restated
financial statements with the Securities and Exchange Commission
until late September because of changes requested by the
commission. By Adam Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST-PILOTS (Undated) _ Northwest developments as Friday
midnight strike deadline nears. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   ISIS-DRUG (Undated) _ The shares of Isis Pharmaceuticals rise
4.8 percent following the Food and Drug Administration's
announcement Wednesday afternoon that it has approved the company's
drug for retinitis. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-ECON (Toronto) _ Canada's central bank, trying to halt
the local dollar's slide, raises the overnight lending rate 1
percentage point, to 6 percent. Stocks fall sharply. By Anthony
DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   NOVARTIS-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Novartis, the world's largest
health-care company, says that earnings rose 14 percent in the
first half and that it will sell low-margin nutrition brands to
increase profitability. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   CHANCELLOR-CAPSTAR (Dallas) _ Chancellor Media buys Capstar
Broadcasting for $4.1 billion in stock, creating the largest radio
broadcaster in the country. By Allen R. Myerson.
</P>
<P>
   PANAMSAT-OUTLOOK (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ The outlook for
Panamsat following last night's explosion of a rocket that was
carrying a satellite whose use Panamsat intended to sell to cable
television carriers and telecommunications companies. By Seth
Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code
</P>
<P>
   A.M. Rosenthal's ``On My Mind'' and Russell Baker's
``Observer''; details to come.
</P>
