<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, Aug.
28, 1998. We will update this budget at 6 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Separate feature and commentary budgets move at 10 a.m. EDT
Monday-Friday. Separate sports and business budgets move at 5 p.m.
EDT Monday-Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456. The night news editor, until 10
p.m. EDT, is Todd C. Duncan at 404-582-7282.
</P>
<P>
   With questions about Washington-originated material, please call
our Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE COVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE _ WASHINGTON, N.C. _ A sluggish Bonnie, downgraded to a
tropical storm, wrung itself out like a washcloth over North
Carolina on Thursday, threatening severe flooding that could prove
far more damaging than the hurricane's winds. North Carolina got
more than 10 inches of rain. (Burritt, Manuel/Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   NOBEACH _ TOPSAIL BEACH, N.C. _ When the weather cleared,
assessment teams today were going out on the beach at Topsail,
N.C., hard hit by Hurricane Fran two years ago. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS _ WASHINGTON, N.C. _ This inland town on the Pamlico
River braced for flooding this afternoon as Bonnie moves over the
Outer Banks. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DAMAGE _ Coastal map showing damages from Bonnie. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NOTEBOOK _ Hurricane Notebook. (Atlanta Jourtnal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ATTN EDITORS: Here are resources Cox has covering Hurricane
Bonnie:
</P>
<P>
   _ Atlanta has reporters Marlon Manuel and Chris Burritt in North
Carolina for the duration of the storm. Their stories are scheduled
to move on the Cox wire by 8:30 every evening. Also, AJC
photographer W.A. Bridges Jr. will file photos.
</P>
<P>
   _ All three daily Cox papers in N.C. are filing. Greenville will
file a late-night story on storm damage. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   _ Elizabeth City, on the coast, and Rocky Mount, a couple hours
inland, are afternoon papers and are also filing stories on damage
in their areas. Their copy will move in the afternoon on the Cox
wire. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   DANIELLE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ What's happening with
Hurricane Danielle and any lingering effects from Bonnie? Checking
beach conditions, EOC officials, water managers about canals,
turtle nests, etc. (Moffett, Palm Beach Post). WITH GRAPHIC AND
FORECAST BOX.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS FLOODING
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-COLONIAS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As floodwaters threatened to
wash away hundreds of modest homes in Rio Bravo and El Cenizo,
about 800 women and children headed to the safety of nearby
shelters. But many of their husbands and fathers remained behind,
to guard what few possessions they own against looters. (Wear,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LAREDO-UPDATE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Fear turned into skeptism among
residents as the forecasted raging floodwaters of the Rio Grande
arrived in Laredo as a sluggish rise, seeping close to, but not
into, nearby homes and businesses. There were no reports of deaths
or injuries in the Laredo area from the river's rise, a result of
heavy rains upstream spawned by Tropical Storm Charley.
(Tanamachi/Wear, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NATIONAL NEWS . . .
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS -- PROVIDENCE, Rhode Island _ Marking the 35th anniversary
of the historic civil rights march on Washington, Rep. John Lewis
travels to Providence, R.I. to speak with Rep. Patrick Kennedy
about what can be done to improve race relations. He will meet with
the Rhode Island Civil Rights Roundtable as well as other civic
groups. (Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   JONBENET _ As the JonBenet Ramsey case moves toward the grand
jury, Patsy Ramsey's sister, Pam Paugh, speaks from her Dunwoody
home. How are John and Patsy Ramsey preparing for the grand jury?
How are they feeling right now? How is the family dealing with it,
including young Burke. What does Pam expect Patsy and John to tell
the grand jury? (Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIAN _ Amnesty International and the American Civil Liberties
Union filed suit Thursday against a Bosnian man living in the
Atlanta area, accusing him of war crimes and genocide during the
East European conflict. It is the first suit of its kind in the
country against a Serbian defendant. The same lawyers successfully
sued an Ethiopian prison guard for atrocities here a few years ago.
(Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECONOMY_ MOSCOW _ Russia indefinitely suspended
exchange-trading of the free-falling ruble after its value slid
Thursday nearly 50 percent from where it stood two weeks ago. The
central bank essentially has left the currency's value to be
determined on the streets in a further sign that it has lost its
grip on the tattered banking and currency system. The ever-deeper
financial crisis comes amid a political vacuum as Prime
Minister-designate Viktor Chernomyrdin struggles to form a
government and rumors continue to swirl that President Boris
Yeltsin may resign. Meanwhile, some opposition parliament members
called for a return to Soviet-style price controls and state
ownership of banks and companies. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   LATAM-ECONOMY _ MIAMI _ Russian's deepening financial crisis has
sent stock markets
</P>
<P>
   in Latin America into a tailspin, while putting pressure on the
region's currencies. Latin American stocks have plunged this week
as Russian losses pushed interest rates higher on concern that
currency devaluations would spread. Economists are hopeful though
that economic reforms in Latin America, such as privatization of
state-owned industries, will stave off long-term economic disaster.
(Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 4 p.m. EDT in both the (i) International and (f)
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BOMBING _ TEL AVIV _ A rush-hour bombing killed no one,
but injured 18, left impressions of nails imbedded in window panes
and brought back the spectre of terrorism to Israel, so often its
target. Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said, ``There's no
apparent connection between this bombing and other recent bombings
in South Africa, Kenya and Tanzania, except in showing that
terrorism must be fought worlwide.'' (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 4 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   DEMS _ Mark Sherman spends the day with House Minority Leader
Dick Gephardt and Democratic campaign head Martin Frost as they try
to shore up support in several close races in California. We'll see
how the Clinton scandal is playing on the stump. (Sherman, Cox
Washington Bureau).
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-SENATE _ From President Clinton's home state of Arkansas
to the Republican bastion of South Carolina, the South is serving
up some of the most competitive Senate contests in the country in
the 1998 mid-term elections. The parties are vying for open seats
in Arkansas and Kentucky and struggling to defend incumbents in
North Carolina (Republican Sen. Lauch Faircloth) and South Carolina
(Democrat Ernest Hollings). Relatively strong Democratic turnout in
the Georgia primary could also make things interesting for Sen.
Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) in the Peach State. (Foskett, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   w/sig needed.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-NCAROLINA _ Can a freshman Republican who has made
District of Columbia's leadership woes his most visible legacy use
the issue to win re-election in North Carolina? Sen. Lauch
Faircloth (R-N.C.), running against millionaire John Edwards,
thinks so. (Foskett., Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-MCLANE _ WASHINGTON _ An IRS decision to deny tax deductions
for losses and for executive cash and stock bonuses could cost
McLane Co., Inc., $17.5 million. (Moskal, Cox News Service 520).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: (For Texas papers)
</P>
