<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-BUDGET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
.
</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
FOOLS-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ Nearly 20 years ago, writer Tina
Andrews heard Diana Ross' remake of the Frankie Lymon hit ``Why Do
Fools Fall in Love,'' remembered Lymon's tragic life and thought,
``Hmm ... Frankie's story could be a decent movie.'' Now, Andrews'
idea of a Lymon biopic is finally coming to a theater near you. By
Glenn Whipp. 
. 
SHORT-FILM (Los Angeles) _ This weekend's ``Summer Shorts at One
Colorado'' is an off-the-wall exhibition of shorts by up-and-coming
filmmakers. And it's literally off the wall because the outdoor
screenings are taking place on the side of a two-story building. By
Bob McCarthy. 
. 
54-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ The people who made ``54'' surely didn't
intend for the movie to prove the old adage that disco sucks. But
they prove it nevertheless. 2 Stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
FOOLS-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love'' features
some fine performances, but the movie never quite decides what it
wants to be. A biography? Courtroom drama? Manifesto on the ills of
addiction? So, it manages to be only interesting _ and never
particularly moving. 2{ Stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
STRANGE-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``I Married a Strange Person,'' from
the drawing table and somewhat twisted psyche of illustrator Bill
Plympton, is wildly imaginative and enjoyably sick. 3 Stars). By
Bob Strauss. 
. 
GAINES-STAGE (Los Angeles) _ Davis Gaines is the Mark McGwire of
musical theater, having played the ``Phanton'' more times (1,956)
than any other phantom, even Michael Crawford. The show returns to
L.A. Sunday through Nov. 1 at the Pantages Theatre, giving us a
chance to talk with this once-alienated youth wo identifies with
the man behind the mask. By Reed Johnson. 
. 
JAZZ-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Groove merchants Medeski Martin &AMP; Wood
have long been lumbered with the acid-jazz tag, an often dismissive
label for various forms of rhythm-based music. By Fred Shuster. 
 
 
 
 
POP-BEAT (Los Angeles) _ When you talk to him, Travis Meeks sounds
young. Which figures, since the leader of popular alt-rock group
Days of the New is just 19. The quartet's self-titled debut on
Outpost/Geffen has spent more than a year on the nation's pop
albums chart. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ The doe-eyed Lauryn Hill was featured
performer on the Fugees' Grammy-winning smash, ``The Score,'' on
which she crooned the ubiquitous cover of Roberta Flack's ``Killing
Me Softly.'' Now comes her engaging and self-assured ``The
Miseducation of Lauryn Hill,'' one of the best releases of the year
and a must-hear for anyone curious about the state of r&AMP;b in 1998. 
. 
EXORCIST-VIDEO (Los Angeles) _ Think vomited pea soup, a 360-degree
head swivel by a foul-mouthed child, the tinkling sounds of Mike
Oldfield's ``Tubular Bells'' and a devil of a time. It must be
``The Exorcist.'' This week, Warner Bros. released a 25th
anniversary special edition video ($19.98) that includes a
30-minute documentary on the making of the film, offering some
fascinating tidbits and a chance to reassess the blockbuster. By
Rob Lowman. 
. 
. 

