<HEADLINE>
HEADLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
LAURYN HILL/``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill''
(RuffHouse/Columbia)!off!
<TEXT>
<P>
   The doe-eyed Hill was featured performer on the Fugees'
Grammy-winning smash, ``The Score,'' on which she crooned the
ubiquitous cover of Roberta Flack's ``Killing Me Softly.'' Now
comes her engaging and self-assured solo opus, one of the best
releases of the year and a must-hear for anyone curious about the
state of r&AMP;b in 1998. The album makes forays into hip-hop with cuts
like ``Doo Wop (That Thing),'' reggaefied grooves on album-opener
``Lost Ones'' and the gorgeous ``To Zion'' featuring Carlos
Santana. Warm and sensitive as a singer, Hill is a groundbreaker as
producer, too. 3{ Stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
