<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-AIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR'S AIDE IS A MODEL OF EFFICIENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1998 San Francsico Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Esther Hwang may be most ogled scheduling
secretary in municipal history.
</P>
<P>
   Hwang _ a recent graduate of the University of California at
Berkeley and a former Miss Asian America _ runs Mayor Willie
Brown's bustling scheduling department, booking roughly two dozen
meetings and events a day, fending off stacks of invitations,
calibrating Brown's days and evenings down to driving and
``cushion'' time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, my job is to take care of the mayor,'' Hwang, 23,
said. ``He's Super Mayor, but he's only human. I have to make sure
his schedule is realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco mayor is a notorious workaholic, but his
special assistant _ who earns $42,760 per year _ keeps her own
swift pace, guiding a sideline modeling career that's taking
flight.
</P>
<P>
   Hwang, who grew up in Los Angeles, recently became the
spokesmodel for a car dealership and a cable company. There are
other deals looming for car accessory work in Las Vegas, Nev., a
good thing because Hwang really likes cars.
</P>
<P>
   The tabloid television show ``Inside Edition'' plans a profile
soon. And on Sept. 2, she'll participate in the Miss California USA
pageant. Last year, she placed fourth out of 77 in the competition,
particularly impressing the judges in the swimsuit portion.
</P>
<P>
   But Hwang's primary calling card is a Web site (www.esther.com)
featuring her in microscopic lingerie, swimwear and casual wear,
none of the photos retouched or airbrushed.
</P>
<P>
   The accompanying text is a trifle tortuous: ``With her long
shiny black hair framing an unforgettable face with her mesmerizing
cat eyes, she is as always armed with a dangerously contagious
smile.''
</P>
<P>
   Web crawlers aren't turning to Hwang's electronic page for the
merits of its prose.
</P>
<P>
   ``People go straight to lingerie, then swimsuits,'' Hwang said,
eyes rolling. ``This site was created not to make money, but to
promote myself as a model. I want people to take me seriously as a
professional model. If people are interested in booking me, the
information is on-line.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Internet watchers, she's huge in Singapore, Korea and
Australia. The most ``hits'' come from California and New York, but
Hwang _ to her bewilderment _ also has a large fan base in
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my staff people called to my attention that she had an
Internet (site) ... I said, what do you mean, what do you mean?''
said Brown, a bemused supporter of his assistant's extracurricular
job. ``I said print it out, let me take a look. It was a very
impressive portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   Hwang, a professional model since she was 16, actually launched
her Web page two years ago, but the site received little attention
until it was described in a newspaper article in June.
</P>
<P>
   The floodgates opened. So many people scanned the site that it
overheated and crashed. Back in operation, it generated about
100,000 ``hits'' a day for nearly two weeks until leveling at about
50 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Hwang was deluged with e-mail and phone calls from police
officers, firemen, divorced men and radio talk-show hosts wanting
to put her on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned them down _ they just wanted to make me look like a
bimbo,'' she said. ``It was like the `Love Connection' in here.''
</P>
<P>
   One guy mailed her Beanie Babies. Another offered her $100 for a
nude photo. Some made crude passes, others offered lucrative sums
to publish porn ads on her site, all firmly rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Catapulted into computerized fame, a stricken Hwang was caught
unprepared. The world instantaneously acquired, she says, a
mistaken impression of her. To outsiders, she says, she seemed not
like a purposeful young woman marketing herself for potential jobs,
but rather a blowsy Internet babe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could put up a sign on the page saying `Don't ask for
nude photos, there aren't any,''' she said with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   Women contacted Hwang as well, accusing her of setting back the
feminist cause a full century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feminists don't like me,'' she said. ``They said if I'm a Cal
grad, why am I out in my underwear? I think being a woman is just
as powerful as being a man. But women forget that the power is not
rooted in losing our femininity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people will laugh in my face, but I am a feminist to an
extent. ... I'm a realist, also. I understand how difficult it is
for a woman to get ahead in corporate America. If you are born with
a brain, it's a given that you use it to advantage. That's how I
feel about other assets you may have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
