<HEADLINE>
SHORT FILMS LONG ON STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For an off-the-wall exhibition, Old Pasadena is
definitely the place to head this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer Shorts at One Colorado,'' a new festival of short
films, starts tonight and runs through Sunday in the historic
downtown area. Films by up-and-coming directors and writers will be
exhibited outdoors on the side of a two-story building in the
Courtyard of One Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The American Film Institute has lined up 11 titles, including
nine award winners. At 8 tonight, three top films by AFI students
will be screened:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``John,'' directed by Marni Banack and produced by J.B. Sugar.
A men's room attendant in an upscale restaurant might be forced to
retire after 20 years on the job. Running time: 21 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Short Wait Between Trains,'' directed by Rick Wilkinson.
Back from the front in World War II, four African-American soldiers
return to the inequality of their native Georgia. Running time: 26
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``When I Was a Boy'' directed by Isabelle Fox. A coming-of-age
comedy about a 12-year-old tomboy. Running time: 17{ minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A party hosted by Il Fornaio will follow tonight's exhibition.
``Summer Shorts'' is free and open to the public. Audience members
can meet the filmmakers in the hospitality suite next to the
courtyard. Reserved seating is available for American Express
cardholders by calling (626) 564-1066.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's slate of shorts shares a theme of love tangles,
while Sunday's program explores the make-believe and includes the
work of Pasadena filmmaker Michael Sokey. Parking is available at
Fair Oaks Avenue and Union Street. For festival information, call
(626) 564-1066.
</P>
<P>
   `SHANGAI' RETURNS: Fifty years after its original release, Orson
Welles' 1948 film noir classic ``The Lady of Shanghai'' is back in
the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Welles' own lady at the time, Rita Hayworth, co-stars with him
as an alluring woman of many secrets married to a rich, older man.
Welles plays a stranger who wanders into their lives. The climactic
shootout in a hall of mirrors is legendary.
</P>
<P>
   The making of this film is a story in itself. Welles needed cash
to finance a stage version of ``Around the World in 80 Days'' he
was directing, so he approached Columbia exec Harry Cohn with a
deal: Money now for a movie later. To bolster his offer, Welles
quickly threw out the name of a paperback an employee was reading.
Though the book turned out to be less than what he expected, Welles
finished the film on time and on budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lady From Shanghai'' opens tonight at Landmark's Cecchi
Gori Fine Arts Theatre, 8556 Wilshire Blvd. For program
information, call (310) 652-1330.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
