<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM STUDIO JAMS TO GROOVE NUMBERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Groove merchants Medeski Martin &AMP; Wood have long
been lumbered with the acid-jazz tag, an often dismissive label for
various forms of rhythm-based music.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the postmodern organ trio went a step further into the
avant-garde by hooking up with turntable maestro DJ Logic for three
tracks on the group's new album, ``Combustication'' (Blue Note).
</P>
<P>
   Although the disc is dominated by cooking groove numbers that
grew out of studio jams, there are also eerie-sounding reflective
pieces, a Latin shuffle, instrumental forays and a Kerouacian
spoken-word performance by blind East Village jazz aficionado/arts
dealer Steve Cannon on the track ``Whatever Happened to Gus.''
</P>
<P>
   Medeski Martin &AMP; Wood (MMW) got its start in the early '90s as a
piano-led ensemble gigging regularly at New York's downtown
Knitting Factory. Eventually developing into an organ-based trio,
MMW released five albums on other labels before moving to the
prestigious Blue Note jazz imprint last year.
</P>
<P>
   The trio was chosen by guitarist John Scofield to back him on
his acclaimed recent effort, ``A Go Go'' (Verve).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our approach hasn't changed much,'' said MMW drummer Billy
Martin. ``We're not really a conceptual band. Basically, when we
start preparing for a record date, we'll rehearse a little bit, but
we don't really know how it's going to end up. We start with some
sketchy ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   DJ Logic (Jason Kibler) appears on the cuts ``Sugarcraft,''
``Start-Stop'' and ``Church of Logic,'' scratching biting rhythms
and ambient textures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always had an affinity for that sort of DJ hip-hop
thing,'' Martin explained. ``We always wanted to work with a DJ but
didn't think we could find someone who could improvise with us on
the spot. Not only does Logic have a great ear, he's just another
musician. He has his own distinctive voice on the turntables.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin says the key to the band's longevity is the chemistry
among the musicians. MMW also includes keyboardist John Medeski and
bassist Chris Wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We admire each other,'' Martin said. ``It's like a family.
We're here to play music, but we're also friends. All our
compositions are collaborations that we spontaneously develop on
the road or in the studio.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin recalls the early years when audiences often were not
used to seeing vintage keyboards on stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning, people were amazed we were carrying this
Hammond B-3 up the stairs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many jazz-based outfits, MMW doesn't mind that its music
inspires movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get crowds moving, that's great,'' Martin said.
``People like to dance in this country, and that's what got us to
play grooves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
