<SLUG> BC-POP-BEAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYS OF THE NEW'S LEADER MEEKS SPEAKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; When you talk to him, Travis Meeks sounds young.
</P>
<P>
   Which figures, since the leader of popular alt-rock group Days
of the New is just 19. The quartet's self-titled debut on
Outpost/Geffen has spent more than a year on the nation's pop
albums chart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other musicians, they're not really into where I'm
going,'' Meeks said this week from Kansas. ``I'm just doing my own
thing, so I can relate to people on a spiritual level.''
</P>
<P>
   The members of Days of the New hooked up in Louisville, Ky. The
album, featuring such radio-friendly tunes as ``Touch, Peel and
Stand'' and ``What's Left for Me?'' was cut in Nashville with
longtime R.E.M. producer Scott Litt.
</P>
<P>
   The group opens for Metallica tonight at Irvine Meadows
Amphitheatre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write songs so quick,'' Meeks said. ``I write on the road,
in hotels, at home. I can do it anywhere. I just get into a zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeks plays almost all the instruments on the nearly completed
Days of the New follow-up album, due in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a little more work to do, some orchestrations,'' the
singer said. ``It's a very musical record. It might sell 2 million
or it might sell 200. It might sell nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   After two years on the road, Meeks said he's learned a hard
lesson about the music business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really fake, and it hurts me as a human being,'' he said.
``I can't stand it when people talk about me like they know me.''
</P>
<P>
   THEY CAME, THEY SAWED...: New Orleans rockers Better Than Ezra
got out the saws and hammers and simply built their own Fudge
Studios.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an old garage off St. Charles Avenue,'' explains
singer-guitarist Kevin Griffin. ``A photographer was using it as
his studio. People say it reminds them of Studio B at Abbey Road in
London because it has 25-foot ceilings and the control room looks
down on the recording room. We put up a disco ball and all these
hand-embroidered gowns and stuff from Mardis Gras in the '70s to
muffle the sound.''
</P>
<P>
   Better Than Ezra's just-issued ``How Does Your Garden Grow?''
(Elektra) was produced, engineered and mixed by Malcolm Burn, who
has twiddled the knobs for Patti Smith, U2 and Iggy Pop.
</P>
<P>
   The trio scored a top-40 hit in 1995 with ``Good,'' fueling
sales of their indie debut, ``Deluxe,'' which eventually reached
the 1-million mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alternative radio is good, but when people see they can make
money, the playlists get tighter and it turns into another type of
hit radio,'' Griffin said. ``That's when you start having all these
one-hit wonders.''
</P>
<P>
   ALLEN AT THE BAKERY: Jazz fans will want to note the return of
pianist Geri Allen to the Jazz Bakery in Culver City from Sept. 8
to 13. Allen's latest disc, ``The Gathering'' (Verve), has received
raves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
