r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOLS-REVIEW-LADN     08-27 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOLS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FOOLS' STUMBLES IN THE TELLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ During his brief life, one-hit-wonder Frankie
Lymon loved many women and even married three of them. But female
companionship could never take the place of the excitement Frankie
felt when he was on stage, performing bouncy ditties like ``Why Do
Fools Fall in Love'' He never let his wives _ or anyone else _ know
him. Today, most people can sing along with ``Fools,'' but would be
hard-pressed to name its singer.
</P>
<P>
   When Lymon died _ and that's where this movie begins _ the three
Mrs. Lymons marched down to his record company's offices, demanding
the considerable proceeds from Diana Ross' hit remake of ``Fools.''
The women didn't want to split the money, and the case ended up
going to trial. And that's where we learn that not only were there
three Mrs. Lymons, but there were three, separate, distinct Frankie
Lymons as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love'' features some fine performances,
particularly by Larenz Tate (``lovejones'') as Lymon and Vivica A.
Fox (``Independence Day'') playing Lymon's second wife, a
street-smart woman who suffered the most from the singer's failed
ambitions and drug use.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie never settles on a tone. Is it a biography?
Courtroom drama? ``Just Say No'' manifesto? Because it never locks
into a groove, the film manages to be only interesting _ and never
particularly moving _ in an A&AMP;E ``Biography'' sort of way. And even
then, the filmmakers are maddeningly haphazard with the information
they choose to include. We're never sure how old Frankie was when
he hit the charts (only 13), a fact we realize only when actual
footage of Lymon looking like little Michael Jackson is shown at
the movie's conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Through the rather ridiculous courtroom sequences, we see the
three Lymons. First, there's the young, confident chart-topper who
toured with Little Richard (who makes an over-the-top appearance _
what other kind could he make? _ as a witness) and seduced
beautiful women like eventual Wife No. 1, Platters singer Zola
Taylor (a wonderfully glamorous Halle Berry).
</P>
<P>
   Soon, though, Frankie was off the charts and spending most of
his time scoring drugs instead of hit singles. Zola goes on tour,
so Frankie hooks up with Wife No. 2, Elizabeth Waters (Fox), whom
he meets after she's caught shoplifting in a department store.
Fast-forward years later, and there's Wife No. 3, a demure
schoolteacher (Lela Rochon) who manages to domesticate Frankie for
a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   The women spend a lot time degrading each other in the courtroom
(``Miss Thing'' is the epithet of choice), which gets old after
awhile. Another problem is the film's lack of insight into the
choices these people made. Director Gregory Nava (``Selena'') hits
all the high points and includes a couple of eye-popping period
concert sequences, but by the end of the film, you don't really
feel you know the characters any more than when it began two hours
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   You sure will be humming the song, though.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
