<HEADER>
A5368 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATIAN-SCHOLAR-ART-BO     08-27 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATIAN-SCHOLAR-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALE OF TWO NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For four months while she was a college student, Nadine
Duplessy bewildered everyone who passed her in the streets of
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Her skin was the color of copper. Braids hung like soft rope
from her head. Yet when she opened her mouth, she spoke their
language with an uncanny traditional inflection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really freaked people out,'' said Duplessy, who was born in
Haiti, came of age in Boston, and at age 20 found herself a walking
anomaly in the city of Chiba, Japan. ``Some people thought I
vaguely had something to do with reggae. Then I took the braids
out, and they thought I was Iranian. There's a large population of
Nigerians in Japan, and even they would come up to me like, `Where
are you from? Because you're not one of us.'''
</P>
<P>
   But where others saw only a question mark, Duplessy saw a
connection. She saw two islands _ one an Asian superpower, the
other an impoverished Caribbean nation _ that shared similar
cultural values, and could share the kind of economic ties that
might spur desperately needed economic recovery in her homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing that potential link has earned Duplessy, now 24, one of
the first prizes in a new scholarship founded this year by two New
York philanthropists. Established with a $50 million charitable
trust by Paul and Daisy Soros, the Soros Fellowships for New
Americans support graduate study for immigrants and children of
immigrants. Twenty fellows, all in their 20s, were chosen this
year; next year the pool of winners will expand to 30.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to create a fellowship akin to the Rhodes and Fulbright
scholarships, an independent panel for the Soros program selected
fellows with an eye to finding future leaders who have overcome
obstacles to achieve excellence. Only two of the 20 winners spoke
English as a first language; six came to the United States as
political refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immigrants have made great contributions to this country and
throughout the entire history of the United States,'' said Paul
Soros, himself a Hungarian-born immigrant who defected to the US
from the Hungarian Olympic ski team in 1948. Daisy Soros, who
serves on the fellowship's board, was born in Czechoslovakia. ``Our
purpose is to find people among today's immigrants who have the
potential to make such contributions, and to enable them to succeed
in their chosen fields.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11 women and nine men chosen include a former New York
Chinatown gang member now in law school, a child of Indian
immigrants who invented a new prosthetic arm, and one of the last
Russian defectors from the Soviet Union, who escaped from the KGB
at age 17 during a US piano concert tour in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Duplessy, who graduated from Harvard College in 1996 with a
degree in East Asian Studies, is one of three Haitians who received
grants this year.
</P>
<P>
   In pursuing her goal of promoting Japanese investment in the
Caribbean, &UR;  &LR; she has temporarily hung up her status as a walking
contradiction inside Japan's uniform society. Instead, she will
stay close to home, starting graduate school next week at the
Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University.
</P>
<P>
   There, she said, she will explore how to build economic
relationships from the many unseen cultural links that already
exist between the Caribbean and Pacific islands.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the connection defies intuition. Only 10
Haitians are known to live in Japan, according to Haitian
Ambassador to Japan Marcel Duret. But some ties do bind the
far-flung islands. Japan has its own embassy in Haiti, and in 1995,
the Japanese government sent two officials to Haiti as part of an
international corps of election observers. That same year, Japan
spent more than $6 million in humanitarian aid to Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For her part, Duplessy instinctively felt the cultural
overlaps when she visited Japan _ from the common diet of rice and
fish to the rigid gender roles separating men and women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds strange, but being in Japan, there really wasn't
that much of a culture gap for me, and I could easily adapt,'' said
Duplessy, as she sat in a coffee shop near her alma mater in
Harvard Square. ``There is a certain way of talking to people who
are older than you, where you don't talk back to them. And the
kids, they study all the time and their parents really emphasize
that, which is how I grew up in Haiti. We were told that our
studies were our lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I started making those links, I thought, maybe there's a
way I can connect these two experiences and give something back to
my country,'' Duplessy said. ``I wasn't sure how, but I could see
the possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   From an early age, Duplessy learned to create possibility out of
hardship. She left Port-au-Prince, Haiti, for the US in 1985 with
her parents and two sisters. She was 11 years old, and spoke no
English. The brutal, 29-year regime of the Duvalier family was
coming to a convulsive end, and her family hoped to escape a life
where her mother could not find work, and where sometimes Duplessy
found little more in her lunch bag than a peanut-butter sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   But while the world she left behind was one of struggle, it was
also one where she ruled the corridors of her school as a popular,
accomplished student. One where she found strong, silent heroes in
a house filled with aunts, grandmothers, and other female
relatives, many of whom worked.
</P>
<P>
   She was a middle child in an idyllic world _ too young to be
bothered with boys, old enough to build a universe of friends.
Suddenly, she was making secret preparations to flee, unable to
tell even her closest friends because of her family's fear that
others might grow jealous of their break for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point it seemed like all of us weren't going to be able
to leave together, and I volunteered to be the one to stay back,''
Duplessy said. ``The year before at our school we had had this big
carnival, and I was chosen as like a queen for this float, then got
sick and couldn't go. And I kept saying, `I have to be queen next
year! I have to!' But then we all ended up leaving at the same time
anyway. I was so bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks of arriving in the United States, however,
bitterness soon gave way to new friends and new stability in
Boston's Dorchester neighborhood, where her aunt and uncle were
well-known in the city's Haitian community. After one year of
bilingual education and one year at the Woodrow Wilson School, she
was admitted at the Boston Latin School.
</P>
<P>
   It was a trajectory that fulfilled the dreams of her immigrant
parents, who had groomed her for medical school and a prestigious
career as a doctor _ still the most respected profession in their
native Haiti. But then, Duplessy got to Harvard, and something
happened: She took Japanese on a lark, and she loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did my roomates think? Crazy,'' she said of her new
obsession. ``I was the Haitian girl from Dorchester, and out of
nowhere I'm taking Japanese. I was walking around everywhere with
index cards with the English words on one side and the Japanese
characters on the other. It was out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   She quelled her parent's anxieties by promising she would go to
business school. But after leaving Harvard, she cut her own path,
studying Japanese business culture in Tokyo, and then teaching
others about what she had learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what kind of relationship can develop,'' Duplessy
said, aware that the path she has chosen to return home _ via Asia
_ may not be the most direct. ``It's something to work toward. But
if you can get people to listen to your ideas, they may start to
see something they never thought was there. So I'm just going to
keep doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
