<HEADER>
A5370 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-HEMINGWAY-BOS &LR;      08-27 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-HEMINGWAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME QUESTION LUSTER OF HEMINGWAY'S `LIGHT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ernest Hemingway wrote ``A Farewell to Arms'' and, with his
suicide in 1961, he wrote the farewell chapter to his own
larger-than-life life. What he failed to write, and may never have
wished to, was a definitive ending to his still-thriving publishing
career.
</P>
<P>
   With news that a Hemingway manuscript gathering dust at the John
F. Kennedy Library will be issued by Scribner's next summer as a
``new'' Hemingway novel, titled ``True at First Light'' and edited
by his 70-year-old middle son, Patrick Hemingway, some have
questioned the motives behind the project. Scribner's is said to
have paid $1 million for the rights.
</P>
<P>
   Is literary propriety being sacrificed to commercial interests?
some wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Or is any Hemingway _ bad or good, incandescent or
inconsequential _ better than no Hemingway at all?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of another author who has enjoyed such a
posthumous publishing life,'' says Hemingway biographer Michael
Reynolds. ``And part of it was planned on his part. He knew some of
the things he'd written couldn't be published in his lifetime. This
was the 1940s and '50s, after all.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's Press editor Robert Weil warns: Beware of the hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inevitably people assume it must be a great work if it's by a
great author, and inevitably they're disappointed,'' says Weil.
``The fact is, most things that did not get published by a great
author when he was alive were not great works in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publishers get caught up in the hype, and then the critics
savage the book and readers express their disappointment. It
becomes a sorry affair.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin Kaplan, a literary biographer who has written books on
Walt Whitman and Mark Twain, questions ``to what extent the author
is really the author'' when a heavily edited work appears 40 years
after his death.
</P>
<P>
   Says Kaplan, ``You have to ask how much value you attach to an
author's motives. Assuming he has some sense of the shape and
wholeness of his reputation, do you risk diminishing it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``True at First Light'' is a thinly fictionalized account of the
author's 1953 safari to Africa. It includes an account of an
interracial sexual episode that may or may not be true, but which
almost certainly would have caused rumblings in the more prudish
1950s. Scribner's will publish the book in July to coincide with
the centennial of Hemingway's birth. It is the fourth major
Hemingway book, all published by Scribner's, to appear in as many
decades, not counting various collections of the author's stories
and letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Movable Feast'' (1964), ``Islands in the Stream'' (1970),
and ``The Garden of Eden'' (1986) all sold six-figure totals in
hardcover and attained bestseller status, according to publisher
Charles Scribner. Of those three, only ``Eden'' was widely panned
by critics as being second-rate Hemingway. A British company is due
to film the novel next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most controversial posthumous Hemingway because it
was the most unfinished,'' Scribner concedes. With ``First Light,''
he asserts, pruning the 850-page manuscript Hemingway left to make
a 300-page novel did nothing to violate the spirit of the work as
Hemingway conceived it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick mostly took out the redundancies,'' says Scribner.
``It was the kind of editing his father would have done if he were
still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Controversy over posthumous publication by famous authors is
nothing new. Edith Wharton's ``The Buccaneers'' did not appear
until 1993, 56 years after she died. The manuscript was completed
by Boston researcher Marion Mainwaring, who wrote the last third of
the novel Wharton had left behind. The book was greeted with
splutters of protest by several prominent critics. John Updike
called it a ``bastardization'' in The New Yorker. New Republic
critic Andrew DelBanco dismissed the effort as an ``act of literary
necrophilia.''
</P>
<P>
   From Charles Dickens and Jane Austen to Ralph Ellison and Henry
Roth, plenty of high-profile authors have seen their work
unearthed, refitted with new material, and reissued from beyond the
grave. Even Margaret Mitchell was not immune to the publishing
industry's modern marketing forces. In 1991, Alexandra Ripley
published a dreadful ``sequel'' to ``Gone With the Wind''; and
three years ago Scribner's published a newly discovered Mitchell
short story whose literary merit was widely questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever faults lie in the Hemingway book, says Wendy Strothman,
editor in chief of Houghton Mifflin in Boston, ``It sure beats
having a sequel written by someone else. To me the question is,
where do you draw the line between serving the public and
exploiting a dead author's reputation? I don't know. The Hemingway
book sounds pretty interesting. I mean, you can turn your nose up
at it, but wouldn't you publish it if you had the chance?''
</P>
<P>
   Louisa May Alcott is another long-gone literary icon who's
enjoyed a prosperous run in the hype-driven 1990s. Two previously
unpublished novels by Alcott have debuted recently: ``The
Inheritance,'' which was discovered by two professors doing
research in Harvard's Houghton Library and published in 1997, with
sales of more than 100,000 copies, and ``A Long Fatal Love Chase,''
edited by Alcott scholar Kent Bicknell and published in 1995.
Publication rights to the latter sold for a reported $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based literary agent Lane Zachary, who handled both
Alcott books, sees at least one parallel between ``Love Chase'' and
the forthcoming Hemingway book. It also dealt with mature subject
matter _ in Alcott's case, a stalking relationship _ deemed too
steamy for its era's sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Says Zachary, ``There was a lot of talk among scholars, Alcott's
heirs and myself, whether `Inheritance' should be published. It was
a first novel, after all, but a lovely one. There was nothing in
there that would embarrass Alcott, and we felt it would provide
insight into her development as a writer.''
</P>
<P>
   However, says Zachary, ``I don't think anything goes. I'm sure
there are pieces writers have written for nobody's eyes. We're
walking a fine line here, because publishing pressure is all about
the dollar. Ernest Hemingway's and Margaret Mitchell's names sell
books. Given that assumption, why waste the opportunity?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1439EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
