<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5374 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS &LR;      08-27 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-LEWINSKY: SPARE US THE DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a December 1997 New Yorker piece, Gore Vidal described a
story that he and investigative reporter Seymour Hersh had heard
about John Kennedy. It was a graphic tale of a bizarre sexual
practice that made the late president seem more satyr than
statesman.
</P>
<P>
   By now, we've been inundated by tales of JFK's bedtime exploits.
It's fruitless to even contemplate whether we had the right to know
about this _ and what would have happened if we did know _ while he
had his finger on the button. In terms of the private lives of
public people, that was light years ago. But even given the recent
torrent of JFK promiscuity stories (In the HBO movie, ``The Rat
Pack,'' he more than holds his own with Sinatra and his swinging
pals.), the disturbing Hersh/Vidal anecdote was beyond the pale.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the latest alleged ``news'' about Bill
Clinton and Monica Lewinsky. Only days after the president took to
the airwaves to grudgingly and obliquely acknowledge a sexual
relationship with the former intern, a story has begun inching its
way up the media food chain. It too, is a seamy tale of a sexual
act between Clinton and Lewinsky. And it is fraught with peril, not
only for journalism, but for our culture.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike JFK's period of ``gatekeeper journalism'' when a few
powerful news outlets controlled the flow of information, we live
in an era of atomized news media and ``geyser journalism'' when
stories are propelled from beneath the surface up into the
mainstream media. (Thus, Gennifer Flowers's tryst with Clinton
migrated from the Star supermarket tabloid to ``Nightline'' and a
George Bush adultery rumor that began in The New York Post made it
onto the network nightly newscasts in one day.)
</P>
<P>
   Given the president's own admissions and Lewinsky's testimony,
it would be naive not to expect the many media references to the
nature of the sex acts between Lewinsky and Clinton. In one widely
quoted passage, this week's Newsweek magazine cited a source saying
that the details in independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report will
make people ``want to throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   But to date, the truly telltale details of the Clinton/Lewinsky
relationship have largely been the province of the media
netherworld and entertainment culture. Citing those ubiquitous
``multiple sources close to the case,'' cyber gossip Matt Drudge
gleefully announced the particulars on Aug. 22. Jay Leno, Howard
Stern, and various talk radio hosts picked it up. According to the
political Hotline newsletter, which is tracking such matters, the
matter has also made it into the London press, including the Daily
Telegraph, The Times, and The Independent.
</P>
<P>
   It briefly reared its ugly head when Republican pundit Mary
Matalin mentioned it on Sunday's ``Meet the Press'' program. (In
yesterday's Washington Post, Matalin said she inadvertently let the
remark slip, noting ``I don't think we need to know any of this.'')
Former Republican Congressman Robert Dornan alluded to it on the
Fox News Channel. And the story also surfaced in Tuesday's New York
Post, a newspaper that is often a conduit for unsavory information
that the mainstream media will not touch until it's first been
disinfected by the tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   My fervent hope that this story spreads no further _ at least
until and unless it appears in Starr's report to Congress _ is not
based on a desire to give Clinton a pass. The fundamental nature of
his relationship with Lewinsky is irreversibly part of the public
record and his presidency probably hinges on the nation's reaction
to it. And for now, we'll ignore the unsubstantiated nature of
these prurient details and the mysterious sourcing.
</P>
<P>
   The real question is when in this voyeuristic media culture do
we finally say ``no mas?''
</P>
<P>
   A good starting point might be when we move from knowing that an
inappropriate sexual relationship took place to knowing exactly
what kind of relationship that was. We are long past the stage when
anyone in the news could expect to shield extracurricular
dalliances from the spotlight. But until now, the painstaking
details of how they got their jollies have never been anyone's
business.
</P>
<P>
   But as was the case with the JFK anecdote, the new Clinton story
threatens to demolish the last bastion of sanity and privacy in a
frighteningly invasive culture.
</P>
<P>
   There is never any turning back the clock when the media marches
over an old taboo. Should we deem it vital to know just how Clinton
and Lewinsky amused each other, it is fair to assume that future
public figures will have to submit to the same scrutiny of the most
intimate of human acts. Who knows? Someday even famous journalists
might be forced to reveal whether they'd ever slipped a dollar into
a G-string at a strip show or used whipped cream in the boudoir.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, this ugly story threatens to cross the thinly guarded
border between the tabloids and tattlers and our living rooms. Many
mainstream news outlets are said to be ``struggling'' with how to
report the details.
</P>
<P>
   For them, this would be a good time to heed the advice of one
former first lady and ``just say no.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1441EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
