<HEADER>
A5377 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-27 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS CLINTON'S OOZE ZONE THINNING?
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Here's a bulletin from a recent meeting of the American
Psychological Society in San Francisco, a story in a British
newspaper The Daily Telegraph headlined ``Men ooze happiness to
women.'' It seems researchers at the University of Chicago have
found that women are happier if they inhale ``an odorless substance
derived from the male hormone testosterone.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear from the story whether all men ooze happiness, or
only some of them, and whether they ooze it all the time, or only
intermittently. My own research, admittedly anecdotal, leads me to
think that male happiness oozing must be a sometime thing. I think,
obviously, of our president, who has oozed more than his share of
happiness in the past. Lately his oozone layer appears to have
thinned, on the home front especially, if we can believe all the
``informed'' analyses of the Clinton marriage that keep popping up.
</P>
<P>
   It's human nature to speculate, I suppose, but who really knows
what's going on there? Every marriage is different. Some have less
to do with sex, or sexual fidelity, than they do with sharing
experiences, goals, values, finances, and other elements and
personal quirks beyond our knowing or comprehending. It's difficult
enough to understand your own marriage, let alone anybody else's.
The Clintons' union is really none of our business, but everything
about the president's personal life is our business now, whether we
like it or not, or whether we feel torn. One part of me doesn't
like it a bit, another wants more details.
</P>
<P>
   In an interesting interview with Maria Henson of the Charlotte
Observer, Ronald A. Heifetz, an authority on leadership who teaches
at Harvard's John F. Kennedy School of Government, suggests that
President Clinton could heal the country by admitting he's a sex
addict and getting some help. ``I think it would be extraordinarily
enlightening for the nation to see their president go to a 12-step
meeting each week,'' Heifetz said. ``I think it would be a great
move forward in giving permission to millions of Americans to face
up to their own problems that are still in the closet.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be extraordinarily enlightening, but it's difficult to
imagine. ``Hi, I'm Bill and I'm a sex addict.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the traditional 12 steps involves apologizing to everyone
you've ever hurt or offended in any way. Given the apparent scope
of his transgressions, this requirement could interfere with his
presidential duties, since he would have to make amends to everyone
who ever voted for him. As we've seen, apologizing isn't the
president's best trick. In that brief, angry speech, he couldn't
say he was sorry to the other woman, besides his wife and daughter,
who deserved an apology, Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   I feel sorry for Lewinsky, maybe because I remember all too
vividly what it was like to be young and stupid and nuts about a
married man. According to some reports, Lewinsky thought she and
the president had a future together. It's pathetic and all too
plausible. The poor foolish girl. She may be sexually sophisticated
but she is (or she was, at least) emotionally naive.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton marriage may defy analysis, but it's easy to imagine
the whole icky arrangement with Lewinsky. It's as old as time. ``My
wife and I have an understanding. ... We lead very separate lives.
... When you walked through that door I knew it was the real thing.
... You're the woman I should have married. ... No, I don't think
you're fat. ...'' He done her wrong. She has every right to throw a
hussy-fit, as a friend of mine put it. She meant to say
``hissy-fit,'' but her sub-conscious knew better. Usually it does.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
