<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENSION FUND RECOUPS FROM MOVIE DEBACLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We just paid $3.24 to rent a couple of grade-B videos, ``My
Stepmother is an Alien'' and ``Troop Beverly Hills.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, we never feel cheated watching Kim Basinger as an
alien or anything else for that matter, and Shelley Long and her 47
outfits was funny enough as the ditzy Beverly Hills mom. Still,
four hours later we weren't so sure we got a bargain after all,
even at $3.24 for the double feature.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine then if you were the Commonwealth of Massachusetts. The
state's pension fund paid $5 million a decade ago to buy into these
same two movies, and a handful of other bombs.
</P>
<P>
   You can thank state Treasurer Joe Malone, who oversees the
pension fund, and a group of securities lawyers, of all people, for
finally getting the dough back.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, seven years after the state's pension fund and other
investors filed suit, a jury in San Diego came back with a finding
that Bear Stearns &AMP; Co., the Wall Street investment banking house,
knowingly misrepresented critical facts in a junk bond financing it
put together in the late '80s for big-time Hollywood producer Jerry
Weintraub.
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded the state pension fund about $6.5 million,
including interest, says Michelle Blauner, a partner in the Boston
firm of Shapiro Haber &AMP; Urmy, which represented the state. Two San
Diego investors were also awarded $500,000 each, and lawyers say
other investors who invested in the $83 million bond offering will
likely be included in the judgment, pushing the total award as high
as $126 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns' attorney, Peter H. Benzian, said Wednesday the
verdict is ``legally and factually in error,'' and said the
investment firm will pursue all available remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts's misadventure in movie making is a legacy of the
days when former Treasurer Bob Crane oversaw the state's pension
fund.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1987 and Weintraub, whose credits included
``Nashville,'' ``Oh, God,'' ``Diner'' and a string of ``Karate
Kid'' movies, was raising money for his own independent production
company. Bear Stearns and Weintraub were barnstorming the country,
telling their story to institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   When the roadshow pulled into Boston's Le Meridien in the dead
of winter, Paul Quirk, the pension fund's executive director was
there, along with Mary Lou Crane, Crane's oldest daughter and then
head of the state's film bureau. Harvard Management, Massachusetts
Financial and Colonial Management also came to hear Weintraub's
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, everyone passed but the state pension fund. It
should have waited for the video like we did.
</P>
<P>
   Weintraub Entertainment Group made five movies and distributed
two others from 1987 to 1990, when it filed for bankruptcy. Besides
``My Stepmother is an Alien'' and ``Troop Beverly Hills,'' there
were other box-office stinkers like ``Listen to Me'' and ``Fresh
Horses'' before Weintraub ran out of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``By any standard, this was not a successful investment,'' says
Quirk, now a managing director of Triumph Capital, a Boston private
equity firm.
</P>
<P>
   The pension fund collected about $1.3 million in interest
payments before the production company collapsed, but eventually
wrote the investment down to zero, says Scott Henderson, who now
heads the fund.
</P>
<P>
   In their suit, the state pension fund and other investors
charged they had been misled about Weintraub's financing
arrangements with its bank and its distributor, Columbia Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The investors said Bear Stearns had represented that the
distribution agreements would provide 70 percent of the movie
financing up front for the movies while in fact Columbia and the
bank had agreed to provide just 7 percent. Bear Stearns denied the
offering documents were misleading, but the jury sided with the
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Weintraub and two other executives had previously settled with
investors for about $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, Malone has had a good run overseeing the $24
billion pension fund, something he has made a centerpiece of his
uphill campaign for the Republican nomination against Acting
Governor Paul Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he won a tough battle in the Legislature to
consolidate the state's two pension funds into one, saving millions
of dollars in cost. More importantly, investment performance has
turned up significantly.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, when Malone took office, the pension funds were ranked
at or near the bottom in returns compared to their peers. Over the
last five years, the fund ranked in the top 8 percent of similar
funds, according to the Trust Universe Comparison Service, a rating
agency. The fund slipped to the 59th percentile over the last 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   Quirk calls the Weintraub debacle a painful lesson in investing
in the movie business. Our advice to readers: buy ``Troop Beverly
Hills,'' sell ``My Stepmother is an Alien.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
