<SLUG> BC-PHONE-SCAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T WARNS COMPANIES OF LONG-DISTANCE PHONE SCAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service client.s)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Think twice before transferring that call. It
could cost your company hundreds of dollars under a perennial phone
scam.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: outside callers target businesses that have
a public branch exchange, or PBX, which routes all calls made from
company phones through a central switch.
</P>
<P>
   The callers ask to be transferred to a phone line that isn't
part of the PBX system, usually an extension beginning with ``90.''
Dialing ``9'' gets the caller an outside phone line, and the zeros
hook him up to a long-distance operator, which then places the
call.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the call is made from an outside line, the company
is still responsible for the tab.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics aren't available on the amount of money companies
lose annually by helping con artists place long-distance calls.
Nevertheless, it's an ongoing scam in an industry rampant with
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Slamming, in which customers' long-distance carriers are
switched without consent, and cramming, in which phone bills are
filled with excess charges, are the most high-profile offenses
these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's plenty of scams, and they're a dime-a-dozen,'' said
Kathi Oram, an AT&AMP;T Corp. spokeswoman in San Francisco. ``When we
shut one down, people think of something else.''
</P>
<P>
   In the PBX scam, the caller often poses as a phone company
technician, who says he needs to check or repair certain
extensions.
</P>
<P>
   Oram said that although her company hasn't seen an increase in
this scam, talk about it swirled through the Internet earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, she said, ``we were getting a rash of calls.''
</P>
<P>
   To quell inquiries, AT&AMP;T, the nation's largest long-distance
company, posted an explanation of the scam on its Web site during
the spring. AT&AMP;T also recommends:
</P>
<P>
   _ If a worker receives such a call, he or she should ask the
``technician'' for a call-back number or for the name and number of
the caller's supervisor. Then hang up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Company management should alert office staff and tell them not
to blindly transfer calls to unknown extensions.
</P>
<P>
   Oram said AT&AMP;T monitors its customers' phone bills and alerts
them to sudden spikes in long-distance, especially international,
calls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1447EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
