<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN CAN'T STABILIZE RUSSIA IF HE KEEPS SHUFFLING HELPERS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editorial......resending from 8-25)   (This 600-word ``separate buy'' commentary is from the Asahi News
Service.)  
  
 (EDITORS: Get your news from Japan and the Pacific Rim straight
from the source _ the Asahi News Service. Its Monday through Friday
report of news, features and distinctive analysis is culled from
The Asahi Shimbun, Japan's foremost newspaper, renowned for its
integrity and thoroughness (with a daily circulation is 12
million.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By THE ASAHI SHIMBUN EDITORIAL BOARD  
 c.1998 Asahi News Service  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Russia all right? Russian President Boris Yeltsin appointed
Sergei Kiriyenko, 36, as prime minister in March, then replaced him
this week by reappointing his old ally Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that whenever Yeltsin makes a radical change in his
inner circle of government, his ratings tank.
</P>
<P>
   When Russia's economic crisis worsened in March, Yeltsin chose
Kiriyenko, the young banker, as prime minister. But the president
was blamed for the devaluation of the ruble in the aftermath of
stock market price plunges, falling currency exchange rates and a
drop in bond prices.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin was brought back five months after being sacked.
Yeltsin probably could not find anyone else as reliable.
</P>
<P>
   But why was the government changed in the first place? It was no
surprise the Duma, the lower chamber of the Russian Parliament,
advocated Yeltsin's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The Kiriyenko administration had just begun making progress with
collecting taxes _ the biggest challenge the Russian government
faces right now. But his impetuousness stirred discontent among
former colleagues in banking and business.
</P>
<P>
   He had to rely upon short-term government bonds and loans
arranged through the International Monetary Fund to cover the
budget deficit, but that could not be expected to permanently
resolve the fiscal crisis.
</P>
<P>
   As the crisis worsened, in part because of the government's
precarious position on the edge of default and coal miner strikes,
ruble devaluation was forced three days after Yeltsin had ruled it
out.
</P>
<P>
   The result was not only a devaluation of confidence in Yeltsin
but a loss of faith in all of Russian politics as well.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there is no warm welcome for the ousted prime minister.
Chernomyrdin oversaw economic policy until a few months ago, and is
thus responsible for the present economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   His strong point, if indeed he has one, is his link to the
financial oligarchy, based on his former position as head of
Gazprom, the national gas utility monopoly, and association with
the opposition in Parliament and among local and foreign
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Can Chernomyrdin stabilize Russia's politics by using such
assets?
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's appointment of Chernomyrdin to be his political
successor reflects recent developments in Russia's politics and its
economy.
</P>
<P>
   First, Russia's political realignment has begun in earnest in
anticipation of the parliamentary election next year and the
presidential election in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential hopeful Chernomyrdin is leaning toward an alliance
with Aleksandr Lebed, governor of Krasnoyarsk. This is leading to a
three-way political race that involves the Lebed-Chernomyrdin
alliance, a group headed by Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, and a third
group led by Communist Party chief Gennadi Zhuganov. Yeltsin must
back Chernomyrdin to save himself.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Russia needs political stability if it is to obtain an
urgently needed $22.6 billion (3.277 trillion yen) IMF loan.
</P>
<P>
   Third, the opposition parties, especially the Communists, the
largest parliamentary opposition, have become ambiguous. Observers
of Russian politics suggest that the recommendation for Yeltsin's
resignation came because the Communist Party and Chernomyrdin's
supporters have become closer.
</P>
<P>
   Could such cooperation between Chernomyrdin and the Communists
result in greater emphasis on industrial policy?
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin and Chernomyrdin must clearly show where their new
regime is headed. If they become caught up in a power and money
struggle rather than wrestling with revival of the economy of
Russia, further sell-offs are unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin wormed his way out of previous repeated economic crises
by changing his aides. This time, he has even hinted at his
potential successor. If he resorts to the same method over and
over, however, he faces the growing problem of being held
accountable, both at home and abroad, for Russia's mess. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 600-word editorial from the Asahi News Service, it
must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York
Times Syndicate sales representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
