<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5398 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-BONNARD-BOS &LR;      08-27 1660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-BONNARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INTERIOR BONNARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARGO MILLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The French painter Pierre Bonnard thought nature was
a snare and delusion. ``What is beautiful in nature is not always
beautiful in painting,'' he wrote. Also: ``Nature sets traps for us
with her themes.'' He refused to paint from the motif, that is,
from a view or composition of objects either stumbled on or
contrived. He also disliked painting from a posed model. ``Live!''
he commanded an artist's model he'd hired, meaning she should move
freely around the studio as she might around a house.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnard himself was a reclusive man, living a very private life,
most content to be part of the wallpaper. &UR;  &LR; There's the story that
when contemplating his arrival in America he shaved off his
mustache so he wouldn't stand out. He was also the most intimate of
painters. In ``Bonnard,'' the wonderful retrospective at the Museum
of Modern Art through Oct. 13, there must be a dozen paintings of
nudes in bed, in the bedroom, in the bathroom, in the bathtub. The
nudes are mostly his wife, the reclusive Marthe; and Bonnard, also
nude, makes the occasional cameo appearance. This is life, not the
model. And there are scenes of French living at its most felt, at
the dining table.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at these largely empty tables you don't so much see the
food as know that it has lived its natural life and moved into
another sphere: More so than most artists Bonnard painted from
memory. If ``all food and flesh'' is one possible reaction to
Bonnard's subject matter, so is ``What's wrong with this picture?''
a reaction to his odd composition. Bonnard, dismissed by critics at
his death in 1947 in his 80th year for his ``agreeable'' canvases,
makes us uncomfortable the way he gets beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Eugene Frederic Bonnard was born near Paris in 1867, the
son of a civil servant in the French ministry of war. He attended
one of the famous lycees in Paris and might have become a lawyer.
His art training was entirely classical: a brief stretch at the
Ecole des Arts Decoratifs, where he complained he did little but
copy from antique sculpture; then the Academie Julien, where like
other students he painted in a coat and wing collar; and finally,
the Ecole des Beaux-Arts. He did a little plein-air painting
outdoors. He did decorative panels, won a poster competition, and
exhibited at the Salon des Independents in 1891. The year before,
Maurice Denis had defined painting: ``We should remember that a
picture, before it is a battle horse or a naked woman or some sort
of narrative, is basically a flat surface covered with paints put
together in a certain order.'' How people saw was under discussion
by novelists such as Proust, poets such as Mallarme, and essayists
in La Revue Blanche, a journal founded by friends of Bonnard.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to his contemporaries Bonnard wrote very little. His
pocket diary with its daily descriptions of the weather _ ``beau''
when fine, ``nuageux, pluvis,'' when cloudy with rain _ sometimes
erupts with exasperated comment: ``Untruth is cutting out a piece
of nature and copying it.'' But when he talked about painting he
was lucky in the friends who recorded what he had to say. Or who
could describe him working. Bonnard, wrote George Besson, used ``an
indescribably blunt pencil that was so short that a landscape or
nude seemed to spring from the ends of his fingers compressed
around an invisible point.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnard has also been fortunate in his two current curators and
their joint catalog. Sarah Whitfield organized the show seen at
London's Tate Gallery earlier this year and she provides the human
dimension along with much else. She goes beyond the Besson
description to see Bonnard's fingers traveling with the pencil,
``feeling their way across the surface of the paper.'' She adds,
``When painting, he sought a similar intimacy with the canvas,
which led to his unorthodox way of working.'' For his part, John
Elderfield, organizer of the show at MoMA, writes about ways of
seeing over the centuries. Most Bonnard canvases are very easy on
the eye but you'd also have to say they are also very strange.
What's that shape? A dog? More of the radiator? A cafe patron or a
chair? Most of us don't see as Bonnard saw; and he certainly had a
very poor opinion of how anyone but an artist looks at things. And
while we can enjoy a Bonnard canvas for its sheer color, for its
domestic scenes, its interiors and gardens, the lesson Bonnard
would want learned from his show is, we shouldn't take this for
anything more than painting. He liked the observation of his
friend, Stephane Mallarme, whose funeral he attended: ``Painting is
not the thing itself but the effect it produces.''
</P>
<P>
   With a Bonnard, the first thing that hits the eye is color. It
is colors remembered, and, he reasoned, why paint outdoors when he
could bring the effect of sun indoors by painting what a bowl of
oranges does to an interior. In one painting Marthe, a
bobbed-haired flapper in 1925, wears a jazzy striped cardigan that
lights up the whole dining room. In some of the bathroom scenes she
is nude except for mules in green or blue. The bathroom is a paint
box with big glowing tiles behind the tub and bright mosaics on the
floor. The tub is huge and white, a lozenge in shape, and light
glints off the metal pipes. In one picture, a little brown dog
stares evilly from the bath mat. That there's a nude in the tub
seems an afterthought. It's long-legged Marthe, with her jaunty
breasts and snub nose. Her skin is all the colors of fire opals.
This is Marthe-remembered, not Marthe-as-is. Bonnard painted her in
the tub dozens of times and curator Whitfield suggests bathing was
hydrotherapy for her weak chest. ``I have all my subjects to
hand,'' Bonnard once said. ``I go and look at them. I take notes.''
The evidence is all those sketches in his pocket diary. ``Then I go
home. And before I start painting I reflect, I dream.''
</P>
<P>
   It may help to know that Bonnard was tall. You sense he looked
down into a scene. He was also nearsighted. He did not use an easel
but pinned his canvases to the wall. So vigorously did he apply the
brush _ he liked Delacroix's comment ``one never paints violently
enough'' _ that the rough texture of the wall would show up through
the paint, rather as rubbing the face of a coin through tracing
paper produces an image. Bonnard's pictures are about what we see
without really analyzing it. We sense the big rim of the tub. We
infer lunch is over by the odd, empty spaces on the tablecloth. The
plates have been removed, and with them the geometry of the formal
meal, but the fruit bowl stays. The window is open. A garden flames
with color, but a garden that exactly fills the window like a
painted canvas shade.
</P>
<P>
   In dining room scenes Bonnard painted in the mid 1930s, the
casement window is shut and the vertical and horizontal of the
window frame just happen to intersect with the back of a dining
chair to suggest the wooden form of an easel. That would make the
vista a painting. In one version, in the view beyond the window,
clear-eyed curators see a river, and there is some cobalt that
could be a river. There's a centerpiece of fruit and (perhaps) one
table setting with cutlery marching out from the plate. The wine
this day is white, and it has been decanted into a tall-necked
carafe. On the right, along the very side of the picture, is a
figure. In the version shown here and called ``Large Dining Room
Overlooking the Garden'' (1934-5) the woman is Marthe and she's
placing a vase of flowers on the table. In another version, the
woman is Bonnard's white-haired grandmother and her form mimics the
scallop of the curtain fold on the left. The figure is painted the
same orangey red as the wallpaper except for a mottling of yellow
that stands for the blur of movement.
</P>
<P>
   During his student days Bonnard had fallen in with a group of
young painters who called themselves ``Nabis,'' Hebrew for
prophets. They moved freely and democratically between the
decorative arts and the fine arts, and Bonnard with them. They
liked tapestry, murals, painted panels, flat surfaces, shallow or
no prospective; and they admired Gauguin. From the way Cezanne
placed his bathers so naturally in a landscape of water, trees, and
rocks, Bonnard learned how to fit his nudes into a room so they
served almost architecturally ``like a post in the door or as a
door into a wall,'' Whitfield writes. This all comes together in
``Man and Woman'' (1900). It's a very formal picture, with strong
verticals and precise geometries, another of Bonnard's plaid
patterns. A folded green screen with metal hinges runs down the
center serving to zone Bonnard standing on the right from Marthe
sprawled on the left in bed. It is morning, and sunny, a ``beau''
for the pocket diary. Bonnard is dressing; he holds something long
and white, perhaps a shirt or discarded nightshirt, that curves
like his long thigh and leg. Marthe's outstretched hand, or perhaps
her toe, attracts two kittens, one a pouncing tiger and the other
fluffy white with a red bow. The sun gilds her skin. The room is
fat with strewn bed linens, the heavy French drapes and duvets, and
all this white makes an emptiness that both separates and embraces
the couple. Some commentators see the placement of Bonnard and
Marthe as Adam and Eve after the Fall, though Bonnard was not known
for religious subjects, but the hinged-diptych effect does
reinforce that. It's also perfectly possible to see the composition
as a conjugal snapshot, a morning like any other. Bonnard, who
seldom painted himself as a painter, seems to be dressing with
purpose, in a fury to be off. In the hands of other painters, the
distraction of the kittens would be sentimental. Here, they fill
the childless Marthe's morning. It is touching, funny, tender, and
harrowing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
