<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS READY FOR LIMITED ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Barring any unforeseen problems, Patriots
rookie running back Robert Edwards will take the field Saturday
night when the team faces the Philadelphia Eagles. Unfortunately
very little has gone as expected for the first-round draft pick
from the University of Georgia during his short time in the pro
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards's pro career has been similar to his college career in
one aspect _ injuries. A nagging groin injury has limited him to
just a brief appearance in the first exhibition game, which means
it's still not known if he can fill the void created in the
offseason when Curtis Martin left for Bill Parcells's New York
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   And, Edwards's woes have only fueled detractors' claims that he
is injury-prone, and undoubtedly he won't shed that label unless he
goes through a stretch without getting hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already have that label on me of not being durable,'' said
Edwards, who injured his groin at the end of the first week of
training camp, then aggravated it during the first exhibition
against San Francisco Aug. 2. This is the first week he has gone
through a complete practice since then, and Edwards said it reminds
him of his career at Georgia _ when he suffered ankle, leg, and
knee injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of time at Georgia watching my teammates play.
But the good thing about this is that it's during the preseason,''
he said. ``Hopefully I can go out there and contribute to the team.
I went full speed (on Monday). I'm not sore or anything. I think
I'm close to 100 percent if not (100 percent).''
</P>
<P>
   Patriots coach Pete Carroll said the team hastened Edwards's
return, which led to the aggravation of the injury. He said that's
not likely to happen Saturday. He will limit Edwards to 12-14
carries. ``We're trying to get him back into shape,'' Carroll said.
``We'll spot his play so we don't wear him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get him back out there. We thought he was OK. The
problem with new guys is that (when they are injured) you can't
decipher where they are. Robert really wanted to play. He had the
right attitude about it. He came back a little early, but now we
have waited and he should be in pretty good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said he doesn't expect to have any problems with
completing his repetitions or catching passes out of the backfield.
He insists that one of his primary struggles will be shrugging off
questions about his durability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea why people label people like that. You have no
control over getting injured,'' he said. ``A person doesn't go out
and get hurt like that. It's God's will. There is only one way (to
get rid of the label), and that is not to get hurt. Any little
injury that I get, people go back to that label. But it doesn't
bother me. It's just a label. It doesn't hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Edwards's absence has hampered a running game that is
arguably the biggest area of concern on the team. And it has
allowed other running backs a chance to earn playing time and show
some consistency. But Derrick Cullors is the only running back
averaging more than 3 yards a carry (4.1).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I am a rookie and I have to build my character for
this league,'' said Edwards. ``It may be short, it may be long. Who
knows? I might jump right in this weekend and then next game and be
productive and take it from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt his injuries have cost him in the competition
for the starting job, Edwards said, ``I don't think it has been a
competition in whether who is going to start or not. The
competition is we're working to make each other better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
