<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONN FENDLER RECALLS KATAHDIN ORDEAL 59 YEEARS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, Maine _ You might think a 60-year-old memory would have
faded by now.
</P>
<P>
   Donn Fendler is 72 and removed by an entire adult lifetime from
the events of that summer of 1939 _ a 30-year military career,
42-year marriage, four kids, six grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   But the adventure on Maine's Mount Katahdin, which made him one
of the most famous 12-year-olds of his day _ not to mention the
best-known Boy Scout _ just will not go away.
</P>
<P>
   His fans, found from grade school to senior citizen homes, won't
let it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why,'' said Fendler last Monday as he sipped iced
tea on the porch of his summer house on the shore of Lake
Sebastacook. ``Sometimes I wonder why there's so much made about a
dumb kid who got lost in the woods and then was lucky enough to get
found.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fendler's story has been touching generations of kids who
read his book, ``Lost on a Mountain in Maine'' and carry it with
them through their adult lives. It is read by entire school
populations, scout groups, and has become one of the classics of
outdoor lore.
</P>
<P>
   The story line is simple enough. In mid-July, 1939, hiking with
family and friends near the top of mile-high Katahdin in Baxter
State Park, blowing fog separated Fendler from his group. Within
just a few moments he was hopelessly lost.
</P>
<P>
   Nine days later, after most of the army of searchers who had
been scouring the area had given up hope, Fendler emerged from the
woods at a fishing cabin on the Penobscot River where he was taken
in and saved.
</P>
<P>
   As the search wore on, only his father, mother, and few others
kept up the hope that he was alive. Meanwhile, the story had been
playing with increasing urgency in all the papers and over national
radio by reporters such as Walter Winchell and Lowell Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   And to listeners across the country who hung on every progress
report, it was joyous news the morning of July 26 when they heard
that the ``little hero'' had been found _ 20 pounds lighter,
covered with insect bites, shoeless and pantless, missing part of a
toe _ but nonetheless alive and safe at last.
</P>
<P>
   As wonderful as the reunion was with his family and friends,
Fendler never had a clue how big the story was playing, or how big
it would remain to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, it was before the war, and I think things were
pretty quiet. There just wasn't much going on in the country, and
so my story caught people's attention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As he was being canoed home, his mother came out to greet him in
another canoe and the family's touching reunion on the Penobscot
River was widely reported. Back at the summer camp in Grindstone
Maine, life went pretty much back to normal after the round of news
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   But then a few weeks later, he recalls, ``I got back home (Rye,
N.Y) and the barrage began.'' The press again swarmed him for
interviews, and his story was featured in Life, the biggest
national magazine of the day. Requests to come speak at Boy Scout
and church groups was so overhwelming that, ``I'd go and hide. I
just got sick of the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   This round of publicity was capped off when Fendler was summoned
to the White House, where President Franklin Roosevelt presented
him with a medal to honor the young hero for his woodsmanship and
stamina _ ``the stuff of which the early pioneers were made.''
</P>
<P>
   It was all a little embarrassing to Fendler then, as it is
sometimes today. He remembers as an uncomfortable 13-year-old,
``the President took me onto his lap and told me about a time he
was lost in the woods.''
</P>
<P>
   But from that day to this, 59 years after his ordeal on
Katahdin, Fendler's story has curious staying power. When the
state's public school system included his book in its unit on Maine
history, he was again besieged by schools, churches, and even
senior citizen groups to come lecture on his experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Between June and October, when he summers in Newport with wife,
Bree, Fendler makes dozens of speaking appearances, and has to turn
away many more. ``I've had to turn down about 20 this year,'' he
says. ``It's just too much. I'd like to do them all, but I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   In his school appearances, he likes to spend at least two
minutes with every child, personalizing the visit, and getting out
a message a simple and straightforward as the story itself. Through
the long wilderness nights of incessant insect attacks, bear
visitations, and hallucinations, three things sustained him, says
Fendler: ``Boy Scout training, thoughts of my family, and the power
of prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Hunt Trail, a popular five-mile hike to the summit of
Katahdin, is largely unchanged in the six decades since Fendler,
his father, two brothers and two friends, made their ascent. Then,
as now, a summer day at the base of the mountain can turn cold and
hostile 5,000 feet higher out on the exposed, wind-scoured granite
above the timberline.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, in the opening chapter of ``Lost on a Mountain in
Maine,'' ghost-written by Joseph Egan, Fendler recounts: ``The top
of Katahdin was just ahead. We could see it through a break in the
cold, misty clouds that whirled about us ... Those last hundred
yards were heavy ones and, in spite of the stiff, rocky climb, I
was cold and shivery.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, ``with all that big cloud-covered mountain below us and
clouds rolling like smoke around us'' Fendler took off ahead of his
companion at the peak, down to find his father lower on the trail.
Within a dozen yards, as ``an extra heavy cloud rolled in around
us,'' the 12-year-old was separated from his party, and within
minutes was hopelessly lost amid the huge glacial boulders, and
with knowledge that in one direction lay a 500-foot cliff. The
deprivation that was to mark the next nine days of his life began
almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the feeling I was right on the edge of a great cliff.
The way the clouds swirled scared me. The rocks about me looked
more like ghosts than rocks, until I tried to climb over them.
Besides, sleet was beginning to fall. It formed slick, thin ice on
the sleeves of my reefer (jacket) and I had to wipe it off my face
... I was wearing a pair of blue dungarees and I could feel the
water seeping through and getting cold about my legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than returning down along the Hunt Trail, Fendler has
split off to the right on Saddle Trail, a dangerous passage in bad
weather because of its exposure. Along this stretch, a desolate
wasteland of loose sharp rocks, Fendler's sneakers got so badly cut
up they were useless, and he had to spend the rest of his ordeal
barefoot.
</P>
<P>
   He knew, according to Boy Scout training and his father's
guidance, that lost hikers should find a stream. ``Follow a stream
down. It will lead to a larger stream, and there are always camps
along the larger stream.''
</P>
<P>
   In Fendler's case, though, the stream he followed flowed north,
into the interior wilderness of the park behind Kathadin. Although
many searchers were convinced that the boy was lost on Katahdin,
and perhaps had perished by falling into one of its many 30-foot
crevasses, he was actually lost in the forest surrounding the
mountain. Thus, even with bloodhounds, he believes the search
parties never came to within 10 miles of him.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, with so many streams coursing down the montain,
Fendler could not find the exact one he followed, and in fact could
never retrace his route before he reached the East Branch of the
Penobscot River.
</P>
<P>
   One time back with his wife, Fendler recalls he got lost again
looking for signs of his boyhood experience on Katahdin. He found a
ranger and told him where he wanted to go. ``The ranger said, `Oh,
you're the boy who got lost up there, aren't you? And you're still
lost.'''
</P>
<P>
   After finishing high school, Fendler joined the infantry during
World War II, and saw action in the Pacific. He then began college
at University of Maine, joined ROTC and became an officer in the
Special Forces (Green Berets) for the next 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Fender fears that romanticizing the event beyond the facts can
diminish the stark and simple realism of the tale. So he avoids
trying to find parallels between the Katahdin story and his later
military life. ``No, I just became what I became,'' he says, ``but
there are three ways the experience did affect my life, and I
always tell the kids this: First, it increased my faith in God and
prayer. Two, I began to understand what responsibility for my
actions was all about, and third a greater appreciation for my
family. I tell the kids I even learned to appreciate my sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   Fendler does not charge for his speaking appearances, and the
profits from his book _ which has sold in the hundreds of thousands
over the years _ go to charity. Before returning to his winter home
in Tennessee, he will have visited dozens of schools in the state.
``It's a great way to meet people and the kides. I just love it.''
</P>
<P>
   He is looking forward to a visit on Cliff Island off Portland
where the entire school enrollment is seven students. The more
chance, he says, to visit with each one individually. He also hand
writes responses to the hundreds of letters he receives, sometimes
in bundles from schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I could send out form letters,'' he says, ``because I
know all the questions they're going to ask. But I figure that if
they can take he time to write, I can take the time to write
back.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, after almost six decades, Donn Fendler's adventure
story, complete with moose, bears, Indian ghosts and
hallucinations, the chipmunk that became his constant companion,
the bloodsuckers in the stream that attached to him and the
constant torment of mosquitoes and black flies, and final
deliverance in the log cabin across the river with the two canoes
out front _ it all remains Fendler's gift to a state he loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, Maine did so much for me, I don't want to sound
corny, but it's nice to give something back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
