<SLUG> BC-HOME-QUIET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERING CONNECTICUT'S `QUIET CORNER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Conn. _ It's a step back in time. A quieter time, when
America was still a colony and small villages dotted the landscape
of rolling hills and lush valleys. A time when elegant
center-chimney Colonial homes rimmed the village common and white
church spires reached toward clear skies. A time when miles of
stone walls were built to keep cows and horses from straying too
far.
</P>
<P>
   These towns still exist today in what is called the ``Quiet
Corner'' of northeastern Connecticut. Although very much a part of
the 21st century, they remain dressed in the clothes of our rural
and agrarian past.
</P>
<P>
   Meandering through Canterbury, Brooklyn, Pomfret, and Woodstock
is Route 169, a 32-mile stretch of roadway that was designated a
National Scenic Byway by the US Department of Transportation in
1996. There are no fast-food joints along this road, whose
existence can be traced to the 1600s. There are no malls or large
grocery stores. No huge signs advertising cigarettes, cars, or
computers.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of elegant pre-1855 homes, large and unique
barns, acres of cornfields and pastures rimmed by stone walls, and
orchards, old graveyards, and sparkling white churches. There are a
few spots where metal storage buildings impose their ugly square
shapes on their pastoral surroundings, but a blink of the eye will
bring travelers quickly to the next Georgian house or Greek revival
cottage.
</P>
<P>
   Although the beauty of the land and the architecture is enough
for some tourists who are seeking quiet, untraveled byways, the
area has other drawing cards as well. Many of the large homes have
been converted into comfortable bed-and-breakfasts. Other homes and
large barns are now restaurants that rival big-city establishments.
Putnam, a former near-ghost town, has been given a second lease on
life by becoming one of the largest antiques centers in New
England. And other businesses have moved into the area and are
thriving, such as Martha's Herbary and the Sharpe Winery, both in
Pomfret.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby woodlands, rivers, ponds, lakes, and country roads are
perfect for hiking, biking, fishing, camping, canoeing, and golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what attracts people is the rural quality of the
area,'' says Nini Davis, director of the Northeast Connecticut
Visitors District. ``It's a very peaceful and relaxed atmosphere
with no skyscrapers or a lot of traffic. We are between Sturbridge
and Mystic Seaport but we are the real thing _ we are not recreated
here.''
</P>
<P>
   To backtrack a bit. During the American Revolution, there were
no battles in this region, and it became the provision state
providing food and other supplies to Colonial troops. With the
onset of the Industrial Revolution, settlers assembled seasonal
gristmills and sawmills. Then, in the early 1800s, textile mills
were built. The textile owners continued to run family farms of 100
acres or more, and it was these farmers, far more wealthy than
those in Vermont or other parts of Connecticut, who built the large
homes that remain today.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1930s, most of the textile mills have shut their
doors. Dairy farms remain but most farmers have switched to raising
beef cattle and growing fruits, berries, flowers, herbs, and
timber.
</P>
<P>
   Canterbury, the town at the southern end of the scenic highway,
was settled in 1697 and incorporated in 1703. Many large Colonial
homes dot the road, and one notable example of ``Canterbury style''
architecture is the 1805 Prudence Crandall Federal/Georgian house.
Now a museum and historic landmark, it was the first academy to
open for black students in 1833. But headmistress Crandall, her
school, and her students were so harassed by the locals that she
was forced to close the school after only one year.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road is the Friendship Valley Inn, a Georgian-style
house that was a stop on the underground railroad. In the 1830s, it
was owned by Quaker George Benson, who sheltered and supported
Prudence Crandall when the community turned its back on her.
Crandall gave the house its name in appreciation for the kindness
shown her by Benson.
</P>
<P>
   Now a bed-and-breakfast, the inn is owned by former Texans Bev
and Rusty Yates, a former school guidance counselor and architect.
This exquisitely decorated inn has five guest bedrooms with private
baths. The library, dining room, and living room have fireplaces
and breakfast is served in a sunny, glass-enclosed porch.
</P>
<P>
   A half-mile from Friendship is the New England Center for
Contemporary Art. Paintings from around the world are displayed in
a four-story barn and a sculpture garden greets visitors as they
enter the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most charming spot in the area is marked by a carved
sign of a lamb with a golden collar. Take a left at the sign and
follow a long driveway with its corridor of tall oak trees leading
to a renovated barn that houses the award-winn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
