<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5413 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLUMS-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      08-27 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLUMS-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BITTERSWEET SIDE OF LIFE IN 90210 LAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - If you're one of those people who never goes to
foreign films because you don't want to read subtitles, here's an
unusual compromise: an American movie that plays like a great
French or Italian slice-of-life film, but in English.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' is a bittersweet tale about a teenage
girl coming of age under the trying circumstances of a family
falling apart at the seams, held together by gumption alone.
</P>
<P>
   Although this true-to-life movie is being marketed as a comedy,
it's not a laugh riot. The humor is tinged with sadness and
desperation, two of the elements that make you think you're
watching something produced in Europe, where real people and their
lives are more important than gross-out gags.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' is not for everyone
(certainly not for the people who are advertising it), the film
will run deep for the right movie lovers.
</P>
<P>
   It features the most impressive performance so far this year, by
young Natasha Lyonne as a 15-year-old girl who raises herself
because there's no one to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The year is 1976, when Viv (Lyonne); her divorced father, Murray
(Alan Arkin); and her two brothers are the ``nomads of Beverly
Hills.'' They move from one cheap apartment to another because
Murray is always broke, making ends meet only by wheedling money
from his rich brother.
</P>
<P>
   When cousin Rita (Marisa Tomei) comes to live with them, Murray
thinks his problems are solved: his brother will support them and
Rita can provide Viv with a woman's guidance. However, Viv has to
look after Rita while dealing with her budding sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' is obviously a personal movie, the
first film from writer/director Tamara Jenkins. It has to be her
own family story. If you were making up a story like this, you'd
make it funnier, cleaner, less of a mess.
</P>
<P>
   To Jenkins' credit, she makes something special of that mess:
the story of a real girl's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' is smart, sometimes shocking, but its
humor is reality-based. Nothing that happens to Viv and her family
is simply there for laughs. Every laugh is grounded by memory in a
moment of fondness or humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins tells her family story with affection but without
sentimentality. She is aware of her family's foibles and doesn't
pass them off as charming.
</P>
<P>
   The film might have been too painful without outstanding
performances from the entire cast.
</P>
<P>
   Tomei (``Unhook the Stars'') is jittery funny, while Arkin
(``Gattaca``) is appealingly pathetic as a hard-working guy full of
big notions, going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Corrigan (``(uffalo '66``), as Viv's would-be boyfriend,
gives the story tension with a subtly shifting character, so we're
never sure whether he's good for Viv or not.
</P>
<P>
   We want him to be because Lyonne (``Everyone Says I Love You'')
turns Viv into the most appealing teenage girl since Alicia
Silverstone in ``Clueless.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyonne mixes an innocent sexuality with a brassy sensuality to
shape a teenage girl uncomfortable with her maturing body yet
wanting to find out what it's all about. Equally dumbfounded and
precocious, Viv moves resolutely forward because she has nowhere
else to go.
</P>
<P>
   You'll either be totally won over by her or wish the film had
subtitles so you didn't go in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' is rated R for profanity, nudity and
sex. 4 stars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
