<HEADER>
A5415 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUEBECOIS-BEACH-ART-B     08-27 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEBECOIS-BEACH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FRENCH CANADIAN RIVIERA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLD ORCHARD BEACH, Maine _ The Maple Leaf flutters alongside the
Stars and Stripes in the town square. Joseph's By The Sea offers
creton with its breakfast eggs; Munchies serves up poutine. The
laundromat on West Grand Avenue promises an ``agreable lessive.''
Bienvenue Canadiens, the signs say. Ici nous parlons Francais.
</P>
<P>
   For the Quebecois who've been flocking to this seaside resort
town 100 miles north of Boston for nearly a century and a half, Old
Orchard Beach is their Riviera, a surf-sand-sun playground that
speaks their language.
</P>
<P>
   Drive past the motels lining Saco Bay and you'll see
blue-and-white Je me souviens license plates in every parking lot.
Walk down the century-old pier or through the amusement park or
along the endless beach during July and early August and you'll
hear French spoken nearly as often as you will English.
</P>
<P>
   French Canadians come here because it's the nearest ocean beach.
They come here because it's a family resort with everything from
arcades to cotton candy. They come here because their parents and
grandparents came here. They come here in reduced numbers, because
the exchange rate between the Canadian and American dollars has
never been worse.
</P>
<P>
   The battered Canadian dollar has taken an undeniable toll on Old
Orchard Beach's business from up north this summer. Fewer Quebecois
have come, and those who have haven't stayed as long as they
usually do. The French-speaking colony here ebbs and flows with
``la monnaie,'' and this has been an ebb year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more expensive now,'' concedes Michel Lavallee, who has
been coming down from Sorel with his wife Lucy for a dozen years.
``But at the same time, when vacation comes, you go.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the loonie is worth only 66 cents, not even enough
for a ride on the Yo-yo at the Palace Playland, many French
Canadians still would rather drive five hours to come here than 10
hours to Nouveau Brunswick, especially if they're only staying a
few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten hours for three or four days is too much,'' says Helene
Jacques, who makes the annual pilgrimage down from Beauce with
husband Mario, son Keven, and daughter Jo-Annie. ``Five hours for
here is OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Old Orchard is 295 miles from Montreal, 286 from Quebec City,
220 from Sherbrooke. The Quebecois used to make the trip by
horse-drawn carriage, then by train, riding the Grand Trunk
Railroad from Montreal to Portland. Now, they pile the family into
vans and Jeeps and campers before dawn and zip down through Vermont
and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Once here, they can choose among more than 100 family-friendly
motels and apartment and condo complexes, many of them with names
such as Beau Rivage, Alouette, Mount Royal, Kebek, and Normandie.
</P>
<P>
   They can eat in restaurants such as the Bell Buoy that feature
bilingual menus in the windows. (One man's fried clams are another
man's palourdes frites.) They can find creton, the ground pork
spread that Memere used to make, or poutine, the cholesterol
trifecta of French fries covered with cheese and brown gravy. They
can pay in loonies. And they know that even though they're south of
the border, they can speak their language and be understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rare case now where a French Canadian comes here and
can't at least speak enough English to get by,'' says Rudy
Bergeron, whose family runs White Cap Village, a
motel-condo-apartment complex. ``But they like to find someone who
speaks French because it's less embarrassing for them.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lure of the beach &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet while the taste of home is pleasant, the Quebecois don't
make the trip for the poutine. ``Why do they come here?'' says
Genevieve Arguin, who went to college in Sainte-Foy and has a
coveted summer job at the Beau Rivage, which pays in Yankee
dollars. ``The beach.''
</P>
<P>
   The old orchard, which mariners once used as a high-ground
landmark, is long gone, but the beach endures. Seven miles of
smooth beige sand, long and wide and firm enough that people used
to have auto races on it and send post-Lindbergh daredevils winging
across the Atlantic from it.
</P>
<P>
   The beach is the attraction. In 1929, the town fathers finally
gave in to the obvious and changed the name from Old Orchard to Old
Orchard Beach. Whenever the townspeople start talking about
changing the image, making the place less about dodgems and
Hawaiian shaved ice and temporary tattoos, they can't get past the
beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a Kennebunkport, with all the shops,'' says
Bergeron. ``We're not a Freeport, with L.L. Bean. We're still
basically a 12-week summer resort. This has always been a Coney
Island type of a place. The beach doesn't change. It's still
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the great fire of 1907, when virtually everything along
the water was incinerated in four hellish hours, Old Orchard was a
stylish Victorian resort with grand hotels, where gentlemen wore
straw hats and ladies carried parasols.
</P>
<P>
   It was reborn as a ``Playground by the Sea'' with an amusement
park and a pier casino that offered vaudeville and big-band dancing
to Glenn Miller and Guy Lombardo on a waxed maple floor beneath a
crystal mirror ball. After the war, Old Orchard Beach evolved into
a beach town for working-class families, particularly the
Quebecois, who arrived en masse as soon as the Canadian building
industry shut down for the second half of July, turning up before
dawn to claim their rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those two weeks when you walked down the street, all you
heard was French,'' says James Harmon, executive director of the
chamber of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   As late as the '60s, nearly 80 percent of the summer visitors
were Quebecois, most of whom came year after year. ``They would
make their reservations for the next year before they left,''
remembers Bergeron. ``Because they knew this would be their
vacation.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Attracting new visitors &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The days of the mass migration are over. The building industry
no longer closes en bloc. Canadians, like Americans, are spending
less vacation time in more places. And the falling loonie has
belted them in the pocketbook. ``Some of our friends said: Are you
crazy going down there?'' says Mario Jacques, who has come here 15
times with Helene.
</P>
<P>
   As more Quebecois are going elsewhere, Old Orchard Beach has
been broadening its marketing base, reaching down to the Middle
Atlantic states and even across to England and Germany. ``There was
a feeling that we were putting all our eggs in one basket,'' says
Harmon, ``and that we should venture out a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, French Canadians still make up at least a third of the
100,000 summer visitors and nearly half during July. The chamber of
commerce's guide has two pages in French, conjuring up an alluring
vision of hot sand and rolling waves.
</P>
<P>
   The Quebecois are hard-core beachgoers. The men put on their
bikini briefs and the women their stylish maillots and spread their
blankets in the morning. They plunge headlong into the icy surf,
which they consider semitropical compared with Nouveau Brunswick
and Gaspesie. They build elaborate sand castles with moats and
crenelated ramparts. When the sun goes away and the breeze
stiffens, they wrap towels around their shoulders and ride it out.
One does not drive five hours to play skee ball. ``We are here for
la mer,'' says Helene Jacques. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reservation fever &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The phone at the Beau Rivage (Beautiful Seashore) begins ringing
in early spring, when the snow is still on the ground in
Trois-Rivieres and L'Epiphanie and Saint-Ferreol-les-Neiges.
``Reservation fever,'' says Jo-Ann Lapointe, who runs the motel
with husband John. The reservations are shorter now, and iffier,
because of the exchange rate. ``This year I'm getting a lot of:
``two days and we'll see what the weather is,'' John says.
</P>
<P>
   But the Quebecois still came this summer, staying in motels with
kitchenettes, bringing their own groceries and cases of Labatt
bleue and maxing out on the breakfast buffet at Pierre's, where
$4.95 gets you all the scrambled eggs, baked ham, corned beef hash,
home fries, French toast, baked beans, fruit, cereal, doughnuts,
and coffee you can manage. On the way out, the cashier says, ``Vous
avez bien mange?'' assuming the diner speaks French.
</P>
<P>
   The Jacques family (Mario is a Shell truck driver, Helene a
secretary) came down from Beauce for four days at the end of July
and slept four to a room. They made their own breakfast, grabbed
lunch on the pier, cooked their own dinner (spaghetti, fondue,
hamburgers), and wrung every possible ray from the Maine sun. ``We
can do this for $600 Canadian,'' says Mario.
</P>
<P>
   Six hundred loonies may go a lot further in Nouveau Brunswick or
Gaspesie, but the Old Orchard habit dies hard. ``I have been coming
here since I was 3 or 4,'' says Jacques Dubois, who drove down from
Sherbrooke in a Pathfinder with his wife and two daughters and
stayed where they always do, at the Crest Motel on East Grand,
where sandy toes are a few dozen steps away. ``You can say at least
40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, The season is longer for the Quebecois. They book
through August and even on Columbus Day weekend, which dovetails
with their Thanksgiving. That is when the town begins shutting
down, and Old Orchard Beach's hosts can finally think about where
they might travel. ``My wife and I are going to take a vacation in
Canada this fall,'' says Rudy Bergeron. ``You can get a great room
there for $50 now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1455EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
