little momentum they have.
</P>
<P>
   This may well be one of the reasons why Berezovksky has anointed
Chernomyrdin both as the premier and, it is safe to assume, the man
whom he sees as heir to Boris Yelstin's throne.
</P>
<P>
   Czar-making is a role which he has long cultivated. In 1996,
fearful of a Communist victory, he and six other magnates paid $3
million towards the Yeltsin reelection campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He was rewarded with a government job _ deputy secretary of the
Security Council, from which he was later removed. But he fought
his way back.
</P>
<P>
   His success was acknowledged, bitterly, by Russki Telegraf, a
