<HEADER>
A5447 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-DEAFMUTE-$ADV2     08-27 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DEAFMUTE-$ADV29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEAF YOUTH SAYS PROMISES OF BETTER LIFE BACK IN MEXICO
UNFULFILLED
 &HT;    With photos, and copy of letter placed in the International
folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Aug. 29 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ He signed his words furiously, eager to tell his
story and break through the silence that envelopes his life.
</P>
<P>
   Braulio David Infante, a 20-year-old deaf-mute, described
through an interpreter and writing why he left Mexico City and
embarked on a journey that took him secretly into California, New
York, Chicago and the American South.
</P>
<P>
   Joining a circle of deaf-mutes who were exploited by their
Mexican ring leaders, Infante sold key chains on subways and at
shopping malls -- until he was discovered last year and voluntarily
deported from Atlanta back to Mexico in October. Mexican
authorities promised him and the other deaf-mutes a better life
than the one he'd left.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly a year later, Infante said, nothing is better. Before
he left Mexico, he doubted he'd ever have the chance to fulfill his
dream of becoming college-educated. There wasn't even a public high
school for him to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he said, those barriers still exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels as if he were deceived by coming back,'' an
interpreter said, while Infante, reading lips, nodded in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year after Infante and other Mexican deaf-mutes were
discovered in semi-captivity in North Carolina, New York, Chicago
and other U.S. cities, Mexico is still struggling with how to best
serve its deaf and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   For poor families like Infante's, life can be especially harsh.
Mexico has no public high school for the deaf. Although the country
has boosted job-training programs and is attempting to integrate
disabled children into regular schools, it offers few services --
such as sign-language interpreters -- who would make attending
ordinary high school possible.
</P>
<P>
   Infante's family, which lives in a tiny cement-floor apartment
in a tough section of this city, has long believed education is key
to overcoming a life confined to menial, low-paid labor. In the
family's home, a book shelf is lined with encyclopedias and ``how
to'' books that Infante's deaf mother bought for her two deaf sons.
</P>
<P>
   Infante devoured the books, but he was only able to complete the
equivalent of junior high school. When he tried to attend a public
high school teachers offered no help and his family was too poor to
hire a private interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Infante's 13-year-old brother, Jose appears doomed to a limited
education as well, said Tomas Infante, the boys' father. Tomas is
not deaf, but he is hearing-impaired and only makes about $50 every
two weeks as a janitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Braulio is very smart,'' Tomas said. ``He wants to get ahead,
so he doesn't have to do work like me and earn so little.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta lawyer Marshall Cohen, who represented Infante and other
deaf-mutes after they were found in Sanford, N.C., agrees that
Infante is ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   After only a few months in the United States, Infante began to
learn American Sign Language and realized that American deaf people
have more access to higher education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time we met with the Mexican Consulate (in Atlanta) he
would always ask if there was a way he could get into school,''
Cohen said. ``I think he saw his time here as an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen has grown increasingly concerned about Infante, who has
conveyed E-mail messages to him in English about his futile
attempts to pursue an education and obtain a job in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Infante befriended a Spanish-speaking American who is studying
Mexico's sign language, and asked her to translate the E-mail and
letters.
</P>
<P>
   In a March letter to Deaf Friend International in Hamilton,
Ohio, he asked for help finding an American high school for the
deaf, where he could begin studying to become an interpreter of
American and Mexican sign languages.
</P>
<P>
   Without a U.S. visa or financial support, however, Infante would
not be able to study abroad.
</P>
<P>
   While Infante was in Atlanta last fall, Mexico's family
development agency, known by the acronym DIF, had promised to help
the deaf-mutes once they returned voluntarily to Mexico, Cohen
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Infante said he's been turned down for jobs at restaurants
and other workplaces because he is deaf. When he went to the DIF
for help he was treated as if he were mentally impaired, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made him play diagnostic games with shapes and colors,
And he told them, 'I'm not a fool. These are games for children,'''
an interpreter said.
</P>
<P>
   Vice Consul Hugo Juarez of the Mexican Consulate in Atlanta
agreed that Infante is ``exceptional,'' and could do well in higher
education. Many of the Mexican deaf-mutes who were in the United
States were illiterate.
</P>
<P>
   Both Juarez and Cohen thought they would be able to get Infante
into a U.S. school. But his family didn't have money to support
him. And he -- like the other deaf-mutes found in North Carolina --
was not offered a visa to stay in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the case of the deaf-mutes in Atlanta was very
different from those in New York,'' Juarez said.
</P>
<P>
   Out of a large group of abused deaf-mutes in New York, 37 opted
to accept special U.S. residency visas offered by the Immigration
and Naturalization Service in exchange for assisting in the
prosecution of several ring leaders. No such deal was offered to
the deaf-mutes there in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The New York ring leaders have been sentenced to between two and
14 years in prison for smuggling and abusing the deaf-mutes.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, two ring leaders received sentences of
between 41 and 46 months.
</P>
<P>
   Another 17 deaf-mutes who were in New York chose to return to
Mexico in July of this year amid more promises of help from the
Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed by the plight of the deaf-mutes, Mexico has paid
more attention to its disabled over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 11, President Ernesto Zedillo met with activists to talk
about the country's integration program for the disabled. In the
last two years, he said, Mexico has seen a 400 percent increase in
the number of educational support teams for the disabled in regular
schools.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Mexico increased a scholarship program for
training unemployed disabled persons by 36 percent in one year.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Democratic Revolution Party announced on
Aug. 24 that they will consider proposed constitutional amendments
to expand guarantees for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day we have a culture that pays more attention to the
disabled,'' said Ricardo Camacho, DIF's director of rehabilitation,
which is involved in resettling the deaf-mutes.
</P>
<P>
   But he admitted ``there is lots more to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing about Infante's troubles, Camacho said he was
willing to meet with the youth personally to see if he could
qualify for a job-training grant or perhaps even find him an
appropriate school.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that public high schools remain out of reach
for most of the deaf who are poor.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Vice Consul Juarez said, ``It makes us very sad. We
became very fond of the deaf-mutes. We did what we could for them
here. Now, as they say here, the ball is another court.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
