<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5463 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOVERNESS-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      08-27 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVERNESS-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOVERNESS' MORE EYRE THAN POPPINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MELISSA MORRISON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Governess'' cloaks viewers in an aura of Gothic mystery, as
its heroine, Rosina (Minnie Driver of ``Good Will Hunting``),
sweeps through gas-lit 19th-century London, and, later, the eerie
moonscape of Scotland's Isle of Skye.
</P>
<P>
   But the intrigue here is not of the first-wife-in-the-attic
variety. ``The Governess,'' directed and written by Sandra
Goldbacher, explores more human mysteries _ identity and the soul.
The film's dark and lustrous tones, its eroticism, the religious
rituals it observes but doesn't explain, and the occasional
dreamlike camera flourishes make something enthralling of a story
that could have been dryly observed.
</P>
<P>
   Rosina, a young Jewish woman, pretends to be a Christian,
calling herself Mary, to work as a governess to support her family
after her father dies. Charles Cavendish (Tom Wilkinson of ``The
Full Monty``), the head of the Scottish family for whom she works,
shuts himself up for long hours in a mysterious laboratory. A maid
whispers something about experiments in capturing shadows; we soon
discover it's actually rudimentary photography.
</P>
<P>
   Rosina's intellectual curiosity draws her through the
laboratory's doors, and to the side of Cavendish; eventually they
become lovers. The photographs are a way for Rosina to escape the
confines of her circumstances. Photography as an X-ray of the soul
is lyrically presented, one of the ways`` The Governess'' uses the
nuts-and-bolts of life to illuminate its abstractions.
</P>
<P>
   Rosina is a winning heroine, playful and confident, not a demure
gentlewoman in rustling skirts. Mary Poppins she's not. She
initially describes her charge, Clementina, as ``a rodent in lace
petticoats.'' (She is played by Florence Hoath of ``FairyTale: A
True Story,'' another movie in which photography's magical
properties figure.)
</P>
<P>
   The British actress Driver, with her broad face and throaty
voice, is alternately plain and beautiful. Her performance is rich;
her Oscar nomination for ``Good Will Hunting'' was definitely not a
fluke. The role is probably the most formidable display American
audiences have seen of Driver, who also had prominent roles in the
movies ``Grosse Pointe Blank'' and ``Big Night.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it's easy for a film made in the '90s but set in the
past to quickly win over audiences with such a character. All the
heroines of films such as ``Ever After'' and ``Sense and
Sensibility'' have to do is behave in a way considered
``unladylike'' for the setting, but admirable today; that is,
opinionated and passionate, tomboyish and robust. Rosina is thS?Bo
then some, and her complexity is one of the many detailed parts
that make ``The Governess'' such a beautiful whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Governess'' is rated R for nudity, sex and other adult
themes. By the way, it's one of the few films in which there's as
much male nudity as female. 4 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
