A5485 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-TEXANSANDTRUCKS-     08-27 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TEXANSANDTRUCKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW INDIE FILM, TEXANS LITERALLY STAND BY THEIR TRUCK
</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A few years back, an aspiring screenwriter
named Robb Bindler walked out of a Longview, Texas, bar, astonished
to see bright lights blazing at a nearby Nissan dealership _ at 2
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Curious, Bindler walked over to investigate, and found a bunch
of people standing with their hands on a fully loaded $15,000
pickup. They had been there for hours, and the last person to take
his or her hand off the pickup got to take it home. Silly stuff,
Bindler thought, and kinda boring. He watched for a half-hour, then
headed home.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Bindler's late-night adventure has evolved into
one of the best movies to play these parts in 1998. ``Hands on a
Hard Body,'' the first-time filmmaker's movie about the contest, is
a funny, fascinating and ultimately moving documentary about
competition, companionship, endurance and the importance of having
a pickup in Texas. The film opens locally Friday; there will even
be a ``Hands On'' contest beginning at 7 a.m. Friday at one
location, in which 20 people will compete for a $16,000 Nissan
Frontier.
</P>
<P>
   The Jack Long dealership in Longview sponsors a ``Hands On''
contest every year. Thousands of people register. Twenty-four
people are randomly chosen to stand with their hands on the truck,
with a five-minute break every hour and a 15-minute break every six
hours. Crouching and leaning are not allowed; the last one standing
wins. It takes days.
</P>
<P>
   When Bindler, now 28, and a friend returned to the dealership in
1995 with a couple of video cameras and microphones, he wasn't
planning a real movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to write a screenplay that was set in East Texas,
and I was going to use the contest as a vehicle _ no pun intended _
to explore some characters and themes that I had in mind,'' Bindler
says. But what was planned as a research documentary turned out to
be a pretty good story on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got really lucky,'' he says. ``We showed up, and characters
emerged, and themes emerged, and drama and comedy and conflict and
everything just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   When describing ``Hands,'' it's hard not to lose things in
translation. Characters do emerge _ most notably, Benny Perkins, a
former winner cocky enough to believe he can do it again; Norma
Valverde, a deeply religious woman who sings hymns during the
contest to stay awake (she believes victory is ordained by God);
and Kelli Mangrum, who wants to win the truck so she can sell it,
pay bills and quit one of her two jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Bindler concedes that the movie risks condescension, especially
with some unintentionally funny comments the contestants make in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went in thinking that this thing was just a goofy,
ridiculous Texas slice of Americana, yeah, but crazy Americana,''
he says. ``Hopefully, in the process of watching the film, the
audience will go through what we went through on the set, which was
a subtle transformation from laughing at, to laughing with, to a
catharsis, to really caring about the people who are involved in
this event for one reason or another.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting an audience to see it was the hard part. The initial
cost _ $10,000 _ was inexpensive by film standards. But Bindler
needed money to get the movie transferred from video to film and
for multiple prints so that it could play the festival circuit.
That's where actor Matthew McConaughey came in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matthew and I grew up together in Longview,'' Bindler says.
``That's how I know him. I called McConaughey and told him I needed
some money, to write me a check, and he said `How much?' and I told
him, and he wrote me a check, and that was his involvement.''
Bindler is reticent about the film's total cost, and McConaughey
was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hands'' started on the festival circuit in Santa Barbara in
1997, and its reputation began to grow. It won the audience award
at the GenArt Film Festival in New York. The Village Voice gave it
extensive coverage. The Hollywood Reporter featured it in a special
edition on marketing movies.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, ``Hands'' played the Austin Film Festival, where it
was a huge hit and caught filmmaker Richard Linklater's attention.
Linklater brought it back to Austin recently as part of an Austin
Film Society documentary series.
</P>
<P>
   Linklater ``put it to the audience in terms of, `If you like
this film, go out and tell your friends about it, because we have
the responsibility and the opportunity to make this film work, to
get it out there in the nation through wider distribution,' ''
Bindler says. The word got out: The movie has played in Austin for
five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It has even played in Longview, where Bindler grew up hanging
out in a movie theater and watching HBO and Cinemax.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contestants hadn't seen the film, so I was freaking out,''
Bindler says. ``To sit in the theater with them as they watched
themselves was a really powerful experience. It was very
worthwhile; they loved the film.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
