<SLUG> BC-`54` </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`54` SOUND TRACK CRANKS IT UP FOR TRUE DISCO FANS 
</HEADLINE>
 DISCO-CD-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DOUG CARROLL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Good news for unrepentant fans of disco music (all
three of you): ``54'' gets it right.
</P>
<P>
   This is not ``The Last Days of Disco,'' the artsy Whit Stillman
film released earlier this year that buried a solid-gold soundtrack
beneath the whiny self-absorption of Manhattan yuppies.
</P>
<P>
   No, ``54'' has the good sense to crank it up, right from the
start. Thelma Houston's sizzling, Philly-flavored ``Don't Leave Me
This Way'' announces during the opening credits that whatever this
movie's failings, its treatment of the music won't be one of them.
</P>
<P>
   If you were into disco _ really into it, not just trying it on
for size like most people _ then the two-CD soundtrack to ``54'' is
a must for the collection. Check out the thumping bass, blaring
horns and soaring strings that were trademarks of the most reviled
(yet secretly admired) pop music of the last 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the more obscure ``Last Days'' film had a more
commercial soundtrack, with familiar songs such as ``Love Train,``
``Got to Be Real,'' ``Good Times'' and ``More, More, More'' _ hits
from the era that were carried by radio to all corners of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Days'' was full of the mainstream dance music that
brought 15-minute fame to Donna Summer, the Village People, and KC
and the Sunshine Band. It's just too bad Stillman made a film about
talking instead of dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Christopher's high-gloss direction gives ``54'' more of a
disco connoisseur's feel, and the songs complement that. In fact,
Studio 54 was instrumental to the success of recording acts of the
day, most notably Gloria (``I Will Survive'') Gaynor.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to hear ``The Hustle'' one more time? This isn't your
movie. Of the 30 vintage songs on ``54's'' two discs, almost half
never made the ``Billboard'' Top 40. And although three of the
recording acts represented _ Chic, Diana Ross and Rose Royce _ had
No. 1 disco hits, you won't find those hits here. Less-prominent
songs by the three were chosen instead.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Convention's lyrically challenged ``Fly Robin Fly'' and
three other No. 1 hits made the soundtrack, but there are songs by
such virtual unknowns as Brainstorm, GQ, Grace Jones, Sylvester and
Destination.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Starr, whose big hit for Motown was the protest song
``War,'' sings ``Contact,'' a funky tune that never charted. And
the group War, of ``Low Rider'' and ``Cisco Kid'' fame, contributes
``Galaxy,'' also merely a blip on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, then, this is music best appreciated by those who
danced their nights away in urban clubs. For those whose disco
memory begins and ends with the ``Saturday Night Fever''
soundtrack, ``54'' might not hold much interest.``
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, where else will you hear a discofied version
of Gordon Lightfoot's ``If You Could Read My Mind''? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
