<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5502 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-911-TECHNOLOGY-HNS &LR;      08-27 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-911-TECHNOLOGY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELL PHONE INDUSTRY GRAPPLES WITH 911 SERVICE REQUIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Some consumers have been unpleasantly surprised
to discover that dialing 911 from a cellular telephone can mean
getting slower assistance than using a regular phone.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Federal Communications Commission last year
ordered wireless carriers to install emergency 911, or E-911,
location-finding technology by October 2001. The 911 service is
available in nearly every part of the United States to summon
police, fire or emergency medical services.
</P>
<P>
   How to implement this new tracking technology was the subject of
a two-day conference held Wednesday and Thursday in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The conference was attended by about 130 cellular service
providers, location technology companies and public safety experts
from around the country who huddled over the problems they see in
deploying location-tracking systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty-three thousand times a day, a wireless phone is used to
call and summon emergency assistance,'' Thomas Wheeler, president
and chief executive of the Cellular Telephone Industry Association,
said in a videotape played at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the challenge for us is what we can do to raise it to the
next level,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies developing location-finding technology see a golden
opportunity in the FCC's mandate.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Wireless Corp. of San Ramon, Calif., is trying to offer a
solution. It has developed a location-tracking system and has three
trial-test commitments with major carriers in Oakland, the
Baltimore area and Billings, Mont.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Hilsenrath, the chief executive of U.S. Wireless, would
not disclose the names of the carriers for competitive reasons but
said he had high hopes they would sign full agreements for his
company's RadioCamera technology.
</P>
<P>
   RadioCamera is essentially a computer set up in the service
carrier's base station, where all wireless transmission signals are
monitored.
</P>
<P>
   Other technologies also are being considered to solve lapses in
completing 911 calls.
</P>
<P>
   SnapTrack Inc. of San Jose, Calif., has come out with a
satellite-based Global Positioning System technology to pinpoint
emergency calls from cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   Many wireless service providers cited problems in determining
which location-tracking technology would be best for their networks
and customers, and how that technology would be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   Among other issues, the carriers were concerned about
implementing technology that would most likely become obsolete; how
to choose a technology that's compatible with all wireless phones;
and the short- and long-term costs of implementation.
</P>
<P>
   Whether carriers have legal immunity for 911 calls is another
big issue. For example, if someone dies because a service provider
mishandles a 911 call, a carrier may get sued.
</P>
<P>
   This is perhaps the biggest issue facing full deployment of 911
location-tracking technology in California, said Reuven Carlyle, a
vice president at Seattle-based XY Point Corp., a company that
develops tracking technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The carriers' networks are ready to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Fox, chief technology officer of BellSouth's mobile phone
services unit, conceded that ``the E-911 mandate is a stake in the
ground, a call to action,'' but added that the industry still
needed to do a lot of homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know exactly what our customers will want,'' Fox
said. ``We need more industry trials before we're able to move much
further. We have a not picked a direction yet. We have a lot to
learn. The clock is ticking. We'll look back on this seminar in a
few years and see how little we knew.''
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the FCC's mandate, which required service
providers to begin using technology that allows public safety
officials to locate the cell phone antenna receiving the call, was
implemented in April.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase, to be instituted by October 2001, requires
carriers to determine the location of a caller within about 136
yards, two-thirds of the time. Land-line phones already have
location-tracking systems in place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
