<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5505 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-`54`-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      08-27 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`54`-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEREVER ACTION IS, `54' ISN'T 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Dozens of celebrity imitators flit through the strobe
lights of the disco nights of ``54.'' We're meant to think: Hey,
wasn't that somebody?
</P>
<P>
   Just as we're meant to think: Aren't those people having sex in
the corner? Doing drugs over there? Having some kind of thrill that
we're not?
</P>
<P>
   But all the to-do shudders by in inconsequential fashion in
``54,'' leaving us with the feeling: Who cares who they were
supposed to be or what they were doing? The celebrity-fawning is as
pointless and shallow as the movie itself.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the 1970s, ``54'' tells the story of high-priced disco
fever from the point of view of Shane (Ryan Phillippe), a young guy
from Jersey who yearns for the bright lights of the big city.
</P>
<P>
   Shane is pretty enough to attract the eye of Steve Rubell (Mike
Myers), who owns Manhattan's hottest disco, Studio 54, where the
rich, the famous and the abused gather to amuse and debauch
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Steve is a drug maven who wants to throw the world's greatest
party _ every night. He loves the beautiful people, but
particularly pretty boys. He gives Shane a bar job, working
semi-naked, catering to the guests.
</P>
<P>
   Is Shane dazzled by the easy drugs and abundant sex? Would there
be a movie if he wasn't?
</P>
<P>
   Shane wants to make it but also make it real. He wants the sex,
drugs and rock 'n' roll, but also peace, love and understanding.
</P>
<P>
   He's not sure what that means, but it involves the efforts of
the coat girl (Salma Hayek) to become a disco singer and her
husband (Breckin Meyer) to hold onto his wife.
</P>
<P>
   All this is conveyed during endless club scenes with everyone
bopping to the beat. Because the look inside the real Studio 54 is
told by someone who didn't know that much about its inner workings,
the movie has no interesting revelations. We've seen the crowd
scenes before in a dozen other party movies.
</P>
<P>
   Because Shane won't let himself go all the way, the film doesn't
even get deep into debauchery, which is ultimately all it has to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   It's like viewing a Roman orgy with a palace eunuch. That's not
where the action is.
</P>
<P>
   The acting and attitudinal faces of the partygoers save the
movie. Phillippe (``I Know What You Did Last Summer'') is confused
and distraught as an empty head getting by on a pretty face.
</P>
<P>
   Myers (``Austin Powers'') is pathetic in a non-shagadelic way as
the aging groovy guy trying to be the life of the party by owning
the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``54'' is in no way a subtle movie, so the fact that first-time
writer/director Mark Christopher works at a shallow level is
appropriate. But adding an excessive number of corny moments _ with
Myers barfing on a pile of money and a disco granny doing drugs and
talking dirty _ bops right over the top.
</P>
<P>
   If ``54'' had been made 20 years ago, it might have been a
shocker. Now it's almost quaint.
</P>
<P>
   While ``54'' does not cheat the disco music, it's not
top-of-the-chart material, and it doesn't make you want to get up
and boogie. Neither does the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``54'' is rated R for profanity, nudity and sex. 2 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1517EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
