<HEADER>
A5516 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HELP!-Q&AMP;A-RETIREMENT-     08-27 1814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELP!-Q&AMP;A-RETIREMENT-PKG-NYTSF-WORTH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING YOU WANTED TO KNOW ABOUT RETIREMENT BUT WERE AFRAID TO
ASK  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (First of four-part package, `THE NEW RETIREMENT')   (RESENDING from Aug. 19)  
  
 (This user-friendly 1,650-word ``separate buy'' personal-finance
story is from ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must
be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times
sales representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267
or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news, and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By AMY K. BARRETT  
 c.1998 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, considering they invented youth as we know it,
baby boomers are no good at growing old.
</P>
<P>
   But not even boomers can fend off aging forever. The year 2011,
when the leading edge of the boom turns 65, just isn't that far
off, and by 2030, 20 percent of the U.S. population will be 65 or
older, compared with 7.5 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of numbers like those, even the most stubbornly
youthful boomers are starting to face up to the reality of
retirement. And it must be said, they don't like what they see.
</P>
<P>
   While many doubt there will be anything left of Social Security
and Medicare, their savings aren't enough to plug the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that baby boomers overall have not saved enough to
fund their retirements, which could last two decades or more (these
days a 66-year-old is expected to live to the age of 82, according
to the National Center for Health Statistics).
</P>
<P>
   It's a state of affairs that Congress couldn't have imagined in
1935, when it designated 65 as the retirement age. But then, the
average life expectancy was 62 years.
</P>
<P>
   As they contemplate life after 65, many boomers wonder how to
prepare and what kind of world they should prepare for. Worried
questions and fairly reassuring answers follow. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AM I SAVING ENOUGH TO RETIRE AT 65? &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The answer depends in large part on where and how you want to
live. You probably have a pretty good idea of how much you'd need
for your desired lifestyle in the community where you now reside.
That's a good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   Take that figure to one of the many Web sites devoted to
retirement (one of the best is www.quicken.com/retire), and use the
on-screen calculator to figure out how much you must save to attain
that post-retirement income.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a pretty alarming number. You may be able to make it
less alarming by retiring to a lower-cost area.
</P>
<P>
   To compare living costs in different parts of the country (and
the world), use the salary calculator at www.homefair.com. If you
know how much it costs to live well in one city, the calculator
will tell you roughly how much the same kind of life costs in
another.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a generational answer to this question. If you're
one of the 77 million boomers, you probably aren't saving enough.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Association of Retired Persons (AARP),
even the top 10 percent of income earners have an average of only
$66,000 in financial assets _ not exactly a fat retirement cushion.
</P>
<P>
   The successor generation to the boomers, the 44 million members
of Generation X, are far more thrifty as a group. Last year, 45
percent of Charles Schwab's customers aged 35 or younger
contributed to their IRAs, compared with 31 percent of people
between 36 and 45.
</P>
<P>
   The non-thrifty may even help power the stock market. A number
of economists, comparing savings rates and stock markets in
different countries, have concluded that U.S. stocks have done well
precisely because Americans have saved so little.
</P>
<P>
   The lower the savings, the explanation goes, the more investors
will demand the highest possible returns _ which the U.S. stock
market has delivered over the past ten years. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IF THE BOOMERS WISE UP AND START INVESTING FOR RETIREMENT,
WON'T THE MARKET CRASH WHEN THEY TURN 65 AND SELL THEIR STOCKS? &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the financial equivalent of the Cold War worry that the
world could be knocked off its axis if every person in China jumped
off a chair at the same moment. It's also about as likely.
</P>
<P>
   You won't see a sudden, wholesale shift from stocks to
fixed-income securities as retirees liquidate 401(k)s, IRAs, and
pension funds. For one thing, not every boomer will turn 65 in 2011
_ don't forget, the baby-boom generation spans 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as older Americans liquidate their savings, younger
ones will be adding to theirs _ after all, they have their
retirements to consider, too.
</P>
<P>
   A more plausible threat to the stock market would be a sudden
shift to saving by those who are consuming heavily now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since they haven't been saving, they have been spending and
fueling the economy,'' says Maureen Allyn, chief economist of
Scudder Kemper Investments.
</P>
<P>
   If boomers suddenly started allocating more of their income to
investments, they would inevitably spend less on products and
services, hurting the economy and, ultimately, the stock market. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ONCE I HIT RETIREMENT, SHOULD I INVEST PRIMARILY FOR INCOME? &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As people get into retirement, they tend to be more
conservative in their allocations,'' says Bob Rudell, president of
Scudder Kemper Retirement Services. They switch out of stocks and
into bonds, CDs, and other assets designed to provide current
income instead of long-term growth.
</P>
<P>
   But a countertrend is emerging. In 1995, some 21 percent of
households headed by people 75 or older invested in stocks, up from
19 percent in 1992, according to the Federal Reserve Board's
``Survey of Consumer Finances.'' At the same time, the percentage
of households investing in CDs and bonds fell.
</P>
<P>
   In part that's because the stock market's performance over the
past ten years has been too good for anyone to pass up, regardless
of age.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, retirees, especially younger ones, need growth as
much as income. ``In order for them to be able to afford another
20-plus years, they need to have some of their money growing more
than the rate of inflation and taxes,'' says Charles Foster of
Blankinship &AMP; Foster, financial planners in Del Mar, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   To find an appropriate split between growth and income, try this
rule of thumb suggested by Craig Hoogstra, director of mutual funds
and special services at the American Association of Retired
Persons.
</P>
<P>
   Money you will need to get to in the next five years should be
invested in stable securities such as short-term Treasury bills or
bank CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Money you'll need to call upon in five to ten years is a good
candidate for a mix of stocks, bonds, and cash.
</P>
<P>
   Money you won't want to touch for ten years or more belongs in
stocks. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WILL SOCIAL SECURITY BE AROUND WHEN I RETIRE? &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even if you don't buy President Clinton's State of the Union
pledge to save the system, Social Security is a fair bet to survive
in some form.
</P>
<P>
   The current system is pay-as-you-go: Taxes on today's workers
pay for the Treasury bonds whose interest payments fund today's
retirees. That's fine until retirees start to outnumber workers.
Then you're going to have some problems.
</P>
<P>
   How bad are these problems likely to be? The Social Security
Administration itself says the present system can't maintain the
current level of benefits past 2030.
</P>
<P>
   And according to one study, by the year 2045, workers could have
to pay between 17 percent and 22 percent of their wages _ about
three times what they pay now _ to fund the program.
</P>
<P>
   That said, consider the source of some of the most alarming
statements about Social Security. Is it out of pure altruism that
many in the mutual-fund business favor turning Social Security into
a kind of giant 401(k) program?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, much of the hand-wringing over Social Security ignores
political reality. Social Security is probably the most popular
social entitlement program in American history. How likely is it
that Washington will let its funding problems fester until it's too
late?
</P>
<P>
   In the end, just as with the budget deficit, the thrift crisis,
and any number of other incipient fiscal disasters, we will
probably muddle through somehow.
</P>
<P>
   Possible fixes to the present system are an incremental one, in
which the retirement age is raised in stages while benefits are
reduced and payroll taxes increased, and a semi-privatized system
in which some mandatory savings go into designated mutual funds and
others into a stripped-down Social Security program.
</P>
<P>
   But in any case, Social Security is likely to make up a good
deal less of total retirement income than its current average level
of 30 percent. So keep funding your 401(k). &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAN I COUNT ON MEDICARE TO COVER ALL OF MY HEALTH-CARE
EXPENDITURES? &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forget Social Security _ Medicare is the entitlement program to
worry about.
</P>
<P>
   The ballooning number of elderly and the rapid increase in
health-care costs have turned the program into a time bomb.
According to the best available estimates, the Medicare trust fund
that pays for hospital and certain nursing and hospice care will
start running a deficit in 2010.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to avoid that outcome is to radically revamp the
system. It's too early to predict Medicare's fate, but a good guess
is that it will evolve into a kind of mega-HMO.
</P>
<P>
   Right now only about 13 percent of Medicare beneficiaries are
enrolled in managed-care plans, says Lisa Alecxih, vice president
of the Lewin Group, a health-care consulting firm in Fairfax, Va.
That percentage is almost sure to grow.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent budget bill, Congress attempted to spur growth in
managed-care-plan membership by adding coverage of the cost of
eyeglasses, prescription drugs, dental care, and hearing aids. The
trade-off: Most plans limit the doctors and the treatments they
will cover.
</P>
<P>
   That means most Americans will probably need some kind of
supplemental insurance _ but not medigap insurance, which ``is not
the bargain it used to be,'' says the Lewin Group's Lawrence Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   Retirees should consider long-term-care insurance, which will
cover not only a prolonged stay in a nursing home but also other
major expenses (such as some organ transplants) that Medicare
doesn't pick up. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Amy K. Barrett is a financial writer in New York
City.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 1,650-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times
sales representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267
or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
