<HEADLINE>
GET A MOVE ON!: RELOCATE FOR A RICHER RETIREMENT  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Fourth of four-part package, `THE NEW RETIREMENT')   (RESENDING from Aug. 19)  
  
 (This user-friendly 1,250-word ``separate buy'' personal-finance
story is from ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must
be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times
sales representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267
or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS A HELPFUL 325-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 350; TOTAL UNCUT VERSION
IS 1,250 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``a''
domestic/general news, ``f'' financial news and ``l'' lifestyle
news files.)  
  
 By SCOTT BURNS  
 c.1998 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The explosion in self-directed retirement plans has, of
necessity, turned millions of Americans into students of investing.
</P>
<P>
   They read magazines like ``Worth,'' join online affinity groups
like the Motley Fool, and trade tips around the watercooler, all to
squeeze a little more return out of their investments.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with trying to do the best for yourself as
an investor. But two basic choices can have a far more dramatic
effect on your well-being in retirement than any portfolio decision
you're likely to make.
</P>
<P>
   These decisions, which have absolutely nothing to do with
investing and everything to do with personal freedom, can
dramatically reduce the income you need in retirement _ or increase
the income you have.
</P>
<P>
   The two key choices to make in retirement are what kind of house
to live in and where that house is located.
</P>
<P>
   And that doesn't mean trading a four-bedroom country French home
in Greenwich for a rusted-out trailer south of Mazatlan. It means
executing the simple geographic arbitrage that American retirees
have been practicing for decades. You know, swap New York for
Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in geography and shelter are great surrogates for a
lifetime of investing. Consider the 50-ish homeowner, comfortably
installed in a suburb in the Northeast, looking forward to a good
20 years of life after retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming his home costs $25,000 a year to operate, he'll need to
save $500,000 just to run his home in retirement. How long will it
take to save that? If he puts away the current maximum of $10,000 a
year into his 401(k) and it compounds at a 10 percent annual rate,
it will take him nearly 18 years to accumulate $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative, our worried friend can ``save'' that $500,000
without picking a single mutual fund _ indeed, without even
touching his portfolio _ just by moving to Arizona or New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Savings like those point up the limitations of the familiar rule
of thumb that says in retirement you need 70 to 80 percent of your
pre-retirement income. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (325-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to knock the rule, as it's based on some pretty
solid real-world experience. The 70 to 80 percent range comes from
Georgia State University in Atlanta, where researchers have been
working on something called the RETIRE Project since 1988 (RETiree
Income REplacement _ get it?).
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, as in previous years, project leader Bruce Palmer took
multiple income levels and adjusted them for the financial changes
that come with retirement _ retirees no longer pay Social Security
taxes and often pay lower federal, state, and local income taxes,
while their personal savings rate usually drops to near zero.
</P>
<P>
   Then the researchers went through the Bureau of Labor
Statistics' Consumer Expenditure Survey to find changes in spending
that occurred at retirement and that reduced (or increased) needed
income by the amount of those changes.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, a family earning $30,000 a year before retirement
would see its spending rise by $327 a year, while a family earning
$90,000 would see its expenses decline by $5,246.
</P>
<P>
   Once the researchers found how much was needed to maintain a
given standard of living in retirement, they worked backward to
calculate tax liabilities and added the result to the amount of
income that had to be replaced at retirement.
</P>
<P>
   That figure clustered at _ guess what _ around 70 to 80 percent
of pre-retirement income.
</P>
<P>
   The RETIRE Project has compiled similar tables for single-worker
and two-earner families, because marital and earning status have
impacts on taxes and Social Security benefits. But before Social
Security benefits, the calculations regularly show that you need
somewhere between 65 and 85 percent of your pre-retirement income
when you retire.
</P>
<P>
   Except for one thing. All this careful calculation assumes that
after you retire you will make very few changes in how you live.
But if you move, you can come up with a whole new set of figures to
plug into the retirement calculator. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (325-WORD END OF OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let's first look at how trading down in the housing market
affects the need for retirement income. Start with the family home.
At last you own it free and clear. It's worth $400,000 and costs
about $24,000 a year to operate.
</P>
<P>
   If you sell it, free of capital-gains taxes, and buy a smaller
house for $200,000, you'll have shelter that might cost $12,000 a
year to support and $200,000 of cash left to invest.
</P>
<P>
   You could put that money in a drawer and pay your expenses for
16 years. Invest the same $200,000 and it might earn enough to pay
all your shelter bills for the rest of your life.
</P>
<P>
   Now suppose your pre-retirement income was $90,000 and you spent
$24,000 on your $400,000 house. A trade-down could cut your income
needs from $56,064 to $48,446. Part of the savings comes from an
expense reduction of $12,000, part from new investment income of
$12,000, and part from the $3,620 in tax savings.
</P>
<P>
   For that $90,000-a-year household, trading down has more value
($27,620) than the household's Social Security benefit ($21,995).
It also cuts the income required from pensions or savings from 47
percent of pre-retirement income to 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, we can carp at these figures any number of ways. A
move from a high-cost, high-appreciation state like Massachusetts,
New York or California would be a breeze to put into effect, while
a move from a low-cost, low-appreciation state like Texas or
Arizona would be a bit tougher to do.
</P>
<P>
   But for millions of families that have been fortunate in
residential real estate but have done poorly in the private-pension
lottery, the trade-down is likely to be the single best way for
them to improve the quality of their retirement.
</P>
<P>
   A more encompassing version of the same idea is to sell your
working-years home and move to an area with all-around lower costs.
There is even a Web site to help you figure how much you can save.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently used by prospective job changers, the Homefair site
(www.homefair.com) has a salary calculator that will tell you how
much you'll need in one location to match the lifestyle you can buy
with a given income in another location.
</P>
<P>
   Just remember that these figures will only get you in the
ballpark. Homefair cautions site users to do their own tax
calculations. Other decisions you make, from the kind of car you
plan to drive to how you plan to spend your time, will also
influence the amount you'll need.
</P>
<P>
   But even the ballpark figures are pretty darn dramatic. Small
wonder that natives in New Mexico and Colorado complain about
immigrants from California inflating home prices. And small wonder
that the snowbird's path from New York to Florida is so well worn.
</P>
<P>
   A move from Manhattan to Fort Myers will cut your cost of living
by an amazing two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly that Social Security check doesn't look nearly so puny
and impotent.
</P>
<P>
   Note that we're not suggesting that you buy a double-wide
trailer and live downwind of a feed lot in Amarillo. All we're
talking about is downsizing the house or moving to an area of the
country that isn't congested.
</P>
<P>
   It's the one way millions of American have to get rich _ or at
least richer _ quick. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Scott Burns is the
personal-finance columnist for the Dallas Morning News and a
regular columnist for WORTH. His E-mail address is
scott &LR; scottburns.com, and his Web-site address is
www.scottburns.com.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
