<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5578 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENDORSEMENT-CONTROVER     08-27 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENDORSEMENT-CONTROVERSY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM MONICA TO O.J., CELEBRITY ENDORSERS CAN BE RISKY BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily _ the rate is not prohibitive _ contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     (-----Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe
to ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE,'' a complete lifestyle and entertainment
package composed of stories _ with accompanying B&AMP;W and color art _
from numerous publications issued by Fairchild Publications.
INQUIRE ABOUT A FREE 30-DAY TRIAL!-----) 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ERIC WILSON 
 c.1998 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   It's like making a deal with the devil.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, there is no better product placement than having an
``it'' starlet wearing a designer's drop-dead gown. On the other,
what happens when celebrities are caught in compromising positions
while wearing designer labels with which they have no commercial
association?
</P>
<P>
   Slap a logo on anything and find out.
</P>
<P>
   After all, paying Demi and Bruce to star in an ad campaign is
one thing, but who'd have thought Monica Lewinsky would become an
unwitting Donna Karan spokesmodel when she wore a DKNY beret to a
November 1996 photo op with the president?
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Grant shilling for Tommy Hilfiger? In 1995, the actor
donned a Hilfiger cap for the most unglamorous of occasions _ his
arrest for soliciting a prostitute on Sunset Boulevard in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   And what would Coco have thought if she knew socialite Jocelyne
Wildenstein _ whose history of cosmetic surgery borders on the
bizarre _ was the sort of person who would create international
headlines as she battled her ex-husband for custody of, among other
things, a $350,000 Chanel couture dress?
</P>
<P>
   Possibly the world's most notorious unpaid product pitchman
these days is O.J. Simpson, the man who sent sales of white Ford
Broncos soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Single-handedly, Simpson pumped up sales of Aris Isotoner gloves
and established Bruno Magli's brand name in the United States by
denying he wore the company's shoes and calling them ``ugly-ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson, unsolicited, has now taken to wearing a Nike cap to
public appearances. Most notably, he was televised wearing the hat
as he discussed an appeal of the multimillion-dollar civil judgment
against him in the deaths of his former wife, Nicole Brown Simpson,
and her friend Ron Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   Is Nike grateful?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't react in any way,'' said Robert Mitchell, Nike senior
manager of corporate communications. ``The main thing here is that
we did not place that product with him. He just went out and bought
it like anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike's reaction _ distant, indifferent, but not damning _
illustrates how companies view these random product appearances.
Whether they can really damage brand equity is a tricky issue, even
if the consequences are only comical.
</P>
<P>
   There is one school of public relations that maintains ``any
press is good press.'' Even if the product is associated visually
with an infamous person, the thinking goes, its image is still
subliminally ingrained in the consumer consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, image can be everything. Since there are more
and more media covering more famous and more notorious faces, the
number of random associations of designer labels linked to news
images is proportionately on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   While many are absurd and probably have negligible impact on the
label, there are much more serious cases when a product repeatedly
is linked to a negative news story or figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect varies according to the brand and the brand's
personality,'' said Erik Gordon, director of the Center for
Retailing Research at the University of Florida in Gainesville.
``Some brands are so tiny that anywhere they are noticed can have a
deep impact,'' he said. ``But for a more established brand, it's
not so simple because the power of a brand extends from so many
things, especially the effects of association.''
</P>
<P>
   Being linked to the wrong person can be a serious problem for a
brand, he said. And while brand managers can pay to have their
products placed in movies, on television or on celebrities,
``there's no way you can pay to keep the wrong people from wearing
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Brands are pretty fragile,'' Gordon said. ``The way to tank a
brand like Diesel would be to have Bill Clinton or David Brinkley
wear it, because that kills the effectiveness of the image that the
brand is young and hip. It doesn't have to be someone like Mike
Tyson or the obvious shock of seeing a mass murderer wearing your
sweatshirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan got a shock in January when Time magazine ran an
up-close image of Monica Lewinsky wearing a DKNY beret in the
well-worn video clip in which she's embraced by President Clinton.
The hat turned out to be part of a 1992 collection; it sold for
$38.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overwhelmed is the word,'' said Patti Cohen, senior vice
president of public relations, describing her reaction to the
ensuing media requests for information about the hat. ``I got a fax
from the Washington Post asking all these questions about a hat on
the cover of Time,'' she said. ``I couldn't quite get why such a
serious publication would be asking such questions about a hat. I
thought it was an April Fool's Day joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fisher, senior vice president of global communication
at Tommy Hilfiger, said companies naturally want to see their
products shown in the best possible light. But, she said, when
products appear in a negative situation, consumers are smart enough
to realize these images are not a reflection on the brand.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger's label is geared to images of diversity,
multiculturalism and a broad range of ages, which in some ways
buffers the company from the side effects of unexpected
associations. Whether the label appears on a rhythm and blues
singer like Aaliyah or on President Clinton, who was photographed
in China last month wearing a polo shirt with a Hilfiger crest,
Hilfiger sees these as positive images.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Hugh Grant situation, Fisher said, ``I don't think
customers would in any way associate Tommy with, uh, the deed.''
</P>
<P>
   But it also seems an obvious conclusion that in an age when
cultural media often is driven by paid product placements, when
sharp-eyed moviegoers and television watchers have become
accustomed to stop-frame images of Kodak cameras and Calvin
Klein-wardrobed sets, consumers notice when these products appear
in other, unexpected places.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Eric Wilson is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To purchase this special ``one shot'' feature _ the rates are
not prohibitive _ contact one of these New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1537EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0262 </DOCNO>
