<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5588 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERRY-FILMREVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-27 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRY-FILM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A MERRY WAR': LIFE OF PURE POETRY TENDS TO OLD GROW 
</HEADLINE>
 REVIEW-NYT   (Production notes at end)  
 (JT)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c. 1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six decades before poetry slams turned a fragile literary art
form into a gladiatorial sport, wiltingly sensitive versifiers who
would faint if asked to declaim their rhymes on a stage could bask
in the fantasy that publishing a slender volume of their exquisite
insights might one day catapult them into international fame and
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   As T.S. Eliot had proved and W.H. Auden was showing, in the
1930s, poets could be stars. According to the myth of the starving
artist, to be a great poet was to follow a higher calling worth
almost any sacrifice of material comfort.
</P>
<P>
   George Orwell's early satirical novel, ``Keep the Aspidistra
Flying,'' published in 1936, zeroes in on this form of narcissism
with a chortling sarcasm. Its main character, Gordon Comstock, is
an advertising copywriter who in a dizzy fit of self-congratulation
quits his well-paying job after his first book of poetry is
reviewed favorably by The Times of London.
</P>
<P>
   Penniless but intoxicated with his ostentatiously proclaimed
freedom, George wanders around London with a notebook under his arm
trilling verses to himself about the beauty of ``bending poplars''
and other earthshaking matters. Even as his living conditions
deteriorate, George, who subsists on handouts from his sister,
self-righteously imagines that he exists on a higher, purer plane
than the rest of humanity.
</P>
<P>
   When an American publication pays him $50 for a manuscript,
George goes temporarily insane. Having suddenly achieved
international renown in his own mind, he celebrates his new
imagined status as a wealthy famous man of letters by blowing the
money on a colossal bender. At a fancy restaurant to which George
takes his girlfriend and his editor for dinner, George obnoxiously
toasts his arrival into the upper class.
</P>
<P>
   Orwell's novel has been turned into a witty film in which the
quiveringly ectomorphic Richard E. Grant is George and Helena
Bonham Carter his increasingly exasperated fiancee, Rosemary. The
book and movie's central metaphor is the inescapable aspidistra, a
plain, hardy houseplant nicknamed ``the cast-iron plant,'' that
symbolizes the middle-class destiny George can't avoid no matter
how strenuously he tries.
</P>
<P>
   If ``A Merry War'' isn't much more than a charming period piece,
Robert Bierman has directed it with a fine awareness of the story's
satirical nuances. ``A Merry War'' refers, among other things, to
the embattled relationship between George and Rosemary, a sensible
graphic artist at his advertising agency who endures George's abuse
and outrageous self-dramatization with a patient tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, an actor who tends to go haywire when not carefully
directed, makes George at once insufferable and sympathetic. His
performance has just enough comic detachment and charm to keep
George from seeming monstrous. Ms. Bonham Carter's Rosemary (a
rather thankless role) is the embodiment of patient middle-class
stolidity. Sooner or later, she knows, George will come to his
senses. But until he does, she is willing to endure bedbugs, walks
in the rain (when he can't afford the bus after a country outing in
which he's squandered his borrowed funds on expensive wine), and
other indignities.
</P>
<P>
   Several sharply observed minor characters give the movie an
extra bite. George's wealthy editor, Ravelston (Julian Wadham), who
(in a conflict of interest) wrote The Times review, is an
ultrasuave cynic who is rarely seen without a glass of Champagne in
his hand and his beautiful girlfriend, Hermione (Lesley Vickerage),
nearby wheedling him into bed. Although the haughty, impatient
Hermione gives lip service to socialist values, she is utterly
disdainful of any sign of working-class grit.
</P>
<P>
   After George temporarily descends into poverty, he prates
ludicrously about how the poor are so much more honest and ``real''
than the rich because they have nothing to lose. While living in
squalor, he also stops writing. The small hard-headed film reminds
us that poets, like serious artists everywhere, need coddling. And
it doesn't come from the lower class but from above.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   A MERRY WAR
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Robert Bierman; written by Alan Plater, based on the
novel ``Keep the Aspidistra Flying'' by George Orwell; director of
photography, Giles Nuttgens; edited by Bill Wright; production
designer, Sarah Greenwood; produced by Peter Shaw; released by
First Look Pictures. Running time: 101 minutes. This film is not
rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Richard E. Grant (Gordon Comstock), Helena Bonham Carter
(Rosemary), Julian Wadham (Ravelston) and Lesley Vickerage
(Hermoine).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1538EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
