<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BUFFETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUFFETT KEEPS CARNIVAL ROLLING AT GREAT WOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANSFIELD, Mass. _ In Jimmy Buffett's new book, ``A Pirate Looks
at Fifty,'' he states why he thinks his audiences come back year
after year. ``It is the spirit of the Carnival,'' he writes. ``It
knows no rules or geographical boundaries. It is a vaudevillian
slap in the face of the hard realities of day-to-day life.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, prepare to get slapped again.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett is back for three summer-climaxing nights, once again
drawing a total of 60,000 carnival-seekers. And Wednesday night,
Buffett satiated them with more musical theater than ever. He sang
three new songs from his Broadway-hopeful musical, ``Don't Stop the
Carnival,'' while his band dressed in blindingly colorful island
costumes. He even did a skit as the story's central character, a
stressed-out Manhattan public relations man who runs away to the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett has lived a similar escape _ it's the basis of his Midas
touch _ and he's still on the road singing about it. As a
court-jesting tapper of the pleasure principle, he remains without
peer. Wednesday night's show, while slow to ignite, still reached
blastoff, as he and a sea of red-eyed Parrotheads found their
nirvana together.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett started the show slowly, playing a first set that had a
few obscure numbers such as ``The Weather Is Here, I Wish You Were
Beautiful'' and the country-inflected ``Take Another Road.'' It was
daring to sandwich them all in a row, and it didn't quite work.
</P>
<P>
   The set picked up, however, with classics ``Pencil Thin
Moustache'' and ``Come Monday,'' followed by the festive ``Public
Relations'' (from ``Carnival'') and the heat-raising ``Changes in
Latitude, Changes in Attitude,'' ``Cheeseburger in Paradise'' (with
a video of him flipping burgers in a funky Southern restaurant),
and ``Last Mango in Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffett made repeated references to the hurricane working its
way up the coast (``This is the calm before the storm!'' he yelled)
and to the tropical heat (no joke) at Great Woods.
</P>
<P>
   As he does every year, Buffett had some new tricks to go along
with the pan-Caribbean music played by his 10-piece band, led by
keyboardist Mike Utley and steel pan player Robert Greenidge (who,
as members of the side band Club Trini, serenaded fans by the front
entrance before the show). For the top new trick, Buffett showed a
video made that day of him bicycling around Boston Back Bay wearing
a Boston Red Sox cap and looking like a tourist on the loose.
</P>
<P>
   The second set was a winner throughout. It started with an
acoustic mini-set featuring the poetic ``Son of a Son of Sailor''
and ``A Pirate Looks at Forty,'' before a ribald segue from ``Bali
Hai'' (from the musical ``South Pacific'') to ``Why Don't We Get
Drunk,'' with a hula-skirted dancer. ``You won't see this in Disney
World,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   And then he rocked out: ``One Particular Harbor'' to
``Margaritaville'' to ``Southern Cross'' and ``Fins,'' and a
surprise encore of Frankie Ford's ``Sea Cruise.'' The carnival was
nearly complete.
</P>
</TEXT>
