<HEADLINE>
BOY SURVIVES SHARK ATTACK OFF CALIFORNIA COAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A shark attacked a teen-aged boy who was
enjoying one of the last days of summer boogie-boarding with
friends, causing two deep wounds to the youngster's right thy.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kathrein, 16, of San Rafael was hospitalized after the
attack Wednesday, but a spokeswoman for the John Muir Medical
Center in Walnut Creek said the injuries were not considered
life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:30 p.m. Wednesday, Kathrein was on his boogie board in
about 5 feet of water, 50 yards out from Stinson Beach, said
Suzanne Summers, a spokeswoman for the Golden Gate National
Recreation Area, which includes the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Kathrein felt something bump his board and then the shark's jaw
closed around his thigh, pulling him off the board, she said.
</P>
<P>
   His friends heard him scream for help, and by the time they, and
a lifeguard, reached him, he had managed to pull himself back onto
the boogie board and begin paddling for shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw this blood, and then we saw his whole entire leg was
right open,'' said Bradley Carroll, another surfer who witnessed
the attack. ``It was really scary. It could have been me. I was
right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Marge Kathrein, Jonathan's mother, spoke to her son by telephone
shortly after the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very brave, and he said, `I'm OK, mom, but my leg
really hurts,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first shark attack ever documented at Stinson Beach,
although the beach has been closed from time to time because of
shark sightings.
</P>
<P>
   Sharks inhabit the waters all along the California coast,
frequently hunting seals and sea lions, experts say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
