<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV03-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MY BEST FRIEND MOVED AWAY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday Sept. 3)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adam learned to ride his bike by going to Johnny's house.
</P>
<P>
   From our driveway, his father and I would watch his white helmet
bob like a pingpong ball until it drifted over to the Colemans'
doorstep and disappeared inside.
</P>
<P>
   How lucky our 7-year-old was, I thought, to have a best friend
within a baseball's throw of our front porch.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the Coleman family moved into our Plant City (Fla.)
neighborhood four years ago, I had staked out their house. We lived
in a quiet subdivision with several retirees and widows, but few
children. So when I noticed the boys' bicycles leaning against
their garage wall and the in-line skates in the driveway, I was
hoping for an age-compatible playmate for my preschooler.
</P>
<P>
   While riding my bike through the neighborhood one day, I stopped
to introduce myself to Marie, the serene matriarch of the Coleman
clan. As luck would have it, her 3-year-old son was just a few
months older than mine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered if Johnny could come down and play with Adam for a
few hours,'' I said. Despite this being the first time we'd met,
Marie searched my face for a few seconds, then strapped him into
the toddler seat on the back of my bike.
</P>
<P>
   It was the beginning of a fine friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny and Adam progressed from wading pools and Duplos to
diving into the deep end of a neighbor's in-ground pool and
exploring the trails through the scrub pine woods behind our home.
</P>
<P>
   The night before first grade, Adam told his father he had prayed
that both his best friends _ Joshua and Johnny _ would be in his
class. Unsure how to dispel the notion that God arranges elementary
school class rosters, Jim just nodded.
</P>
<P>
   Walking into Mrs. Adam's class that morning, we were floored to
see Johnny and Joshua sitting at their new desks. Adam wasn't
surprised in the least.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were sometimes weeks where tempers flared or
feelings were hurt, Adam and Johnny remained friends throughout the
year.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the teacher became concerned about him at one point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adam seems to have little interest in making new friends,''
she wrote on his progress report. ``He's extremely loyal to the
ones he already has.''
</P>
<P>
   As his parents, though, we were happy with his choice. Johnny
was a polite, bright child who shared many of Adam's interests. And
they were learning diplomacy with each other, becoming less eager
for adult intervention during their bickering.
</P>
<P>
   Many a Saturday afternoon, especially after Adam's little
sister, Sarah, arrived on the scene, I would invite Johnny over or
send Adam to his house, gaining a few hours to play with the baby
or catch up on chores.
</P>
<P>
   So when the decision for our family's move to Atlanta was
reached, Johnny and Adam went through the pangs that are universal
to best friends everywhere: How do we say goodbye?
</P>
<P>
   There was the all-night Nintendo fest/sleepover, the dinner out
at their favorite pizza joint, a trip to Discovery Zone to play
``Men in Black'' laser tag. But the most heart-rending, at least to
their parents, were the letters and gifts that were passed back and
forth the last week: a favorite Gak pack, a note reading ``You will
be my best frend (sic) always,'' a gray-and-blue Orlando Magic
T-shirt, and a computer print-out photo of Johnny and Adam with
their arms slung around each other's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   The day of the move, they played with favorite action figures on
the boxes and ran from room to empty room in our house, trying to
preserve the adventure of the day instead of the inevitable ending.
</P>
<P>
   The final goodbye was brief _ just a quick handshake in the
front yard _ but there were tears over unrelated slights for hours
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   When we called Marie soon after settling into our new home, she
said Johnny's first assignment in second grade was to write about
who he was and what his summer had been like. This is what he
wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Johnny Coleman. I have eight people in my family.
Hockey is my favorite sport. My best friend moved away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
