<HEADER>
A5668 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BOMBING-0828-C     08-27 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BOMBING-0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAEL BOMBING KILLS NONE, BRINGS TERROR SPREE BACK TO ISRAEL
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV A rush-hour bombing Thursday killed no one but injured
18 Israelis, left impressions of nails in metal window panes and
the brought world's latest act of terror to Israel, so often its
target.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the victims of the nail bomb, placed in a large plastic
trash bin on the corner of two four-lane streets, were lightly
injured and had already been released from the hospital by Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   But, windows were shattered up to the third floors of buildings
on both sides of the street, attesting to the deadly potential of
what police said was just a small, possibly one pound, bomb. The
steel post of a nearby pay telephone was punctured and shredded by
shrapnel.
</P>
<P>
   There had been no arrests by Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, visiting victims in a
Tel Aviv hospital, said the bombing appeared to the work of a
Palestinian terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   He said it could not be linked to the spree of bombings lately,
including at a Planet Hollywood in South Africa and the U.S.
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, except that it showed the need to
fight terrorism worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu referred to recent comments by U.S. President Bill
Clinton in vowing an American war against terror, and said that
Israel has been making that effort already. ``That is precisely our
policy,'' Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing came a week after a rabbi was killed in his house in
Hebron, in an area occupied by Israel since the 1967 war, and a
couple weeks after two Jewish settlers were ambushed and killed in
the occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
   However, all indications were that the peace talks between
Israel and the Palestinians over land captured by Israel in the
1967 war would apparently continue, albeit in the same faltering
way they have for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on terrorism lately has centered on threats to
Americans, sounded recently by fundamentalists reportedly connected
to dissident Saudi millionaire Osama bin Laden. For Israelis on the
streets of Tel Aviv, the bombing made a scene that was disturbing
but familiar.
</P>
<P>
   A damaged clock was stopped at 8:39 a.m., the (local) time of
the bombing, in the key shop of 50-year-old Moshe Mendelson, who
had crouched against a wall when he heard the explosion across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   His front window was shattered and his glass counter broken by
debris, but he was uninjured and lucky that a minivan was between
him and the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is we are thinking about it all the time. It is in
our veins,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after the bombing, his shop was open for business.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we have to do. We just have to go on. What they
want to do is interrupt our lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mendelson also wanted the Israeli government to go on with the
peace talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Palestinian President Yasser Arafat condemned the
bombing but Netanyahu said the peace process would progress if
Arafat fought terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Steinberg, professor of political science at Tel Aviv's
Bar Ilan University, said the fact that there were no fatalities in
the bombing would keep it from derailing the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, would account for coverage in the local media
that was subdued compared to two suicide bombings that killed 21
people last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
