<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT-ENDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SOUTH TEXAS, TORRENTIAL RAINS EASE DROUGHT RESTRICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JERRY NEEDHAM  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The silver lining in the recent tropical downpour
in South Texas is that the drought appears to be ending.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in San Antonio and the Edwards Aquifer water
authority that serves the region eased water-use restrictions
Wednesday, although they urged continued conservation measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The authority recognizes that many water suppliers have opted
to remain in conservation mode, and we applaud those efforts,''
said Greg Ellis, the Edwards Aquifer agency's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are reducing the water-use restrictions now, it is
important for citizens to remember that we still have five or six
weeks of potentially hot weather left in our South Texas summer,''
San Antonio City Manager Alex Briseo said. ``With that in mind, we
urge citizens to keep their outdoor water use to a minimum.''
</P>
<P>
   Restrictions under both the aquifer authority's and city's
drought-response plans were triggered at the same time by falling
aquifer levels earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains triggered by a sputtering Tropical Storm Charley
caused severe flooding along the Rio Grande in South Texas and in
Mexico. At least 17 deaths have been blamed on the flooding on both
sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis called the rainfall ``temporary relief.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a region, we need to stay focused on using water
efficiently year-round to help get us through the dry spells,''
Ellis said. ``We need to start thinking about next summer, and the
water we don't use today will help increase aquifer levels next
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The drought-response plans are designed to slow the rate at
which water is withdrawn from the aquifer.
</P>
<P>
   The authority can impose administrative fines of up to $1,000
per day per violation and also file lawsuits to seek civil
penalties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
