<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TEXANS AND TRUCKS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A few years back, an aspiring screenwriter
named Robb Bindler walked out of a Longview bar, astonished to see
bright lights blazing at a nearby Nissan dealership _ at 2 a.m.
Curious, Bindler walked over to investigate, and found a bunch of
people standing with their hands on a fully loaded $15,000 pickup.
They had been there for hours, and the last person to take his or
her hand off the pickup got to take it home. Silly stuff, Bindler
thought, and kinda boring. He watched for a half-hour, then headed
home. Six years later, Bindler's late-night adventure has evolved
into one of the best movies to play these parts in 1998. ``Hands on
a Hard Body,'' the first-time filmmaker's movie about the contest,
is a funny, fascinating and ultimately moving documentary about
competition, companionship, endurance and the importance of having
a pickup in Texas. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   T R A V E L &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GREAT WALL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEIJING _ My visit to Beijing was nearly over. I'd ridden a bike
to Tiananmen Square, where elaborate kites flew under the stern
watch of Chairman Mao. I'd demanded a refund from a Chinese
cabdriver. I'd even taken a bite of a bean curd dish that looked
like a brownie but smelled like a cow patty. I'll bet cow patties
taste better. Big cities can be fun, but I can take only so much of
them. I hadn't seen the countryside, and I still hadn't seen the
Great Wall. By NICHELE HOSKINS. (Accompanied by GREAT WALL-HOW TO.)
Story has moved in ``t'' travel category &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHNSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ They called him Second Place Jesse. His name was Jesse
Stahl, a bronc-bustin' African-American cowboy from California
whose life span straddled the waning years of the past century and
the first third of the current one. Stahl, in the estimation of
some old hands, was the best in his day at the business of riding
uncooperative horses _ even better than the legendary ``Booger
Red'' Privett. But that is a matter of opinion. Suffice it to say
that Second Place Jesse was in the same league with Booger Red. By
CECIL JOHNSON. Story has moved in ``k'' commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F I N A N C I A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
