<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5736 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0828-C     08-27 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PRESSURE MOUNTS ON YELTSIN TO LEAVE AS RUBLE CONTINUES ITS
FREEFALL
 &HT;    With LATAM-ECONOMY-0828.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Russian ruble continued its uncontrolled drop in
value Thursday, a free-fall that sent shock waves through the
world's stock markets and placed increasing pressure on President
Boris Yeltsin to step down.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors swirled throughout Moscow of Yeltsin's imminent
resignation, prompting the Kremlin to issue repeated and firm
denials of what it called ``absolutely groundless, idle
inventions.''
</P>
<P>
   Suffering from a political vacuum and ever-deeper economic
chaos, Russia offered further evidence Thursday that its central
bank has lost its grip on the tattered banking and currency system.
</P>
<P>
   The bank indefinitely suspended exchange-trading of the ruble
after its value slid Thursday nearly 50 percent from where it stood
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The official exchange rate of 7.86 rubles to the U.S. dollar,
like the ruble itself, was rendered meaningless. The value of the
ruble was essentially left to be determined on the streets, where
it was trading as low as 11.5 to the U.S. dollar, compared to 6.2
on Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister-designate Viktor Chernomyrdin, struggling to form
a new government after Yeltsin cleaned house Sunday, said he was
``doing my utmost to avert a disaster for the country and the
people.'' He said he would pursue market reforms while dealing with
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But Alexander Shokhin, the leader of a parliamentary faction
aligned with Chernomyrdin, said the new government may implement
Soviet-style price controls and state ownership of some banks and
companies. It may also eliminate the ruble's status as a
convertible currency and print more money to pump up the economy at
the risk of sparking massive inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Such steps would reverse Russia's evolution to free-market
capitalism since the Soviet Union collapsed seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's economy and the chill it has cast over global markets
will dominate the summit between Yeltsin and President Clinton
scheduled to begin Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's largest creditor, Germany, warned the government
Thursday that it could expect no further aid from the West unless
it pursues meaningful free-market reforms. ``Without he reforms it
will not be possible to mobilize money,'' Chancellor Helmut Kohl
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, dollars were scarce as Russians clamored to trade
their rubles for a safe-haven currency. To protect their assets,
banks have frozen or limited withdrawals, making it difficult for
Russians to retrieve their savings and impossible for some
companies to pay wages or buy imported goods.
</P>
<P>
   While Yeltsin remained in seclusion at his country residence,
Chernomyrdin held consultations with opposition leaders, including
Communist Party head Gennady Zyuganov, increasing speculation that
he will seek to form a coalition-style government.
</P>
<P>
   Zyuganov said the Kremlin was becoming increasingly amenable to
Communist Party demands.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist-dominated Duma, the lower house of parliament, is
to decide Friday when it will schedule debates on the issue of
Chernomyrdin's confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Communists and other opposition parties continued the call for
Yeltsin's resignation. A commission of government officials and
opposition parliament members drafted a broad power-sharing
agreement that would force Yeltsin to give lawmakers more control
over cabinet appointments and government policies.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin angrily denied the speculation about Yeltsin's
resignation, including a CBS News report that Yeltsin had signed an
order providing for his resignation sometime in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Linnik, editor of Pravda newspaper, called the ailing
Yeltsin, 67, ``a president who is ruling in absentia.''
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts said it was doubtful that Yeltsin would resign
before Chernomyrdin wins Duma confirmation as prime minister. It
also seemed unlikely that Yeltsin would leave office before his
scheduled summit with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The United States urged Russia's new government not to abandon
pro-market economic reforms and to move quickly to stabilize its
battered economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it changed course in any kind of fundamental way that would
be a serious concern to us,'' Clinton's National Security Adviser
Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin said Yeltsin would be in his offices there on Friday
where he is scheduled to meet with the visiting Bulgarian
president. Yeltsin also will hold consultations with Chernomyrdin
on the political and economic crisis, and with acting Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov on the upcoming summit with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5740 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATAM-ECONOMY-0828-CO     08-27 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATAM-ECONOMY-0828-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIAN CRISIS HAMMERS AWAY AT MARKETS THROUGHOUT LATIN AMERICA
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0828.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Teetering on the brink of disaster, Russia seems bent on
taking Latin America down with it.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial crisis, along with depressed markets in Asia,
is sending Latin stocks into a tailspin while pushing interest
rates higher to ward off concerns that currency devaluations might
spread.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many analysts have become wary over the future of
Latin America's leading markets, which were among the darlings of
emerging markets only in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say the worst is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia and Asia have sneezed and Latin America may catch
pneumonia,'' said Jerry Haar, a senior research associate at the
University of Miami's North-South Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be rough sledding through 1999,'' he said. ``And
we sure haven't seen the worst of it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, thanks to a flurry of economic reforms across Latin
America in recent years, including the privatization of antiquated
state-run enterprises and the overhaul of banking systems, few
expect a repeat of the recession that swept the region in 1981 on
the heels of a debt crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts still predict a regional growth rate of 2 to 3 percent
this year, compared to 5.2 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot rides on politics and on the performance of Latin
America's own policymakers over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Stock indexes in Mexico and Brazil have fallen to at least
19-month lows this week. Markets also have tumbled in Argentina,
Chile, Colombia, Peru and Venezuela as regional dollar bonds have
plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   Among currencies, the Mexican peso has suffered the most,
falling 21.7 percent this year, to 10.19 American cents.
</P>
<P>
   But in general it's Venezuela that's been hit hardest by the
financial turmoil. There, a drop in oil prices already has had an
impact on a worrisome budget deficit and raised fears of a currency
devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   The Venezuelan stock market has plunged to a 29-month low, while
bonds are trading at levels not seen since the country's banking
crisis in 1995. At the same time, interest rates have skyrocketed
as the government works to raise money to finance its ballooning
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse from an investor's standpoint, a populist
presidential candidate, Hugo Chavez, has made a lot of noise about
not paying the foreign debt and is now favored to win December's
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   In Argentina, President Carlos Menem said Thursday that the
economy will bear up despite market turmoil that has sliced 40
percent off Argentine stock values this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The peso will not move one cent. The banking system is intact
and the stock market is slowly recovering from an imbalance, which
is not ours,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Economists also are watching Brazil, Latin America's largest
economy, where speculators have begun a new assault on the
currency, the real, hoping to force a devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   To fend off these attacks, Brazil's central bank on Monday
unveiled measures to attract dollars and keep foreign reserves at
$70 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil is not doing too bad because it just privatized its
phone company and got more than $14 billion, but where are they
going to get $14 billion next summer?'' Haar asked.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Brazil sold its 19 percent interest in the
state-controlled phone utility Telebras to raise badly needed cash.
</P>
<P>
   October's presidential election has added to a climate of
uncertainty in Brazil and so, if investors were to lose confidence,
a devaluation of the real would be likely.
</P>
<P>
   But President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, who's running for
re-election, said the economy will remain sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the means to react calmly and firmly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
