<HEADER>
A5764 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLES-BUFFALO-ART-3T     08-27 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-BUFFALO-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUFFALO, N.Y.: WHERE A SENSE OF PLACE IS CAST IN STONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Like a dowager in decline, Buffalo still has
good bones to remind people of her more prosperous and glamorous
days.
</P>
<P>
   Drive out Delaware Avenue, one of the fine boulevards radiating
from downtown. They were laid out by Joseph Ellicott, a brother of
Andrew Ellicott, Pierre L'Enfant's chief surveyor in the planning
of Washington. Look at the baronial manors that line it, like the
Williams-Butler Mansion at the corner of North Street. This is an
urban version by Stanford White of the castles his firm turned out
for the Vanderbilts in Newport and the Hudson Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the 19th century, when such houses were built, and early
in the 20th, when architects of genius like Frank Lloyd Wright
worked here, Buffalo was a city of burly self-confidence and
substantial riches, drawn from the great factories and steel mills
on its periphery. Grain elevators towered over its waterfront. An
outpost of the East and a gateway to the West, it was a
transportation hub, profiting from its privileged position at the
point where communication lines from New York City _ the Erie
Canal, which opened in 1825, and later the New York Central
Railroad _ reached the Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   The architect of the monumental Art Deco City Hall, John J.
Wade, said that it ``expresses primarily the masculinity, power and
purposeful energy of an industrial community.'' So it does, with
reliefs of toiling workers above columns resembling gigantic Roman
fasces. It also memorializes, with bronze statues at the facade's
corners, the two presidents who came from Buffalo, Millard Fillmore
and Grover Cleveland. Neither quite made the first team.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Truman said derisively of Fillmore: ``At a time when we
needed a strong man, we got a man who swayed with the slightest
breeze. About all he ever accomplished as president, he sent
Commodore Perry to open up Japan to the West, but that didn't help
much as far as preventing the Civil War was concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Roosevelt, a wholly different character, took the
presidential oath of office in Buffalo at the apogee of the city's
power in 1901, after William McKinley was assassinated while
opening the Pan-American Exposition. Only the Parthenon-like
headquarters of the Buffalo and Erie County Historical Society
remains from the dozens of buildings built for the exposition.
</P>
<P>
   The city has changed swiftly in the last half-century. Most of
the mills have closed; the children and grandchildren of the
blue-collar workers who manned them are mostly white-collar
workers. The State University of New York at Buffalo, with two
campuses, is now the city's largest employer.
</P>
<P>
   With a population of 330,000, Buffalo remains the state's
second-largest city, but it is dwarfed by New York's 7.5 million.
And then there are the jokes about the snow; Buffalonians say
Rochester gets more, many years, but Buffalo gets the jokes, every
year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this remains a tightly knit, family-oriented, heavily Roman
Catholic community, still a rich ethnic stew of Polish-, Irish-,
Italian- and German-Americans. It is fiercely proud of its football
Bills and hockey Sabres,as well as Ani DiFranco, the punky pop
star who runs her own record company here. Buffalo stands apart,
less homogenized than many American cities. It eats hamburgers with
the rest of us, but also Ted's charcoal-grilled hot dogs and
Wardynski's kielbasa, Perry's ice cream and of course Buffalo
chicken wings.
</P>
<P>
   Every block or so has its tavern, with a fish fry on Friday
night, and people tend to identify themselves by their parish. Ask
them where they live, and they answer, St. Monica's, or Holy
Family, or St. Stanislaus.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Russert, a native son and the anchor of ``Meet the Press''
on NBC, is Buffalo's booster in chief. He boasts about the Bills,
when they're winning, about the city's five lovely parks designed
by Frederick Law Olmsted, and about the accomplishments of people
like Peter Crotty, the state and local Democratic leader who helped
make John F. Kennedy president and Robert F. Kennedy a senator.
Crotty lived all his adult life in the same simple South Buffalo
house, a self-taught scholar of Latin who liked to read ``The
Aeneid'' in his basement library.
</P>
<P>
   Culturally, Buffalo owes a huge debt to the discerning eye and
open wallet of a dynamo named Seymour H. Knox, universally known as
Shorty. Thanks largely to him, the Albright-Knox Art Gallery houses
one of the nation's best collections of modern art. It has two
buildings, a Greek revival temple whose design derives from that of
the Erechtheum on the Acropolis, with caryatids carved by no less
than Augustus Saint-Gaudens, and a sleek International Style
addition by Gordon Bunshaft, a Buffalo native famous for Lever
House in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
