</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5769 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLES-BUFFALO-ART-2N     08-27 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-BUFFALO-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUFFALO, N.Y.: in Manhattan.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Albright-Knox's collections date back to the cycladic era,
but it excels in European and American painting of this century.
Mark Rothko and Jackson Pollock are represented among artists from
this side of the Atlantic, along with many others, and from the Old
World, stars like Max Beckmann and Henri Matisse, whose quickly
brushed ``Glimpse of Notre-Dame in the Late Afternoon'' is one of
my favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Other museums can match such canvases, but only Buffalo has a
roomful of the jagged, vividly colored pictures of the reclusive,
inadequately celebrated Clyfford Still, who gave the Albright-Knox
no fewer than 31 works.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities have been missed in Buffalo. It is cut off for the
most part from Lake Erie, by expressways and industrial jungles,
taking far less advantage of the water's scenic and recreational
potential than Chicago, with its parks, piers and beaches along
Lake Michigan. But Buffalo has an even longer history of
architectural distinction than Chicago; you could do worse than
take it as a textbook for a course in modern American buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Hobson Richardson, the great forerunner of the modern
movement, built his first neo-Romanesque building in Buffalo. It is
a vast mental hospital, now called the Buffalo Psychiatric Center,
with a pair of rusticated, chateaulike sandstone towers at its
center. A series of pavilions is linked to them and to one another
by curving passageways that can be sealed off in the event of fire
or other disturbance _ an early example of form following function.
Even in its current shabby state, this is a building of real
magnificence.
</P>
<P>
   Next in the pantheon comes Louis Sullivan, and he is
significantly represented in Buffalo, too. With his partner,
Dankmar Adler, he designed the Guaranty Building, the first
skyscraper entitled, in my view, to be called a masterpiece. With
the Wainwright Building in St. Louis, it is one of only two
surviving Sullivan skyscrapers, and it would have been lost were it
not for the labors of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. Completed in
1896, it is a century old, but it looks as fresh as the day after
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Its frame is steel, but every square inch of the exterior is
covered with Sullivan's foliate ornamentation, executed in ocher
terra-cotta so that the building ``reads'' from a distance as
stone. The filigree reaches a climax at the corners atop the
13-story structure, which is capped with a row of oculi and a flat,
overhanging roof. Inside, much of the vibrant decor has been
preserved _ the intricate metalwork of the elevator cages, door
handles and balusters; the mosaics, the crisp lighting fixtures and
an exquisite stained-glass skylight. How could anyone have thought
of tearing it down?
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan's protege and onetime draftsman, Frank Lloyd Wright,
left the most distinctive architectural mark on this city: five
houses, with a sixth nearby. But his greatest Buffalo project, the
Larkin administration building, a looming, almost unadorned
structure finished in 1906, was demolished only 44 years later. It
had the stark, geometric power of the churches in Santa Fe and
Taos. Today, it is universally considered one of the landmarks in
modern industrial architecture, along with the equally massive AEG
building by Peter Behrens in Berlin. Its soaring atrium, central if
rudimentary air-conditioning system and metal office furniture were
decades ahead of their time.
</P>
<P>
   All of Wright's residential work in the area, which remains
standing, was commissioned by people with a connection to the
Larkin Company, then a flourishing mail-order firm. The William R.
Heath house, built for a Larkin vice president, strikes me as
forbiddingly fortress-like, especially when compared with the Robie
House in Chicago, for which it was a kind of prototype. But no such
criticism can be leveled at the houses clustered in the Parkside
section, near the Buffalo zoo (a rather cramped place, which
nonetheless boasts an animated group of gorillas and spectacular
snow leopards).
</P>
<P>
   The Walter V. Davidson House, commissioned by a junior Larkin
executive, shows what Wright could do on a relatively limited
budget, using stucco instead of brick or stone and clear instead of
stained glass. For the nearby Darwin D. Martin complex, now being
restored after long periods of neglect, the sky was obviously the
financial limit. The main house is a large, splendidly horizontal
affair, with terraces, elongated urns, deeply overhanging roofs and
interior spaces that flow seamlessly into one another; it is much
the best example of the Prairie Style outside the Midwest. A
pergola, now lost, connected it to other buildings, notably a trim
little gardener's cottage and the subtly cruciform George Barton
house, which was built for Darwin Martin's sister and her husband,
who, like Martin, worked for Larkin.
</P>
<P>
   Graycliff, a summer house that sits on a cliff above Lake Erie,
in the town of Derby, south of Buffalo, was yet another Martin
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was also connected, through his marriage to the writer
and philosopher Elbert Hubbard's sister, to Hubbard's Roycroft
community at East Aurora, half an hour east of Buffalo. This was a
semi-Utopian Arts and Crafts colony that for a time rivaled Gustav
Stickley as a producer of furniture, metalwork and other decorative
arts. The handsome Roycroft Inn, built to house visitors to the
community, has been faithfully restored, down to the last carpet
and table lamp, and it is once again operating as a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the buildings that have gone up in Buffalo in the last 75
years, the most influential by far is the Kleinhans Music Hall,
designed by the father-and-son team of Eliel and Eero Saarinen.
</P>
<P>
   It looks back to the elder Saarinen's Romantic Revival buildings
in Finland, like the Helsinki railway station, and, especially in
the airy interior, forward to the younger Saarinen's sweeping
curves in the TWA building at Kennedy Airport in New York City and
the terminal at Dulles Airport in Washington. The acoustics
approach perfection.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Philharmonic Orchestra, the main tenant in the
Kleinhans hall, has been skating along the edge of bankruptcy in
recent years; its players even advertised, a few years back, for
another city to adopt it. That was quite a comedown for an ensemble
whose music directors have included Josef Krips, William Steinberg,
Julius Rudel and the composer Lukas Foss, a champion of innovative
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Theater has done a lot better, and by next spring, residents and
visitors alike will be able to see mega-musicals on a new stage of
Shea's Performing Arts Center, which is built around an ornate old
movie palace. For roughly half the year, Buffalo can also profit
from the excellent George Bernard Shaw Festival at nearby
Niagara-on-the-Lake in Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   This year's edition, running from April 15 to Nov. 1, features
Shaw's ``Major Barbara'' and John Galsworthy's ``Joy.''
</P>
<P>
   The prime attraction for visitors to the Buffalo area is, of
course, Niagara Falls, half an hour north by freeway. The world has
been beating a path to the falls for more than two centuries;
Joseph Bonaparte, Napoleon's nephew, took his bride there in 1803,
establishing a tradition. These days, 10 million visitors a year
come to view the spectacle of billions of gallons of gray-green
water crashing over a precipice that extends for 3,600 feet, in two
parts _ the American Falls on the United States side and the
spectacular Horseshoe Falls on the Canadian side.
</P>
<P>
   Some are impressed, some aren't. Henry James called the falls
``the most beautiful object in the world,'' but Oscar Wilde
dismissed them as ``the second most disappointing experience of
American married life.'' The point is, both made the trip, and so
should you, if you get as close as Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   You can view the cataracts from the Skylon, a tower on the
Canadian side; from the Maid of the Mist, a little boat that bobs
in the spray underneath, and from the Cave of the Winds walk along
the base of the cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   But for my money the best vantage point is Queen Victoria Park,
also on the Canadian side, where you can stroll in bountiful,
immaculately kept gardens directly opposite the falls. They look
close enough to reach out and get your finger wet.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS IN 3rd TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
