<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE'S-BUFFALO-ART-3     08-27 1691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE'S-BUFFALO-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUFFALO, N.Y.: innovative programs.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A BUFFALO VISITOR'S PRIMER
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about visiting Buffalo, N.Y., along with
travel and lodging tips:
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   HYATT REGENCY, 2 Fountain Plaza, Pearl and Huron Streets, (716)
856-1234. In the thick of things downtown, a block or two from
theaters, this is the city's best hotel. It is also a useful piece
of urban recycling, combining a modern glass atrium, something of a
Hyatt hallmark, with a building dating from 1923. Three bars and
two restaurants produce a fair amount of hubbub. Weekend rate: $85
a night, single or double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   ADAM'S MARK, 120 Church St., (716) 845-5100. Until a few months
ago, this was a Hilton; its name and ownership have changed, and it
will get a major face lift starting later this year. With 475 rooms
and suites, it is Buffalo's largest hotel, overlooking the
waterfront at the point where the Niagara River flows into Lake
Erie. Fine health facilities, including six indoor tennis courts.
Weekend rate: $99 a night, based on double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   MARRIOTT, 1340 Millersport Highway, Amherst, (716) 689-6900.
Location, location, location _ in this case a few minutes from the
airport, on the way to Niagara Falls and not too far from downtown
Buffalo. The rooms are cookie-cutter specials, though adequate
enough. Welcome features are a year-round indoor-outdoor pool and a
garden courtyard overflowing with summer bloom. Weekend rate: $109
to $119 a night, based on double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   ANCHOR BAR, 1047 Main St., (716) 886-8920. Frank and Teressa's
Anchor Bar remains unchanged, a dingy neighborhood tavern where
most of the food is eminently forgettable and the chicken wings,
invented here, are immortal. Well, almost. They deep-fry them on
command, a minimum of 10 to an order, which is plenty for a snack
for two. Pay your $5.65 and marvel at the improbably habit-forming
qualities of these chubby chicken chunks nestling in a puddle of
hot sauce, with celery sticks and Roquefort dressing.
</P>
<P>
   ENCHANTE, 16 Allen St., (716) 885-1330. In a bohemian
neighborhood called Allentown, near downtown, Enchante serves a
modest lunch that reminds you why the French still rule the
culinary roost. Alain Jorand's menu and decor are a little faded,
but what counts is what's on the plate. Trained by Gerard Boyer,
the great three-star chef in Champagne, he makes a sinful
vichyssoise, using both the green and white parts of leeks, and
other satisfying dishes.
</P>
<P>
   FRITZ, 6010 Goodrich Road, Clarence Center, (716) 741-5085.
Easily the best restaurant in the area, this is the creation of
Joerg Fritz Goeing, a onetime cruise-ship steward from northern
Germany who met and married, Love Boat style, a young woman from
Buffalo. The setting is cool, blond, clean-cut; the food is
Pacific-influenced. Try the steamed clams with Thai spices or the
tuna California rolls with sesame seeds and a cantaloupe and
cucumber salsa.
</P>
<P>
   HUTCH'S, 1375 Delaware Ave., near Gates Circle, (716) 885-0074.
Every Friday and Saturday night, they run 200 or more people
through this bubbling bistro, with paper table coverings and Thonet
chairs, and everyone eats well. The rib-eye steak rubbed with
garlic, stuffed poblano chiles, dark-hued french fries and tuna are
all exemplary. There is swift service from waiters in long white
aprons, and check the wine prices: 1995 Ridge Zinfandel Pagani
Ranch, $37.
</P>
<P>
   SCHWABL'S, 789 Center Road, West Seneca, (716) 674-9821.
Schwabl's makes one of the great sandwiches in America _ beef
sliced thinly from a steamship round when you order it, piled on a
round roll studded with caraway seeds and pretzel salt, moistened
with natural juices and perked up, if you like, with a smear of
horseradish and a Molson's on draft. They call it beef on weck
(short for ``kuemmelweck''), and it's well worth the drive from
downtown Buffalo, or Toronto, for that matter. The family has been
in the business since 1837.
</P>
<P>
   MING TEH, 126 Niagara Boulevard, Fort Erie, Ontario, (905)
871-7971. Across the Peace Bridge from Buffalo, this Chinese
restaurant serves Beijing, Cantonese and Szechuan dishes. Gaudily
ugly outside, understatedly modern inside, it faces the
swift-flowing Niagara River, where you can watch the speedboats
dart past on summer evenings. Our pickled Szechuan cabbage soup
with pork, tangy steamed vegetarian dumplings and chewy dry-fried
beef strips with ginger and garlic were all subtle and complex.
Sweet but disorganized service. Architecture
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAMS-BUTLER MANSION, Delaware Avenue and North Street.
Several times a year the garden is open to the public for charity
and community events. It is the mansion's centennial. Designed by
Stanford White.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO CITY HALL, 65 Niagara Square, (716) 851-4200. Tours can
be set up through the superintendent's office, (716) 851-5991, 8
a.m. to 4:30 p.m., Mondays through Fridays. There is an observation
deck that is not accessible to the handicapped. Designed by John J.
Wade.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO PSYCHIATRIC CENTER, 400 Forest Ave., (716) 885-2261.
Designed by Henry Hobson Richardson. Once a month during the
summer, the Preservation Coalition of Erie County conducts tours.
It is a National Historic Landmark. The grounds were designed by
Frederick Law Olmsted.
</P>
<P>
   GUARANTY BUILDING, 28 Church St., (716) 854-0003. Designed by
Louis Sullivan and Dankmar Adler. Open Mondays through Fridays, 8
a.m. to 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAM R. HEATH HOUSE, 76 Soldier's Place. A private residence,
designed by Frank Lloyd Wright.
</P>
<P>
   WALTER V. DAVIDSON HOUSE, 57 Tillinghast Place. A private
residence, designed by Frank Lloyd Wright.
</P>
<P>
   DARWIN D. MARTIN COMPLEX, 125 Jewett Parkway and 118 Summit
Avenue, (716) 856-3858. Designed by Frank Lloyd Wright.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINHANS MUSIC HALL, 370 Pennsylvania Ave., North Street at
Richmond Avenue, (716) 885-5000. Designed by Eliel and Eero
Saarinen. From Sept. 19 to June 5, 1999, the Buffalo Philharmonic
Orchestra will perform at the hall two or three times a week. Doc
Severinsen will be the guest conductor on Sept. 25 and 26. Other
guest appearances with the orchestra include Johnny Mathis on Oct.
16 and 17. For concerts by guest artists, tickets are obtained
through Ticketmaster (716) 852-5000. Tickets: $21 to $45.
</P>
<P>
   GRAYCLIFF, 6472 Old Lake Shore Road, Derby, N.Y., (716)
838-0536. A summer house designed by Wright for Darwin Martin.
Tours are offered Saturdays from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. and Sundays 2 to
4 p.m. by reservation, or at the door if space is available.
Information: (716) 947-4590. The one-hour tour includes the house
and grounds and is open to children 10 and older. Admission: $10.
An exhibition of historic photographs is on display.
</P>
<P>
   ROYCROFT INN, 40 South Grove St., East Aurora, N.Y., (716)
652-5552. A bed-and-breakfast inn designed by Elbert Hubbard in the
late 1800s. Three-, four- and five-room suites, ranging from $120
to $210 a night. There is also a restaurant but no room service.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT-KNOX ART GALLERY, 1285 Elmwood Ave., (716) 882-8700.
Currently under renovation, it is scheduled to reopen in early
October with half of the permanent collection on view. Tuesdays
through Saturdays, 11 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, noon to 5 p.m. Half
admission until spring, when the renovation is to be finished.
Tickets: $2; 12 and under free.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO ZOO, 300 Parkside Ave., (716) 837-3900. Through Sept.
30, Mondays through Fridays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Saturdays and
Sundays to 5:30 p.m. Beginning Oct. 1, weekday 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.;
Saturdays and Sundays to 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO AND ERIE COUNTY HISTORICAL SOCIETY, 25 Nottingham Court,
at Elmwood Avenue, (716) 873-9644. The exhibition ``The Buffalo
Past and Present Photo Show'' is on view through September.
Tuesdays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, noon to 5
p.m. Admission, $3.50; $2 for the elderly; $1.50 for children 7 to
15 years old; free for children under 7.
</P>
<P>
   SHEA'S PERFORMING ARTS CENTER, 646 Main St., (716) 847-0850.
Closed for renovation through May 5, 1999, when it will reopen with
``Phantom of the Opera.'' On Oct. 13-18, the center will present
``Riverdance'' at an alternate space, the University of Buffalo
Center for the Performing Arts in Amherst. Tickets: (716)
852-5000..
</P>
<P>
   SHAW FESTIVAL, Queen Street, Niagara-on-the-Lake, Ontario, (800)
511-7429. Season runs from April through November. This weekend,
the productions are ``Waterloo'' by Conan Doyle (today at noon);
Shaw's ``Major Barbara'' (Friday, Saturday and Sunday at 2 p.m.);
``The Shop at Sly Corner'' by Edward Percy (today at 2 p.m.,
Saturday and Sunday at 8 p.m.); ``Joy'' by John Galsworthy
(Saturday at 2 p.m.); Shaw's ``John Bull's Other Island'' (Saturday
and Sunday at 8 p.m.); Shaw's ``Lady's Not for Burning'' (Friday
night and Saturday night at 8; Sunday at 2 p.m.); Kaufman and
Hart's ``You Can't Take It With You'' (Friday night at and Saturday
at 2 p.m.); Oscar Wilde's ``Lady Windemere's Fan'' (Saturday night
and Sunday night at 8); ``Foggy Day'' by George and Ira Gershwin
(Friday night at 8 and Sunday at 2 p.m.); Shaw's ``Passion, Poison
and Petrifaction'' (Saturday and Sunday at noon). Tickets: $15 to
$65 in Canadian dollars (about 40 percent less in American
dollars).
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   CONTINENTAL AIRLINES has a direct flight to Buffalo from Newark,
N.J. The 14-day advance ticket is $214. Last-minute fares are $189
each way. On some flights there are some last-minute one-way way
fares available for $79 and $159. Information: (800) 525-0280.
</P>
<P>
   US AIRWAYS has a direct flight from New York City's La Guardia.
The 21-day advance ticket, with an overnight stay on Saturday, is
$160 round trip. There is a special $120 round-trip rate, available
with three days' notice, that requires a Saturday departure and a
return Monday or Tuesday. The last-minute rate for a weekday
departure is $400 round trip; it is $200 for weekend departure.
Information: (800) 428-4322.
</P>
<P>
   _ R.W. APPLE Jr.
</P>
