<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-FILMS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREVIEW OF UPCOMING FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, the traditionalists tell us, the time of frivolity and
carefree film-going comes to an end as summer ebbs, and serious
viewing begins as the days grow shorter. Yeah, which is why there
are two cartoons this fall about ants and one about a guy who dies,
comes back as a snowman and learns what it means to be a real
father. That one must be based on the Jane Austen novel.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, the final release dates of the films
previewed are not yet firmly set.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 4: ``The Chambermaid.'' A Spanish working man finds a
career on stage spinning melodramatic, romantic fantasies about a
chambermaid he met the night before she sailed on the Titanic.
Directed by Bigas Luna. Samuel Goldwyn.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 11: ``Simon Birch.'' Inspired by the John Irving novel,
``A Prayer for Owen Meany,'' the film tells the story of a young
man named Simon (Ian Smith) who is born tiny and stays that way.
Naturally, he believes that God made him small for a reason and
aims to find out what that reason is. His only friend, Joe (Joseph
Mazzello), is on a quest of his own _ when his mother was killed in
an accident, the secret of his father's identity died with her.
Ashley Judd and Oliver Platt co-star. Mark Steven Johnson wrote and
directed. Touchstone.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 18: ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries.'' Based on a
memoir by Kaylie Jones, the daughter of writer James Jones (``From
Here to Eternity''), this is the story of an American family living
in Paris in the '60s. The father (Kris Kristofferson) is a novelist
and World War II veteran haunted by his war experiences. Barbara
Hershey co-stars. James Ivory directs his and Ruth Prawer
Jhabvala's script. October Films.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 18: ``Rush Hour.'' Jackie Chan plays a detective from Hong
Kong who teams up with Los Angeles police officer Chris Tucker to
solve a kidnapping and avert international catastrophe. Brett
Ratner (``Money Talks'') directs. Fine Line.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 25: ``Pecker.'' Director John Waters sends up the New York
art photography world in this story of an 18-year-old named Pecker
who works in a Baltimore sandwich shop and takes pictures of his
peculiar family, a hobby that casts the fellow into unexpected
celebrity status. Edward Furlong, Martha Plimpton, Christina Ricci
and Brendan Sexton II star. Fine Line.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 25: ``Ronin.'' Robert De Niro leads the cast in this story
about former intelligence agents and Cold Warriors who meet in a
warehouse to begin an adventure that involves recovering a
mysterious briefcase for an unknown employer. Friendship, betrayal
and love ensue, as they must in every tale of international
intrigue. Stellan Skarsgard, Jean Reno, Natascha McElhone and
Jonathan Pryce join in the fun, directed by John Frankenheimer.
United Artists.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 2: ``Antz.'' The voices of Woody Allen, Sharon Stone, Brad
Pitt, Sylvester Stallone and Anne Bancroft star in this
computer-generated animation comedy about a drone ant (Allen)
toiling in a colony in Central Park who yearns for the queen's
beautiful daughter (Stone) but gets nowhere with her until a twist
of fate turns him into an unlikely hero. Paul and Chris Weitz wrote
the script. Eric Darnell and Tim Johnson directed. Dream Works SKG.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 9: ``Holy Man.'' Eddie Murphy plays a television evangelist
trying to prove that shopping by TV can be a religious experience.
Jeff Goldblum, Kelly Preston and Robert Loggia co-star and Stephen
Herek directs. Tom Schulman (``Dead Poets Society'') wrote the
script. Touchstone.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 16: ``Pleasantville.'' Oscar-nominated screenwriter Gary
Ross (``Big,'' ``Dave'') wrote and directed this fairy tale about
two teen-agers who enter a black-and-white 1950s television
program. Soon, they turn the TV denizens to color. Joan Allen,
William H. Macy, Jeff Daniels, Tobey Maguire, Reese Witherspoon and
J.T. Walsh star. Fine Line.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 16: ``American History X.'' A family is torn apart by hate
and prejudice in Tony Kaye's exploration of one man's struggle to
reform himself and save his brother. Edward Norton, Edward Furlong
and Fairuza Balk star. Fine Line.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 16: ``Beloved.'' Nobel Prize laureate Toni Morrison's novel
is set in Ohio after the Civil War and follows a woman (played by
Oprah Winfrey) who escaped slavery but is haunted by its aftermath.
Danny Glover, Thandie Newton and Kimberly Elise co-star. Jonathan
Demme directs the script by Akosua Busia, Richard LaGravanese and
Adam Brooks. Touchstone.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 16: ``The Impostors.'' Stanley Tucci stars in and directs
this comedy about two down-and-out Depression-era actors who are
looking for the perfect roles. Tucci is Arthur, thin and verbose,
who hopes to perform a great death scene, and Oliver Platt is
Maurice, impulsive and excessive, and devoted to Arthur. The cast
includes Campbell Scott, Isabella Rossellini and Tony Shalhoub. Fox
Searchlight.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 23: ``Living Out Loud.'' Holly Hunter and Danny DeVito star
in this story of an elevator operator who falls in love with a
divorcee. Queen Latifah co-stars. Richard Gravenese, who wrote
``The Fisher King'' and ``The Bridges of Madison County,'' wrote
and directed. Fine Line.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 6: ``The Mighty.'' Maxwell is a slow-witted giant
13-year-old boy who befriends Kevin, a tiny Einstein in leg braces.
The two outcasts form a friendship that gets them through rough
times. A lofty cast populates this feature by director Peter
Chelsom (``Funny Bones''): Gena Rowlands, Harry Dean Stanton,
Sharon Stone, Gillian Anderson and James Gandolfini. Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 6: ``Elizabeth.'' Cate Blanchett (``Oscar and Lucinda'') is
Elizabeth I, the daughter of Henry VIII and Anne Boleyn, who was
imprisoned by her half-sister Mary when she was 16, but who rose to
be crowned queen seven years later. The cast includes Geoffrey
Rush, Christopher Eccleston and Fanny Ardant. Shekhar Kapur
directed. Gramercy Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 6: ``Jack Frost.'' Michael Keaton plays the title figure, a
musician about to make it big, but whose career has taken him away
from his wife (Kelly Preston) and son (Joseph Cross). After dying
in an accident, he returns to be a real father to his son in the
form of a snowman. Troy Miller directs. Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 13: ``Velvet Goldmine.'' Todd Haynes, director of ``Safe''
and ``Poison,'' comes up with this story set against the glitter of
the '70s rock scene in London. When a rock star is shot on stage
during a performance the question is: Was it murder or a publicity
stunt? Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 20: ``A Bug's Life.'' The voices of Phyllis Diller,
Jonathan Harris, Madeline Kahn, Kevin Spacey, Roddy McDowall, Julia
Louis-Dreyfus and Michael McShane enliven this Disney-Pixar
animated feature about a misfit on an ant farm named Flik who tries
to save his colony from a greedy gang of grasshoppers and their
evil leader Hopper. John Lasseter (``Toy Story'') and Andrew
Stanton direct. Haven't they heard of ``Antz''? Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 20: ``At First Sight.'' A New York architect (Mira Sorvino)
falls in love with a blind masseur (Val Kilmer) and convinces him
to undergo experimental surgery to restore his sight. But there's a
price to pay for the gift, which is explored in this love story
based on a true story by Oliver Sacks (``Awakenings''). Irwin
Winkler directs. MGM.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 25: ``Babe: Pig in the City.'' The pig returns in this
sequel to the Oscar-winning hit. This time, Babe travels to a
storybook city where he encounters an assortment of animal friends
and learns how a kind and steady heart can heal a sorry world.
James Cromwell and Magda Szubanski (the farmer and his wife) return
and are joined by Mickey Rooney. George Miller, who produced the
first film, directs this one. Universal.
</P>
<P>
   Also scheduled for release in November:
</P>
<P>
   ``Condo Painting.'' Director John McNaughton looks at the life
and mind of New York painter George Condo, as well as the
relationship between high art and pop culture in the late 20th
century. William S. Burroughs and Allen Ginsberg appear in
interviews. October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slam.'' This won the 1998 Sundance Film Festival Grand Jury
Prize. Saul Williams plays a rapper-poet in Washington, D.C., who
is arrested on a drug charge and is swallowed up by the capitals'
criminal justice system. In prison he meets a beautiful writing
teacher (Sonja Sohn), who recognizes his talent and inspires him.
Marc Levin wrote and directed. Trimark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
