<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5821 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HYDE-PROFILE-$ADV30-H     08-27 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYDE-PROFILE-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENRY HYDE WOULD LEAD ANY IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY BY THE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Congress ends up launching an impeachment
inquiry into President Clinton's behavior, the spotlight would
focus intently on Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the portly chairman of
the House Judiciary Committee and one of the senior statesmen of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, 74, a 23-year House veteran whose district is clustered
around O'Hare airport in Chicago's western suburbs, gets first
crack at the long-anticipated report of Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr on President Clinton's conduct in the Whitewater and Monica
Lewinsky matters. The report is expected on Capitol Hill next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is gearing up already, with both Republicans and
Democrats hiring lawyers and staff in case the House decides to
trigger the constitutional machinery that could remove a president
from office.
</P>
<P>
   Although any such proceedings are almost guaranteed to be
fraught with razor-edged partisanship, there's widespread agreement
among Democrats and Republicans that if anyone can bring a sense of
decorum and common purpose to this process, it is Henry Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a man for all seasons, particularly this season, because
he has transcended partisan politics,'' said Rep. Lamar Smith,
R-Texas, a Judiciary Committee member. ``I think he'll be a
unifier, not a divider.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, while not relishing the prospect of delving further
into Clinton's sexual relationship with Lewinsky, believe Hyde is
their best hope for fairness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chairman has made great efforts to avoid charges of
partisanship,'' said Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., also a Judiciary
Committee member. ``I think he's eager to come out of whatever
happens with the country saying `Good job, Henry.'''
</P>
<P>
   At 6'3'' with considerable girth and a grandfatherly mane of
white hair, Hyde is the gentle giant of the House's conservative
leadership. He is best known for his staunch opposition to abortion
and sponsorship of the 1976 Hyde Amendment restricting federal
expenditures for abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also is an implacable foe of gay rights, having steered the
1996 Defense of Marriage Act through the Judiciary Committee. The
law allows states not to recognize same-sex marriages performed in
other states, and defines marriage as something reserved for men
and women in terms of awarding federal benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde does not always walk in lock step with House Speaker
Newt Gingrich and the other GOP conservatives. For example, he
opposes term limits, which he calls the ``dumbing down of
democracy.'' Hyde also opposes repeal of the assault weapon ban,
saying he doesn't want ``the kid next door having a flame thrower
or a Gatling gun.''
</P>
<P>
   As stridently conservative as he is on some issues, friends and
colleagues in both parties say he manages to put forward his views
with aplomb and humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cares fervently about a number of issues, but the reason we
all admire him is that he manages to deal strongly with these
issues, but seldom offends anybody,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde would need all these assets to guide his contentious
committee, if it is tasked to explore whether to recommend that the
full House consider impeachment. Panel members range from Rep. Bob
Barr, R-Ga., who first called for Clinton's impeachment in November
1997 three months before Lewinsky leaped into the national
limelight, to Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., the committee's senior
Democrat whose verbal assaults regularly sting Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Abner Mikva, former Clinton White House counsel and federal
judge who befriended Hyde when both represented Chicago-area House
districts in the 1970s, called Hyde an ``institutionalist'' eager
to see that the presidency _ and Congress itself _ come through any
scandal as unsullied as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry is a partisan, a conservative rock-ribbed Republican,''
Mikva said. ``On the issues, I expect that he and Bill Clinton
couldn't be further apart. But this is an institutional problem.
Henry realizes that if it comes before Congress, hard as it is, the
partisan concerns should be put aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's style contrasts sharply with that of Rep. Dan Burton,
R-Ind., the caustic chairman of the House Government Reform and
Oversight Committee who referred to President Clinton as a
``scumbag'' in a newspaper interview earlier this year. Burton's
continuing probe of campaign finance irregularities in the 1996
election has made little progress amid partisan crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, by contrast, is a nice guy from Chicago who grew up in a
household so poor that the family subsisted on chop suey. The Hydes
were devout Catholics. His father worked for the telephone company,
collecting nickels from pay phones and his mother read St. Thomas
Aquinas.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde interrupted his career as a basketball star at Georgetown
University to serve in the Navy in the South Pacific during World
War II. He married his Georgetown girlfriend, Jeanne Simpson, in
1947 and they had three sons and a daughter. She died of cancer in
1992, a loss that remains palpable for Hyde, according to friends.
</P>
<P>
   He received his law degree from Loyola University in Chicago in
1949, worked as a defense lawyer, and served in the Illinois
General Assembly from 1967 to 1974. It was there that he began his
personal crusade against abortion after a colleague tried enlisting
him as a co-sponsor of an abortion rights law.
</P>
<P>
   He won his seat in Congress in November 1974, three months after
President Richard M. Nixon resigned in the Watergate scandal.
Twenty-four years later, Hyde finds himself on the brink of a
similar whirlwind.
</P>
<P>
   When Starr hands over his report to Congress, the House
Judiciary Committee would investigate, hold hearings and ultimately
decide whether to recommend impeachment. If the panel makes such a
recommendation, the full House then would vote on impeachment,
which is an accusation similar to an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The issue would move to a trial in the Senate where House
Judiciary Committee members would prosecute and the president could
field his own defense team. Chief Justice William Rehnquist would
be the judge. The jury would be the 100 senators. A two-thirds vote
is needed for conviction and removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   In 1868, the House moved to impeach President Andrew Johnson,
but the Senate fell short of the two-thirds majority necessary to
convict and expel him.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1974, the Judiciary Committee under the chairmanship of
Rep. Peter Rodino, D-N.J., voted on bills of impeachment against
Nixon. On Aug. 8, Nixon announced his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Rodino, according to Stephen Hess of the Brookings Institution,
had come to the chairmanship strictly through seniority and was not
particularly known for his adroit leadership skills. Nevertheless,
he showed great ingenuity in forging a consensus that ultimately
pushed Nixon out of office, thus avoiding the ordeal of a Senate
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder now because you have sharp-tongued ideological
members on both sides and the media in general gives politicians
less breathing room,'' Hess said. ``The whole scene is more
cynical, so there is less reason to expect (a bipartisan solution).
But I expect if it does happen, it will be because of Henry Hyde.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1711EDT &QL; 
