<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: PAPERWEIGHTS _ BEAUTY PLAYS ALL THE ANGLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What do President Clinton, King Farouk, Eva Peron,
Colette and Truman Capote all have in common?
</P>
<P>
   They all collected glass paperweights. And why not?
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of glass paperweights is as practical as it is
esthetic. Alan Kaplan, the son of a longtime Manhattan antiques
dealer, Leo Kaplan, is only half joking when he asks: ``What other
kind of art is as easy to maintain? All it takes is Windex or
vinegar and water. Glass paperweights don't break easily, and they
are fake free.''
</P>
<P>
   At last count, Leo Kaplan, whose antique shop is at 967 Madison
Ave., at 75th Street, had 350 antique glass paperweights for sale
at $250 to $80,000 apiece. It has all kinds of weights:
19th-century Bohemian examples, pieces from the top French glass
houses like Baccarat, Clichy and Saint Louis, and specimens from
England and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But fake-free? Perhaps to experts like the Kaplans. The rest of
us need professional guidance or a lot of study. This will be
possible soon, when Christie's previews its sale of the Homer G.
Perkins collection of glass paperweights in Los Angeles from Sept.
12-14 and in New York from Sept. 19-22. The auction will be held in
New York at Christie's on Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, a former president of the Paperweight Collectors'
Association, a group with chapters all over the world, is selling
his second collection of weights. He sold the first in 1981. ``With
that accomplished, I thought I was cured,'' he said, ``but it was
not to be.'' He started buying them again two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 180 lots in the sale are weights with flowers, swirls,
overlays, reptiles and butterflies. Among the rarest examples is a
Baccarat garlanded engraved horse similar to the one sold by the
New-York Historical Society at Sotheby's on Jan. 18, 1995, in a
sale which set the record ($1,503,768) for a paperweight auction.
That horse sold for $40,250, a record for a Baccarat equestrian
weight sold at auction. It had a pre-sale estimate of $15,000 to
$20,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the Christie's sale, the popular favorite among
nonspecialists will probably be the Gila monster weight made by
Pantin, a French factory. It has a black reptile with orange
markings crawling under green plants with yellow flowers (yellow
flowers are the rarest color, according to Alan Kaplan). It has a
low estimate ($3,000 to $4,000) because it has a crack, but it may
well appeal to boys of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   The history of glass paperweights is short. French glassmakers
evidently got the idea to make paperweights after attending the
Austrian Industrial Fair in Vienna in 1845. At the fair, a Murano
glassworker, Pietro Bigaglia, displayed his Venetian wares. A 1975
book, ``Paperweights for Collectors,'' by Lawrence H. Selman and
Linda Pope-Selman, relates that a few of those weights, bearing the
initials BP, have survived. ``They are usually abstract in
design,'' the authors write, ``containing bits and pieces of
colored glass rods and occasionally silhouette canes representing
famous people, gondolas, or initials.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Bigaglia examples were the inspiration, the French
houses of Baccarat, Clichy and Saint Louis suddenly began making
fine glass paperweights. The golden age of paperweights was 1845 to
1860. Soon English factories also began producing paperweights, at
Stourbridge in the Midlands and George Bacchus &AMP; Sons at
Birmingham. As Melissa J. Bennie, the Christie's expert on
paperweights, pointed out, ``The English shapes are usually
different; each company had its own distinctive molds.''
</P>
<P>
   Another expert, Paul Hollister, has written that the English
weights were more pastel and brighter in color than ones in France
and ``were for the most part uninspired.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Boston &AMP; Sandwich Glass Co., Gillinder &AMP;
Sons, Mt. Washington and the New England Glass Company also began
making weights after the 1850s. But as the 20th century approached,
paperweights were no longer fashionable, and fewer were made. Today
most collectors buy weights made in the mid-19th century.
</P>
<P>
   The amazing variety of styles is documented in ``The Collector's
Dictionary of Glass'' (1961), by E.M. Elville. The most
recognizable weights are called millefiori (thousand flowers),
decorative glass made by fusing glass rods of different shapes and
colors that are then thinly sliced in cross sections. A lot of
weights, including some millefiori, depict flowers, fruit, animals,
reptiles and human figures. Sulphide weights incorporate medallions
or portraits, made of a porcelainlike substance, that usually
portray famous figures like Napoleon or the pope.
</P>
<P>
   The antique-paperweight market goes through cycles. After a
lull, it is heating up again. ``There's a strong collecting group
out there right now,'' Ms. Bennie said, ``and new players.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Stair, a former dealer who consults at Christie's, said:
``Most of the new collectors are men _ doctors, industrialists,
movie directors _ interestingly enough. The market is wider than it
used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeal, according to Judy Murphy, the proprietor of Copley
South Antiques in Cape Neddick, Maine, is ``age and history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when most people's desks are covered with phones,
computers and mounds of paper,'' she said, ``it's nice to have
something not produced in the modern world.'' Mrs. Murphy is
selling a 19th-century English piece called an end-of-day
paperweight, made with leftover glass remnants swept up at the end
of the day. It costs $975.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Feingold, the owner of Gem Antiques at 1088 Madison Ave.,
at 82nd Street, has a lot of paperweights for sale. ``When I
started 30 years ago, the market was American,'' he said. ``Now I
sell to the Orient, Europe, South America and Mexico, even
Australia.'' His weights average $2,000 to $3,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Acevedo, owner of the Alexander Gallery at 942
Madison, at 74th Street, has been collecting weights since the
1960s. (He bought the rare black salamander at Sotheby's last April
29 for $160,000.) He tries to limit his collection to 30 pieces, so
he is constantly selling as he trades up. ``I had a field day for
years,'' he said. ``Until this year, I didn't have much
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly good paperweight collections can be seen at the
Corning Glass Museum in Corning, N.Y.; the Bergstrom-Mahler Museum
in Neenah, Wis., and the new Southern Alleghenies Museum of Art at
Ligonier Valley, in western Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   In Ligonier, the New York architect Michele Rudolph has invented
a new way to display paperweights, a spectacular paperweight wall
of glass that lets people see the weights from all angles. ``It was
inspired by Le Corbusier's chapel at Ronchamp,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The museum displays the collections of Walter Carlyle Shaw and
his daughter Elizabeth Shaw Gamble. Situated amid the horse farms
and golf courses of rural Ligonier, between Frank Lloyd Wright's
Falling Water and Pittsburgh, it is one of the country's most
beautifully sited museums.
</P>
