u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      08-27 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Careful Steps On Career Path &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Renee Zellweger has a few things in common with Ellen Gulden,
the character Ms. Zellweger plays in the coming ``One True Thing,''
which also stars Meryl Streep and William Hurt and is to be
released by Universal on Sept. 18. Ellen is a budding magazine
writer, and Ms. Zellweger initially wanted to major in journalism
when she entered the University of Texas. The two are brainy. They
are also uncompromising, but in a way that sets them apart and also
explains why Ms. Zellweger, a surprise hit in ``Jerry Maguire'' two
years ago, has been choosy in the parts she has played since then
and is only now emerging with a major role in a big picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her ambition defines her,'' Ms. Zellweger said of Ellen, a
young woman who reaches a personal crisis in part because her
family life conflicts with her professional aims. ``I'm not like
that,'' she observed. ``I think I'm a determined person, but not
for the same reasons as her, not at all costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Success has come relatively quickly for Ms. Zellweger, but, so
far at least, it has been largely on her terms, an unusual thing
for a 29-year-old actress. The tendency when an attractive young
woman hits it big is to accept the many roles that require good
looks even if they don't offer much substance. Ms. Zellweger has
rejected that approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, when you start out, especially when you're just
starting out, and if you're blond, to play the bimbo, the party
girl, the ex-girlfriend is kind of a natural,'' said the blond Ms.
Zellweger, who hails from Katy, Texas ``It's a really frustrating
process.''
</P>
<P>
   She added in her breathy whisper of a voice, ``I decided I
wasn't going to be in those kinds of films _ you know, the triple-D
girl by the keg.'' In this spirit, she was cast against type as an
independent-minded young Hasidic wife in the critically praised ``A
Price Above Rubies.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Zellweger has not gone unscathed. She played Tammy, a
girl who has a one-night stand with Ethan Hawke in ``Reality
Bites.'' ``There's always something to learn,'' Ms. Zellweger said
of the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``One True Thing'' is a quiet, emotionally intense drama about a
young woman called back to her parents' home after her mother falls
ill. She reluctantly puts her writing career aside and wrestles
with the self-absorption of her father, a renowned college
professor, and the seeming superficiality of her mother, a
housewife caught up in the rhythms of small-town life.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the story, based on the the novel by Anna Quindlen, a
former columnist for The New York Times, is about people learning,
reluctantly, to listen to their hearts rather than their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Which is a bit like the way Ms. Zellweger describes her own
deliberate career path. ``It was never so much about taking what
you can get as what you want ultimately from what you do,'' she
said. ``I always thought it was so much harder to double back and
get on the right road after you do that sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tolkien Times 3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In its biggest, and perhaps most unusual, financial commitment
ever, New Line Cinema has decided to spend more than $130 million
producing a film version of J.R.R. Tolkien's classic fantasy tale,
``The Lord of the Rings.'' But for Robert Shaye, New Line's
chairman, the issue is not spending huge sums but saving $50
million, sort of like the person who says that buying a Rolls-Royce
for the cut-rate price of $100,000 is really saving $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Tolkien project is exceptional because it involves the
consecutive production of three different movies, generally
following the story line of Tolkien's trilogy about the journey of
Frodo Baggins as he fights the Dark Lord, Sauron, and saves the
hobbits. The movies are expected to run in close proximity, perhaps
six months apart, starting on Christmas 2000.
</P>
<P>
   There are great risks as well as potential rewards. If the first
movie fails, this will bode ill for the remaining two. But it will
actually be a relatively low-cost production, in spite of the huge
overall price tag. The director, co-writer and co-producer will be
Peter Jackson, a New Zealander best known for his role as a writer,
producer and director of ``Heavenly Creatures.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson will be filming the three movies in New Zealand, where
productions are significantly cheaper than in the United States. In
addition, he has started a special-effects company in New Zealand,
which is expected to produce the large number of computer-generated
shots to be used in the fantasy films.
</P>
<P>
   Shaye said that by making the three films together, without the
need to create a new infrastructure each time, the overall costs
would be reduced by as much as $50 million. Jackson said the films
would be shot over the period of a year, with short breaks in
between. The movie would be largely live action with some computer
enhancement.
</P>
<P>
   In another twist, Jackson was originally working with Miramax on
the project. But when he insisted on making it into more than one
movie, which is what Miramax wanted, it allowed him to take the
idea elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many projects I'd spend three and a half years
on,'' Jackson said in a telephone interview from Wellington, New
Zealand. ``But `The Lord of the Rings' is so special, so
remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It's always been regarded as impossible to film, but
with what we can do with the computers now, it's just the right
time.'' He said that, in another effort to keep costs down, the
movies would use relatively unknown actors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Battle Joined &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The technology pioneer Steve Jobs is not exactly unfamiliar with
ferocious competition, but he was unusually upbeat in a recent
interview in describing how he sees his position in a market that
has grown dangerously cluttered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so far ahead of anyone else it's not funny!'' Jobs
exclaimed. Referring to his new film, ``A Bug's Life,'' he added,
``It has 10 times the computer power of anything we did in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Jobs is well known as a founder and currently interim chief
executive of Apple Computer, but he was talking in this instance
about another passion, movies. ``A Bug's Life,'' an animated movie
his company, Pixar, will be releasing through the Walt Disney
Company in November, is a contender in what promises to be the most
heated battle ever in the market for children's films.
</P>
<P>
   Five major movies with animation will be released between
October and Christmas in a contest that some people believe could
alter the competitive landscape, depending on who can actually turn
a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Bug's Life,'' which follows Pixar's last film, ``Toy
Story,'' and will be released on Nov. 20, offers, as Jobs puts it,
``the most striking animation ever made.'' ``The Rugrats Movie,''
to be released by Paramount on Nov. 20, builds on the hugely
popular cartoon franchise from Nickelodeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt,'' due on Dec. 18 from Dreamworks, is
regarded as an expensive effort by the new studio to steal a
significant portion of the animated-movie business from the leader,
Disney. And then there are ``Antz'' , a co-production of Dreamworks
and due on Oct. 2, and ``Babe: Pig in the City,'' due on Nov. 25
from Universal, a sequel to ``Babe,'' a film that involves live
action and a modest amount of computer effects to give the illusion
that the animals are talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would have thought the summer was a much more likely time
for some of these,'' said Joe Roth, the chairman of Disney's movie
division. ``You worry about this competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the studios has approached the problem by trying to
argue that its film is unique and not really in competition with
the others. Terry Press, the head of marketing for Dreamworks, for
instance, said that both ``Antz'' and ``The Prince of Egypt'' were
not solely children's movies, but rather were aimed at a slightly
older audience, for those 8 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Friedman, the vice chairman of Paramount, said that ``The
Rugrats Movie'' would enjoy the benefit of an instantly
recognizable franchise and that it would be about family values.
</P>
<P>
   And some are more straightforward. ``We think we have a very
good film,'' Jobs said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
