<HEADER>
A5862 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-FICTION-COX     08-27 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-FICTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pain, peril break serenity of daily life
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 30: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ason is killed, a wife dies, a lover ends a long relationship.
As Yeats wrote, ``Things fall apart; the centre cannot hold.'' That
line from ``The Second Coming'' leapt to mind in reading three
well-wrought novels in which day-to-day reality is irreparably
shattered.
</P>
<P>
   -- Reservation Road. By John Burnham Schwartz. Knopf. $24. 292
pages.
</P>
<P>
   When the Learner family, returning from an outdoor concert,
stops by a gas station, 10-year-old Josh is killed by a hit-and-run
driver. His parents, Ethan and Grace, and 8-year-old sister Emma
struggle with guilt, anger and emotional paralysis. The killer,
Dwight Arno, hides his crime. He is a lawyer whose own life was
shattered when he beat his son, Sam, and his wife on the night she
ended their marriage. The novel moves forward in alternating
first-person voices of Ethan, Dwight and Grace. Their lives
intertwine in ways they do not recognize, but that readers do.
Eventually, Ethan pieces together the puzzle and confronts Dwight,
whose concern for Sam in the face of his own peril creates an
unusually moving scene. No character is solely good or evil, solely
perpetrator or victim in this gut-wrenching great American tragedy
from the author of ``Bicycle Days.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Death in Summer. By William Trevor. Viking. $23.95. 214
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Thaddeus Davenant, impoverished owner of a British country home,
marries the wealthy Letitia and they are blessed with a baby,
Georgina. When Letitia is killed in a bicycle accident, the fusty
Thaddeus feels guilty because he didn't love Letitia, married her
for her money, and because they argued before she died. Meanwhile,
Georgina needs a nanny, and the applicants, including one named
Pettie, are unqualified. Thaddeus reluctantly accepts the services
of Letitia's mother, Mrs. Iveson, who moves into the house, much to
the chagrin of the obsessed, spying Pettie. That summer there will
be two more deaths and an abduction, but to tell more would ruin
the tale. Yet, this is not so much a mystery as a marvelous dance
of class consciousness and language. Each character is presented
through a particular syntactical tenor, growing, much like flowers,
page by page in Trevor's subtle linguistic landscape.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Essence of the Thing. By Madeleine St. John. Carroll &AMP;
Graf. $22. 234 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Nicola, who has lived happily with Jonathan in a London flat for
years, is shocked when he abruptly announces he has ceased to love
her. Nicola is devastated, but still she irons the creep's shirts,
hoping he'll change his nerdy little mind. Gradually, she comes to
her senses and moves out and on with her life. American women, who
were reading this sort of thing back in the '70s, may at first
wonder why this book was nominated this year for a Booker Prize.
But as dialogue succeeds dialogue, as more couples come onstage,
the plot turns into an exploration of how to keep one's
individuality in a relationship. In one hilarious scene, two
friends cut inches off Nicola's hem, put her in fishnet hose, top
her off with the perfect hat and take her dancing all night.
Exhilarated, she returns to find guess who begging forgiveness.
Anyone who watches ``Ally McBeal'' can intuit her decision.
Sometimes, when things fall apart, they get better.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
