<HEADER>
A5863 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ERINGEL-VIDEOS30-COX     08-27 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERINGEL-VIDEOS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Closer inspection finds `Ryan,' `Titanic' kindred
spirits in film
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 30: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first glance, about all that last year's smash hit,
``Titanic,'' which arrives in video stores this week, would appear
to have in common with this year's unanticipated hit, ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' is that they both feature boats. Lots of little
boats for ``Saving Private Ryan's'' celebrated D-Day sequence and
one very big boat for ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   They also both have certified heartthrobs at their center:
``Titanic's'' blue-eyed blond, Leonardo DiCaprio, and ``Saving
Private Ryan's'' blue-eyed blond, Matt Damon.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, they seem completely different. One is a hugely
expensive, rumor-plagued, unabashedly commercial behemoth. The
other is a carefully controlled, rumor-free, prestige picture.
One's Oscar-winning potential seemed almost an afterthought _ a
surprising yet somehow inevitable bonus of its immense box office
success. The other's Oscar chances seem part of its existence from
the very beginning while, conversely, its unexpected box office
clout (four weeks in the top spot) wasn't part of anyone's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Look more closely, however, and similarities surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both have similar forms,'' points out Michael Wilmington, the
lead film critic for the Chicago Tribune. ``It's a classical
Hollywood form. The John Ford paradigm. The story of `Stagecoach'
(the 1939 Ford film that launched John Wayne's career). A group of
people undergoing a crisis. And that crisis is revealing. Character
is stripped bare.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs. ``And I'm not referring to the sketching scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Another parallel, Wilmington continues, is the way both movies
``are framed by something in the present that gives meaning to the
past. In a sense, they have exactly the same endings.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, consider the wraparound style of storytelling
that applies to both films. In each case, the main action, be it
the love story aboard the Titanic or the mission to find Private
Ryan, is book-ended by a present-day prologue and epilogue. In
James Cameron's script, elderly Gloria Stewart remembers her
tragic, life-altering teenage romance while staring at the rusted
hull of the once-mighty Titanic. In the Steven Spielberg film,
seventysomething Harrison Young seeks validation for his life while
staring at the grave of a fallen soldier.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the most literal level, both are framed with flashbacks by
survivors,'' says Matthew Bernstein, associate professor of film
studies at Emory University. ``The two frameworks create that sense
of inevitability and fate. Of things out of control. Of who
survives and who doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People really connect with the various vignettes of
catastrophe in both movies,'' he adds, echoing Wilmington's Ford
paradigm. ``The idea of making difficult choices when the chips are
down.''
</P>
<P>
   A further likeness, notes Bernstein, is the simple fact of both
films' technical virtuosity. ``An aesthetic of astonishment'' is
his phrase.
</P>
<P>
   ``In `Titanic,' you've got this incredible spectacle. This ship
breaking apart and sinking in a way that's never been visualized
before. There's something similar in `Saving Private Ryan.' A
catastrophic battle scene that's never been photographed in that
way before. That immense scope coupled with that hand-held,
you-are-there camera work that immediately pulls you in.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bernstein says he thinks it's important to
give credit to the characters. ``People really connected with that
conventional romance between Leonardo DiCaprio and Kate Winslet.
They find them very winning and endearing characters. And in
`Saving Private Ryan,' you have to give a lot of credit to Tom
Hanks and his reincarnation of Jimmy Stewart. Again, people really
connect with that all-American good guy. So both combine the epic
with the intimate in very compelling ways.''
</P>
<P>
   One final similarity: For all their size, both ``Titanic'' and
``Saving Private Ryan'' are personal projects, propelled by their
directors' unique vision. Neither is a sequel. Neither is a
pitch-perfect example of demographic-think. Both are films their
directors had to make. Maybe that's what audiences really connected
with _ a story worth telling told by an artist who had to be the
one to tell it.
</P>
<P>
   As Spielberg said to one interviewer, ``As I had children and as
I grew up, I wanted to leave something behind that I could really
be proud of that wasn't just dinosaurs stepping on stuff. ... I
felt I had a kind of duty to those veterans of World War II to
finally acquit them of their experience in a non-Hollywood way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
