<HEADER>
A5864 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICALS-HITZ-COX     08-27 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICALS-HITZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta's producer at large
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York_When Alex Hitz was 8 years old and an overnight guest
at the White House, then-President Carter gave him his bathrobe,
saying that the boy ``must be cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Hitz said recently, he was a little spooked, too. He'd
glanced in the Lincoln Bedroom, where his stepfather (then-Atlanta
Symphony Orchestra maestro Robert Shaw) and mother, Caroline, were
to sleep, and ``That room looked like it was full of ghosties.''
Young Alex opted to bunk in the Nixon Study, solo, and passed the
night without incident.
</P>
<P>
   Hitz at 30 is still a bit of a maverick and has the perfect job
description for someone of an independent bent: free-lance producer
at large.
</P>
<P>
   After various endeavors in his early 20s (art dealer, co-owner
of an Atlantra restaurant), the Washington and Lee University(Va.)
graduate went to see his famous stepfather receive a Kennedy Center
Honor in 1991 and there met lyricist and co-honoree Betty Comden.
They hit it off so well that Hitz became an associate producer of
the 1997 Central Park mounting of her ``On the Town,'' launching
that vintage musical toward its upcoming Broadway production. He
simultaneously helped produce last fall's ``The Triumph of Love,''
an 18th-century comedy set to new music that had some glowing
reviews but didn't live long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shouldn't be surprised,'' Hitz says with a rueful smile,
``but I find myself in a dog-eat-dog business that can be
terrifying. I learned a lot from Margo Lion (producer of ``Angels
in America''), but at some point you have to take your knocks and
figure out the political pyramids on your own.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitz also was associate producer of the current Broadway revival
of ``The Sound of Music,'' expected to announce a tour soon. He's
done this while commuting almost weekly between his Ansley Park
condo and the Carlyle Hotel, his Gotham base of operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love both places, and it's also nice to get away from both
places,'' says the suave, single Southerner as he digs into a
Carlyle breakfast, a polka-dotted handkerchief artfully spilling
from his blazer pocket. In the words of Virginia Adair, a longtime
family friend: ``I don't think anyone gives a better dinner party
than Alex. He's got such an eye for detail, and he's got his
lyrical side; you just know he'll go far.''
</P>
<P>
   Rawson Foreman, an Atlanta lawyer and Hitz's cousin, recalls,
``I can remember Alex as a kid peddling around Ansley Park, talking
up a storm, finding out everything, building a social network. Now,
when I hear him talk about having dinner with Prince Charles, and
producing Broadway shows, it's like he was taken up in a spaceship
and this incredibly sophisticated fellow was sent back down!''
</P>
<P>
   Hitz's main role in the aforementioned shows has been raising
money _ some of it from friends in Atlanta, a good chunk of it lost
when ``Triumph'' tanked _ but now he's embarking on a more creative
path. He's one of the conceptualizers of ``68,'' a musical about a
girl's coming-of-age in that stormy year. His co-producers have
impressive credits: Richard Frankel (``Driving Miss Daisy''), Heidi
Ettinger (who designed the ravishing sets for ``The Secret
Garden'') and Jonathan Reynolds (author of ``Geniuses,'' who's
writing the musical book). Hitz says they're talking to Stephen
Trask, hottest theatrical rock songwriter of the moment (``Hedwig
and the Angry Inch''), about composing the score. The show will be
workshopped in New York in January with an eye toward a
pre-Broadway tryout in Washington in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Hitz is also developing films _ one about the British
photographer and costume designer Cecil Beaton, and another with
``an Atlanta story, possibly with a very well-known screenwriter I
can't mention yet.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, ``The Sound of Music'' is, in Hitz's words,
``perking right along at the box office,'' and the production
reminds him of why all the aggravation is worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a moment during the cast party at Tavern on the
Green,'' Hitz says, ``when I saw the lights twinkling in the trees,
the people dancing and drinking champagne, and I thought, `Hmm _
there are worse businesses to be in.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
