<HEADER>
A5866 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICALS-REGIONAL-COX     08-27 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICALS-REGIONAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Civil War', `Aida' make regional rounds
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 30: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In terms of new musicals this fall, there is as much action out
of town as in. Major players of the theater world can be seen at
such perennial Broadway steppingstones as Boston, as well as newer
tryout cities such as Atlanta and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the major musicals trying out in the regional theaters
and on the road:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida.'' Atlanta has given
birth to several important plays and players in recent years, but
in terms of sheer show-biz visibility it's never seen the likes of
this: a world premiere collaboration between the Alliance Theatre
and Walt Disney Theatrical Productions. Songs are by Elton John and
Tim Rice, coming off their triumphant score for Disney's ``The Lion
King.'' Author Linda Woolverton (``Beauty and the Beast'') is
giving a somewhat contemporary spin to the biracial love-triangle
immortalized in Verdi's 1871 opera. Judging by a hearing of
rehearsals in New York, the music will rock; judging by a glimpse
of sets and costumes being loaded into the Alliance, the show will
dazzle. (Previews Sept. 17, opens Oct. 7).
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Fosse: A Celebration in Song and Dance.'' It's been 10
years since choreographer Bob Fosse collapsed and died on a
Washington street _ on his way to one of his shows, in tryouts _
and his legend only looms larger today. Livent (``Ragtime'') is
producing this compilation of his stylish, sensual dances. Variety
praised the show in its recent Toronto premiere. It's conceived by
Gwen Verdon, Fosse's one-time wife and frequent leading lady, and
co-choreographed by Ann Reinking, who so brilliantly adapted the
spirit of his dances for ``Chicago.'' (Previews Sept. 8, opening
TBA, through Sept. 27, Colonial Theatre, Boston. Previews Oct. 9,
opening TBA, through Dec. 6, Ahmanson Theatre, Los Angeles.
Expected to move to Broadway in December or January).
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Civil War.'' The War Between the States as ... a
musical? Springtime for Stonewall? A Ken Burns documentary with
production numbers? Not exactly. Burns has no role in this new
musical, but it uses some of the historical writings (by Lincoln,
Whitman, Frederick Douglass) that informed his magnificent PBS
series. Certainly these writers outshine the middlebrows who
usually collaborate with composer Frank Wildhorn, who has two shows
on Broadway (``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde,'' ``The Scarlet Pimpernel''). Though
he has a long way to go before reaching Andrew Lloyd Webber's
success, Wildhorn shares the Brit's knack for surviving bad reviews
with slick pop tunes that people love. They can hear them on two
advance CDs, one sung by Nashville stars for October release, and
the other a cast album to hit stores in January. (Previews Sept. 8,
opens Sept. 16, Alley Theatre, Houston).
</P>
<P>
   -- ``By Jeeves.'' Speaking of Lloyd Webber, his output has
slowed in recent years, and his most recent musical, ``Whistle Down
the Wind,'' is getting retooled in Great Britain. In the meantime,
he's put back into play the only other flop of his career, also
reworked, a 1970s collaboration with the endlessly imaginative
comic playwright Alan Ayckbourn. It's based on the beloved comic
stories of P.G. Wodehouse. (Previews Oct. 17, opening TBA,
Goodspeed Opera House, East Haddam, Conn.)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Gypsy.'' When the trumpet-voiced Betty Buckley (who sang
``Memory'' in ``Cats'') is found in a medium-size theater in
Millburn, N.J., you know there's a lack of top-shelf work for her
in Gotham. Then again, a trouper such as Buckley will go almost
anywhere for one of the best-written musicals (Arthur Laurents,
Jule Styne, Stephen Sondheim) and one of the greatest roles, Mama
Rose, memorably played by Ethel Merman and Tyne Daly in years past.
Could the 1959 classic again be a candidate for Broadway? (Previews
Sept. 9, opening TBA, Paper Mill Playhouse).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
