<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5869 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAPPELL-COX     08-27 2079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPPELL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Relative obscurity suits Chappell, a writer's writer
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 30: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Teresa K. Weaver
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fred Chappell is a poet and novelist of modest aspirations. ``I
don't really have any confidence that I will be remembered, or any
desire to be remembered,'' he says a few hours before delivering
the fall convocation address at Georgia College &AMP; State University
recently. ``If I am going to be remembered, I guess I'd like to be
remembered as someone who did less harm than he was capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in khakis, a blue Oxford button-down and only slightly
crooked bow tie, Chappell projects a genial, farm boy persona that
can't quite conceal his ability and his intellect. He is poet
laureate of North Carolina, a professor at the University of North
Carolina-Greensboro and the author of some 20 books of fiction,
poetry and short stories. Partly because he is not flashy and
partly because he hails from a writer-rich state that has nurtured
Reynolds Price, Anne Tyler, William Styron, Kaye Gibbons and
countless others in the contemporary pantheon, his name isn't as
widely known as his admirers would like. But at age 62, Chappell
basks in the freedom of ``relative obscurity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred is a real marvel, an authentic genius to work so well in
every known mode and genre _ and to be so prolific and so
public-spirited,'' says fellow North Carolina writer Lee Smith
(``News of the Spirit''), who has known Chappell since the early
1960s. ``But Fred is a writer who would rather write than market
himself. He spends so much of his time talking to little groups of
poetry ladies ... and he's spoken at every podunk school in North
Carolina over the years. He's always taken such care to respond
personally to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way: He's not schmoozing at Cape Cod every
summer. ... But he has this incredible national reputation among
writers, and he's at the peak of his powers right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Chappell writes with the poet's love of language: ``The wind had
got into the clocks and blown the hours awry.'' His stories are
almost equal parts realism and fantasy, tall tales and mountain
yarns, hymns and dream sequences. Old people are ``age-bent,'' and
children are ``pigtail age.'' Knucklebones are as white as if the
``skin had been peeled off them.'' Sentences shoot out of a mouth
``like a rock from a slingshot.'' Things happen in places called
Worrisome Creek and Forgetful Mountain. And every year, teetotaling
grandmas quite knowingly allow some of their carefully canned grape
juice to ferment. Above all, Chappell's work is built on an abiding
sense of community _ not of a particular family or town, but of
humankind _ and an unfailing reliance on humor as a tool of
survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my aims in writing has always been to capture that
first excitement I got on reading writers who knocked me flat on my
butt when I was young: John Steinbeck, Ray Bradbury and, a little
later, Thomas Mann. And poets _ Keats, wooooo! Gee, that was good
stuff! It still is.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Chappell's fiction feels autobiographical, although he's
quick to say he's not sure exactly how much really is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiction is memory and imagination _ neither one of them is
factually accurate. They are both accurate in a more profound,
important way. They're emotionally accurate. ... So I don't know if
anybody ever actually said a certain amount of dialogue. I have no
idea if I heard it somewhere or if I made it up on the spot. My
feeling is I probably don't make up too much of this stuff. But it
gets all jumbled from various sources, and it comes out the best
way it can.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I think I have in my head is a lot of phony memories. My
earliest memory is of someone leaning over a crib or a bassinet.
There was this huge, enormous, ugly face _ probably my daddy or
mother _ and I was frightened by it. But whether that's a real
memory or not I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Chappell is at once a product of and an escapee from the
Appalachian Mountains. Born and reared near the ``grimy'' little
mill town of Canton (population 5,000) in western North Carolina,
he discovered writing as many youngsters do, by way of reading. For
whatever mystical reason, the young Appalachian found something
irresistible in the nearly impenetrable prose of Thomas Mann. He
was entranced, and life on the farm was no longer an option.
</P>
<P>
   A raw talent for writing helped get Chappell into Duke
University(NC), where he spent the first two years ``drinking beer
and reading books out of the library and not going to class.'' ``I
was not a poster boy,'' he admits freely. ``I still am not.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the displaced farm boy became immersed in the
classics, studying the various styles and forms that would help
shape his own distinctive voice.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Chappell's fiction and poetry is firmly grounded in the
rural South, but throughout there are allusions on a much grander
scale to influences ranging from Dante, Baudelaire and Rimbaud to
Pound, Haydn and even Bob Dylan.
</P>
<P>
   In his four-cycle poem ``Midquest'' (1981), the grandmother
warns the narrator, Ole Fred, not to get ``away from what you
are.'' Chappell seems to have found comfortable ground: Although he
``deserted'' his homeplace for a life of writing and academia,
clearly he plows much of that rural territory over and over again
in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to train yourself to be an observer,'' Chappell says.
``And a lot of things you pick up without really observing. You
just kind of take it in through your pores. And after you learn to
observe, there's a difference in the quality of observation. This
was a problem in a lot of my material. I had learned to observe
after those experiences happened to me. So I had to bring tools
from later in life to bear on experiences in my earlier life
without falsifying those feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Chappell has always found inspiration in the everyday: ``girls,
cats, wine, weather _ all the good stuff.'' And with a little
inspiration, the details of an ordinary life become universal.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that was the life of Little Mary,'' Chappell wrote in
``Farewell, I'm Bound to Leave You'' (1996). ``She had got through
it, we each of us thought, the way you eat a plate of food when
you're not hungry a bit. She was only forty-three when she died. I
forget what medical reason the doctor wrote down, but it wasn't the
one that counted. The truth was, she wore out. Just wore thin and
then wore through, like a shirtsleeve at the elbow.''
</P>
<P>
   In his entire life, Chappell has spent only nine months living
outside the South: In 1967-68, he and his wife lived in Florence,
Italy, courtesy of a Rockefeller Foundation grant. Since 1964,
Chappell has taught literature and creative writing at the
University of North Carolina-Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teaching is what I do for a living. It's my vocation. ...
That's how I think of myself.'' After the instinctive pause of a
storyteller, he adds slyly, ``That's not always how my students
think of me. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   On a typical day, Chappell rises at 5 or 5:30 and writes for
four hours. ``And then, after that, I owe my soul to the company
store,'' he says. From early October until spring, schoolwork
generally ``overtakes'' him, and writing time has to be squeezed
into his daily routine whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   He composes everything in longhand _ poetry in pencil, fiction
in pen. ``I think it's nice to feel the pressure of your
personality on your words,'' he explains. ``You can't get that on a
computer. ... Plus, it just doesn't look right to sit in a bar and
type on a computer, but it's perfectly legitimate to sit in a bar
with a pen and scribble poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   When a poem or a chapter is ready, he often reads aloud to his
wife of 39 years, Susan. ``Mostly I trust her judgment,'' he says.
``Sometimes she's just dead wrong, but mostly I trust her
judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Chappell's soft-spoken manner and old-school charm allows his
self-deprecating humor to sneak up on you. He takes his work
seriously but never himself. It's a mind-set he tried to impress
upon students at Georgia College &AMP; State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a writer, failure is my stock in trade,'' he said in his
convocation address Aug. 19. ``Every book I have published, every
poem I have written, is but a dim and scrawny shadow of the one
that was in my mind when I sat down to compose.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he explains, ``failure that comes after the best
possible effort has been put forth'' is not only acceptable but
honorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have looked upon this earth for 62 summers and have observed
statesmen and starlets, administrators and apple-pickers, warriors
and weavers, and scholars and students by the hundreds and have
concluded that those who succeeded rarely did so because of
brilliance of intellect or superabundance of talent. They succeeded
through strength of character _ which in some cases amounted to
arrant stupidity: They were too dumb to know when they were licked
or too stubborn to admit defeat when it was over them like thermal
underwear.''
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of Chappell's convocation visit, all incoming
freshmen were required to read his novel ``Brighten the Corner
Where You Are'' (1989) and come to school prepared to discuss the
book in ``circles'' with faculty, staff and community members. At
several events during orientation, Chappell spent time talking to
the students, most of whom were new to his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meeting Fred Chappell was magical for many of these
students,'' says Rosemary DePaolo, second-year president of the
college. ``He both entertained them and stretched them. He expected
them to know certain things ... so now in class they want to learn
about those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Chappell's appearance was part of the college's newly defined
mission to focus on being _ proudly and unapologetically _ a
liberal arts university. As a teacher, a writer and a dedicated
student of the classics, Chappell is happy to do what he can to
help the cause. His roots in education extend even beyond his 34
years on the Greensboro campus: His parents were both
schoolteachers until, ``curious about what it would be like to
eat,'' they went into the retail furniture business. ``But our
house was always full of books,'' he remembers.
</P>
<P>
   Chappell is working now to conclude a story line that he began
in 1971, centering on the character of Joe Robert Kirkman,
protagonist in the four-cycle poem ``Midquest'' and three novels:
``I Am One of You Forever'' (1985), ``Brighten the Corner Where You
Are'' and ``Farewell, I'm Bound To Leave You.'' This fourth and
final novel in the series takes place after Joe Robert's death, as
his son Jess _ a thinly disguised, ``much nicer version'' of the
author as a boy and ultimately a man _ searches into his father's
life to see if he can understand this strange, eccentric figure.
</P>
<P>
   In a passage from the unfinished novel, Chappell reintroduces
Joe Robert:
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps you have seen the posters for the freaky old science
fiction movies of the 1950s. The muscular intrepid spaceman, having
arrived in a distant planet, steps out of his rocket, ray gun in
hand, to save the horrified blond damsel from the clutches of some
ill-tempered ambulatory fungus with too many tentacles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is my father, rescuing the Princess of Rational Thought
from the Superstition Monster _ only his spacesuit is such a one as
Charlie Chaplin might wear: ill-fitting and spotted with leaky
Band-Aids, equipped with a fishbowl helmet direly in need of
Windex. Upon close inspection his superscience ray gun turns out to
be a water pistol. The damsel in distress, bearded and balding,
bears an unfortunate resemblance to Charles Darwin.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of closing the books on the fictional lives of Joe
Robert and his family triggers some jumbled emotions in the writer
who created them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it will feel like to be through with it,''
Chappell says. ``It might feel like I've lost a limb. And a lot of
writers go into a deep, dark depression when they finish a book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually I feel a great sense of relief when I'm done with a
book, but this one I have a little apprehension about. It just
feels a little ragged to me. Terry Kay called the other night,
though ... and said every writer he knows hates the book when he
finishes it. So that's giving me some hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
