<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5870 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICALS-COX     08-27 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will John's score for ``Aida'' lead pack of new fall shows?
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 30: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_All ears will be on Atlanta this fall. The reason:
Broadway is starved for catchy melody and smart lyric, the
specialty of Elton John and Tim Rice. Their Disney/Alliance Theatre
musical, ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida'' (previewing Sept.
17) is expected to move to New York in early 1999, provided that
the British hit makers' sound can grab sophisticated young adults
the way their score for ``The Lion King'' delights families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elaborate Lives'' is just one of the tantalizing unknown
quantities of the new season's musicals. For instance, can
Atlanta-bred playwright Alfred Uhry tailor popular entertainment
from the city's notorious Leo Frank case of 1913? Will
``Footloose'' lose its dizzy charm in translation from film to
stage?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the critical long-term question is whether kings of pop
songwriting from the past three decades _ exemplified by John _ can
revitalize musical theater. Can they fill the void that gapes as
such old masters as Stephen Sondheim, Jerry Herman, John Kander and
Fred Ebb enter their sunset years? Can they pick up the slack as
London-based hit meisters Andrew Lloyd Webber, Alain Bloublil and
Claude- Michel Schonberg slow their creative pace?
</P>
<P>
   Of the middle-aged pop kings, Paul Simon, Jimmy Buffett, Barry
Manilow and Randy Newman have scored only mixed success in their
theatrical debuts over the past two years. They could use
encouragement, and a successful outing by John _ in Atlanta, and
later in Gotham _ would give it to them.
</P>
<P>
   Following are fall's most noteworthy Broadway tuners.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Little Me.'' Martin Short, a terrific singer as well as
comedian, plays the riotous multicharacter role created by Sid
Caesar in 1962. The divine Faith Prince plays the daffy femme
fatale who has the deja vu sensation of marrying the same man over
and over again. This star power is essential, because as we saw at
the Alliance two seasons ago, the score and Neil Simon book are
problematic. (Previews Sept. 30, opens Oct. 29, Roundabout
Theatre.)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Footloose.'' It's an adaptation of the popular 1980s film
about a kid who sets his heartland town a-boogeyin' with forbidden
dance. A squad of songwriters (including Kenny Loggins) beefed up
the Tom Snow score, which includes the Oscar-nominated ``Let's Hear
It for the Boy.'' Trying out at Washington's Kennedy Center on
Tuesday through Sept. 20, the new show boasts red-hot director
Walter Bobbie of ``Chicago'' fame. (Previews Oct. 2, opens Oct. 22,
Richard Rodgers.)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``On the Town.'' The great choreographer Jerome Robbins, who
died this month, conceived this 1944 musical about three sailors
getting every inch out of their last 24-hour shore leave, a
dizzying tour of the City in its prime. Featuring ``New York, New
York,'' the show bursts with the youthful joie de vivre of Robbins
and three other creators in their 20s: Leonard Bernstein (music),
Betty Comden and Adolph Green (book and lyrics). The revival is
produced and directed by George C. Wolfe (``Bring in 'da Noise,
Bring in 'da Funk'') and his Joseph Papp Public Theatre/New York
Shakespeare Festival. (Previews Oct. 20, opens Nov. 19, Gershwin.)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Parade.'' A girl's mysterious murder in the Deep South, an
anti-Semitic mob, a press-circus trial, a lynching ... all the
elements of an American musical, right? Then again, in the words of
Uhry, ``A show about death at sea (``Titanic'') won a Tony, so who
knows?'' Indeed. Uhry, known for a gentle, mostly comic approach to
Atlanta characters (``Driving Miss Daisy,'' ``The Last Night of
Ballyhoo'') delves into the darker side of his hometown's history
with his musical book about the infamous Leo Frank case of 1913.
The premiere is co-produced by Livent (``Ragtime'') and Lincoln
Center, with Hal Prince (``The Phantom of the Opera'') directing.
(Previews Nov. 12, opens Dec. 17, Beaumont.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
