<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW `TITANIC' GOES BY TRUCK  
 NEW VIDEO RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one knows exactly how big it will get. But big.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing approaches this,'' said Stan Meyers, executive vice
president of Baker &AMP; Taylor, the country's second largest video
distributor. After many years in the business, Meyers has seen the
biggest: ``The Lion King'' (the very biggest), ``Jurassic Park,''
``Forrest Gump,'' ``Men in Black.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, casting a larger shadow across the landscape than
the spaceship in ``Independence Day'' (the second biggest), comes
``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   No centralized count is available, but dealers say that about 26
million copies of the film, to be released Sept. 1 by Paramount,
are now in the distribution pipeline. The studio won't confirm that
figure, only that it took 6.5 million miles of videotape (260 times
around the planet) to fill the videocassettes that are, in turn,
packing, by the studio's estimate, the 1,000 tractor-trailer trucks
needed to get all that plastic to stores by midnight Monday, when
``Titanic,'' priced at $19.95, officially goes on sale.
</P>
<P>
   Lay those trucks bumper to bumper and, Paramount has calculated,
the convoy would stretch 40 miles. Bob Webb, a vice president of
Ingram, the country's largest video distributor, said a truck would
carry 38,000 copies of ``Titanic.'' But the film is on two tapes,
so if a tractor-trailer loses its contents on the highway, it could
require the cleanup of 76,000 videocassettes.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, all those millions of cassettes would send the
Titanic, along with a container ship or two, straight to the
bottom. How many of them will finally be bought by consumers can't
be determined, of course, but retailers say that millions of
advance orders from fans indicate that the first shipments will be
sold out during the first few weeks. That, they add, will lead to
heavy reordering. ``We're already seeing that,'' Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster, the nation's largest chain, promises there will be
copies enough for everybody come release day. That puts pressure on
other chains to follow suit. ``We're guaranteed to have it, and if
we don't, people will get a free rental,'' said Julie Gschwend, a
vice president of Video Avenue, a chain of 20 stores in South
Florida. Each store, she said, will stock 200 rental copies and
between 200 and 300 copies for sale. So far the chain has logged
more than 8,500 pre-orders, she added.
</P>
<P>
   In its initial shipment phase ``The Lion King'' tallied 22
million copies, with about 30 million ultimately sold to consumers.
On the basis of its 26 million-copy start, ``Titanic'' may well
exceed that.
</P>
<P>
   All the factors that made the movie the biggest box-office
attraction ever are expected to weigh in once again for the video.
``There's Leo,'' said Larry Moyer, a manager of Video Stop, a chain
in Oregon and southern Washington, referring to Leonardo DiCaprio,
the film's megastar, a major draw for millions of adolescent girls.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers, no matter how many times they may have watched the
movie in theaters, have figured strongly in the presale, and they
are expected to be a presence at ``Titanic''-related festivities at
many stores on release day. Blockbuster stores will stay open
Monday night until 2 a.m. (actually Tuesday morning). In Florida,
Video Avenue stores will stay open past midnight. The pizza will be
free.
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   The Real Blonde
</P>
<P>
   Mangling some Arthur Miller dialogue, Joe (Matthew Modine) lands
an assignment in a Madonna video. Meanwhile, his girlfriend
(Catherine Keener) takes self-defense classes and helps primp a
supermodel named Sahara (Bridgette Wilson) for spreads shot by
Blair (Marlo Thomas), a voraciously intense fashion photographer
who knows all about taking pictures but nothing about what they
represent. Finally, there's Joe's friend Bob (Maxwell Caulfield), a
smirky, sex-obsessed type on the prowl for a genuine blonde. Using
a sharp satirical eye, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times,
Tom DiCillio ``directed this shrewd comedy with a sharp notion of
exactly what he wants to skewer.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1997. Paramount. $29.99. 101 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Capitaine Conan
</P>
<P>
   In Bertrand Tavernier's film, the fiery, war-loving Conan
(Philippe Torreton) has trouble accepting the fact that World War I
is at an end and that he must disband his French irregulars
fighting on in the Balkans. Providing a temperamental and
philosophical counterpoint is the intellectual Lieutenant Norbert
(Samuel Le Bihan), the story's resident ethicist. While a hand-held
camera probes everywhere during trench warfare, memorably ambiguous
characters carry out an elaborate moral inquiry in a ``vast yet
subtle film'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1996. Kino. $79.95. 130 minutes. French with English subtitles.
No rating.
</P>
<P>
   Soul in the Hole
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn streets are ingrained in the brand of basketball and
the people who play it in Danielle Gardner's pulsating documentary.
At the center of the story are the blustering Kenny Jones,
organizer and patriarch of Kenny's Kings, and his star guard Ed
(Booger) Smith. A tireless self-promoter, Jones is macho mother hen
to his players off the court and their loud, crude advocate on it.
Booger, on the other hand, coolly slides by and for a short time
becomes the New York playground prize of an Arizona junior college.
Soon, though, he's back in Brooklyn, swallowed up by the big city
from which he came in a film that lacks the sociological impact of
``Hoop Dreams'' and ``remains predominantly upbeat and utterly
nonjudgmental'' (Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1997. Xenon. $59.99. 100 minutes. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   Homegrown
</P>
<P>
   When Malcolm (John Lithgow), an affluent grower of marijuana, is
shot dead, his three stooges (Billy Bob Thornton, Hank Azaria and
Ryan Phillippe) scoop up all the weed they can carry and flee to
Lucy (Kelly Lynch), who is the operation's packager. Later the trio
notices that the entire crop still stands unmolested by rippers
(thieves) and ripe for the selling. From then on in Stephen
Gyllenhaal's film, everybody has ``a high old time huffing and
puffing through this happy sermon on the wages of greed'' (Lawrence
Van Gelder). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. 101 minutes. R. Release date:
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   STRAIGHT TO VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   NANOOK OF THE NORTH. Long a staple in the silent-film public
domain, Robert Flaherty's famous 1920 documentary (or photoplay, as
it was called then) about the hardships of an Eskimo hunter and his
family in the Hudson Bay region of Canada has undergone a
cutting-edge modernization with its first digitally mastered
edition. Kino. $24.95. 70 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   THE BRIDGE. During the last few days of World War II in Europe,
the Nazis rounded up seven teen-age boys from a high school, threw
them into uniform and sent them out to defend a bridge in the path
of the advancing Allies. Actually, the Germans had planned to
withdraw them before the attack arrived and blow up the bridge, but
the sergeant who knew that information was killed before he could
so inform the students, who are left to be mowed down. It's not
pretty. If combat scenes in ``Saving Private Ryan'' are
stomach-churning, Bernhard Wicki's film, Bosley Crowther wrote in
The New York Times, ``has let us have it right between the eyes.''
1961. VCI. $19.98. 102 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL RIDES OUT. That's the English title for ``The Devil's
Bride,'' as it's known in the United States, one of the better
films from Britain's Hammer Studios. When young Simon gets involved
with a Satanic cult ruled by the malicious Mocata, the Duc de
Richelieu _ despite his title, this is a modern drama _ springs to
the rescue with a potent ritual (and it had better work). 1968.
Anchor Bay. $14.98. 95 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
