<HEADLINE>
`MIDSOMER MURDERS': THAT PROFITABLE PROPHET COMMUNED WITH DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Strange things are afoot again in the Buckinghamshire village of
Midsomer,  &QL; 
this time at the Lodge of the Golden Wind Horse. That's a comfy
commune whose paying customers hope to be transported to a higher
spiritual plane. Trouble is, some people there are leaving this
lower plane rather abruptly. Dead, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Well, this series isn't called ``Midsomer Murders'' for nothing.
Dark mysteries lurk beneath the bright blue skies. But Chief
Inspector Tom Barnaby is determined to straighten things out. He
always does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death in Disguise,'' this two-part tale of old-fashioned
deception under New Age trappings, is the third of five A&AMP;E
``Midsomer'' dramas, based on the novels of Caroline Graham. The
first hour of this charmingly lightweight diversion begins at 10
Friday night, with the loose ends tied into a conclusion next
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Barnaby (John Nettles) is first summoned to the lodge by one of
its residents, May Cuttle (Judy Cornwell), a dotty, cello-playing
woman of a certain age. One of the commune's two founders, William
Carter (Robert Pickavance), has taken a fatal plunge down a flight
of stairs after a loud argument with the other founder, Ian Craigie
(Michael Feast), the long-haired mystic known to his followers as
the Master.
</P>
<P>
   A tragic accident? Barnaby wonders, although his eager young
aide, Sgt. Troy (Daniel Casey), is not inclined to see foul play.
Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But as Barnaby begins to discover, some of the people seeking
enlightenment at the lodge are also seeking to escape from life's
complications. That includes Suhami (Anna Bolt), who turns out to
be an heiress, the very estranged 18-year-old daughter of a nasty
tycoon (Miles Anderson), who makes the mistake of showing up at the
lodge for a visit and further tarnishes the tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   And what a coincidence! Another resident, Trixie (Tilly
Blackwood), is the tycoon's discarded girlfriend. ``We had a
zoological fling,'' he snorts to the inspector. ``It lasted three
days.'' She hasn't forgiven him, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Master, who started the commune looking for
profit but has begun to warm to his role as prophet. Alas, he, too,
is ``astrally harvested,'' as one of his followers puts it,
dispatched with the knife used to carve the evening's nut roast.
Vegetarian diet, you understand.
</P>
<P>
   As all the two-dimensional characters bluster about, nearly
tripping over the red herrings planted in the script, the
three-dimensional Barnaby looks for answers, earnestly determined
to make sense of it all. You can try to sort things out before he
does, or let your mind fall into step with him. Either way, the
time will fly.
</P>
<P>
   Nettles' portrayal of the decent detective, rounded out by brief
glimpses of his home life with a loving wife and daughter, keeps
the proceedings from floating away on a cloud of froth. Not that
there's a serious moment in these two hours. This is not memorable
drama, spine-chilling melodrama or arch satire. But it is a
restorative trip to the country.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it includes a bit of death. But that's life.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MIDSOMER MURDERS: Death in Disguise'
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E, Friday night at 10 and next Friday at 10
</P>
<P>
   Written for television by Douglas Watkinson and based on the
books by Caroline Graham. Baz Taylor, director; Brien True-May and
Betty Willingate, producers; Veronica Castillo, associate producer;
Nigel Waters, director of photography; music by Jim Parker.
Produced by Bentley Productions in association with A&AMP;E. Delia
Fine, A&AMP;E executive in charge.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: John Nettles (Inspector Barnaby), Daniel Casey (Sgt.
Troy), Judy Cornwell (May Cuttle), Michael Feast (Ian Craigie),
Anna Bolt (Suhami), Miles Anderson (Guy Gamelin), Tilly Blackwood
(Trixie) and Robert Pickavance (William Carter).
</P>
</TEXT>
