<SLUG> BC-PERSON-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I MARRIED A STRANGE PERSON!': MIND OVER MATTER, LITERALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Kerry's new husband, Grant, begins doing peculiar things _
like making a swarm of insects suddenly appear around his
mother-in-law's head _ Kerry begins to wonder exactly what kind of
man she has just vowed to spend her life with. Is he a robot, she
wonders, the anti-Christ, a space alien, the Messiah? ``Oh, no,
it's worse than I thought,'' she concludes. ``He's working for the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   He isn't, actually. It's just that Smilecorp, the conglomerate
that wants to steal Grant's newfound superpowers, has its own
private army, so there are a lot of soldiers and tanks around.
</P>
<P>
   You could, however, watch all of Bill Plympton's animated film
``I Married a Strange Person!'' without figuring that out. The
story is a standard linear narrative, but the filmmaker seems
reluctant to spell out the plot developments clearly.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the movie, Grant, a square-jawed hunk of a
cartoon nice guy, develops a bump on the back of his neck. The bump
gives him the power to make things happen just by thinking about
them. This includes turning his wife into any woman he's
fantasizing about during lovemaking. Soon he's on a television talk
show, billed as an illusionist. As a result, Smilecorp's chief
executive officer, the head of its army and a washed-up comedian
named Solly all try to get their hands on Grant's bump. The chase
is on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plympton is clearly an inventive animator with great visual
style, including the animation equivalent of terrific camera
angles, but feature film may not be the best form for appreciating
his talents. An hour and 54 minutes is an awful lot of
shape-shifting humans, graphic sex scenes (sometimes between
normally inanimate objects), bloody body parts and exploding lawn
ornaments at one sitting.
</P>
<P>
   Plympton's animation is aggressive, to say the least, sometimes
grotesque and definitely not to everyone's taste. The film begins
with a pair of flying ducks having sex in midair and ends with what
looks like a woman tying a man's hands together with his own
intestine. On the gentler side, Grant also has the power to stop a
bullet speeding toward his head by turning it into a hero sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `I MARRIED A STRANGE PERSON!'
</P>
<P>
   Produced, animated and directed by Bill Plympton; director of
photography, John Donnelly; edited by Anthony Arcidi; music by
Maureen McElheron; released by Lions Gate Films.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 114 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH THE VOICES OF: Charis Michelsen (Kerry) and Tom Larson
(Grant).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
