<SLUG> BC-TROOPS-TEACHERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUALITY TEACHERS EMERGING FROM U.S. MILITARY TROOPS, SURVEYS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A five-year program called Troops to Teachers that
has sent more than 3,000 veterans to the classroom has proved to be
a boon for states needing good educators, according to surveys
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As it was downsizing the military, the Defense Department
started the TTT program in 1994 to help people find second careers
in teaching. Two federal grants of $65 million each funded the
program, which has placed teachers in 48 states.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, California, Florida and Virginia have benefited most from
the program, with each hiring more than 200 vets. The program is
scheduled to end in October 1999, according to its director, John
Gantz.
</P>
<P>
   The surveys of more than 1,100 teachers and 380 school
principals found that overwhelmingly they have been satisfied with
the program. The teacher survey was conducted by the National
Center for Education Information (NCEI), a Washington-based
research organization, and the administrator poll was taken by TTT
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-one percent of the teachers who responded said they liked
their jobs, and about 70 percent of the administrators who hired
the veterans ranked them ``among the best'' teachers or ``well
above average'' or ``above average.''
</P>
<P>
   Eden Reyes, a former Air Force computer operator who teaches
fifth grade at Landrum Elementary in San Benito, Texas., about 10
miles northwest of Brownsville, said at a news conference here that
his military experience has helped him in teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes said the most important skill he learned in his 20-year
military career was how to be a positive role model. Many of his
pupils are growing up in one-parent families, he said, and many
``have brothers, fathers, uncles in prison. From me they need to
see there is a different way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that in teaching he has also relied on his experiences
working with computers, maintaining discipline, staying calm in
difficult situations and living in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   In social studies, Reyes said, he shares with his students
first-hand knowledge about European countries. That excites his
students, he added, making ``them feel like they, too, have the
potential to one day visit those places.'' As a south Texas native,
he said, he wants his students to know that ``the sky's the
limit.''
</P>
<P>
   George C. Willett, director of the Washington state TTT program,
reported that teachers in the program often say, ``This is
something I've always wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   John Osteen, principal of Lake Taylor High school in Norfolk,
Va., said of one teacher he hired from the program: ``He demanded
the best from every student without acting like the stereotypical
drill sergeant.''
</P>
<P>
   C. Emily Feistritzer, director of the education information
center, said 90 percent of teachers in the TTT program are male and
noted that the field they have entered is dominated by females.
More of the TTT teachers _ 29 percent _ are from minority groups,
compared with about 10 percent generally in the field, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The reports said 29 percent of TTT teachers are mathematics
instructors, compared with 13 percent of teachers nationally. Ten
percent of the TTT veterans are special education teachers, double
the national rate. Thirty-eight percent of TTT educators teach
biology, chemistry and physics compared with 26 percent of regular
public school teachers in those fields.
</P>
<P>
   Feistritzer said former military personnel are also more willing
to teach in ``combat zones'' such as the inner-city or rural towns.
Twenty-four percent of TTT instructors are in the inner-city
compared with 16 percent of regular teachers, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
