<SLUG> BC-TV-PAX-545-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FAMILY-FRIENDLY' PAX GOES FOR A PIECE OF THE TV PIE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The symbolic birth of the PAX TV network is a ripe slice of
business legerdemain.
</P>
<P>
   It's late in the 1970s. Lowell ``Bud'' Paxson owns a little AM
radio station in Florida. An advertising client owes him a thousand
dollars. The client refuses to pay but instead offers Paxson an
overstock supply of 112 electric can openers. Paxson loads them
into his van.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, on his radio station, Paxson seized the
microphone and offered the can openers to listeners for $9.75
apiece. The station's five phone lines lit up. In 15 minutes, the
can openers were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson parlayed that day's revelation into television's Home
Shopping Network, then into a string of penny-ante UHF TV stations,
and now into a weird network that will crackle to life at noon
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Now mega-wealthy and a born-again Christian, Paxson is seeking a
``family-friendly'' niche in the broadcasting spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   That supposedly means no gratuitous sex, violence or raw
language. Accordingly, Paxson has stocked his new network with a
few sterilized original shows and such off-network reruns as
``Touched by an Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   PAX TV is expected to reach about 70 percent of the nation's TV
homes in the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The network's launch is backed by a $25 million advertising
campaign, and the goal is to gain a 1 percent share of the national
viewing audience within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone tuned in at noon Monday will see, barring a Paxson
disaster, the debut of an informational and celebrity-interview
show called ``Great Day America.'' You get the impression that the
whole PAX TV audience will be people who wake up at sunrise,
stretch their arms and say to themselves, ``It's a great day,
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is a bit odd because the president of the new network,
working under chairman Paxson, is Jeff Sagansky, the sad-eyed
former programming chief at CBS. Bud Paxson is an outsider still
based in Florida. Sagansky is a Hollywood insider. Paxson is a
tub-thumping Christian. Sagansky is a Jew.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels he has this calling from God,'' Sagansky recently
said of his new boss. ``I don't feel the same calling.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's Sagansky who'll oversee such original programming as
``It's a Miracle,'' a studio-based show about the power of faith,
and ``Cloud Nine,'' the umbrella title for kiddie cartoons hosted
by a trio of winged teen angels.
</P>
<P>
   Those are weekend shows. The weeknight prime-time schedule is
centered on reruns of ``Touched by an Angel,'' ``Dr. Quinn,
Medicine Woman'' and ``Diagnosis Murder.'' The likes of ``Eight Is
Enough,'' ``The Hogan Family,'' ``Here's Lucy'' and ``The Love
Boat'' are also sprinkled around the PAX TV schedule.
</P>
<P>
   You could say that PAX TV had its official introduction to
network life even before its launch, when CBS filed suit earlier
this month to stop production of a ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman''
special for PAX TV. CBS owns the show, which it canceled in May,
and claims the special is unauthorized. So already PAX TV is duking
it out in litigation with the source of much of its programming.
</P>
<P>
   Not even on the air yet, and already PAX TV is Touched by a
Lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
