<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOGARTH-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM HOGARTH ART REVIEW: SHARP EYE (AND WIT) FOR FOIBLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (bl)  
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not many visual artists view their work as plays or novels, but
that was how the English satirist and social critic William Hogarth
(1697-1756) saw his. He spun out scathing sagas in the form of
paintings and engravings, produced in series like the famous
eight-part ``Rake's Progress'' (1735) and the six-chapter
``Marriage a la Mode'' (1745).
</P>
<P>
   Hogarth, whose gift for genre helped to breed the first really
English style of painting since the Middle Ages, was part of the
great era of English satire. Manners, morals, culture and politics
came under his comic and cynical scrutiny, and he compared his work
to the wittily moralizing novels of his contemporaries Henry
Fielding (on whom he had considerable influence) and Daniel Defoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have endeavored to treat my subjects as a dramatic writer,''
Hogarth wrote. ``My picture is my stage and men and women my
players, who by means of certain actions and gestures are to
exhibit a dumb show.'' Using a wealth of often symbolic detail, he
translated the novelistic into visual terms. Most of his prints
demand ``reading'' with the same focused attention as a meaty book.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Age of Hogarth: Paintings and Prints from the Collection
of Earle W. Newton, '38,'' at the Mead Art Museum at Amherst
College, celebrates, slightly belatedly, the 300th anniversary of
Hogarth's birth in 1697 and provides an engaging precis of his
work. Included are a selection from his larger thematic groups of
engravings, lesser-known single prints and a few paintings,
although only one is by Hogarth himself. The rest are by followers
or contemporaries, including two fine portraits by Joseph Wright of
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The material is drawn from the extensive holdings of Newton, an
alumnus of the college who went on to found American Heritage
Magazine and to nurture a lifelong interest in the Georgian period
and Anglo-American history.
</P>
<P>
   Hogarth's use of novelistic detail runs riot in ``A Rake's
Progress'' (probably the best-known of his works today because of
its reprise as an opera by Igor Stravinsky). As was his custom, he
began it as a series of canvases, partly inspired by French rococo
and Dutch genre painting, from which he made engravings for popular
dissemination. (People followed prints in the 18th century almost
the way they do, say, episodes of Masterpiece Theater today.)
</P>
<P>
   It tells the story of Tom Rakewell, a cad and a spendthrift who
dissipates his miserly father's fortune in drink, gambling and
womanizing, ending up in a madhouse. Scene 3 of the series, on view
here, shows assorted wastrels carousing around a tavern table, as
the inebriated Rakewell, in disheveled finery, is groped by one
woman while another steals his watch. The sleazy company also
includes two quarreling whores (one spits a stream of gin at the
other); a ``posture woman'' who is disrobing to gyrate naked on a
platter for the guests' amusement; a pregnant street singer holding
a lewd ballad, and a prostitute who sets fire to a map of the
world. They carry on in a shambles of broken dishes and
wineglasses, spilled food and drink, defaced pictures on the walls.
The abundance of garrulous detail, with every figure socially
placed and characterized by Hogarth's brilliant graphic skills, is
overwhelming; in our age of Minimalism and jump cuts, it boggles
the mind.
</P>
<P>
   His moral outrage was more sensationally expressed in ``The Four
Stages of Cruelty'' (1750), a sort of ballad _ and, incidentally,
an animal-rights tract _ about a murderer and animal abuser, Tom
Nero, who is eventually hanged. The most grisly is the fourth
stage, ``The Reward of Cruelty,'' in which the dead Nero, the rope
still around his neck, is shown on a dissecting table being carved
up (a common practice after an execution) by a team of zealous
surgeons. As Nero's entrails are pulled out, a dog prepares to
feast on his discarded heart.
</P>
<P>
   But Hogarth was not always given to moral lessons. His single
print ``The Enraged Musician'' (1741) is pure social comedy,
mocking the distance between high culture and daily existence. In
it, an effete, bewigged musician, in royal garb and brandishing a
violin bow, leans protestingly out a window as the cacophony of
street life assails him. Peddlers bawl out their wares; an
impromptu band of music makers includes a child beating a drum; a
beggar woman cries for alms, dogs yap and a little boy urinates.
</P>
<P>
   Hogarth was not above using his graphic talents for personal
invective. The most salient example is ``The Bruiser'' (1763), done
the year before his death. It is an attack on John Wilkes, a
journalist and politician, and Charles Churchill, a cleric, both of
whom had publicly maligned him, in part for his opposition to the
popular statesman William Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve this vituperative putdown, Hogarth erased his own
cocky face from a self-portrait, ``Gulielmus Hogarth (Self-Portrait
With Pug)'' (1749), and put in its place a likeness of Churchill as
a big, drunken bear, holding a tankard of beer and drooling over
his clerical garb. Trump, the pug dog in the original self-portrait
is still there, but in this version he urinates on a copy of
Churchill's screed against Hogarth. An inset at the bottom right of
the print shows Hogarth whipping the bear, with Wilkes also present
in the guise of an ape. If all this seems slightly schoolboyish, it
was, but the work of an extraordinarily clever schoolboy who could
exploit a grudge with graphic genius.
</P>
<P>
   Hogarth's last print, ``The Bathos or Tailpiece'' (planned as a
tailpiece to all his engraved works but not published until 1764),
is a punning allegorical summation, surreal in its content and
still managing to be funny. A comment on what he viewed as the
degeneration of England and at the same time a satire on the
romantic love of ruins expressed in the fashion for ``sublime''
paintings, it depicts the figure of Time, collapsed against a
ruined column, accompanied by a broken scythe and hourglass. He
breathes out the word ``Finis'' as he expires. Surrounding him are
such played-out props as a cracked bell and broken palette, the
ruins of a church and a tavern called the World's End, and in the
distance a hanged man.
</P>
<P>
   Enemies, political embroilments and disillusionment had sapped
Hogarth's cocky ebullience, but they didn't dim a talent that,
although steeped in the manners and mores of 18th-century England,
we can still relate to. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Age of Hogarth: Paintings and Prints from the Collection
of Earle W. Newton '38'' remains at Mead Art Museum, Amherst
College, in Amherst, Mass., through Sept. 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
