<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Singletary a role model for Georgia public servants
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hugh Singletary wrote me a note about his father, Dr. H. Titus
Singletary Jr., who is critically ill with cancer in his Atlanta
home. He spent 35 of his 70 years as associate superintendent of
Georgia schools.
</P>
<P>
   His son Hugh and daughter, Anne Kinnan of Tampa, collaborated on
a tribute to their father, ending with these words: ``It's an honor
to have a role model like the one we've had. He has made such a
difference in the lives of so many. I am thankful to be a part of
his extraordinary journey.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a great journey from a Thomas County(Ga.) farm near
Thomasville, where he was born and where he first realized he
wanted to be a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in Georgia remember _ and are glad for _ the gifts
he brought to public service. At the behest of her husband, former
Gov. George Busbee, Mary Beth Busbee called me about Dr.
Singletary. Let him know while he still lives, she said, how
valuable he is to all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Singletary began as a school teacher and gradually took his
ideas for the betterment of students and teachers to the top. He
met his future wife, Emmie Lane, when they taught side by side in a
country school.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a grand office across from the Capitol,'' his daughter
wrote, ``but most of his time was spent in school classrooms and
face-to-face meetings with people in every facet of the school
system. He performed his job with passion that now seems
nonexistent in the hustle and bustle of today's workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   His family regards Dr. Singletary's ``passions'' as first his
children, then his friends, his church (Johnson Ferry Road Baptist)
and his beloved Georgia Bulldogs and Atlanta Braves. He progressed
to a great encompassing love of three grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from Georgia Southern College in Statesboro, served
four years as a drill sergeant during World War II and received his
doctorate degree from the University of Georgia. While he was
governor, former President Jimmy Carter appointed Dr. Singletary to
the office of associate superintendent of schools, a job considered
by educators to be the highest in the school system.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Singletary retired 18 years ago and promptly began serving
as principal of Woodland Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   He received many professional honors, but the work he did as a
prayer person and counselor, receiving calls from troubled people
at his church, was special and memorable.
</P>
<P>
   His children wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``We were blessed with a dad who will influence our daily life
forever. As he began to fight for his life, the week before his
grandson, Franklin, was born, he knew it would be a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extra bonus years we've had include my two brothers'
weddings, many wonderful holidays, (and) a special retreat in St.
Simons for fishing, walking the beach, and holding together the
family we deem so dear.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Busbee, who knew Dr. Singletary well and observed his
conduct of school affairs, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great leader in education in this state, as well as a
kind and compassionate gentleman. He was a very devoted family
person, and the professional awards and honors he received are too
many to enumerate.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
