<SLUG> BC-JENKINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's clear from Tamara Jenkins' new movie about adolescent
humiliations, that the writer-director has been there
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With ``Slums of Beverly Hills,'' writer-director Tamara Jenkins
turns Hollywood's obsession with teenage boys upside down: She
recalls those awkward years from a woman's perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins' movie, opening today, focuses on teenage Vivian
(Natasha Lyonne), who's coping with her nomadic, all-male family
and the humiliations of puberty. Especially when she goes from a
flat chest to a C-cup overnight.
</P>
<P>
   It's the sort of experience with which most women can identify.
Not so men. Jenkins even tripped on a gender barrier while talking
to a movie executive about ``Slums.'' He remembered what a gas it
was, as a high schooler, to ogle and ``accidentally'' bump against
girls whose breasts had developed over the summer. She remembers it
quite differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think that was like for the girls?'' she asked
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Female maturation is a very visible thing _ it's public, in a
way,'' Jenkins says of her first feature film, speaking from her
New York home. ``If an adolescent female gets breasts, it's like
they become a conversation piece for the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Slums''' witty, honest look at the issues facing Vivian isn't
for everyone. ``Some men are really unnerved by the material,'' the
director says. ``But some people feel really liberated, because
they've never seen this presented before.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just a boy-girl reaction, either. New York gossip
columnist Cindy Adams left a press screening midway through but
showed up at the reception. ``She gave me this look, like I was the
dirtiest girl she had ever seen,'' Jenkins says. ``She rolled her
eyes up and down my body like, `You little trollop.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Slums'' is a fictional take on Jenkins' own youth as the only
girl in an all-male family after her parents' divorce. ``I wanted
to revisit teenage sexuality and growing up without guidance, and
having to figure things out in this all-male environment, in this
ridiculously rich town.''
</P>
<P>
   The script's earliest form has an Atlanta connection: Jenkins
began working on the material in the mid-1980s while acting at
Theater Works in Boston, a company run by Vincent Murphy and Tim
McDonough, now faculty members in the Emory University(Ga.) theater
studies department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worshipped them!'' Jenkins exclaims. ``Tim McDonough taught
me everything. He was so generous and brilliant and insightful.''
(The Emory professors also have a connection with the new movie
``Next Stop, Wonderland.'') McDonough, who taught Jenkins at the
University of Massachusetts, introduced her to the work of
monologist Spalding Gray and others, encouraging her to try her
hand at autobiographical work. Soon enough, she was projecting
photos of her family on a Theater Works wall, telling stories about
her strip-club-running father and hat-check mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funny and mesmerizing,'' McDonough says. ``She already
had her own voice, and she used the slides in her storytelling in
an indelible way.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy remembers, ``It was so vivid to see this young woman turn
the spotlight on herself. Watching that sort of fearlessness was
one of the first times that made me think, `This is how feminism
can work.'''
</P>
<P>
   After performing that first time, Jenkins acted out a moment so
awkwardly endearing, it could be something out of her movie: ``I
made a beeline for the women's room, so Tim wouldn't find me and
tell me my show (stunk).'' (Actually, he stuck his head through the
bathroom door to congratulate her.)
</P>
<P>
   During those first performances, Jenkins discovered something
surprising: The audience cracked up. Jenkins says, ``Here I was
thinking, `Oh my God, my stories are tragic _ and they're
laughing!' It was from that I started to build a sense of what my
tone was.''
</P>
<P>
   The seriocomic tone of ``Slums'' was itself an issue with the
executives at the Fox Searchlight studio. ``They kept saying it was
a comedy, and I kept saying it was a bleak comedy,'' she recalls.
``It was hard, making them understand that something can be funny
and bleak at the same time. The truth is, this family (in the
movie) is poor, they're homeless, and this is a fractured world
they live in.'' But the movie is still very funny. And, yes, bleak.
Maybe that's what makes it feel like real life.
</P>
<P>
   THE JENKINS FILE
</P>
<P>
   -- Age: 35
</P>
<P>
   -- Home base: New York
</P>
<P>
   -- Career: ``Slums'' is Jenkins' first feature movie. She has
made two short films, ``Fugitive Love'' (1991) and ``Family
Remains'' (1993).
</P>
<P>
   -- Next project: ``I've started to do some writing, but it's in
the pre-verbal stages.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
