<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5991 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREAN-MEMORIAL-$ADV3     08-27 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREAN-MEMORIAL-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE YEARS AFTER OPENING, KOREAN WAR MEMORIAL IS FALLING APART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For U.S. veterans who fought in the Korean War, a
memorial on the Mall in the nation's capital was a long time
coming.
</P>
<P>
   President Ronald Reagan was in the White House when Congress
authorized construction in 1986. President George Bush broke ground
in 1992, and President Clinton dedicated the memorial in 1995, 42
years after the end of the bloody conflict that killed 36,913
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after only three years, a section of the memorial is
crumbling and the Army Corps of Engineers estimates it will take a
year and $2 million to fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this memorial was dedicated in 1995, it was intended to
be a lasting and fitting tribute to the bravery and sacrifice of
our troops who fought in the `forgotten war,''' said Sen. Paul
Sarbanes, D-Md. ``Unfortunately, just three years after its
dedication, the monument is not lasting and is no longer fitting.''
</P>
<P>
   The memorial has two main sections. One area known as ``the pool
of remembrance'' now looks like a highway construction site,
complete with trenches, wheelbarrows, sandbags, fluorescent orange
caution cones and piles of gravel. The pool and grove currently are
blocked off by a high wooden fence. Behind the fence, the pool is
dry.
</P>
<P>
   As originally built, the pool section consisted of a large
circular pond about 50 feet across surrounded by a grove of lush
Linden trees embedded in a stone walkway. The pool was intended to
create a zone of contemplation, with the rush of the water blotting
out the sounds of aircraft and traffic.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's what the designers wanted.
</P>
<P>
   However, faulty irrigation and drainage systems are blamed for
killing the Linden trees, which have been removed, leaving 40
gaping holes. Pavement stones that were fitted around the base of
the trees have been dug up because they settled and became
pedestrian hazards.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has the attention of the National Park Service,
which maintains the memorial, the American Battle Monuments
Commission, which sponsored the memorial's construction, and the
Army Corps of Engineers, the construction managers.
</P>
<P>
   The other section, the ``field of service,'' is an eerie tableau
of 19 life-size stainless steel statues depicting a battle-weary
squad on patrol. The squad has members from all U.S. military
branches. A gaunt GI wearing a rain poncho is bringing up the rear.
He cautions visitors with an outstretched hand at his side in a
``stop'' position, his face contorted as if about to speak.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the GIs is a long, black granite wall with more
than 2,400 etched images of U.S. servicemembers. On the other side
is a granite headstone listing the 22 nations that gave support to
South Korea during the 1950-1953 conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Sarbanes complained to the Senate last month that the site's 1.3
million annual visitors have to cope with construction hassles
``instead of experiencing the full effect of the memorial.''
</P>
<P>
   The condition of the memorial, located just east of the Lincoln
Memorial and south of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial, angers
veterans groups that helped raise $13.2 million in private funds to
construct it. About $1 million in tax money was used for the
original project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned about the deterioration,'' said Phil Budahn,
a spokesman for the American Legion, the largest veterans group
with 2.9 million members. ``There are bugs in any major
construction project, but the bugs here are like cockroaches. They
can't seem to get rid of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Problems began cropping soon after the memorial opened.
According to the Army Corps of Engineers, the pool sprang leaks and
became clogged with leaves; the lighting system didn't provide
enough illumination at night, causing a pedestrian hazard; and
visitors slipped on smooth walkway stones.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these problems have been fixed. The cost: about $1.2
million. But by far the most costly problems are the pool and
grove.
</P>
<P>
   The underground irrigation system that fed the trees never
worked properly, according to William Lecky of Cooper-Lecky
Architects, the firm that designed the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   By the time that problem was discovered, the trees had been
deprived of water. After the irrigation system was fixed, the
underground drainage system that took water away from the trees
broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, the trees didn't get water during very hot periods.
Then they were flooded and the water couldn't be drained away so
they drowned,'' said Lecky. ``As a result, the trees in the grove
around the pool all died.''
</P>
<P>
   The Corps of Engineers estimates that it will cost $2 million to
fix the pool and grove and replace the trees, a tab Sarbanes wants
taxpayers to pick up. The lawmaker sponsored an amendment to next
year's defense appropriations bill directing the Army to find the
money to fix the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Conley, a spokesman for the American Battle Monuments
Commission in Arlington, Va., said that without the money, repairs
might have to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't finish off the project,'' Conley said.
</P>
<P>
   The Corps of Engineers is trying to determine whether faulty
design or construction are to blame for the problems. As a result,
officials are considering whether to file a claim against
Cooper-Lecky or against the construction company. Laurel, Md.-based
R.J. Crowley Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't reached any kind of a decision yet. There hasn't
been any type of claim formed at this point,'' said Doug Garman, a
spokesman for the Army Corps of Engineers in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Lecky asserted that the design was sound. Crowley executives did
not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Garman said the Corps is hopeful that the
repairs will be complete by next July, in time to commemorate the
50th anniversary of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Haupricht, 48, from Toledo, Ohio, who mans a veterans
information stand near the memorial, isn't so sure. ``It takes them
so long to do anything around here,'' Haupricht said. ``If
construction goes on another year, it'll have taken longer than the
Korean War.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1757EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
