<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERWAR-PHOTO-REVIEW     08-27 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERWAR-PHOTO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHY REVIEW: IMAGERY OF SLUMBER AND DANGER BEFORE THE
APOCALYPSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the first images you see in ``Modern Times:
Photography Between the Two World Wars'' in the Howard Gilman
Gallery at the Metropolitan Museum of Art is Henri
Cartier-Bresson's 1933 picture of a Spanish boy with his back
arched in front of a wall splattered with paint or blood. ``Has
this child been stabbed or is he in the throes of an ecstatic
dance?'' the text on the wall asks. ``Actually he is arching his
back to catch sight of a ball.'' Somehow, knowing the boy's real
situation does not change the atmosphere of danger and ecstasy. The
picture still invites a momentary panic that the boy is about to
drop dead.
</P>
<P>
   A similar feeling pervades Ilse Bing's 1936 photograph of a
jumping horse. The horse is on its hind legs about to leap into
white flames while a few men stand around blithely unaware of the
danger. The photograph was taken at a circus in New York City in
1936. It's benign enough. But isn't it also possible that Bing, a
German photographer, was commenting metaphorically about where
Europe was heading in 1936?
</P>
<P>
   Walking through this exhibition of 50 Surrealist,
Constructivist, Bauhaus and De Stijl photographs from German,
Russian, American, Mexican, English, Italian and Dutch
photographers in the 1920s and 1930s is like stumbling into a
warehouse full of metaphors about the fate of humanity. Although
most of the pictures are straight and unmanipulated (save for a few
of Man Ray's Rayographs and some negative prints by Laszlo
Moholy-Nagy), they are far from straight in effect. Just about
every one appears to contain a barely concealed portent.
</P>
<P>
   There are way too many images of humans leaping and falling (or
about to fall) for this theme to be accidental. Lux Feininger has
two exuberant pictures of dancers titled ``Euyrythmy, or Jump over
the Bauhaus.'' Man Ray's picture of Jacqueline Goddard, printed as
a negative image, catches her with long white hair flying straight
above her head as if she had just jumped into deep water. Alexander
Rodchenko's picture of a student sunbathing on a window ledge in
Moscow is a picture of both leisure and impending suicide. There
is, as the wall text points out, ``dynamism latent even in a body
at rest.'' It might fall.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the falling pictures in the show, though, the most
impressive is Willi Ruge's 1931 shot called ``The Photographer,''
showing Ruge's own legs and feet dangling over an aerial view of
Berlin during his seven-minute parachute jump.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures in this exhibition suggest that between the wars,
photographers were unusually attracted to liminal states between
ecstasy and danger, leaping and falling, life and death. In
addition to all the leapers and fallers, for example, the show has
far more than its share of sleepers and dolls. Once again, this is
no accident. The Surrealists went looking for them, and when they
did not find them they made do with what they found: dead men,
artists with shut eyes, pigs' legs, sticks on a beach.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1931 photo, Manuel Alvarez Bravo caught a man dozing on a
ledge, one hand under his head and another lodged dreamily in his
crotch. His sleep is the kind that Andre Breton envied: ``I would
like to sleep, in order to surrender myself to the dreamer.''
</P>
<P>
   But the deepest sleeper in the show is a dead man. In 1922, when
Marcel Proust died, Jean Cocteau told Man Ray to take some
pictures, and he did. The sheets in the photograph are white and
Proust looks young and tired with his dark hair and dark circles
under his eyes. ``Those who have seen this profile of calm, of
order, of plenitude,'' Cocteau wrote, ``will never forget the
spectacle of an unbelievable recording device come to a stop,
becoming an art object: a masterpiece of repose next to a heap of
notebooks where our friend's genius continues to live on like the
wristwatch of a dead soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   This quotation, pointing out the paradoxical proximity of a dead
body and the live notebooks, suggests that what the Surrealists
liked about sleepers and dreamers was closely related to what they
liked about dolls and mannequins: they all exist on the slender
ledge between consciousness and unconsciousness, between the
animate and the inanimate.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Bellmer made a virtual career out of freaky-looking dolls
with too many arms and legs. One of his works in the show, an
illustration for Paul Eluard's poems ``Les Jeux de la Poupee,'' is
a picture of a headless doll hanging in a closet with a surfeit of
polka-dotted legs pouring out of its torso, terminating in a
cluster of patent-leather shoes. The other, from a tiny book he
made, is a photograph of one of Bellmer's dolls standing in front
of a blueprint for her design and looking petulantly away from the
ghostly image of her designer, Bellmer himself.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, many Surrealist dolls had to bear an awful lot of
symbolic weight. But not all of them. In 1932, Claude Cahun (Lucy
Schwob) took a picture of a doll she traced in the sand on the
beach. The doll has a feathered cap, a spoon for a hand and a bit
of a phallic electrical cord sticking out of its body. It is
clearly in danger of being washed away soon. Dora Maar also made
fun of the craze for human stand-ins. Her ``Portrait of Pere Ubu,''
the fat monster from Alfred Jarry's play ``Ubu Roi,'' is actually a
picture of a baby armadillo taken very close up. You can see the
scaleson his nose, his old lidded eyes and his begging paws.
</P>
<P>
   While the Surrealists were obsessing over their dolls, monsters
and body parts, the Bauhaus and De Stijl photographers were
developing their own fetishes: girders, buildings, bridges and
cities. Laszlo Moholy-Nagy's reverse print of the spiral staircase
and girders of the Transborder Bridge in Marseilles and Ernst
Scheel's gasometer, a picture of the interior of a great white dome
with a fragile ladder leading up to it, are, in one sense, just big
built objects. But their grandeur makes them emblems of a modern
world order, one that seems, at least in retrospect, vertiginous,
even precarious.
</P>
<P>
   It is generally assumed that Constructivist, Bauhaus and De
Stijl artists, who were keen on geometry, rational design and
erector sets, have nothing in common with the Surrealists, who were
keen on sleep, irrationality and dolls. But in this show the border
between them begins to erode.
</P>
<P>
   Has the curator, Pierre Apraxine, somehow managed to find
photographs that break the rules, or has the suggestiveness of
Surrealism, with its metaphorical imagery, infected the more sober
modernist pictures? Whatever the case, here the two approaches seem
uncannily united. And their common ground is the ledge high above
the city.
</P>
<P>
   One photograph by Moholy-Nagy brings this out quite clearly. We
see a building with pure white walls and black squares for windows.
In one of the upper floors, a man is hanging outside the window
stenciling delicate, inconsequential designs around the frame. It's
all very gay until you notice that the man is supported only by a
wooden plank resting on the sill. Is it an ingenious suspension
device or a small diving board?
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern Times: Photography between the Two World Wars'' remains
at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, Fifth Avenue at 82nd Street, New
York, through Oct. 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
