<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Aug. 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tropical storm Bonnie will plod northeastward near the Middle
Atlantic coastline Friday. Its strongest winds, with gusts to
hurricane force, will remain over the open Atlantic to the east of
the storm center. However, gusty winds from the northeast with
speeds to gale force will buffet the immediate shores from
southeast Virginia to southern New Jersey. Rough seas will produce
considerable beach erosion.
</P>
<P>
   As tropical air circulating around the storm is drawn toward the
northwest, it will encounter a stalled front along the Northeast
coast. This will be the lifting mechanism for the sultry air. The
result will be bands of heavy rain that will push northward ahead
of Bonnie's path. The eastern sections of the New York City region
as well as southern New England should notice rain. Flooding is
possible as several inches of rain fall. There will be a distinct
edge to this precipitation shield so that areas just to the west
will see little rain.
</P>
<P>
   The interior Northeast will be sunny and pleasantly warm and the
Southeast will be brighter, but rather hot. A few tropical showers
will drench southern Florida. Hurricane Danielle should strengthen
as it passes well north of Hispaniola.
</P>
<P>
   Thundershowers will attend a warm front in the Great Lakes and
western Ohio Valley. A push of drier, very warm air into the Plains
will be accompanied by active breezes and sunny skies.
</P>
<P>
   A return flow of humid air into the southern Rockies will
trigger afternoon thunderstorms. The vast majority of the West will
be sunny and hot with record high temperatures in the Great Basin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Focus: Stalling Tactic &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, the center of Tropical Storm Bonnie was
located 40 miles south of Elizabeth City, N.C., about 200 to 300
miles short of the more progressive ocean position that computers
had, about 30 hours earlier, predicted. The forecast was based on
the assumption that speedy high-altitude winds from the southwest
would capture the storm and steer it rapidly northeast. But
hurricanes can modify their environment and alter steering winds.
As Hurricane Bonnie moved north, its upper-level circulation of air
offset westerly steering winds, causing the storm to stall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
