<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AHAB'S-WIFE-ART-REVIE     08-27 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AHAB'S-WIFE-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: AHAB'S WIFE, IGNORED IN `MOBY-DICK,' TRIES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEN JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Near the beginning of ``Moby-Dick,'' Herman
Melville's epic tale of Faustian obsession, the narrator, Ishmael,
learns about the man under whom he's about to embark on a
three-year whaling cruise. It seems that Captain Ahab might be
dangerously depressive, even a little crazy. But, declares
Ishmael's informant, Captain Peleg, it is ``better to sail with a
moody good captain than a laughing bad one.'' To which he adds,
``Besides, my boy, he has a wife _ not three voyages wedded _ a
sweet, resigned girl.''
</P>
<P>
   This single reference to the doomed captain's spouse has
furnished the conceptual basis for ``Ahab's Wife or the Whale,'' a
performance to be presented at the Snug Harbor Cultural Center on
Staten Island from Sept. 17 to 20, and for an exhibition of
contemporary art now on view there called just ``Ahab's Wife.'' The
latter is supplemented by prints from Melville's collection and a
presentation of scrimshaw.
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonderfully suggestive idea. How would Melville's
all-male yarn read from a woman's point of view? Imagine a feminist
sequel to the novel or a Spielberg movie in which Sigourney Weaver
sets out to recover her husband's body, redeem his soul and face
down the monster whale.
</P>
<P>
   How the idea will be realized in the performance, which was
conceived and developed by the sculptor Ellen Driscoll, the poet
Tom Sleigh and the choreographers Amy Spencer and Richard Colton,
remains to be seen. Though variously interesting, the visual art
exhibition falls short of hopes aroused by the title, in part
because only two artists deal directly with Melvillian themes and
only one of those, Ms. Driscoll, explores the idea of Ahab's wife.
Ultimately, it's hard to say who Mrs. Ahab is or what she means.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Driscoll's work, which is the core of the show, consists of
three dozen paintings and prints on paper, several sculptures and
some models of props for the performance.
</P>
<P>
   The paper items, all modest in size, are made in a brushy,
neo-Expressionist style that calls to mind the murkier paintings of
Francesco Clemente. Certain symbolic motifs recur _ a female figure
in a hoop skirt, a globe, whale eyes, spirals _ and there's a
portentousness about them that's not inappropriate for Melville's
allegorical grandiosity. But overall, these vague, fragmentary
musings add up to no coherent narrative or symbolic vision.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Driscoll's sculptures have rough little plastic figures
isolated from one another in glass vessels, implying some unknown
story of emotional estrangement. Only ``The Eye of the Whale,'' in
which one of these figures crouches over a big glass eye embedded
in an oval steel table, comes close to a capturing the viscerally
cosmic imagery that the novel evokes. Rough models for props, like
a paper hoop skirt bearing a map of the world, shed no more light
on Ahab's wife's character, story or meaning, and one is left
feeling that there's some powerful visual work yet to be made of
this idea.
</P>
<P>
   French sculptor Driss Sans-Arcidet, on the other hand, addresses
the novel (though not Ahab's wife) too literally. He has
constructed a dark corridor of blood-red walls to which he has
attached wooden relief assemblages, one for each of the novel's 135
chapters. The panels are butted edge to edge, creating an
enveloping patchwork environment.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, Sans-Arcidet's devotion of two and a half years to
this project, including reading as well as art-making, suggests an
Ahab-like single-mindedness, but the assemblages express little by
way of tragic hubris or madness. They consist of great quantities
of model-scale nautical bric-a-brac _ toy boats, rigging, fishing
gear, sharks' jaws _ glued to panels, Cubist style, and given an
overall antique patina. It produces more the atmosphere of a
seafood restaurant than the spirit of sublime adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing one gallery, Janet Gillespie and Arden Scott produce
works that relate to ``Moby-Dick'' only insofar as they have to do
with boats and the sea. Ms. Gillespie makes finely painted,
smallish surrealistic pictures filled edge to edge with turbulent
seas upon which, in some cases, small empty boats are tossed. In an
earlier work, farm plows sink through the frothy surface into dark
green depths. Ms. Scott fashions sculptures in the form of
abstracted antique boats using twiggy branches, twine-wrapped
steel, paper or copper screening. At best, these works have a
stately formality.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining two artists, Sam Christian Holmes of Baltimore and
Arnold Schalks of the Netherlands, are each working on public
artworks that are unfinished. Holmes will build a gate
incorporating imagery suggested by discussions with residents of
the Richmond Terrace Apartments, a public housing project. An
exhibition of materials, photographs, drawings and text arising
from this effort is on view. Schalks, in collaboration with New
York artist Ron Rocco, is constructing a computer-equipped kiosk
near the ferry terminals that will be open from Tuesday until Sept.
14.
</P>
<P>
   The prints from Melville's collection include small, finely
engraved copies of drawings of disasters at sea by an English
academician named C. Stanfield and a set of engravings of paintings
by J.M.W. Turner. Though modestly scaled, these images vividly
express an experience of the ocean that most late-20th-century
people can only dimly imagine.
</P>
<P>
   If you go to Snug Harbor, which is worth a trip no matter what's
on view, don't miss the exhibitions of scrimshaw and prints. Some
of the objects intricately carved from whalebone by unknown sailors
_ a magical box ornamented by two upright miniature columns ending
in fists holding snakes, for example _ have as much formal and
imaginative ingenuity as anything contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahab's Wife'' remains at the Snug Harbor Cultural Center, 1000
Richmond Terrace, Staten Island, New York City, through Oct. 4.
Open on Wednesdays through Sundays noon to 5 p.m. Information about
the performances, scheduled Sept. 17- 20: (718) 448-8534.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
