<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHERRY-THEATER-REVIEW     08-27 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHERRY-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEKHOV UPDATED: GOT A PROBLEM WITH THAT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By ANITA GATES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Honestly, the idea of chasing actors across
Washington Square Park as they performed Chekhov was not all that
appealing. That's the sort of thing the Gorilla Repertory Theater
Company does. The actors perform a play in some outdoor setting,
but when the scene shifts, nobody puts a new set in place; instead,
the actors just move to a different area of the park, courtyard or
whatever. The audience follows.
</P>
<P>
   So it came as a great relief to learn that the Gorilla Rep's new
production of ``The Cherry Orchard'' required only one migration by
audience and cast, to the orchard itself for Act II. Acts I, III
and IV take place in the Ranevsky family's parlor _ represented
here by Oriental rugs, one chair, a tea cart, a bookcase and an
empty gilt frame nailed to a tree. The audience sits on the ground,
on fairly comfortable skateboard hills.
</P>
<P>
   The next surprise comes in Act I when a Ranevsky daughter
announces, ``Mama's still not playing with a full deck.'' The
script also includes the lines ``Get over it,'' ``Okey-dokey,''
``Close, but no cigar'' and ``You got a problem with that?''
</P>
<P>
   This is definitely the Cliff's Notes version of ``The Cherry
Orchard,'' and I mean that in a nice way. Longtime devotees of
Chekhov who have seen the most experienced theatrical companies in
the world perform his work and who revisit his plays to reflect on
the universality of his meaning should not attend. Reducing ``The
Cherry Orchard'' (the playwright's last work, written in 1904) to
under 90 minutes would surely seem like sacrilege.
</P>
<P>
   But to newer devotees, who haven't seen all the plays a dozen
times, Leah Ryan's new adaptation, as well as the skilled cast's
collective performance, can be an eye-opener. She has distilled the
story, emphasizing the humor and discarding most of the tragedy.
The latter seems like a mistake, but Chekhov, we're told, always
insisted that ``The Cherry Orchard'' was a comedy anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Making the play relevant to our times isn't much of a stretch.
The story is that of a formerly wealthy family on the verge of
bankruptcy. The only solution, it seems, is to sell their cherry
orchard. A nouveau riche neighbor, out of the kindness of his
heart, suggests an alternative: subdivide the orchard, build summer
cottages there and rent them out. But the Ranevskys won't hear of
it. The orchard represents the genteel past to them, and besides,
as Mama comments, ``I hate tourists.''
</P>
<P>
   So they do nothing. As a result, the estate is sold out from
under them (to Lopahin, their newly rich friend), everybody is
displaced, the servants don't know what to do, and the orchard is
destroyed. At one point, in Act II, Trofimov sums it all up: ``We
do nothing but drink vodka and theorize and complain about how
depressed we are.'' Yeah. Don't you love Russian theater?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cherry Orchard'' continues on Friday and Sunday nights at
the southwest corner of Washington Square Park through Sept. 27.
Admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE CHERRY ORCHARD'
</P>
<P>
   By Anton Chekhov; adapted by Leah Ryan; directed and designed by
Christopher Carter Sanderson; stage management by Eric Hurliman,
assisted by Lee Etta Sutton and Ann Carr; costumes by Karen Flood.
Presented by the Gorilla Rep. At Washington Square Park.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Mary Frank Swaim (Lyubov), Tim Moore (Gayev), Erica
Schmidt (Anya), Lynda Kennedy (Varya), Todd Batstone (Lopahin),
Benjamin Bauman (Trofimov), Christopher Berg (Pishtchik) and Mel
Jerdem (Firs).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
