A6067 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEAR-CRIME-HNS &LR;      08-27 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEAR-CRIME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXANS' FEAR OF CRIME DROPPING, POLL INDICATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texans are far less afraid of crime in general
than they were 20 years ago, a trend that would seem to pattern the
drop in the crime rate, according to a new study by Sam Houston
State University.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, more than half of those surveyed were afraid to walk
alone at night in their neighborhoods, but today only 1 in 3 Texans
express that fear, according to the survey conducted by the
Huntsville university's Criminal Justice Center.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, nearly half of those queried in 1978 feared being
alone in their homes at night, compared with slightly more than 1
in 5 harboring such concerns today.
</P>
<P>
   There was little difference among blacks and whites on this
issue. The percentage of those who said they were afraid to walk
alone at night within one mile of their homes dropped by roughly 20
percentage points for both groups; among Hispanics the percentage
of those who said they were afraid dropped 13 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Texans still have unrealistic fears of becoming victims of
violent crime. And the media's intense focus on crime, particularly
violent crime, feeds those fears by creating the perception of far
more crime than actually is occurring, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Although those surveyed indicated they mostly feel safe in their
homes and neighborhoods, their fears emerged when they were asked
about concerns regarding specific crimes, such as rape, assault and
burglary. Fifty-nine percent said they think they will become crime
victims in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The finding was nearly the same as in 1978, when 57 percent of
respondents expressed such fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how you go about measuring the level of concern
people have about crime, there does not seem to be a significant
change in people's concerns today compared with 20 years ago,''
said Dennis Longmire, a professor of criminal justice who headed
the study. The survey has a margin of error of plus or minus 4.5
percentage points, meaning results could vary by that much in
either direction.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Fabelo, director of the governor's Criminal Justice Policy
Council, said the survey findings that Texans are less fearful in
their neighborhoods today is ``remarkable'' given the intense media
focus on crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's showing that people are more sophisticated in
distinguishing between immediate fears and that caused by media
focus'' on crime coverage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texans surveyed were certainly mindful of the media. Like
Americans everywhere, residents of this state pin more blame on
violence in the media _ from movies to local television newscasts _
for causing crime rates to increase. From 1978 to 1998, the
percentage of those who thought movie violence contributed to crime
nearly doubled _ from 25 percent to 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The survey showed a specific shift in fear of assault, with
nearly twice as many Texans today fearing they might be beaten or
attacked with a weapon as there were in 1978. Twelve percent of
those surveyed said they fear being beat up during a crime in the
next year and 14 percent said they fear becoming the victim of a
criminal with a knife or other weapon. That compares with 7 and 8
percent, respectively, of those surveyed in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   While those expressing fear of violent crimes do not represent a
huge number of Texans, Longmire said, the findings are
``significantly higher'' than the '78 figures and are completely
out of proportion with the actual likelihood of falling victim to
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The popular image of crime (in the media) focuses on personal
violent crime, whereas the empirical reality is that most people _
if they are going to be the victim of a crime _ most people are
going to be the victim of a property crime as opposed to a personal
violent crime,'' Longmire said.
</P>
<P>
   But both violent crime and property crime rates are down
statewide. In Houston the overall crime rate cropped 3.3 percent
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that the fear of becoming the victim of a
burglary has decreased 10 percentage points over the past two
decades, to 24 percent of respondents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very, very infrequently, or very rarely, do the news media
talk about burglary or theft kinds of crimes,'' he added. ``What
you see in the newspapers, what you see on television, what you
watch in dramatic representations of crime are people getting shot,
people getting assaulted, stabbed, kicked and beaten severely,
people being robbed as opposed to burglarized.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
