<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6068 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BE-BOP-1200(4TAKES)-N     08-27 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BE-BOP-1200(4TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEEL THE CITY'S PULSE? IT'S BE-BOP, MAN! 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: A list of New York City sites associated with be-bop and
books, CDs and videos about be-bop is at the end of the article.) 
 Ann Douglas, the author of ``Terrible Honesty: Mongrel Manhattan in
the 1920s,'' teaches at Columbia University. She is working on a
book about American culture in the 1940s and '50s.  
(js) 
 By ANN DOUGLAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1964, Thelonious Monk, one of the pioneers of
be-bop and perhaps jazz's greatest composer, was asked by an
interviewer to define jazz. Though Monk disliked questions and
usually ignored them, this time he didn't miss a beat: ``New York,
man. You can feel it. It's around in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl (Bud) Powell, another of be-bop's originators, fragile but
divinely gifted, had a habit of standing, oblivious to passers-by,
on a street corner, pad in hand, writing down what he was hearing,
mixing insides and outsides into startlingly fresh combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Change often registers as sound before it is fully assimilated
as culture. Be-bop was the electrifying first-time translation of
post-Depression America into musical language, and its creators
found in New York their capital. The only place he would be willing
to live if he couldn't live in New York, Monk said, was the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Monk and Powell both grew up in Manhattan, Monk in the San Juan
Hill neighborhood in the West 60s and Powell in Harlem. They were
``already in Xanadu,'' as Monk's biographer Laurent de Wilde puts
it. But be-bop's two other founding fathers, Charlie (Bird) Parker
and John Birks (Dizzy) Gillespie, were from Kansas City, Mo., and
small-town North Carolina, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   In 1937, Gillespie, then 19, brash and teeming with
intelligence, came to New York. Though the job he had been promised
fell through, he stayed on, living on 25 cents a day, because, in
his words, New York had ``a different caliber of musicianship than
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker hoboed his way to the city in 1939 at 18, arriving in
raggedy disarray with nothing to his name but audacity and several
years of fiendishly intensive, innovative practice on his
instrument. Working as a dishwasher at Jimmy's Chicken Shack in
Harlem, he heard Art Tatum, a master of jazz piano at its most
demanding. After a trip back South, Parker reappeared in January
1942 at the Savoy Ballroom in Harlem, playing alto saxophone with
the Jay McShann Orchestra, a Kansas City band. Parker's
performance, faster than flight, shattered preconceptions with
every note.
</P>
<P>
   Between sets, Parker hung out on the corner of 140th Street and
Lenox Avenue, looking at the Savoy's big sign and taking in the
sights and sounds of the streets. He liked shifting the scenery,
scrambling his associations; better ideas come that way, he said.
When McShann's band left town, Parker stayed behind, ``just digging
New York,'' in McShann's words, to pursue what Parker called ``that
real advanced New York style.''
</P>
<P>
   Be-bop (bop for short) was sometimes labeled ``New York Jazz,''
and it is, in fact, the only major school of jazz to which the city
can lay proprietary claim. Jazz of the '20s, dominated by Louis
Armstrong, originated in New Orleans, migrating to New York only
after a formative detour in Chicago. Armstrong inspired '30s swing,
the music of the big bands led by Benny Goodman, Artie Shaw, Glenn
Miller, Count Basie and Duke Ellington, the ``mother bands,'' as
Gillespie called them, whose music the be-boppers both emulated and
revolutionized.
</P>
<P>
   New York's jazz sound had always depended on the piano, as
Chicago's had on the horn, and bop was piano-based. Powell and Monk
were pianists; though his instrument was the trumpet, Gillespie
worked out his (and Parker's) innovations on the piano, then wrote
them down.
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie integrated Latin and African music into his ``Cu-bop''
sound. Powell had mastered Debussy, Chopin and Bach by his teens,
and Parker listened avidly to Bartok, Stravinsky and Hindemith.
Monk's trademark hats, ranging from black Chinatown caps to
Scandinavian fur crowns and Charles Lindbergh-style pilot gear,
were a parade of multicultural insignia. Bop's wide-ranging
allusiveness, its quicksilver expressivity, angular dissonance and
shockingly extended palette of pitches and rhythms echoed the
international mix, the fluidity and speed of New York life.
</P>
<P>
   Bop began at roughly the same time as World War II, in 1940 when
Monk, then 23, was hired to play with Kenny (Klook) Clarke, the man
who transformed jazz drumming, at Minton's Playhouse in Harlem.
Gillespie jammed with them after his regular engagement, and Parker
joined them a year later. When Minton's closed for the night, they
adjourned to Clark Monroe's Uptown House, an after-hours club where
an extraordinary teen-age drummer named Max Roach played in the
band.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's entrance into the war in late 1941 imposed gas
rationing, entertainment taxes and curfews, sharply restricting
travel. The swing bands were touring bands, and some of them
continued to tour, but now everyone was looking for a long-term
base in a big city, easily accessible by public transit.
</P>
<P>
   What hurt swing helped be-bop. The expense and risks of touring
(especially down South) had been far greater for black musicians
than for white. The cramped quarters of many city clubs suited the
young bop musicians, eager to work with the small ensembles that
maximized opportunities for experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   Even the musicians' strike of 1942, which banned recording, had
its advantages. Errors were taboo in a big band or a recording
studio, where mainstream taste set the standard. But Monk urged
musicians: ``Make a mistake. Play what you want and let the public
pick up'' on it.
</P>
<P>
   Swing was first and foremost dance music. Bop, however, though
it tracked the body's rhythms with new exactness and daring,
militantly demanded of its audience acute listening rather than
motion. Like their great predecessors Lester Young, Coleman
Hawkins, Roy Eldridge, James Johnson and Art Tatum, the be-boppers
played and reworked Tin Pan Alley's classic songs. But as angry
critics noted, you couldn't always recognize the original in its
offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Preternaturally quick-witted, Parker liked to refer to Jerome
Kern and Oscar Hammerstein II's ``All the Things You Are'' as
``Yatag,'' an allusion to Parker's favorite line in the song, ``You
are the angel's glow.'' As ``Yatag'' makes the part stand for the
whole, skimming off the first letters of the words and abstracting
the words into a new sound, bop pulled apart and rearranged chords
and melodic motifs from older songs, exteriorizing the tunes'
harmonies and opening everything to extended improvisation, bop's
raison d'etre.
</P>
<P>
   The titles of swing standards like ``Star Dust,'' ``Honeysuckle
Rose'' and ``What Is This Thing Called Love?,'' though evocative,
needed no translation, but what was one to make of Monk and Kenny
Clarke's ``Epistrophy'' or Parker's ``Klactoveedsedsteen''?
(Parker's anxious producer consulted a dictionary and a
psychiatrist before a Parker initiate told him, ``Man, it's just a
sound.'')
</P>
<P>
   The word ``be-bop,'' which both Monk and Gillespie claimed to
have coined, described the music's unconventional stop-and-start
form, especially Gillespie and Parker's witty eighth-note pair
conclusions. The purpose of bop's irregular phrasings, side-sliding
harmonies and whirlwind pace, was, in Kenny Clarke's words, to
``raise the standards of musicianship,'' to tell people, ``Whatever
you go into, go into it intelligently.'' The be-boppers were the
real New York intellectuals, the hippest, smartest men in town.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
