<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6069 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSY-BOMBINGS-FBI-     08-27 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-BOMBINGS-FBI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENYAN HOSPITAL WORKERS PLAYED KEY ROLE IN EMBASSY BOMBING ARREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although FBI Director Louis J. Freeh on Thursday
praised U.S. investigators for bringing a suspect in the Nairobi
embassy bombings to New York, court documents show that the big
break in the case may have come from alert Kenyan hospital workers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the documents, the suspect, Mohamed Rashed Daoud
Al-`Owhali, and another unnamed suspect drove a vehicle loaded with
homemade bombs to the U.S. embassy in Nairobi on the morning of
Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle exploded, demolishing an adjacent secretarial
college and sending debris ripping through one of the Kenyan
capital's most congested streets. The blast killed 247 people,
including 12 Americans, and injured thousands more.
</P>
<P>
   Another 10 people died in a nearly simultaneous explosion at the
U.S. Embassy in Dar es Salaam, in neighboring Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   In his confession to authorities, Al-`Owhali, also known as
Khalid Salim, said the bombing was intended to be a suicide mission
and that he expected to die in the blast.
</P>
<P>
   But Al-`Owhali survived, receiving only cuts and abrasions on
his face and hands and a large wound on his back from the
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Following the blast, he was taken to a local hospital where he
was treated with other victims and later released.
</P>
<P>
   Before he left the hospital, Al-`Owhali allegedly discarded in a
bathroom two keys that fit the padlock on the rear of the bombing
vehicle and three bullets for a gun he had left behind in the
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital employees discovered the keys and bullets and alerted
Kenyan authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Kenyan officials confronted Al-`Owhali and took
him into custody. On Aug. 12, he was turned over to the FBI. After
eight days of questioning, Al-`Owhali confessed to the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In his confession, Al-`Owhali said he was trained in terrorist
camps in Afghanistan, including several camps affiliated with al
Qaeda, an international terrorist group led by Usama bin Laden.
Al-`Owhali, whose nationality is unknown, also admitted to
attending conferences and meeting with bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials suspect bin Laden may have financed and planned
the two embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh praised the Kenyan authorities for their ``extraordinary
cooperation, assistance and professionalism.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, U.S. authorities brought Al-`Owhali to New York
City where a U.S. magistrate will decide which U.S. court should
try him.
</P>
<P>
   A New York grand jury and the FBI field office there had been
investigating bin Laden's role in at least three terrorist attacks
or plots, officials said, including the 1993 World Trade Center
bombing, an aborted plot in New York to bomb bridges and tunnels
and a November 1995 car bombing in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, that
killed five Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In the complaint filed against Al-`Owhali, the bombing suspect
is charged with 12 counts of murder, one count of murder conspiracy
and one count of using weapons of mass destruction. If convicted on
all charges, Al-`Owhali would face a sentence of life in prison
without parole.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney general in charge of New York City, Mary Jo
White, said the charges ``show this nation's commitment to track
down and prosecute all those who commit heinous, cowardly acts of
international terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   A second bombing suspect, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, was reportedly
en route to New York. Odeh had been held by Kenyan authorities
since Aug. 14, a week after his arrest in Karachi, Pakistan, on the
day of the bombing. Odeh is said to be either a Jordanian or
Palestinian who obtained Kenyan citizenship in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh said other suspects are being investigated and also could
be sent here for trial.
</P>
<P>
   In retaliation for the embassy bombings, the United States last
week staged cruise missile strikes against targets in Sudan and
Afghanistan it said were linked to bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The decision to try Al-`Owhali, and perhaps others, in this
country represented a swift resolution of a potential diplomatic
problem of whether Kenya or the United States would handle the
first prosecutions from the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyan officials were said to be eager to seek justice for the
hundreds of Kenyan victims but also wary that a trial there for an
attack on a U.S. target might invite new terrorist assaults on
Kenyan targets.
</P>
</TEXT>
