<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BE-BOP-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      08-27 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BE-BOP-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: in town.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1941, white fans began to flock to Minton's. A few years
later, popular demand brought bop downtown, to the small, crowded
clubs on 52nd Street, known as ``Swing Street,'' or just ``the
Street,'' then thronged with servicemen, taking business from black
entrepreneurs but gaining wider exposure for the music. In 1943 and
1944, Gillespie and Parker went on tour with the Earl Hines and
Billy Eckstine bands.
</P>
<P>
   Bop's uptown, inner-city origins, however, determined its
nature. The city it dramatized was not the Big Town as
traditionally seen by the provincial eager to learn cosmopolitan
ways but, in Leslie Fiedler's words, ``the only home of the
essentially homeless,'' the refuge of the outsider, the fugitive
and the rebel.
</P>
<P>
   Although swing musicians joined the armed forces in droves, and
Glenn Miller's band became the Army Air Force Band, bop musicians
were skeptical of donating their services to a nation that defended
abroad liberties it abrogated at home. There were nearly 100 race
riots in 1943, including one in Harlem. Dizzy Gillespie put his
draft board on notice that he might not be able to distinguish a
white German soldier from a white U.S. one; like Monk, he was
promptly classified 4-F.
</P>
<P>
   Be-bop, the invention of the musicians who stayed in New York
instead of going to war, in Langston Hughes' words, ``let midnight
out on bail.''
</P>
<P>
   The four major pioneers of be-bop were temperamentally very
different, though the two New Yorkers, Powell and Monk, tended to
stick together, while Gillespie, bop's organizer and statesman,
found in Parker ``the other side of my heartbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Irrepressibly high-spirited, practical, and a master of public
relations, Gillespie introduced dark glasses, berets and hip black
English to the mainstream. Asked if his goatee was an affectation,
he replied, ``No, man, it's a fetish.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing with Cab Calloway at the Cotton Club in 1939, ``Diz the
Wiz'' mugged and threw spitballs on the bandstand while up front
Calloway, dressed to kill in a trademark white zoot suit, tried to
put over a sentimental love song. In 1963, on a short-lived run for
the presidency (he decided that the office was ``below my
station''), Gillespie promised to rename the White House the
``Blues House.''
</P>
<P>
   Short, with irregular features and cheeks that ballooned as he
played, decidedly unglamorous, Gillespie looked like the sidekick,
the comic foil to the leading man in the movies. In fact, he was
the only grown-up in bop's inner circle, the only one who was not a
drug addict or an alcoholic or a psychiatric patient.
</P>
<P>
   Until his death in 1993, frolicking at speeds previously
unimaginable in upper octave reaches the jazz trumpet had hitherto
only sighted, Gillespie was a jazz warrior. His music inscribed a
new hieroglyphics of energy, turning adrenaline into avant-garde
art and the sheerest, hardiest form of courage.
</P>
<P>
   Parker spent his short life serving two exacting masters, his
heroin habit and his music. In the mid-'40s, carelessly dressed in
rumpled, gangster-style pin-striped suits, gorgeous to look at,
full of mischief and unspeakably charismatic, he was New York's
lord of misrule, brooking no interference. ``Wait, Baby,'' he would
say to his favorite cabby, as he jumped out to score drugs,
disappearing for hours. ``Don't move.''
</P>
<P>
   When a white proprietor reproved Parker's musicians for using
the same entrance as the club's white patrons, Parker smashed the
glasses from which the band had been drinking, explaining to the
indignant owner that they were without value since black lips had
touched them. In Paris, a fan presented him with a rose; he
promptly ate the petals, then put the stem in his lapel. A genius
on several fronts, he quoted Baudelaire and the Rubyaiyat (``The
bird is on the wing,'' a favorite line, was one of several possible
sources for his nickname) and wept when a friend read the Koran
aloud to him in Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   No one could depend on Bird. In his autobiography, Miles Davis,
who played trumpet for Parker's group in the mid-'40s, tells of one
date at the Three Deuces, a 52nd Street club. Parker missed the
rehearsal he himself had called, appearing just as the gig began,
then picked up his horn and played every tune in precisely the key
the band had rehearsed. ``Did you ever doubt this?'' his look said,
as he took off on a Pied Piper flight of brilliant invention.
</P>
<P>
   Parker was a magician, a con man of gargantuan appetites, to
whom everything came with uncanny ease: music, women and, finally,
ruin. He died at 34 in New York on March 12, 1955, of cirrhosis and
complications. The attending doctor, who didn't know him, estimated
his age as somewhere between 50 and 60.
</P>
<P>
   If Parker was the renegade prince destined never to reach the
throne, Monk seemed to have been born already in possession of his
kingdom, centuries into his rule. His given name, Thelonious Sphere
Monk, was not a name but a title. Miles Davis rightly described bop
as ``an all-black thing,'' but talent was always more important
than race. The incompetent were ruthlessly eliminated, and Monk,
dark-skinned, 6 feet 2 inches and weighing upward of 200 pounds,
was often the one to do it. Incapable of lying or being merely
polite, he would tell some unlucky musician who tried to sit in
with him at Minton's: ``That's not the way we play. We changed all
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Legendary for his protracted silences and oblique utterances,
Monk thought in cryptograms. ``Monk,'' he pointed out, was simply
``know'' spelled backward, with the ``w'' on its back. ``It's
always night, or we wouldn't need light,'' he'd say.
</P>
<P>
   The peculiar density of his person was that of some rare form of
matter, forged in fires unknown, that accrues more energy and mass
than it can ever transmit. On several occasions, Monk was beaten by
the police or arrested for simply being somewhere, a hotel lobby or
an airport, with no visible purpose. Racism was very much a factor,
yet as his manager, Harry Colomby, put it, against an authority as
resolutely unnegotiated as Monk's, ``people defended themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Monk's first and most devoted subjects were women, first his
mother; then his wife, Nellie, and finally his friend, the wealthy,
glamorous and eccentric Baroness Pannonica de Koenigswarter, known
as Nica to her friends. Nica painted a little, using a mixture of
acrylic, milk, scotch and perfume, and became a passionate,
dedicated patron of the new jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Nellie, who supported him until his career took off in the late
'50s, can be seen in documentaries of Monk on tour in the '60s,
putting on his jacket or counting receipts while he munches an
apple. During the long, possibly drug-induced, depressive illness
that blanketed in silence the six years before his death in 1982,
he moved to Nica's house in Weehawken, N.J. Nellie came from
Manhattan almost every day to cook.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the big swing bands, bop seldom featured female
vocalists. Bop was an all-male gang. Women served; they didn't
play. Monk wanted dependability, not sex. When a pale and beautiful
blond woman tried to approach him at a club, he looked at her and
asked, ``How do I know you're not a ghost?''
</P>
<P>
   His compositions were magisterial jazz balladry, a haunting
series of shifts among reiterated pressure points, articulated with
the utmost precision, sculpted in stone. Yet his speech was often
incomprehensible. He visibly refused to do the physical work of
shaping and enunciating words. It didn't interest him.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Monk came to represent the same incorruptibility
and unassimilable African-ness that he admired in the singer Paul
Robeson. During the race riots of the late '60s, Monk's face
appeared on a mural in Chicago, next to those of Malcolm X and
Patrice Lumumba.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
