<P>
   Houston Chronicle  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6080 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BE-BOP-3RDTAKE-NYT &LR;      08-27 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BE-BOP-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK: PATRICE LUMUMBA. 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   A musical prodigy who was playing with professional musicians
before he was 10, the young Earl (Bud) Powell sported a ``conk''
hairstyle, dressed impeccably in stiff-collared white shirts and
black suits, and announced, ``I am the Earl of Harlem!'' Yet by all
accounts, even then he was gentle, almost naive, his large eyes
either veiled or too unguarded.
</P>
<P>
   His instrument claimed, and devoured, his vast authority. During
performances, as the room filled with demonically swift chromatic
runs, large, implacably rich chords and heartbreaking melodies,
there seemed to be no separation between player and piano. He
didn't rest well, he later told a doctor, because ``I never stop
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   What chance Powell had for a life outside his music ended in
Philadelphia in early 1945 when he tried to intercede with some
white policemen who were harassing his friend Monk. The officers
beat him about the head so severely that the scars were visible
until his death.
</P>
<P>
   He began drinking too much and using drugs. In 1947, at 22, he
entered his first mental hospital, where he was subjected to
experimental anti-psychotic medications and electroshock treatments
that dazed and terrified him.
</P>
<P>
   He told his story in the titles he gave his most characteristic
compositions, ``Dance of the Infidels,'' ``Un Poco Loco,'' ``Tempus
Fugue-it,'' ``I'm Sorry, Please'' and ``Glass Enclosure.'' His
extraordinary mind was intact, but difficult to access. In 1953, he
was declared incompetent to manage his own affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Powell was bop's baby in the bullrushes, its sacred child,
helpless and wise with all the knowledge for which birth usually
serves as censor. Asking for affection from those he loved with
direct fervor, he is the only person with whom Monk is known to
have held hands in public. In happy moods, he ate and laughed with
gusto, but his instinct for the fault lines of human brutality and
deprivation was flawless. Talking to a Japanese pianist he had just
met, he wanted to know if it bothered her that her husband was an
American. When she said no, he asked, ``But what about Hiroshima?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ill-fated,'' he wrote in a poem found on his bedside table
right after his death on July 31, 1966, yet his music possessed
healing properties for the tortures it ecstatically explicated.
Visiting him in the hospital in the late '40s, a friend discovered
that he had drawn a keyboard on the wall by his bed. As his fingers
ran over the keys, Powell asked, ``How do you think it sounds?''
</P>
<P>
   Together these men created a new musical language, giving New
York a dazzling portrait of itself in sound. In a '70s interview,
Gillespie said that be-bop was ``a love music.'' Bop is
mind-dancing; it's about seduction, about hearing notes that are
intimated rather than played, ghostly air-sketching in dialogue
with sonic bravado, an impossible mix of intellect and rapture.
</P>
<P>
   Bop catches you as you are, not yesterday or tomorrow, but
today, this moment, in all its unfathomable complexity, bringing
you the world before it is coined into convention, while it is
still gold. Running down a city street in the early '40s, Parker
turned and called back to his friends, ``You can do anything you
want to!''
</P>
<P>
   Pick up your Walkman, the listener's instrument. Put on a be-bop
tape, and walk around 125th Street or what's left of the old Times
Square or Avenue B. If you're a New Yorker, you're a bop musician,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a selection of sites that are associated with the be-bop
musicians in New York:
</P>
<P>
   1. Savoy Ballroom, Lenox Avenue and 140th Street, Harlem.
Charlie Parker played in this legendary jazz and dance hall with
the Jay McShann Orchestra in his early days in New York, in January
1942, astounding listeners, including Dizzy Gillespie who
recognized him at once as ``my colleague.'' Bud Powell played here
with the Cootie Williams band in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   2. Monroe's Uptown House, 198 W. 134th St., Harlem. With
Minton's, be-bop's birthplace. An after-hours club run by the
ex-hoofer Clark Monroe (his brother Jimmy married Billie Holiday),
where in 1943-44 Gillespie and Parker perfected the be-bop sound
after finishing their regular gigs elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   3. St. Nicholas and 140th Street (exact address unknown),
Harlem. Powell was born here on Sept. 27, 1924, in an apartment
building on the corner; his father, William, was the building's
superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   4. Minton's Playhouse, 210 W. 118th St., Morningside Heights.
Club run by Harry Minton, who provided superb free soul food for
musicians on Monday nights in exchange for free music. Charlie
Christian, Kenny Clarke, Thelonious Monk, Parker and Gillespie made
musical history here in the early 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   5. Hotel Stanhope, 995 Fifth Ave., at 81st Street, Manhattan
(also its current site). Parker died here in Baroness Pannonica de
Koenigswarter's luxury suite on March 12, 1955, while watching the
Tommy Dorsey band on television. Monk visited here often in the
late 1950s (despite complaints about his late-night piano playing).
</P>
<P>
   6. Hotel Bolivar, Central Park West and 83rd Street. The
Baroness moved here in the late 1950s; Monk composed ``Blues
Bolivar Ba-lues'' in her honor, then moved with her to her new home
in Weehawken, N.J., facing the New York skyline, where he remained
until his death.
</P>
<P>
   7. St. Peter's Church, 54th Street and Lexington Avenue,
Manhattan (also its current site). Monk's funeral took place here
on Feb. 22, 1982, with musicians playing for three hours.
</P>
<P>
   8. 243 West 63rd Street (now Lincoln Center). Monk grew up here
in the old San Juan Hill black district, then largely populated by
West Indians. He moved to Lincoln Towers on West End Avenue in
1967, but kept the lease on his original home until his death in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   9. 52nd Street, between Fifth and Sixth avenues, known as ``The
Street.'' A magical block of jazz clubs (since razed for office
buildings), including the Onyx, Spotlite, Three Deuces and Kelly's
Stable. Gillespie, Parker, Powell and Miles Davis played here in
the mid-1940s. The new jazz had hit white Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   10. Birdland, 1678 Broadway, at 53rd Street, Manhattan. The most
successful of the new jazz palaces, intended to succeed The Street.
It opened on Dec. 15, 1949, with dozens of (caged) birds on view
and Charlie (Bird) Parker presiding. Powell, Monk, Gillespie and
other bop pioneers played here over the years as well. (The current
club known as Birdland is at 315 W. 44th St. in Manhattan.)
</P>
<P>
   11. Town Hall, 123 West 43rd St., Manhattan (still open). Monk
held a large band concert here in 1959 to universal acclaim. Powell
gave his last performance here in 1965; he was led out onstage, and
played like a doom-struck ghost.
</P>
<P>
   12. 216 West 19th Street. Eager to become ``a New York
musician,'' Gillespie lived here with his brother, James Penfield,
when he first came to town from Philadelphia in 1937, eating for 25
cents a day.
</P>
<P>
   13. The Five Spot, Cooper Square. Monk gained real recognition
playing here in 1957; he was accompanied by the explosive young
tenor saxophonist John Coltrane. The New Yorker described its
ambiance as ``Greenwich Village of `The Iceman Cometh' period and
decor.''
</P>
<P>
   14. The Jazz Gallery, 80 St. Marks Place. Another showcase for
Monk's genius, beginning in 1960. Between sets, he walked the
streets, playing with the traffic like a ``matador,'' remarked his
saxophonist Steve Lacy.
</P>
<P>
   15. 151 Ave. B, near 10th Street. Parker moved here with his
fourth and last wife, Chan, in 1950, bringing the black avant-garde
to downtown white bohemia.
</P>
<P>
   16. Blue Note Club, 131 W. Third St. (also its current site).
Gillespie celebrated his 75th birthday here for four weeks in 1992;
backed by a multitude of jazz greats, he covered his entire corpus.
</P>
<P>
   17. 7 Middagh St., Brooklyn. Richard Wright, whose best-selling
novel, ``Native Son'' (1940), first sounded the militant black note
that bop would make part of the world's music, lived here in an
artists' collective, with Carson McCullers and others, from 1941 to
1943.
</P>
<P>
   18. Dewitt Clinton High School, Bedford Park, the Bronx. Powell
was a student here in the late 1930s, with young James Baldwin. (It
is not recorded whether the two met.) He left school in 1939 to
play piano full time.
</P>
<P>
   19. Creedmore Hospital, Queens Village, Queens. During his first
major breakdown, Powell was treated here, on and off, in 1947-48.
In his few weeks out, he recorded some of his greatest, most
dazzlingly lucid music on the Clef and Blue Note labels.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
