<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BE-BOP-4THTAKE-NYT &LR;      08-27 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BE-BOP-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: Note labels.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selection of material about be-bop and its musicians.
The recordings range in price from about $12 to $15 a CD.
</P>
<P>
   Books
</P>
<P>
   ``The Birth of Be-Bop: A Social and Musical History,'' by Scott
DeVeaux. (University of California, 1997. $35.) Richly historical,
wonderfully detailed and sensible story of bop's emergence out of
swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swingin' the Dream: Big Band Jazz and the Rebirth of American
Culture,'' by Lewis Erenberg. (University of Chicago Press, 1998.
$28.) Accurate, elegant account of the relation of swing and be-bop
to changing national ideas of the American dream amid the events of
the Depression and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``The History of Jazz,'' by Ted Gioia. (Oxford, 1997. $30.)
Possibly the best survey to date, and particularly strong on bop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Klook: The Story of Kenny Clarke,'' by Mike Hennesey.
(University of Pittsburgh Press, 1994. $22.50 in paperback.) The
story of bop's pioneer drummer, told in part in his own words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Straight, No Chaser: The Life and Genius of Thelonious Monk,''
by Leslie Gourse. (Schirmer Books, 1997. $27.) The first researched
biography of Monk in English, based on extensive interviews with
his family and fellow musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monk,'' by Laurent de Wilde; translated by Jonathan Dickerson.
(Marlowe &AMP; Co., 1997. $22.95.) Brilliantly perceptive homage to
Monk and New York by a French-American jazz musician and historian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bird's Diary: The Life of Charlie Parker 1945-1955,'' by Ken
Vail. (Penguin, 1996. $19.95.) A chronological account of Bird's
great decade, including his major interviews, telegrams, letters,
poems and reviews; full of photographs of bop's key scenes and
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie Parker: His Music and Life,'' by Carl Woideck.
(MacMillan, 1998. $15 in paperback.) Exhaustively researched, most
reliable account of Parker's life, with dense and rewarding
analysis of the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance of the Infidels: A Portrait of Bud Powell,'' by Francis
Paudras; translated by Rubye Monet. (Da Capo Press, 1998. $18.95 in
paperback.) The story of Powell's last decade, told by the
Frenchman who tried to rescue and protect him. The basis for the
movie ``Round Midnight'' (1986) with Dexter Gordon, and a wildly
sentimental, deeply truthful act of love by a self-proclaimed
``passionate disciple.''
</P>
<P>
   CDs
</P>
<P>
   ``Young Bird'' (Vol. 5). Media Seven. Parker and Gillespie at
their youthful, dazzling best. Includes ``Dizzy Atmosphere,'' ``A
Night in Tunisia,'' ``Show Nuff'' and ``Salt Peanuts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Diz 'n' Bird at Carnegie Hall.'' Roost. The 1947 concert.
Includes ``Koko,'' ``Cubano-Be, Cubano-Bop,'' ``Hot House'' and
``Confirmation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bird and Diz.'' Verve. Recorded in New York in 1950 with
Thelonious Monk on piano. Includes several takes of ``Bloomdido,''
``My Melancholy Baby'' and ``Leap Frog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Compact Jazz: Charlie Parker.'' Verve. Includes ``Lover Man,''
``K.C. Blues'' and ``Now's the Time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Best of Thelonious Monk: The Blue Note Years.'' Blue Note.
Monk's early recordings of many of his masterpieces, including
``Ruby My Dear,'' ``Misterioso,'' ``Round Midnight,''
``Epistrophy'' and ``Ask Me Now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Essential Thelonious Monk.'' Columbia. Monk with his 1960s
trio, doing versions of ``Rhythm-a-ning,'' ``Blue Monk'' and
``Crepuscule With Nellie,'' among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thelonious Monk with John Coltrane.'' Jazzland/Riverside.
Coltrane and Monk make his classics, including ``Ruby My Dear,''
yield new dimensions. Coleman Hawkins is also on tenor sax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bud Powell Jazz Giant.'' Verve. Early and unsurpassable
Powell. Everything is gold, but note ``Cherokee,'' ``Tempus
Fugue-it,'' ``I'll Keep Loving You'' and ``Yesterdays.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Best of Bud Powell: The Blue Note Years.'' Blue Note. ``Un
Poco Loco'' and ``Glass Enclosure'' are here, as well as strong
evidence that Powell's gift was still alive in the late 1950s and
early 1960s. Listen to ``Bud on Bach,'' ``John's Abbey'' and ``Like
Someone in Love.'' Videos
</P>
<P>
   Videos
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrating Bird: The Triumph of Charlie Parker.'' (Kultur,
$19.95). Great clips of Parker and Gillespie, as well as many of
their swing predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thelonious Monk: American Composer.'' (BMG, $19.99).
Straightforward account, with an extraordinary clip of Monk and his
trio doing ``Round Midnight.'' Amazing interviews, especially with
the pianists Randy Weston and Barry Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Straight, No Chaser: Thelonious Monk.'' (Warner, $14.99).
Directed by Clint Eastwood and full of fascinating sequences, this
video looks at the darker side of Monk, particularly the mental
illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jazz Hoofer: Baby Lawrence.'' (Rhapsody Films, $19.95; to
order, call 860-434-3610). Documentary of perhaps the greatest tap
dancer ever, Monk's favorite dancer, a ``jazz percussionist'' who
translated Charlie Parker's music into stunning motion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
