A6085 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-EUROPE-NYT &LR;      08-27 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE WORRIES ABOUT CONSEQUENCES OF RUSSIAN CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: RUSSIA-RDP, RUSSIA-BANKS, RUSSIA-COALITION,
RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT, RUSSIA-U.S., RUSSIA-U.S.-ASSESS, RUSSIA-IMF,
RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS, MARKET) 
(bl) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Concern mounted in European capitals Thursday that
Russia's monetary crisis, which is creating turmoil in world
financial markets, could throttle economic growth in their own
countries or weaken Russia's commitment to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But with German Chancellor Helmut Kohl in the fight of his life
for re-election a month from now and with President Clinton and
Russian President Boris Yeltsin both seen to be in weakened
political positions, few here saw much chance of quick, decisive
action during the U.S.-Russian summit meeting planned for next week
in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Stanley Fischer, deputy managing director of the
International Monetary Fund, raised eyebrows with an interview
Monday with the German daily newspaper Frankfurter Allgemeine
Zeitung that was sharply critical of inaction by the Group of Seven
earlier this month when Russia was forced to stop supporting the
value of the ruble against foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear to me that the situation was untenable after the
G-7 didn't rush to Russia's aid,'' the newspaper quoted him as
saying. ``I'm not sure Chancellor Helmut Kohl would not have
behaved differently if the elections were taking place two years
instead of weeks from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the Germans, of course, no other European country was
ready to support Russia financially,'' he added. ``And since, as we
all know, the American president is weakened at the moment and
can't exercise leadership from a position of strength, the chance
was missed to give a boost to Russia in a situation that was by no
means hopeless.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohl, campaigning in Berlin on Thursday, spoke by telephone with
French President Jacques Chirac of France, German officials said,
and planned to call Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   European political leaders' public advice to Yeltsin and his
prime minister-designate, Victor Chernomyrdin, was the same
Thursday as it has been all along: Without radical changes in the
Russian financial and economic system, more Western help will not
work, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be possible to mobilize German and international aid
without reforms,'' Kohl said. ``Without sensible reforms, it won't
turn out well.''
</P>
<P>
   European officials tried to reassure investors in their own
financial markets Thursday that Russia's economy was too small for
a collapse to do serious damage to their own much larger economies.
</P>
<P>
   European leaders' real concern is not about economic stability
but political stability in Russia, which is still a nuclear power
with an army bigger than all European armed forces put together.
And all European leaders, for years, have backed Yeltsin as the
bulwark of his country's commitment to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Fear that this commitment could come unraveled, some financial
analysts suggested, also might explain Thursday's panic in European
markets. ``Sidelining of Mr. Yeltsin Prepared,'' the French
newspaper Le Monde reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And after the Paris stock market fell more than 4 percent, Peter
Thorne, an analyst with Banque Paribas, said Thursday, ``Russia
obviously has nuclear weapons, and I think the psychology is that
Russia is more important than it really is.''
</P>
<P>
   French officials, just emerging from their annual August
vacations, said something needed to be done to reinforce the IMF,
which is providing Russia with a $22.6 billion rescue package. Much
of the latest installment of that money was spent by Russia's
Central Bank in a failed attempt to defend the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac, in a speech to French ambassadors from around the world,
said Wednesday that the IMF needed a decision-making political body
at the ministerial level to strengthen its ability to deal with
crises. International aid would only succeed, he said, ``if the
necessary internal reforms supported by President Yeltsin are
resolutely put into effect by the new government of Mr.
Chernomyrdin.''
</P>
<P>
   French Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn said the same
thing Thursday after a meeting here with his German counterpart,
Theo Waigel.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss-Kahn said he and Waigel were considering sending a
letter to Chernomyrdin, who is widely seen in Europe as likely to
proceed slowly with the kind of fiscal and financial changes that
Western experts say are needed to nurse Russia's economy back to
health.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists wondered openly Thursday why the Group of Seven
industrial countries, led by the United States, had not taken a
more active role in managing the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``For too long, Russia has been pretending to observe the
conditions imposed by the IMF and the IMF has been pretending that
it was doing so,'' Christian de Boissieu, an economics professor at
the Sorbonne, told the influential French daily newspaper Le Monde.
``The G-7 should take over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others have asked why the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development in London, founded to help free-market economies emerge
in Russia and other former Soviet republics and satellites, has not
played a more prominent role in the latest crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss-Kahn said that officials of the Group of Seven countries
_ the United States, Canada, Germany, Japan, Britain, France and
Italy _ were in close contact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
