<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO OTHER WAY OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the past six months, I have been predicting
that the only way President Clinton will ever quiet the Monica
Lewinsky scandal is to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Many Clinton associates have dismissed that as a unrealistic
notion on the grounds that he is by nature a fighter and not a
quitter. They simply could not envision him voluntarily walking
away from the job he fought so hard to get.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the president's troubles have escalated so dramatically
since his partial confession to an improper dalliance with the
former White House intern that what once seemed improbable now
looks like the best way out.
</P>
<P>
   His initial instinct in the face of hordes of current calls for
his resignation may be to dig in his heels and defy them all. But
eventually he will do it. Not because it is the right thing to do.
He is not in the habit of acting for that reason. He will do it
because he must.
</P>
<P>
   So long as Clinton remains in office, the relentless trashing of
both the occupant and the institution of the presidency will never
abate. Two more years of this would be too much to take.
</P>
<P>
   He cannot begin to rehabilitate himself politically until he is
no longer the focus of power and is off center stage, back in
private life. Handing over the Oval Office to Vice President Al
Gore would immediately give the country fresh leadership,
reassuring continuity and relief from the political heartburn of
lechery in high places.
</P>
<P>
   If evidence of any more Clinton lechery appears in Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr's pending report to Congress, voters will
find it virtually impossible to continue separating the president's
private conduct from his public performance, as many have thus far
been doing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet impeachment has always seemed a disproportionate, irrational
way out. It would be shameful if Congress went that far and if
Clinton himself let it go that far.
</P>
<P>
   An indictment and criminal trial in a regular court would be a
legal and historical outrage, given the constitutional separation
of powers. That should not happen and few think it will.
</P>
<P>
   The third alternative, congressional censure, would generate
considerable psychological and political pain but have no legal
impact. While it would leave Clinton in office, it would rupture
White House relations with Congress and grind the nation's business
to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   The national preoccupation with presidential sex will never end
so long as Clinton remains in the White House. It will continue to
distract and disrupt the country. It is demoralizing his Democratic
supporters. As I wrote in February, he cannot outrun this.
</P>
<P>
   So there is no responsible option for him except a graceful
exit, in his own time, on his own terms, in his own way.
</P>
<P>
   I do not think that time has yet come, despite the current calls
for his resignation. But it is inevitably approaching.
</P>
<P>
   More of this drama must play out before a voluntary presidential
departure would be appropriate. Starr's report will clarify issues
about which we are still only speculating. Congress must register
its collective reaction in some preliminary way to Starr's
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The fall election will settle the question of whether Clinton
will face a strengthened Republican majority or a somewhat more
friendly Democratic-controlled House. And if Gore is to have the
constitutional option of serving two full terms as president, he
cannot inherit the White House until Jan. 21. (The Constitution
limits any unelected president to one full, elected term if he has
served more than two years before he runs for election).
</P>
<P>
   One development unlikely to happen is a further Clinton
explanation of his sexual adventures with Lewinsky. There's not
much he can say that will make people approve of what went on.
Silence is the wisest course here.
</P>
<P>
   There have always been Clinton-haters who want his head on a
platter, no matter what the justification, so they can press their
own policy agenda free of his interference. I do not fall into that
category. I mostly approve of his public performance and believe he
has been sincerely trying to do what is best for the country.
</P>
<P>
   But the resignation talk now comes not from a vast right-wing
conspiracy but from editorial writers and other nonpartisan
observers who are genuinely concerned that Clinton is such damaged
goods he can no longer govern.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
