<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6088 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-GALANT-ART     08-27 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-GALANT-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITSUBISHI GALANT: DRESSED UP AND ITCHING TO BE LIFE OF THE PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., August 30)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Mitsubishi's advertising line for its 1999 Galant,
``Wake up and drive,'' is aimed at prospective buyers, but it could
also apply to the company's marketing subsidiary in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   For three consecutive years, Mitsubishi has sold fewer than
200,000 cars and trucks in this country; Toyota sells that many in
two months. Mitsubishi's plant in Normal, Ill., hasn't run at full
capacity since it opened in 1988. The Japanese parent company
suffered a $740 million net loss last year, and its credit rating
was recently cut by Moody's Investors Service.
</P>
<P>
   Operations in the United States have provided a crucial profit,
but the parent needs more. So the American managers have received
an edict: Wake up and drive, or else. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi installed new managers for its U.S. marketing
operation, based in California, and they have responded, moving to
reorganize the company and revitalize its network of dealers. The
company has adopted a new brand identity with a theme of ``Spirited
Products for Spirited People.'' A single ad agency with a
consistent message has replaced the dozen agencies that produced
corporate and dealer advertising. and now Mitsubishi has introduced
a new version of its best-selling vehicle, the midsize Galant, that
embodies many of the changes at the company. This is not just the
crucial debut of a make-or-break car, but the re-introduction of an
entire franchise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After driving two versions of the Galant, I concluded that
Mitsubishi was on track with both the car and its brand image.
Backed by an attention-grabbing advertising campaign _ at nearly
$50 million, it is the company's largest ever _ the Galant should
finally be noticed. After years in which the previous car remained
largely anonymous, the all-new model rates a spot on anyone's
shopping list of midsize family sedans.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is fierce in this market, and the Galant goes
head to head with the two best-selling cars in America last year _
the Toyota Camry and Honda Accord _ along with the Mazda 626 and
Nissan Altima, the new Pontiac Grand Am and Oldsmobile Alero, and a
host of other competent cars from import and domestic companies.
</P>
<P>
   In their dimensions, all these midsize sedans seem stamped from
the same cookie cutter. The Galant has moved from the compact class
to midsize status, as determined by the Environmental Protection
Agency's system of measuring interior space. The '99 is a tad
longer, taller and wider than the model it replaces.
</P>
<P>
   So Mitsubishi asked itself how it could compete with Honda and
Accord, since its car's proportions are nearly identical and its
features are virtually the same. It has less to spend on
advertising and fewer dealers to push its product.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it needed to establish a brand image, since
consumer surveys found that 25 people gave 25 different answers to
the question of the company stood for. Responses ranged from a
``maker of exciting, high-tech vehicles'' to ``the best deal in
town.'' Worse, many consumers knew Mitsubishi made cars, but could
say nothing beyond that about the company or its products. On a
more positive note, many consumers gave the company's vehicles a
higher fun factor than its competitors, which led to the ``spirited
vehicles'' line.
</P>
<P>
   Once that theme was established, Mitsubishi's new advertising
agency, Deutsch Inc., developed an MTV-style campaign suggesting
that a mainstream family can have the practicality of a Camry and
Accord, plus some excitement. The teaser ads heralding the Galant's
arrival this summer suggested that ``there is life after four
doors.'' Another showed a Galant racing through urban streets while
a narrator says: ``You have a family. You have a house. You have a
dog. You have a pulse.''
</P>
<P>
   In promoting the vehicle, Mitsubishi emphasizes styling,
spirited performance and a strong value. The Galant's primary
design originated in Japan, but for the first time the automaker's
California studio modified the exterior slightly. The Galant has an
attractive, sweeping roofline, which reminded me somewhat of the
latest Volkswagen Passat. Sharp side creases and a squared-off rear
deck lid give the Galant a tailored look. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi's American styling studio also designed a different
interior for the United States market. The most noticeable change
is that the audio system now resides in a more handy place, above
the climate controls. The interior is tasteful, attractive and
comfortable, with the controls logically situated and easy to
operate. But like all Japanese-made midsize cars, it is quite
generic. Were it not for the name badges, even the best-informed
consumer would probably not be able to tell one cabin from another.
</P>
<P>
   The Galant comes in four trim levels. The DE remains the entry
model, though it accounts for only a small percentage of sales. The
midlevel ES is most popular, and is expected to account for
three-quarters of sales. The LS is the most luxurious version. And
a new model, the sporty, limited-edition GTZ, joins the line for
the first time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every model comes with air-conditioning, power windows and door
locks, an AM/FM radio with cassette player, an auxiliary 12-volt
power outlet in the center of the dashboard, variable intermittent
wipers, solar tinted glass and two trip odometers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Safety equipment includes optional side air bags. Anti-lock
brakes are optional on four-cylinder models, standard on V6
versions. The Galant, however, lacks a three-point belt for the
middle rear passenger, a feature that the Camry and Accord have. I
like these center shoulder belts, believing that they help to
protect the children I transport in a parents' car pool.
</P>
<P>
   The new Galant is quiet, and it seems to have achieved its goal
of matching the near-silence of the Camry. A companion climbed
behind the wheel and could not tell that the engine was running.
</P>
<P>
   The Galant sets itself apart from the Camry, and most of the
other cars in its class, in the way it performs. With either
engine, it is a spirited performer, and surprisingly fun to drive.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Mitsubishi convinced its Japanese parent to
equip the American version with a powertrain different from those
sold in Japan. Instead of the 1.8-liter four-cylinder in Japanese
versions, the Illinois-made Galant has a 2.4-liter four rated at
145 horsepower, significantly more than the Accord, Camry and 626.
With 155 foot-pounds of torque, more than its prime competitors,
the Galant is quick away from stoplights and it dashes around
slower-moving cars in highway passing maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   Also for the first time, the Galant is available with a V6
engine, as are the Accord and Camry. Mitsubishi expects nearly a
third of Galant buyers to select the V6, a 3-liter power plant
derived from the engine in the Montero Sport. The Galant V6
produces 195 horsepower and 205 foot-pounds of torque, nearly
identical to the Camry's rating.
</P>
<P>
   For now, both Mitsubishi engines come with a new,
smooth-shifting four-speed automatic transmission that adapts its
shifting pattern to the driver's style. Unfortunately, no manual
transmission is currently available. A five-speed manual will be
offered later in the model year, but only with the four-cylinder
engine. This seems short-sighted; though fewer buyers are choosing
stick shifts, their availability would seem essential in a car
intended to be a sporty alternative to the leaders of the class,
most of which do offer a manual. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The suspension of the American-built Galant also differs from
the Japanese version. MacPherson struts replace the multilink front
suspension of the previous Galant for improved stability, more
responsive handling and easier manufacturing. The GTZ model that I
drove has tighter suspension tuning, making it fun to toss around;
a rear spoiler and black-on-white gauges add to its flair.
Nevertheless, my second test car, a four-cylinder ES, proved that
even a more basic version could be fun. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Galant has always attracted bargain hunters, since its slow
sales allowed customers to wheel and deal. The new models start off
with attractive prices. The base model is $17,410, including
delivery, slightly under the least expensive 1999 Camry. The Galant
ES V6 is an even better deal, starting at $20,410 _ some $2,000
less than V6 versions of the Camry, Accord and 626. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the new Galant, Mitsubishi set out to emphasize styling,
lively performance and a strong value. On all counts, it seems to
have achieved its goals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
