NYT-08-27-98 1900EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6094 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT-     08-27 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA CRISIS' DIRECT IMPACT ABROAD MAY BE MODEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: RUSSIA-RDP, RUSSIA-BANKS, RUSSIA-COALITION,
RUSSIA-EUROPE, RUSSIA-U.S., RUSSIA-U.S.-ASSESS, RUSSIA-IMF,
RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS, MARKET) 
(bl) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Fears of an economic meltdown in Russia
sent shockwaves through Germany and put heavy new pressures on
Central Europe on Thursday, but many economists and government
officials said the reaction was driven more by market psychology
than economic fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   In Hungary, the Budapest stock exchange plunged 15 percent, and
the central bank intervened to shore up confidence in its currency,
the forint.
</P>
<P>
   In Poland, which after Germany is the second-largest exporter to
Russia, government leaders warned the country to brace for slower
growth and more stringent economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to prepare ourselves for a certain domestic shock
effect, because the export possibilities will shrink,'' warned
Polish Finance Minister Leszek Bacerowicz. Polish officials have
trimmed their growth projections for next year from 6 percent to
about 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, the stock market plunged almost 4 percent Thursday
amid continued worries about German banks, which have been by far
the biggest lenders to Russia. Wednesday, Standard &AMP; Poor's lowered
its rating for Deutsche Bank, which holds about $750 million in
unguaranteed loans to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, one of Russia's most stalwart
supporters, warned that Moscow would have no hope of further
outside financial help unless it began carrying out long-promised
economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the reforms, it will not be possible to mobilize money
either from international financial organizations or from
Germany,'' Kohl told reporters Thursday in Berlin. ``If they don't
follow through, the situation will look bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But even though the Russian crisis spooked almost every market
in the world, many economists and government leaders said that
Russia's direct economic impact on other countries remains modest.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's most important economic assets are its vast reserves of
natural resources, from oil and gas to metals like nickel, platinum
and gold. But the financial crisis is at most likely to accelerate
the production and export of those commodities, in order for Russia
to obtain hard currency.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, German banks aren't quite so exposed as the numbers
suggest. At least 90 percent of their $30.5 billion in outstanding
loans to Russia are guaranteed by the German government. As a
result, analysts and bank executives continue to believe that they
face little more than a bad case of heartburn.
</P>
<P>
   That means that it is the German government _ which could end up
with a bill of $10 billion to $20 billion to clean up the mess _
that will to bear the brunt of the financial burden. ``The Russian
problems are usually discussed in terms of the impact on the German
banks, but they should probably be discussed in terms of their
impact on German public finances,'' noted Holger Schmieding, senior
European economist at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, losses from the guarantees Bonn made _ in part as a
political gesture to Russia for its support of German reunification
_ will not all come in one year, giving the government breathing
room to prepare itself.
</P>
<P>
   The economic repercussions in Germany of Russia's crisis are
also likely to be muted. While Germany is also the world's biggest
exporter to Russia, that trade accounts for only about 5 percent of
the country's total sales abroad and 0.2 percent of its economic
output.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's darkest shadows were cast over Central European
nations, which have thus far have managed to avoid being tarred by
the financial crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic have the biggest
economies within Central Europe. Though the Czech Republic remains
mired in its own economic problems, Poland and Hungary have
maintained strong growth and continued to draw heavy foreign
investment in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   But now those two countries are struggling to avoid the
guilt-by-association based on their historic ties to Russia.
Analysts said the stock markets in both were also hammered by
foreign investors who had lost heavily in Russia and were selling
the central European stocks to cover those losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are irrationally trying to sell, while there are really
few buyers,'' said Christian Faber, a trader at Wood &AMP; Co. in
Warsaw, told Bloomberg News on Thursday. ``A number of funds that
need money are forcing this selling situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few days, the Polish zloty has declined by about 8
percent against the U.S. dollar. Prices on the Warsaw stock
exchange dropped about 6 percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Polish President Alexander Kwasniewski warned Thursday that the
country will have to follow stringent economic policies to prevent
its own credibility from being damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not add our own virus to the viruses coming from
abroad,'' Krasniewski told reporters in Krakow on Thursday. ``We
must be persistent about reforms, financial discipline and measures
increasing exports.''
</P>
<P>
   Hungarian markets were badly rattled as well. Though the forint
has been relatively stable, the central bank intervened to support
the currency Thursday after it slipped about 2 percent against the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   More surprising was the plunge in Hungary's stock market, which
has been one of the most vibrant and one of the best performers in
Central Europe. In the past week, prices on the Budapest stock
exchange have declined about 20 percent, and most of that decline
took place Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   National Bank of Hungary president Gyorgi Suranyi said Thursday
night the fears have been exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I foresee a relatively modest impact from the Russian crisis,
because the fundamentals of the Hungarian economy are very
strong,'' said Suranyi in a telephone interview. Hungary's economy
is growing at an annual rate of 5 percent and its exports are
climbing 20 percent this year. Only a negligible 4 percent of
exports go to Russia, while about 70 percent go to the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weight of Russia in the world economy cannot be considered
that great,'' said Suranyi. But he added: ``If it creates a
subsequent spillover that affects North America or the European
Union, then we definitely will have to face greater challenges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
