<HEADLINE>
PEEPING TOMS AND NOTED AUTHORITIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Emma Thompson &LR;  may not be a first lady, but she played a first
lady in ``Primary Colors.'' At the opening of that movie at the
Edinburgh International Film Festival this week, Thompson gave her
unvarnished opinion of her role model and her role model's nemesis:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hillary Clinton  &LR; ``is pretty amazing,'' said the actress. ``One
of the things we have to face up to is that sex and power have gone
hand in hand for thousands of years. What is unusual about this
situation is  &UR; Ken Starr &LR; . The investigation is terrifying. I find
Starr a terribly frightening figure. It is extraordinary the powers
he has, this  &UR; J. Edgar Hoover &LR;  incarnation.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Dick Morris &LR; , who was adviser to  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR;  before he was
caught telling secrets to a girlfriend he hired by the hour, took a
tone of high disapproval in an op-ed piece in Wednesday's New York
Post. The president has let the  &UR; Lewinsky &LR;  scandal distract him,
writes this wise counselor.
</P>
<P>
   Citing failed tobacco legislation, thwarted education and child
care proposals and unfixed problems in the Social Security system,
Morris asserts, ``The blunt fact is that Bill Clinton has not been
a very good president since the Lewinsky scandal darkened his
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Vanity Fair reported last summer that New York Mayor  &UR; Rudolph &LR; 
 &UR; Giuliani &LR;  was having an ``intimate'' relationship with his
communications director; then, when the mayor ran for re-election,
his wife,  &UR; Donna Hanover &LR; , refused to join him during the campaign.
Does this sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News reports that the Giulianis have been attending
church together recently and even hosting dinners. ``They're
spending more time together,'' said one dinner guest. ``They're
trying to get along. He's making a conscious effort to spend more
time with the family.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Nostalgic  &UR; John Bix  &LR; forwards a clipping from March 27, 1995,
in which  &UR; Herb Caen  &LR; described ``an amazingly sexy affair'' between
the deputy governor of the Bank of England, married, and an unnamed
sweetheart. Much of this relationship was said to have been carried
out on the floor in the office of the man's boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't we have scandals as juicy as the Brits'?'' wrote
Caen.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Washington Times reports on claims in the official
newspaper of the Palestinian Authority that Monica Lewinsky is a
Zionist secret agent who purposely embroiled Clinton in scandal to
distract the president from encouraging Israel to withdraw from
occupied Palestinian lands. Meanwhile, the Jewish newspaper the
Forward says the president has been spending at least part of his
vacation reading the Psalms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ A series of poems by  &UR; Thom Gunn &LR;  about  &UR; Jeffrey Dahmer  &LR; is the
text for ``Troubadour,'' a song cycle by  &UR; Jay Lyon  &LR; that will be
performed Sunday in San Francisco. A group of disapproving
listeners walked out of a reading of the poems in Chicago, says
Gunn, but they probably wouldn't have minded poems about
 &UR; Napoleon &LR;  or  &UR; Julius Caesar &LR; , who certainly claimed more victims.
As for Dahmer, ``I'm writing about him like Shakespeare wrote about
Macbeth.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Mary Tyler Moore &LR;  was toilet-trained by the time she was 12
months old, reports Biography magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I don't think anybody has the right or need to see my penis.
Nobody needs that to continue living their life.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Actor Ryan Phillippe explaining why he refused to do full
frontal nudity in the new movie ``54.'' Phillippe's statement, from
the Los Angeles newspaper Fab, was gleaned by Ken Maley.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My agent, among other people, said, `You shouldn't do Playboy
again because people are just starting to take you seriously.' I
thought, `How sad. Do I have to sacrifice being perceived as a
sensual woman in order to be taken seriously?' ''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR;  Cindy Crawford, in People magazine, on a nude Playboy photo
spread that will appear in October, 10 years after her first nude
photo spread. Crawford admits that ``some things aren't quite as
high or perky as they were.''
</P>
</TEXT>
