<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6103 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-TRAVERS-BOS &LR;      08-27 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-TRAVERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEILA'S FLAG ON A QUEST AT TRAVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Trainer Elliott Walden has seen enough.
After watching Victory Gallop, who won the Belmont Stakes after
finishing second in both the Kentucky Derby and Preakness, chase
Coronado's Quest around the track to no avail in the Haskell at
Monmouth Aug. 9, he sought a solution to the problem _ a solution
with long ears.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Sheila's Flag, a 14-karat rabbit, whom Walden put into
Saturday's 129th running of the $750,000 Travers Stakes at Saratoga
to ensure that Coronado's Quest does not have things all his way
during the 1 1/4-mile journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was entered by design,'' said Walden. ``I just didn't say
anything about it because I didn't want you guys asking a lot of
questions. I don't know if we'll actually run him, we'll just see
how it plays out. I'm not sure if it's right to say that we entered
him for a fast pace. The best word is `honest.' We just want to
make sure that we have an honest pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila's Flag is an allowance horse who has won only two races
in eight starts and has never raced past a mile. He has about as
much chance as a $4,000 claimer at Rockingham Park of winning the
Travers. But his Prestonwood Farm stablemate, Victory Gallop, is
the real deal who has been first or second in his last 10 starts
(six wins) and was listed Thursday as the 7-5 favorite for the
Travers, just ahead of Coronado's Quest at 8-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like he ran a great race in the Haskell,'' said Walden
of Victory Gallop, who trailed Coronado's Quest by a length and
one-quarter. ``What might have hurt us a little bit is that, from
the eighth-pole in, he couldn't get outside. Coronado's Quest was
weaving all over the place. When he took dead aim on Real Quiet
(winner of the Derby and Preakness) in the Belmont, he came from
outside, not inside. We need to save as much ground as possible in
a race of this magnitude; we learned that in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think the distance of the Travers, the wider turns, the
length of the stretch, and the fact that he's sitting on a big race
are all in his favor. He's done well after competing in the Triple
Crown. Durability is one of his attributes. People should give him
credit for it. He's still here fighting the battles. I think a lot
of that has to do with his size. He's not an overly big type horse.
He's more athletic, he has a more nifty step than a larger horse
has.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that might work against Victory Gallop is that he has
lost the services of outstanding jockey Gary Stevens, who rode him
in the Preakness, Belmont, and Haskell. Stevens was injured at Del
Mar Sunday, tearing cartilage in a knee while trying to control an
unruly 2-year-old during warmups. Victory Gallop will now be ridden
by Alex Solis, who was replaced folowing an overland tour in the
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alex rode him very well in the Derby and the Arkansas Derby,''
said a diplomatic Walden. ``He's been victorious on him (in
Arkansas). We're very fortunate that Alex has been on him and we
can get him in this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   With Real Quiet out for the year with stifle problems, the race
for the 3-year-old championship could well be decided in the
Travers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as confident as I can be,'' said Walden. ``I wouldn't
change places with anybody on Saturday. Of course, that doesn't
assure winning. He's been working well on the main track. He's
thrived on it. In every work he's had here, he's gone the last
eighth in around :11. That's a big-time race horse. I think if he
wins the Travers he should be 3-year-old champion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shug McGaughey, who trains Coronado's Quest, was unfazed by
Walden entering a rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't be influenced by what anybody else does,'' said
McGaughey of his cantankerous but talented charge, who has won his
last four starts and will be ridden by the meet's leading jockey,
Mike Smith. ``He'll be laying up close. If that horse goes out,
we'll track him. Let them do what they feel they have to do. I'm
not worring about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to have fun. I'm looking at Saturday as a fun day for
me. I've learned that, when you have the goods, you should enjoy
yourself. It's different if you're taking over an 8-1 shot that
you're just hoping will run well. Coronado's Quest is a good horse.
We always knew he was a good horse, and we're happy that he's been
showing it lately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
