<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-SITES-FOR-SENIORS-(SENIOR-MONTH)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENIORS ON THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
  &HT;    (To publish this ``separate buy'' article it must be purchased
-- the rate is not prohibitive -- from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax, 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    (--Mexico, Central America, South America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los
Angeles, 310-996-0075; fax, 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    (----- Please call or fax for a price quote.)
 By ANN ORR  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Seventy-five-year-old Rollie Howes never figured he'd have any
use for computers, much less the Internet. But thanks to some
persistent arm-twisting by his nephew, he borrowed a laptop
computer and took the plunge.
 &HT;    Within 24 hours, Howes went from techno-novice to dedicated Web
surfer. The clincher was when he was able to locate long-lost
photos of the submarine he served on in World War II.
 &HT;    Howes is in good company on the Net, with more and more seniors
going online every day. Retired Rutgers professor Isabel Wolock
used the Internet to book a vacation villa in Spain and keeps up
with book, movie and theater reviews by visiting the New York Times
Web site.
 &HT;    Sixty-one-year-old auto executive John Grettenberger uses
America Online's Personal Finance Channel to track his investments
and frequents the Mayo Clinic's site for the latest information on
health-related issues.
 &HT;    There's something for everyone on the Net, whether you're 7 or
70. For seniors who have never touched a computer, how to get
started is the biggest concern _ and, indeed, getting hooked up is
the greatest challenge of the whole online experience.
 &HT;    Perhaps the best way to begin is with the help of a friend who's
already computer-savvy. If technology-minded friends are in short
supply, there's a terrific paperback book, ``Young   Heart,
Computing for Seniors'' (McGraw-Hill, 1996, $22.95), that tells you
all you need to know to successfully use a computer and hook up to
the Internet.
 &HT;    Classes in computer use and the Internet, offered by public
libraries and community colleges, are another popular and
affordable way in which people of all ages can get started.
 &HT;    Once you're online, the choices of interesting things to do are
endless. E-mail is particularly useful; it's a great way to stay in
touch with friends and the grandchildren. You can even send them
animated, talking greeting cards.
 &HT;    A growing number of quality Web sites are being created
especially for older computer users. In addition to news, feature
articles and advice, many have ``chat rooms'' or bulletin boards
where visitors can gather to ``talk'' and exchange information.
 &HT;    On the Internet you'll find information on virtually any topic,
including health, nutrition, travel, finance and various leisure
activities.
 &HT;    Get connected, and check out these great Web sites:
 STARTER SITES  
 &HT;    + SeniorCom (www.Senior.com). Want to check out retirement
communities without leaving your house? How about chat with others
or find out what events and classes are scheduled in your area? You
can do all this and more at this informative site. Best of all,
there are hundreds of links to other useful Web sites focusing on
travel, health and wellness, social security, services for the
aging and more.
 &HT;    + The American Association of Retired Persons (www.aarp.org).
Here's the place to find out where the AARP stands on issues of
importance to seniors. There's also a wealth of information on such
topics as health and aging, money management, wills and living
trusts, and grandparents raising grandchildren. AARP members can
get discounts on car rentals, hotels, airlines and even online
services (800-424-3410).
 &HT;    + SeniorNet (www.SeniorNet.com). This nonprofit organization's
site offers chat rooms and discussions on politics, travel,
gardening and health, with links to senior organizations and
publications on the Web. SeniorNet also teaches adults (age
50-plus) to use computers and the Internet at more than 140
learning centers nationwide. Call 415-495-4990 for information on
courses.
 TRAVEL  
 &HT;    + CyberRentals (http://cyberrentals.com). Planning a vacation?
Visit this site that lists homes, condos, chalets and other real
estate available for rent. Booking a beach house in the Virgin
Islands or a waterfront cottage on Lake Michigan has never been
easier. Each listing includes a description and photo of the
accommodations, rates and contact information.
 &HT;    + Yahoo! Seniors' Travel Pages
(www.yahoo.com/Recreation/Travel/Seniors/Airline_Programs/). If you
need to make an airline reservation, be sure to stop by this site
first. You'll find information about special fares as well as links
to several major airlines' senior citizen discount programs. Other
features of this Web site include car rental and hotel
accommodations information plus a mechanism for checking flight
times.
 HEALTH AND NUTRITION  
 &HT;    + Mayo Health Oasis (www.mayohealth.org). For information on
health, nutrition and exercise, the Mayo Clinic's site is terrific.
The Medicine Center pages are particularly useful; you can look up
8,000 prescription and over-the-counter medications to learn about
side effects, interactions with other drugs and so on. You can also
post questions to Mayo Clinic physicians and search the site by any
subject.
 &HT;    + OnHealth.com (www.onhealth.com). What ails you? This excellent
Web site lets you check an extensive disease database, gives you a
set of tools to retrieve and save important personal health
information, and keeps you up-to-date on the latest news in
medicine.
 FINANCE  
 &HT;    + AOL's Personal Finance Channel. America Online members will
want to take advantage of this excellent resource that lets you
stay up-to-the-minute on the latest financial news. You can track
your investments online, find mutual funds that match your needs
and obtain expert advice on retirement planning, insurance and
more.
 &HT;    + Money Magazine (www.money.com). This site offers interesting
articles on money-related issues, from selecting mutual funds to
finding the best deals on CDs, credit cards and loans. Visitors can
get advice from experts on money management and find out how to
save money on their taxes. Onscreen calculation tools can help you
make instant financial assessments and projections.
 CURRENT EVENTS  
 &HT;    + The New York Times (www.nytimes.com). Catch up on the latest
news and weather, read book, theater and movie reviews and check
the latest sports scores at this Web site run by the newspaper. You
must register first (it's free) and then you'll be able to access
all pages on the site. A great way to stay informed and involved.
 &HT;    + Time Magazine (www.time.com). The online version of this
publication brings you national and international news, plus
coverage of the arts, politics, money and technology. The site is
searchable, so you can quickly key in on just those articles that
interest you. There are lots of opportunities to contribute as
well, through polls and surveys.
 HOBBIES  
 &HT;    + Amazon.com (www.amazon.com). With 3 million titles, this site
beats any bookstore, hands down. Here you can read book and music
reviews, purchase these items in a secure ordering environment and
search an extensive database for books on any subject you desire.
 &HT;    + Epicurious (www.epicurious.com). If cooking is your passion,
this is the place to be. Features include a recipe file containing
more than 7,600 recipes from Bon Appetit and Gourmet magazines,
along with restaurant reviews and practical kitchen tips. On the
forum pages, you can communicate with other culinary enthusiasts to
find just the right ingredients for that Key lime pie Aunt Martha
used to make.
 &HT;    + Ancestry.com (www.ancestry.com). The ultimate resource for
those interested in tracing their family roots, this site offers
genealogy lessons, an ancestry search (90 million names!) and
recommendations for helpful genealogy books, magazines and Web
sites.
 &HT;    + Yahoo! Hobbies and Crafts Links
(www.yahoo.com/Recreation/Hobbies_and_Crafts/). Most of the search
engines (like Yahoo!, Excite and InfoSeek) have pages such as this
one. Type in the word ``hobbies'' in the search field and you'll
come up with a page of links to hobby sites. Just about every
leisure time activity has a site somewhere on the Web, be it
astronomy or woodworking, gardening or ham-radio operation. If you
don't find links for your particular hobby on Yahoo!'s page, try
one of the other search engines.
 &HT;     c.1998 Ann Orr  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ann Orr is senior editor of Children's Software Revue of
Flemington, N.J., an organization that helps families find quality
software and Web sites.) &LR; 
