<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEBOK-YANKOWSKI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKOWSKI NEW CEO AT REEBOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking to break out of its slump and placate unhappy investors,
Reebok International Ltd. Thursday named Carl Yankowski president
and chief executive of the Reebok brand, the fourth person to hold
that position in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Yankowski, a well-traveled executive whose resume includes stops
at PepsiCo Inc., Polaroid Corp., and Sony Electronics Inc., will
replace Robert Meers and report to company chairman Paul B.
Fireman.
</P>
<P>
   With $3.64 billion in sales Reebok is the world's second largest
maker of athletic shoes behind Nike Inc. But Reebok, based in
Stoughton, Mass., is in danger of being overtaken by Adidas AG.
</P>
<P>
   If Yankowski can rejuvenate Reebok, he would be a likely
candidate to succeed Fireman.
</P>
<P>
   Although Fireman has previously hinted he might step down if he
couldn't improve Reebok's bottom line, he reiterated again yesteday
that he has no plans to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intentions are to continue,'' said Fireman, who added
later: ``I'm not just walking out the door by any means. I'm
partnering with Carl to restore the luster of the brand.''
</P>
<P>
   The 50-year-old Yankowski, who said he holds two degrees from
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, has picked a difficult
time to make his debut in the footwear industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, Reebok was an industry laggard as Nike
sprinted ahead with Michael Jordan and its ``Just do it''
advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Now with a glut of sneakers on the market and with consumers
less susceptible to the marketing pitches of superstar athletes,
most companies are struggling, including Nike.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there is anecdotal, but by no means conclusive,
evidence that some young consumers are more inclined to buy hiking
boots rather than athletic shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole industry is very soft,'' said Dick Silverman, the
associate publisher and executive editor of two trade publications,
Footwear News and Sportstyle Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge for Yankowski is ``how Reebok is going to
differentiate itself from its main competitor,'' said Laidlaw
Global Securities analyst Peter A. Russ in a reference to Nike.
</P>
<P>
   Yankowski, an engineer by training, acknowledged as much.
</P>
<P>
   In visiting sneaker stores, he noted that Reebok products tend
to get lost in the huge ``walls of shoes'' that retailers use to
display their wares.
</P>
<P>
   His marketing priorities would be to make Reebok stand out at
retail and do a better job of delivering the message of how Reebok
products benefit consumers, Yankowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean Reebok might change ad agencies again?
</P>
<P>
   Reebok currently uses four ad agencies, including two in Boston,
Heater Advertising and its sister shop, the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to reserve judgment on that,'' Yankowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Yankowski said he's helped boost number two brands before. At
Pepsi, he helped improved Mountain Dew's market share, and he takes
partial credit for a famous ad campaign of 25 years ago that had
the tagline, ``Is it live or is it Memorex?.''
</P>
<P>
   Fireman, meanwhile, noted that Sony's sales soared during
Yankowski's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Given the turmoil in the footwear industry, many companies have
seen high turnover, perhaps few more than Reebok.
</P>
<P>
   If stability is part of what's needed to revitalize Reebok,
Yankowski may not be the man to provide it, analyst Russ said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy who's spent 2 1/2 and three years at a lot of
places,'' Russ said of Yankowski. ``He doesn't look like a culture
builder.''
</P>
<P>
   Meers, Yankowski's predecessor, who will continue to assist
Fireman in an undefined role, made a three-year commitment to lead
the Reebok brand.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how long he will stay with Reebok, Yankowski replied,
``I'm prepared to stay as long as it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite industrywide turbulence, there are some bright spots for
Reebok, said Silverman of Footwear News. New shoe lines
incorporating Reebok's DMX cushioning system have sold well.
</P>
<P>
   While that news should cheer investors, many won't be satisfied
until Fireman steps down, Russ said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think investors will be happy until Fireman goes,''
Russ said. ``He can put a lot of Band-Aids on the wounds, but the
big problem Reebok faces is what Paul Fireman sees when he looks in
the mirror in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the stock markets plunged, Reebok shares hit a
52-week low, dropping 1/2 to close at 15 5/16 on the New York Stock
Exchange. Less than a year ago, Reebok shares were trading just
below 50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
