<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS GRAPPLE WITH CLINTON SAGA ON CAMPAIGN TRAIL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A pall has settled over areas of the country where
Democrats had hoped to pick up congressional seats this November,
leaving party leaders wondering whether they can overcome
uneasiness generated by President Clinton's problems.
</P>
<P>
   With well-financed candidates and a heavily bankrolled plan to
turn out the party faithful, House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt,
D-Mo., had hoped Clinton's popularity and a steady economy would
help Democrats retake Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But as more details of Clinton's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky leak out, party activists say it's anybody's guess as to
how voters are going to react Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed this might overshadow more important
issues,'' long-time Democrat Penny Gold of Louisville, Ky., said
earlier this week as Gephardt campaigned in her hometown for
attorney Chris Gorman, who is challenging Republican incumbent Anne
Northup in what's expected to be one of the most competitive races
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The issues _ education, preserving Social Security, and managed
health care _ are what Gephardt tried to concentrate on during a
campaign swing through eight states this week. But as he wound down
his three-day trek from Pennsylvania to Washington state, he looked
weary and worried about whether his message was getting through to
voters.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, after answering yet another question from
reporters about what impact ``the president's problem'' might have
on the elections, Gephardt moaned, ``Isn't it time we had an
election in this country on an issue?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we'd all rather this (Lewinsky controversy) not be a
focus at all,'' the minority leader said. But he said Democrats
can't continue to wring their hands over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as disappointed as anybody, but that's history. It's time
to move on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But business as usual could be difficult as details about the
Clinton-Lewinsky relationship emerge and independent counsel
Kenneth Starr prepares to send a report to Congress that could lead
to impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's troubles, said pollster Bill McInturff of Public
Opinion Strategies, is ``sucking up all the oxygen'' in terms of
the attention Democrats had hoped to stress on real issue
differences with the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for the Lewinsky controversy, the Democrats could
be focusing on a Clinton record they claim has boosted the economy,
reduced crime and saved education programs from Republican attempts
to scrap them.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that, McInturff said, has been ``talked away'' to a
large extent by the national focus on the president's admitted
relationship with the young former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Lewinsky problem is nor viewed as seriously as the
Watergate scandal, McInturff said it contains echoes of 1974 when
lots of Republicans stayed home in mid-term elections after
President Nixon resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the nightmare scenario for Democrats,'' McInturff said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats need to pick up 11 seats to take control of the
House. They hope that a bigger labor turnout and better-financed
candidates will make the difference in 30 races they consider
winnable.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt acknowledged that the president's problem could
``depress turnout generally.'' Still, he insisted that the party
``can win the House with whatever is going on'' come Election Day
``if we've got the right candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   A new poll released Thursday by the Pew Research Center for the
People &AMP; the Press may give Gephardt some hope that in the end the
Lewinsky matter won't make a difference. The poll found that 61
percent of likely voters say the president's troubles won't affect
how they vote on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we don't see any less interest in Democratic voters
with regard to turnout,'' said Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew
center.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin auto worker Dave Townsend said he plans to support
Democrat Lydia Spotswood of Kenosha in her bid to unseat Republican
Rep. Mark Neumann because of the Lewinsky matter, and he believes
other Democrats and independent voters will be moved to do the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is an important election for dealing with issues,
regardless of what's going on with Clinton,'' he said. ``And I
think if the Republicans continue to try and make an issue out of
him and Monica Lewinsky it's going to probably give them a black
eye.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be too early to tell what impact the matter will have on
voter turnout, but Clinton's troubles have so far shown no sign of
eroding his appeal among party donors.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials say they are still ``on track'' to raise
their goal of $3 million in mid-September at a big New York
fund-raiser with the president. They expect to raise more than that
at a Los Angeles fund-raiser featuring the president in late
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the New York event is any indication, I don't see any
problem,'' said one Democratic Party official. But the official
emphasized that candidates this fall will be less dependent on the
president and the national party for money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set out to recruit good candidates in this election cycle
who could raise their own money,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats also plan to spend more than $2 million on
get-out-the-vote efforts this year in a handful of close races,
which is nearly five times what the party spent on all the 1996
races.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
