<SLUG> BC-MARKET-BONDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS GETS LOW RATES FOR $500 MILLION OF NEW BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Thursday's big stock market decline may have had some
equity investors ripping out their hair, but it provided a golden
opportunity for the Commonwealth of Massachusetts to issue $1
billion in debt at low interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The state issued $500 million in new 20-year bonds at a
favorable 4.89 percent interest rate, and refinanced another $500
million in bond debt in a two-part deal that resulted in an even
better 4.17 percent rate. In that transaction, the state replaced
$500 million in existing high-interest bonds with more attractive
variable-rate bonds, and then immediately swapped them, through a
competitive bidding process, to lock in a low fixed rate.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Massachusetts taxpayers will save an estimated $25
million in debt payments (based on the value of today's dollars)
over the 20-year life of the bonds, said First Deputy Treasurer
Thomas Trimarco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a very successful transaction,'' Trimarco said.
``We were positioned to be in the bond market at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   The attractive bond deal was made possible because of Thursday's
357-point plunge in the Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   When the stock market dives, investors typically pull their
money out of volatile stocks and seek more secure havens, such as
money market accounts and US Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike stocks, which represent ownership in a company, bonds
represent debt. Investors who buy bonds agree to lend money to a
government or corporation at a particular interest rate to finance
various capital projects.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices fluctuate based on prevailing interest rates. If the
bond is paying more interest than the rate generally available
elsewhere, people will pay more for it. Likewise, if the bond is
paying less than prevailing interest rates, it becomes less
attractive, and the bond price falls.
</P>
<P>
   Prices on municipal bonds, like the ones issued Thursday by the
Commonwealth, typically track those of US Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   When the demand for these bonds surges, as it did Thursday,
prices go up and yields _ the bond's interest rate divided by its
purchase price _ go down.
</P>
<P>
   The state had already been planning to sell bonds Thursday, but
decided to issue even more debt when it sensed the market
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just fortuitous timing,'' Trimarco said Thursday. ``We
went to bed last night thinking our deal today would be worth
somewhere between $800 million and $900 million,'' he said. But
because bond rates were so favorable, the state boosted the amount
to $1 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1914EDT &QL; 
