A6128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-INVESTORS-NYT &LR;      08-27 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-INVESTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE INDIVIDUAL INVESTORS APPEAR TO SHIFT AWAY FROM STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: MARKET, MARKET-LOSES, MARKET-INVESTORS,
MARKET-COMMODITIES, RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS, RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT,
RUSSIA-EMERGE) 
(bl) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Individual investors, whose determination to buy
stocks whenever the market takes a tumble has been the bulwark of
the bull market of the 1990s, appear to be weakening under the
weight of a monthlong decline in equity prices.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, individuals have been pouring more of their new
cash into the safe haven of money-market funds than into any other
investment category, while at the same time many of them have been
pulling money out of stocks. So far, August appears to be the
weakest month for new purchases of equity mutual funds in several
years.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the country's largest sellers of mutual funds _
including Fidelity Investments, Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. and T. Rowe
Price Associates _ said Thursday their customers have pulled more
money out of equity funds in August than they put in. Others,
however, including the Vanguard Group, say that investors have been
net buyers of equity funds.
</P>
<P>
   But all of the fund companies report a significant jump in flows
of cash into money market and fixed-income funds, another shelter
typically sought by investors in times of market turmoil. In
addition, there are signs that the skittishness has spread to
investors in 401(k) and similar retirement plans, who typically
have been less likely to make quick shifts from one asset class to
another.
</P>
<P>
   What apparently has been weighing on investors' resolve is the
slow-and- steady decline of stock prices since the market indexes
hit new highs in July. A volatile market has provided a few days of
rapid gains, but those have inevitably been followed by further
declines, as the slump has stretched from days into weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, while broad market indicators like the Dow Jones
industrial average still show gains for the year, a growing number
of mutual funds, which generally buy stocks that are smaller than
those in the market indexes, have lost money since the beginning of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Even at fund companies where investors have continued to buy
equity funds, they appear less steadfast than in previous market
downturns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our cash flow remains strong, but the numbers appear to be
very volatile,'' with heavy inflows one week and none the next,
said Peter Anderson, chief investment officer at American Express
Financial Advisors in Minneapolis. ``That tells me that people are
a little uncertain. What every investor has been taught is to buy
the dips. It takes some time to disabuse them of the notion. But I
think it's slowly beginning to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   With a few days of trading left in August, it is not yet clear
whether the universe of all equity funds will suffer net
withdrawals for the month, which has not happened in the mutual
fund industry since September 1990. Two data services that track
mutual fund cash flows on a weekly basis, AMG Data Services and
Trim Tabs Financial Services, report that U.S. equity funds have
taken in slightly more money than they paid out in August.
</P>
<P>
   But even those small inflows would be a dramatic decline from
the $19.3 billion that flowed into equity funds in July. According
to the Investment Company Institute, a trade group, $145.5 billion
flowed into stock funds in the first seven months of the year,
nearly 8 percent more than in the same period last year and an
average of almost $21 billion per month.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone sees a negative sign in the recent slowdown in
purchases of equity funds. Charles Biderman, president of Trim Tabs
Financial Services, of Santa Rosa, Calif., said that individuals
have continued to invest nearly $4 billion per week. Instead of
going into stock funds this month, however, it has been temporarily
parked in money-market funds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fund managers have accumulated $30 billion in cash this month,
and individuals have put another $20 billion into money-market
funds,'' Biderman said. ``That means there's $50 billion on the
sidelines waiting for the market to stabilize,'' which he called a
bullish sign.
</P>
<P>
   Among the large mutual fund companies, only Vanguard offered
evidence of recent bullishness among equity investors. Based on
flows so far this month, Vanguard expects its stock funds will take
in about $1.7 billion in new money this month, roughly half of
July's total, according to Brian Mattes, a Vanguard principal.
Almost as much, about $1.6 billion, is expected to flow into money
market funds, which Attes said ``is certainly the highest amount in
years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a measure of caution being shown,'' he said.
``Investors are not making big exchanges out of equities, but money
that might have otherwise found its way into the equity market is
going into more conservative categories.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, investors were cashing in some of their stock
investments. At Fidelity Investments, the country's biggest fund
company, more than $1.8 billion flowed out of stock funds while
more than $4.5 billion flowed into money market funds, said Scott
Beyerl, a Fidelity spokesman. T. Rowe Price saw ``moderate net
outflows'' from its equity funds for the first time in five years,
said Steven Norwitz, a vice president.
</P>
<P>
   And at Charles Schwab in San Francisco, which sells the mutual
funds of several hundred fund companies, nearly $1.9 billion fled
from equity funds, said spokesman Greg Gable. The last time that
withdrawals exceeded new deposits in stock funds sold through
Schwab's Mutual Fund marketplace was in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a kind of steady withdrawal from equity funds over
the past month, unlike in some of the past downturns where you get
a sharp decline and investors return right afterwards,'' Gable
said. He said individuals who invest directly in equities had
generally still been putting some new money into stocks, continuing
to buy after sharp market declines.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawals from equity funds at some of the largest fund
companies might not be worrisome if they were restricted to
investors who use mutual funds to time the markets, quickly darting
in and out when they believe a sudden upward or downward move is
approaching.
</P>
<P>
   But a new measure of trading activity among investors in 401(k)
programs, devised by pension consultant Hewitt Associates, shows
that in the last month investors have been three times more likely
to shift money out of stocks and into the safer havens.
</P>
<P>
   The recently introduced Hewitt 401(k) Index tracks the daily
transfer activity of 1.4 million participants in large-company
401(k) plans with $62 billion in assets. On 17 of the the 23 days
that the financial markets were open from July 27 through
Wednesday, investors shifted money out of equity funds and into
fixed-income funds, according to Hewitt. That resulted in a net
shift of $484 million of those retirement plan assets out of stocks
over the past month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
