<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6131 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS &LR;      08-27 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR CHALLENGES MOBSTER'S CLAIM OF FBI IMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A federal prosecutor Thursday challenged the substance
_ and the very existence _ of gangster/informant Stephen Flemmi's
claim that the FBI gave him permission to commit any crime short of
murder, and accused him of concocting an agreement that he knew the
FBI and prosecutors would never endorse.
</P>
<P>
   That's the reason why the alleged immunity deal, which Flemmi
claims former FBI supervisor John Morris agreed to in April 1985,
was never put in writing, Assistant US Attorney Fred M. Wyshak Jr.
asserted Thursday while cross-examining Flemmi in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so absurd, that Mr. Morris would not or could not put
it in writing,'' Wyshak argued. ``Because no one in the FBI or in
the US attorney's office would ever go along with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi said he didn't believe he needed a written contract. He
claimed that he was unaware at the time that the FBI documented its
dealings with top-level informants like him.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi insists his agreement with Morris was sealed during a
dinner meeting at Morris's Lexington home in April 1985. But, as
prosecutors have pointed out, that was more than two years after
Morris left the organized crime squad that oversaw Flemmi and his
criminal partner and fellow informant, James ``Whitey'' Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a gentleman's agreement,'' said Flemmi. ``We shook
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi claims that Morris gave him and Bulger permission to
commit any crime as long as they ``didn't clip anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Wyshak pressed Flemmi on whether that deal included,
for instance, rape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's what he meant,'' Flemmi answered. ``He
knows I'm not a rapist.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the agreement would permit him and Bulger to rob banks,
Flemmi replied, ``I would think anything short of murder I would be
protected for. I think it was my discretion. Basically all
organized crime matters, that's the way I understood it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyshak asked if truck hijacking was covered by the immunity
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it involved organized crime matters, it would be,'' Flemmi
said. The wide-ranging deal, he added, covered crimes ``past,
present and future.''
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi, Bulger, New England Mafia boss Francis Salemme and
several others were indicted in 1995 on extortion and racketeering
charges stemming from what prosecutors allege was a decades-long
joint criminal conspiracy between the Irish and Italian mobs.
Flemmi wants those charges dismissed because of his alleged
immunity deal.
</P>
<P>
   US District Judge Mark L. Wolf is holding hearings, in part, to
determine whether Flemmi's immmunity claim is valid. In the absence
of any written agreement, Wolf must decide if Flemmi had an
``implied agreement'' with the FBI and, if so, whether it is
legally enforceable.
</P>
<P>
   The government claims there was no such agreement, and even if
there were it would be the result of FBI misconduct and therefore
invalid.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Flemmi claimed his FBI contacts, principally agent John
Connolly, his longtime handler, knew about his criminal activities.
But when prosecutors grilled him about specific crimes he'd
mentioned to the FBI, Flemmi invoked his Fifth Amendment right
against self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   When he wouldn't say whether he'd told Morris about shaking down
preeminent bookmaker/informant Burton ``Chico'' Krantz, Wyshak
asked Wolf to hold Flemmi in contempt of court. Wolf &UR;  &LR; declined, and
Flemmi conferred with his lawyer, Kenneth J. Fishman, then gave his
answer: No, he had never told Morris or Connolly about Krantz.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was the same when Flemmi was asked about shaking down
more than a dozen bookmakers and drug dealers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
