A6133 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-CLINTON-HOLLYW     08-27 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CLINTON-HOLLYWOOD-NAT </SLUG>

 &HT;        CLINTON'S CASH COW: 90210
 &HT;    President's defense relies on Hollywood donors  
 &HT;     By Elliot Zaret  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Aug. 27 -- Call it the President's Hollywood
Lifesaver.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton Legal Expense Trust, the President's new legal
defense fund, has been buoyed by large contributions from Clinton's
high-powered Hollywood friends.
</P>
<P>
   California led the states in donations to the fund, with its
residents giving $423,000 -- more than 28 percent of the $1.5
million collected as of June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that money -- $250,000 of it -- came from 25 donors who
maxed out on the fund's voluntary $10,000 limit. Those donors
include Clinton's traditional Hollywood supporters, such as Steven
Spielberg, his wife Kate Capshaw, Barbra Streisand, David Geffen,
and Tom Hanks.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, half of the money raised came from 97 donors who
gave more than $1,000, according to a States News Service analysis.
And none of that would have been possible under the President's
former legal defense fund, which limited donations to $1,000 per
individual.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the first defense fund folded in January, having
raised only $1.5 million over three-and-a-half years.
</P>
<P>
   The new trust fund was founded in February by former Arkansas
Sen. David Pryor and five other trustees, shortly after the first
reports of an affair between the President and Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 21 -- four days after Clinton admitted having the
relationship -- the fund released its report showing $2.2 million
collected from about 17,000 individuals in all 50 states and the
District of Columbia, according to the trust.
</P>
<P>
   But the trust only released the list of donors that had given
before June 30 -- which is the portion of the list that has been
reviewed by their accountants. At that point, about 9,950 people
donated a total of $1.5 million to the embattled President.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased with the broad and ongoing support we have
seen for the President and the First Lady,'' said Pryor. ``We
believe that no First Family should face such a financial burden
while trying to carry out the work which the American people
elected the President to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The trust set a voluntary limit of $10,000 per individual donor,
and does not accept money from PACs, registered lobbyists,
corporations, labor unions or other organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The higher limit allowed Clinton to cash in on the resources of
his Hollywood friends and other large donors. In all, 72 people
gave the maximum $10,000 contribution.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer than 100 donors making up half of the fund, the other
9,850 people averaged donations of about $150 each, according to
the computer analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The largest contingent of donors were retirees. Nearly 4,700 of
the 7,668 donors who listed their occupation -- about 61 percent --
said their occupation is ``retired'' or ``retiree.'' The retirees
added about $411,000, or about 27 percent, to the fund. About 2,300
donors did not list an occupation.
</P>
<P>
   To get contributors, the trust sent a solicitation letter to
people on lists of donors from the Clinton-Gore presidential
campaign and from the Democratic National Committee list, said
Peter Lavallee, administrator o the Clinton Legal Expense Trust.
</P>
<P>
   The two-page letter begins, ``Dear Friend: In today's political
climate, public service can exact a disturbing price. There is,
perhaps, no better example than the financial crisis now facing
President and Mrs. Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavallee said a ``surprizing number'' of people contacted the
fund on their own asking how they could help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
