<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYSTEMSOFT-SHAKEUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYSTEMSOFT FOUNDER STEPPING DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Asian economic crisis that is affecting the electronics
industry in that region is generating big losses and a management
shake-up at SystemSoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Natick, Mass. firm reported Thursday a pretax loss of $6.3
million in the second quarter, compared to a $749,000 profit a year
earlier. Revenues plummeted to $2.6 million from $12.9 million in
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the slump, SystemSoft founder and chairman Robert
Angelo is giving up his role as chief executive. That post will be
taken by former Cullinet Software vice president Frank Sola In
addition, Deborah Besemer, &UR;  &LR;  hired last December as president and
chief operating officer, has resigned from the firm. Bessemer
formerly headed worldwide field operations at Lotus Development
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   SystemSoft is also restructuring its operations. It will sell
its Japanese subsidiary to a Tokyo firm that is majority-owned by
Standard Microsystems Corp. of Hauppauge, N.Y. The company is also
licensing some of its software to a Taiwanese company which will
employ 45 SystemSoft workers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; After the restructuring, the number of SystemSoft's employees
will shrink from 135 to 75.
</P>
<P>
   SystemSoft makes a variety of software products to improve the
performance of laptop and desktop computers. One of its key
products is software that is built into a special chip found on
computer motherboards. Most motherboards are made in Asian nations
being battered by that region's economic slump. As a result, said
SystemSoft vice president of marketing John Ambrose, motherboard
makers are sharply reducing production.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, SystemSoft's line of software for connecting PC
card devices to laptops has largely been superseded by improvements
in Microsoft's Windows 95 and Windows 98 operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   To recoup, SystemSoft is going to focus on its CardWizard
product line for Windows NT-based laptop computers, and on
SystemWizard, a program that automatically detects and repairs
problems with laptop and desktop machines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This simplified business strategy is the chief reason Besemer
is leaving the company, said Sola. ``Her skills are suited for a
large organization,'' he said. ``Right now we don't see the need
for a COO. The company is going to be smaller in size.''
</P>
<P>
   Sola said he would decide in the next 60 days whether the
company would replace Besemer. Efforts to reach Besemer by
telephone were unsuccessful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
