<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORWAY-TUNNEL-ART-760     08-27 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORWAY-TUNNEL-ART-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORWAY HOPES AMBITIOUS TRANSPORT PROJECTS WILL HELP RETAIN RURAL
LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HITRA ISLAND, Norway _ Norwegians have long looked out on their
deep fjords, snow-crested peaks and scatterings of scrub-covered
islands as soaring symbols of their wilderness culture.
</P>
<P>
   But shown that scene today, they are more likely to wonder how
they can scale over it, bore through it or burrow under it.
</P>
<P>
   The breathtaking scenery that inspired Grieg's symphonies,
Munch's paintings and Ibsen's plays and poetry is now in thrall to
the creative instincts of Norway's plucky bridge and tunnel
builders.
</P>
<P>
   Flush from North Sea oil, Norway is connecting its sparsely
inhabited outcroppings and linking its interior fjordside villages
clinging to sheer rock faces in a desperate effort to stanch the
flow of people to towns and cities from the breathtaking wild that
inspired Norwegians' view of themselves as pastoral dwellers of one
of the world's most majestic countrysides.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Norway is constructing some of the world's most
ambitious transportation projects in some of the world's most
remote locations.
</P>
<P>
   On this largely barren island off Norway's meandering west coast
there is a new 3.5-mile-long, three-lane underwater tunnel that is
the world's deepest and second longest. Built at a cost of $41
million, it links the mainland to a place that has just 4,100
inhabitants. Work has already started on a $69 million tunnel from
this island to its even smaller neighbor, Froya. Only 4,000 people
live there.
</P>
<P>
   On the North Cape at Norway's Arctic tip, construction is under
way on a $140 million bridge and tunnel project to Mager Island,
home to 3,600 people and almost as many reindeer. An additional
$135 million is going into the earth in the mountains east of
Bergen to link the towns of Aurland (population 1,900) and Laerdal
(2,250). Its 15.2-mile length will cast the current world
record-holder, the 10.1-mile-long St. Gotthard tunnel in
Switzerland, into distant second place.
</P>
<P>
   With 2,800 miles of rail, road and hydroelectric power tunnels
snaking their way under fjord and mountain, Norwegians are able and
practiced underground.
</P>
<P>
   The projects stand up to cost analysis only when you factor in
Norway's passion for portraying itself as a nation of
self-sufficient rustics. There is a deep Norwegian desire to
celebrate the country's rural heritage, and one consequence of that
is a public policy intended to provide the infrastructure to
outlying areas so that people will stay there and not retreat to
towns and cities.
</P>
<P>
   Kjell Erik Vindtorn, a contemporary poet, once said, ``Inside
every Norwegian there lies buried a vast mountain range,'' and that
notion is the inspiration in Oslo, the capital city, of the
development strategy known as the ``District Policy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``First there is our traditions and our culture,'' said Ranghild
Queseth Haarstad, the minister of local government and regional
development. ``Then there is the fact that our most important
export articles _ oil, fish, lumber and tourism _ are in those
districts. If we're going to exploit them, we have to have people
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the incentives provided to the north and the west coast by
the national government are unconditional per-inhabitant grants to
local governments, exemptions from payroll taxes for local
businesses, increased child-benefit payments, and investment and
operating subsidies to start-up enterprises. One northern town is
reported to have offered $3,300 to any woman who would marry a
local man.
</P>
<P>
   The 165-member national assembly known as the Storting is
heavily weighted toward rural interests and has little sympathy for
complaints from urban legislators that their projects, benefiting
many more people, are being cheated to finance provincial
undertakings. The Granfoss Tunnel in Oslo, which cannot get money
for urgently needed repairs, handles 23,000 cars a day, 100 times
more than the new North Cape tunnel, through which only 230
vehicles will pass daily.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by the Aftenposten newspaper last month tracking
migration patterns showed that 23 percent of those asked would
prefer to live in cities of at least 100,000 people, a figure that
was disproportionately representative of young people and up from 8
percent in a similar survey in 1992. An additional 25 percent said
they preferred small-town life to rural life.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Haarstad acknowledged that the District Policy was not
keeping everyone from leaving and that flight to the towns and
cities continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, `` she added, ``we can wonder how bad it would be if we
hadn't done these measures.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a broad political agreement in Norway that we should
preserve our traditional population patterns,'' Ms. Haarstad said.
</P>
<P>
   As she sat in her bleached wood, brightly lit high-rise office,
she emphasized that her own roots were in a small town in the east
and that she left Oslo whenever she could for one of her two cabins
in the countryside, neither with running water.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of claim exasperates Thomas Hylland Eriksen, an
anthropologist at the University of Oslo. ``Norwegians will tell
you they long to go off to a cabin that is cold, dark and
uncomfortable and has no electricity and is as far away from the
road as possible so you have to carry your things a great
distance,'' he said. ``In fact, these places in the countryside can
be very comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1991 satirical pamphlet called ``How to Understand and Use
a Norwegian,'' the humorist Odd Borretzen wrote, ``Because the
Norwegian is, after all, a son of the Wilderness, who lives a
simple life in harmony with Natur, he has concealed the telephone
in a rustic bookcase, hidden the telefax in a rose-painted wooden
chest with iron bands, and covered the electric oven with
pebbles.''
</P>
<P>
   Eriksen argued that the myth was losing its force because the
country's identity was changing. ``Norway was built as a nation on
images of countryside and nature,'' he said. ``It worked very well
in the 1850s when that's all we had. But people now like what can
be found in cities, a little cultural life, the cinema, cafes,
shops. They like feeling part of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Coastal Norwegians call the string of boat connections and
winding inland roads that wrap around the fingers of water that
make their shoreline so serpentine ``Highway One.'' Ask anyone
living on the hundreds of islands that dot the coastline what
bothers him the most, and he'll tell you it's waiting for the next
boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to travel a lot, and we get very stressed looking at
our watches and remembering when the ferry leaves,'' said Ole
Haugen, manager of a salmon farm on Hitra. ``Norwegians like to
feel free, and today, thanks to the tunnel, we feel free, 24 hours
a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Egil Hestnes, Hitra's mayor, said the only people who had
objected to the tunnel here were the ferryboat owners and
``romantics.'' He classed the latter as ``outsiders who came here
because they wanted to live on an island.''
</P>
<P>
   While welcoming the tunnel, some of this windswept island's
shepherds, fishermen, crabbers and sailors needed help in coming to
emotional terms with it. A professor from the Department of
Psychiatry and Behavioral Medicine at the University of Trondheim
had to run 18 local residents through two days of therapy before
they could overcome their claustrophobia and be coaxed into their
grand new installation.
</P>
<P>
   The descent into the Hitra Tunnel is so steep that drivers are
encouraged to take it in lower gears. At its bottom, 870 feet below
sea level, the moisture often condenses, setting off ceiling fans
that blow dense fog into the kinds of billows opera directors
conjure to announce the arrival on stage of Wagnerian antiheroes.
</P>
<P>
   There is no danger of being delayed by traffic: the tunnel
handles an average of only 25 cars an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about this Arcadian building boom, Eriksen said: ``You
know the joke about that, don't you? If the bridge is built for six
families who live on an island, all six use it once to pack up
their things and move off the island.''
</P>
<P>
   But for many Norwegians it is no joking matter. In a newspaper
article typical of the kind frequently published these days, the
Aftenposten ran an article on Else Steffensen, who at 83 found
herself the last inhabitant of a western island that once supported
nine farms and 50 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how it must have looked after the Black Death,'' the
article read, ``cultivated earth that the forest is slowly
reconquering, uninhabited, partly collapsed houses, no people, no
animals.'' It concluded, ``You can see it almost everywhere in
Norway's outer reaches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
