role in the Russian economic and political situation. By R.W. Apple
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   This will move by  &UR; 9:00 p.m. Eastern time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Washington) _ What is IMF doing? What did
Chernomydin and Camdessus, the IMF chief, say to each other at
their Crimea meeting? By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these stories from the Foreign Desk of The Times,
we plan these from The  &UR; Financial Desk &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   The ledeall will move by  &UR; 9 p.m. Eastern time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ In the wake of Russia's economic and
political turmoil, stocks fall sharply; the long bond's yield sets
another record low. At the close, the Dow industrials were off 357
points, Nasdaq down 81; the long bond was up 1 3/32, with th yield
at 5.38 percent. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   These stories have  &UR; MOVED &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-EUROPE (Paris) _ With the monetary crisis in Russia
creating turmoil in global financial markets, concern grew in
European capitals Thursday that the crisis could throttle economic
growth in their own countries or weaken Russia's commitment to
democracy. But with Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany in the fight
of his life for re-election a month from now and with President
Clinton and President Boris N. Yeltsin both seen to be in weakened
political positions, few here saw much chance of quick, decisive
action during the U.S.-Russian summit meeting planned for next week
in Moscow. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Fears of an economic
meltdown in Russia sent shockwaves through Western Europe and put
heavy new pressures on central European nations like Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic. In Hungary, the Budapest stock
exchange plunged a heart-stopping 15 percent Thursday and the
central bank intervened to shore up confidence in its currency, the
forint. In Poland, which is the second largest exporter to Russia
after Germany, government leaders warned the country to brace for
slower growth and more stringent economic policies. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-INVESTORS (New York) _ Individual investors, whose
determination to buy stocks whenever the market takes a tumble has
been the bulwark of the bull market of the 1990s, appear to be
weakening under the weight of a month-long decline in equity
prices. In recent weeks, individuals have been pouring more of
their new cash into the safe haven of money-market funds than into
any other investment category, while at the same time many of them
have been pulling money out of stocks. So far, August appears to be
the weakest month for new purchases of equity mutual funds in
several years. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   These stories will move by  &UR; 8:30 p.m. Eastern time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-LOSES (New York) _ How bad was Thursday's stock market
selloff? Really bad. By almost every statistical measure, share
prices have been suffering some of the worst declines in more than
a decade this August. And in many ways, the numbers behind the
headlines are even uglier than some investors realize. The result:
huge paper losses have accumulated for millions of investors in a
month of volatile and tempestuous trading. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS (New York) _ Russia's economic meltdown
claimed another victim on Thursday. The Republic New York Corp.,
considered to be one of the most conservatively managed banks in
the U.S. but one that also trades in some of the world's most
exotic markets, said losses in Russia will wipe out all of its
third quarter earnings. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-COMMODITIES (Undated) _ While millions of investors
focused on the globle plunge in stock markets Thursday, a key index
of commodities from oil to cotton fell to a its lowest level in
21-years. And that may be even more worrisome for investors in the
long run than the 4.2 percent fall in the Dow Jones industrial
average. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   This story will move by  &UR; 9:00 p.m. Eastern time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-EMERGE (Undated) _ A look at the impact of the Russian
economic turmoil as it affects emerging markets. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer.
</P>
