<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-FLOODING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONNIE CHURNS NORTHWARD IN WEAKENED STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ After a 36-hour deluge, Hurricane Bonnie
slackened to a tropical depression Thursday and churned back toward
the sea, leaving hundreds of thousands of residents without power
but generally relieved by the limited destruction.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton declared North Carolina a disaster area after
the hurricane smashed across Cape Fear, the state's southernmost
point, and strafed much of the coast with 12 inches of gale-driven
rain before losing its punch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  By the time Bonnie reached the state's delicate Outer Banks
Thursday, the storm's top winds had weakend from 115 mph to barely
65 mph, too slow to wreck much property yet still strong enough
that reporters had to shout into microphones from their beachfront
perches.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane left uncounted millions of dollars in damages in
its wake. But the destruction paled in comparison with the
multibillion-dollar ruin caused by previous hurricanes, most
recently Fran, which also made landfall at Cape Fear, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost our lights, but, thank the Lord, we didn't lose our
lives,'' said Corinne Wilson, 37, as she waited with her three
children for cold sandwiches at a Salvation Army truck in
Wilmington. The city of 95,000, just north of Cape Fear, absorbed
the brunt of Bonnie's rage.
</P>
<P>
   The storm is expected to leave North Carolina and return to sea,
where, forecasters said, it will regain power as it lurches
northeast and skirts south of Cape Cod Friday night or early
Saturday. Meterologists said the storm could return to hurricane
strength over the ocean, and tropical storm advisories were issued
for coastal communities as far north as Watch Hill, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   But the chances of Bonnie's punishing New England as severely as
it pummeled North Carolina were considered slim. Although North
Carolina escaped catastrophe _ no one was killed and no major
structure was destroyed _ a long stretch of coastline bore the
scars of a serious storm beating.
</P>
<P>
   Floodwaters surged through many communities, washing away cars
and kitchen appliances, and generally vindicating government orders
to evacuate more than 500,000 people from coastal regions in North
Carolina and South Carolina as the 450-mile-wide hurricane
approached.
</P>
<P>
   In Jacksonville, N.C., where the storm forced the Marine Corps
to halt normal operations at sprawling Camp Lejeune, rescuers
pulled two men to safety after they abandoned their car in
floodwaters and clung to a pole.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie unleashed 12 inches of rain on Jacksonville in less than
36 hours. With an inch of rain the equivalent of a foot of snow,
the downfall was comparable to 12 feet snow falling in the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, motor boats replaced motor vehicles on many roads.
And the entire downtown section of Washington, a small community on
the banks of the Pamlico River, was under water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a hurricane stay on and just continue to
batter an area like this hurricane has,'' North Carolina Governor
Jim Hunt said on ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt activated 800 national guardsmen and put 500 more on
standby. More than 2,000 prison inmates also were poised to help
with the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the cleanup got under way, there was the distant
threat of Hurricane Danielle, which is about 300 miles northwest of
the northern Leeward Islands. Forecasters said it was too early to
tell whether Danielle would hit the US mainland.
</P>
<P>
   For now, cleanup crews have work aplenty all along the coast,
from Calabash, near the border with South Carolina, to Atlantic
Beach, a short commute from the Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
   As the torrential rain subsided and insurance claims agents went
to work, many streets that were not under water were receptacles
for toppled trees, utility poles and windblown debris. In some
areas, so many pine boughs and needles filled the streets that they
smelled like Christmas trees.
</P>
<P>
   Roofs were ripped off many buildings, siding and shingles off
others. Mobile homes were uprooted. And scores of street signs were
twisted.
</P>
<P>
   More than 13,000 people remained in shelters. Mandatory
evacuation orders remained in effect for many barrier islands, and
curfews were still in place in many other coastal communities where
power was not expected to be fully restored until next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the Carolinas, more than 400,000 people were still without
power. Hardest hit was Wilmington, where 90 percent of the homes
and businesses remained without electricity. But even as utility
crews from several states converged on the area, residents
expressed relief at their relatively minor misfortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared to death when Bonnie got close,'' said Kate
Parker, 70, as she sat on her front porch, waiting for power to be
restored.
</P>
<P>
   When Hurricane Fran struck two years ago, every large tree on
Parker's property toppled, including a mammoth oak that crushed a
home across the street while a family slept inside. The oak is
gone, but the destroyed home sits unoccupied, a powerful reminder
of Fran's wrath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so afraid it was going to happen all over again,''
Parker said. ``But this storm was not as intense. It just took
longer to leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
