</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WORCESTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SUPPORTERS TURN OUT TO CHEER THEIR MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GEETA ANAND  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ John Yarosh supported President Clinton in
1992, and as he stood outside Worcester Regional Airport waiting
for the president's plane to arrive, he said he remains an ardent
fan - just a more self-conscious one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still love his policies. I really do think he has great
ideas,'' said Yarosh, a student at the Rhode Island School of
Design, as he cradled his daughter in his arms. ``But now I don't
wear my Clinton T-shirt too much. It's a little embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Yarosh, many of the thousands who came out to greet the
president Thursday said they were disappointed by his affair with
White House intern Monica Lewinsky but believe strongly in his
public policies and still support him. And because of the battering
he's taken in the media, they said, they wanted to let him know.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only reason I'm here -- to show him I'm still with
him. That a man can have an affair and still do his job. That is a
private issue to me,'' said Boni Hycner, a college student who
lives in nearby Charlton.
</P>
<P>
   In making Worcester the first stop in the rebuilding of
President Clinton's public image, his political advisers seem to
have chosen well.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of protestors carryied signs saying, ``Liar,'' and
``Resign,'' and two men dressed up in wig and costume impersonating
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr and Monica Lewinsky, complete
with blue dress. But overall, the crowd appeared overwhelmingly
sympathetic. Just the sight of the president's back in the distance
elicited screams from some of several hundred people assembled at
the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Standing 10-deep in some places along his motorcade route, this
old-fashioned city delivered an old-fashioned welcome. ``We Love
You Still, Bill and Hill,'' read one sign. ``We The Irish Love You
Mr. President,'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. James McGovern, who invited Clinton to Worcester
months ago, said he was surprised by the size and emotion of the
crowd, having been nervous about the president's reception.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``It was almost as if people were going out of their way to
say, `We're with you,' That's what they were saying, those that
came up and spoke to him,'' McGovern said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was so uplifted by the crowds that he stayed five hours
rather than the one hour that was planned, McGovern said. Clinton
joined McGovern, Senators John Kerry and Ted Kennedy, Worcester
Mayor Raymond Mariano and others for lunch at Scano's Bakery, a
local hangout.
</P>
<P>
   When they emerged over an hour later -- Clinton having consumed
the bakery's special of Steak Bomb, cannoli and a Diet Coke _ a
huge crowd had gathered and again lined the route to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   If Worcester wanted to boost the president's spirits, it
succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept saying, `This is great, this is great,''' said
McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   Not since President Lyndon Johnson spoke at the Holy Cross
commencement in the 1960s has a president stopped in this city, and
hundreds who held tickets to Clinton's speech had to be turned
away.
</P>
<P>
   As police looked on anxiously, a stream of people loudly debated
the handful of protestors marooned on a corner, a street away from
Mechanics Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never mind politics, the president is human. He made
mistakes,'' Bobby Harris, one of Worcester's best known
professional boxers, told the man impersonating Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haven't you ever made a mistake? I have. Everyone has a closet
and no one would be happy to have it opened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Starr impersonator, who identified himself as Tom Fuller of
Nashua, N.H., argued that the president should be held to a higher
standard. ``Are you saying you would cheat on your wife?'' he
prodded Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't. But if I did, it's my problem and my wife's
problem. You guys go home,'' Harris responded.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, people seemed somewhat comforted, even as they were
embarrassed, by the president's fallibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I put myself in the same situation and a little cutie comes
up, I could be tempted too,'' said Seymour Solomon of Worcester, a
dermatologist. ``I don't know if I'd do it in the Oval Office,
though. But I'm a middle aged man, too. I understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
