<HEADER>
A6156 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-BANK-560&AMP;ADD-N     08-27 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANK-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S LARGEST BANKS STRUGGLE TO STAVE OFF DEATH THROWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: a 1stld-writethru expanding this story is scheduled to move
by 8:30 p.m. ET.) 
(See also: RUSSIA-RDP, RUSSIA-COALITION, RUSSIA-EUROPE,
RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT, RUSSIA-U.S., RUSSIA-U.S.-ASSESS, RUSSIA-IMF,
RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS, MARKET) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It was a brief but wild ride for Russia's cowboy
banking empires, and like the economy on which they were saddled,
it looks to be meeting a disastrous end.
</P>
<P>
   Capping two weeks of increasingly alarmist rumors, the Russian
government said Thursday night that it intends to nationalize
SBS-Agro Bank, by most measures the country's third-largest. Within
minutes, five more major banks announced plans to merge. In two
days, 10 of the country's 15 biggest banks have either combined,
folded or been earmarked for government takeover. They will not be
the last.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian banking system is insolvent, the victim of bad
management, very bad bets on the stability of the ruble and
execrable investments in near-worthless government bonds. By one
estimate, the combined balance sheets of the 15 biggest banks are
at least $4 billion in the hole, a figure that leaps every day the
Russian ruble continues to drop.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 1,600 or so banks, mostly so small as to be
insignificant, are being dragged along in the fiscal undertow. Many
will not be missed, for Russian banks are not banks as westerners
know them. Some are money-launderers; some currency speculators;
some investment houses or pension funds or insurance companies or
conduits to offshore subsidiaries. The biggest are cash drawers for
vast conglomerates, moving money among their component companies. A
very few served average families and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The critical question now is what to do with them next. On a
purely rubles-and-kopecks basis, the solution is pretty clear:
``Under normal market conditions, banks would fail,'' said Alex
Kotcherguine, the bank credit specialist for Russia and Eastern
Europe for Paribas European Investment in London. ``But there are
no normal market conditions in Russia, as we have all learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there is already an open struggle over whether to let
the banks die or use the country's dwindling resources to keep them
on life support. Neither alternative is pleasant: one wipes out up
to 80 percent of all banks, with unknown effects on their creditors
and customers.
</P>
<P>
   The other would require printing more money to shore up sickly
banks and their wealthy owners _ and that would threaten to
re-ignite inflation. Russia's ousted economic reformers, along with
the western investors who stand to lose billions from a total
collapse of the system, want the government to shut down the
sickest banks and focus its rescue on the few worth saving. So, it
is said, do some banks controlled by industrial behemoths _
so-called oligarchs _ whose businesses benefit from foreign trade
and western credit, such as oil exporters.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the sickest banks, controlled by other oligarchs,
are dead set against that. The board of SBS-Agro said Thursday
night that it had been blindsided by the government's takeover plan
and demanded that the Kremlin pay ``hundreds of millions of
dollars'' in obligations, presumably in bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The newly designated prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin, may be
somewhere in the middle. A draft economic program approved by his
supporters in the Russian Duma Thursday called for increased
protection of banks and depositors, but offered no specifics beyond
a denial that the proposals were radical.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the government has shut only one of the top 15 banks,
Imperial Bank, which had defaulted earlier on a $50 million foreign
loan and was closed Wednesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In terms of global finance, this battle seems at first to be
almost piddling. The combined assets of all Russian banks as
figured by the Central Bank last January totalled a mere $100
billion _ less than the ninth-largest bank in America, First
Chicago NBD Corp. Russia's largest bank, state-controlled Sberbank,
is only about as big as Summit Bancorp, the 28th-largest U.S. bank.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do the banks have deep roots in the economy. Few Russians
trust much of their money to them _ proportionately, household
deposits are 6 to 10 times smaller than in many western countries _
and the vast bulk of savings are in a single bank, Sberbank, which
almost certainly will not be allowed to fail. One motive behind the
string of mergers, some analysts say, is for weak banks to ally
themselves with the few banks that serve households and small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning is that the government will nurse those banks
first and terminate others _ such as Imperial _ whose failures will
not drain the wallets of ordinary workers. But assets and deposits
are not what count most in the current crisis. The banks matter in
part because they fed the government's appetite for easy credit
over the last five years, when deficits were mounting.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Russia's biggest banks established industrial empires _
and close ties to politicians _ by lending the government money,
then accepting shares of state-owned companies in lieu of payment
on the loans. The business of financing government activities at
ever-growing interest rates became a staple of bank business and
provided capital for other, riskier ventures such as currency
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   When Russia declared a temporary halt to paying off its bond
debt on August 17, Russian banks held 105 billion rubles in
short-term bonds _ then about $17 billion _ at interest rates as
high as 150 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The banks' size also masks their importance to the economy.
Except for the big state- and city-owned banks, many large Russian
banks are the financial string that ties together the business
conglomerates of the oligarchs and other financiers. Not only do
the banks manage their finances and supply them with loans _ often
at sweetheart rates _ but it is commonly believed that they move
money in and out of Russia for tax and investment purposes.
</P>
<P>
   And a huge amount of money has fled Russia _ according to Credit
Suisse-First Boston, at least $66 billion from 1994 to 1997 alone.
Cyprus, the best-known offshore tax haven, is home to at least
2,000 subsidiaries of Russian companies, according to Steven
Shevoley, a Thomson Bankwatch vice president who watches Russian
banks from the island. Had that money remained in the country, it
would have spurred domestic investment and reduced the government's
need for deficit spending, one root of its current woes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
