<HEADLINE>
SOME MUTUAL FUND INVESTORS SEEKING SAFER HAVENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When not analyzing the fickle buying habits of grocery shoppers,
Michael P. Manix is counting the money in his three stock mutual
funds. While convinced his investments will bear fruit over time,
Manix has blanched at Wall Street's rollercoaster volatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in this for the long haul, and I'm sitting tight,'' said
30-year-old Manix, a financial analyst for Star Markets Co. in
Waltham. ``But if I had a new, big sum of cash right now, I'd park
it a money market fund for a couple of months until everything
calmed down _ if it did calm down.''
</P>
<P>
   With his double-edged view of investing, Manix is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   While brokers shuddered Thursday at the Dow's worst one-day
plunge since the October 1997 crash, America's individual investors
avoided panic selling of their stock funds and again showed the
resilience they have become famous for in this summer of steep
market swings.
</P>
<P>
   But investors have also begun to show a new trait _ an increased
willingness to buy more conservative investments that offer havens
of safety amid the stock market's storm, and a readiness to finance
such purchases by moving some money out of stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   After years of shoveling ever larger quantities of cash into
equity funds, helping to fuel the domestic stock market's record
bull run, Americans may finally be growing nervous over what the
market's near-term future holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may be getting a little wary and are taking what they
would normally put into a stock fund and sitting on it in money
market or even a bond fund,'' said Thomas B. Tyson, an analyst at
Financial Research Corp.
</P>
<P>
   That could portend a sea change in the investing habits many
observers see as underpinning Wall Street's spectacular gains over
the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds hold more than 19 percent of all US corporate
stock, or $2.8 trillion in assets, making them powerful players on
Wall Street when their managers buy or sell shares. But stock funds
may no longer be Americans' unrivaled investment of choice.
</P>
<P>
   So far this month, investors have put new money into stock funds
at the slowest rate since 1991, when the US economy emerged from
recession and personal investing took off. After years of pouring
up to $20 billion a month and more into stock funds, investors had
put only $1.1 billion into such funds over the first three weeks of
August, according to Mutual Fund Trim Tabs, a fund tracking firm.
The slowdown comes after stock funds drew in a net $19.3 billion in
July, roughly even with June, according to the Investment Company
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, money market funds _ short-term, conservative funds
that usually invest in stable government and corporate debt
securities _ have attracted an avalanche of new cash.
</P>
<P>
   Such funds drew in $24.9 billion in July, after outflows of
$1.59 billion in June, ICI data showed. Taxable bond funds, another
conservative investment, also gained in popularity, attracting $6
billion in new cash last month after winning $3.47 billion in June.
</P>
<P>
   And over four weeks through August 25, investors had sent a
whopping $45.4 billion to money market funds _ a 50 percent
increase over July's level, according to IBC Financial Data Inc. of
Ashland.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers, combined with anecdotal evidence from a dozen or so
investors, suggest the $5.1 trillion fund industry may be in the
midst of a major change as Wall Street heads into what some
observers are calling a correction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the stock market turmoil has lasted over a month
may be beginning to eat into investor confidence,'' said Peter G.
Crane, IBC's director. ``People may no longer be willing to buy the
dips,'' he said, referring to investors who sweep in to buy
battered stocks. ``It's less that investors are fleeing the market,
and more that they're avoiding new stock purchases.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average lost more than 4 percent
Thursday in a day of wild swings on fears about Russia's growing
financial and political crises. The index is now 12.6 percent below
its July 17 record high, and is up just 3.3 percent for the year.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index _ full of the big-name blue chips
that most equity fund investors own _ slipped 3.84 percent. And
after years of big gains, the 25 largest mutual funds are down
anywhere from 5.4 percent to 17.94 percent since July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Institutions were behind most of the selling, analysts said. But
while professional investors talked frantically of Moscow's
meltdown and Asia's effect on US companies, average investors were
less excitable, if a bit wary. Some were unruffled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried _ it's supposed to fluctuate,'' declared
Mahendra Bakshi, a computer programmer with a small fortune in 12
stock funds. ``These things are just going to happen from time to
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Major fund companies reported slight increases in the number of
calls from concerned investors. But they saw no signs of a dreaded
exodus from stock funds that could further roil the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of our investors have stayed with their
investment plans and not pulled money out of their accounts,'' said
Anne W. Crowley, a spokewoman for Fidelity Investments. ``But we
have noticed a trend this month in which new money has been
predominantly toward more conservative investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Fidelity estimates investors will pull $1.8 billion
out of equity funds over August, equivalent to 0.5 percent of the
firm's total equity assets, compared to net inflows of $900 million
in July. But Fidelity predicts gangbuster sales of money market
funds at a whopping $4.5 billion this month, nearly double July's
$2.3 billion. Most of the money leaving stock funds so far this
month has gone into money market funds, Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   The Vanguard Group, the nation's second biggest fund company,
said investors had sent $1.7 billion to its stock funds so far this
month, a steep drop from $3.8 billion in July. But money going into
Vanguard money market funds has nearly doubled to $1.6 billion.
Investors also put more money into bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 100 percent in stocks, and I'm kind of nervous,'' said
Jeffrey S. Cone, 37, a pharmacist in Weymouth with $80,000 in six
mutual funds and a passel of individual stocks. ``I'm thinking of
putting future contributions in bond funds _ just thinking. But
I'll keep the stocks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
