<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRATEGIES TO DEFLECT AN OFFICE DISTRACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Rick Brinkman calls them ``blurters.'' They are the
co-workers who blurt out loud any and every thought. They are among
the reasons a typical office worker is interrupted every nine
minutes throughout the workday.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know where Brinkman, co-author of ``How to Deal With
Difficult People'' and ``How to Bring Out the Best in People at
Their Worst,'' got the every-nine-minute average for office
interruptions. But however often they occur, it helps to have tips
for stifling them.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, blurters can be ignored or cut off. But no-bones-about-it
rudeness may damage long-term working relationships _ and that may
be more harmful than a few lost minutes of time.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent Institute for Management Studies seminar in Kansas
City, Brinkman sounded a theme familiar to many workplace trainers:
(begin ital) You can't change others, but you can change your
responses to them.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   So, here are Brinkman's suggestions for interruption control:
</P>
<P>
   --Rearrange your office furniture. Position your back toward
your door or the aisle. If you don't raise your head and, even
accidentally, make eye contact with passers-by, you won't give them
unconscious invitations to enter your work space.
</P>
<P>
   --Check your body language. If you're busy but you react to an
intrusion by leaning back from the desk, raising your head or
removing your hands from your keyboard, your body is saying that
you're ready to talk.
</P>
<P>
   --Adopt an office signal that means ``don't interrupt.'' Closed
doors are obvious, but not everyone has a door. Some offices agree
on an item of apparel, such as a baseball cap, that can be donned,
or a desktop accessory, such as a small flag, that can be raised.
</P>
<P>
   --Stack things on your ``visitor chair.'' Making it harder for
someone to plop down may prevent protracted visits, although true
blurters have no trouble sharing while standing up.
</P>
<P>
   (One worker told me she tried the stacking trick, but the
resident office wanderer simply stood in her cubicle long enough to
consume 30 little Tootsie Rolls. Ancillary lesson: Hide the candy.)
</P>
<P>
   --Deflect conversation by your response. Say to the gossiper:
``Thanks for the info, but I won't stay in the loop if I don't get
this done.'' To the complainer: ``I hear you, but I can't give you
the time you deserve right now.'' To the hovering boss: ``Thanks
for the advice. I better get on it right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Notice the statements of thanks, the message of empathy. Even if
you don't mean it, it's a somewhat positive response. The blurter
may not leave upset.
</P>
<P>
   You also might say at the outset, ``I only have a minute.'' But
you have to mean it. After one minute, say, ``I'm sorry. I have to
get back to work now,'' and do it.
</P>
<P>
   Once a conversation starts, Brinkman advises, you shouldn't
theatrically eye your watch and say, ``Oops! Gotta go!'' when the
other person is talking. Do it while you're talking. It's less
rude.
</P>
<P>
   Some managers may have the ability _ and a secretary's help _ to
block out times when they're noninterruptible. Most workers can't.
Most need to perfect individual blurter-deflection skills.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, most of us are blurters at some time or another. In
an I-blurt, you-blurt, we-all-blurt world, it's sometimes
worthwhile to let others blurt with impunity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
