<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6168 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONOMY-GROWTH-BOS &LR;      08-27 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-GROWTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMISTS SEE STRONG US PACE DESPITE WORLD UPHEAVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The world economy has churned up enough black
clouds to produce a major storm: Russia has joined Asia in a
financial meltdown, Latin American stocks are in a tailspin, and
once-mighty Japan has so far failed to moved with certainty to fix
a severe banking crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Yet economists still forecast continued growth for the US
economy. Not even Thursday's 357-point drop in the Dow Jones
industrial average, fueled in large measure by Russia's economic
crisis, forced many to budge from predictions that the US economy
would continue to expand for at least the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``These events, as dramatic as they are, just wouldn't be
sufficient to derail the US economy. The fundamentals here still
continue to be strong,'' said Wayne Ayers, chief economist at
BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, economists say the bleak news of recent months,
which includes a renewed US war against terrorists and President
Clinton's uncertain political future, cannot overpower the
likelihood that Americans will continue to enjoy high unemployment
rates and the ability to earn and spend money.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean that the nation is immune to the current
global financial turmoil. The US economy will certainly slow in
future months from the robust 3.9 percent growth of 1997, which was
followed by a torrid 5.5 percent hike in the first quarter of this
year. In a report Thursday, the government said gross domestic
product rose 1.6 percent in the second quarter, a slight revision
from the 1.4 precent it initially estimated in late July.
</P>
<P>
   Economists expect the slow growth to continue and say the odds
of a downturn remain modest.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Perna, chief economist at Fleet Financial Group, pegs
the odds of a recession in the next 12 months at 30 percent, up
from a 20 percent chance last fall. He foresees the economy growing
2.25 percent in the second half of this year, or 3.4 percent for
all of 1998, and slowing to 1.8 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   At Standard &AMP; Poor's/DRI, the Massachusetts forecasting firm,
chief US economist Cynthia Latta also puts the odds of recession at
about 30 percent in 1999. She predicts economic growth of 2.5
percent for the rest of this year, slowing to 1.5 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Ayers, offering a more optimistic assessment, says the risk of
recession is no more than 20 percent while growth will top 2
percent for the rest of this year and will slip to an even 2
percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why they are so far unfazed by the economic crisis in
Russia, economists said that Russia has always been more important
to the United States politically than economically.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of Commerce, trade with Russia
totalled $7.6 billion last year, accounting for a tiny portion of
the US economy and making Russia only the 32d-largest trading
partner of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It would take a larger event than Russia's downturn to raise the
odds of a recession in the next few months, several economists
said.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of event?
</P>
<P>
   China could devalue its currency, which would reduce the price
of its exports and help it sell more products abroad. That would
likely force the already battered Asian nations of South Korea and
Indonesia to cut the value of their currencies, possibly followed
by the likes of Brazil and other emerging markets. The result would
be a smaller market for US goods abroad and a larger flood of cheap
products into the United States. All that would make it harder for
US companies to sell their wares, dampening profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take something on the order of China devaluing its
currency, which would trigger other nations doing the same, to
shift things so that the most likely outcome in the US is a
recession,'' Perna said.
</P>
<P>
   But some economists say the US economy is so strong that it
could weather devaluation by China. Latta, for example, built a
weakened Chinese currency into her prediction of 1.5 percent US
economic growth next year.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger fear for her is that Latin America will slip into
recession. ``We export a lot of stuff there. It is a much more
important trading partner than Russia,'' Latta said.
</P>
<P>
   Economists also fear Japan will not clean up its troubled
banking sector, leading to a continued recession in Asia's largest
economy. Japan has the power to turn the Asian flu into pneumonia,
Latta said, magnifying the effects of the Asian crisis worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important factor for the US economy is probably the
stock market, economists said. Consumer spending accounts for
three-quarters of US economic activity, and consumers appear to be
spending these days because stock market gains have made them feel
wealthy. A sharp stock market drop could prompt them to stop
spending, raising the odds of recession.
</P>
<P>
   Ayers said it would take an additional drop of 15 percent or 20
percent, beyond Thursday's decline, to produce a US recession.
Perna said the market would have to fall even further to have that
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Mitigating fears of a recession is the fact that US
policy-makers have room to respond to signs of a downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Japan, where interest rates are already at rock-bottom,
the Federal Reserve can cut the federal funds rate from its current
level of 5.5 percent. This interest rate, which banks charge each
other for overnight loans, has been as low as 3 percent in the last
decade, and lowering it would encourage more lending, spending, and
economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Also, unlike Japan, where the government has been loathe to cut
taxes, the US Congress could respond to a recession threat by
returning tax money to consumers. ``This has not always been the
case, particularly when politicians were paralyzed because of the
huge budget deficit we were running,'' Perna said.
</P>
<P>
   Given the current headlines, it is easy to draw a doomsday
scenario for the world economy. But for each Russian crisis and
Latin American stock drop, economists said, it is worthwhile to
consider the American who just bought a new cellular phone, the
biotech firm that just brought a product to market, or the Internet
start-up that hired a laid-off Digital Equipment Corp. worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just an extremely dynamic economy, with all kinds of
activities going on,'' Latta said. ``People continue to take risks,
and venture capitalists are willing to finance them, and you don't
find that every place in the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
