<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Friday,
Aug. 28. If you have any questions, please call the Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4786.
</P>
<P>
   ATWORK-COLUMN (Undated) _ Some strategies to deflect an office
distraction. Workplace column by DIANE STAFFORD. Story will move in
the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Undated) _ With a general election a little
more than two months away, national Republican advisers are
suggesting that candidates approach the White House sex scandal
with caution, if at all. Democrats, on the other hand, worry that
the scandal could cast a cloud over efforts to elect their
candidates to Congress and other offices. By JIM SULLINGER. Story
will move in ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   LOTTERY-LAUNDER (Kansas City, Mo.) _ A Powerball ticket
accidentally run through the laundry could be worth $24 million for
a man from the Kansas City area. He took fragments to the lottery
office this week, hoping to strike it rich. The state Lottery
Commission is testing to see whether it is the real deal. By OSCAR
AVILA. Story will move in ``a'' category.
</P>
</TEXT>
