<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6171 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-KAN &LR;      08-27 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON CAMPAIGN TRAIL, CAUTION IS WATCHWORD REGARDING CLINTON SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLINGER  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: With a general election a little more than two months
away, national Republican advisers are suggesting that candidates
approach the White House sex scandal with caution, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   They reason that if voters think Republicans are promoting a
scandal that people want to go away, a backlash could strike GOP
candidates this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, on the other hand, worry that the scandal could cast
a cloud over efforts to elect their candidates to Congress and
other offices. In North Carolina, a Republican challenger already
is using a commercial linking Clinton to a Democratic congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Most politicians, however, are tiptoeing around the Clinton
scandal as if it were a cold they could catch. Phrases such as ``We
really need to wait for Kenneth Starr's report'' are common among
those watching opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until then, things are going to be unsettled,'' said Fred
Logan of Leawood, a former Kansas Republican Party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   One candidate who isn't skirting the issue is U.S. Rep. Vince
Snowbarger, a GOP incumbent seeking re-election in Kansas' 3rd
District. He was one of the few officeholders in the nation to call
immediately for Clinton's resignation after his nationally
televised address Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Snowbarger acknowledged that his position could come back to
haunt him. But he also said this was what he honestly believed. The
Democrat who wants to unseat Snowbarger, Dennis Moore, hasn't said
much about the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, he issued a statement criticizing the president's
personal conduct and joining the chorus of politicians saying they
will wait for independent counsel Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   John Thompson, a media consultant in Springfield, Mo., said that
the recent missile strikes against Afghanistan and Sudan were only
temporary diversions and that the spotlight would return to the
scandal, especially when the next sensational revelation surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd advise Republicans to keep their powder dry,'' said
Thompson, who works primarily for GOP candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Snowbarger said the fact that so many Americans questioned the
president's motives in ordering the missile attacks points up the
credibility problem Clinton now has with the public.
</P>
<P>
   Logan said an unsettled political picture terrifies those
charged with running campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Senate Minority Leader Anthony Hensley, a Topeka
Democrat, said: ``Republicans are going to be very careful this
doesn't become partisan and backfire on them. Of course, Democrats
have to keep their distance, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four years ago, the nation watched the Republican Party
go down to a humiliating defeat as Democrats gleaned an election
windfall from Watergate in the fall of 1974. The lesson hasn't been
lost on today's politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference, of course, is in the polls,'' Hensley said.
``In 1974, the bottom dropped out from under Nixon. That hasn't
happened to Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats worry that it could.
</P>
<P>
   Another politician calling for resignation is Sen. John Ashcroft
of Missouri. His spokesman, Steve Hilton, said the senator
proclaimed in January that if the sex allegations were true,
Clinton should resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Ashcroft) has consistently addressed the question of the
president's behavior as a matter of principle,'' Hilton said.
</P>
<P>
   Although political fallout doesn't seem a worry for Snowbarger
or Ashcroft, other politicians remain concerned.
</P>
<P>
   They don't seem to know just where the scandal is going or what
effect it might have.
</P>
<P>
   One casualty, they suggest, might be voter turnout in November,
which wasn't expected to be large anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Snowbarger said, demoralized Republicans just lost
energy and stayed home on Election Day. Will Clinton's problems
have the same effect on unaffiliated voters and Democrats, groups
Moore needs if he's going to defeat Snowbarger in a largely
Republican district?
</P>
<P>
   ``The significance of this confession on the public in general
is that it increases the disgust for politics and politicians, and,
very frankly, I think it may affect turnout, and turnout may affect
this race,'' Snowbarger said.
</P>
<P>
   If people ignore the voting booth because of the scandal, he
said, the real loser will be the political system.
</P>
<P>
   Burdett Loomis, a political science professor at the University
of Kansas, said Americans don't have to look at the scandal to be
worried about the health of American politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were already looking at a low voter turnout, and half the
seats in the (Kansas) House aren't being challenged this year,''
Loomis said. ``Of 435 races for Congress, only about 30 are truly
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans involved in campaigns say they can't
afford to worry about outside influences they can't control.
</P>
<P>
   Does Chris Esposito, Moore's campaign manager, worry that events
in Washington will cost his candidate an election?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's premature to answer that question,'' he said. ``I worry
about fund-raising and turnout every day. The bottom line is that
an honest discussion of the issues and differences between Dennis
Moore and Vince Snowbarger will drive turnout.''
</P>
<P>
   Social Security, he predicted, will play a much greater role in
Moore's campaign than Clinton's self-described inappropriate
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Snowbarger said there was no ``monolithic Republican position''
on how to deal with Clinton's problems. He said there was sentiment
among some Republicans that Clinton should serve out his term.
</P>
<P>
   Snowbarger said these Republicans want to keep an ``ineffective
Clinton'' in office and let the Republican-controlled Congress play
an even bigger role in driving national policy.
</P>
<P>
   And what about future revelations of misconduct? Logan said a
lot of campaign officials are not only nervous but holding their
collective breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should petrify campaigns,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
