</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CODFISH-COUNCIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS WANT MORE FACTS BEFORE ALTERING COD LIMITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEABODY, Mass. _ Confronted by a roomful of angry fishermen, New
England fishing regulators retreated from taking emergency actions
to protect the rapidly declining cod population in the Gulf of
Maine Thursday, but they warned that more restrictions are likely
to come soon.
</P>
<P>
   Federal biologists last month urged the New England FIshery
Management Council to reduce fishing to ``near zero'' in the
once-abundant cod fishing ground that extends from the waters off
Maine to Cape Ann in Massachusetts. If that isn't done, they
warned, the cod population soon could collapse.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, council members said they wanted to know more
about effective recent limits on cod fishing have been before
closing a fishing ground that is vital to hundreds of small boat
fishermen, many of them already economically distressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have to reduce (cod) mortality. The status quo is not
good enough,'' council member Eric Smith told the audience of more
than 100, but the council will wait until December, when it will
know more about the 1998 catch.
</P>
<P>
   The frayed nerves and short tempers of fishermen were much in
evidence Thursday, after five years of increasingly complex
regulations designed to prevent overfishing through a labyrinth of
catch and size limits, rules governing the mesh of nets, and other
restrictions that vary from place to place.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, dozens of fishermen began shouting in protest of a
council proposal to increase the size of the mesh in fishermen's
nets so that smaller fish get through. ``Look what you're doing to
us! We're just trying to make a living,'' shouted one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know where the fishermen are coming from and they are scared
to death, and they have good reason to be,'' said council member
Jim Kendall, who also works for the New Bedford Seafood Coalition,
before the council decided to delay action on requiring larger mesh
nets.
</P>
<P>
   But council members were aware that delaying action may make
matters worse. Years of delay led to the collapse of one of the
world's greatest fishing grounds, Georges Bank, in 1994, and 13 of
the fishing grounds that the council oversees still are being
fished beyond safe limits.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the National Marine Fisheries Service has concluded that
the cod population in the Gulf of Maine could collapse as well
after three consecutive years of record-low catches of maturing
fish and extreme fishing pressure from boats that no longer fish
Georges Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen countered that cod seems to be increasing where they
fish, but Fisheries Service biologist Ralph Mayo told the council
that anecdotes don't change the fact that the overall fish
population is falling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew this was coming ... for the past couple years. There
was going to be something that affected local guys,'' said Mayo in
an interview, referring to the small-boat fishermen who can't
change fishing grounds if the Gulf of Maine closes. ``Now their
backs are to the wall, both literally and figuratively.''
</P>
<P>
   The council left open the possibility that they will crack down
on Gulf of Maine cod fishing in December, after they have analyzed
the impact of reducing the daily allowable catch from 1,000 pounds
to 400 pounds this year. In particular, council members said they
would consider closing parts of the Gulf where cod spawn from
February to April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want industry to feel that because we vote up or down
on (emergency actions) that the discussion is over. There still
will be discussion of Gulf of Maine cod,'' said council chairman
Joseph Brancaleone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
