r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTTERY-LAUNDER-KAN &LR;      08-27 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-LAUNDER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTTERY OFFICIALS TESTING TICKET THAT WENT THROUGH THE WASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ This money laundering could be costly.
</P>
<P>
   A Powerball ticket accidentally run through the laundry could be
worth $24 million for a man from the Kansas City area. He took
fragments to the lottery office Tuesday, hoping to strike it rich,
and took more in on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The man told lottery officials he bought the ticket at the
convenience store where Saturday's winning ticket was sold. The
state Lottery Commission is testing to see if it is the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   The ticket certainly isn't in winning shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have kids, and I've seen their milk cards when they go
through the washer or dryer look like that,'' said Mike Loftus, the
Missouri Lottery's regional manager in Kansas City. ``It is what it
is _ bits of paper that may or may not be anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Where else but the lottery can untold riches hinge on a dollop
of detergent or the whims of the spin cycle? Ticket mishaps happen
more often than you would think with this much on the line.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City area man, whose name hasn't been released by
lottery officials, never claimed to have a winning ticket. But he
wanted to check. Loftus said an outside laboratory will try to
reconstruct and examine the ticket. Experts can study the ticket's
bar code to determine its authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Scroggins, executive director of the Missouri Lottery, said
that ``at first glance,'' the mangled ticket appeared to be one
where the player selected the numbers. Lottery officials have not
revealed whether the winning numbers _ 7-11-21-22-49, Powerball 19
_ were chosen or randomly generated.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating matters, Loftus said, some of the submitted
fragments contained traces of a ticket bought in Kansas. It's not
clear if the mystery man submitted two mangled tickets or just one
mistaken one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we have clear, convincing, compelling information, we
will not declare it a winner,'' Scroggins said. ``I could see how
it might be disconcerting if you thought you had a winning
ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Disconcerting? Call it your worst nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of poor Giovanni Conterno, an unemployed resident
of Turin, Italy. Conterno tore up a $60,000 winning ticket after
heckling youths convinced him it was worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Or the sad, sad story of Dale Miller, a Florida man who washed
his ticket with his trousers before learning it was a winner. He
threw the ground-up ball away, thinking it was worthless. Then he
learned it could have been identified by lottery officials, and he
spent hours in a fruitless search at a landfill.
</P>
<P>
   However, sometimes the stories have happy endings.
</P>
<P>
   Three friends from Connecticut were able to redeem their winning
$40 million lottery ticket that was in a cooler when a can of
whipped cream exploded over it.
</P>
<P>
   And a state representative in Ohio sponsored a special bill so
Frank Louis III could receive his $100,000 prize, even though his
ticket had disintegrated in the wash. Louis was able to provide
clear evidence that he bought the winning ticket with three others
at a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a feeling of complete hopelessness and helplessness,''
Louis said Wednesday. ``I was so upset at myself for even being in
that situation. But it worked out. I sure wish that fella (in
Kansas City) all the luck in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   States have complex security measures to identify winning
tickets. That's to protect themselves and preserve the credibility
of their games, officials in several states said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Lottery Commission has a chemist on staff who designs
tickets to make them difficult to alter. Oregon contracts with
state police to interview vendors and winners. Manufacturers
maintain a sizable database with detailed information about where
tickets are sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most states have very high-tech methods to check,'' said Barry
Miller, managing editor of Lotto World magazine. ``These lotteries
are open so much to criticism that they do everything possible for
security.''
</P>
<P>
   What about that fine print on the back of the Missouri ticket:
``Tickets are void and will not be paid if stolen, unissued,
illegible, mutilated, altered, counterfeit in whole or in part,
misregistered, defective, incomplete, printed or produced in
error.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri officials said they try to pay a winning ticket even if
it's not in perfect shape.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Torres of the Oregon Lottery said: ``We try to go to
whatever extent we can to pay the prize, but you have to guard that
ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   His office had to deny a prize when a winner's ticket flew out
his car window.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had all the information, but he didn't have a winning
ticket,'' Torres said. ``You do feel bad, but there's only so much
you can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
