A6177 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     08-27 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROUGH THE YEARS WITH ROBERTO DURAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)(SLANG) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ It is the sadness of his sport, the cruelty of his
trade, the unforgiving folly of his untamed lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I can still fight,'' he says, and, oh, could Roberto
Duran fight when he was young and when his reflexes responded
instinctively to his savage commands and when the ring was a place
for him to terrorize people with his theatrical ferocity that made
him the most fearsome gladiator of his generation.
</P>
<P>
   I saw Roberto Duran fight when he was snorting and snarling and
scowling and leaving victims battered haplessly in his feral wake.
</P>
<P>
   I was there at the Olympic Auditorium in February and March of
1973 when he beat up on a couple of Mexican opponents with a wicked
insouciance.
</P>
<P>
   I was there at the Olympic Stadium in Montreal on that rainy
June 20, 1980 evening when he beat Sugar Ray Leonard across 15
dramatic rounds.
</P>
<P>
   I was there at the Superdome in New Orleans on Nov. 20, 1980,
when he uttered his infamous no mas
</P>
<P>
   to Leonard in a shameful surrender that diminished his
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   I was there at Caesars Palace on Nov. 10, 1983, when he regained
a measure of redemption by giving the supposedly invincible, much
larger Marvin Hagler a frightful scare before losing a close
15-round decision.
</P>
<P>
   I was there at Caesars Palace on June 15, 1984, when all his
carousing caught up to him as he went down in two rounds to Thomas
Hearns.
</P>
<P>
   I was there to see him at his best and at his worst, and when he
was at his best there were few in the history of his mean sport
better than this flawed man who emerged from the dangerous streets
of Panama City to cut a memorable swath in his profession.
</P>
<P>
   I was there to see him fight for millions of dollars in front of
awed audiences who thrilled to his deft combinations and thundering
punches and aggressive tactics that so often turned his fights into
solo recitals of his punishing skills.
</P>
<P>
   And I never dreamed I'd be there tonight, on August 28, 1998,
less than a year and a half before the millennium, to watch Roberto
Duran attempt to win the WBA middleweight title from William Joppy
in Elvis Presley's old ballroom at the Las Vegas Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sad, sad spectacle,'' says Bob Arum, and, for once, Arum isn't
saying it because his eternal rival, Don King, is the promoter of
this card that will be shown on Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   It is sad only because Roberto Duran, at 47, no longer should be
doing what he started to do for wages on March 8, 1967 when the
Vietnam War was raging and Lyndon Baines Johnson was president of
the United States and his 28-year-old opponent wasn't even born.
</P>
<P>
   It is sad only because Roberto Duran has to continue fighting
because he has children to support and because he is broke despite
earning more than $50 million during his career.
</P>
<P>
   It is sad only because Roberto Duran has had 115 fights (102-13,
69 KOs), and he is at an age when his anatomy is more vulnerable to
serious risk than it was when he was young and quick and able to
get out of the way of punches meant to maim him.
</P>
<P>
   It is sad only because I remember Roberto Duran when his
presence stirred the multitudes to poetic hymns instead of the
ridicule that now greets his walk down the aisle towards his
appointed destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fight because I still like to,'' he says, and he was to pick
up a pittance, $200,000, to fight tonight because he has to these
melancholy days in which he serves as a symbol of everything that
is wrong in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't you tired of doing it?'' he was asked the other day at
a press conference.
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged with resignation, and said through an interpreter,
``Yes, sometimes. But I must continue. This is what I do. I'm a
fighter. It's what I do best.''
</P>
<P>
   The old fighters like George Foreman and Larry Holmes and Carlos
Palomino and Sugar Ray Leonard keep coming back because they miss
the big paydays and the adulation.
</P>
<P>
   But Roberto Duran never has gone away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duran's like a fighter from my era,'' says the veteran fight
figure Bennie Georgino, and Georgino's era was in the 1940s and
1950s when people like Sugar Ray Robinson and Ezzard Charles
detested hanging up their gloves. ``He's just unbelievable. He's
not what he once was. But he's still damned good.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes me feel uncomfortable that Roberto Duran still is
fighting. I wish boxing's governing bodies would pass laws to keep
aging men like Roberto Duran from ravaging their legacies and
risking their health, but boxing's governing bodies are nodding
toadies for the promoters.
</P>
<P>
   They do what they know will make money for their sport instead
of doing what they know will make sense for the boxers, including
one like Roberto Duran who has no business fighting any longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working extra hard for this fight,'' says Duran
nonchalantly.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Roberto Duran spewed venom, and made
threatening gestures to the person he was scheduled to fight.
</P>
<P>
   The years have done something to Roberto Duran that they do to
all human beings, even the fiercest.
</P>
<P>
   They have mellowed him.
</P>
<P>
   The fire that once burned in his eyes is now gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing is a job to me now,'' he concedes. ``At one time, it
was war. No more. Now it's something I just have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, there were shouts and laughs and thrills
surrounding Roberto Duran.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's only pity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
