<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Friday, Aug. 28 and thereafter. The stories will carry the ``f''
financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For questions
about stories, contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818)
713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WHY (Los Angeles) _ Why is a currency crisis in Russia
swamping the U.S. stock market? After all, Russia's entire stock
market is smaller than some single American companies. Russia's
economy is still primarily internal, and Germany is the major
investor in Russia, not the U.S. Why us? By Deborah Adamson. (Will
move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BEAR-MARKET (Los Angeles) _ Don't look now, but this isn't just
a sell-off or temporary correction on Wall Street, it's a Bear
Market or, at least, in many segments of the market not reflected
in the oft-quoted Dow Jones industrial average. The Russell 2000,
considered the best benchmark of the nation's small cap companies,
fell 20 percent below its all-time high earlier this week. The
Daily News/Bloomberg Index of top Valley-area companies hit that
dubious mark Thursday. The Dow Jones and the S&AMP;P 500, by the way,
are about 10 percent below their all-time highs. By Ben Sullivan.
(Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
