<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Friday, Aug. 28 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   LA-RUSSIANS-REACT (Los Angeles) _ Russian emigres in L.A.'s San
Fernando Valley are concerned about the political and economic
chaos back home. By Sharline Chiang and Jin Whang. (Will move in
the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-CHARTER-REFORM (Los Angeles) _ A dramatic showdown looms as
warring factions present their opposing arguments to the elected
city charter reform commission, prior to a vote by the commission
on whether to expand the Los Angeles City Council. By Patrick
McGreevy. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HORSE-SEIZE-FOLLO (Los Angeles) _ Devastated horse owners who
donated their pets to Renae Ferguson swamped police stations and
animal control offices, desperate to learn the fate of their
horses. Police are scrambling to build their case against her and
her father, after each made bail. By Melissa Schmitt. (Will move in
the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WHY (Los Angeles) _ Why is a currency crisis in Russia
swamping the U.S. stock market? After all, Russia's entire stock
market is smaller than some single American companies. Russia's
economy is still primarily internal, and Germany is the major
investor in Russia, not the U.S. Why us? By Deborah Adamson. (Will
move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BEAR-MARKET (Los Angeles) _ Don't look now, but this isn't just
a sell-off or temporary correction on Wall Street, it's a Bear
Market or, at least, in many segments of the market not reflected
in the oft-quoted Dow Jones industrial average. The Russell 2000,
considered the best benchmark of the nation's small cap companies,
fell 20 percent below its all-time high earlier this week. The
Daily News/Bloomberg Index of top Valley-area companies hit that
dubious mark Thursday. The Dow Jones and the S&AMP;P 500, by the way,
are about 10 percent below their all-time highs. By Ben Sullivan.
(Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
