<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WON'T OFFER MORE MONEY TO RUSSIA, AIDES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: RUSSIA-RDP, RUSSIA-BANKS, RUSSIA-COALITION,
RUSSIA-EUROPE, RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT, RUSSIA-U.S.,
RUSSIA-U.S.-ASSESS, RUSSIA-IMF, RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS, MARKET) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER and STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Russia in economic freefall and only four days
before a planned summit meeting between President Clinton and
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, U.S. officials said Thursday that
Clinton would go to Moscow with words of encouragement but no new
money.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials were hastily rewriting the summit script even as
they scrambled to devise a longer-range plan to prepare for a
Russia without Yeltsin, who has been the focus of U.S. policy for
years.
</P>
<P>
   While the Clinton administration talked Thursday of creating new
policies for a new Russia, the United States seemed to be watching
the events from the sidelines and with a hesitation that contrasted
with the quickly offered monetary aid and statements of assurance
that have met earlier, less serious, crises in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say they have no new answers to Russia's
political and financial crises, and no new money to provide beyond
what the International Monetary Fund has already pledged, and
Clinton has already told that to Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not hit the ground with a bag of tricks,'' a senior
official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Highlighting this sense of uncertainty, a senior U.S. official
for the first time suggested that the summit meeting might be
delayed or canceled, after days of insistence that it would take
place as scheduled despite the lack of a functioning government in
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The official, describing the situation in Russia as ``extremely
fluid,'' said that the administration was watching news reports
with one eye and the financial ticker with the other. As rumors of
Yeltsin's imminent resignation swirled, the value of the Russian
currency tumbled and the Dow Jones industrial average was down for
a time by more than 350 points.
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Samuel Berger repeated the
administration position that the U.S.-Russian relationship was
built on policies, not personalities. Echoing Clinton's comments to
Yeltsin in a telephone call Tuesday, Berger urged the Russian
president and his acting premier, Viktor Chernomyrdin, to continue
on the path of economic reform laid out by the previous government
of Sergei Kiriyenko, whom Yeltsin sacked Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the composition of the government is obviously for the
Russians to decide,'' Berger said during a briefing on the
apprehension of two suspects in the Aug. 7 embassy bombings in
Africa. ``What we were _ what we are concerned about and would be _
are extremely interested in is the policy direction that the new
government takes. Does the new government stay essentially on
course with respect to economic reform and with respect to
democracy, or does it change course? If it changed course in any
kind of fundamental way, that would be of serious concern to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger was the only senior U.S. official to address the Russian
crisis on the record Thursday, a sign that the administration was
mystified by developments in Moscow and uncertain what to say about
them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ignored reporters' shouted questions about Russia during
a visit to Worcester, Mass., for a speech on education policy, and
later lashed out at staffers for not adequately briefing him on the
situation or preparing him for questions on it.
</P>
<P>
   But one White House aide said it was unlikely that Clinton would
have said anything Thursday on the unraveling situation in Russia
in any case, for fear of roiling financial markets and adding to
the instability in Moscow. ``Anything you say, the words get parsed
beyond all belief,'' the official said. ``You say something and it
gets picked apart, and it means whatever investors want it to
mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton received a detailed briefing book for the summit at his
vacation home on Martha's Vineyard on Wednesday night, but it was
not clear whether he had yet read it. Glyn Davies, the executive
secretary of the National Security Council, flew to the island
earlier this week to help prepare Clinton for next week's summit
and to brief him on developments in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke with British Prime Minister Tony Blair late
Thursday afternoon about the Russian crisis and Clinton's visit to
Ireland and Northern Ireland next week, immediately following his
two days in Moscow. The two leaders agreed that continued economic
reform in Russia is ``vital,'' a British spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers returned early to
Washington from vacation to oversee economic preparations for the
summit.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott was in Moscow in a
series of urgent last-minute meetings to try to salvage some
concrete results from next week's meeting and to gauge the climate
for U.S.-Russian relations in months to come.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's departure could certainly scotch plans for the summit,
but U.S. officials discounted reports that he was preparing to step
down. ``Obviously, the situation is tumultuous and day-to-day,''
one administration official said. ``We've heard the rumors, but no
one has given us any hint as of yet that there is a change'' in
Yeltsin's status.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still our expectation that the summit will go forward and
be productive,'' this official said
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the impending summit is a gift for U.S. officials.
It gives them a short-term event to focus on and allows them to put
off for another day the far more difficult question of how to deal
with a foundering and virtually bankrupt nation that possesses
thousands of nuclear weapons. Discussion of those questions has
been put on hold, one official said, until it is clear who will be
running Russia next week _ and after.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
