<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6188 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-2NDTAKE-N     08-27 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: and after.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Also unclear is whether the IMF will deliver the next $4.3
billion payment of a loan package, due Sept. 15. It depends on
Russian legislative action to reform the tax and pension systems _
votes that look increasingly unlikely. The Duma, the lower house of
Parliament, must first confirm Chernomyrdin as prime minister, and
the debate could be contentious and long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot save Russia, only Russia can do that,'' a senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president can't calm the markets,'' he said. ``The markets
will be affected only by clear evidence of Russian seriousness of
purpose, from Yeltsin to the Duma, to fix the problems and ensure
that foreigners get a fair shake. But Clinton can engage Yeltsin in
a discussion of the political imperatives of handling the
economics.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone call to Yeltsin on Tuesday, Clinton pushed him in
that direction, an official said. ``Both Presidents reaffirmed the
importance of a clear, decisive strategy for tackling Russia's
economic crisis,'' said Barry Toiv, deputy White House spokesman.
``President Yeltsin stressed that this will be the top priority of
the new Russian government.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior U.S. officials, in a sign that they believe the Yeltsin
era is all but over, see the summit as a way to begin to build
bridges to the next generation of Russian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's main public address of the two-day summit _ a speech
next Tuesday to students and young business leaders _ is an
explicit effort to speak over the heads of Russia's current leaders
to its people.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will speak about the evolving relationship between the
countries and offer sympathy for the pain of the transformation
Russia is now suffering through, an official involved in summit
preparations said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Clinton is scheduled to meet a dozen or more
parliamentary and regional leaders, another effort to engage with a
new generation of leaders not tainted by the Communist era or the
difficult transitional years of Yeltsin's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of U.S. policy in the United States and in Russia have
often questioned what they call Clinton's overly close relationship
with Yeltsin, ignoring other potential Russian leaders.
Administration officials respond that presidents deal with
presidents, that Russia has only one president at a time, and that
U.S. officials are in contact with Russian politicians at all
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Reddaway, a Russia scholar at George Washington
University, said he thinks Clinton should cancel his trip, in part
because there will be no one of real authority to engage, and in
part because Clinton may be greeted with ``nasty demonstrations or
comments'' from Russians who resent his close relationship with
Yeltsin, whom many Russians revile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be foolish to undertake any initiative, political or
economic, in this volatile situation,'' Reddaway said. ``You can't
have a serious negotiation because there's no real government, and
it's hard to have negotiations with a president who may not be
there for more than a few weeks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
