<SLUG> BC-INVESTOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Advice from a pro: Stay calm in storm
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Does Wall Street's plunge portend worse things to
come?
</P>
<P>
   What should investors do?
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Atlanta money manager Richard Walsman of Sherrill &AMP;
Hutchins advisory:
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-term investors should continue to hold good investments.
Now is not a time to sell, especially if you have to pay taxes on
sizable gains, because you'll have less money to invest when you
put the money back into the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, wild swings in stock prices can be unsettling, even for
savvy investors who realize that a market tumble often serves as a
pause that refreshes.
</P>
<P>
   So it's helpful to keep this in mind:
</P>
<P>
   Stock market declines are unpredictable, not only in timing but
in magnitude. Since 1953, the average stock market drop lasted
eight months. About 75 percent of the declines were recouped in
seven months, with a full rebound, on average, in just over a year.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market rises more often than not. Take the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index. Since 1926, the odds have been 7-to-3 that
it will rise over any 12 months, and 9-to-1 over any five-year
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the longer the investment horizon, the less chance
you're going to have a loss,'' said analyst James Floyd of the
Leuthold Group, a Minneapolis-based investment and research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Study after study shows that market timers, who dart in an out
of stocks as the outlook changes, perform worse that those who do
not attempt to guess at market swings.
</P>
<P>
   The reason?
</P>
<P>
   Most of the increase in stock prices comes in very short bursts,
according to a University of Michigan study of the market between
1963 and 1993. It showed that 95 percent of the gains came in just
1.2 percent of the trading days.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors believe stock market declines are an opportunity
to buy bargain-priced stocks. Walsman is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I would not put all of my uninvested money (in) all at one
time,'' he cautioned. ``The market could go lower before it starts
going up. So it makes sense to commit some money along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Buy quality investments, such as stocks of companies with solid
balance sheets and bright sales and earnings prospects. That's
because in broad market declines, virtually everything goes on sale
initially, but the cream eventually rises to the top.
</P>
<P>
   That also applies to well-run mutual funds, Walsman said. ``I
was just about to pick up the phone to invest my 96-year-old
mother's cash in a growth stock mutual fund,'' said Walsman of the
no-load Marsico Focus Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
