<HEADLINE>
BRUINS, ALLISON FAR APART ON CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He came to Boston to visit some buddies, such as Red
Sox pitcher Tim Wakefield, play in a charity softball game with Ray
Bourque and Don Sweeney, skate a few days, and address some issues
with regard to his living arrangement. But one thing that did not
bring Bruins star center Jason Allison to town is negotiations on a
new contract. The restricted free agent said talks with the club
are at a virtual standstill, the sides miles apart.
</P>
<P>
   Allison, who suited up with a number of other players Thursday
at Boston University, is resolute in his position that he be paid
what he feels he is worth. However, the club is willing to ante up
significantly less, some $6 million over three years if Allison
reaches his incentives. Allison, Boston's top scorer last season,
said that if management is serious about that figure, ``We're in
trouble _ big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant general manager Mike O'Connell said, ``Oh, we're
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison finished ninth in the NHL in scoring with 83 points. The
23-year-old Ontario native was third in plus/minus with a plus-33
and ninth in balloting for the Hart Trophy as MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what their thinking was when they said it was
fair,'' said Allison. ``I don't know if that was their first offer
and it was low because they thought my (demands) were high. If they
honestly think I'm going to go down there for three years, I won't.
I'm willing to work something out. I want to stay here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad it has to be this way. That's the way they do things.
If it goes down to maybe they want to wait until camp to see if
I'll fold in, I'm not going to. They might as well just hammer it
out now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have a reputation for paying less than most teams,
keeping salaries in line, and not showing the kind of monetary
insanity demonstrated by other teams. But in Allison's view, that
doesn't mean he should agree to shorter money than he might make
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the right way to look at things,'' he said. ``If
you're in New York, you shouldn't say, `I'm in New York, I should
ask for more than I deserve,' or `I'm in Boston so I have to take
less.' That's what they want everybody on the team to think.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying teams should go out and sign free agents for $6
million but (the Bruins) are in a big market, they have the money,
they do well, it's a great hockey city. Pay your guys what they
deserve and that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' position is that Allison has had one terrific
season, which doesn't guarantee that subsequent ones will be the
same. O'Connell, who said he was reluctant to discuss the situation
because he feared a controversy would turn off fans much the way
the Mo Vaughn acrimony has, believes the club has done its homework
and that the offer to Allison is not only realistic but proper
under the collective bargaining agreement in place.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins sign Allison to a one-year deal, he has
arbitration rights next summer. O'Connell said that would be fine
with them because they are comfortable with their preparation for
the arbitration process. They'd be willing to agree to a three-year
deal if terms could be worked out, but he doesn't believe a
two-year deal would serve the club's purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what I say, people are going to think we're
cheap no matter what we do,'' said O'Connell. ``The ball's in the
air right now. Where do we go from here? I don't know. We'll see
how it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears to be going nowhere, which means that when training
camp opens for veterans Sept. 12, Allison will be nowhere in sight.
He acknowledged that the three-year proposal appears to be high,
but from the perspective of being the ninth-leading scorer in the
league, ``It's not high, it's low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their argument isn't that they don't think I'll do it again,
it's that I've only done it once and that's all they have to pay
me,'' said Allison. ``Right now they do (have leverage) but when
the season starts, who's got the leverage? I don't want it to come
down to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of upset that they didn't try a little harder. I'm
not surprised it's not done yet, but I am surprised they waited so
long. I figured they'd want to get me signed up so I can get ready
for camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I want to do is sit out, but if it's my only
option ... and I'm pretty stubborn, so ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good year last year, we had a breakthrough year with
a young team. Everyone is going to get better. If we don't get
everyone back, where does that leave the team?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bruins assistant general Mike O'Connell said the club is
attempting to schedule a meeting with Ray Bourque to negotiate an
extension of the 37-year-old defenseman's contract.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque has one year remaining, which will be his 20th season in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell expects to sit down sometime before training camp,
likely right after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque consistently has said he won't decide whether to play
after this season until he determines how he feels physically. It's
likely that he would want to stick around if the Bruins became a
legitimate Stanley Cup contender.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins captain is scheduled to become an unrestricted free
agent at the end of the season, and the Bruins would like to lock
him up to prevent a bidding war for his services next July 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
