<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKSTOCKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big Southeast banks mostly insulated from Russian troubles
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Bank stocks fell sharply Thursday, triggered by an
announcement from Republic New York that it will take a $110
million charge in the third quarter for losses in Russian
government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The major banks doing business in the metro area suffered along
with their peers. But they have little overseas exposure and
virtually none in Russia. The exception is NationsBank, which is
soon to mate with BankAmerica. The latter has long courted the
world.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica has $412 million invested in Russia, but that's not
a large slice of pie given that the total assets of the new company
will be about $570 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For its own part NationsBank has a total exposure of about $1.6
billion in Asia and $3.2 billion in Latin America, spokesman Robert
Stickler said. Combined that represents about 1.6 percent of
NationsBank's assets of $308 billion.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank closed at $65, down $4.25, BankAmerica at 73.75,
down $3.87 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a major player in the international arena,'' said
SunTrust Banks spokesman James Armstrong. ``The total amount
outstanding, including loans, acceptances (and) deposits at foreign
banks is $351 million, which is less than 1 percent of our loans.
Almost all of that is Canadian or U.K. exposure,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   SunTrust Banks hit a 52 week low of $58.37 1/2 before closing at
$59.25, down $2. It had reached a 52-week high a little over a
month ago and a few days prior to displeasing the market with the
announcement that it will buy Crestar Financial of Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our total loan exposure in Asia, which is typically short-term
trade financing in Korea, Japan, and Southeast Asia is
approximately 1 percent, or $1.3 billion, of our total loan
portfolio,'' said Mitchell Singer, a spokesman for First Union.
</P>
<P>
   As for investments by First Union, by policy it does not ``have
exposure to emerging markets,'' said John Peters, who heads the
group that makes investments for the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our foreign government bond portfolio, everything around the
world, constitutes about 8 percent,'' or $3 billion, of the banks
investment portfolio. ``A little over half of that is exposure to
Germany,'' which has done well, he said. ``At the end of June our
foreign division had unrealized gains of $50 million.''
</P>
<P>
   First Union closed $1.37 1/2 lower at $50.37 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Wachovia, which lost $3.06 1/4 to $79.25, said it has no loans
or equipment leases in Russia, and its international loans and
leases total $700 million out of total assets of $65 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
