 Thursday, Aug. 27, 1998     
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file these stories for
Friday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920. For questions about Houston
Chronicle sports stories, please call the Houston Chronicle Sports
Department, 713-220-7896.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: CLINTON-DEMS.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSY-BOMBINGS-FBI (Washington) _ Although FBI Director Louis
Freeh praises the work of U.S. investigators for the capture of a
suspect in the embassy bombings in Africa, court documents show
that the case's big break may have come from Kenyan hospital
workers who alerted the authorities to keys retrieved from the
wounded suspect. By MARK HELM. (1stld-writethru filed)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEMS (Washington) _ A pall has settled over areas of the
country where Democrats had hoped to pick up congressional seats
this November, leaving party leaders wondering whether they can
overcome uneasiness generated by President Clinton's admission of
an affair with a young White House intern. By GREG McDONALD.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   TROOPS-TEACHERS (Washington) _ A highly regarded, five-year
``troops to teachers'' program that has sent more than 3,000
veterans from front lines to classrooms is now ending. The National
Center for Education Information, a private research organization
here, releases a survey showing how the vets feel about a wide
range of education issues. By NICOLE TSONG. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCHOOLS (Worcester, Mass.) _ President Clinton takes a
brief break from his Martha's Vineyard vacation to deliver a speech
on crime and violence in schools. The president made no mention of
his affair with Monica Lewinsky, but he was confronted with a few
sign-wielding people urging him to resign. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   FEAR-CRIME (Austin, Texas) _ Texans are less afraid of crime now
than they were 20 years ago, according to a study by Sam Houston
State University's Criminal Justice Center. In 1978, more than half
of those surveyed were afraid to walk alone at night in their
neighborhoods; today only 1 in 3 express that fear. By KATHY WALT.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-AFTERMATH (New Bern, N.C.) _ Bonnie has been downgraded
to a tropical storm and continues to creep along the coast of North
Carolina, dumping rain but causing no deaths or major damage.
Forecasters believe the remnants of the hurricane may continue to
hug the coast as it moves north. By TONY FREEMANTLE.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ For the past six months, I have been
saying that the only way to quiet the Monica Lewinsky scandal is
for President Clinton to resign. But while I think his departure is
inevitable, he must exit in his own way, on his own terms, in his
own time. And that time has not yet come. By MARIANNE MEANS.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS-100WINS (Houston) _ For the first time in franchise
history, the Houston Astros have a realistic chance to win 100
games in a season. With 29 games remaining, the Astros need to win
17 games to hit the magic number. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-SOLICH (Lincoln, Neb.) _ It is never easy to replace a
legend. Just ask some of those who have tried _ Fred Akers, Phil
Bengston, Earle Bruce, Ray Perkins. That is especially true in
college football _ where coaches often are bigger than the players
they guide. Frank Solich is the latest to take the leap as the
longtime Nebraska assistant takes over for his former boss, Tom
Osborne. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HYDE-PROFILE (Washington) _ House Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., faces the ultimate challenge of his 23-year career in the
House: navigating it through possible impeachment proceedings
against President Clinton. Democrats and Republicans alike say that
if anyone can prevent the process from degenerating into a partisan
mudbath, it's Hyde. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   KOREAN-MEMORIAL (Washington) _ To U.S. veterans who fought in
the Korean War, a memorial on the National Mall here was a long
time coming. It opened in 1995, 42 years after the bloody conflict
ended. Now, after only three years, it's crumbling because of
serious construction defects that will take a year and $2 million
to fix. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed)
</P>
