<HEADER>
A6198 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WBL-STING-LADN     08-27 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WBL-STING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUG PULLED ON STINGRAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Katrina Price was the first to arrive. The
rookie from Stephen F. Austin made the long haul from Waco, Texas,
with the help of her sisters, stopping overnight in New Mexico
before finishing to the 23-hour trek to Long Beach on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Williams arrived Monday, with a brace on her left knee.
She came early to have an MRI test performed Tuesday and, like
Price, to locate an apartment for the upcoming season. Natalie
Williams
</P>
<P>
   lives in Seal Beach.
</P>
<P>
   A tryout for practice players was planned for Sunday at the
Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Natalie Williams, who was preparing to leave for
Colorado Springs to train with the USA national team, everyone was
due to report Monday. Despite disturbing financial issues
confronting the troubled American Basketball League, located in Bay
Area conclave of Palo Alto, the grassroots women's professional
league was set to begin its third season of existence, its second
with the StingRays franchise in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Training camp was still a month away, but Maura McHugh was
excited about the prospect of coaching this transformed team.
</P>
<P>
   Season ticket sales were extremely slow, as well as corporate
sponsorships, but the front office was confident things would turn
around quickly once the players came in and used September to
market themselves to the community. The team was in the process of
signing sponsorships with Gillette and Vons.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Bill McGillis continued to work tirelessly into
the night, making speech after speech on the StingRays' behalf
during the day. He had a skeleton staff no marketing or ticket
director that was doing the best it could with very limited
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Media director Linda Reid was finishing up the media guide that
highlighted the coming of Natalie Williams and the return of
starters Beverly Williams, Clarissa Davis-Wrightsil
</P>
<P>
   and Andrea Nagy.
</P>
<P>
   And then, poof, just like that it was gone. The enduring
practices, the long road trips, the hopes and dreams of returning
to the championship, the 15-hour work days, all of it was gone in
an instant. Effective immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe in the ABL and I'm optimistic about the ABL's
future,'' McGillis said. ``I understand that this was a business
decision. The investors in the league have spent a lot of money.
The goal is to sustain the league. It's unfortunate that we're not
going to give the franchise more time to mature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were making progress. It's difficult to project what this
market could do at this time. Southern California is the toughest
sports market in the country. There's plenty of evidence of that.''
</P>
<P>
   McGillis was offered the general manager job in Columbus, McHugh
was offered a position in the league's player personnel office.
Neither have accepted and are unsure if they will. Like a deck of
cards, the players were divided up and shuffled off to the other
nine teams. The league is going to fly Price to Philadelphia, where
her car and personal things will be shipped, Beverly Williams plans
to return to Austin and have surgery next week for a torn anterior
cruciate ligament, before reporting to the two-time defending
champion Columbus Quest.
</P>
<P>
   After learning about the league's decision to fold the StingRays
on Wednesday, McHugh spent much of the morning and afternoon trying
to contact players. Some she reached. Others received calls from
Tracey Williams,
</P>
<P>
   ABL vice president in charge of player personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been the hardest thing for me, talking to the
players,'' McHugh said, sitting in her office at the World Trade
Center. ``There was some sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand why they did what they did. I know that what they
did was for the longevity of the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league has to look at what's best for the league. We look
at it with tunnel vision.''
</P>
<P>
   McHugh's involvement in the future of the league is uncertain.
She has two years remaining on her contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thing is to be a coach,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now she'll consult with her agent to figure out her next move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm keeping all my options open.''
</P>
<P>
   She's not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Natalie Williams, the former Portland Power center and league
MVP last season, was traded to the StingRays on her insistence to
use a clause in her contract that stated she could play in Long
Beach. That's the main reason she signed for two years. She has
nothing personal against Portland, which she helped win the Western
Division last season and where she was reassigned to return, she
just wanted to be in nearby Southern California where she was a
two-sport All-American at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   She's now relying on her agent and lawyers to figure out whether
she's a free agent or if her contract is void.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally don't know for sure,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   She just wishes the league could of have had a little more
patience with the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I think Long Beach would have done a lot better. I
think more people would have come to the games than they estimated.
I know in L.A. people come as they will. It's unfortunate that they
didn't give them a chance. I think it definitely would have been a
lot more than last year,'' Williams figured.
</P>
<P>
   The league rushed to get a team into Long Beach, where it
thought it could thrive in a large television market as well as
feed off the Long Beach State women's basketball tradition of the
'80s, ABL chief executive officer Gary Cavalli said.
</P>
<P>
   On the first point, the networks ``didn't give us credit for
being in Long Beach. We were in Long Beach, not L.A.,'' Cavalli
said. On the second strategy, ``The Long Beach State tradition
seems to be a thing of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, so are the StingRays.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Venus Lacy, the 1996 Olympian and former center for the
StingRays, has signed a one-year contract extension with the
American Basketball League. Lacy was traded to the expansion
Nashville Noise for Stacey Lovelace, who originally was with the
now-defunct Atlanta Glory. ... Results from an MRI test taken
Monday show that Los Angeles Sparks center Lisa Leslie suffered a
strained right knee. Leslie was expected to join the national team
in Colorado Springs next Monday and participate in a five-game
tournament with the Australian national team, followed by a WNBA
select-team tour in Brazil. Doctors, however, have recommended that
she not play for a month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
