<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BOMB-ART-NYT &LR;      08-27 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BOMB-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB EXPLODES IN TEL AVIV, WOUNDING A WOMAN SERIOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map and a photo are being sent to NYT
graphics/photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A pipe bomb exploded in a trash can on a busy Tel
Aviv street Thursday, causing one serious injury and adding to a
new wave of tension in Israel and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions, in turn, have followed new signs that Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu may finally be prepared to strike a
deal with the Palestinians that would enable peace negotiations to
resume. The negotiations have been effectively frozen since March
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Police described the bombing as a ``terrorist attack,'' a term
usually denoting Arabs. There were no immediate arrests, and no
Palestinian organization claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion happened at about 8:50 a.m. on Allenby Street in
central Tel Aviv. Police said the crude device consisted of about
100 grams of explosive in a pipe packed with nails.
</P>
<P>
   The plastic bin absorbed much of the blast, though many
surrounding shop windows were shattered. One woman was reported in
serious condition, and about 20 other people were treated for cuts,
burns or shock.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing was the first in Tel Aviv since March 1997 and the
first in Israel in almost a year, and it came at a time of
heightened tensions on the northern border and in Hebron in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In the north, a barrage of Katyusha rockets fired by guerrillas
of the militant Islamic Hezbollah movement from southern Lebanon on
Tuesday struck the Israeli town of Qiryat Shemona and parts of
western Galilee. The rockets caused only minor injuries and damage,
but they raised the threat that Israel would retaliate and trigger
a new round of violence in the north.
</P>
<P>
   The Katyusha attack followed an Israeli strike that killed a
leader of another Islamic militia, Amal. The chief, Husam Amin, was
struck by a laser-guided missile fired from an Apache helicopter
gunship as he drove in his car near Tyre on the Lebanese coast.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear, however, whether the Hezbollah strike was in
retaliation for the killing of Amin, or for an earlier shelling of
Hezbollah strongholds by Israel's Christian allies in southern
Lebanon, the South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah has insisted for several years that it fires rockets
into northern Israel only when Israel or the the South Lebanon Army
launch attacks outside Israel's self-proclaimed buffer zone in
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In Hebron, more than 1,000 militant Jewish settlers gathered
Thursday in the tiny, hill-side settlement known as Tel Rumeida to
mark the end of the seven-day mourning period for a 63-year-old
rabbi who was stabbed to death in his home by an assailant who
climbed through a window.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Rabbi Shlomo Raanan, a grandson of a venerated
chief rabbi in Palestine before the establishment of the state of
Israel, raised the level of hatred in the old center of Hebron,
where about 450 militant Jews live under heavy army protection,
even higher that usual. Though only seven Jewish families live in
the cluster of prefabricated houses in Tel Rumeida, they are
regarded as among the most radical of the Hebron settlers.
</P>
<P>
   The 20,000 Palestinians who live in the section of Hebron still
under Israeli military control have been under a curfew since the
shooting, which has been lifted for only a few hours daily to
enable the Arabs to shop. But settlers have repeatedly tried to
beat Palestinians, or to damage their windows, market stalls or
cars.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 Israeli troops were mobilized for the memorial
service Thursday, and the only incidents were a few scuffles as
settlers tried to beat and eject Palestinian photographers and
television cameramen.
</P>
<P>
   At the memorial service, militants voiced standard demands that
the government cease ceding land to ``terrorists'' and that the
army take stern action against them.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the stabbing last week, Netanyahu pledged
his government would build permanent housing for 50 families in Tel
Rumeida. The promise was apparently intended to placate the
settlers. Both President Ezer Weizman and Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, whose moderate politics have made them special targets
of settler antipathy, were fiercely denounced at Thursday's rally.
</P>
<P>
   When Weizman paid a condolence call on Rabbi Raanan's family
last Sunday, he was assailed by a well-known radical, Baruch
Marzel, who shouted, ``You are a spy and a danger to the public and
should be put in an institution.'' Marzel was summoned by police
under Israeli laws against abusing public officials, and he said he
was questioned and released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions have risen just as new signs were surfacing that
Netanyahu might be approaching a decision on withdrawing Israeli
forces from 13 percent of the West Bank _ which would enable
negotiations with the Palestinians to resume.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week in Oslo, Norway, Yasser Arafat, head of the
Palestinian Authority, declared that he could accept Israel's plan
to include existing nature reserves as part of the 13 percent
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   But in subsequent statements, the Israeli leader appeared to
retreat on another issue, that of convening the full Palestinian
National Council _ the ``parliament'' of the Palestine Liberation
Organization _ to redraft the Palestinian covenant and excise all
calls for Israel's destruction. Netanyahu had been reported ready
to settle for the task to be done by some body other than the
council, which includes many Palestinian radicals in exile.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting victims of Thursday's explosion in Tel Aviv, Netanyahu
declared, ``I want to declare in the clearest possible way that
there will not be a deal if the Palestinian Authority does not
fight _ in deeds and words _ murderers and terror.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
