<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-RITTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS RAISED ABOUT US STANCE ON IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS   AND COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just six months after the United States avoided a
war with Iraq, diplomats and independent analysts say the Clinton
administration has ineffective sanctions and no viable weapons
inspection to check Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of the most outspoken American on the UN
inspection team raised questions Thursday about why Washington
softened its stance against Baghdad and blocked surprise
inspections even while talking tough about a possible attack.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Ritter, a retired Marine captain who spent the past seven
years as a weapons inspector, fanned the controversy Thursday, a
day after resigning, when he said the UN Security Council and the
Clinton administration were breaking promises to disarm Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter's conclusion: Iraq would keep its weapons of mass
destruction. ``People (who) think that they can just sit back and
say sanctions can bring Iraq into the fold; they are wrong,''
Ritter told the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview with the Globe, Ritter gave the impression of a
man who had been abandoned by his country. He confirmed that he had
been questioned by the FBI for sharing intelligence with Israel,
but he called the investigation ``baseless.''
</P>
<P>
   United Nations sources confirmed a Washington Post report that
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright and other top US officials
had pressured the UN special commission teams, known as UNSCOM, to
call off surprise inspections in Iraq several times in the past
eight months. The administration did not want to provoke a fight
with Iraq that could lead to military conflict or an end to the
econonomic sanctions imposed by the UN, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping up pressure on the administration to define its Iraq
policy, John McCain, a member of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, Thursday called for hearings on Iraq after the summer
recess.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings should examine whether the administration has
thwarted Iraq's development of chemical and biological weapons ``or
whether it has sought merely to avoid another inconvenient crisis
in the Persian Gulf,'' McCain wrote to committee chairman Strom
Thurmond, a fellow Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is evident that our policy on Iraq is coming unglued,''
said another Republican, James M. Inhofe, chairman of the Senate
Armed Forces Readiness Subcommittee. While Democrats in Congress
mostly kept their criticisms muted, an aide to an influential
Democratic senator who follows the Persian Gulf questioned whether
the administration had been soft on Iraq. ``I would guess there's
going to be some explaining to do,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy is especially worrisome for President Clinton
and Albright, who repeatedly vowed not to make concessions during
last winter's standoff with Hussein. They defused a crisis with
Iraq in February by letting Secretary General Kofi Annan mediate
with Hussein as three US warships cruised offshore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very troubling,'' said L. Paul Bremer III, the Reagan
administration's director of counterterrorism. ``I didn't like the
Kofi Annan agreement then and it looks naked now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bremer traced the current troubles with Iraq to 1991, when
President Bush halted the Gulf War while most of Iraq's Republican
Guard troops, tanks, and weapons were still intact. As the war
ended, Hussein agreed to abandon all efforts to produce chemical,
biological and nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're saying he can keep the weapons too _ at least that's
what it looks like,'' said Francis Brooke, a spokesman for the
Iraqi National Congress, a group that opposes Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   In a press conference at UN headquarters, Richard Butler, the
director of the inspection teams, said the Clinton administration
had not placed ``undue'' pressure on him to rein in inspectors.
Butler also praised Ritter, 37, as a ``man of integrity'' who
served courageously in the face of intense Iraqi hostility.
</P>
<P>
   UNSCOM sources privately said they felt betrayed by Washington
and the United Nations. ``There are voices up there on the 38th
floor that do whisper that ... it's Butler's fault,'' one UNSCOM
official said, referring to senior aides to Annan who have
advocated a gentler approach to dealing with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters, Ritter said the disarmament effort will
fail unless the United States resumes its threat to use force
against Iraq. He also accused Annan of being too conciliatory
toward Iraq, which has invaded its neighbors and killed ethnic
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secretary general is not a fair broker and his office
includes a number of officials with pro-Iraqi bias,'' Ritter said.
</P>
<P>
   A UN spokesman, Fred Eckhard, characterized Ritter's comments on
Annan as unfair. Annan's job includes acting as a sounding board
for the grievances of all member states, including unpopular
countries like Iraq, Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has often singled Ritter out for criticism, calling him a
spy for the CIA and the Israeli intelligence service Mossad. ``The
resignation of the American-Zionist intelligence officer Scott
Ritter from the Special Commission is because his connection with
the Zionist Mossad was uncovered,'' a spokesman for the Ministry of
Culture and Information said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter scoffed at the allegations, but he made no secret of his
unhappiness at being questioned by the FBI. ``Scott Ritter has been
the target of so much abuse by the Iraqis and he has held up
remarkably well,'' said Ewen Buchanan, a spokesman for UNSCOM.
``They call him a spy, they vilify him and they hound him in the
media and he takes it all in stride.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a State Department official said the United
States is seeking to tighten economic constraints on Iraq. The
officials said the United States has stepped up pressure on Turkey
and Jordan to prevent hundreds of millions of dollars worth of
smuggled oil from crossing the border.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Washington also wants the Security Council to deduct the more
than $600 million Iraq earns from smuggling from the more than $5
billion Baghdad is allowed to sell each year in order to buy food.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; And some observers said the Clinton administration is better
off deemphasizing the threat of force. Richard W. Murphy, a former
assistant secretary of state for the Near East and South Asia under
Presidents Reagan and Bush, said that looking for every bit of
weapons material in Iraq is a fruitless exercise.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  He recommended placing stiffer economic sanctions on Hussein
until he complies with every last demand or loses power.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I can understand Ritter's frustration,'' Murphy said, ``but
my attitude is there are some things we are never going to get
done: We're never going to totally uproot all of Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marcus reported from Washington and Lynch reported from the
United Nations.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
