<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBYA-LOCKERBIE-370&AMP;A     08-27 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBYA-LOCKERBIE-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GADHAFI SAYS `NEGOTIATION' IS NEEDED ON LOCKERBIE SUSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Col. Moammar Gadhafi said Thursday that Libya
would have to negotiate certain guarantees before he could feel
confident about turning over for trial two suspects wanted in the
1988 bombing of a Pan Am jet over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with CNN from Tripoli, Gadhafi seemed obsessed
with fears of U.S. and British trickery. Experts say he may be
afraid that the two suspects, who are intelligence agents, will be
kidnapped by the West or pumped at the trial for more information
than he wants to see made public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not sure America and the U.K. have good intentions to
solve this problem,'' Gadhafi said in English. ``I expect mines. I
expect tricks, conditions, to make the trial impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he was stopping short of a promise to turn over
the agents, the Libyan leader added, ``Negotiation must be done.''
</P>
<P>
   He also warned against unspecified unacceptable provisions in a
U.N. Security Council resolution that would suspend sanctions
imposed on Libya in 1992 and 1993. Under the sanctions,
international air travel to and from Libya is barred, and the
Libyans are not permitted to import arms and spare parts for the
oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution would also threaten ``further measures'' if Libya
failed to turn over the two agents.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects, Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa
Fhimah, would be tried before a panel of Scottish judges in a
special courtroom in an as-yet-undetermined place in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the United States and Britain had demanded a
trial in Scotland or the United States. Of the 270 people killed in
the crash over Lockerbie, 189 were Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gadhafi, dressed in casual Western clothes rather than the more
elaborate desert robes he often wears, was seated in a wheelchair
during the interview Thursday. He said he had broken his leg when
he fell while taking part in sports.
</P>
<P>
   At the Middle East Institute in Washington, Mary-Jane Deeb,
editor of the Middle East Journal, said Gadhafi's appearance in a
wheelchair re-ignited interest in reports that his motorcade had
been shot at on a trip through the desert a few months ago.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``There were rumors that the motorcade was attacked and that
shots were fired and that he was hurt,'' she said. ``A few days
later, statements were made that said nothing had happened to him.
But then he turned up in hospital saying that he had been playing
soccer and that he had to have hip surgery or something of the
sort.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a couple of months ago, and I would assume by now
that he should have been on his own two feet'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Deeb, a professor of international relations at American
University and the author of two books on Libya, said Gadhafi's
repeated references to Western tricks and pitfalls reflected not
only his fears that too much information would emerge in a trial
but also that other nations work the way Libya does, and that his
intelligence agents could find themselves whisked off to Washington
as captives.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lives in a world of conspiracies and fears and anxieties,''
she said. ``He is a despot in his own country, and that's what he
would probably do himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Arab diplomats here say that while Gadhafi knows he is now
closer to having sanctions lifted than he has been in more than six
years, he also knows that he faces some political risk in turning
over one of the two men. Megrahi is a member of a powerful Libyan
tribe that supports the Libyan leader, who is not popular with
other tribes in a society based on tribal loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   To turn Megrahi over to the British and Americans could inflame
his tribe, a Middle Eastern official said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Gadhafi's comments and government statements over the last few
days have left U.S. diplomats perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't pretend to interpret what Libya's position is,''
said Peter Burleigh, the deputy U.S. representative at the United
Nations. ``I don't think it's clear. It is not clear to me that
they have accepted the proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told
reporters, ``We will know whether they have accepted formally when
the suspects show up at the court.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
