<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6220 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-ART-(800)2TAKE     08-27 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-(800)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS AROUND THE WORLD RUSH TO THE EXITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: MARKET, MARKET-LOSES, MARKET-INVESTORS,
MARKET-COMMODITIES, RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS, RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT,
RUSSIA-EMERGE) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock market investors around the world rushed the
exits Thursday. Too many troubling economic questions and not
enough calming answers spurred selling from the time Wall Street
opened.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst trading day this year, the Dow Jones industrial
average fell 4.19 percent, or 357 points, to close at 8165.99. The
Nasdaq composite fell 81.72 points to close down 4.62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dow average now 12.5 percent below its July 17 high of
9337.97, investors are well into what Wall Street calls a
correction. Bear market territory _ defined as a stock price
decline of 15 percent to 20 percent _ is at hand.
</P>
<P>
   World markets fell in unison, with the exception of Hong Kong,
which was up slightly. In Europe, key indexes fell 3 percent to 6
percent, with the Dax index in Germany dropping 4.48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, disappointed in Japan's inability to repair its
broken-down economy, drove the Nikkei 225 index down 3.04 percent
long before trading began in the United States. Policy paralysis
seems to have overtaken Japanese politicians, who appear unwilling
to take steps to solve their well-documented problems. The Nikkei
has fallen 16.5 percent this year from its March high.
</P>
<P>
   Volume in U.S. stocks was heavy Thursday: 940 million shares
exchanged hands on the New York Stock Exchange, close to the record
1.1 billion shares that traded last October when the market
declined 554 points. Margin calls were a major factor in the
carnage Thursday, as brokerage firms asked investors who had
borrowed to buy stocks to prop up their depleted portfolios with
more cash. During the morning, when an investor telephoned the
mutual fund giant T. Rowe Price to move some funds, a recorded
message announced that there would be a two-minute wait before a
representative picked up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Traders and money managers reported a flood of early selling
that continued in waves all day. Even though stocks tried to rally
several times during the day, few, if any, buyers were willing to
pick through the rubble for bargains. The market closed at its low
for the day, a sign of overwhelming market weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit Thursday in U.S. markets were shares of big
international banks, down an average 6.6 percent on fears of
exposure to Russia-related lending losses. But rampant selling
ravaged even the most favored stocks, such as Coca Cola, General
Electric, Microsoft as well as internet darlings Excite Inc. and
Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   That even the healthiest companies' shares got punished was
attributable to investors forced to meet margin calls on their
emerging market investments. American investors are learning the
hard way, that when an investor has to cough up cash because his
foreign investments are cratering, he sells whatever he can. Often
that means selling the biggest, most liquid investment he has. Or
the investment he still has a profit in.
</P>
<P>
   It is a vicious circle, said William Dudley, economist at
Goldman, Sachs in New York. ``People are becoming increasingly
risk-averse, leading to lower equity prices, increasing pressure on
emerging market economies. Absent right now is any mechanism to
break that dynamic up.'' As a result, Dudley believes investors
should brace themselves for more downside moves.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news started early Thursday. At 9:46 a.m., shares in
Republic New York Corp, the parent of Republic Bank, halted trading
in anticipation of a news report. Minutes later, the bank announced
it would take a $110 million charge in the third quarter for losses
in Russian government bonds. The loss would virtually eliminate
earnings for the period, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it became clear that the ultimate impact of the
Russian disaster was still unknown. If Republic Bank, known for its
strong balance sheet and conservative lending practices, was hurt
by Russia, what would happen to more aggressive lenders?
</P>
<P>
   With its announcement, Republic Bank became the first domestic
bank to shed light on its Russian losses. Market historians noted
that Republic was also the first domestic bank, back in the
mid-1980s, to reveal the extent of its exposure to lesser-developed
country debt that later hammered Citicorp and other American banks.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in financial stocks Thursday found themselves in a
nightmarish version of the child's game of hot potato. Exposure to
Russia's ruble devaluation and effective default on its debt is
only starting to be defined. And since many of the losses will be
taken by investors who bought or sold derivative securities, where
the folks who took the other side of a given trade, called
counterparties, are not immediately identifiable, it could be weeks
before the true effects of what may be $100 billion in losses are
known. Some investors wondered why a country as economically
inconsequential as Russia should play such a dramatic role in world
market turmoil. Yes, Russian wields nuclear firepower, but it
accounts for just 1 percent of the world's trade, roughly
equivalent to that of Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts explained Russia's role in Thursday's world market woes
this way: what happened there could very well replay in the
emerging markets of Latin America. When investors see their
portfolios lose 80 percent of their value, as those holding Russian
debt have, two things happen. Assets in other emerging markets need
to be repriced lower to reflect this new economic reality. And, as
those assets are repriced, investors and lenders withdraw from the
markets, cutting off companies' access to capital.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's default also made it painfully obvious that the
International Monetary Fund is no longer ready or able to bail out
countries in economic despair. Bailouts in Korea, Malaysia and
Thailand had lulled investors into believing that the IMF was
effectively a guarantor of their investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capital is contracting rapidly from every place that has to
pay a premium to get money,'' said Martin Armstrong, chairman of
Princeton Economic Institute in Princeton, N.J. ``The Russia impact
is having serious significance in the sense that banks that have
taken hits there go down the entire emerging market group and
withdraw their credit lines.''
</P>
<P>
   So what investors are facing now is the very thing Wall Street
fears the most: the unknown. The devil we know, an imploding Russia
in this case, is bad enough. The devil we don't know, what other
economic disasters lie ahead, most particularly in Latin America,
is considerably worse.
</P>
<P>
   All eyes are on Latin America. That's because a crisis in these
nations would strike a severe blow to both American investors and
corporations. Some 25 percent of Brazil's $300 billion in domestic
debt, for example, is held by foreign investors. More important,
around 20 percent of U.S. exports go to Latin America.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some investors marveled at the selling that has taken some
stocks down 75 percent from their highs. One money manager said
that this is what happens when investors buy stocks only because
they are going up. ``People have been investing by the direction of
earnings and not looking at value,'' said David Eidelman, at
Eidelman, Finger, Harris &AMP; Co. in St. Louis. ``If earnings are
going higher, they buy. But when they start to see earnings come
down, they look at the direction not the value.'' As a result,
stocks get bid down too low. To paraphrase Oscar Wilde, these
investors, so-called momentum players, know the price of everything
and the value of nothing.
</P>
<P>
   More than one professional trader said that Thursday's action in
U.S. stocks was reminiscent of the beginning of the end of the
great bull market of the late 1960s and early 1970s. These traders
recalled that the 1973 bear market, which removed 45 percent from
the Dow Jones industrial average, didn't begin in earnest until the
Nifty Fifty stocks _ names like Polaroid _ crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, approximately 15 stocks _ including Dell
Computer, Lucent Technologies and Cisco Systems _ have held up
while the rest of the U.S. market have fallen. Thursday, even these
shares fell hard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
