<HEADER>
A6225 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-FOREIGN-POLICY-D     08-27 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FOREIGN-POLICY-DECEIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SHOULD APOLOGIZE FOR FOREIGN-POLICY DECEIT  
 (THIS EDITORIAL WILL APPEAR IN FRIDAY'S ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - (begin ital) Good evening. This afternoon in this
room, from this chair, I testified before the Office of Public
Opinion. I must take complete responsibility for all my actions,
both public and private. And that is why I am speaking to you
tonight. As you know, in a deposition, I was asked questions about
my relationship with the U.N. Special Commission and my efforts to
delay or prevent intrusive weapons inspections in Iraq by United
Nations teams.
</P>
<P>
   While my answers were legally accurate, I did not volunteer
information. Indeed, I did have a relationship that was not
appropriate. In fact, it was wrong. It constituted a critical lapse
in judgment and a personal failure on my part for which I am solely
and completely responsible. (end ital) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, it could happen.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it should happen.
</P>
<P>
   So outrageous is the clandestine abandonment of candor and
principle in the implementation of U.S. foreign policy, that it,
too, probably requires a public apology by the president.
</P>
<P>
   While the administration was proclaiming the right to
``unfettered, unconditional inspections'' of any site in Iraq, at
any time, Clinton officials, according to the ``Washington Post,''
repeatedly were trying to halt surprise searches for weapons of
mass destruction in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the United States withdrew critical equipment and
personnel that had helped U.N. inspectors with their tasks.
</P>
<P>
   So unprincipled has been U.S. policy in this regard that the
longest-serving U.S. weapons inspector, former Marine intelligence
officer Scott Ritter, resigned in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   He said the failure to aggressively push ahead with the
inspections was ``a surrender to Iraqi leadership'' and made a
farce ``of the commission's efforts to prove that Iraq was
concealing chemical, biological and nuclear weapons programs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I fought in the war,'' he said. ``Americans died in the war. I
was told by my government in April 1991, in a U.N. Security Council
resolution the United States sponsored, that Iraq was going to
disarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've devoted seven years, at tremendous personal sacrifice.
I've poured my heart and soul into disarming Iraq, and this means I
was wasting my time. It means we lost the Gulf War. That's why I
care. I care deeply about this. The whole world should be shamed by
this.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this is not the first time that men of high integrity
have walked away from Clinton's unsavory policies.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen W. Walker resigned his eight-year foreign-service job as
a desk officer for Croatia, describing U.S. policy as ``misguided,
vacillating and dangerous. . . . Our actions (or perhaps, more
appropriately, inaction) have undermined and threatened not only
the fate of the Balkans and the hundreds of thousands of victims
there, but also vital U.S. national interests,'' Walker wrote in
his resignation letter.
</P>
<P>
   The Walker resignation followed the departures of Marshall
Harris, the Bosnia desk officer, and Jon Western, an intelligence
research specialist, who quit in protest over the failure of the
United States to respond appropriately to the Balkan tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   We do not know where the Clinton administration goes from here
in an endeavor to restore honor and truthfulness in foreign
affairs, but a public apology would be a fine place to start. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
