<HEADER>
A6227 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS-560     08-27 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA LOSSES WILL WIPE OUT THIRD-QUARTER EARNINGS FOR REPUBLIC
CORP. 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: MARKET, MARKET-LOSES, MARKET-INVESTORS,
MARKET-COMMODITIES, RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT, RUSSIA-EMERGE) 
(js) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Adding to anxiety about the risk banks are facing
around the world, Republic New York Corp., considered one of the
most conservatively managed banks in the United States, said
Thursday that its losses in Russia would wipe out all of its
third-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republic, which trades in some of the world's most
exotic markets, was the only bank to disclose losses in Russia
Thursday, it was hardly the only bank stock to suffer from the
fears of shareholders. Investors, reacting to a confluence of real
or expected economic downturns in several regions, have concluded
that the financial risks facing banks in the near future are too
worrisome. They fled bank stocks with a vengeance Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the entire world just got a margin call and everyone
is stampeding out of emerging markets,'' said David Berry, a
banking analyst with Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods Inc. ``Everybody wants
their money back at the same time. The '90s are over.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks were not the only companies feeling the heat. Shares of
leading brokerage firms like Merrill Lynch and Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter sank Thursday, with losses in the shares of Lehman Brothers
outpacing the group. Lehman plunged $7.25, or 12.6 percent, to
$50.4375.
</P>
<P>
   An individual close to Lehman's trading operation said the firm
expected a ``several million dollar'' loss on a Latin American swap
transaction involving the Russian ruble. This person said that
emerging-markets turmoil might reduce third-quarter earnings by
about 11 percent from the company's earlier projections. A Lehman
spokesman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Republic said it planned to take a $110 million pre-tax charge
in the quarter for losses related to a sharp drop in the value of
short-term Russian bonds known as GKOs.
</P>
<P>
   Republic, which earned about $119 million in the second quarter,
also said it would take a charge of $45 million against reserves
because of ``current and anticipated Russian counterparty
defaults.'' Republic declined to specify what that charge involved,
but analysts said the language suggested losses on derivatives.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate announcement, Safra Republic Holdings SA, a
private European banking unit that is 49 percent owned by Republic,
said it would take a third-quarter charge of $65.9 million because
of losses in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Republic is controlled by Edmond Safra, a legendary banker whose
family has been involved in the industry for more than 150 years.
It is also one of the trading houses favored by George Soros, one
of the world's leading currency speculators. Soros' investment
company announced Thursday that it had lost about $2 billion in
Russia over the last year. Republic and Soros' company declined to
comment on any trading Soros may have done through the bank.
</P>
<P>
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, shares of Republic
plunged $4.625, or 9.23 percent, to $45.50. Other bank stocks were
also battered, continuing more than a monthlong slide born out of
concern about economic problems in Asia, Latin America, and Eastern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of J. P. Morgan plunged $13.1875, or 11.2 percent, to
$104.75; Chase Manhattan fell $6.125, or 9.34 percent, to $58.125;
Bankers Trust fell $8.3125, or 9 percent, to $83.8125; Citicorp
fell $11.875, or 8.9 percent, to $122; BankBoston dropped $2.375,
or 5.74 percent, to $39; and BankAmerica fell $3.875, or 5 percent,
to $73.75.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The losses in Russia are an unaccustomed, though not unheard of,
blow for Republic, the nation's 21st-largest bank with about $60
billion in assets. Safra, 66, chairman of Safra Republic, currently
owns 28.5 percent of Republic New York.
</P>
<P>
   Although it maintains a traditional branch network in New York,
Republic's more intriguing businesses are in private banking,
precious metals trading and financial services it performs for
securities firms and highly volatile hedge funds. Indeed, many
hedge funds, like those of Soros, have been battered recently in
emerging markets such as Russia, and their losses may have been
felt by Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing for J.P. Morgan or Bankers Trust to make an
announcement like this because they're usually much more active in
those markets,'' said Gerard Cassidy, a banking analyst with Tucker
Anthony, a research and brokerage firm in Portland, Me. ``But
Republic, and rightfully so, has always been perceived as far more
cautious and conservative. For this to happen to them is a real
shock.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is not the first time Republic's trading operation has
suffered a setback. A federal judge in New York recently forced the
bank to pay more than $13.5 million to two wealthy Pakistani
investors, Zahid Ashraf and his wife, who contended the bank
mishandled trading accounts involving complex currency
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the disastrous effect losses in Russia are having on
Republic's earnings, most of the largest U.S. banks have ample
cushions to absorb any losses there.
</P>
<P>
   Citicorp and Chase, for example, each earned more than $1
billion in this year's second quarter and said they had $420
million and about $500 million respectively in exposure to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said J.P. Morgan, which earned $402 million in the
second quarter, had exposure of less than $400 million in Russia,
but it is also one of the world's biggest traders and underwriters
of emerging-markets debt and could be more severely hurt by
problems in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust, which declined to comment on its earnings
outlook, may be one of the most vulnerable big banks in Russia.
Analysts said the bank, which earned only $164 million in the
second quarter, had exposure in Russia of roughly $1 billion,
including about $500 million to hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, it is clear that Russia is only part of the mix
when it comes to investor worries about economic developments
overseas, worries that are not likely to be put to rest until banks
and other companies begin reporting third quarter earnings in
October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
