<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONDERLAND-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEXT STOP' IS A GO IN LOOK AT '90S LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MELISSA MORRISON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - ``Next Stop Wonderland'' is an indie film in a lot of
the right places.
</P>
<P>
   It has a sketchy, impressionistic rhythm, the camera circling
around its characters documentary-style. The bossa nova soundtrack
gives this talky romance both sophistication and warmth, but,
unlike the swelling orchestration of most mainstream movies,
doesn't italicize every big moment. Its lead, Hope Davis, has
silky, blond, Hollywood-worthy hair, but a deadpan gaze that would
leave a studio stud like Keanu Reeves stammering his lines.
</P>
<P>
   It's these features that helped anoint ``Wonderland'' the
official sensation of the 1998 Sundance Film Festival, the
independent world's most prestigious competition. Miramax Films,
the independent world's most prestigious distributor, purchased the
movie after its first screening, which is tantamount to winning the
lottery with your first ticket.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is interesting treatment of a story that wouldn't
be out of place as a half-hour network TV episode, much less a
big-screen Jennifer Aniston-type vehicle: Single girl, recovering
from bad break-up, is unwillingly cajoled by her mother into a
disastrous series of dates with guys she meets through the personal
ads. Meanwhile, she and the designated Mr. Right keep missing each
other by inches.
</P>
<P>
   Davis (a regular in independents such as ``The Daytrippers'' and
``The Myth of Fingerprints``) plays Erin, a Boston nurse who has
been dumped by her Greenpeace-slogan-spouting boyfriend _ ``You do
not like the masses!'' he cites as a reason for leaving _ and has
soured on men. We know she should end up with Alan (Alan Gelfant),
a plumber and aspiring marine biologist who's much better than his
loutish, yuppie friends.
</P>
<P>
   The movie arranges for Erin and Alan to cross paths several
times, without connecting _ one of those nice cinematic gimmicks
that, again, in the hands of a mainstream director, would be the
movie's focus. Here, it's just a series of nicely underplayed
asides.
</P>
<P>
   There are some subplots involving the aquarium at which Alan
volunteers, and his troubles with a loan shark. They, too, are the
stuff of situational television and don't seem to serve much of a
purpose. But they don't intrude much on the heart of the movie,
which is Erin's defrosting as she negotiates through a forest of
dwarves to meet her prince.
</P>
<P>
   Director/co-writer Brad Anderson maintains a taut line of
low-key humor. That comes mostly from interplay between the two
leads and the crazies that surround them. Davis and Gelfant are the
anchors: She's wry and sharp, even in her mopey state. He's decent
and sexy, and hopeful, despite the obstacles blocking him in
pursuit of his ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   The bit players, though, come from a stranger planet _ Alan's
lawyer brother and his weak-chinned pals, who all misattribute the
same line about ``the hobgoblin of little minds,'' and Erin's
coworkers, whose characters are drawn with crayons. ``Wonderland''
occasionally colors outside the lines, as with a trigger-happy,
homophobic security guard. With such characters and a plot hatched
in Sitcomland, ``Wonderland'' isn't quite an indie wonder.
</P>
<P>
   But these are quibbles in what is otherwise a delightfully
sidelong love story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next Stop Wonderland'' is rated R for some adult and sexual
situations. There's no nudity, and little profanity. The only
violence involves a fish. 3 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
