A6231 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOLS-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      08-27 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOLS-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK'N'ROLL STAR PLAYS ROMANCE WAY OUT OF TUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - In rock and roll, if the way up doesn't get you, the
way down will. Rock fame will make someone out of nothing, then
turn around and make nothing out of someone.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Frankie Lymon story, as told in the movie named after
his big hit, ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love''?
</P>
<P>
   In Lymon's case, they should have asked, why do fools fall in
love three times?
</P>
<P>
   The movie is set during a lawsuit, when three disputatious women
claim to be Lymon's widow, thus entitled to the royalties that he's
owed for his songs.
</P>
<P>
   As the women testify about how they met the singer, we travel to
the early days of rock, when Frankie (Larenz Tate) and his group
become an overnight sensation, the princes of doo-wop.
</P>
<P>
   That's when he falls in love the first time, with Zola (Halle
Berry), who sang with the Platters.
</P>
<P>
   This early part of the story captures the highs of rock,
Frankie's love of performing and the rush of his fame.
</P>
<P>
   All of which falls apart far too quickly, as his group breaks
up, his manager loses interest, and Frankie turns to hard drugs.
</P>
<P>
   His second love, Elizabeth (Vivica Fox), represents the ugly
side of what can happen to a young guy who becomes a has-been
before he can even become what he wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   Emira (Lela Rochon), wife No. 3, picks up Frankie's story when
the singer tries to reform and resist the lure of rock-and-roll
comeback fame.
</P>
<P>
   Director Gregory Nava holds the story together, despite rapid
movement through time and point of view, to reveal the dark,
destructive side of fame.
</P>
<P>
   Nava ``(Selena)'' doesn't use many songs, but stages them with
great excitement. Instead, he primarily focuses on what happens
when the music stops.
</P>
<P>
   Berry ``(Bulworth)'' and Fox ``(Soul Food)'' are excellent, as
they deal not only with the past but with each other, adding a
level of humor that comes from surviving hard lives without
cracking.
</P>
<P>
   Tate ``(The Postman)'' personifies the thrill of performing in
front of a cheering crowd and the sense of bewilderment when the
cheering fades and the thrill is gone.
</P>
<P>
   No denying that the real Lymon had the heat but lost it. Same
goes for the movie, which circles a few times too many around the
same material.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the picture is enlivened by an appearance from the real
Little Richard, who adds a little wopbopaloobopalopbamboom to the
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love?'' is rated R for profanity, drug
use, nudity and sex. 2 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
