<SLUG> BC-CANADA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA RAISES INTEREST RATE TO PROTECT ITS DOLLAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ After weeks of hesitation, Canada's central bank
raised its benchmark interest rate by a full percentage point
Thursday in an effort to halt the slide of the Canadian dollar,
which has lost more than 10 percent of its value against the U.S.
dollar this year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the increase in the overnight lending rate to 6 percent,
the Canadian dollar swooned again, to 63.34 U.S. cents in New York
from 63.79 cents on Wednesday, leading many analysts to question
the effectiveness of the central bank's actions and to worry about
its effect on the national economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will help at all,'' said Jeffrey Cheah, a
financial market analyst with Standard &AMP; Poor's MMS here.
``Consumer confidence is already at very low levels because the
currency is depreciating almost every day. This will just compound
the lack of consumer confidence in Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock market did not help matters either, with the Toronto
Stock Exchange following the sharp decline of other markets. The
exchange's index of 300 stocks fell 372.84 points, or 6.04 percent,
to 5,799.46.
</P>
<P>
   John McCallum, chief economist at the Royal Bank of Canada, said
the central bank had wanted to ride out current conditions,
thinking higher interest rates were unnecessary because the
Canadian economy was slowing anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian dollar _ called a loonie because the dollar coin
bears the image of a common loon _ has been battered by contraction
in the commodities market and problems in Asia and Russia. On
Wednesday, it suffered its biggest one-day loss in three years,
falling .73 cent, to 63.79 cents, an all-time low.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when the Bank of Canada said: `Enough is enough. We
go,' '' McCallum said.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's largest banks quickly followed suit and raised prime
lending rates 1 percentage point to match the central bank's move.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Thursday, the Bank of Canada indicated
that the continuing slide in the value of the dollar represented a
diminishing confidence in Canadian investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's increase in interest rates is aimed at providing
support for the Canadian dollar in order to bolster confidence,
while preserving monetary conditions that will help to sustain the
present noninflationary expansion of the economy,'' the bank's
statement said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The rate increase was the first in more than eight months.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other analysts, McCallum sees raising interest rates
as a fairly useless move in the face of so many other problems
around the world. ``We're in the eye of a storm, with Russia
crumbling and Asia suffering through difficult times,'' McCallum
said. ``These are forces beyond our control. If we try to resist
with interest rate hikes, what we will get are negative effects on
our economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the Canadian economy has managed to retain much of
its strength despite the currency troubles. With practically no
inflation and a federal budget surplus, analysts had expected
growth to be relatively brisk this year, until Thursday's
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Cheah of Standard &AMP; Poor's said the agency would be revising
gross domestic product estimates downward. ``The interest rate hike
is not going to have an immediate impact but will be most strongly
felt three to six months from now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The economic effect of the higher interest rates will be offset
somewhat by the advantages of a cheaper dollar, which helps exports
and tourism, McCallum said.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts expect the loonie to continue losing value, but
how far it will slide is anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Canadian dollar is going to hit 61 before Mark McGwire
does,'' Serge Lacroix, a vice president of bond investments at
Levesque Beaubien Geoffrion Inc. in London told Reuters. The first
baseman for the St. Louis Cardinals hit his 54th home run on
Wednesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
