</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-PADILLA-MURDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREVIOUS SEX OFFENDER ARRAIGNED IN GIRL'S MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUTNAM, Conn. _ Composed as she clutched a child's photo album,
Millie Mercado waited for the arraignment of her daughter's alleged
killer to begin.
</P>
<P>
   She waited for 2 hours and 10 minutes before the muscles in her
face broke apart, and she quietly collapsed. She bent her head, and
a curtain of hair hid the tears that flowed for her only child,
11-year-old Angelica Padilla, who was murdered Aug. 13 as she
delivered newspapers in her neighborhood in nearby Willimantic. But
Mercado's soft wimpers escaped, and echoed against the blond wood
walls of the Putnam Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Jose A. Torres entered the courtroom bound in
chains to face capital murder charges that he brutally killed
Angelica in a sexually motivated crime. Torres, a 26-year-old
convicted sex offender whose history of assault sat unread and
unknown inside a local police registry for two years in
Willimantic, listened as a Spanish interpreter translated the
proceedings. A not-guilty plea was entered on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   In a graphic recounting of the incident meant to ensure a $1
million bond for Torres, state attorney Mark S. Solak said Angelica
``was literally butchered.'' He said the slashing of her throat in
a basement laundry room just below Torres' apartment amounted to a
``virtual decapitation of the little girl's head,'' cutting into
several major arteries.
</P>
<P>
   As Solak spoke, quiet wails erupted in the courtroom, one of the
few displays of emotion during the 9-minute arraignment. The
hearing began with a stern call for order by Judge Samuel Sferrazza
that sealed the courtroom off from a town's two-week-old anxiety
and its last 12 hours of explosive anger following Torres' arrest.
</P>
<P>
   When Sferrazza granted the $1 million bond, only a tight, hushed
``yes'' escaped from the back of the court.
</P>
<P>
   But the carthasis in Willimantic was palpable Wednesday night,
when a mob of 300 neighbors from the Colonial Townhouse complex on
Foster Drive, where Angelica and Torres both lived, gathered at
Building 14 to witness his arrest. They cheered police on and
shouted out, ``Killer!'' as he was led away from the complex.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday in court, Torres' public defender, Mark Shapera, said
the climactic public arrest has already tainted the case against
his client.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case should be tried in a court of law, not to a mob and
not through the media,'' said Shapera, who requested a medical and
suicide watch and protective custody for Torres. ``The state has
orchestrated this case. ... I don't think it has the strong
evidence it claims it has.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapera also said Torres was denied his right to see a lawyer
after requesting one 30 times.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the court after the hearing ended, Solak responded to
claims that police had played to the media. ``Those charges, I
believe, are absurd,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The arraignment left Millie Mercado with little of the stoic
mask she had arrived with, when she and five relatives had locked
arms and proceeded into the court wearing white T-shirts with
pictures of Angelica over their chests. Shattered as she stood
before a bank of microphones after the hearing, Mercado said, ``I
couldn't be grateful enough to everyone in the community for
everything everyone has done.''
</P>
<P>
   The arraignment was held in Putnam, about a 20-minute drive from
Willimantic, because of concerns about security, State Police said.
That fact, and the jeers from a crowd of residents as Torres was
led from the court in a police car, underscored the trauma and
violent emotion that have scarred this college town in northeast
corner of Connecticut, once known as the thread capital of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Willimantic, a town of 20,000, had not seen a homicide in two
years; at its height, Angelica's murder drew dozens of
investigators into an exhaustive pursuit to solve it. The case
prompted Connecticut's governor, John G. Rowland, to authorize a
$50,000 reward. As the investigation narrowed to Torres, police put
his apartment under constant surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, who was working for a local bungee cord maker, knew
Angelica and her mother; he was a customer at Angelica's uncle's
jewelry store. But the family and most of their neighbors did not
know a key fact about Torres: He had been released from prison last
year after serving time for sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   The information on Torres and other criminal sex offenders was
available to anyone who had sought it at the Willimantic Police
Department. A few did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can count them on one hand,'' said Lieutenant Paul Decarli.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, in the past week, the black binder that had lain
almost dormant became a crucial piece of the investigation, and it
was withheld from the public. The withholding of the sex offender
list touched off protests by public officials across the state and
by parents, and led to an appeal to the Connecticut Freedom of
Information Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy, some here say, could end up saving a child: It
has brought more public attention to the list than at any time
since Megan's Law was passed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
