<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-SUSPECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US BRINGS NAIROBI BOMBING SUSPECT TO NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As one tiny unit of a sprawling underground network
of Islamic militants, Mohamed Rashed Daoud Al-'Owhali went from one
terrorist training ground in Afghanistan to another in preparation
for his mission.
</P>
<P>
   In the name of Allah, and with the guidance and dollars of Saudi
billionaire Osama bin Laden, Al-'Owhali became expert in the art of
hijacking, kidnapping and explosives before the twin bombings of US
embassies in Africa, believing he would not survive.
</P>
<P>
   As fate would have it, Al-'Owhali made it, while 258 people,
including 12 Americans, died, and 5,000 others were injured in the
blast of a bomb he drove to the Nairobi embassy. Indeed, it was
Al-'Owhali who kicked off the Aug. 7 attack, throwing a flash
grenade at a security guard protecting the compound.
</P>
<P>
   This, at least, is the portrait of Al-'Owhali's involvement
sketched by the Clinton administration's highest-ranking law
enforcement officials who announced his arrest and indictment at a
press conference. Attorney General Janet Reno called it the fruit
of ``the most extensive overseas criminal investigation in
history.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI Director Louis Freeh would not detail how many other
suspects are in custody or being questioned about the bombings at
US embassies in Nairobi as well as Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, except
to say that the wide-ranging investigation was still at its
earliest stages. An FBI official, however, confirmed that another
suspect was on the way from Egypt. Officials wouldn't say whether
another suspect released by Kenya, Mohamed Sadiq Odeh had arrived
by Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali was flown from Kenya to New York to face his 14-count
indictment in connection with his role in the bombing of the
Nairobi embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, filed by FBI special agents and unsealed
Thursday, said the defendant traveled from Lahore, Pakistan to
Nairobi, where he cased the embassy before driving the bomb-laden
vehicle. Injured on his neck, face, and back, he was treated in a
hospital, where he allegedly discarded two keys that fit a padlock
on the back of the vehicle and three cartridges for a gun left in
it.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 9, he was apprehended by Kenyan authorities, who turned
him over to US authorities. According to FBI agents, he waived his
right to silence and described his involvement. Freeh specifically
gave thanks _ and credit _ to Kenya and Tanzania for help in the
search and arrest of Al-'Owhali, who was first taken into custody
by Kenyan authorities, and is also known as Khalid Salim Saleh Bin
Rashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That cooperation ... has brought us initially to the charge we
will speak about today,'' said Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have linked arms with law enforcement around the world and
vowed as one that justice will be done,'' Reno added.
</P>
<P>
   According to a complaint filed by FBI special agents, Al-'Owhali
tied the Afghani training camps he attended to Qasda, an
international terrorist organization led by bin Laden, who US
officials believe masterminded the embassy bombings as well as
targeting US soldiers in Somalia and other international attacks.
Bin Laden has repeatedly issued edicts to his followers to target
and kill Americans worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali also described the camps as dedicated to opposing
non-Islamic governments with force and violence and that he
attended conferences and meetings with bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 FBI personnel, including bomb technicians and
investigators, are still sorting through the rubble in Nairobi,
working with Kenyan authorities to uncover clues in the bombing.
The embassy in Dar es Salaam, was also bombed on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali's indictment includes charges of premediated murder
of the 12 Americans killed in the Nairobi bombing, conspiracy to
commit murder, and conspiracy to use a weapon of mass destruction
against the US.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
