<SLUG> BC-CENDANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDIT REPORT CITES CENDANT'S EX-CHAIRMAN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By ADAM BRYANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The audit committee of Cendant Corp. said Thursday in a
long-awaited report that Walter Forbes, its former chairman, bore
some responsibility for the accounting irregularities that wiped
out billions of dollars of Cendant's market value after the
problems were disclosed in April.
</P>
<P>
   The report said, for example, that Forbes failed to create a
corporate culture intolerant of inaccurate financial reporting;
that he failed to put in place appropriate controls and procedures
to catch such problems, and that he failed to inform himself
adequately about the sources of the company's profits.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who resigned from the company in July and received a
severance package worth more than $35 million, has maintained for
months that he knew nothing about the unusual accounting changes
before they came to light, and, therefore, was not responsible for
them.
</P>
<P>
   The audit committee's report _ based on work by its legal
counsel, Willkie, Farr &AMP; Gallagher, as well as the accounting firms
of Arthur Andersen and Deloitte &AMP; Touche _ will likely be a case
study for accounting students for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The report said, for example, that ``pervasive'' irregularities,
which created about $500 million before taxes of fictional profits
for the last three years, included inflating operating income,
decreasing expenses and adjusting its balance sheet ``particularly
to show a greater cash balance than the company actually had on its
books.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said the company improperly used funds set aside to
cover the cost of the merger in December of CUC and HFS to create
Cendant. For example, the report said Forbes received $500,000 from
Cendant's merger reserves for ``undercharging'' the company for
trips he took in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Thursday, Forbes said: ``The audit committee's
investigation is complete and it found absolutely no evidence that
I had any knowledge of or involvement in the accounting
irregularities previously disclosed by Cendant. Any suggestion that
I `should have known' about the fraud is completely unfounded.
There is and was no way I could or should have known about the
fraud and I never did or ever would condone any improper conduct
under any circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Brown, chairman of the accounting department at the Stern
School of Business at New York University, said there had been many
cases of companies' using one or two of these techniques. ``But to
see an organization use a combination of many of them is somewhat
amazing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the audit report provided a strong example of how the
``tone at the top'' set by senior company officials affects
behavior at all levels. ``If the tone is set in a rather lax
fashion, it is such fodder for fire to sweep through to the next
level and the next level,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on many public companies to show steady earnings
growth appears to have influenced Cendant's behavior. The audit
report said that many of the accounting irregularities resulted
from the company's inflating earnings so it would not fall short of
the expectations of Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If actual income in a particular quarter was 10 cents per
share and consensus analysts' expectations were 18 cents per share,
then adjustments of approximately 8 cents were made, without
support, to increase earnings,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Since April, however, investors have steadily lowered their
expectations after a stream of bad news, and Cendant's shares hit a
new low Thursday of $11.625, before closing at $13.375, down
$1.1875. Cendant's shares have fallen 68 percent since April.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Silverman, the former chairman of HFS who is now chairman,
chief executive and president of Cendant, said the company has
``put in place a series of financial controls to ensure these
improprieties cannot occur at Cendant.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate announcement not related to the audit committee
report, Cendant said that it would file its much-anticipated
restated financial statements in late September to reflect changes
requested by the Securities and Exchange Commission. The SEC
request reflects shifting notions about when companies that rely on
memberships, such as health clubs, should recognize revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The Cendant board named a new audit committee Thursday, composed
of four former HFS directors. The board also terminated, for cause,
E. Kirk Shelton, the former president and chief operating officer
of CUC, saying that he, along with Forbes, bore responsibility for
the accounting problems.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Shelton said that he ``had absolutely no knowledge
of, or involvement in, any improper conduct at CUC or Cendant.''
Because he was terminated for cause, Shelton will not receive any
severance payments.
</P>
<P>
   The report also stated that Cosmo Corigliano, the former chief
financial officer of CUC, and Anne Pember, the former controller of
CUC, directed the accounting irregularities, and that the two
former executives did not make themselves available to the
independent investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Naftalis, a lawyer for Corigliano, said his client was
``shocked that certain Cendant employees have apparently admitted
making improper financial entries and that those employees would
falsely attempt to implicate him in their wrongful conduct.'' He
added that Corigliano ``never engaged in any accounting or
financial wrongdoing or advised anyone else to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Gredd, an attorney for Ms. Pember, was unavailable for
comment, according to her assistant.
</P>
</TEXT>
