<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS PLAN HEARINGS ON IRAQ ARMS MONITORING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., N.Y.)  (See also ROSENTHAL-COLUMN, moved in `k' file) 
(mk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senior Republicans on the House and Senate foreign
affairs committees said Thursday that they would hold hearings to
determine whether the Clinton administration has weakened
inspection efforts by the U.N. Special Commission directed to
disarm Iraq of biological, chemical and nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Subcommittee on Near Eastern and South Asian Affairs, and
Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., chairman of the House Committee on
International Relations, said they were deeply troubled by
allegations by Scott Ritter, a senior American inspector who
resigned on Wednesday in protest of administration policy and
Security Council inaction on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter, 37, a former Marine intelligence officer, said in his
resignation letter and in interviews on Wednesday that the
administration had helped scuttle aggressive inspections by the
Special Commission, known as UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, he said, it advised UNSCOM's chairman to defer a
critical inspection that in his view could have produced important
new proof of Iraq's determination to retain weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Several administration officials adamantly denied Ritter's
assertions again Thursday. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
insisted that the administration is ``the foremost supporter'' of
the Special Commission. ``We believe it is absolutely essential for
Saddam Hussein to come clean in terms of weapons of mass
destruction,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Brownback and a spokesman for Gilman said their hearings
would explore whether the administration's actions matched its
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Ritter's charges ``credible, specific and substantial,''
Brownback said that the administration has shown ``little resolve
in containing Iraq and removing Saddam Hussein from power.''
</P>
<P>
   His hearing is scheduled for Sept. 9. A spokesman for Gilman
said that committee would probably also hold its hearing in early
September.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with reporters Thursday, administration officials
and foreign diplomats supportive of the American position sought to
counter Ritter's charges that his inspections had been stymied on
the verge of uncovering Iraq's hidden weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   One diplomat said that his government shared Washington's view
that inspections planned by Ritter last July _ one of which he said
targeted President Saddam Hussein's personal office _ would have
been needlessly provocative without providing new information about
Iraq's violations of its disarmament commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that ever since UNSCOM's creation
seven years ago, the United States had fought for greater access to
Iraqi sites, most recently this March, when Ritter conducted a
particularly aggressive inspection at the Iraqi Ministry of
Defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
