</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Local Serb sued as war criminal
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- A Bosnian Serb described as a model employee at a
Tucker compressor plant committed wartime atrocities against Muslim
and Croat prisoners in the former Yugoslavia in 1992, a federal
lawsuit filed in Atlanta charges.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnian refugee Kemal Mehinovic, 42, of Salt Lake City, claims
in the lawsuit that he was repeatedly brutalized by Nikola
Vuckovic, a former Bosnian Serb soldier who now lives in Clarkston.
</P>
<P>
   Mehinovic filed suit after learning from friends that Vuckovic
was living in the Atlanta area, said one of his lawyers, Paul
Hoffman, chairman of Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   Vuckovic declines to comment until he consults with a lawyer,
said one of his supervisors, Don Hood, human resources manager of
Our Way Inc. ``He did say, `This is all lies,''' Hood said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is the first of its kind against a Serbian defendant
living in the United States, Hoffman said. The Alien Tort Claims
Act and the Torture Victim Protection Act allow claims to be
brought against human rights violators found within U.S. borders.
The San Francisco-based Center for Justice and Accountability and
the American Civil Liberties Union of Georgia are assisting
Mehinovic in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be no safe haven in Georgia for war criminals,''
said Gerald Weber, the ACLU's local legal director.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit details chilling claims of abuse by Vuckovic:
</P>
<P>
   Mehinovic, who co-owned two restaurants and a bakery in his
hometown of Bosanski Samac, was awakened from a mid-day nap by Serb
police on May 27, 1992. They arrested him without a warrant and,
before taking him away, beat him with batons in front of his wife
and two children.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next six months, Mehinovic was repeatedly tortured by
Vuckovic, the lawsuit says. Vuckovic beat Mehinovic ``with metal
pipes, baseball bats, chair legs, wooden batons, his fists and
heavy boots, and at one point forced his legs apart and beat his
genitals, stating, 'You won't be needing this anymore,''' the
lawsuit claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was beaten with, in his words, anything they could get
their hands on,'' said Shawn Roberts, another of Mehinovic's
lawyers. ``The beatings would last about an hour until he lost
consciousness.'' She said her client had no military or political
affiliations.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs eventually released Mehinovic in October 1994 in an
exchange near Sarajevo. He reunited with his family and arrived in
the United States in July 1995. Mehinovic travels throughout the
country to perform maintenance work on various buildings, Roberts
said, declining to name his employer.
</P>
<P>
   After establishing himself on U.S. soil, Mehinovic began
``believing he was finally free of his persecutors,'' Roberts said.
But when he learned that Vuckovic was living in the Atlanta area,
he ``began having horrible nightmares and was unable to focus on
his new life in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Vuckovic was served with the lawsuit, filed Wednesday, where he
works as a laborer at Our Way, a Tucker company that makes
compressors for air conditioners and refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   Vukovic has been a ``model employee,'' said Hood, a supervisor.
He described the Serb as ``very easy going, friendly and very nice.
... I can't stress to you what a good employee he's been.''
</P>
<P>
   Vuckovic described himself as an orthodox Serb whose wife is
Muslim, Hood said.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1,200 Bosnian refugees live in metro Atlanta,
according to the Center for Applied Research in Anthropology at
Georgia State University. Most are Muslim, but some Serbs married
to Bosnian Muslims are also allowed to enter the United States.
Being in mixed marriages made them possible targets for persecution
in their native land.
</P>
<P>
   Our Way president Bobbie Bailey said her company, which employes
350 people, hired Vuckovic through local church ministries. ``We
always check people out,'' she said. ``We've had good results
working with the church. But we wouldn't have any specific
knowledge about their backgrounds.''
</P>
<P>
   In April 1992, Serb paramilitary forces, revolting against
Bosnia's declaration of independence from Serbia-controlled
Yugoslavia, took control of Mehinovic's hometown of Bosanski Samac.
</P>
<P>
   Vuckovic, a soldier in the Serb Army, arbitrarily detained and
tortured Bosnian Muslims and Croats with the specific intent of
destroying their ethnic-religious groups, the lawsuit claims. He
was a member of the 2nd Posavina Brigade, commanded by Simo Zaric,
and he had regular contact with Stevan Todorovic, the Serb chief of
police, the suit says. Zaric and Todorovic have been indicted for
war crimes by the United Nations International Criminal Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   With the lawsuit, said Hoffman, a Los Angeles lawyer, ``We want
to be able to lay out the facts of this case, have a jury listen to
these violations and issue a punishment in the form of civil
damages. We also want the U.S. government to take some action about
a man that has committed these types of crimes (and) that is living
in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman pointed to a similar case filed in Atlanta to show how
difficult it is to get people deported from the United States for
war crimes and human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, U.S. District Judge G. Ernest Tidwell awarded three
women $500,000 each in damages against an Ethiopian torturer.
Tidwell said each woman ``clearly established her claims of
torture'' against Kelbessa Negewo, who brutalized them 15 years
before they came to North America.
</P>
<P>
   Negewo, a former bellhop at the Colony Square Hotel, was granted
U.S. citizenship after Tidwell issued the order, said Hoffman, who
represented the women. ``We still can't believe it,'' he said.
``It's outrageous that an agency of the U.S. government would grant
citizenship to someone found liable of torture.''
</P>
<P>
   The women have not collected any money in their judgments
against Negewo, who cannot be located by their lawyers, Hoffman
said. They want the Immigration and Naturalization Service to
revoke Negewo's citizenship, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
