<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush keeps them lean on the campaign tour
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ As John Thrasher boarded the seven seat
King Air, the soon-to-be House Speaker had one thing on his mind as
the plane left St. Petersburg _ Steak and Shake.
</P>
<P>
   Little did he know that in the Jeb Bush campaign, food is often
an afterthought. Worse, there was no Steak and Shake ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really hungry,'' Thrasher kept saying with a smile and a
certain degree of determination. ``I didn't have dinner last
night.''
</P>
<P>
   The morning had already been spent touring a technical education
school in St. Petersburg as part of a two-day, six city, fly-around
that Bush's campaign had organized with the intention of grabbing a
spot on the evening news. Campaign press secretary Cory Tilley kept
careful score of the news coverage and as the trip began reaching
the end, Bush had managed to be interviewed by nearly every major
television station in the state.
</P>
<P>
   As Thrasher grew hungrier, Bush, who was traveling with his
running mate, Commissioner of Education Frank Brogan, just couldn't
pull himself away from the adult students at the technical
education school.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Bush got to Westwood Elementary School in West Palm
Beach, Tilley was anxiously looking at his watch. They had to be in
Fort Myers by 2 p.m. and they were getting behind schedule. There
would be sandwiches on the plane but Thrasher couldn't wait any
longer.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush chatted with kids and read the book Rat-a-tat-tat to
a group of first-graders, Thrasher began thinking about the school
cafeteria where they were supposed to join the kids for lunch but
the campaign staff really wanted to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in line with the kids, Thrasher filled his tray with
chicken and rice, black beans and a slice of cake. The Jacksonville
Republican proclaimed it ``great, fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush made the evening news. Thrasher had lunch. And the plane
took off only a few minutes late for Fort Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Should Bush win and become governor, he's learned an important
lesson about Thrasher, Bush said with a laugh. ``If I have to
negotiate with him, I just won't feed him until he gives in.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
