</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memories kindle civil rights candle for new generation
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ Thirty-five years ago, Jack Hughes left his
white, middle-class community outside Dayton, Ohio, for the streets
of the nation's capital to protest the lack of opportunity and
equality for African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   On the anniversary of that day Thursday, Hughes shook the hand
of Georgia Democratic Rep. John Lewis, the only major speaker at
that historic march still alive, and cried.
</P>
<P>
   He cried because in hearing Lewis speak again, he realized how
far the movement had come since that march in Washington, the day
that Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his ``I have a Dream''
speech. He cried because of what he believes is left to do if the
social barriers between blacks and whites are to be removed
permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll take another 500 years, but it will happen,''
said the 70-year-old Hughes, who now lives in Providence. ``That
march really changed my life. I became a lot more active in trying
to get rid of prejudices.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis came to Providence at the invitation of Rep. Patrick
Kennedy (D-R.I.), son of Sen. Edward Kennedy (D-Mass.). Lewis and
the younger Kennedy joined forces at the tiny Sheldon Street
Church, a multiracial church built by an immigrant more than 90
years ago, to mark the anniversary of the march and to spark
discussions about the current state of race relations in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all came over here on different ships, but we all live in
the same boat now,'' Lewis told the packed, racially mixed audience
at the church. He said that if someone had told him 35 years ago
that he would be standing at the podium of a church talking to such
a mixed audience, he wouldn't have believed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell all of you, don't give up, don't give in,'' Lewis said.
``Keep your eye on the prize. Let's create an interracial democracy
in America, let's walk into the wind and let the spirit of history
be our guide.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the legal barriers of segregation have been removed,
the country should focus on tearing down the less obvious walls of
racism, Kennedy said. For example, the focus should be on how to
improve public schools and housing in African-American
neighborhoods and how to make sure that blacks have an equal chance
at economic success through bank loans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that is more of a challenge in some ways because the
prejudice is not so black and white,'' said Kennedy. ``It requires
challenging a culture and changing belief systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling a speech that his late uncle Robert F. Kennedy
delivered in Cape Town, South Africa, during the years of
apartheid, the younger Kennedy said eliminating racism from society
comes from changing individual attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is only from calling on us to change individually that we
can change as a collective whole,'' Kennedy said. The anniversary
of the march should ``cause a pause for reflection in society and
challenge us as individuals. ... I think the burden is not on the
African-Americans or other minorities. The burden rests on the
majority of white Americans to lead the charge.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing Lewis speak, Terri Anderson and her son, Benjamin,
10, stood at the entrance of the church, unraveling the meaning of
his words.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he said meant so much to me,'' said Anderson, who is
white and married to a black man. ``I wanted my son to hear
first-hand about the civil rights movement, hear first-hand about
the struggle they had to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin looked up at his mother. ``The message I learned is
that I have rights,'' he said softly. ``And I have to fight to keep
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at the posh dining room of the Citizens Bank Building
overlooking the city, Lewis signed copies of his book ``Walking
with the Wind,'' a memoir of his journey from a childhood spent
preaching to chickens and picking cotton in rural Alabama to his
present position as the highest-ranking African-American in the
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Montiero, an official of the Providence chapter of the
NAACP, who marched with Lewis 35 years ago, said the division
between the races still exists, in part from African-American
groups' excluding whites from the process of healing racial wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like asking people with cancer to find a cure for
cancer,'' Montiero said. ``We need to address this as a society.
It's an American problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
