A6246 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-RUBLE-COX     08-27 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RUBLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Russians rushing to empty banks
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON. Ohio -- Everyday lately, Kevin Begin of Dayton leaves
his Moscow apartment for work and sees between 200 and 400 people
lined up outside his Russian neighborhood banks desperate to get
cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the banks don't have any cash and it's a cash
economy,'' said Begin, who works for Centerville's Hayden
Associates, an engineering firm that built three wastewater
treatment plants in Russia for Pepsi Cola Co.
</P>
<P>
   The run on the banks is only one sign of the economic turmoil in
Russia. The ruble is losing value and the Russian Central Bank
halted dollar sales for the second consecutive day Thursday.
Western corporations have difficulty getting cash to their
employees. And the Kremlin vehemently denied rumors Thursday that
President Boris Yeltsin had resigned or made provisions for his
resignation in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a state of panic. Russians take everything with a
grain of salt. They are used to instability,'' Begin said Thursday
from Moscow. ``But there is concern. Russians love their children
also and they want to feed them just like anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia is a poorer country than most Americans realize, Begin
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is unstable. The economy is plunging. The ruble
is plunging. People here live on $200 a month, and when you have to
pay American prices on $200 a month (it's difficult,)'' Begin said.
``Everything is imported. Russia makes nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Begin, 44, plans to spend another two or three months in Moscow
where he is training operators and testing equipment for Pepsi's
new wastewater treatment plant. But if the country becomes
unstable, he may return in two or three weeks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Hayden, project engineer for Hayden Associates, said
his company has been there off and on for two years and is now
completing the last of three wastewater treatment plants. He and
his partners are trying to figure out a way to get cash to Begin so
he can pay his rent, Hayden said. Hayden plans to return to Moscow
for a month.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Flannery, director of international operations for
TransWave International Inc. in Dayton, said his company has
$400,000 in sales lined up in Russia. TransWave sells equipment to
monitor and maintain pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   Flannery is taking a wait-and-see attitude toward the Russian
economy and political situation because even though things are
down, Flannery says the country hasn't hit rock bottom yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can almost always sink lower there,'' said Flannery who has
masters degrees in Russian history and contemporary Russian studies
and has lived and worked in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is glad to hear Yeltsin is still in power. ``The
status quo is better than the unknown. It's as simple as that,''
Flannery said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin and his economic reformers have deadlocked with the
communists dominating the Russian legislature, Flannery said.
Russia has few economic engines and the government is ineffective
at collecting and spending tax revenue, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are disgusted. They don't know what to do. But the
status quo is better (than the unknown,)'' Flannery said.
</P>
<P>
   American corporations have moved into Russia and the newly
independent states to do business since the fall of the Iron
Curtain in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
