<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6250 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-U.S.-NYT &LR;      08-27 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBASSY BOMBING SUSPECT ARRAIGNED IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ATTACK-ARRAIGN, ATTACK-CAPETOWN) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal authorities brought a suspect in the
bombings of the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania to the United
States on Thursday, saying he had admitted that he was trained at
terror camps in Afghanistan by Osama bin Laden, the Saudi born
multi-millionaire suspected of having directed the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Mohamed Rashed Daoud Al-'Owhali, was said to have
acknowledged that he rode as a passenger in the truck that carried
the massive bomb to the Nairobi, Kenya, embassy, according to a
detailed criminal complaint unsealed Thursday in U.S. District
Court in New York.
</P>
<P>
   He was also said to have told investigators that he threw a
dummy grenade at a security guard seconds before the blast and then
prepared to die in a bombing that he said was designed as a
``martyrdom operation in which he did not expect to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Fragments from the blast left a large wound in his back and cuts
on his hands and face, but he survived. And Thursday, the slight,
bearded man with a bandage on one wrist was brought by FBI agents
from Nairobi to a U.S. courtroom in New York. U.S. Magistrate
Sharon Grubin informed him of the charges against him, including
conspiracy to commit murder, the use of a weapon of mass
destruction and 12 counts of murder, one each for the dozen
Americans who died in the Nairobi bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali is not the only suspect headed for a U.S. court, law
enforcement officials said Thursday. He will be followed Friday by
a second man, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, who has been in custody in
Nairobi for nearly two weeks. Odeh provided one of the first
breakthroughs in the case, after he was initially detained on a
flight from Nairobi to Karachi, Pakistan, on Aug. 7, the day of the
bombings. Pakistani officials have said that Odeh provided
extensive details of his role in the plot. But pending his arrival
in New York, federal officials would would not discuss the case
against Odeh in any detail.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said the decision to bring the two suspects
to New York was related to the sealed grand jury indictment
returned against bin Laden in New York.
</P>
<P>
   That federal grand jury is expected to hear evidence about the
bombings and may return a superseding indictment that would be used
to bring prosecutions in New York against those involved.
</P>
<P>
   Any statements to U.S. authorities by Odeh or Al-'Owhali could
be presented to the grand jury as evidence against bin Laden, who
came under federal investigation after the World Trade Center
bombing in 1993. Officials said the sealed indictment of bin Laden
was issued before the East Africa bombings and that it charges him
with several terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, FBI Director Louis Freeh would
not discuss bin Laden's legal status nor would he comment on
reports that the indictment accused bin Laden of plotting to kill
President Clinton in 1994 during a visit to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali first emerged as a possible suspect when Kenyan
authorities contacted him two days after the Nairobi bombing,
according to a federal complaint signed by FBI Agent Daniel
Coleman. He was arrested the same day and confessed to taking part
in the plot during two interviews with FBI investigators on Aug. 12
and Aug. 20, the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   He told investigators he traveled from Lahore, Pakistan, to
Kenya on July 31. With several unidentified confederates he went to
the embassy Aug. 4, three days before the bombing, to inspect the
buildings and grounds in preparation for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the bombing, the complaint said, Al-'Owhali, along
with another man, traveled in a truck carrying a huge homemade bomb
from an undisclosed location in Kenya to the embassy. The identity
of the driver or whether he survived was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali first told Kenyan authorities _ apparently while he
was in a hospital _ that he had been wounded while standing on an
embankment with a friend as the explosion occurred. But the Kenyans
were suspicious because he said he was wearing the clothes he wore
at the time the blast, although they showed no traces of blood from
his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   He told the Kenyans that he had thrown away in a hospital
bathroom two keys that fit a padlock on the rear of the bomb-laden
vehicle and three bullets from a gun he had left behind in the
truck. Hospital employees later retrieved the keys and bullets from
the area that Al-'Owhali described.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali told the investigators that he had been trained in a
number of camps in Afghanistan, including ``camps affiliated with
Al Qaeda, an international terrorist group, led by bin Laden.'' At
the bin Laden camps, Al-'Owhali said he was trained in the tools of
terror, including explosives, hijacking and kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   During the interviews recounted in the complaint, Al-'Owhali
said he attended conferences and meetings with bin Laden and knew
of an order, signed by bin Laden and other militants saying that
American civilians were legitimate targets of terrorist acts. In
the Kenya and Tanzania bombings, more than 258 people died and more
than 5,000 were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant was flown to a military airport in upstate New
York on Wednesday night and taken by helicopter under heavy guard
to FBI headquarters in Manhattan. He was being held in a federal
prison next to the U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, Al-'Owhali also completed a financial affidavit,
in support of an application for a court appointed lawyer. In it,
he said he was unmarried, had no home and had never been employed.
But he reported that he had $12,000 from his father and owned a
1992 Chevrolet Caprice. Al-'Owhali had been identified as Yemeni
citizen, but officials in Yemen denied this.
</P>
<P>
   If found guilty of laws which make it a federal crime to carry
out terrorist attacks overseas, Al-'Owhali could face a maximum
sentence of death or life in prison. Al-'Owhali's was ordered held
in jail pending a hearing Sept. 28. His court appointed lawyer,
Yuanchung Lee, would not comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at FBI headquarters, senior law enforcement
and diplomatic officials in Washington hailed the action as an
important victory in the U.S. war against terrorism, in large part
because they had succeeded in bringing a suspect in an overseas
attack from Africa into a U.S. court within 20 days of the bombing
</P>
<P>
   Freeh said Thursday that no decision had made on where to try
Al-'Owhali, Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney in New York, appeared
at a news conference at FBI headquarters, suggesting that any
defendants in the bombing plot would probably be tried in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
