<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-ARRAIGN-ART-360&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS SUSPECTS IN KENYA BOMBING ARE BROUGHT TO NEW YORK, CITY STEPS UP
SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(See also ATTACK-U.S., ATTACK-CAPETOWN) 
(js) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After learning Thursday that two suspects in the
bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Kenya would be detained and
prosecuted in New York City, city officials announced immediate
plans to increase security in a section of lower Manhattan
dominated by court and municipal buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said that most of the measures would be
modest. But he acknowledged that a few of them, including the
erection of barricades and the closing of a portion of Pearl
Street, would cause some complications for traffic and pedestrians
_ annoyances that he sought to place in some context.
</P>
<P>
   ``As citizens, we all pay some degree of a price to live in a
free and democratic country,'' he said Thursday afternoon. ``And
the burdens of this and the patience that people have to have in
order to endure is well worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on the Thursday, federal officials announced that
Mohamed Rashed Daoud al-'Owhali had been brought to Manhattan on
Wednesday night, but they declined to reveal the location of a
second suspect, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh. The two, both of whom have
ties to a financial supporter of Islamic militants, Osama bin
Laden, are suspected of having taken part in the Aug. 7 bombing of
the embassy in Nairobi that killed at least 247 people, including
12 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were informed of the decision as they were bringing the
people back,'' Giuliani said. ``The city has to react to it. And we
will. We will react to it. We're part of America, and the United
States should prosecute these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after the United States bombed what it said were
terrorist-linked locations in Afghanistan and the Sudan _ in
response to bombings in Kenya and Tanzania _ the mayor announced
that the city had increased security around courthouses, embassies
and other buildings that might be likely terrorist targets.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With Thursday's developments, city officials said they would
increase security around the U.S. Court House in lower Manhattan.
That courthouse, a majestic building at 500 Pearl St.that sits amid
other public buildings, including the detention facility where the
suspects are likely to be held while awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening, workers using forklifts began placing cement
barriers behind police headquarters near the court house. A dump
truck loaded with sand was parked at the corner of Pearl Street and
Park Row, blocking traffic from passing the jail where al-'Owhali
is being held.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason for anyone to be alarmed,'' the mayor said.
He added that the city is ``just taking reasonable precautions,
reasonable steps, to protect against the possible problems that
could occur.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
