<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6261 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-EMERGE-NYT &LR;      08-27 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-EMERGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATIN MARKETS PLUNGE, CREATING NEW FEARS FOR WORLD ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: MARKET, MARKET-LOSES, MARKET-INVESTORS,
MARKET-COMMODITIES, RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS, RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT,
RUSSIA-EMERGE) 
(JT) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock markets in Latin America plunged Thursday,
raising more doubts about whether the region will be able to
survive the economic crisis that has swamped Asia and is now
pulling Russia to its knees. Currency declines in Mexico and the
fear of a devaluation in Brazil is also adding pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is not only important to the governments and citizens
of Brazil, Mexico, and Argentina, who have fought back with
economic reforms since the drubbing they took in the wake of the
Mexican peso devaluation in 1994-1995.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America is also a region whose consumers are big buyers of
American exports and and if their pace slows down that will put
another drag on the American economy.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico alone is one of America's top three export markets and
the plunge of the peso to record lows is surely going to curb
Mexican buying, as the weaker peso raises the cost of American
goods. The peso has fallen 10 percent in value since the end of
July.
</P>
<P>
   ``If emerging markets get weaker, that takes away a leg from
under U.S. corporate earnings,'' said Christopher Alderson, head of
emerging markets at Rowe Price Fleming in London.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, the Bovespa index dropped 10 percent and is now down
39.5 percent since the end of July. In Mexico, the chief market
index fell 6.1 percent and is off 34.6 percent since July 17, the
day that the Dow Jones industrial average hit its recent record
high. Argentina's Merval index fell 10.6 percent and the Venezuelan
stock market index dropped 9.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the equity selling in Latin America, analysts said
Thursday, is being forced by the need of hedge funds to raise cash
to pay off loans they took out to make big bets in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   As fast as stock markets are falling, Latin American bond
markets are keeping up, which is forcing interest rates higher.
According to the J.P. Morgan emerging market bond index, the
difference, or spread, between the rates on U.S. Treasuries and
those on Latin American governments bonds is 13 percentage points,
putting rates on long-term Latin American bonds at over 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This surge in rates since the beginning of August will add to a
countries borrowing costs and, more importantly, will make it
harder for Latin American countries to rollover their current
foreign debt as it comes due in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the focus in the near term will be on Brazil. Alderson
said that Brazil has around $50 billion in short-term debt that has
to be refinanced over the next several months, a task that will not
be more difficult. And as the time for rollovers approaches,
international investors are likely to get more jittery.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is also critical to the outlook for all emerging markets
because it is seen as the country that is the most vulnerable to a
currency devaluation. The devaluation is Russia, which economically
is less important than Brazil, has sent a shock wave through
emerging markets. A Brazilian devaluation would probably do much
more damage.
</P>
<P>
   The rout in Latin America Thursday was mirrored in other
emerging markets. In Eastern Europe, the stock market in Hungry
plunged 14.4 percent, the market in Poland dropped 6.1 percent and
the main index in the Czech Republic fell 6.8 percent. The RTS
index in Russia plunged 17.1 percent and is off 84 percent for they
year.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, the key emerging markets were off much less, falling in
the 1 percent range. But that may have been because they were
closed before the full brunt of the negative news from Russia
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6263 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-LOSSES-NYT &LR;      08-27 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-LOSSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY EVERY MEASURE, THE LOSSES ARE HUGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: MARKET, MARKET-LOSSES, MARKET-INVESTORS,
MARKET-COMMODITIES, RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS, RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT,
RUSSIA-EMERGE) 
(JT) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By almost every measure, share prices have been
suffering some of the worst declines in more than a decade, racking
up huge paper losses for millions of investors in a month of
volatile and tempestuous trading.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, for instance, the Dow Jones industrial average, the
most widely followed market barometer, fell 357.36 points, or
nearly 4.2 percent, the 15th-largest one-day decline in percentage
terms since 1945.
</P>
<P>
   It was so volatile that a year ago, the drop would have halted
trading on the Big Board and the Nasdaq for at least half an hour
during the day because of ``circuit breaker'' rules that called for
investors to be given a breather after such a steep decline.
</P>
<P>
   Those rules, however, were modified after the Dow tumbled 554
points on Oct. 27, 1997. Now it would now take a fall of 900
points, or about 11 percent, for trading to be halted. A drop of 10
percent or more has occurred just twice, in October 1929 and
October 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In October last year, the Dow plummeted 7.2 percent on its way
to a 13.2 percent decline from a high reached in early August 1997.
The Dow rallied, however, soaring in early 1998 and reaching a new
high, 9,337.97, last month, which prompted talk of the Dow
surpassing 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   But rapidly eroding corporate earnings growth and global
economic crises in places like Japan and Russia have helped send
the Dow into a nasty spiral, which ended Thursday at 8,165.99 _
about 12.5 percent below its all-time high, well past the 10
percent decline marker that many Wall Street analysts consider a
``correction.'' The Dow had been hovering around the 10 percent
line for several weeks before Thursday's selloff pierced it. A drop
of 20 percent or more from an all-time high, many analysts say,
would constitute a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts were quick to point out that the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index, another widely followed measure, is still
up 7.4 percent this year, and the Dow is up 3.3 percent, in line or
slightly ahead of many projections for this year. But the carnage
of the last few weeks paints a bleak picture. Of the companies that
make up the S&AMP;P 500, for example, more than half are down for the
year, meaning that huge gains in a select few large companies are
masking a nastier downturn in the broader market.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is the Russell 2000 index, a measure of smaller
company stocks, which is down 16.7 percent this year and more than
21 percent from its July high, which seems to suggest a wide swath
of smaller stocks have already entered a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   And while many expected a mild summer of trading, July was the
heaviest trading month in history on the New York Stock Exchange,
with more than 14 billion shares changing hands; August is on pace
to surpass that figure, with about 13.3 billion shares traded
already and two trading sessions left. Thursday, more than 936
million shares changed hands, the second-highest volume day ever on
the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key components to this summer's downturn has been
volatility, the gigantic price swings that Wall Street analysts
fear could unnerve investors worldwide. Almost every other day, the
Dow and other indexes seem to have price swings of 1 percent or
more.
</P>
<P>
   August is also shaping up to be an ugly precursor to bad
Octobers. In 1990, an steep selloff of 10 percent in August
pre-dated a sharp September and October drop. And declines last
August sent the market into an October swoon. This August, the Dow
is down 8.1 percent, one of the worst monthly declines of the
decade.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
