<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AVOIDS CONTROVERSY IN SPEECH OUTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. -- President Clinton, embarking on perhaps the
most difficult resurrection campaign of his career, ventured
Thursday into this Massachusetts Democratic stronghold, where he
received rousing support from rank and file supporters but a
measured reception from some of the state's leading politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Even while a crowd at Mechanics Hall roared its approval and
others lined the roadways to wave at Clinton's passing limousine,
state officials said they were withholding judgment on his
political viability. Most notably aloof was Sen. John Kerry, who
pointedly passed up a chance to offer his personal support, saying:
``I'm not going to make any judgments on anything until I read the
Starr report.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a note sounded repeatedly and to varying degrees on a day
when Clinton himself made no mention of his personal troubles or
the political crisis that has enveloped his presidency. As applause
filled the air all around them, the state's Democratic politicians
said they supported Clinton's issue stands and praised his policy
successes, but tried to distance themselves from his personal
problems by saying they will await the report from independent
counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people still recognize he's the leader, and he has a
personal problem that has to be addressed,'' said Rep. Joseph
Moakley, a Democrat from South Boston who attended the event. ``And
when (the Starr report) comes, we will address it. We have to
decide individually, by looking at the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he wished Clinton had apologized in his Aug. 17 speech
during which he confessed his adulterous affair with Monica S.
Lewinsky, Moakley flatly added: ``Most people were looking for him
to be more contrite.''
</P>
<P>
   In public, in his first significant public appearance since he
delivered that speech, Clinton met with an enthusiastic reception
in a city where Democrats outnumber Republicans by about four to
one.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping out the door of his small jet on the tarmac of the
Worcester airport, Clinton beamed and waved to the crowd of
schoolchildren who squealed and yelled in unison. Sunshine poured
down, and Clinton's smile -- his entire demeanor -- seemed in sharp
contrast to the melancholy air he has carried during his rare
public outings on his Martha's Vineyard vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Clinton seemed to like being in Worcester so much that
he later made an unscheduled stop at Scano's, an Italian bakery and
lunch shop, where he stripped off his coat, took up a booth in the
corner and ordered what the proprietor described as a steak bomb,
hold the cheese. In the middle of what is supposed to be his summer
vacation, he sat in the restaurant for over an hour and a half
talking with the locals and the politicians who accompanied him.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton first pulled into town, driving down Pleasant Street,
hundreds if not thousands of residents turned out to greet his
passing motorcade, some of them holding welcoming signs, others
not.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the Blessed Sacrament Church, a man held a bumper
sticker aloft proclaiming, ``Impeach Clinton Now.'' On the sidewalk
outside of Dooley's dry cleaner, several people unfurled a banner
that said, ``Monica should have had her dress cleaned here.''
</P>
<P>
   At Mechanics Hall, the event was part policy speech on school
safety, and part pep rally. Outside, a couple of hundred protesters
held signs in the air and chanted for Clinton's resignation.
Inside, two officials in particular made a tacit note of Clinton's
problems and tried to brush them off. Rep. Jim McGovern, who is
involved in a reelection campaign against Republican state Sen.
Matthew Amorello, told the crowd, and Clinton, that Worcester
remained behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a city of fair-weathered friends,'' McGovern said.
``A friend from Worcester is a friend for life, and you, Mr.
President, through your policies, have been a friend of
Worcester.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, biting his lower lip, mouthed the words `Thank you,
Jim.'''
</P>
<P>
   And Edward Gardella, the city's police chief, seemed to nearly
bring Clinton to tears when he said, ``We can certainly be proud
that William Jefferson Clinton is our president.''
</P>
<P>
   But their remarks stood in contrast to the sentiments expressed
by others. Attorney General Scott Harshbarger gave a policy speech
most memorable for its lack of energy, and Kerry's only real
reference to Clinton, who sat on the stage behind him, came when he
said, ``We welcome your central leadership on these vital issues
before the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who has faced his own personal problems throughout his
political career, seemed more forgiving and tried pointing his
speech, as well as private comments beforehand, toward policy
rather than politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to get on, want to move on,'' he said. ``They want
a president who will lead on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the state's most senior Democratic politicians turned
out to lend Clinton a symbolic but important nod of support at the
most difficult time in his political career. Kennedy was the first
to greet Clinton on the tarmac of the Worcester airport, followed
by Kerry, Reps. Moakley, McGovern, Richard Neal and Ed Markey. The
mayor of Worcester, Raymond Mariano, spoke of Clinton warmly in his
public address.
</P>
<P>
   In the crowds, the many members of the public seemed ready to
offer some measure of forgiveness. ``I don't want to hear about it
any more,'' said Barbara Perotto, the wife of a Worcester city
council member. Said Donna Swanstrom of Worcester: ``Other people
do things similar to what he did and they don't get fired for it.
Let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Three times at the Mechanics Hall event, Clinton received a
standing ovation. On the stage, he seemed to glow in the applause
and the klieg lights, waving at the crowd with a broad smile
splashed across his face. His speech, however, stuck to a
well-trodden topic for him: school safety. His rambling speech
including an offer of money for states to continue with a police
recruitment program using college tuition inducements.
</P>
<P>
   He also touched on other aspects of his policy agenda, including
environmental protection, preserving Social Security and campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is critical business ahead of us _ business that we will
take up as soon as Congress comes back to work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House reacted with glee over the trip. ``The president
was very pleased,'' said Clinton spokesman Barry Toiv. ``He really
enjoyed the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some political strategists questioned the wisdom of his
trip, and Massachusetts Republicans said they were thrilled to have
Clinton in their state during an election season, given the
personal and political baggage he carried with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing a trip like this so soon after everything that happened
in Washington just exposes everyone to more pain when they should
be doing some healing,'' said Michael Cudahy, an independent
political consultant. ``It looks to me like it's terribly
political.''
</P>
<P>
   Cudahy added: ``I can't believe Jim McGovern is thrilled to have
him in Worcester right now. I think it's very self serving and I
think he's hoping for good pictures and get in and out and prove to
his political base that he's still viable.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Amorello, McGovern's opponent in the autumn election: ``I
think it's a thrill to have the president visit your hometown, but
given the circumstances surrounding this visit, I would not be on a
podium with him because of his repugnant behavior and that he lied
to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the people of Worcester seemed to disagree. Mary Scano,
of the restaurant and bakery Scanos, was at St. Joseph's Catholic
Church when her husband, Mauro, raced inside saying, ``Mary, Mary,
the president wants to meet you.''
</P>
<P>
   She rushed back to her shop to have an audience with the
president, and later said, ``He is a great president, and they
ought to cut out this baloney.'' She later added: ``So he lied. I
lie. When I was on the council, I lied.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jill Zuckman of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
