<HEADER>
A6268 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERRORIST-BOMBINGS-HN     08-27 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORIST-BOMBINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECTED TERRORIST FACES CHARGES IN U.S. 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal lawmen have brought a suspected terrorist
to the United States to face murder and conspiracy charges in the
Aug. 7 bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, Kenya, President
Clinton and his national security team said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed Rashed Daoud al-'Owhali, who was captured by Kenyan
officials within three days of the bombing, was flown to the United
States on Wednesday night and arraigned Thursday in the U.S.
District Court in Manhattan, N.Y. The bombing killed 247 people,
including 12 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press, quoting Kenyan Attorney General Amos Wako,
also reported that a second suspected terrorist, Mohammed Sadiq
Odeh, was en route to the United States. However, FBI Director
Louis Freeh would neither confirm nor deny that report.
</P>
<P>
   In its criminal complaint, the Justice Department alleges that
al-'Owhali ``together with others known and unknown, unlawfully,
deliberately, and with malice aforethought, murdered (12) United
States nationals.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised the arrest and custody as ``an important step
forward in our struggle against terrorism,'' but he added, ``there
is a long road ahead'' to prevent similar attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enemies of peace and freedom undoubtedly will strike
again. Our resolve must be for the long run,'' Clinton said. ``No
matter what it takes, how long it takes or where it takes us, we
will bring to justice those responsible for the murder and maiming
of American citizens. We will defend our interests, our people and
our values.''
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, al-'Owhali could face the death penalty or life in
prison without possibility of parole.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate Judge Sharon E. Grubin on Thursday ordered
al-'Owhali to be detained pending a Sept. 28 appearance in the
federal district court. The suspected terrorist, listening on
earphones to an Arabic translation of Grubin's comments, nodded his
head as the judge informed him of his rights, The Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The federal complaint also alleges that al-'Owhali, a Yemen
native, told FBI agents that he had learned how to make explosives,
hijack and kidnap at terrorist training camps run by Osama bin
Laden, head of the al Qaeda terrorist group. The U.S. military
bombed some of the camps in Afghanistan last week, as well as a
suspected chemical weapons factory in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has blamed bin Laden for ordering the Nairobi bombing
and a similar attack the same day at the U.S. Embassy in Dar es
Salaam, Tanzania. Bin Laden has not been charged in the bombings,
but Freeh called the suspected terrorist ``a primary subject of our
current investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   No Americans were among the 11 people killed in the Tanzania
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, al-'Owhali, also known as Khalid Salim Saleh bin
Rashed, told law enforcement officials that he and an unidentified
conspirator drove a vehicle containing a bomb from an undisclosed
location in Nairobi to the embassy Aug. 7, the federal complaint
states. He tossed a grenade-like device at an embassy guard before
the devastating explosion, which the suspected terrorist said he
did not expect to survive.
</P>
<P>
   While being treated at a local hospital for bomb-related
abrasions to his face, hands and back, al-'Owhali said he disposed
of some evidence in a bathroom receptacle. He said the evidence
included two keys to the padlock on the bomb-laded vehicle and
three bullets for a gun he left in the vehicle. Hospital employees
have recovered these items, the federal complaint states.
</P>
<P>
   Special agents of the FBI interrogated al-'Owhali shortly after
his arrest in Kenya after advising him of his rights under the U.S.
Constitution to remain silent and to seek the advice of an
attorney, the complaint states. He waived his rights before
answering the agents' questions, the complaint states.
</P>
<P>
   The federal complaint is based on the sworn statement of FBI
special agent Daniel J. Coleman, who said he based his comments on
his investigation of the bombing and statements from other law
enforcement officials and witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said they submitted the complaint solely to
establish before the U.S. court that they had probable cause to
arrest the defendant. The officials said they have additional
evidence that has yet to be disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said al-'Owhali's arrest and
retrieval was part of the ``most extensive overseas criminal
investigation'' in U.S. history, involving more than 500 U.S. law
enforcement personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great wrong has been done, but we are not going to rest,''
Reno said. ``We are going to pursue every last murderer until
justice is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright called the arrest and
retrieval of al-'Owhali an initial step in establishing ``the full
truth about who planned and perpetrated these cowardly acts of mass
murder.'' She also said the arrest and last week's U.S. bombings in
Afghanistan and Sudan should serve as a warning.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White, who will lead the federal
government's prosecution of al-'Owhali, said the charges against
him illustrate the United States' commitment to prosecute
``heinous, cowardly acts'' of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This investigation will not end until every terrorist involved
in the bombings in Kenya and Tanzania is identified, taken into
custody and prosecuted to the fullest extent of the law,'' White
said. ``That is the least that we owe to those who gave their lives
in the service of their country, to those foreign nationals who
died in the mindless violence, and the thousands of others who were
injured.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
