<HEADLINE>
DAVIS CUP HAS BOSTON ORIGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Petra Falk was not jealous, even though her
guy was hugging an old love Thursday at Longwood Cricket Club as
though he'd never let go.
</P>
<P>
   Falk was gracious, realizing that Jonas Bjorkman, the leading
man at the MFS Pro Championships, had been enamored of this
alluring stranger for years, since he was first able to lift a
tennis racket back home in Vaxjo. Long before he met Petra.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Swedes preceding him _ Bjorn Borg, Stefan Edberg, Mats
Wilander among them _ Bjorkman had pursued the shapely stranger
relentlessly across the world, and finally caught up for a
champagne tryst in Moscow four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we drank some champagne together,'' says Bjorkman, who
Friday goes up against the startling French qualifier, Sebastien
Grosjean, in a quarterfinal. ``But since then, we've been apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Bjorkman, with a No. 12 in the universe, winner of more singles
and doubles matches (111) than any rival last year, caresses the
stranger again.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing here anyway?'' he coos. ``I thought you
were in Stockholm.''
</P>
<P>
   Silence.
</P>
<P>
   In the manner of the Sphinx, another of the world's treasures,
the stranger _ the gleaming, sterling Davis Cup _ generally remains
mute in the presence of adoring humans.
</P>
<P>
   But Kevin Jenness, who _ along with an armed guard _ squired the
Cup into the clubhouse for a reunion with Bjorkman and another
persistent suitor, Roy Emerson, has the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a homecoming,'' says he, an executive at the jeweler
Shreve Crump &AMP; Low. ``The Davis Cup shouldn't be seen as a stranger
in Boston. Not at all. A Harvard kid named Dwight Davis
commissioned its creation by Shreve's here in 1900.''
</P>
<P>
   Conceived in Boston, but delivered in Concord, N.H., by
craftsmen selected by Shreve's (William Morton and and Warren
Peckman, on a design by Rowland Rhodes), the Cup has since been
sought by thousands of tennis players in an annual quest for the
world team championship.
</P>
<P>
   It all began in The Bean, and though the aged crock will soon be
99, it has lost none of its luster or sweat appeal to the athletes
yearning to abduct it for their homelands. This year 135 countries
entered the fray, bent on Cup-napping the prize away from Bjorkman
and Sweden. Four survive: Sweden against Spain, the US against
Italy at Milwaukee a month hence.
</P>
<P>
   Because he dipped into his mother's cookie jar for about $1,000
to purchase the Cup and launch his vision of a worldwide
tournament, Dwight Davis was, naturally, the US playing captain in
1900. His Longwood clubmates and fellow Harvards, Holcombe Ward and
Malcolm Whitman, accompanied him to a 3-0 triumph over Britain.
</P>
<P>
   That happened at Longwood, the original Back Bay site at the
corner of Brookline and Longwood Avenues, where the Winsor School
now stands. Three years later, same grass courts, the Brits won and
the Cup was off on its endless globetrotting rounds to such ports
of call as Paris, Santiago, Johannesburg, Sydney, New York,
Goteborg, Prague.
</P>
<P>
   Jenness had taken the beguiling, ornately engraved 15-pound bowl
(13 inches in height, 18 in diameter) from its aluminum traveling
case as Joe Cogan of American Protective Services stood by
discreetly, his revolver out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never knew the Cup needed a bodyguard,'' says Roy Emerson. An
MFS celebrity guest, Hall of Famer Emmo was the principal in eight
Australian Cup heists between 1959 and 1967. ``Long time no see,''
he smooches the stranger, once a photo-op cradle for his baby son,
Antony Emerson in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of great parties _ beer or champagne _ drinking
from the Cup,'' he recalls. No bodyguards, no guns in his day, but
Emmo reckons a few people got blasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' says Jenness, ``the Cup is insured for $250,000. It
would probably cost that to duplicate it, but it's really
irreplaceable. A work of art of a bygone era. You couldn't find the
craftsmen now.''
</P>
<P>
   Shreve's is working on a new, larger base to accommodate the
victors' names as the Cup prepares for a new century.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be ready for the final in November,'' says Jenness.
``But, Jonas,'' he tells Bjorkman, ``the Cup has been in our
workrooms. That's why you haven't seen it in Sweden since you beat
the US last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who wins this year, the Cup, not seen at Longwood
in a quarter-century, will be no stranger next year. Marking its
100th year of existence will be a July 17-19 Cup joust, the US
against an opponent to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really pleased to be part of Boston's great 1999 summer
along with the All-Star Game and the Ryder Cup,'' says Longwood
president Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   Bjorkman, winning the decisive doubles with Jan Apell, first
snuggled with the Cup after the 1994 victory over Russia, a
spectating disappointment for a local hacker named Boris Yeltsin.
Last year he won two singles and the doubles in the 5-0 bageling of
the US.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' says Bjorkman. But he obediently ends the embrace
because the patient, forgiving Petra Falk wants to see Boston and
have lunch at Quincy Market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
