<SLUG> BC-TEN-MFSPRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSTER TURNS ON THE PRESSURE, DEFEATS LAPENTTI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It hasn't been the best of years for Thomas
Muster. He hasn't won a tournament, although he has reached one
final, at Estorial, Portugal, where he lost in three sets.
</P>
<P>
   Muster, 30, has seen his ATP ranking drop: He was No. 9 when
last year's schedule concluded, now he's No. 24. He won $2.1
million last year, but he's up to just over $400,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, Muster had little trouble in doing away with
Nicolas Lapentti, Ecuador's best player, 6-2, 6-4, in the second
round of the MFS Pro Championships Thursdayat Longwood Cricket
Club. Lapentti, ranked 57th, had trouble with Muster, who is strong
on clay as well as hardcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fighter, he fights you for every point,'' said
Lapentti, 22. ``He's never going to give you a free point so you
have to go out there and have a very positive attitude and be ready
to play for three hours. On hardcourt or on clay, he's very
difficult to play.''
</P>
<P>
   In Muster's words, this has been an ``average'' year for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys would be happy with what I've done this year,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only 13 players 30 or older have cracked the top 10 in the men's
pro rankings, but Muster, who is one of them, doesn't think age is
a factor yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like I'm 30,'' he said. ``I can still play with
guys 10-12 years younger than me. I don't think I have a problem
with anyone around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy for a guy who has been there for so long to
maintain a certain level,'' Lapentti said. ``He's been around and
sometimes it's not easy to motivate himself after all he's done in
his career. He's a fighter and he's still trying to get up there.
He's never going to be easy to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Muster's 44 career titles, 40 have been on clay _ tops among
active players. Muster is third among active players in career
titles, and second to Boris Becker in matches won (701-611). He's
had three hardcourt titles, including the Lipton last year in Key
Biscayne, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take my results the last two years and I would say I'm a
hardcourt guy,'' Muster said. ``I don't know who brought up clay,
even though I've won most of my tournaments on clay and most of my
matches have been on clay, as well as my best results.''
</P>
<P>
   Muster feels he is preparing well for next week's US Open, in
which he will play 15th-ranked Alberto Berasategui in the opening
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coming together slowly; I feel all right,'' he said.
``For me, it's important to get matches, and during this stay in
the States, I've had six matches and that's pretty good going into
the Open. That's plenty of practice games.''
</P>
<P>
   In other matches at Longwood Thursday, Cedric Pioline, ranked
17th, decked No. 52 Andrew Ilie, 6-4, 6-3, and Gianluca Pozzi, the
oldest player on the tour at 34, defeated Lionel Roux, 5-7, 6-2,
7-6 (7-3), in 2 hours and 38 minutes. Roux won the first 2 points
of the tie-breaker, but Pozzi won the next 6.
</P>
<P>
   Pioline, the tourney's No. 3 seed, put pressure on Ilie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was going to place some winners and make some
mistakes, so I was only watching for any problems,'' said Pioline.
``He tries to hit so hard and sometimes he overhits and there's
nothing you can do. He's hitting a winner or makes a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little off on my finishes,'' Ilie said. ``I played 75
percent and I needed to be at 100 percent to beat him. I was trying
to put shots away but I was a little bit off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
