<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6284 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-COMMODITIES-NY     08-27 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-COMMODITIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMODITIES PRICES FREE FALL PUTS MAJOR PRESSURE ON PRODUCING
NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: MARKET, MARKET-LOSES, MARKET-INVESTORS,
MARKET-COMMODITIES, RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS, RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT,
RUSSIA-EMERGE) 
(JT) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While global stock markets plunged, a major index of
commodity prices on everything from oil to cotton fell to its
lowest level in 21 years Thursday. And that may be more worrisome
for investors in the long run than Thursday's 4.2 percent decline
in the Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   Each tick down in the price of oil, copper, cotton, and gold
puts more economic pressure on the nations that produce them. And
many of the major producers are emerging market countries
experiencing a financial crisis, like Russia, which is a major
exporter of oil and precious metals, or countries considered
vulnerable, like Mexico, also a major oil producer.
</P>
<P>
   Already commodity prices have fallen 20 percent in the last year
and heightened the concerns about the developing world that began
with the Asian financial panic in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a flu, it's catching; it's dominoes,'' said William
Byers, director of futures research at Bear Stearns &AMP; Co. ``Not
only is the psychology spreading, but the economic weakness is
spreading.''
</P>
<P>
   The drop came on the same day that markets around the world
tumbled as Russia's economic crisis deepened. Millions of
investors, seeking to flee the market turmoil, rushed to the
relative haven of United States Treasury securities, pushing
long-term yields to their lowest level in 30 or more years.
</P>
<P>
   For the American investor worried about the strength of the
economy, which by all current signs is still strong, and corporate
earnings, which have been weakening, so far the fall in commodity
prices and the drop in American interest rates has been good news.
</P>
<P>
   While tough on emerging market and other producer countries, the
lower prices have cut corporate costs here and spurred consumer
spending. And the damage that had been done to American commodity
producers has not had a major impact on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The fall in interest rates has also been a positive for the
American economy, by bolstering housing and capital investment.
Thirty-year mortgage rates have now been less than 7 percent for
more than two months. Thursday, the yield on the 30-year Treasury
bond fell to 5.34 percent the lowest for long-term yields in 30
years. The 10-year note yield, a benchmark for home mortgage rates,
fell 5.06 percent, its lowest since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   These forces have, so far, have more than offset the drag from
the Asian economic crisis, which has led to a sharp drop in demand
for American exports. And this is one reason the American economy
has slowed much less than many economists expected in the last six
months.
</P>
<P>
   But with the global economic turmoil spreading from Asia to
Russia and now pressuring Latin America, it appears less likely,
some analysts said, that the positives of lower interest rates and
low commodity prices will be enough to offset the growing drag from
a global economic slowdown on American corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Already many economic forecasters who had bet on the offsetting
impact from lower commodity prices and lower interest rates have
been scaling back their economic forecasts for the second half of
the year. And a steep fall in American stocks, which would dampen
consumer spending, may force a further scaling back, which would
not be good for the outlook for corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you correct the problems'' in Asia and Russia, said
Richard Berner, chief economist at Mellon Bank in Pittsburgh, ``the
stimulus will be a minor offset.''
</P>
<P>
   The backwash from the Russian turmoil pushed the
Bridge-Commodity Research Bureau index of 17 commodities down 1.88
points, to 196.24, the lowest since December 1977, a year of sharp
declines in agricultural prices that lead to farmer protests.
</P>
<P>
   The impact from the commodity price decline has gone beyond
emerging market countries. In Canada, a major commodity producer
itself, the currency dropped to another record low, forcing the a
the Bank of Canada to raise its benchmark interest rate one
percentage point to 6 percent. The increase also helped send the
Toronto Stock Exchange index down 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Two forces have been pushing commodity prices lower and will
continue to do so, several analysts said Thursday. One is the
falling demand from Asia, which for example was a major consumer of
copper for new construction. The other is that countries in
trouble, like Russia, are expected to sell what they can to raise
money, adding to the supply in an already weak market.
</P>
<P>
   William O'Neill, director of futures research at Merrill Lynch,
said that there had been big sales of platinum and paladium by
Russia in Japan and sales of gold and silver in Zurich and London.
The crisis, he said, ``inspires them to sell as much as possible.''
The government controls much of the countries precious metals.
</P>
<P>
   The selling by Russia was an odd twist. Gold had been thought of
for years as refuge in the time of political and economic crises,
and a few gold bugs still hold that belief. But Thursday the price
of gold plunged, dropping to a 19-year low on in the spot market in
London of $276.55 an ounce, down $5.70.
</P>
<P>
   Commodity selling is also coming from countries like Australia
who currency also fell to a record low Thursday. But because most
commodities are priced in dollars, the weaker Australian dollar
means gold and other commodity sellers can reap a nice profit when
the sales are translated back into the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
   This all means that commodity prices _ and the pain that they
are bringing to already troubled economies _ still have a way to go
before they hit bottom. ``I don't think we are there yet,'' said
Berner of Mellon Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
