<HEADER>
A6285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CBS-SPINOFF-NYT     08-27 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBS-SPINOFF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS TO SPIN OFF BILLBOARD AND RADIO BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an effort to boost its sagging stock price, CBS
Corp. said Thursday that it planned to spin off up to 20 percent of
its radio and outdoor advertising businesses in an initial public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS stock has fallen 25.8 percent from its 52-week high of
$36.625 on April 8 because of investor concern about the
profitability of the television network, which lost money last year
as its ratings continued to lag. By taking public a piece of the
lucrative radio and advertising operations and creating a separate
company for them, CBS President Mel Karmazin hopes to showcase the
corporation's far more profitable operations and remind investors
that those businesses are unrecognized in CBS' own stock price.
Karmazin owns 1.1 percent of CBS. In a day of dreadful news on Wall
Street, CBS stock jumped $2.0625, to close at $29.25.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to raise about $3 billion, the bulk of which
would be used to reduce its $5 billion in debt, and free it either
to buy back stock or make acquisitions. CBS Chairman Michael Jordan
told analysts the company wants to buy more television stations.
But that is a problem because the company's 14 television stations
already reach 32 percent of U.S. television households, close to
the federal limit of 35 percent. Although the three broadcast
networks have lobbied the Federal Communications Commission to get
that ceiling raised to 50 percent, experts say a change is
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Stations owned by networks generate operating profit margins
anywhere from 35 percent to 55 percent, while today the networks
themselves would be happy with margins of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to dispel repeated rumors that he is unhappy with the
network business and would like to sell it, Karmazin emphatically
told analysts that he had no plans for a sale, adding that people
who believe CBS will sell the network should sell the stock, said
one person who attended the conference. Karmazin called the network
his ``favorite'' business.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have expressed skepticism about a sale of the
network, in part because they say it is unlikely that CBS could
find a buyer now at a high price.
</P>
<P>
   But turning the network around could prove difficult. The major
networks' overall audience share continues to decline. Desperate to
break through the growing clutter of rival cable services, each
network has paid heavily for the costly rights to highly visible
sports events.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS network showed a loss last year and is expected to do so
again this year, in part because of a failure to attract the
younger prime-time audience that commands higher advertising
dollars. Still, Karmazin promised analysts that next year, the
first year of the network's National Football League contract _
with fees that start at about $300 million and escalate _ would be
profitable at CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin said the company anticipates $180 million in 1999 cost
savings generated by layoffs and programing changes. The layoffs,
which the company said would cut costs by as much as $40 million,
would take place across the board at the corporate level and at the
network, including news, sports and programing, though the radio
and advertising division would be unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has roughly 13,000 employees, about 5,000 of whom work at
the network, including 1,400 people in the news division. Though
the company did not quantify the breadth of layoffs at the news
division, another person close to CBS foresaw a reduction of about
100 people. CBS plans to take a $50 million restructuring charge in
the third quarter to account for severance payments related to the
layoff.
</P>
<P>
   The company also plans to slash programing costs by $80 million
to $95 million. ``Murphy Brown,'' ``Cybill,'' ``Step by Step'' and
``Family Matters'' all face ratings declines and are being taken
off the air. Those series, each of which costs CBS $1.8 million an
episode, are being replaced by seven new programs, including ``King
of Queens'' and ``Maggie Winters,'' each of which costs roughly
$600,000 an episode. CBS will have an ownership interest in six of
the new series, so the company will retain roughly half of any
syndication revenues. However, if the new shows fail, the company
faces additional costs in finding replacements.
</P>
<P>
   In putting a value on the new radio company, Karmazin told
analysts that in 1999 the radio group was expected to generate
roughly $1 billion in cash flow, or earnings before interest,
taxes, depreciation and amortization. Other companies with radio
and outdoor advertising, like Clear Channel Communications, are
trading at 20 to 23 times cash flow. Using that figure, the new
company, which would own 155 radio stations and the outdoor
advertising business and would operate under the name Infinity
Broadcasting, would be worth $20 billion to $23 billion, analysts
said. It would carry roughly $750 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   The initial public offering, which is expected to be completed
in November, is unlikely to stop rumors of a sale or merger.
Jessica Reif Cohen, who follows the media for Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.,
has said that even if CBS is not sold, it might do some kind of
joint venture with Time Warner Inc. to merge the two companies'
news operations. Time Warner owns the Cable News Network. And the
two companies could cross promote the CBS Network and the Time
Warner's WB Network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
