u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCHOOLS-HNS &LR;      08-27 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCHOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS TO SHIFT FOCUS TO POLICY ISSUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ Warmed by the embrace of fellow Democrats,
President Clinton tried Thursday to turn the nation's focus back to
policy issues and away from the sex scandal that has imperiled his
tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton interrupted his Martha's Vineyard vacation for a
20-minute flight to this working-class, heavily Democratic city
where he attempted to reclaim those issues that he had hoped would
define his two terms in office.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim McGovern, the congressman who invited Clinton to
Worcester, set the tone for the enthusiastic support dished out to
the president, from the crowds that lined the streets to the
hundreds jammed into a concern hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a city of fair-weather friends. A friend of
Worcester is a friend for life and you, Mr. President, through your
policies, have been a true friend of Worcester,'' McGovern told
Clinton as the audience erupted in applause.
</P>
<P>
   But outside Mechanics Hall, an ornate pre-Civil War structure, a
small crowd chanted, ``Resign, resign'' as the president arrived.
Handmade signs with similar messages were held by bystanders along
the motorcade route. A large banner reading ``Liar!'' also was
paraded around the street.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had been secluded with first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
and daughter Chelsea on the island off the Massachusetts coast
since admitting an affair with former intern Monica Lewinsky and
conceding he lied to his family and the American people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the people of Massachusetts strongly support the
president's initiatives on health care for children, education
reform, a cleaner environment,'' said Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.,
a survivor of several personal scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the kinds of issues that are of concern to the
people of Massachusetts and I think across the country. I think
people want to get on, want to move on,'' Kennedy told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, at least temporarily, is banking on just that
as advisers debate whether the president should again address the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's national address Aug. 17 was long on defiance and
short on contrition, and it renewed anxiety among Democrats in an
election year. The speech, in which the president criticized
independent counsel Kenneth Starr, was roundly panned on Capitol
Hill and calls have increased for Clinton to broach the subject
again.
</P>
<P>
   But he avoided any talk of scandal Thursday, instead speaking of
the issues facing Congress when it returns from its August recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot afford to relax. We must become more rigorous. And
we must ... use the newfound confidence of America to think more
boldly, not less boldly, for our children's future,'' Clinton told
his audience.
</P>
<P>
   The president cited Social Security reform, education, health
care, the environment and campaign finance reform as issues facing
the nation. ``And these things are important,'' Clinton said. ``So
I say to you, the energy that brought you here today, the concern
you have for these issues, you need to bring it back to every
single major challenge this country faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the president made the trip here to announce the
release of an early warning guide for teachers and principals to
identify problem students before they turn violent and to announce
the release of $30 million to states to provide college
scholarships to aspiring police officers.
</P>
<P>
   But, unofficially, the White House also was gauging the level of
public support for the president and seeking a friendly venue for
his first venture before an audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stomach turned a little last week when I watched,'' said
Laura Erickson, 24, a teacher of juvenile delinquent girls, who
attended Thursday's event. ``I feel better. I'm interested in what
he has to say today.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Murgo, 72, a retired tollbooth attendant and audience
member, said, ``It's nobody's business. Let him get on with his
work.''
</P>
<P>
   In an adjacent hall where a larger crowd had watched the
president's remarks, supporters shouted at reporters: ``Good
riddance to you, press.'' The White House strategically turned up
the volume of swing music, drowning out reporters' questions to the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as a sign of Democratic skittishness, Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass., turned aside questions about whether he supported Clinton.
Kerry instead noted he had been on vacation and wanted to talk
about issues.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 schoolchildren, several carrying ``welcome'' signs,
greeted the president as his small jet landed at Worcester Regional
Airport. Reporters who normally travel aboard Air Force One with
the president were banished to a second plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he should have lied to us like he did,
especially on national television,'' said Dan Lodi, 17, a senior at
South High Community School. But the teen-ager added, ``We've all
done some things we're not proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was not the only member of the administration making a
public appearance Thursday while under a cloud of doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, at town meeting on school violence in
San Francisco, made his first public statement about a new Justice
Department inquiry into whether an independent prosecutor should be
appointed to look into fund-raising phone calls he made from his
government office for the 1996 Democratic campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue to fully cooperate with the Justice Department
during their preliminary inquiry,'' Gore said, ``and I remain
confident that they will conclude that, as I know, everything that
I did was legal and proper. He refused to answer reporters'
question on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-day investigation was set in motion Wednesday by Attorney
General Janet Reno. Last year, Reno had refused to request an
outside prosecutor, but she reopened the question after the recent
discovery of a memo which suggested Gore may have known he was
soliciting ``hard money'' contributions that would go directly into
candidate campaigns rather than only party-building ``soft money''
donations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's staff has said the vice president was questioned by
Justice Department on the memo before he left on a two-week
vacation in Hawaii, which concluded Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
