<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6301 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAA-AIR-SAFETY-ART-NY     08-27 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-AIR-SAFETY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATAL PLANE CRASH COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A deadly commuter plane crash near Detroit last
year probably could have been prevented if the Federal Aviation
Administration had adequate procedures for certifying turboprop
planes and had put into effect the lessons learned from a similar
crash, federal safety officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   New procedures developed in response to a crash in 1994 of a
turboprop in Roselawn, Ind., that killed 68 people, probably would
have prevented the accident in Detroit, but their implementation
was lost in a bureaucratic tangle in the FAA, the National
Transportation Safety Board said at a meeting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Both planes had been certified by the FAA as safe for flying
into ice, but the aviation agency still does not know everything it
needs to make that determination, the board said, and it called for
new testing on all turboprop models in service in this country.
There are 1,500 such planes in passenger service, carrying about 54
million passengers a year.
</P>
<P>
   And the safety board called for an immediate campaign to educate
pilots on new strategies for flying through icing conditions. Many
new strategies were developed after the 1995 crash of an ATR-72
owned by an American Airlines affiliate, American Eagle. Those
lessons were not incorporated by most other airlines, including
Comair, which flies as the Delta Connection, the board said. The
plane that crashed on approach to Detroit was an EMB-120, en route
from Comair's hub in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time we see an accident like this repeating itself, on
information we should have already learned, its an indictment of
the whole system,'' said James Hall, chairman of the Safety Board.
``Icing needs to be aggressively approached, as windshear was in
the '80s, so hopefully we can eliminate it as a factor in future
accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about how well the FAA regulates aviation safety, Hall
said, ``we aren't getting what we're paying for.''
</P>
<P>
   Turboprops are not as safe as jets, primarily because of
susceptibility to ice, top officials of the Safety Board said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA, apparently resigned to taking one of the most severe
public beatings of the last few years, was terse in response. Eliot
Brenner, the assistant administrator for public affairs, said, ``we
got the recommendations, and we're looking at the process issues
raised by the board.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to look at anything that can make that system
operate better,'' Brenner said.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA also distributed a chronology of actions it has taken
since the second crash.
</P>
<P>
   A key problem identified by the Safety Board Thursday was that
Embraer, which builds the EMB-120, had written a new procedure that
probably would have prevented the accident, but the information got
lost between two branches of the FAA and no one instructed the
pilots. The new procedure, to regularly inflate a hard-rubber
baloonlike boot on the wing whenever the plane is in icing
conditions, was developed as a result of the Roselawn crash. Before
that crash, rules required pilots to inflate the deicing boot only
after ice formed.
</P>
<P>
   Procedures developed by manufacturers only go to pilots as
requirements if the FAA wants them to. That did not happen with
regard to icing procedures. ``After all of the investment, after
all of the tragedy of Roselawn, to have information that was
generated not make it into the cockpit is something we never want
to see happen again,'' said Hall. The Safety Board is an
independent, advisory agency; the FAA regulates pilots, airlines
and aircraft manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Detroit crash the FAA had been studying six previous
loss-of-control incidents in EMB-120s; there has been at least once
since then. The board said Thursday that ``despite the accumulated
lessons of several major accidents,'' the FAA's posture on the
risks posed by ice had remained ``incremental and reactive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comair plane accumulated ``sandpaper ice'' on its wings,
rough enough to disrupt the airflow and cut lift very sharply. An
ice-free wing on a turboprop that can fly at an inclination to the
wind of up to 18 degrees, but with ice it may lose lift and cause a
crash at only five or six degrees, investigators said. But the
sandpaper ice may be so thin that it is difficult to see from the
cockpit, they said. The phenomenon of rough ice has been known
since the 1930s, and Safety Board investigators found in the FAA's
files a draft memo, dated one year before the crash, noting that
EMB-120s in airline use tended to develop control problems from
coats of ice so thin that their crews did not perceive a risk.
</P>
<P>
   But the tests used to approve the design of the plane are for
thick ice accumulation, not sandpaper ice, on the theory that if
planes can handle thick ice they can handle anything smaller. This
may be wrong, Safety Board engineers said. And by writing standards
that do not include testing for sandpaper ice, ``It does not cover
something that you may encounter in normal flight,'' said Bernard
Loeb, director of the office of aviation safety.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all turboprops have a ``pneumatic boot'' system to
counter ice build-up, but at the time of the crash, pilots at five
of the seven airlines flying them were trained NOT to use it until
thick ice was visible, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The boots are on the forward edges of the wings, thick rubber
balloons that alternately inflate and deflate to break off
accumulated ice. Common wisdom among airlines and FAA regulators is
that pilots should not turn the system on until visible ice has
developed, for fear of letting ice build up in a bulge shape on top
of the inflated boots, in which case the boots would inflate and
deflate within little ice pockets, without breaking the ice, a
purported phenomenon called ``ice bridging.''
</P>
<P>
   But the safety board said that this belief was obsolete, because
such bridging is not possible on modern aircraft. After Roselawn,
Embraer amended the aircraft manual to call for turning the system
on whenever ice was suspected. In the plane that crashed, the
pilots had already turned on a system to heat the propellers and
the windshield, as called for in company procedures, in
anticipation of ice.
</P>
<P>
   The change ws approved by the FAA's office of aircraft
certification. But the certification office never told the office
that regulates airplane operations. Loeb said that the FAA had told
Board investigators that there was no requirement for information
to be passed between the two branches.
</P>
<P>
   Embraer told Comair, too, and Comair sent a memo to pilots about
a month before the accident mentioning the advice. But the airline
did not make it a rule for pilots. A spokeswoman for the airline,
Meghan Glynn said Thursday that the airline would have no comment
until it had a chance to read the board's report.
</P>
<P>
   Loeb said that under the system now in use, airlines have the
final say on such advice. ``The operator can choose to do what we
wants to with it,'' he said, ``the idea being, you build them, we
fly them, and we know how to fly them better than you because we do
it every day.''
</P>
<P>
   John Goglia, a member of the safety board, complained, ``not to
pass that kind of information on to people, who are operating these
airplanes in these conditions on almost a daily basis, is
unconscionable.'' The Board wants the airlines to either adopt the
manufacturers' procedures or demonstrate why they should not.
</P>
<P>
   Brenner said that Jane Garvey, the administrator of the FAA, was
``tied up on other issues'' and was not available to answer
questions about the Safety Board's criticisms. But, he said, ``she
has been very closely following this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
