<HEADER>
A6314 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-BANK-1STLD-WRI     08-27 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S LARGEST BANKS STRUGGLE TO STAVE OFF DEATH THROWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Adds more info on government-bank relationships and how banks'
practices exacerbated recent financial crisis; details and
polishing throughout.)  (See also: RUSSIA-RDP, RUSSIA-COALITION, RUSSIA-EUROPE,
RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT, RUSSIA-U.S., RUSSIA-U.S.-ASSESS, RUSSIA-IMF,
RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS, MARKET) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It was a brief but wild ride for Russia's cowboy
banking empires, and, like the economy on which they were saddled,
they appear headed for disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The banks' importance lies less in their size or conventional
banking duties but in their roles as lenders to the government and
as currency speculators. They gave the government easy credit and
got hooked on the returns, and when things started going really
sour two weeks ago, their flight to the dollar made the situation
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Russian banking system is insolvent, the victim of bad
management, very bad bets on the stability of the ruble and
execrable investments in near-worthless government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Their behavior has left their best client _ the government, now
led by Acting Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin _ with the
unenviable choice between pleasing the entrepreneurs behind many
banks and keeping the banks afloat, or shutting them down and
risking social unrest with unknown consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Capping two weeks of increasingly alarmist rumors, the Russian
government said Thursday night that it intends to nationalize
SBS-Agro Bank, by most measures the country's third-largest. Within
minutes, five more major banks announced plans to merge.
</P>
<P>
   In two days, 10 of the country's 15 biggest banks have either
combined, folded or been earmarked for government takeover. They
will not be the last.
</P>
<P>
   By one estimate, the combined balance sheets of the 15 biggest
banks are at least $4 billion in the hole, a figure that leaps
every day the Russian ruble continues to drop.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 1,300 or so banks, mostly so small as to be
insignificant, are being dragged along in the fiscal undertow. Many
will not be missed, for Russian banks are not banks as westerners
know them, and most Russians keep their savings either at home or
in the giant, government-owned Sberbank, which almost certainly
will not be allowed to go under. Of the smaller houses, some are
money-launderers; some currency speculators; some investment houses
or pension funds or insurance companies or conduits to offshore
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest are cash drawers for vast conglomerates, moving
money among their component companies.
</P>
<P>
   The critical question is what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   On a purely rubles-and-kopecks basis, the solution is pretty
clear: ``Under normal market conditions, banks would fail,'' said
Alex Kotcherguine, the bank credit specialist for Russia and
Eastern Europe for Paribas European Investment in London. ``But
there are no normal market conditions in Russia, as we have all
learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there is already an open struggle over whether to let
the banks die or use the country's dwindling resources to keep them
on life support.
</P>
<P>
   Neither alternative is pleasant: one wipes out up to 80 percent
of all banks, with unknown effects on their creditors and
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The other would require printing more money to shore up sickly
banks and their wealthy owners _ and that would threaten to
re-ignite inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's ousted economic reformers, along with the western
investors who stand to lose billions from a total collapse of the
system, want the government to shut down the sickest banks and
focus its rescue on the few worth saving.
</P>
<P>
   So, it is said, do some banks controlled by industrial behemoths
_ so-called oligarchs _ whose businesses benefit from foreign trade
and western credit, such as oil exporters.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the sickest banks, controlled by other oligarchs,
are dead set against that. The board of SBS-Agro said Thursday
night that it had been blindsided by the government's takeover plan
and demanded that the Kremlin pay ``hundreds of millions of
dollars'' in obligations, presumably in bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin may be somewhere in the middle. A draft economic
program approved by his supporters in the Russian Duma Thursday
called for increased protection of banks and depositors, but
offered no specifics beyond a denial that the proposals were
radical.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the government has shut only one of the top 15 banks,
Imperial Bank, which had defaulted earlier on a $50 million foreign
loan and was closed Wednesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   In terms of global finance, this battle seems at first to be
almost insignificant. The combined assets of all Russian banks as
figured by the Central Bank last January totalled a mere $100
billion _ less than the ninth-largest bank in America, First
Chicago NBD Corp. Russia's largest bank, state-controlled Sberbank,
is only about as big as Summit Bancorp, the 28th-largest U.S. bank.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do the banks have deep roots in the economy. Few Russians
trust much of their money to them _ proportionately, household
deposits are 6 to 10 times smaller than in many western countries.
</P>
<P>
   One motive behind the string of mergers, some analysts say, is
for weak banks to ally themselves with the few banks that serve
households and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning is that the government will nurse those banks
first and terminate others _ such as Imperial _ whose failures will
not drain the wallets of ordinary workers.
</P>
<P>
   But assets and deposits are not what count most in the current
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The banks matter in part because they fed the government's
appetite for easy credit over the last five years, when deficits
were mounting.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Russia's biggest banks established industrial empires _
and close ties to politicians _ by lending the government money,
then accepting shares of state-owned companies in lieu of payment
on the loans.
</P>
<P>
   The business of financing government activities at ever-growing
interest rates became a staple of bank business and provided
capital for other, riskier ventures such as currency speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Between the beginning of 1995 and the middle of 1996, the volume
of short-term government debt ballooned from 1.5 percent of the
nation's gross domestic product to close to 8 percent. And of that
8 percent, as much as five percent was interest payments to
bondholders _ primarily banks.
</P>
<P>
   When Russia declared a temporary halt to paying off its bond
debt on August 17, Russian banks held 105 billion rubles in
short-term bonds _ then about $17 billion _ at interest rates as
high as 150 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the big state- and city-owned banks, many large
Russian banks are the financial string that ties together the
business conglomerates of the oligarchs and other financiers.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the banks manage their finances and supply them with
loans _ often at sweetheart rates _ but it is commonly believed
that they move money in and out of Russia for tax and investment
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   A huge amount of money has fled Russia _ according to Credit
Suisse-First Boston, at least $66 billion from 1994 to 1997 alone.
Cyprus, the best-known offshore tax haven, is home to at least
2,000 subsidiaries of Russian companies, according to Steven
Shevoley, a Thomson Bankwatch vice president who watches Russian
banks from the island.
</P>
<P>
   Had that money remained in the country, it would have spurred
domestic investment and reduced the government's need for deficit
spending, one root of its current woes.
</P>
<P>
   The banks' role as private kitties for industry, combined with
lax supervision from political appointees in the Russian
government, abetted another problem: poor management. No one knows
how much money Russian banks lost through insider deals, fraud and
outright stupidity, but the sum surely is huge, analysts say.
Through poor investments, wrongheaded speculation and shoddy
lending, Russian banks already have lost at least 190 billion
rubles this year alone, according to the investment firm Brunswick
Warburg. That is roughly $22.5 billion at this week's rate of 8.5
rubles per dollar, and far more at the rate that prevailed earlier
this year of about 6 rubles per dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The banks have inadvertently worsened the government's problems
since the full-blown fiscal crisis emerged this month by rushing to
convert their own ruble holdings into dollars.
</P>
<P>
   When the government tried to free up cash for strapped banks
late last week by reducing the amount of capital they are required
to keep on hand, virtually all the freed money was immediately
converted into dollars _ and the ruble dropped another 10 percent
in a single day. In the last 10 days alone, the government has
spent more than $2 billion of its hard-currency reserves defending
the ruble, in part from its own banks.
</P>
<P>
   The futility of that effort became apparent this week, when the
Central Bank finally announced that it would stop defending the
ruble and shut down the currency exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
