<SLUG> BC-DANIELLE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurricane Danielle remains quiet
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- Forecasters won't know until Saturday
morning, but Hurricane Danielle appears to be destined for an
uneventful death at sea.
</P>
<P>
   The small, speeding storm is not expected to threaten Florida
and likely will turn north by the weekend and miss the U.S.
mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The models are indicating it will continue on a northwest
track and then turn,'' said Bob Ebaugh of the National Hurricane
Center in Miami. ``The conditions are looking favorable for us
right now. We'll just have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Danielle, the fourth named storm of the Atlantic season, was
expected strengthen from Thursday's 90 mph winds as it travels at
about 18 to 20 mph through today. Forecasters believe it has not
been influenced by Hurricane Bonnie, the storm that moved on a
similar path and then pounded the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is enough separation between the storms that
Bonnie has not affected Danielle,'' Ebaugh said. ``It's just the
way the conditions are set up right now that has made them go on
roughly the same course.''
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean islands were spared Thursday as Danielle stayed well
to the north, and high-level winds sheered the top of Danielle's
storm clouds and cut its speed. Unlike the 400-mile-wide Bonnie,
Danielle's hurricane-force winds extended only about 45 miles from
the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody just keep an eye on it without anxiety,'' said Brian
Jarvinen, a forecaster at the hurricane center. ``On Saturday,
we'll know for sure what's going to happen here. It'll still be far
enough away from anybody that it shouldn't cause a lot of
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a tropical wave moved Thursday night through the
Florida Straits and into South Florida and is expected to bring
showers and thunderstorms here today and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At noon today, with tours and refreshments, Palm Beach County
will formally open its new Emergency Operations Center at the
corner of Military Trail and Belvedere Road in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The $6.5 million building with state-of-the-art electronic
monitoring and communication equipment has concrete walls that can
withstand 200 mph storm winds.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, it appears Danielle won't be around to mark the
festivities or test the structural engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
