<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Floods soak Carolina coast
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, N.C. -- Parking lots turned into swimming holes.
City streets became canals for canoes. Refrigerators floated like
buoys.
</P>
<P>
   As Tropical Storm Bonnie lazily exited North Carolina late
Thursday night, nearly 20 inches of rain fell in eastern parts of
the Tarheel State and contributed to extensive flooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flooding is going to be greater than we thought,'' Gov.
Jim Hunt said. ``The tides came up and our rivers couldn't get
out.'' That meant they overflowed into houses, streets and
businesses. Hunt said he would maintain a state of emergency ``for
several days.''
</P>
<P>
   On the waterfront of Washington's business district, the Pamlico
River spilled over a bulkhead and flowed 200 yards across a parkway
and through the backdoor of Pamlico Provisions, a general store
that sells kayaks and dry goods.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jimbo McKeon boarded and caulked the doors facing the
river but couldn't stop six inches of water from flooding his store
Thursday. The water wedged strings of green seaweed under McKeon's
plywood barricade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to live on the river, you've got to expect
there's going to be a possibility of a flood,'' McKeon said. ``I
take a little, the river takes a little. I guess we're even now.
I've sold a lot of kayaks and I guess the river is telling me I
need to take a vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   In four hours, the Pamlico advanced from its banks and
threatened to cross Main Street. McKeon's Dumpster floated about 50
yards. A Volkswagen started bobbing. But when the storm passed east
of here in the afternoon, a west wind started driving the river
back to the sound and the flooded backstreets of downtown cleared
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Like spots all over eastern North Carolina, residential
sidestreets in Washington were impassable. Drivers tentatively
crept through water deep enough to float small boats and deputies
cautioned motorists to slow down so wakes wouldn't wash into
houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn how to drive here. You just know where it's going to
flood,'' said Melody Cutler, who snapped a picture of a flooded
intersection. ``It's going to take some time to drain.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pamlico County, on the west side of Pamlico Sound behind the
Outer Banks, officials said wind damage was minimal compared to
Hurricane Fran in 1996. But some low-lying spots had 2 feet of
standing water that flooded houses and carried away refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   Similar stories emerged from Onslow County, where the New River
flows through Camp LeJeune on the coast midway between Wilmington
and Morehead City. Near Jacksonville, officials recorded between 25
inches and 30 inches of rain over 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Onslow County public relations director Briar Bogin said
flooding can be more aggravating than wind damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times with a flood, there's nothing you can do but
wait,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, the foot of the N.C. 210 bridge to North Topsail
Beach on the Onslow County coast was under water. City hall
temporarily was moved to the mainland and residents were issued
re-entry passes to the island.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. 17 bridge connecting Washington and Chocowinity was
closed for about four hours Thursday when the storm surge where the
Tar and Pamlico rivers meet flooded the highway. ``Once the water's
drained off, it's ready to use,'' said Allen Lewis, an engineer for
the state transportation department.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the Pamlico has been a friend to Washington. The
town became a primary supply port during the Revoluntionary War
after other ports were barricaded. Later, the economy developed
around the harvest of oysters and crabs.
</P>
<P>
   But early Thursday, nervous merchants worried the river had
turned against them. Water lapped at the back of brick buildings on
Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   After an overnight curfew expired at daybreak this morning, a
group of men gathered at the Sloan Insurance building on Main
Street overlooking the swollen Pamlico. Given his profession, it
would stand to reason that owner Mike Sloan carries insurance for
potential losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do. But that doesn't make me feel any better,'' Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Ron Clark, 53, and his wife moved to Main Street
into a two-story, clapboard house built in 1840. The house has
hardwood floors, ``the whole deal,'' he said. A magnolia tree now 7
feet in diameter and more than 100 feet tall was planted when the
house was built. Old-timers told Clark he'd stay relatively dry
since he was on the high side of the street. Still, Clark didn't
need to go far to see water spilling out of the Pamlico.
</P>
<P>
   He had a small amount of water in his basement from heavy rain
but Clark had no intention of abandoning the house. ``If it's
lasted 160 years, I hope it lasts one more hurricane,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
