<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOBEACH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Development on risky land pays a price
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH TOPSAIL BEACH, N.C. _ As he surveyed the damaged roofs,
washed-out foundations and sand-clogged roads in Hurricane Bonnie's
wake, Otis Sizemore slowed in front of his bluish-gray duplex
overlooking the churning gray ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like I did fairly well,'' said the North Topsail
Beach alderman, eyeing the plywood he had nailed over the windows
of his home. ``I'm not taking it down yet. I'm not taking any
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   This narrow spit of a town, at the northern end of Topsail
Island between Wilmington and Jacksonville, suffered Hurricane
Fran's most punishing blows two years ago. Largely rebuilt but
still showing scars from North Carolina's most costly natural
disaster, North Topsail Beach escaped Bonnie's strong winds and
tidal surges with far less severe damage than during Fran's strike.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as North Topsail's residents are returning to their
homes after spending two nights in emergency shelters, motels and
other places, they're keeping a worried eye on the forecast for
Danielle, the latest hurricane churning in the Atlantic toward the
Southeastern coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very real concern here that if another storm comes up
here, it could do very much harm,'' said Sizemore, 62, who spent
$70,000 on repairs after Fran.
</P>
<P>
   He's relieved that damage seemed confined to roof damage and a
missing garbage can.
</P>
<P>
   But all around Sizemore's duplex, called Surf Royal, extensive
damage illustrated the vulnerability of North Carolina's heavily
developed barrier islands to pounding storms.
</P>
<P>
   A sizable portion of the northern end of North Topsail is
considered so risky for building that projects are not eligible for
federal flood protection. Even so, two subdivisions, Dolphin Shores
and Cape Island, are under development.
</P>
<P>
   After Fran, town officials hauled in tons of sand to rebuild the
dunes that had protected water-front houses, apartments and
high-rise condominiums. But on Thursday, Sizemore estimated that
Bonnie had washed away half of the new dunes.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday afternoon, crews scraped sand from the roads and
straightened utility poles. Some sections of N.C. 210 were several
inches deep in water, while a several-block-long stretch of Topsail
Road was covered by sand and littered by remnants of wooden decks.
As he traveled at the island's northern tip, Sizemore defended the
right of people to buy property, as long as they're advised of the
risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come down here, buy a piece of property, buy insurance,
cross their fingers and go on from there,'' he said as he passed by
a precarious-looking gray house named ``Living on the Edge.'' ``We
do not live out here unaware.''
</P>
<P>
   But the storms are nonetheless frustrating to beach dwellers.
``This is the third one I've been through, and going back is going
to be a big hassle,'' said Luther McCarter, 33, a North Topsail
resident picking up a re-entry pass at Dixon Elementary School in
Sneads Ferry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
