<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RETURNS TO PUBLIC ARENA WITH SPEECH ON SCHOOL SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-WOMEN) 
(JT) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ Wading into a public arena for the first time
since he admitted to what he called inappropriate behavior with a
White House intern, President Clinton on Thursday received a strong
vote of confidence for his public policies but a mixed review of
his personal conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left his wife and daughter back at the first family's
vacation retreat on Martha's Vineyard and flew to this Democratic
stronghold Thursday morning for a speech on school safety that his
advisers hoped would help refocus the nation and the news media
away from his private life and onto policy matters.
</P>
<P>
   He attracted a presidential-campaign-size crowd, including
hundreds of onlookers packed along a motorcade route of nearly six
miles from the Worcester airport to the historic Mechanics Hall,
where he addressed an audience of 1,200 people and never referred
to his personal situation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech was delivered before news of the plunging stock
market and the precarious situation of Russia's president, Boris
Yeltsin, and sounded more boiler plate than urgent.
</P>
<P>
   While it was meant to highlight school safety, it grazed over an
assortment of policy items, including the economy, terrorism,
Social Security, school construction and health care.
</P>
<P>
   His decision Monday night to make Worcester his debut city
sparked a burst of hometown pride. And those who heard his speech
gave him sustained applause and standing ovations.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim McGovern, the freshman Democrat who had invited Clinton
here months ago, declared from the stage at Mechanics Hall: ``This
is not a city of fair-weather friends. A friend from Worcester is a
friend for life, and you, president, have been a true friend of
Worcester.''
</P>
<P>
   But behind the bunting and resounding applause, many were
careful to distinguish between the president's policies and his
personal life. And signs along the motorcade route were mixed. For
every poster that said ``We support you,''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of you, Mr. President'' or ``We're still with you,
Mr. President,'' others ordered him to ``Resign now!'' or simply
said ``Liar!'' One placard offered a ``Scarlet A.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Whitney, the 63-year-old Democratic mayor of nearby
Fitchburg, who attended the speech after being called by the White
House advance staff, said, ``I have the highest respect for the
office of president.'' But she added that the person in the office
should be a role model for the nation and Clinton ``is not my kind
of role model.'' Another loyal Democrat refused to come. Connie
Lukes, a city councilwoman, boycotted the event, condemning Clinton
and saying, ``The emperor has no clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even McGovern's wife, Lisa, 39, said she had to separate her
personal feelings about the president from his policies. Sitting in
the front row of Mechanics Hall with her four-month-old son, she
said that she was ``disappointed in what he did personally, but
that won't get in the way _ I'm worried about child care and
education, and he has been great on those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, part of the official delegation that greeted
the president and traveled around with him, grew slightly testy
when reporters pressed for his reaction to the president's personal
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything to say,'' he said, an uncharacteristic
response from a politician who so enjoys the public eye that he is
routinely referred to as John (Live Shot) Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I support what the president is doing'' on school
safety, but when asked whether he supported him personally, he
declined to comment, saying he would address the matter next week
when the Senate returns to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   On the topic of school safety, Clinton said that every school in
the country would soon receive a copy of a guide to help teachers
and parents recognize troubled children who might be prone to
violence. According to the guide, such signs include social
isolation, bad grades and ``inappropriate access'' to firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The president resolutely avoided any mention of his personal
life, despite agreement among many of his advisers that he should
offer more contrition to augment his Aug. 17 admission that he had
an ``inappropriate'' relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day Thursday, Clinton appeared by turns drained
and relaxed. He shook nearly every hand in sight. And he apparently
felt no need to rush back to Martha's Vineyard, lingering for more
than 1 hour 45 minutes with Sen. Edward M. Kennedy and other
Democratic politicians at Scano's Restaurant here where he shed his
suit jacket and downed a ``steak bomb'' submarine sandwich with
french fries.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the restaurant, Mary Scano, a former member of the
City Council, strongly supported Clinton. Asked about his admission
of an improper relationship, she said: ``So he lied. I lie. When I
was on the Council, I lied.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the scores of people waiting to meet Clinton outside the
restaurant was Charlie Gallagher, 32, an electrician. He said he
wished the president had apologized more, if only to get the whole
thing over with. But, he added: ``He probably didn't do anything
different than any other married man would have done, in terms of
trying to cover up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Moakley, from Boston, who ate lunch with the president,
said that it would be difficult for Clinton to say anything more
about Ms. Lewinsky. ``You don't get a second shot at an apology,''
he said. ``You've got to get it right the first time.'' Asked if
Clinton got it right the first time, Moakley said: ``Almost.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
