<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HOMER BUSH IS NO LONGER A MERE MASCOT  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For most of this season, Homer Bush has been a
first-hand witness to the excellence of the New York Yankees, a
25th man with a good view.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no weak spots,'' he said Thursday night, somewhat
stunned to be making his second straight start, a consequence of
his crucial home run Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some teams, you get to their fourth hitter, maybe they have a
good fifth hitter, but then you can pitch around him,'' Bush said,
looking around the clubhouse crammed with talent. ``We've got a
fourth hitter, a fifth, a sixth, a seventh, an eighth. Man, when
does it stop?''
</P>
<P>
   It does not even stop at the 24th man. Bush made the team this
spring on the fault line on the X-ray of Luis Sojo's hand. At
first, he was a marginal player whose sweetness (a word not often
used in baseball these days) radiated around the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys score so many runs, they get tired; that gives me a
chance,'' Bush said. ``I love going into a game to pinch-run. I
don't just jog, I take off running. I love hearing them cheer for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   He understands that some of the cheers are for what he
represents, but he can live with that.
</P>
<P>
   This is his eighth professional season, his first full year in
the majors, and he is overtly grateful.
</P>
<P>
   He comes from East St. Louis, Ill., one of eight children, whose
father, a police officer, was shot to death when he was off-duty.
</P>
<P>
   His mother struggled to keep the family together, and now he has
the chance to earn a few dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring he had a month's grace, he hustled and he hit and he
backed up the infielders, and when Sojo came back, Bush stayed. He
was hitting .362 in 25 games going into Thursday night, and his
biggest hit came in Wednesday's second game, with the Yankees
suffering through a four-game losing streak, and Knee-Jerk City
going into its normal panic.
</P>
<P>
   With two runners on base, Bush was trying to ``maybe drive in a
run with a sacrifice fly.'' He made an educated guess on a
fastball, and saw the outfielders' backs, and said to himself,
``You just hit a big-league home run,'' which he had never done
before.
</P>
<P>
   He pumped his fist and raced home, taking full note that the
first man out of the dugout was Chuck Knoblauch, the regular second
baseman, who was getting a rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knobby was talking to me the whole game,'' Bush said. ``He was
telling me what to expect out there. That made it easier, inning by
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would know if somebody was mad because you were playing,
but that's the thing about this team. He's making six million fish
and he's excited for me. You don't have anybody hoping you fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody sent a couple of ushers to bargain with the fan who had
captured Bush's ball. They said they would accept a ``gamer'' bat
in return for the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm giving them a bat from Derek Jeter or Bernie Williams, one
of the stars,'' Bush said, quite seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Monahan, the Yankee trainer, later presented him with the
ball, enclosed in a clear plastic case, with the words ``1st Major
League Home Run vs. Sparks 8-26-98 Yankee Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush pointed at the ball and said, ``Look, it's lopsided,'' then
gave a smile that could light up the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Bush went out to the Garden State Mall in Paramus,
N.J., and was proud when people asked for his autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm using all of this as a learning tool,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can contribute to this team, I can play anywhere in the
major leagues, whatever the situation happens to be. My stock has
gone up. At least, that's how I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   He watches what the regulars do:
</P>
<P>
   ``Clutch hitters. We had that brawl with Baltimore, and Bernie
comes back and hits a home run and then Tim Raines follows with
another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plays Scott Brosius makes at third base. These guys make
it look easy, but I see the bad side. They get upset if they have a
bad game. This game is not as easy as they make it seem.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night Joe Torre decided to rest Brosius, who had played
both games Wednesday, and he started Bush, who had played only one
game at third.
</P>
<P>
   When reporters told him he was in the starting lineup, Bush
said, ``Oh, yeah.'' Then he checked, and found it was true. It's
that kind of season. The 25th man can play, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
