<HEADLINE>
FBI, TEXAS RANGERS INVESTIGATING TEXAS HOUSING OFFICIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A state housing official is under investigation
by the FBI and the Texas Rangers in an alleged scheme to profit
from federal low-income housing money she oversees, according to
court documents and state officials.
</P>
<P>
   Florita Bell Griffin, a member of the board that oversees the
Texas Department of Housing and Community Affairs, is one of
several Bryan residents accused of an elaborate conspiracy to
improperly obtain federal funds aimed at building homes for the
poor, documents filed in a flurry of lawsuits in Bryan show. She
denies any wrongdoing
</P>
<P>
   ``Specifically, I am investigating allegations that these
individuals participated in a scheme to fraudulently receive tax
credits, down payment assistance, real estate acquisition, and
interim construction financing from a state agency. . .,'' FBI
agent Robert W. Martin said in a sworn affidavit last May seeking a
warrant to search Griffin's two-story home in Bryan for documents.
</P>
<P>
   Martin cited a tape-recorded meeting, a handwritten note on how
to divide certain profits and other evidence in the FBI's
possession, and said there was probable cause to believe Griffin
and her partners engaged in several federal offenses. These include
theft or bribery concerning programs receiving federal funds,
conspiracy to defraud the United States and aiding or abetting in
such criminal activities.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Griffin is accused of using her influence as a
public official to approve federal subsidies for low-income real
estate deals in which she had a secret interest. She has also been
sued by a Fort Worth-area developer who claims she secretly plotted
with others to defraud him. In turn, she filed her own libel and
slander lawsuit against him and another FBI informant.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of those allegations that were made are absolutely untrue
and will be proven to be untrue if necessary. I would hate to have
my reputation ruined,'' said Griffin, formerly a Bryan city planner
and lecturer at Texas A&AMP;M University's department of landscape
architecture and urban planning.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin was appointed by Gov. George W. Bush in 1995 as one of
nine members of the board that oversees housing and community
affairs department, which awards government subsidies for projects
around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin and others, noting that they are subjects of a criminal
investigation, have declined to produce documents or give oral
depositions in the related civil suit, asserting their Fifth
Amendment right against self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI is doing their job. It's an ongoing investigation,''
said Sam Adamo, Griffin's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI probe includes ``serious and complex allegations
involving a potential conflict of interest,'' said Bush spokeswoman
Karen Hughes. She said the governor's office called the Texas
Rangers into the investigation shortly after learning of the
allegations April 27 from another housing board member.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the governor's office has been told that the federal
investigation might be completed this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the FBI asked Bush's office not to remove
Griffin from the housing board or to take any other action that
could interfere with the criminal investigation, Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors about the probe have swirled within the housing
department for weeks, said the agency's outgoing executive director
Larry P. Manley.
</P>
<P>
   Manley resigned his own post this week amid criticisms, which he
calls unfair and untrue, that Texas could lose federal money that
the agency did not allocate to low-income housing projects quickly
enough. He said his resignation was unrelated to questions about
the agency's handling of federal funds, including the criminal
investigation of Griffin. His plan is to return to private
business, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no obvious violation of any laws based on what we've
seen here,`` Manley said. ''I don't know anything about what's
going on in this whole FBI analysis. We're making referrals where
appropriate and then we're out of the picture.``
</P>
<P>
   Court documents and records at the housing agency show that
Griffin participated in two favorable board votes in 1997 to award
federal tax credits for an apartment project in Bryan called One
Golden Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Mitchell of Tarrant County has claimed in a civil
lawsuit and to federal law enforcement authorities that he was
victimized in an ``incredible conspiratorial fraud'' in which
Griffin secretly participated in One Golden Oaks and hid part of
her personal share in a company called Arkofa Consulting. Also
involved in the alleged scheme were Terry Roberts, Joe Lee Walker
and Barry Hammond, all of Bryan, according to the FBI affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, FBI agent Martin said Griffin is accused of
buying a block of land for the apartment project along with
Roberts, Walker and Hammond as secret partners in a company called
B. Hammond Homes Inc. Mitchell was led to believe the land actually
cost $15,000 an acre and agreed to pay that amount for 23 acres.
What he did not know is that the secret partners had already bought
the land as part of a larger 131-acre block for only $2,000 an
acre.
</P>
<P>
   The secret partners allegedly came away with parcels of roughly
28 acres each and placed the titles under names of relatives and
Arkofa. Hammond, who later agreed to act as an FBI informant,
placed his property in his own name. A handwritten note, cited by
the FBI as showing how profits from a subsequent deal involving the
land would be divided, indicate that Griffin took part of her
earnings in the form of home repairs performed by Hammond, a
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   In another deal the FBI is investigating, Griffin, Hammond,
Roberts and Walker are accused of seeking federal assistance for a
single-family home development in Bryan called Shadow Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Hammond told the FBI that Griffin was involved in that deal from
the start and ``stated on several occasions throughout the spring
and summer of 1997 that Shadow Wood would receive board approval
for (Texas Department of Housing and Community Affairs)
assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin's libel and slander suit against Mitchell and Hammond
denies that she was a secret investor in B. Hammond Homes, that she
participated in secret meetings or that she had hidden any interest
in deals under a corporate name.
</P>
<P>
   She asserted that Hammond made defamatory statements in a
publication in a ``drug-induced false belief'' that she and Walker
were trying to defraud him. Griffin doesn't name the publication
that printed Hammond's allegations and doesn't elaborate on the
issue of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly question the credibility of her two accusers.
They have their motives for saying what they've said,'' Adamo,
Griffin's attorney said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
