<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-AFTERMATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELATED NORTH CAROLINA OFFICIALS EXPRESS RELIEF OVER MINOR HURRICANE
DAMAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TONY FREEMANTLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHOCOWINITY, N.C. _ Big Al Crisp is one unlucky guy.
</P>
<P>
   While most residents of North Carolina's coastline breathed a
sigh of relief Thursday, emerging from houses and shelters to
discover minimal damage by Hurricane Bonnie, Crisp was wading
through waist deep water inspecting his flooded business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad,'' he said looking out over his waterlogged inventory
of recreational vehicles. ``I tell you, it's sad. This is the third
time one of these storms has done this to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for most everyone else, Crisp was in the minority
Thursday, one of the few with the unpleasant task of counting their
losses rather than their blessings.
</P>
<P>
   When Hurricane Bonnie churned through the Atlantic Ocean off the
North Carolina coast three days ago, it was a Category 3 storm 400
miles wide with winds of 115 mph. Many feared it would cause severe
damage to an area that had barely begun to heal from the last big
storm.
</P>
<P>
   But as it weakened to a tropical storm and headed out to sea
Thursday, state officials expressed relief that damage to
structures, to fragile beaches, to trees, to power lines were all
being tallied in the ``minor'' column.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, they were elated that Bonnie had caused no loss of
life or serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's amazing, really,'' said Susan Perkins, a spokeswoman
for the state division of emergency management. ``People here are
surprised and happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie was downgraded to a tropical storm in the early afternoon
Thursday after coming ashore 24 hours earlier near Cape Fear and
then tracking slowly up the North Carolina coast, dumping sheets of
rain. Wilmington, the biggest city in its path, received upward of
8 inches, and forecasters had predicted as much as 20 inches could
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Bonnie was moving so slowly, anywhere between 4
mph and 8 mph after landfall, led officials to express concern that
severe flooding would occur. And while the rain did fall in sheets,
the only significant flooding occurred along the banks of the
Pamlico River near the city of Washington, and it was caused by
storm surge, not rain.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are still so fresh in the minds of many residents
here, Bonnie was often compared to hurricanes Fran and Bertha,
which struck in 1996
</P>
<P>
   Fran and Bertha both sent water into the basement of dentist
Jeff Rumley's house on the Pamlico River, a house built in 1874 by
a North Carolina lumber baron and which, presumably, has weathered
many such storms. Bonnie failed to measure up to her predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was nothing like it was with Fran,'' Rumley said. ``This
(water) came in real slow and it's starting to leave real fast. It
didn't push in like Frank and break things as it went. It just rose
real slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   About 80 miles away, near Cape Carteret, Claude Murdoch, a
67-year-old, ``semi-retired'' mechanic had already mopped the mud
off the floor of his modest house on the shores of the Intracoastal
Waterway. The flood damage to his place was also the result of
storm surge, which had further damaged the pier he is trying to
build that keeps getting torn up by hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and her (his wife Jessie B. Murdoch), we mopped it real
good,'' Murdoch said as the winds whipped the sound behind him into
dancing whitecaps. ``She's got cancer real bad. I still got damage
from Fran I ain't ever fixed. I would have if I didn't have to work
to pay for her radiation treatments.''
</P>
<P>
   By later afternoon, convoys of power company trucks headed into
the hurricane area from their staging area in Raleigh, ready to
restore power to the 250,000 people still without it. Convoys of
National Guard troops also were headed to the coast to offer their
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton on Thursday declared 10 North Carolina
counties disaster areas, an act that opens the federal financial
spigots and which will help those whose property was damaged by the
storm.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt was to take a helicopter tour
Friday of the area affected by Bonnie. It will probably be
Saturday, state officials said, before state and federal teams from
the Federal Emergency Management Agency can do a detailed
inspection of damage. Until that happens, they said, it is not
possible to provide an estimate of the amount of damage caused.
</P>
<P>
   But preliminary reports coming in from some of the beaches
closed during the storm indicated damage to houses and beaches was
not severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Structural damage seems to be sort of minor,'' said Perkins.
``It appears there is some beach erosion, some roofs ripped off,
some flooding in some of the buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins and other state officials attribute the lack of deaths
or serious injuries to the mass evacuations. The majority of people
asked to leave the area Tuesday obeyed, heading inland to
relatives, hotels or one of the shelters set up by the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday evening, Perkins said, 11,500 people remained in
shelters, but they were heading home in increasing numbers.
</P>
<P>
   As for Big Al Crisp? Well if his insurance company pays him like
they have twice before, he will stay where he is, he said, where he
grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can replace property,'' he said. ``But you can't replace
life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
