<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-STOCK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Multinationals, market feel Moscow's crunch
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Russian and Asian economic and currency crises
weigh heavily on the minds of skittish investors, and they didn't
hesitate to unload shares of multinational companies Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the victims was Atlanta-based Coca-Cola, whose stock was
downgraded by an analyst who said the company's reliance on
international markets make it increasingly vulnerable to currency
gyrations.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's stock fell $4.43 3/4 in heavy trading to close at
$74.75 on a day it and other multinationals sent the Dow Jones
industrial average tumbling 357.36 points. The index is now 1,171
points below its record 9,337.97 set on July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and investors are concerned that weakening economies in
Russia, Asia and emerging markets may make it more difficult for
Coca-Cola and other companies doing business around the world to
continue their strong profit growth. Coca-Cola does business in 197
countries and gets 70 percent of its sales and 75 percent of its
profit from international operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia is just the latest in a series of crises or adverse
events in emerging markets,'' said Douglas M. Lane, a beverage
analyst with Merrill Lynch Global Securities. ``Maybe it was the
final straw, but I want to stress that it's much more widespread
than just Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2131EDT &QL; 
