<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6344 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOCKS-ANALYSIS-COX     08-27 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-ANALYSIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. economy OK, but world situation raising some fears
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The U.S. economy is an island of strength in a
widening sea of foreign economic and currency failure, but it's by
no means clear how long that will last.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the greatest danger is that the current disarray in
international economic leadership could make a bad situation
disastrous. The result could be a U.S. recession, so far regarded
as unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton hasn't got any business going to Russia to
meet with (President Boris) Yeltsin. He should call a meeting of
G-7 (industrial) nations to hammer out a plan,'' said Georgia State
University economist Donald Ratajczak.
</P>
<P>
   He said the chief financial problem facing Asia, Russia and
elsewhere is the lack of lending capacity by the International
Monetary Fund and major foreign banks, essential to keep those
economies going.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big shock is not that Russia is defaulting, but that the
IMF can't help them,'' said Ratajczak. ``That means they can't give
any more help to Asia and Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that U.S. banks are still strong, with the
lending power needed to service a growing U.S. economy _ which
government figures showed on Thursday to be stronger than expected.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's not too late to stop the avalanche of
global economic failure before it reaches the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for investors, but the big question is still
how much and how long these foreign problems will affect the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think the seriousness of the foreign threat has
been exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marketplace is vastly over-reacting to the risks to our
economy from foreign problems,'' said Alfred Goldman, chief
strategist for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts were forecasting a slowdown in the bull market
even before the Asian crisis surfaced last year, based on the
longer-range prospect for slower U.S. economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   What happened, say analysts, is that investors may have known
that profits would slow, but only reacted when the actual slowdown
showed up in first- and second-quarter corporate earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   According to First Call, the earnings of Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
companies grew about 3.4 percent in the second quarter against the
comparable 1997 numbers, or about the same as in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``As estimates for the third quarter continue to be revised
downward, the odds continue to rise that third-quarter earnings
will be similar to the last two quarters,'' said First Call
Research Director Charles L. Hill.
</P>
<P>
   While it took foreign economic problems to trigger this year's
sell-off in stocks, analysts say the severity of the decline was a
product not only of slower earnings growth but high stock
valuations.
</P>
<P>
   The price-to-earnings ratio of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 is 25.
Historically, it should be 15. And many individual stocks have P/Es
that are far above that of the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had long feared that overvaluation, coupled with the
length of the 1990s bull market, would greatly worsen the sell-off
when it came.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, that's what happened: 63 percent of all stocks
listed on the New York Stock Exchange are down 20 percent or more
from their 52-week highs, and 48 percent are down 25 percent or
more, according to industry research.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are divided over how long this correction will last,
and how far the indexes will fall. But most agree it's the kind of
pain that investors have been warned about for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wisdom of dip buying is being put to the test,'' said
Standard &AMP; Poor's analyst Arnold Kaufman in a Web site report.
``The recent series of failed rally attempts has immobilized buyers
for the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these threats to the market, the mood among some leading
Wall Street analysts is still fundamentally upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kaufman, ``the decline won't cascade from here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Individual investors, many of whom intend to stay with
automatic stock buying via 401(k) programs, should soon come to the
market's rescue,'' said Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman reiterated his forecast that the Dow will bottom out at
about 8,000 _ only 166 points from Thursday's close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recommended some buying about 20 minutes ago,'' he said
Thursday when called.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
