r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DEBARTOLO-TEX     08-27 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DEBARTOLO-TEX </SLUG>
 
SALE OF DeBARTOLO TRACKS CALLED OFF 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sale of horse racetracks Louisiana Downs, Remington Park and
Thistledown was called off late yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Call Now Inc., a publicly held company with a subsidiary that
operates Retama Park horse track in suburban San Antonio, put down
a refundable $2 million deposit in July in a bid to buy the tracks
from the Ohio-based DeBartolo Corp. for an undisclosed amount.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal was contingent on Call Now securing financing for
the purchase, and that apparently never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Call Now chairman William Allen and his son-in-law, company
president Bryan Brown, could not be reached for comment. Call Now
headquarters was recently relocated to San Antonio from Miami
Shores, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mutual agreement,'' said John York, the senior vice
president of the DeBartolo Racing division. ``Both of us worked
hard trying to get it done, but it simply wasn't to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're neither sad nor glad this thing has ended. Everyone
should know that it's business as usual at DeBartolo Racing.''
</P>
<P>
   York said that Call Now was satisfied with the operation of the
tracks, and that DeBartolo Racing was satisfied with the company's
due diligence.
</P>
<P>
   But although York would not elaborate, problems with financing
became apparent this week. Call Now failed to respond to requests
by the Louisiana and Oklahoma racing commissions for basic
information such as Social Security numbers of Call Now principals,
so that mandatory background checks could be completed.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in horse racing at the DeBartolo Corp. has visibly
waned since the December 1994 death of founder Edward DeBartolo
Sr., a fan of the sport who loved to bet on horses.
</P>
<P>
   York said published industry reports that the corporation has
been ``openly peddling the tracks'' since DeBartolo's death are
untrue. However, York said that after news of Call Now's interest
in buying the tracks was made public, other groups stepped forward
to express possible interest as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not those people will resurface now, I don't
know,'' York said.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Downs, acquired in the mid-1970s by DeBartolo, is
located in Bossier City and has been the most profitable of the
three tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Remington Park in Oklahoma City was built by the company in 1988
at a cost of $94 million but has lost money.
</P>
<P>
   Thistledown in suburban Cleveland, a minor-league track located
near the DeBartolo corporate headquarters of Youngstown, was the
company's first racing venture, purchased in 1961.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
