<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Low injuries, costs bring sighs of relief
 &HT;    By Steve Visser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunny skies were expected to brighten North Carolina today as
people start cleaning up after Bonnie, the much-anticipated monster
hurricane that bullied the coast but proved to be little more than
a big, wet bag of wind.
</P>
<P>
   The damage appears minimal, with preliminary estimates at less
than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Casualties, too, appeared slight. In Hyde County, a man was cut
when a window broke and a firefighter was injured when a wall
collapsed on him during an electrical fire. Neither injury was
life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   There was some flooding, about 10,000 people remained in
shelters, and 276,500 people didn't have electricity Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that to Hurricane Fran in September 1996. That storm
turned into North Carolina's costliest disaster when, instead of
turning north, it plowed through the middle of the state, causing
$5.2 billion in damage and 22 deaths. The state was just recovering
from Hurricane Bertha, which had hit two months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, slow-moving Bonnie may be best remembered as a boon
for scientists who were trying to learn more about hurricanes'
behavior by circling the storm in a converted Air Force spy plane,
getting previously unavailable views.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got to have a hurricane, this is the kind of
hurricane you want to have,'' said Capt. John Williams, the Coast
Guard's commanding officer of the ports of Wilmington and Morehead
City after inspecting damage.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday afternoon, Bonnie's winds had fallen to 65 mph, but
the coast did take a pounding with hours of heavy rain. The storm
drenched Jacksonville with 10.4 inches of rain. Wilmington, which
was in Bonnie's cross hairs Wednesday, got 9 inches, Greenville,
7.6, and Emerald Isle, 6.7.
</P>
<P>
   The storm was expected to have moved offshore by today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
