<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-CRISIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA WOE JOLTS WORLD, US MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US stock market tumbled by more than 350 points Thursday,
caving in to the deepening crisis in Russia that hammered virtually
every other stock market in the world.
</P>
<P>
   After withstanding the bad news emanating from Russia all week,
the Dow Jones industrial average registered its third-biggest point
drop in history, plunging 357.36 points, or 4.2 percent, to
8,165.99 in the second-heaviest trading day ever. In percentage
terms, the decline was the worst since Oct. 27, 1997, when waves of
bad news in Asian financial markets took their toll in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, from Tokyo to Madrid to Caracas, stock markets in
industrial and emerging countries fell like dominoes, shaken by
Russia's instability and continued concerns about Japan's economic
gridlock. Adding to the financial turmoil, prices of commodities
plunged to a 21-year lows before recovering slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been involved in the capital markets 15 years, and I've
never seen anything as widespread as this,'' said Mark Madden, an
international portfolio manager for Pioneer Mutual Funds in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   While stocks tumbled, investors flocked to US Treasury bonds, a
haven for international investors in times of uncertainty. Prices
on 30-year Treasury bonds soared. Yields, which move inversely with
bond prices and which influence interest rates on loans, fell to
5.34 percent. That is the lowest closing yield since the government
began regular sales of bonds 21 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors are expected to be extremely nervous
today amid fears that the long-running bull market in stocks may be
ending.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow is off 12.6 percent from its July 17 record of 9337.97,
exceeding the 10 percent loss that marks an official stock market
correction.
</P>
<P>
   The market seemed to hit bottom numerous times during the day.
After a hectic morning of selling, the Dow dropped by 353 points
before recovering somewhat. At noon, it was down just over 275
points but fell further during the day. By around 3:30, as it
showed signs of calming down, it plunged further.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kept testing the low and then it went right through it,''
said Lawrence Horwitz, managing director of Primark Decision
Economics in Boston. ``Russia with its big political presence was a
big factor in that. The problems there opened a lot of eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of evidence for investors searching for trouble
spots in currencies and stock markets worldwide. In Russia, where
rumors of President Boris Yeltsin's downfall are raging and a
meltdown of the ruble has occurred, the Russian Trading System
index fell 17.13 percent to end at its lowest recorded level since
its introduction in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Stock market drops Thursday started in Japan and continued
westward.
</P>
<P>
   The Nikkei index of 225 Japanese stocks fell by 3.04 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Eastern European markets, which are directly tied to Russia,
stock market indexes plunged as international investors divested
their holdings after Russia this week announced a debt
restructuring plan that forces investors to accept huge losses.
</P>
<P>
   In Western Europe, Spain's stock index, the IBEX 35, suffered
the biggest decline because of its business ties with Latin
America, where markets were also down again Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Money managers noted that connections between European companies
and emerging markets are a weak spot. For example, Germany's
biggest bank, Deutsche Bank, which is a lender in Russia, lost 7
percent of its value Thursday. The DAX index in Germany fell 4.48
percent. London's FT-SE fell 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's index, the Sao Paulo Bovespa, fell 10 percent to its
lowest level since Nov. 21, 1996, while Mexico's Bolsa index was
down more than 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, investors who took their cues from
Russia's crisis also were reacting to a potent mix of economic
worries. Japan has failed to resolve a severe banking crisis.
Economic woes in Russia and Asia may be spreading to Europe and
Latin America, and could shake the US economy, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just a fear you're going to end up with a global
recession from all this mess,'' said Robert MacIntosh, portfolio
manager for Eaton Vance Management in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, declining issues swamped
advancing issues 2,872 to 360 on volume of 934 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks of blue-chip companies such as Coca-Cola Co. and J.P.
Morgan, which have extensive international operations, were
hammered. But declines were distributed across virtually every
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite slumped 81.72 points, or
4.6 percent, to 1,686.41, the second-biggest point decline in that
market's history.
</P>
<P>
   The government said Thursday that the nation's economic growth
cooled to a 1.6 percent annual rate in the second quarter. The
report, which was no surprise to economists, played little role in
the market's dive.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, portfolio managers and market watchers said
individual investors were remarkably calm. Much of the selling was
by managers of hedge funds selling their high-risk stocks or by
Wall Street brokerage firms unloading stocks. The NYSE did not fall
enough to set off the automatic circuit breakers put in place after
the 1987 crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sense of panic as there have been in previous down
markets. The systems all work. People are just selling stuff,''
said Giles McNamee, an investment banker with FAC Equities in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The US stock market has been sky-high for months and due for a
fall, said Kenneth Heebner, portfolio manager for CGM Funds in
Boston. Stock prices have been trading at astronomical levels of 23
to 25 times their estimated earnings, he said. The historic rate is
about 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan led the Dow's decliners, down 7 1/8 to 110 13/16,
and Citicorp was down 7 3/8 at 126 1/2. Global consumer companies
also took a hit. Coca-Cola fell 4 7/16, closing at 74 3/4. Procter
&AMP; Gamble Co. declined 2 5/16, closing at 80 9/16. Gillette was off
1 5/8, closing at 43 1/4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
