</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Ex- change, declining issues swamped
advancing issues 2,872 to 360 on vol- ume of 934 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks of blue-chip companies L such as Coca-Cola Co. and J.P.
Mor- gan, which have extensive interna- tional operations, were
hammered. But declines were distributed across virtually every
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq L composite slumped 81.72 points, or
4.6 percent, to 1,686.41, the second- biggest point decline in that
mar- ket's history.
</P>
<P>
   The government said yesterday that the nation's economic growth
cooled to a 1.6 percent annual rate in the second quarter. The
report, L which was no surprise to economists, played little role
in the market's dive.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, portfolio managers L and market watchers said
individual investors were remarkably calm. L Much of the selling
was by managers of hedge funds selling their high-risk stocks or by
Wall Street brokerage firms unloading stocks. The NYSE did not fall
enough to set off the automatic circuit breakers put in place after
the 1987 crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sense of panic as there have been in previous down
markets. The systems all work. Peo- ple are just selling stuff,''
said Giles McNamee, an investment banker L with FAC Equities in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The US stock market has been sky-high for months and due for a
fall, said Kenneth Heebner, portfolio manager for CGM Funds in
Boston. Stock prices have been trading at as- tronomical levels of
23 to 25 times their estimated earnings, he said. The historic rate
is about 6.5 L percent.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan led the Dow's de-H cliners, down 7 1/8 to 110 13/16,
and Citicorp was down 7 3/8 at 126 1/2. Glo- bal consumer companies
also took a hit. Coca-Cola fell 4 7/16, closing at 74 3/4. Procter
&AMP; Gamble Co. declined 2 5/16, closing at 80 9/16. Gillette was off
1 5/8, closing at 43 1/4.
</P>
</TEXT>
