<SLUG> BC-CONGO-REBELLION-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGO'S WAR TURNS TO BRUTAL KILLINGS ON KINSHASA'S STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ Even as the fighting just outside the capital
diminished Thursday, the government severely tightened security,
and evidence emerged that civilians and soldiers had brutally
killed several suspected rebel infiltrators.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, government officials sounded a triumphant note,
holding two news conferences in which they attacked Rwanda and
Uganda, the countries that propelled Laurent Kabila to the
presidency less than two years ago but that are now backing the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   At one news conference, Kabila's Cabinet chief, Abdoulaye
Yerodia, said more than 1,000 prisoners had been captured,
including some in a eucalyptus field near the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were even some up in the trees _ all naked,'' Yerodia
said in a hourlong news conference, which he ended by sticking a
big cigar in his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The government's claims were difficult to verify because
soldiers forbade foreign reporters staying at two hotels from
leaving their buildings and kept the city under tight control.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers severely restricted access to streets, erecting
checkpoints every several hundred feet and demanding to see
people's identification cards and car registration documents, said
hotel workers and taxi drivers who had traveled in from the area
outside the city's diplomatic and business center.
</P>
<P>
   The government's actions were apparently aimed at identifying
potential rebels who had infiltrated the city. And in keeping with
that goal, government soldiers and local police officers wore their
shirts inside-out to distinguish themselves from possible
impersonators.
</P>
<P>
   A representative of the World Health Organization here said that
Kinshasa's hospitals were overwhelmed with wounded, and that
fighting prevented the delivery of crucial medical supplies from
Brazzaville, across the river in the neighboring Congo Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The government carefully massaged the messages it wanted the
world to see from Kinshasa Thursday, organizing two trips for a few
reporters. The first trip, by helicopter, seemed intended to
demonstrate that the government controlled the airport, 17 miles
southeast of the city's center, although gunfire could be heard
nearby. The sounds of heavy shelling and gunfire that were heard in
Kinshasa for several hours on Wednesday, however, died down
Thursday, as government officials said their forces were clearing
remnants of rebel forces from the airport area.
</P>
<P>
   The message the government wanted to convey with the second trip
was less clear, though potentially much more explosive. In late
afternoon, government soldiers escorted a pool photographer to
certain neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   On a road to the airport, the pool photographer reported seeing
at least 10 charred bodies of what were said to be rebels, as a
crowd of local residents claimed credit for the killings. In
another area, the photographer shot pictures of government soldiers
tossing a living man over a bridge and shooting him with rifles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's popular justice,'' the soldiers said, accusing the
Rwandans of bringing hate into the Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of this civil war on Aug. 2, government
propaganda has focused on stirring up the deep historic resentment
of the ethnic Tutsi of eastern Congo, who are leading this
rebellion, and the Rwandan Tutsi, who most Western diplomats
believe are backing them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The two groups, along with Uganda, are the ones who yanked
Kabila from obscurity to lead a successful rebellion against Mobutu
Sese Seko, the longtime dictator of this country, which he had
named Zaire. So at the beginning of his presidency, Kabila had
several top aides who were Tutsi, but he eventually cut his ties
with them, when their roles in the government made him unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Kinshasa, many Congolese express open hatred of the
ethnic Tutsi in eastern Congo. And the government has increased
popular support for the war by portraying it explicitly as an
attempted foreign invasion by Rwandan Tutsi and Congo's tiny Tutsi
minority.
</P>
<P>
   It was impossible to determine whether the rebels killed
Thursday in public were ethnic Tutsi. Government officials had said
on Wednesday that most of the rebel infiltrators appeared to be
Congolese, former soldiers in Mobutu's army, who joined the
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the dead men's ethnicity, the message was interpreted
by Rwanda as an attack on Tutsi.
</P>
<P>
   The previous civil war that brought Kabila to power had its
roots in the ethnic conflicts between Hutu and Tutsi that exploded
into massacres in Rwanda in 1994. Hutu hard-liners, who had
organized the killings of an estimated half-million Tutsi and some
moderate Hutu, fled into refugee camps in Congo. They used the
camps as bases to launch attacks on Rwanda, and in 1996, Rwanda's
Tutsi-led government backed Kabila's uprising hoping it would empty
the camps.
</P>
<P>
   But Rwanda, as well as Uganda, has complained that Kabila has
failed in keeping peace in its border areas. Rwanda has also
complained that Kabila has not guaranteed the safety of the ethnic
Tutsi living in eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels now control most cities in eastern Congo, but have
lost their ascendancy in the region southwest of Kinshasa. Soon
after the start of the insurrection, rebels flew more than 1,000
miles from eastern Congo to its westernmost point, and began a
seemingly unstoppable march into Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   But the rebels' fortunes changed after the war began widening
into a regional conflict, as Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia began
buttressing Kabila's poorly organized army with arms and
battle-hardened troops. With the influx of troops and arms, the
government's forces have gained the upper hand in the region
southwest of the capital. With their allies, the government's
forces are expected to soon eliminate the rebel presence in the
southwest. The rebels still control key points southwest of here:
the port city of Matadi and the huge Inga hydroelectric dam, which
feeds power to the Kinshasa region.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the lack of power and the interruption of shipments
along the Congo River, the capital's gas stations were closed
Thursday, residents said. Youths who sell gasoline on
street-corners by the gallon _ known here as Little Gadhafis _ had
raised the price, taxi drivers said. And residents said the price
of food had tripled everywhere because of scarcity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
