<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG12-TV-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG 12 REAPS LUCRATIVE DEAL ON FOX CABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Big 12 Conference agreed yesterday to a lucrative
renegotiation and extension of its contract with Fox Sports Net for
football cable telecasts through the year 2007.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Big 12 and Fox Net agreed to a five-year deal worth
$42.5 million. The new deal calls for the next seven years to be
worth $129.2 million; the revised total rights fees over the
contract's 10-year length will be $156.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this indicates stability,'' said Kansas chancellor
Robert Hemenway, the Big 12's chief executive officer. ``I think
this is a good indicator of the health and the future of the
conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Combined with its contracts with Fox Net and ABC, the Big 12
will earn nearly $32 million per year in television rights fees.
Barry Frank, the conference's television negotiator, said that puts
it on a par with the Big Ten and Southeastern conferences in
television revenue.
</P>
<P>
   However, Frank said that talks with ABC Sports to renegotiate
that deal have broken off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will not be a change in that contract until it
expires,'' Frank said. ``I wouldn't call it ominous. It was simply
a matter of not being able to agree on numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big 12's deal with ABC runs through 2003 and at about $16
million per year. Part of the discussions involved ABC's desire to
have the Big 12's cable rights move from Fox to ESPN, the network's
corporate brother.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, though, because its initial contract was due to expire in
2000, had more urgency in its desire for a new deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fox deal in no way prevents us from going forward, but
there's no real urgency right now,'' ABC Sports spokesman Mark
Mandel said. ``We have a long-term commitment with the Big 12. I
would call this a pause in the normal ebb and flow of
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   In 2003, the Fox Net contract will allow the Big 12 to
renegotiate the Fox deal. Frank said that the ABC contract will end
at the same time is a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to football, the new Fox contract calls for cable
telecasts of 18 women's basketball games in addition to telecasts
of regular-season and championship events in conference Olympic
sports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0475 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WOMEN-1STLD-W     08-27 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WOMEN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBARRASSED, ANGRY, FORGIVING ... WOMEN SPEAK OUT ON CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Deletes phrase after `intern' in 4th graf `who...dress?')  (See also CLINTON-SPEECH) 
(JT) 
 By JANNY SCOTT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is something startling about the vocabulary that women who
have supported President Clinton now use in conversations about
him: phrases like skirt chaser and laughingstock, nouns like idiot
and jerk, adjectives like feckless, sleazy, self-indulgent, gross.
</P>
<P>
   But it is equally striking that so many of the same women want
Clinton to remain in office. They say he has been a friend to
women. Even now, they could imagine voting for him again, if he
were able to run.
</P>
<P>
   In dozens of interviews in which women across the country were
asked how they felt about Clinton in light of the details of his
sexual entanglement with Monica Lewinsky, many struggled to
reconcile the person they had believed he was with the disturbing
details of what they now know he did.
</P>
<P>
   That is, how to reconcile the man who appointed Ruth Bader
Ginsburg to the United States Supreme Court and named the first
female attorney general and secretary of state with the man who was
caught philandering in the White House with an intern.
</P>
<P>
   The reconciliation is not coming easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been surprised by how profoundly this has shaken me,''
said Nell Minow, a shareholder activist and mother of two from
McLean, Va. ``On behalf of the 24-year-old girl that I used to be
and the 46-year-old wife that I am now, I feel very shaken and
betrayed on a personal level.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-stakes soap opera broadcast live from Washington has
touched deep-rooted feelings not only about Clinton but about a set
of issues many women know well _ the marital infidelity of
middle-aged men, the degree of responsibility of younger women, the
appropriate reaction of a wife.
</P>
<P>
   It has become what Ms. Minow called ``one of the rare,
Rorschach-test moments that come along that really define a lot of
inner conflicts'' _ just as the O.J. Simpson case seemed to define
where people stood on race issues and the Anita Hill case did on
sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, women seemed simultaneously to reveal feelings
about politics and marriage, about wayward presidents and husbands:
They were appalled, they were embarrassed, they wished they did not
know; they wanted him to stay, they wanted him out; they were
disappointed: How could he be so stupid?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's gross,'' said Anne Bernays, a 67-year-old
novelist in Cambridge, Mass. ``And sleazy and self-indulgent and
risky, above all risky,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Many had little sympathy for Ms. Lewinsky. They called her a
groupie, silly and star-struck, in way over her head. Others saw
her as a victim. As for Hillary Rodham Clinton, some admired her
outward composure over the past two weeks, while a few wished she
would just get mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have respected Hillary enormously _ up until yesterday,''
said Letty Cottin Pogrebin, an author and a founding editor of Ms.
magazine, the day after the Clinton family departed on vacation,
holding hands. ``It was the hand holding, the `We love each other.'
'' Ms. Pogrebin, 59, said she wished Mrs. Clinton would get angry.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the women interviewed had voted for Clinton in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since his first presidential campaign, women have strongly
supported Clinton. In the 1996 election, the gender gap among
Clinton voters was 11 points. In public opinion polls, women have
consistently given Clinton slightly higher job approval ratings
than have men.
</P>
<P>
   But in a televised address on Aug. 17, he admitted for the first
time that he had had an inappropriate relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky. Testifying in the grand jury investigation of the matter
earlier that day, he acknowledged that they had had ``inappropriate
intimate physical contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, however, is said to have described the
relationship differently in her own grand jury testimony, several
sexual encounters in a private study down a short hallway from the
Oval Office. She is said to have testified that Clinton also
caressed her breasts and genitals.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it was sexual contact between a married president
and a subordinate not much older than his daughter. To many women,
terms like ``romance'' do not quite fit. Some described Clinton's
behavior as sadly pathological; others used terms like ``tawdry''
and ``disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there no greater expression of power?'' asked Catharine
Stimpson, dean of the graduate school of arts and science at New
York University, reflecting on Clinton's arrangement with Ms.
Lewinsky. ``Is that not aristocratic? It's like eating without ever
doing the cooking or the shopping.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many women said they were not surprised. They had suspected as
much since the story first broke. And, as many Americans have said
all along, they said they consider the matter none of their
business and wish it would go away.
</P>
<P>
   Some said sex should not be used to measure morality or
immorality; nor should lying about sex, which they take to be
commonplace. They said they judge their presidents by other
standards, and, by those standards, Clinton had measured up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just kind of tacky behavior,'' said Ms. Bernays. ``Also,
I think it's _ I love this word _ feckless. That he obliged loyal
people like Betty Currie to have to defend themselves and pay
enormous lawyers' bills, just because he can't keep his pants
zipped _ that's feckless.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Bogin Cohen, 61, a volunteer from Boston, said she had
figured all along that Clinton was a man of ``unrestrained
appetites and poor judgment.'' She said she had voted for him
anyway, believing he was better than the alternatives, and that she
could imagine doing so again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of things are gray in life,'' Ms. Cohen said. ``I think
his actions are deplorable and I don't really forgive him and I
think he did damage to the presidency. But I wouldn't not vote for
him if I thought he were the best person for the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were stunned to find themselves so upset. For years, they
had given Clinton the benefit of the doubt. They had done their
best to overlook the unsettling details leaking out over the last
seven months. But finally, the details had become impossible to
ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Minow, who recalled licking envelopes and distributing
flyers for Clinton, said she felt betrayed on behalf of the young
woman in her first job who she once was. Recalling the
vulnerability of that position, she said she was appalled by anyone
who might exploit a woman at that point in her life.
</P>
<P>
   She said she also felt betrayed as a wife whenever any
``middle-aged man opts for the smooth skin and the adoring gaze.''
Finally, as a former Clinton volunteer, she said she felt betrayed
``that he would risk everything I thought we both cared about for
something so stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``I don't know what would upset me more: if he cared
about her or if he didn't. I assume he didn't. This is not the
Wallis Simpson of America. It seems like such a tawdry,
exploitative, stupid relationship. And it's hard to reconcile that
with Mister-I-Feel-Your-Pain.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Ms. Lewinsky, Joan Smith, 50, who owns a hair salon in
Middletown, Conn., dismissed her as an opportunist.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda Daniloff, a 35-year-old university public relations
executive in Cambridge, Mass., said she figured Ms. Lewinsky had
embarked upon the relationship willingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is not a child at all,'' said Susan Becker, a former
costume designer who is now a producer in Los Angeles. ``It's not
like `I had no idea this man was married!' Let's be honest. It
would seem that she had an agenda. So I don't really have any
sympathies in that department.''
</P>
<P>
   To others, it was almost immaterial whether she was a consenting
adult, because she was in a situation in which consent was
complicated by the extreme imbalance of power between the people
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the outset, I thought, `Hey, 21, that's plenty old enough
to consent,''' said Miriam Horn, 40, a writer in Manhattan who is
working a book on Mrs. Clinton's Wellesley College classmates.
``Thinking back to my own 21-year-old-ness, I guess that feeling
has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I think he's completely responsible, almost no
matter what she did,'' she said. ``The gap is so unfathomable
between a 21-year-old intern and a man more than twice her age who
is not only the president but a man of famous charisma. I think his
obligation to exercise restraint is obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   There were similarly split feelings about Mrs. Clinton's
handling of the matter, including the sentiments expressed in a
statement after Clinton's speech, in which a spokeswoman stated
that Mrs. Clinton loved and forgave him, was committed to their
marriage and was relying on her religious faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor Hillary,'' said Ms. Cohen of Boston, thinking back on the
day of Clinton's televised admission. ``I mean, yes, he got her to
the White House. But what a terrible day she had. And even if she
knew it _ and I'm sure she knew it _ she has to eat crow in public
because of this jerk.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pogrebin, who said she has raised money and campaigned for
Clinton since 1991, said she now wants him to resign. ``He has lost
his political usefulness,'' she said. But most of the women
interviewed said they still wanted him as president, despite
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, in this reactionary climate, Clinton passes for something
like a bulwark for certain civil liberties and principles that
women believe in,'' said Ann Douglas, an English professor at
Columbia University. To continue to support him, even now, is
completely defensible, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that means I'm a grown-up,'' said Douglas, who said
she voted for the Green Party candidate in the last presidential
election. ``Politics are interest politics. I have my interests. I
will think twice about demolishing someone who has worked,
comparatively speaking, to protect the things I care about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
