<HEADLINE>
TCU DEFENSIVE END IS A MORE MATURE MENACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By TERRANCE HARRIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU defensive end Aaron Schobel isn't into
how he's perceived.
</P>
<P>
   Which means being first in drills is not his concern. And it is
not uncommon to see the 6-foot-4, 240-pound sophomore sulk and
become irritated with practicing.
</P>
<P>
   These are not consistent characteristics for the Horned Frogs'
most accomplished and punishing player on the defensive front.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think I come off that way just to take the pressure
off of myself,'' Schobel said. ``Sometimes I want people to think
I'm lazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Schobel may have put on too convincing an act for the new
coaching staff when spring practice opened in March. But as the
spring session went on, Schobel began to show flashes of his
redshirt freshman campaign, when he made 69 tackles, including
seven quarterback sacks and a team-best eight stops for negative
(minus-61) yardage.
</P>
<P>
   Schobel often served as a defensive menace during the spring as
first-year coach Dennis Franchione and his assistants attempted to
install the new offense. And it has carried over into fall camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's developed a maturity and understands he must make
a commitment to the game and the preparation for it in order to be
as good as he wants to be,'' TCU defensive line coach Stan Eggen
said. ``What's making him a better football player is he is
starting to understand that just gliding along will not do.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one of Schobel's greatest obstacles has been his
superior athletic ability. Blessed with exceptional quickness and
agility and an understanding of how the game is played, the former
Columbus High School standout has always seemed to shine without
much effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaron is just a football player, and that's the highest
compliment to give somebody,'' Franchione said. ``He knows how to
play the game, and he's got great instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably relies on his instincts maybe too much, but they
are good to him, and he can get by on them sometimes. The Lord has
given him something to play the game with that not everybody has.''
</P>
<P>
   Understanding that more would be required of him, Schobel made a
commitment during the off-season strength and conditioning program.
He has returned stronger, perhaps in the best condition of his
life, for his second season as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, I was satisfied with what I was able to
accomplish last season,'' said Schobel, whose brother Matt, a
quarterback, transferred to TCU this summer from Texas A&AMP;M. ``But
if I were to have a similar season this year, then I would
definitely be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it has been important for me to work hard and to
push myself even when maybe I'm not into it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Eggen stops short of deeming Schobel the primary
play-maker up front this season, he does recognize the
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he continues to improve as he has this fall, then I believe
he is certainly a person that opposing teams need to be concerned
with,'' Eggen said. ``But a lot is going to depend on Aaron.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2154EDT &QL; 
