<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-CAPETOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 SUSPECTS HELD IN CAPE TOWN BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa _ Police investigating Tuesday's bombing
of a Planet Hollywood restaurant here stopped an Air Egypt plane on
the tarmac as it was to take off for Cairo on Thursday and detained
three people, a police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman was careful to say that the three _ a man and two
women _ were ``not our No. 1 suspects or anything'' and that they
were not charged but were simply being questioned.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing is being investigated by the FBI for any link to the
bombings earlier this month of the U.S. Embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania, attacks the United States has accused a Saudi exile,
Osama bin Laden, of backing.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives here received an anonymous tip saying that the three,
all South African Muslims, were involved in the Plant Hollywood
bombing, which killed one person and wounded 26, said the police
spokesman, Senior Superintendent John Sterrenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Police went to the airport, found what he called ``discrepancies
in their travel documents,'' removed the trio from the plane and
detained them, initially under the Aliens Control Act.
Fingerprints, tests for traces of gunpowder and other forensics may
follow, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for People Against Gangsterism and Drugs, an
anti-crime group led by conservative Muslim clerics, reacted
angrily to the arrests, saying the man held was a member of the
group and on a pilgrimage to Mecca with his wife and a family
friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disgusted with the unfair manner in which he's been
treated,'' the group's spokeswoman, Abeeda Roberts, said. ``What
about his privacy? What about the safety of his family?''
</P>
<P>
   She was particularly upset, she said, that the national
television network had shown the three suspects' faces and used
their names. Her organization and the police have refused to
release the names.
</P>
<P>
   A legal adviser to anti-crime group, Cassiem Parker, accused
police of ``singling out Muslims leaving the country'' in order to
announce that they had solved the crime quickly. He said police
would not tell him where the three were being held and were
questioning them without lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Police and prominent Muslims repeatedly mention the Oklahoma
City bombing, which was initially assumed to be the work of Islamic
terrorists but turned out to be carried out by far-right Americans.
Police here say they do not want to be similarly embarrassed, and
are scrupulously avoiding saying whom they suspect in the Planet
Hollywood attack.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Parker accused the South African police of
incompetence and of ``adding to Islamophobia.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roberts insisted that FBI agents have been torturing members
of her anti-crime group in South African jails in an effort to
obtain information about the embassy bombings. No U.S. official was
available Thursday night for comment on the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Something like ``Islamophobia'' is clearly at work in the Cape
Town area, where as many as 400,000 Muslims live. Muslim callers to
radio stations have described being hounded off buses by hostile
remarks and fearing that their children will be beaten up at
school. And Muslims of all political stripes fear being branded in
the public eye as terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday morning, a local paper, quoting anonymous
sources, initially reported that security cameras inside the
restaurant had taped a prime suspect, a ``Morrocan-looking man who
was from Zimbabwe but now lives in the Cape area.'' It was never
explained how the cameras picked up the man's life history.
</P>
<P>
   Later, police issued a statement seeking to quash the story,
saying security cameras had shown a person ``behaving in a highly
suspicious manner'' but that restaurant employees who saw the tape
later said it was more than a month old.
</P>
<P>
   There are more tapes, a police spokesman said, but it is not
known whether the Planet Hollywood cameras were taping on the night
of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, Parliament held a debate over the bombing.
The National Party, which ruled during the apartheid era, and the
Freedom Front, which represents conservative Afrikaners, accused
the government of being soft on crime and called for the return of
the death penalty. The government's minister for safety and
security replied that ``responding in panic or irresponsibility
will be playing into the hands of the terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, FBI bomb experts looked over the site of the
explosion with their South African counterparts but declined to
speak to reporters. In the afternoon, Mandela paid a brief surprise
visit.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims Against Global Oppression, a group originally blamed for
the blast by an anonymous caller, held a news conference Thursday
to denounce the bombing as a cowardly act and convey its
condolences to the wounded. The group's leaders said the bombing
and phone call were probably an attempt to malign them or to spread
religious tension.
</P>
<P>
   They also said they would still hold a march on the U.S.
Consulate in Cape Town on Saturday that they had announced a day
before the restaurant blast. They handed out leaflets bearing the
headline ``Death to America'' that described the U.S.
cruise-missile attacks on the Sudan and Afghanistan as acts of
terrorism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
