<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NOMADIC KELLY LEAVES HAPPY TRAIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Left-hander Greg Cadaret, the Rangers' most
recent acquisition, sauntered through the clubhouse upon his
arrival at The Ballpark in Arlington on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cadaret, who that afternoon joined his eighth major-league
organization since first appearing with the 1987 Oakland Athletics,
recognized another well-traveled face from across the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always around,'' teased the Panamanian with the
baritone voice and his right hand extended. ``Are you following
me?''
</P>
<P>
   The rich, deep voice belonged to Roberto Kelly, a 33-year-old
reserve outfielder whose awareness for three-digit sequences
extends beyond his recognition of a batting average.
</P>
<P>
   It encompasses area codes.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's travelogue includes stops in eight area codes over the
past seven seasons despite a career batting average of .290 and a
productive .323 this season for the Rangers and manager Johnny
Oates.
</P>
<P>
   Explain that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good question,'' Kelly responded. ``I wish I had an
answer for it.''
</P>
<P>
   No one does.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin compared Kelly's movement to that of
third baseman Todd Zeile, whom the Rangers acquired July 31 from
the Florida Marlins for two minor-league players.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not bad guys,'' Melvin said. ``Clubs want them more
than they don't want them. They're desirable players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Mariners, Kelly's employers the previous season,
wished for his return after the outfielder hit .298 during
September and .308 during their best-of-five, divisional playoff
series against the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing but positive things to say about the guy,''
said Mariners manager Lou Piniella, who dismissed the notion
Kelly's travels suggest a clubhouse problem. ``He played well for
us. It was a matter of economics. We wanted to sign him, but his
agent was asking for more than we could afford.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella told Oates a similar story, as did the Minnesota Twins'
Tom Kelly, another of the outfielder's previous managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lou told me that they did not want to get rid of him. They
liked him. That's all he had to say,'' Oates recalled. ``I went to
Tom Kelly, and he said the same thing. That got me excited.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that the Atlanta Braves also desired Kelly,
but Melvin signed the outfielder to a two-year contract in December
worth a guaranteed $3.85 million. It proved to be Melvin's
successful attempt in strengthening the Rangers' bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never looked at it as a team getting rid of me,'' said
Kelly, who enters today's doubleheader against the Chicago White
Sox with 12 home runs and 34 runs batted in despite only 201
at-bats. ``I've always looked at it as another team wanting me.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of area codes demonstrate that.
</P>
<P>
   718: American League All-Star for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   513: National League All-Star for the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   404: Acquired by the Braves from the Reds for a 1994 pennant
race that never materialized because of a players' strike.
</P>
<P>
   514: Traded by the Braves (with outfielder Tony Tarasco and
pitcher Esteban Yan) to the Expos for center fielder Marquis
Grissom, one of three All-Star outfielders _ the others being Paul
O'Neill and Henry Rodriguez _ involved in trades for Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   213: Hit .364 (4-for-11) for the Dodgers during their 1995
best-of-five, divisional playoff series against the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   612: Hit an American League-best .406 against left-handers for
the Twins in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   206: Hit .298 during September and .308 during the Mariners'
1997 best-of-five, divisional playoff series against the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Kelly calls the 817 area code home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when I came here that I was going to be the fourth
outfielder,'' he said. ``I'm happy I've been able to fulfill that
role. You know what? We could (complain) and moan about not
playing, but where would that get us?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not 22 years old anymore, so I wanted to go to a team that
had a chance to play in the postseason. I'm happy to be here, and
I'm satisfied with the job I'm doing. I don't know how much longer
I'll be doing this. I've been to the playoffs. I want to go to the
World Series and win it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
