<HEADLINE>
RICKY II THE ONE FOR TEXAS TECH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The other Ricky Williams is quietly making a name for himself.
</P>
<P>
   And if for the moment he is but an afterthought to a college
football public more familiar with the Heisman Trophy candidate of
the same name at the University of Texas, so be it. This, says the
Texas Tech sophomore tailback from Duncanville, is far from being a
personal problem.
</P>
<P>
   The comparison ``is going to happen, but it's a great situation
for me,'' said Williams, who last season broke the school's
freshman rushing record set by Red Raiders career leader Byron
Hanspard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky Williams at Texas is a great running back who is going
to get the publicity because of the success he's had. I keep
telling myself that my time will come and I have to step up, then
I'll get the same kind of publicity. I've worked hard. I'm
confident. It's just a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams emerged from a pack of tailback candidates a year ago
to start the season opener against Tennessee, replacing Hanspard,
who left a year early for the NFL. By season's end, Williams had
rushed for 894 yards on 201 carries (4.4-yard average). Included
was a season-high, 179-yard performance against Kansas and a
131-yard game against the Longhorns, in which the more famous Ricky
Williams was held to 80 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Tech's Williams also caught 10 passes for 130 yards and averaged
19.3 yards on 11 kickoff returns while making the Big 12
commissioner's academic honor roll for the fall semester.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky did way better early than we thought he would,'' coach
Spike Dykes admitted. ``He came from a really good high school
program, and he had the skills and a work ethic that a lot of guys
don't have at that age. But I still thought that because of his
(lack of) size, it would take him a while. He started out as the
No. 6 tailback. Then we play Tennessee, and he's in the starting
lineup. ''
</P>
<P>
   Williams says he has grown an inch and a half to 5-foot-9. He
has gained 14 pounds to 192, yet can still run the 40 in the
4.4-second range. Bigger, stronger and more confident, Williams is
now counted on as a leader of a rebuilt Tech offense that features
new faces at quarterback, center and both guards. Yet that unit may
still be a strength of a team that enters next week's opening game
against UT-El Paso thinking of reaching a major bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main goal right now is to try and beat UTEP,'' Williams
said cautiously, then warming to the subject. ``But we want to
really put in a big effort to get a roll going in our first five
games (UTEP, North Texas, Fresno State, Iowa State, Baylor) and
then see what happens from there.''
</P>
<P>
   His impressive rookie season hasn't taken the edge off Williams'
drive, said veteran Tech running backs coach Jack Tayrien.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky is one of those kids who has a lot of football savvy,
but he busts his tail working hard,'' Tayrien said. ``He's not very
big, but he's durable. He was definitely a surprise last year, but
(he) just came in and from the start didn't make many mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has tremendous quickness and great vision. He's as good as
anybody I've ever coached at picking up blitzes (on pass
protection). And when he's not carrying the ball, he does a great
job faking, which is very important because he's the focus of our
play-action passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dykes has seen the other side of Williams' potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky runs with a great deal of thrust,'' Dykes said, ``but
changing direction has never been his long suit. The other day in
practice, though, I saw him make a cut he couldn't have even
thought about making a year ago. He's starting to get pretty good
at that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Williams is far from satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last season wasn't bad,'' he said. ``But looking back, I can
see where I need to improve at a lot of things. I want to gain more
yards, score more touchdowns. I want to try and make everything
perfect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
