<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATION OVER, BUT WHAT'S UP WITH MAVS' USSERY?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Excuse my confusion, but ...
</P>
<P>
   Since the Mavericks, as an organization, are unable to market
basketball success, they have done a good job of bringing a focus
to the next best thing:
</P>
<P>
   attempting to sell family entertainment instead of W's.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, why is Terdema Ussery still holding a job? And his
job starts right at the top of the organization. President and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   The story broke six weeks ago that the Mavericks had conducted
an in-house investigation of Ussery involving multiple counts of
sexual misconduct within the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Mavericks attorney Tom Luce, upon request, issued a
statement, saying, ``the matter has been completed. The
organization has addressed the situation. Terdema Ussery is
president of the team, and will continue his efforts to build a
championship organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, Ussery may be innocent, and can be assumed as such
until proved otherwise. But the stonewalling of this situation,
starting with owner Ross Perot Jr., had led to an assumption of
guilt, at least to some degree.
</P>
<P>
   If guilty, Ussery should have been fired by Perot.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, if Ussery has been found innocent, then where
is the public announcement? This man's reputation has been
seriously damaged, and he has also been left dangling.
</P>
<P>
   Until yesterday, the only answer in six weeks, came from Luce.
Then everyone went silent.
</P>
<P>
   Did Junior assume we all just forgot? Or that this dirt could be
swept under Roy Tarpley's old locker?
</P>
<P>
   Perot is admittedly naive about the business end of professional
sports, but he's certainly not that clueless.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, even the Cowboys' organization was using the Ussery case
while trying to media-manage that neck-slashing in the
training-camp dorm room.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous front-office voices for the Cowboys offered an
admittedly valid opinion that the media weren't hammering the
Mavericks over the Ussery in-house investigation. So why then, they
asked, couldn't the Cowboys ``no comment'' their way through
Neckgate on the premise it was being handled ``internally''?
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the Cowboys later received support from both
Judge Manny Alvarez and the NFL league office that there was no
criminal intent with the incident or hush money payoff involved.
</P>
<P>
   Each of us can decide independently if that's believable, but
you did notice, I'm sure, how the incident suddenly faded from the
media's cross hairs.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason the Ussery case has become media dormant is due
to the NBA's lockout and lockdown on news. Nothing about the NBA is
newsworthy at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Once, however, the lockout ends, and a new NBA season
approaches, the sexual misconduct investigation involving Ussery
will surface again, and again, and ...
</P>
<P>
   So was he cleared of the charges, or what?
</P>
<P>
   Ussery, surely, has that answer by now. But he was not saying
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team has addressed it, and I will not elaborate beyond
that,'' Ussery said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Luce is telling us it's business as usual at 777 Sports
St. But there has still been no answer on Ussery's guilt or
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Ussery may be forced to play the corporate game, meaning silence
unless instructed by lawyers to speak. But when your professional
reputation goes on the line, don't you have to publicly defend
yourself, regardless? Provided, of course, there is innocence.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest disappointment, however, centers on Perot, who most
of us in the local media have regarded as a man of honor. But at
the moment, Junior comes across as weak and wobbly. Is Perot
allowing a guilty man to continue to be the boss of his basketball
workplace, or is he allowing the innocent to dangle in a helpless
state?
</P>
<P>
   Then again, could Perot be preparing to sell the Mavericks,
therefore making the decision on Ussery the problem of the next
owner?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hicks still has plenty of stall space in his sports
franchise barn. Hicks would be more than happy to move the
Mavericks in with the Rangers and Stars. The more the better for
Hicks, at least from a sports TV network standpoint, which is Hicks
ultimate goal.
</P>
<P>
   And knowing Don Carter, there is no way he could be pleased
about even a hint of a team executive being involved in a sexual
misconduct scandal. Particularly one involving ``multiple'' team
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Would Carter buy back the Mavericks? Yes. Like right now.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks haven't had basketball appeal in a long while. But
now there's also decay upstairs. If Ussery is innocent, tell us.
Otherwise, Junior Perot should begin the housecleaning by removing
himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
