<SLUG> BC-DEMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Close but not too close to Clinton
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, WASH. _ House Democratic leader Richard Gephardt said
Thursday he still intends to appear with President Clinton at a
series of Democrat fund-raisers this fall, despite his recent
criticism of Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing Clinton's role as the Democrats' money-raiser,
Gephardt said he and Clinton will be at events in New York, Boston,
Los Angeles and St. Louis, Gephardt's hometown, in September and
October.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats hope to raise $18 million for the November elections,
of which $6 million would go to candidates for the House. ``That's
what we think we need to be competitive,'' Gephardt said during a
day of campaign stops with candidates in Oregon and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said he has yet to talk to Clinton since Gephardt
returned from a family vacation in France this week. Earlier in the
week, he said Clinton's conduct was ``reprehensible'' and he could
not rule out the possibility of impeachment if the facts warrant
such action.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's comments were widely interpreted as a signal to House
Democrats and Democratic candidates that they need not defend
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats need to gain 11 seats in the House to regain the
majority they lost in 1994. If that happens, Gephardt almost
certainly would replace Newt Gingrich as speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Democrat walked a fine line Thursday at events in
Portland, Vancouver, Olympia and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He took pains to dispel the notion that he is distancing himself
from the president, even as candidate after candidate said they
were not anxious for Clinton to campaign for them.
</P>
<P>
   In Portland, for example, Democrat David Wu said he is ``very,
very happy'' with the lineup of Democrats who are scheduled to
visit Oregon, a list that does not include Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said he needs to assure the public that Democrats will
deal objectively with the report independent counsel Kenneth Starr
is expected to send to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider this some effort to do anything other than be
straightforward, honest and realistic about where we are, what
needs to be done and how I hope this would proceed,'' Gephardt
said. ``If this is a partisan street fight, then we've let the
American people down.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gephardt, essentially agreeing with comments Gingrich made
this week, said it was extremely unlikely that Congress would hold
hearings before the elections. ``I don't even know that there's
going to be a report'' before then, Gephardt said. ``I hope there
isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
