<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flood's aftermath
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi and Ralph Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For the moment, Del Rio's heartbreak is getting
state and national attention. But perhaps the cruelest aspect of a
disaster is that the aftermath has such a long shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   Aftermath will be a constant companion to the residents of the
Val Verde County seat long after the television crews and reporters
are gone. What will be left is the drudgery of cleaning up, and
picking up the pieces of daily life in the aftermath of a flood
that left 17 dead on both sides of the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government can offer loans and grants to repair and
replace homes lost. Those left homeless will find temporary
shelter. But where do you go to replace the love and counsel of
those who drowned? There will be no lines to recover the very
personal treasures like photo albums lost to the flood.
</P>
<P>
   The psychic and spiritual loss may not be fully felt until
later. Right now, the focus is on cleaning up the damage done to
the city of 34,000.
</P>
<P>
   It is an awesome physical task to rebuild and recover after a
disaster. Electricity, telephone and gas service have been
restored. And people are slowly being allowed back into the San
Felipe barrio to deal with the aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   There were 250 homes destroyed and another 300 damaged citywide,
according to Marta Sepeda, an assistant city attorney in Del Rio.
Water service has been restored, she said, but the water isn't yet
drinkable. Potable water is still a need.
</P>
<P>
   Those left homeless and with no other place to go remain at the
Del Rio Civic Center. There is a need for volunteers there, Sepeda
said. Eventually, there will be a need for dump trucks, cranes and
building materials.
</P>
<P>
   The City of Del Rio is getting help from neighboring counties
which are lending trucks and personnel. Law enforcement officers
from surrounding counties and towns are there to help keep order
and relieve Del Rio officers. The City of Austin sent firefighters,
a medic and an emergency room physician to lend assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Those assistance efforts are commendable, an example that people
have the heart and willingness to help a neighbor in distress.
</P>
<P>
   Central Texans know all too well what misery a flood can bring.
</P>
<P>
   How to help
</P>
<P>
   To make donations of cash to help victims of flooding call:
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross of Central Texas: 928-4271
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio Chapter of the American Red Cross: (210)
224-5151. Donations can also be sent to 3642 E. Houston, San
Antonio, 78219.
</P>
<P>
   To make donations of food or clothing call:
</P>
<P>
   The Salvation Army: 416-0607. The Salvation Army can pick up
donations, or they can be dropped off at the Salvation Army at 4216
S. Congress Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
