<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0488 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6396 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-NCAROLINA-COX     08-27 1511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-NCAROLINA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Classic race heats up in Tarheel State
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, N.C. -- Appearing at a fund-raiser here for Sen.
Lauch Faircloth (R-N.C.), fellow Republican Sen. Strom Thurmond of
South Carolina set aside his plate of east Carolina barbecue and
cut straight to the punch lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now why won't sharks attack trial lawyers?'' Thurmond demanded
in an unsteady voice. ``Professional courtesy.'' The crowd in the
banquet room at the Best Western hooted.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many trial lawyers does it take to change a light bulb?''
he continued. ``Three. One to change the bulb and two to sue him
for malpractice.'' Keith Whited, a local lawyer, winced. ``That
hurt,'' Whited said under his breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you hear about the trial lawyer that was hurt in an
accident?'' Thurmond pressed on to the crowd's delight. ``An
ambulance backed up suddenly.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the 1998 North Carolina Senate campaign, featuring
perhaps the Senate's most vulnerable incumbent, most talked-about
challenger and plenty of third-rate lawyer jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The point of Thurmond's digs was not lost on the white,
middle-aged crowd in this heavily Republican area of the Tarheel
State. Faircloth's opponent in the Senate campaign is John Edwards,
a 45-year-old trial lawyer who has already spent $3.5 million to
win the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Raleigh attorney is everything Faircloth, a wealthy hog
farmer who turned 70 this year, is not: youthful, telegenic and
charismatic. The combination has already made Edwards the darling
of the Washington media buzz circuit, which loves to anoint and
promote upstart challengers in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also are enjoying a renaissance in North Carolina. In
1996, the party reclaimed two House seats after losing four in
1994, evening the House delegation to six Democrats and six
Republicans, and re-elected a popular Democratic governor, Jim Hunt
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   But Edwards, who has never held political office, still faces an
uphill battle. He is running as a Washington outsider in a year
when voters elsewhere seem to be putting more value on experience.
And Edwards faces an incumbent, who despite his plain-spoken,
parochial manner, is a savvy tactician with deep roots in North
Carolina politics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Faircloth beat the late Sen. Terry Sanford, a
much-loved former North Carolina governor and president of Duke
University, against long odds just a year after he switched parties
and remade himself from a conservative Democrat into a conservative
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Image is everything
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Faircloth has been remaking his image once
again, this time to appeal to the tens of thousands of new, mostly
moderate Republicans who have moved to take jobs in Charlotte and
North Carolina's booming Research Triangle, a high-tech center
located around Raleigh, Durham and Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Senate Banking Committee, Faircloth made
headlines attacking first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's financial
dealings in the Whitewater controversy, winning points with
conservatives but losing them among many women voters.
</P>
<P>
   Faircloth is happy to talk about the Clintons now _ off the
record. In public, he is smoothing his image among women voters by
highlighting his support of legislation that created a new, 40-cent
stamp that generates money for breast cancer research. Faircloth
signed as a co-sponsor of the bill, sponsored by Sen. Dianne
Feinstein (D-Calif.), last year.
</P>
<P>
   Faircloth also now is supporting a bipartisan health care
proposal to regulate health maintenance organizations after
opposing efforts to regulate health care in his first term.
</P>
<P>
   In his first term, Faircloth backed legislation to sharply
curtail the federal Clean Water Act, pushing changes that would
have exempted half the nation's wetlands from federal protections.
Now, he is promoting his opposition to oil drilling off North
Carolina's coast.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Faircloth, who ranks among the most conservative
Republicans in the Senate, is looking more like a Democrat, says
Thad Beyle, a political scientist at the University of North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Republicans are doing this,'' says Beyle. ``As they
get closer to the election, they suddenly have to be viewed as
Democrats and move away from more of their knee-jerk ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   Faircloth shrinks at the suggestion he's swung left to help his
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always been a conservative, but certainly not to the
extent that I'm not very much aware of the fact that we have to
keep an open mind for advancements and opportunity,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As for the closeness of the race _ the most recent polls put
Faircloth 9 points ahead of Edwards _ Faircloth notes that
``anybody who is the Democratic nominee, Saddam Hussein, will get
40 percent of the vote.''
</P>
<P>
   `Up for grabs'
</P>
<P>
   Much like neighboring Georgia, North Carolina has become a
toss-up state for Republicans and Democrats, largely because of the
roughly 20 percent of the electorate who label themselves
independents.
</P>
<P>
   These voters tend to vote Republican, but don't necessarily
share the conservative ideology of Sen. Jesse Helms (R-N.C.), the
state's archconservative, says Ferrel Guillory at UNC's Center for
the Study of the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are in some ways up for grabs,'' says Guillory. ``They
may bring their Republicanism with them, but they don't know Lauch
Faircloth ... It's an interesting and dicey electorate for both
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Faircloth's Senate seat hasn't been held by an incumbent since
1968.
</P>
<P>
   Faircloth, however, isn't ignoring his conservative base. In
what appears to be a pitch to white conservatives, the Republican
Senate campaign committee ran nearly $400,000 of ``issue ads''
touting Faircloth's role in stripping Washington Mayor Marion Barry
of his control over city finances.
</P>
<P>
   That record sits well with older voters such as Charles Hampton.
``He has the same philosophy we have,'' said Hampton, who attended
Faircloth's fund-raiser here. ``I like what he tried to do in the
district, make it more efficient instead of wasting money.''
</P>
<P>
   At his Burlington fund-raiser, Faircloth pledged never to raise
taxes and vowed to vote to override President Clinton's veto of
legislation banning certain late-term abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Coalition literature distributed at the event gave
Faircloth a 92 percent voting record. The score matched Faircloth
against a zero for Sen. Edward M. Kennedy (D-Mass.), a lightning
rod for Southern conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a classic race between and a conservative, a working
man, a businessman, a man who has spent his life in business, and a
liberal, a man who announced that he was going to be a warrior for
unions and personal injury attorneys,'' Faircloth told the crowd of
200.
</P>
<P>
   Populist themes, lawyerly scenes
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, meanwhile, appears to have succeeded in energizing
Democratic voters around his populist campaign themes of more
federal support for education, enacting a patients bill of rights
and devoting budget surpluses to repay the Social Security trust
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Spending heavily on television, Edwards captured the Democratic
nomination against two rivals without a runoff _ even after
Faircloth called Edwards ``North Carolina's No. 1 personal injury
lawyer'' in an attack ad. ``He makes millions suing people,'' the
ad said.
</P>
<P>
   The mill worker's son from Robbins, N.C., is spending a lot of
his time putting a positive face on his vocation. Edwards tells
voters that he will be the ``fiercest, most passionate advocate''
they will have in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He has also refused to take any special interest money from
political action committees, another attempt to blunt attacks that
he is just another wealthy trial attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards most celebrated case was a claim he successfully pursued
on behalf of a young girl whose insides were sucked out by a faulty
swimming pool drain. He frequently compares voters to jurors and
delivers his stump speech in much the same way he would address the
jury box in one of his cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he's going to fight for the regular people on the
street,'' says Joe Adams, an Asheville attorney who attended a
rally for the candidate in western North Carolina. ``He's just not
bought and paid for before he gets there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, Edwards has proposed that he and
Faircloth pool their campaign money to purchase prime time
television and debate one another on the issues, forgoing
television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Faircloth dismisses the proposal as a ``political ploy'' and a
``meaningless gesture,'' but Edwards says voters are tired of
politics as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of it is very simple, to at least move down the road
to replacing 30-second sound bites and negative attack ads with a
substantive, real discussion,'' Edwards says. ``What I'm saying is
let's step out and try to make North Carolina a shining example of
what it can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
