<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6397 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTH-SENATE-COX     08-27 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-SENATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate contests in South to produce heavy ad campaigns
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ With Labor Day and the unofficial beginning of the
fall campaigns just around the corner, U.S. Senate candidates from
around the South are preparing to unleash millions of dollars in
television advertising to grab voters' attention.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Michael Coles' challenge to Republican incumbent
Paul Coverdell in Georgia, the South will feature some of the
hottest races in the country. Democrats are trying to recoup ground
lost during the last three election cycles, while Republicans want
to fatten their dominance in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans now control the Senate 55 to 45, but the majority is
less imposing than it might seem. Under Senate rules, 60 votes are
required to end debate and vote on bills, meaning an organized
minority can tie the chamber up in knots.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.), who is leading the GOP Senate
election effort, wants to put his party closer to the magic
filibuster-proof number of 60.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to have an excellent year,'' says McConnell, who
nonetheless doubts that Republicans can pick up five seats.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey (D-Neb.), who is leading the Democrat's effort,
says the party's agenda of putting more teachers in the classroom
will make Democrats competitive in the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will have a clear alternative to what Republicans
are offering,'' Kerrey says.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a preview:
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas: Democrats lost a Senate seat in President Clinton's
home state in 1996, but this year have nominated a strong candidate
to succeed Sen. Dale Bumpers (D-Ark.).
</P>
<P>
   Blanche Lambert-Lincoln, a former congresswoman from the
Razorback State, is leading her GOP opponent by 20 points in the
most recent polls. Lincoln left Congress in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican candidate is state senator Fay Boozman, who is
less well known to voters. Most problematic for Boozman is that
voter surveys indicate that only 7 percent of the electorate is
undecided about the two candidates, leaving the Republican little
ground to pick up.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky: McConnell's home state features the other open Senate
contest in the South. Sen. Wendell Ford (D-Ky.) is retiring, and
two congressmen with established names are vying to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Scotty Baesler, a former University of Kentucky basketball
star, won the Democratic nomination in a hard-fought campaign
against a wealthy businessman and the state's lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Baesler faces Rep. Jim Bunning, a former major league pitcher
who was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts rate the race a toss-up, but Bunning faced a much less
rigorous primary fight and has more money to spend in the general
election. In a signal of how important the contest is to McConnell,
the Kentucky Republican recently sent his Washington chief of
staff, Kyle Simmons, down to Kentucky to join the Bunning campaign.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina: Sen. Fritz Hollings (D-S.C.) has stayed a
Democrat since he was first elected to the Senate in 1966. In the
intervening years, however, the voters in South Carolina have
switched to the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Hollings won re-election in 1992 with 51 percent of the vote and
this year faces Rep. Bob Inglis, who has the strong backing of both
the state and national Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina: The Democrats' best hope of knocking off an
incumbent may be in the Tarheel State, where conservative Sen.
Lauch Faircloth (R-N.C.) faces a wealthy trial lawyer from Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   John Edwards posted a strong showing in the primary, beating two
challengers without a runoff. He is accepting no political action
committee money and has invested more than $3 million of his own
money in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama: Sen. Richard Shelby (R-Ala.), who switched to the
Republican Party in 1994, runs as a Republican for the first time
this year. There isn't much of a contest.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats nominated Clayton Suddith, a retired ironworker who
has raised virtually no money in his bid to unseat Shelby. Shelby
has nearly $5.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana: The Democrats' bye this election cycle goes to Sen.
John Breaux (D-La.), a popular incumbent who has the support of
many of the state's Republicans. State Rep. Jim Donelon, the
Republican nominee, has been struggling to raise the money to put
his face before voters.Florida: Sen. Bob Graham (D-Fla.), a former
Florida governor, is also enjoying leads in the polls over state
Sen. Charlie Crist, the likely Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Republicans, however, appear poised to elect Jeb Bush,
former President Bush's son, the next governor of Florida. Crist
could benefit from a good Republican showing but still faces long
odds against the popular Graham.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks to come, we will preview some of the more
contentious Southern contests, beginning today with the
Faircloth-Edwards race in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
