<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6402 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERRORISM-PENTAGON-SP     08-27 1528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORISM-PENTAGON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMANDO UNITS TRAINED TO SEIZE OR DESTROY TERRORIST WEAPONS  
 (WITH TERRORISM-PENTAGON-UNITS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bracing for a protracted struggle with international terrorists,
the Pentagon is prepared to mount commando strikes against terror
groups or rogue nations that threaten to use weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Units of the multi-service U.S. Special Operations Command are
engaged in intensive practice missions to seize nuclear weapons,
and to destroy chemical or biological factories and storage sites.
The commandos would be used when conventional military firepower,
such as the cruise missiles used in last week's U.S. strikes in
Afghanistan and Sudan, would be ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   The 47,000-man U.S. Special Operations Command, headquartered at
MacDill Air Force Base, Fla., took on the new mission three years
ago, said retired Gen. Wayne Downing, who commanded the force
during 1994-96.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been running scenarios for `loose nukes' for the last 10
years,'' Downing said in an interview. But in 1995, the command
received a major infusion of additional funds for new equipment and
training for ``direct action'' operations to find, neutralize and
retrieve nuclear weapons in ``hardened'' or underground sites that
missiles or bombs couldn't damage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years a number of rogue states _ particularly North
Korea and Libya _ have built hardened underground nuclear and
chemical weapons factories. These sites are either tunnelled under
mountains or buried so deep that they are likely impervious to
aircraft or missile attack, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Downing and other U.S. experts say the underground sites reflect
the foreign regimes' reaction to the air campaign against Iraq in
the 1991 Persian Gulf War. ``All of our adversaries saw what our
(precision-guided munitions) could do so they put them
underground,'' Downing said.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post reported last week North Korea is digging a
massive underground facility 25 miles northwest of its existing
nuclear plant at Yongbyon that may be a new nuclear weapon
fabrication plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are looking at a whole range of deeply buried
facilities,'' said Dan Goure at the nonprofit Center for Strategic
and International Studies in Washington, D.C. ``Many of them are
built under mountains ... where stuff goes on may be thousands of
meters under rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Goure said parts of the Yongbyon nuclear complex are deemed
impervious to air strikes, even from a tactical nuclear weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very tough targets,'' Downing agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. John Shalikashvili, who was chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff during 1993-97, said preparing to use ``human
sources'' to take out nuclear or chemical weapons ``before they are
used against us'' is a top Pentagon priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is (the special operations force community) putting an
emphasis on developing the training and techniques to do that? The
answer is yes,'' Shalikashvili said. ``Is that a very high
priority? The answer is yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Special Operations Command spokesman George Grimes confirmed
that counterproliferation, including the recovery of nuclear
weapons, is the command's ``No. 1 priority mission.'' Grimes said
most details are classified, including which units are involved.
</P>
<P>
   Some details on the role of special operations units are found
in unclassified Pentagon reports to Congress on
counterproliferation, or using the military to thwart the spread of
nuclear, chemical or biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   A May 1, 1998, report cites the U.S. Special Operations Command
mission to include ``supporting, training and equipping (Defense
Department) teams to detect, neutralize and `render safe' ...
weapons and devices in permissive and nonpermissive environments
both in the United States and overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Special Operations Command, a subordinate unit of the
U.S. Special Operations Command, is a highly classified operation
headquartered at Fort Bragg, N.C. It controls two elite commando
units, the Army's Special Forces Operational Detachment-Delta,
known as Delta Force, and the Naval Special Warfare Development
Group, which replaced the Navy's Seal Team 6 as the maritime
counterterrorist force.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Pentagon nor military services officially
acknowledge the existence of Delta or the Navy group. The Army
describes the Joint Special Operations Command only as ``a joint
headquarters designed to study special operations requirements and
techniques; ensure interoperability and equipment standardization;
plan and conduct special operations exercises and training; and
develop joint special operations tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Maj. Gen. Douglas Brown, who took over as head of the
Special Operations Command earlier this month, and his predecessor,
Maj. Gen. Michael Canavan, declined requests for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Outside sources estimate the ``black,'' or covert, element of
the Special Operations Command consists of fewer than 1,500
hand-picked personnel, including 800 members of Delta Force,
another 200 in the Naval Special Warfare Development Group, and
several hundred support specialists.
</P>
<P>
   A small group of personnel within each commando organization has
the responsibility to operate classified portable detection
equipment to locate and identify weapons, and to neutralize nuclear
devices so they can be retrieved from the target area, one
ex-commando said, speaking on condition his name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   Downing said many aspects of a counterproliferation mission are
identical to skills the special operations forces have honed for
decades, including covert insertion into a hostile area, secure
communications, long-range reconnaissance and close-quarters
combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a planning standpoint we never looked at
counterproliferation as anything different from our tactics,''
agreed the former commando. ``It's just a different form of
training.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense officials are tight-lipped about the commando planning,
citing the need to prevent potential adversaries from learning
about U.S. military capability. But some details have emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Canavan, commander of the Joint Special Operations Command
during 1997-98, revealed training details in a rare interview last
summer to the trade magazine Armed Forces Journal International.
</P>
<P>
   One such practice mission, involving members of Delta Force,
took place at an underground tunnel complex in Nevada operated by
the Energy Department for nuclear weapons tests.
</P>
<P>
   The commandos blasted their way through armored doors and
navigated a maze of tunnels thousands of feet long while wearing
sealed protective garments and using closed breathing systems.
</P>
<P>
   Their orders were to locate and fight their way into a guarded
underground facility to seize one or more nuclear weapons before
they could be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the commandos were armed with assault rifles tailored
for close-quarters combat shooting and night-vision goggles.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers carried special communications equipment that could
function in the labyrinth of tunnels, and special high-intensity
flares to illuminate their way through the facility.
</P>
<P>
   A smaller number carried portable sensing devices to locate and
identify the radioactive trace emanations from nuclear warhead
material, and highly classified equipment that would enable them to
immobilize _ ``render safe'' _ the weapons so they could be hauled
away.
</P>
<P>
   Canavan described Delta's performance as improving but still
short of the capability Pentagon planners want.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're as good as our equipment,'' Canavan said. ``I
think we have about a 60 percent solution out there ... our biggest
challenge is getting into these deep underground shelters.''
</P>
<P>
   Canavan said the greatest challenge facing commandos attacking
an underground target are ``breathing, seeing, communicating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go out to the National Test Site ... where we train,
the tunnels are 3,000 meters long,'' Canavan told the magazine.
``And if the tunnel is full of dust you can't see. We have a
two-million candlepower flare (but in one instance) we couldn't see
the door until we were six inches from it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy Seal commandos have focused their planning and training
toward interdiction of sensitive weapons or weapon materials at
sea.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy is installing a ship-mounted system that can identify
trace elements from nuclear, chemical or biological materials
loaded aboard ships. The experimental system has been installed on
several dozen warships, according to the Pentagon
counterproliferation report.
</P>
<P>
   Other special operations units, such as the Army's three Ranger
battalions and Special Forces groups assigned to other military
commands, would likely provide combat support to commandos in any
mission, officials said. The Rangers, for example, could be used to
seize an airfield to allow the commandos to be brought in.
</P>
<P>
   And depending on the nature of an incident, outside experts from
the Energy Department, FBI or U.S. intelligence community might be
included in a raiding force to provide specific expertise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
