<HEADER>
A6407 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-MARKET-1STLD-W     08-27 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MARKET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-(800)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETS JOLTED, DOW OFF 4.1 PERCENT AS RUSSIAN ECONOMIC SLIDE ADDS
TO PRESSURES ON YELTSIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Changes 2nd sentence of lede graf to clarify; adds quotes from
investors throughout)  (Also moved in `f' category as MARKET-NYT; with MARKET-LOSSES,
MARKET-INVESTORS, MARKET-COMMODITIES, RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS,
RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT, RUSSIA-EMERGE) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock market investors around the world rushed the
exits Thursday. The depth of the economic problems in Russia and
Asia proved too unfathomable for investors, who scoured the
horizons for a haven.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst trading day this year, the Dow Jones industrial
average fell 4.19 percent, or 357.36 points, to close at 8165.99.
The Nasdaq fell 81.72 points to close down 4.62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dow average now 12.5 percent below its July 17 high of
9337.97, investors are well into what Wall Street calls a
correction. Bear market territory _ defined as a stock price
decline of 15 percent to 20 percent _ is at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Investors struggled to absorb the full impact of Russia's
economic woes _ its central bank has stopped supporting the ruble
and has defaulted on its ruble-denominated debt. Institutions that
had bought the country's debt saw the value of their holdings fall
to around 10 percent of its worth just last week.
</P>
<P>
   But the fear that the economic unraveling in Russia could spread
to the emerging market countries of Latin America acted as the
greatest depressant on stocks worldwide. Indeed, investors
everywhere wondered which economy would be the next to crumple.
</P>
<P>
   Major markets fell, with the exception of Hong Kong. In Europe,
key indexes fell 3 percent to 6 percent, with the Dax in Germany
dropping 4.5 percent. Latin America's markets were punished even
more, with Mexico's main index falling 6 percent and Brazil's
nearly 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointment over Japan's inability to repair its broken-down
economy drove the Nikkei 225 index down 3.04 percent long before
trading began in the United States. Policy paralysis seems to have
overtaken Japanese politicians, who appear unwilling to take steps
to solve their country's well-documented economic and banking
problems. The Nikkei has fallen 16.5 percent this year from its
March high.
</P>
<P>
   When the stock market opened in the United States, traders and
money managers reported a flood of early selling, selling that
continued in waves all day. Even though stocks tried to rally
several times, few, if any, buyers were willing to pick through the
rubble for bargains. The market closed at its low, a sign of
overwhelming market weakness and a sign of caution for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks of big international banks, which were down an average of
6.6 percent, were among the hardest hit on fears of Russia-related
losses. But rampant selling ravaged even the most favored stocks,
such as Coca-Cola, General Electric and Microsoft, as well as
Internet darlings Excite Inc. and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   The suffering of the healthiest companies can be attributed in
part to selling by investors who had to raise cash because of
losses on their emerging market investments. When an investor has
to cough up cash because he has borrowed heavily to make foreign
investments that are cratering, he sells whatever he can. Often
that means the biggest, most liquid investment. Or the investment
that still shows a profit.
</P>
<P>
   It is a vicious circle, said William Dudley, an economist at
Goldman, Sachs in New York. ``People are becoming increasingly risk
averse, leading to lower equity prices, increasing pressure on
emerging market economies. Absent right now is any mechanism to
break that dynamic up.'' As a result, Dudley suggests that
investors brace for more market declines.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news started early. At 9:46 a.m., shares in the Republic
New York Corporation, the parent of Republic National Bank of New
York, were halted from trading. Minutes later, the bank announced
it would take a $110 million charge in the third quarter for losses
in Russian government bonds. The loss would virtually eliminate
earnings for the period, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it became clear that the ultimate impact of the
Russian disaster was still unknown. If Republic Bank, known for its
strong balance sheet and conservative lending practices, was hurt
by Russia, what would happen to more aggressive lenders?
</P>
<P>
   With that announcement, Republic Bank became the first domestic
bank to enumerate its Russian losses. Market historians noted that
Republic was also the first domestic bank, back in the mid-1980s,
to reveal the extent of its exposure to lesser-developed country
debt that later hammered Citicorp and many other American banks.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in financial stocks Thursday found themselves in a
nightmarish version of the child's game of hot potato. Exposure to
Russia's ruble devaluation and effective default on its debt is
only starting to be defined. And since many of the losses will be
taken by investors who bought or sold derivative securities, where
the parties who took the other side of a given trade are not
immediately identifiable, it could be weeks before it is known who
is on the hook for what may be $100 billion in losses. In the
meantime, investors ask: Losses, losses, who's got the losses?
</P>
<P>
   Some investors wondered why a country as economically
inconsequential as Russia should play such a big role in world
market turmoil. Yes, Russia wields nuclear firepower, but it
accounts for just 1 percent of the world's trade, roughly
equivalent to that of Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts noted, though, that what happened in Russia could very
well replay in the emerging markets of Latin America. When
investors see their portfolios lose 90 percent of their value, as
those holding Russian debt have, two things happen. Assets in other
emerging markets need to fall in price to reflect the new economic
reality. And, as those assets are repriced, investors and lenders
withdraw from the markets, cutting off companies' access to capital
and making financing more expensive for governments.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's default also made it painfully obvious that the
International Monetary Fund is no longer ready or able to bail out
countries in economic despair. Bailouts in Korea, Malaysia and
Thailand had lulled investors into believing that the IMF was
effectively a guarantor of their investments.
</P>
<P>
   So what investors are facing now is the very thing Wall Street
fears the most: the unknown. The devil we know, an imploding Russia
in this case, is bad enough. The devil we don't know, what other
economic disasters lie ahead, most particularly in Latin America,
is considerably worse.
</P>
<P>
   All eyes are on Latin America. That's because a crisis in these
nations would strike a severe blow to both American investors and
corporations. Some 25 percent of Brazil's $300 billion in domestic
debt, for example, is held by foreign investors. More important,
around 20 percent of United States exports go to Latin America.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even in the United States, the stock market carnage is worse
than it first appears. Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette reported
Thursday that the average stock was down 38 percent from its high.
</P>
<P>
   One money manager said that the selling was overdone and the
result of investors buying stocks only because they are going up.
``People have been investing by the direction of earnings and not
looking at value,'' said David Eidelman, at Eidelman, Finger,
Harris &AMP; Co. in St. Louis. ``If earnings are going higher, they
buy. But when they start to see earnings come down, they look at
the direction not the value. To paraphrase Oscar Wilde, these
investors, so-called momentum players, know the price of everything
and the value of nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to the slide Thursday, brokerage firms asked
investors who had borrowed to buy stocks to prop up their depleted
portfolios with more cash, known as margin calls.
</P>
<P>
   More than one professional trader said that Thursday's action in
United States stocks was reminiscent of the beginning of the end of
the great bull market of the late 1960s and early 1970s. These
traders recalled that the 1973 bear market, which removed 45
percent from the Dow Jones industrial average, did not begin in
earnest until the Nifty Fifty stocks _ names like Polaroid, Avon
and IBM crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, approximately 15 stocks _ including Dell
Computer, Lucent Technologies and Cisco Systems _ had held up while
the rest of the United States market had fallen. Thursday, even
these shares fell hard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
