<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6412 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-U.S.-1STLD-WRI     08-27 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBASSY BOMBING SUSPECT ARRAIGNED IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (lowercases first `a' in al-'Owhali; recasts story to give more
prominence to second suspect and for editorial smoothing)  (See also ATTACK-ARRAIGN) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal authorities brought a suspect in the
bombings of the U.S. Embassies in Kenya and Tanzania to the United
States on Thursday, saying that he had admitted that he was trained
at terror camps in Afghanistan run by Osama bin Laden, the
Saudi-born multimillionaire suspected of having inspired, organized
and financed the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities have also seized a second suspect for
prosecution. This suspect, who provided one of the first breaks in
the case, is expected to reach New York on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The first suspect, Mohamed Rashed Daoud al-'Owhali, was said to
have acknowledged that he rode as a passenger in the truck that
carried the massive bomb to the Nairobi embassy, according to a
detailed criminal complaint unsealed Thursday in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali was said to have told investigators that he threw a
dummy grenade at a security guard seconds before the blast and then
prepared to die in a bombing that he said was designed as a
``martyrdom operation in which he did not expect to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali survived the explosion, though fragments from the
blast left a large wound in his back and cuts on his hands and
face. And Thursday, the slight, bearded man with a bandage on one
wrist was brought by FBI agents from Nairobi to a New York
courtroom. U.S. Magistrate Sharon Grubin informed him of the
charges against him, including conspiracy to commit murder, the use
of a weapon of mass destruction and 12 counts of murder, one each
for the dozen Americans who died in the Nairobi bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The second suspect, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, has been in custody in
Nairobi for nearly two weeks, law-enforcement officials said. He
was initially detained on a flight from Nairobi to Karachi,
Pakistan, on Aug. 7, the day of the bombings. Pakistani officials
have said that Odeh provided extensive details of his role in the
plot. But pending his arrival in New York, federal officials would
not discuss the case against Odeh in any detail.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said the decision to bring the two suspects
to New York was related to the sealed grand jury indictment
returned against bin Laden in New York.
</P>
<P>
   That federal grand jury is expected to hear evidence about the
bombings and may return a superseding indictment that would be used
to bring prosecutions in New York against those said to be
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Any statements to U.S. authorities by Odeh or al-'Owhali could
be presented to the grand jury as evidence against bin Laden, who
came under federal investigation after the World Trade Center
bombing in 1993. Officials said the sealed indictment of bin Laden
was issued before the East Africa bombings and charges him with
several terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, FBI Director Louis Freeh would
not discuss bin Laden's legal status nor would he comment on
reports that the indictment accused bin Laden of plotting to kill
President Clinton in 1994 during a visit to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali first emerged as a possible suspect when Kenyan
authorities contacted him two days after the bombing in Nairobi,
according to a federal complaint signed by FBI Agent Daniel
Coleman. He was arrested on that day, and confessed to taking part
in the plot during two interviews with FBI investigators on Aug. 12
and Aug. 20, the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint, he told investigators he traveled
from Lahore, Pakistan to Kenya on July 31. With several
unidentified confederates he went to the embassy Aug. 4, three days
before the bombing to inspect the buildings and grounds in
preparation for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the bombing, the complaint said, al-'Owhali, along
with another man traveled in a truck carrying a huge homemade bomb
from an undisclosed location in Kenya to the embassy. The identity
of the driver or whether he survived was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali first told Kenyan authorities _ apparently while he
was in a hospital _ that he had been wounded while standing on an
embankment with a friend as the explosion occurred. But the Kenyans
were suspicious because he said he was wearing the clothes he wore
at the time of the blast, although they showed no traces of blood
from his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   He told the Kenyans that he had thrown away in a hospital
bathroom two keys that fit a padlock on the rear of the bomb-laden
vehicle and three bullets from a gun he had left behind in the
truck. Hospital employees later retrieved the keys and bullets from
the area that al-'Owhali described.
</P>
<P>
   Al-'Owhali told the investigators that he had been trained in a
number of camps in Afghanistan, including ``camps affiliated with
al Qaeda, an international terrorist group, led by bin Laden.'' At
the bin Laden camps, al-'Owhali said he was trained in the tools of
terror, including explosives, hijacking and kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   During the interviews recounted in the complaint, al-'Owhali
said he attended conferences and meetings with bin Laden and knew
of an order, signed by bin Laden and other militants, saying that
American civilians were legitimate targets of terrorist acts. In
the Kenya and Tanzania bombings, more than 250 people died and more
than 5,000 were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant was flown to a military airport in upstate New
York on Wednesday night and taken by helicopter under heavy guard
to FBI headquarters in Manhattan. He was being held in a federal
jail next to the U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, al-'Owhali also completed a financial affidavit,
in support of an application for a court appointed lawyer. In it he
said that he was unmaried, had no home and had never been employed.
But he reported that he had $12,000 from his father and owned a
1992 Chevrolet Caprice. Al-'Owhali had been identified as Yemeni
citizen, but officials in that country denied it.
</P>
<P>
   The two were seized under U.S. laws that make it a federal crime
to carry out terrorist attacks overseas, and Kenya agreed to their
capture.
</P>
<P>
   If found guilty, al-'Owhali could face a maximum sentence of
death or life in prison. He was ordered held pending a hearing
Sept. 28. His court-appointed lawyer, Yuanchung Lee, would not
comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at FBI headquarters, senior law enforcement
and diplomatic officials here hailed the action as an important
victory in the U.S. war against terror, in large part because they
had succeeded in bringing a suspect in an overseas attack from
Africa into a U.S. court within 20 days of the bombing
</P>
<P>
   Freeh said Thursday that no decision had made on where to try
al-'Owhali. Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney in New York, appearing
at a news conference at FBI headquarters in New York, suggesting
that any defendants in the bombing plot would probably be tried in
New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
