<SLUG> BC-CHANCELLOR-CAPSTAR-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDING RADIO MERGER WAVE, CHANCELLOR WILL BUY CAPSTAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (js) 
 By ALLEN R. MYERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The radio merger wave started by deregulation two years
ago has reached a new crest. Chancellor Media Corp. said Thursday
that it planned to buy Capstar Broadcasting Corp. for $2.3 billion
in stock plus nearly $1.8 billion in assumed debt, surpassing CBS
as the nation's largest chain of radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company would have 463 stations with more than 65
million listeners in 105 markets and revenues of about $2.3
billion. While such consolidation has reduced the industry's
expenses and raised its profitability, critics say that diverse
local ownership is rapidly vanishing.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Media's position is substantially the work of Hicks,
Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst, the leveraged buyout firm, which has sought to
capitalize on relaxed restrictions on how many stations one company
can own. Hicks, Muse owns about 15 percent of Chancellor and 59
percent of Capstar and stands to hold 25 percent of the combined
company. Thomas Hicks, chairman of Hicks, Muse, is also chairman of
Chancellor and Capstar and his brother Steven is Capstar's chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor hopes to appeal to national advertisers wishing to
saturate local markets by offering them clusters of radio stations
along with its television stations _ which are part of its pending
acquisition of Lin Television _ and its billboards.
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize the value of such chains, CBS announced Thursday
that it would sell the public 20 percent of its radio operations.
The Capstar acquisition was expected; Hicks and Jeffrey Marcus, the
chief executive of Chancellor, have long spoken of such plans.
Combining the companies will yield about $70 million a year in cash
flow _ or earnings before debt payments and depreciation _ because
of increased efficiency and revenue, they said. The companies
otherwise expect total cash flow of about $1.2 billion next year.
Chancellor, which has 108 stations in 22 large markets, can bring
its more sophisticated sales abilities to Capstar, which has 355
stations in medium-sized markets, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the magic that occurs in the larger markets in the
business we're bringing to the medium and smaller markets,'' Marcus
said. Even the big-city announcers could handle work for groups of
smaller stations.
</P>
<P>
   Capstar, in fact, already runs many ``virtual stations,'' which
have no announcers of their own but instead deliver feeds from
distant announcers who tape or broadcast shows for other stations.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and analysts applaud the prospects for such
efficiencies to raise the profit margins of smaller stations, which
are typically lower than those of larger stations. And some
analysts wondered whether Chancellor was paying enough. ``I was a
little disappointed in the price that Capstar got, though it was
certainly in the realm of reasonableness,'' said Gordon Hodge of
Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Because of the large Hicks, Muse presence in both companies,
working out terms that other shareholders would consider fair
required extra time, with most of Wall Street's leading firms
advising one party or the other. Marcus said he expected the deal
to improve Chancellor's earnings performance next year.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's consolidation has drawn attacks, however, from
some who say that consolidated ownership has stifled local radio
voices. ``This is what we're getting,'' said Andrew Jay
Schwartzman, president of the Media Access Project, a law firm
representing civil rights groups, referring to the Chancellor
announcement. ``More and more of the same.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for Chancellor to trade at least 0.48 share
for each Capstar share, or as much as 0.505 share depending on
Capstar's performance for the rest of the year. In the broader
market rout, shares of Chancellor fell $2, to $42.75, and Capstar
dropped $2.1875, to $19.3125.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
