<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-DISAPPEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.) 
LOST IN SURF, OR MAYBE EVADING ARREST
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ With Hurricane Bonnie bearing down on the Eastern
Seaboard and rough surf advisories in effect, it was just the type
of emergency call that rescue workers had been bracing for.
Kimberly Kuda flagged down a police officer in Point Pleasant Beach
just after 7:30 p.m. Monday to say her future husband had been
swept into the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   As a Coast Guard helicopter and rescue boats frantically
searched the dark, gnashing ocean, Ms. Kuda, 21, appeared so
distraught that an emergency psychiatric team was brought in to
help, said Detective Sgt. Harry DiCorcia of the Point Pleasant
Beach police. But now, after unexpected twists, investigators say
they believe that her fiance, Antonio Mandarino Jr., 23, may still
be alive and that his drowning and her distress were a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   First, a telephone caller suggested to the police that
Mandarino, who has a long criminal record, might have faked his
drowning to avoid prosecution on a number of charges in Bergen
County. Then, Ms. Kuda also disappeared. Police officials said she
was apparently the only person to witness Mandarino's alleged
drowning. So Thursday, the authorities again mounted a search.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, they had no need for the Coast Guard.
Instead, Point Pleasant police teamed up with the Bergen County
Sheriff's office to try to find the couple, particularly Mandarino,
who has previously been arrested in at least a half dozen northern
New Jersey towns on charges including marijuana and gun possession,
assault, aggravated assault, passing bad checks, shoplifting and
receiving stolen property.
</P>
<P>
   Bergen County Sheriff Jay Alpert said Mandarino was scheduled to
appear in Bergen County Superior Court in Hackensack on Sept. 14 to
face a charge of eluding the police. Fred Schwanwede, the first
assistant prosecutor in Bergen County, said Mandarino had escaped
from a detective who was trying to stop him for questioning in
Saddle Brook, N.J. Officials would not say what the detective
wanted to question Mandarino about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think clearly at this point that it's nothing more than a
hoax,'' Alpert said. ``And it goes beyond just a false police
report. You have people that risked their lives. Divers that were
down there, going into rough surf, looking for somebody they
thought was there, which is something that is almost
incomprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   The search included a Coast Guard helicopter with a crew of four
and rescue workers in boats, including a 41-foot Coast Guard
utility boat and a rigid-hull inflatable craft, said Petty Officer
Mike LaPearl. The helicopter costs $3,638 an hour to operate, he
said, the utility boat $313 an hour and the rigid-hull inflatable
$233 an hour. In all, officials estimated the cost of the rescue
effort at more than $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Alpert said that he and his wife had watched news accounts of
Mandarino's drowning and that their hearts had gone out to the
heartbroken fiancee. ``It evokes all kinds of emotions,'' he said.
``A young couple supposed to get married in November, she's sitting
on the beach and sees her fiance whisked away by a wave. Now, she
has disappeared and is presumably with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Detectives are searching for the couple and for Ms. Kuda's
silver 1997 Mercury Tracer, with New Jersey license plate RF394H,
he said .
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Ms. Kuda left Point Pleasant police headquarters
about 1:30 a.m. Tuesday and returned to the house in Oakland, N.J.,
where she lived with her fiance and his father. Late that morning,
she gave an interview by telephone to The (Hackensack) Record. ``He
went into the water, and I saw a wave come and take him in,'' she
told the newspaper. She also said they had gone to the shore
because they could not afford to take a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Then, she vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Mandarino's father, Antonio Mandarino Sr., has told local
newspapers that he believes his son may still be alive. Reached by
telephone, he said he did not know where the couple might be or
what had happened to his son. ``He's not here,'' the father said.
``I don't know where he is. You got to talk to his girlfriend. If
you could find her, she knows everything. I don't know anything.''
</P>
<P>
   According to police, Ms. Kuda flagged down an officer for help
shortly after 7:30 p.m. Monday, saying her fiance had been standing
in knee-deep water. Ms. Kuda reported that ``a wave knocked him
down and took him into the ocean and that was the last she saw of
him,'' DiCorcia said.
</P>
<P>
   If Mandarino is found and faces the Bergen County charge of
eluding police, he could face five to 10 years in prison if
convicted. But if the drowning was a hoax, officials said, he and
Ms. Kuda could face considerably more serious charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
