<HEADER>
A6441 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-MEDIA-1STLD     08-27 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-MEDIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TV CREWS, COVERING STORM MEANS GETTING WET
</HEADLINE>
 
(Corrects spelling to `Morehead,' sted `Moorehead' in lede)   (See also: HURRICANE-BONNIE) 
(jw) 
 By RICK BRAGG 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORFOLK, Va. _ Beside an overturned basketball goal in Morehead
City, N.C., Jim Cantore abandoned the comparative safety of his
Weather Channel ``live'' truck, planted his feet, squinted one eye
against the blowing rain and, with his pants legs flapping madly
and the wind itself rushing into the microphone, brought Hurricane
Bonnie into America's living rooms.
</P>
<P>
   On a trembling dock in Wrightsville Beach, N.C., Kerry Sanders,
an NBC correspondent, braced himself against a boat's mast and,
apparently in some danger of being blown into the surging water,
went live with the news that the storm's winds had reached almost
70 mph.
</P>
<P>
   In a parking lot in Wilmington, N.C., protected from the wind
but not rain by a hotel wall, a bedraggled-looking Martin Savidge
gave periodic updates to CNN viewers while shelter waited just
steps away.
</P>
<P>
   And in Nags Head, N.C., his face peppered by stinging rain and
sand, Jeff Morrow of the Weather Channel stood before heaving waves
and warned of worse to come as his cameraman wiped water off the
lens with a rag.
</P>
<P>
   It was not always so dramatic here on the southern East Coast,
as television crews from around the dial tracked Bonnie's fury _ or
lack of _ over the past two days. Aerial views on some channels
showed the same damaged house over and over and the same overturned
tree was brought to America's attention again and again.
</P>
<P>
   But, from networks like CNN and the Weather Channel, whose
viewership often rises significantly in times of crisis, to local
stations who dispatched dozens of reporters to stand at the water's
edge and give stern warnings of a catastrophe that never came, one
thing was clear:
</P>
<P>
   The only way to cover weather is to stand in it.
</P>
<P>
   It is the best way, forecasters say, to impress upon viewers the
importance and danger of what is happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell it like it is,'' said Cantore, who has loved the
science of weather since he was a boy in New England, jumping in
rain puddles.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he said, the camera's eye shows people the rushing
surf, the waving trees, the downed power lines, all the things that
could kill.
</P>
<P>
   It tells people why it is important to leave when a sheriff's
deputy knocks on the door and informs them of a ``mandatory
evacuation,'' something many homeowners and even tourists ignore,
forecaster said.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``stand-up'' in gale-force winds has another purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more likely to stay with the program than go to the
clicker,'' if they see someone out in it, someone apparently
braving the elements, said Jack Loftus, vice president of
communications for Nielsen Media Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to communicate it from the safety of studio,
but it's another to put it on the line, to put yourself in harm's
way,'' he said. ``It gets pretty exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 1.5 million households had tuned into the Weather
Channel as the storm bore down on the North Carolina coast. The
Weather Channel's average audience, in good weather, is about
200,000.
</P>
<P>
   And it is Cantore's presence here in harm's way on the southern
East Coast, not the calibrations and prognostications at the home
office of the Weather Channel back in Marietta, Ga., that holds the
viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasters from CNN, the Weather Channel and other networks
said they would not place one of their reporters in peril for a
live shot, and stressed that reporters more often set up their
camera's far from the coastline, usually across barrier islands,
when high winds threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would never put them in harm's way,'' said Connie Malko, a
senior publicist for the Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   But viewers do have at least the impression that the reporter is
going someplace that they would probably not go.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's serious stuff,'' Loftus said of the live broadcasts,
``when you see somebody out there, right on the beach or boardwalk.
That does rivet your attention, partly because you want to see if
he gets blown away.''
</P>
<P>
   Cantore said it negated the credibility of the newscast to take
foolish chances, or hype a weather system that had become less
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as he did his stand-up as Hurricane Bonnie faded from
hurricane to tropical storm, he picked a place where the wind blew
in off an inlet and contained no flying debris.
</P>
<P>
   There are always some risks, he said, but the secret is to avoid
foolish ones, while still being close enough to the storm's eye to
convey its power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to remove myself from the protection of the live
truck,'' he said Thursday morning, taking the viewer with him out
into the 60-mph gusts as the storm finally began to weaken.
``That's a pretty good gust right there,'' he said, leaning into
the wind, only wobbling a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about 60,'' he said, and it is no wild guess. Cantore
is a trained meteorologist, what he calls a field meteorologist,
and this week, he has been on more television sets than Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   His Weather Channel has become the hot ticket item on the
Weather Service web page, where people can order Weather Channel
gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell in love with weather,'' said Cantore, who has had only
a few hours' sleep over the past week. For lunch on Thursday, he
had an orange, Milano cookies and Frosted Mini Wheats, covered in
Cheese Whiz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a big kid who loves to go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   But he understands how dangerous weather is. He tells the story
of how he once watched floodwaters cover over his live truck as he
watched from a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Local television crews seemed determined to emulate the networks
in their coverage, by sending people in rain gear out to the
beaches _ even though it looked a little silly as people in shorts
and T-shirts frolicked in the light rain around them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
