<HEADLINE>
AMOCO SUED OVER BRAIN TUMORS IN WORKERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill. Ala., Md.)  (jw) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Over several decades, 19 current or former employees
of an Amoco Corp. research center in the Chicago suburbs have been
stricken with brain tumors and four of them have died. Nobody knows
why, and researchers hired by Amoco have been trying to figure out
whether the cases have a common cause.
</P>
<P>
   This week, four former employees and the surviving relatives of
three others filed suit against Amoco, saying it ``exhibited
reckless disregard for the health and well-being'' of the
employees. The suit, filed in Cook County Circuit Court, charges
that Amoco exposed the employees in its Naperville research center
to ``defective, unsafe and/or unreasonably dangerous chemicals''
and that the company failed to take adequate measures to protect
its workers.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the 19 employees were stricken with an especially
deadly type of brain tumor, called a glioma. And all seven worked
on similar chemical research projects over the last 28 years. So
researchers have said they are paying close attention to about 34
research projects out of the tens of thousands the center has
worked on.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Dean, a spokesman for Amoco, said the corporation had been
investigating the cancer cases since 1989. Last summer, Amoco asked
research teams from the University of Alabama at Birmingham and
Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore to study the medical
histories of all 8,000 people who have ever worked at the center.
</P>
<P>
   In April, researchers outlined some of their findings. One
conclusion was that the seven men with glioma all worked at one
time or another in the same three-building complex at the center.
Five of those men worked in one of the complex's buildings, number
503, most worked on the third floor and three worked in a
laboratory housed in a wing of the building that is now closed.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Wells, Amoco's manager of epidemiology, told The Chicago
Tribune in April that because so many of the cases occurred in
people who worked in a small area, the number of glioma cases was
``about seven times higher than what you'd expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean said Thursday that he could not comment on the lawsuit. But
he said: ``We're going to continue to aggressively investigate and
leave no stone unturned. Our primary concern remains the health and
well-being of our current and former colleagues. Our mission
remains to ensure a safe work environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Hawes, a lawyer representing the plaintiffs, said she
hoped to expand the case into a class-action lawsuit. Ms. Hawes
said three of her clients had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these people are still alive,'' she added, ``but their
situation is not good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
