<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-NEBRASKA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU NIXES SERIES WITH NEBRASKA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By TERRANCE HARRIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU has withdrawn from its three-game series
against perennial football power Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts _ agreed upon by former TCU athletic director
Frank Windegger and Nebraska athletic director Bill Byrne _ would
have had the Frogs traveling to Lincoln, Neb., in 2000, the
Cornhuskers coming to Fort Worth in 2001 and the game returning to
Lincoln in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   TCU, 1-10 last season, avoided a $100,000 forfeit fee by
agreeing to play the Cornhuskers once sometime in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie North, TCU director of football operations, said
yesterday that withdrawing from the games should not be viewed as a
TCU inferiority complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``In no way are we scared of people,'' North said. ``We just
want to have a chance to keep our kids healthy and play out the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   North said no agreement has been made for replacement games but
said a deal could possibly be in the works for a three-game series
against Arkansas State, which was 2-9 last year.
</P>
<P>
   TCU athletic director Eric Hyman could not be reached for
comment yesterday. Byrne, having dealt with several programs that
pulled out of contracts in recent years, is not pleased with TCU's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand when a team is down; schools such as TCU need
some relief,'' Byrne said. ``But, on the other hand, when teams get
new athletic directors and football coaches, deals go sideways. And
I'm getting tired of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevada-Las Vegas, Utah State and Houston are among teams that
have withdrawn from games with Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   TCU would have received $400,000 for the game in Lincoln and
almost certainly would have had a capacity crowd for the game in
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The contract for the third game was never signed but would have
been played during the third week of the 2002 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If TCU is as bad as they say they are, then we don't want a
mismatch either,'' Byrne said. ``We'd rather for it to be more
competitive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
