<SLUG> BC-GLF-WORLD-SERIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICKELSON TAKES CROOKED PATH TO LATE-SEASON SUCCESS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio _ Phil Mickelson knows how to bounce back from
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   When Mickelson tied for 34th at the PGA Championship last month,
it meant another year passed without him winning a major
championship. That left Mickelson with two options: either he could
sulk until 1999, or he could spend the rest of the year proving he
is still one of the world's top golfers.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson chose the latter. The day after the PGA ended,
Mickelson won the bizarre AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am, a
tournament that finally ended Aug. 17 after being postponed for
more than six months. Then Mickelson almost won again on Sunday,
finishing tied for second at the Sprint International.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Mickelson continued his torrid stretch at the NEC
World Series of Golf. Shooting an opening-round four-under par 66,
Mickelson held a one-stroke lead over Tiger Woods and Craig Parry
at the challenging Firestone Country Club South course.
</P>
<P>
   Funny how quickly things change. Mickelson was struggling only a
few weeks ago, and after this weekend he was planning to take two
months off. But following Thursday's round, Mickelson said he might
put his vacation on hold. Who could blame him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little disappointed after the third round of the PGA,
but Pebble gave me some momentum, and it carried over,'' Mickelson
said, after a round that featured six birdies and two bogeys. ``At
Pebble, I really started to hit the ball well and feel comfortable,
hitting the ball solid, better balance, just my swing over all. I'm
looking at this tournament as being big for my year. If I play
well, I'm going to add some tournaments and see what I can do about
finishing on top of the money list. If not, I'm going to take some
time off. It's really a big swing tournament for me on which way
the next couple of months are going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson is sixth on the year's PGA Tour money list
($1,512,646), but winning this weekend's first-place check of
$405,000 could move Mickelson to No. 1, a position currently held
by Vijay Singh ($1,694,253), who shot an opening-round 71.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Thursday's round will only boost Mickelson's
confidence in a tournament where he usually plays well. Mickelson
won the NEC World Series of Golf in 1996, he finished second last
year and he finished fourth in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   One of the longest layouts on the tour (7,139 yards), Firestone
Country Club is a place where Mickelson can display his power off
the tee and his creative touch around the green. The highlights of
Mickelson's round included a birdie-birdie-birdie streak on Nos. 11
through 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like about Firestone is that it's difficult for
players to separate themselves from the field,'' Mickelson said.
``You can be patient and not worry about guys shooting eight or
nine under par.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday ended with Woods and Parry in close pursuit of
Mickelson, while five players were tied for fourth place at 68 _
Justin Leonard, Tim Herron, Greg Turner, Brian Watts, and Shinichi
Yokota. It was a bogey-free day for Woods, who made three birdies
and punctuated his round with a birdie on No. 18, hitting a
gorgeous 9-iron approach shot to within two feet of the cup.
</P>
<P>
   With 11 top-10 finishes on tour this year, but only one victory,
Woods figured he may be due to break through. ``You've just got to
keep giving yourself chances,'' said Woods. ``This year,
unfortunately either someone has outplayed me, or I haven't made
the shots when I really needed them. With nine holes to go, you've
got to give yourself the chance. That's all I look forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Parry, a 32-year-old veteran from Australia, Thursday's
round was welcome. Parry has not played up to his usual standards
this year, and although he switched putters recently, he was not
sure the change would solve his problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the putter,'' Parry said. ``It was the idiot on the
end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   With 13 career victories on tour, Mickelson, 28, has enjoyed
plenty of highlights, but the lack of a major championship is the
one glaring omission on his resume.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson admits he thought he would have won a major by now,
but his best finish at a major this year was a 10th place tie at
the United States Open.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Mickelson, there is nothing he can do about
the majors until next year's Masters. But with a victory this
weekend, Mickelson could become the first three-time winner on tour
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played well the last three years here, so I have
confidence,'' Mickelson said. ``I'm looking at this tournament as
an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
