<SLUG> BC-NOVARTIS-EARNINGS-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVARTIS, PROFIT UP 14 PERCENT, WILL SHED SOME FOOD LINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Out to gain some market momentum, Novartis AG of Switzerland,
the world's largest health care company, reported a 14 percent gain
in first-half earnings Thursday and announced a plan to unload
several slow-selling nutritional brands and combine its nutrition
and over-the-counter drug divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks largely to a jump in investment income, Novartis'
earnings in the first half rose to 3.553 billion Swiss francs, or
$2.4 billion, from 3.117 billion francs a year earlier. Operating
profit was up only 2 percent, to 4.1 billion francs, because of
higher marketing costs.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Novartis earnings met most analysts' expectations,
its stock ended lower on a day of deep market losses worldwide. The
shares fell 66 Swiss francs in Zurich, or 2.7 percent. On the New
York Stock Exchange, Novartis' U.S. depository receipts, which
represent one-twentieth of a share, fell $2.50, to $77. By
comparison, the shares of Schering-Plough fell $4.8125, to
$97.0625; Pfizer lost $4.125, to $103.875; and Merck was down
$4.25, at $129.125.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have long expected Novartis to pare some of its
disparate brands. Created from the merger of Ciba-Geigy and Sandoz
in 1996, Novartis, based in Basel, makes everything from Neoral, a
blockbuster transplant drug, to such cupboard staples as Ovaltine,
Ex-Lax, Sunkist products and Gerber baby and junior foods.
</P>
<P>
   The realignment will allow Novartis to eliminate 380 jobs,
mostly administrative positions in Europe, and parcel off seven
units, including Roland snacks, Wasa crisp bread and Redline, a
U.S. distributor.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Daniel Vasella, the company's president, said in an
interview Thursday that the brands would probably be sold
separately and that the steps were unlikely to be completed before
year-end. ``We'll create some synergies and get a clearer focus on
the marketplace,'' Vasella said. ``The brands that are being
divested had relatively little in common with some of our other
brands.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Novartis plans to dispense with some food items, the
company appears to be following a strategy some of its competitors
are abandoning. Aside from food, Novartis is a giant seller of
pharmaceuticals and agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
   Few drug companies have remained leaders in all three, choosing
instead to shed one of them to divert more money into research and
development for new drugs. Once the American Home Products
acquisition of Monsanto is completed, the combined company would be
comparable to Novartis in pharmaceuticals and agricultural
products. Yet, American Home Products sold many of its food brands
well before the acquisition was announced.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Novartis has failed to stir the enthusiasm
among investors that some of its U.S. competitors _ like Pfizer,
with its introduction of Viagra, or Warner-Lambert, red-hot from
the sales of Lipitor and Rezulin _ have.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Vasella to sell Gerber as a way to focus
more on pharmaceuticals. But that option does not sit well with the
Novartis boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would I want to do something like that?'' he asked. ``We
looked at what was our strongest brand in nutrition, and it's
Gerber. It's one of the top brands in the U.S., sort of in the
class as Coke.''
</P>
<P>
   Novartis said it would take a charge of about 120 million
francs, or $81 million, this year to revamp its nutrition division.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
