<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS TIGHTEN WILD-CARD RACE IN A BLOWOUT  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bobby Valentine found himself in a quandary at
3Com Park Thursday. His starter for the Mets, Armando Reynoso, had
made 27 pitches in the first inning and 28 pitches in the second,
and he had pitched out of serious jams both times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always pitches like that,'' Valentine later said of
Reynoso, who entered the game against San Francisco with a 5-0
record in five starts this year. ``You have to give him some rope
because that's the way he pitches. You start taking him out of the
game, he'll never be able to win.''
</P>
<P>
   So the manager stayed with Reynoso, though he had Willie Blair
warming up in the third. But Reynoso could never shake his funk.
The 32-year-old right-hander allowed three runs in a 29-pitch third
inning and was charged with four more runs when he could not escape
a two-out jam in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Greg McMichael and Mel Rojas contributed some kindling to the
fire, too, as the Giants buried the Mets, 11-3, and pulled within a
game of New York, which leads the National League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat was the fourth in the last five games for the Mets
(73-61), who could fall into a tie with Chicago for the wild-card
lead, pending the Cubs' outcome in Colorado Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso conceded he did not have command of his best pitch, his
cut fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in trouble every inning,'' said Reynoso, who left the
bases loaded in the first. ``I got out of it in the first. Later, I
couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   In his four and two-thirds innings, Reynoso allowed 10 hits and
7 runs, walking 5 and striking out 4, while mostly pitching behind
in the count.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't get any strikes called,'' Valentine said. ``He was
forced back into the plate. And when he threw it over, they got
some hits. There were just too many balls. But he was probably due
for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager added: ``When he pitches, he pitches to both sides
of the plate. And when he doesn't get strikes called, it's not
necessary to swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso ended up throwing 117 pitches, 48 of them for balls. By
comparison, the 42-year-old Danny Darwin threw 77 pitches in five
and two-thirds innings, which was one more inning than Reynoso
pitched. For his entire outing, Darwin (8-10) threw only three more
pitches than Reynoso did over his first three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Darwin also collected a pair of singles off Reynoso, the third
and fifth innings, to double his season total to four. Darwin was
hitting only .048 (2 for 42) before Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Darwin joked that he had been told earlier in the
season that he should wear glasses at the plate. When asked what
kind of vision he had, Darwin, the third-oldest player in the
majors, said, ``About 0/36.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets still had visions of winning the game after Darwin's
bases-loaded single in the third had given San Francisco a 3-0 lead
instead of a 4-0 lead because Lenny Harris threw out Ellis Burks at
the plate to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets then loaded the bases with nobody out in the fourth
against Darwin, on singles by Edgardo Alfonzo and Mike Piazza
sandwiched around a John Olerud walk.
</P>
<P>
   But Brian McRae, celebrating his 30th birthday with the
distinction of being the fifth-toughest National League player to
double up this season (1 for every 150.7 at-bats), grounded to
second and into a double play. When Carlos Baerga grounded hard
back to Darwin, it was still 3-1 Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about the only way I hit into double plays, hard and
right at someone,'' said McRae, who grounded into only his fourth
one of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' failure to muster more than one run from the threat
was magnified when Reynoso surrendered a one-out homer to Burks in
the fifth, before allowing two-out singles to Rey Sanchez and
Darwin (an infield hit to short). Marvin Benard followed with a
run-scoring single to left. Out went Reynoso and on came came
McMichael, who yielded a two-run double to Bill Mueller.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, San Francisco led, 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   One inning later, after the Mets had pulled within 7-3 on
Piazza's 25th homer of the season, McMichael allowed a two-out,
three-run pinch-homer to Shawon Dunston, who celebrated with his
son, Shawon Jr., in the Giants' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Shawon Jr. was the team's honorary bat boy and tending to chores
when his father homered. He slapped hands with several Giants and
then headed on the field to gleefully jump into his father's arms.
</P>
<P>
   In the Giants' seventh, Rojas, who had struck out Barry Bonds
with two on to end the sixth, was touched for a leadoff homer by
Jeff Kent. And the Mets headed to Los Angeles on a sour note.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were in it right until Dunston's homer,''
Valentine said of the shot that put the Mets down by 10-3. ``The
No. 9 spot kind of killed us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
