<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6457 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAA-AIR-SAFETY-1STLD-     08-27 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-AIR-SAFETY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANE CRASH COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for complete rewrite)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A deadly commuter-plane crash near Detroit last
year could probably have been prevented if the Federal Aviation
Administration had put into effect the lessons learned from a
similar crash two year earlier, Federal safety officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, of the National Transportation Safety Board, also
criticized the agency for certifying turboprop planes like the one
involved in the Detroit crash as safe for flying into ice, saying
the FAA does not know enough to make the determination.
</P>
<P>
   The board also called for new testing on all turboprop models in
service to determine whether they were safe to fly in such
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   New de-icing procedures developed by the manufacturer of the
Comair EMB-120 that crashed near Detroit on Jan. 9, 1997, killing
all 29 people aboard, could have prevented the ice buildup that
caused the plane to nosedive, the safety board said. Officials of
the board harshly criticized the agency for not ordering the
procedures, which were developed after a turboprop crash in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time we see an accident like this repeating itself, on
information we should have already learned, its an indictment of
the whole system,'' said James Hall, chairman of the safety board.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board also called for a campaign to educate pilots on
new strategies for flying through icy conditions. Many new
strategies were developed after the 1994 crash, in Roselawn, Ind.,
of an ATR-72 owned by an American Airlines affiliate, American
Eagle. Sixty-eight died in that accident. The board said those
lessons were not used by most other airlines, including Comair,
which flies as the Delta Connection.
</P>
<P>
   If icing was dealt with aggressively, Hall said, ``hopefully we
can eliminate it as a factor in future accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about how well the FAA regulates aviation safety, Hall
said, ``We aren't getting what we're paying for.''
</P>
<P>
   The safety board is an independent, advisory agency; the FAA
regulates pilots, airlines and aircraft manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The response from the FAA, apparently resigned to taking one of
the most severe public beatings of the last few years, was terse.
Eliot Brenner, the assistant administrator for public affairs,
said, ``We got the recommendations, and we're looking at the
process issues raised by the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenner said that Jane Garvey, the administrator of the FAA, was
``tied up on other issues'' and was not available to answer
questions about the Safety Board's criticisms. But, he said, ``she
has been very closely following this.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency also distributed a chronology of actions it has taken
since the second crash.
</P>
<P>
   A key problem identified by the Safety Board Thursday was that
Embraer, which builds the EMB-120, had developed a new procedure
that probably would have prevented the accident, but while one
branch of the FAA had approved the plan, that information did not
get to the branch that would have made it a requirement for pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The new procedure, to regularly inflate a hard-rubber.
balloon-like boot on the wing whenever the plane is in icing
conditions, was developed as a result of the Roselawn crash. Before
that crash, rules required pilots to inflate the de-icing boot only
after ice had formed.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all of the investment, after all of the tragedy of
Roselawn, to have information that was generated not make it into
the cockpit is something we never want to see happen again,'' said
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Detroit crash the FAA had been studying six incidents
in which EMB-120s had lost control; there has been at least once
since then.
</P>
<P>
   The board said Thursday that ``despite the accumulated lessons
of several major accidents,'' the FAA's posture on the risks posed
by ice had remained ``incremental and reactive.''
</P>
<P>
   Turboprops are not as safe as jets, primarily because of
susceptibility to ice, top officials of the safety board said
Thursday There are 1,500 such planes in passenger service, carrying
about 54 million passengers a year.
</P>
<P>
   Ice on a wing can cause a plane to lose lift and lead to a
crash, investigators said. The Comair plane accumulated ``sandpaper
ice'' on its wings, rough enough to disrupt the airflow and cut
lift very sharply. But the sandpaper ice may be so thin that it is
difficult to see from the cockpit, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon of rough ice has been known since the 1930s, and
investigators from the safety board found in the FAA's files a
draft memorandum, dated one year before the Detroit crash, noting
that EMB-120s used by airlines tended to develop control problems
from coats of ice so thin that their crews did not realize there
was a risk.
</P>
<P>
   But the tests used to approve the design of the plane are for
thick ice accumulation, not sandpaper ice, on the theory that if
planes can handle thick ice they can handle anything smaller. This
may be wrong, engineers from the safety board said. And by writing
standards that do not include testing for sandpaper ice, ``It does
not cover something that you may encounter in normal flight,'' said
Bernard Loeb, director of the office of aviation safety.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all turboprops have a ``pneumatic boot'' system to
counter ice build-up, but at the time of the crash, pilots at five
of the seven airlines flying them were trained not to use it until
thick ice was visible, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The boots are thick rubber balloons on the forward edges of the
wings that alternately inflate and deflate to break off accumulated
ice. Common wisdom among airlines and FAA regulators is that pilots
should not turn the system on until visible ice has developed, for
fear of letting ice build up in a bulge on top of the inflated
boots, in which case the boots would inflate and deflate within
little ice pockets, without breaking the ice.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the safety board said that this belief was obsolete, because
such an effect is not possible on modern aircraft. After the
Roselawn crash, Embraer amended the aircraft manual to call for
turning the system on whenever ice was suspected. In the plane that
crashed, the pilots had already turned on a system to heat the
propellers and the windshield, as called for in company procedures,
in anticipation of ice.
</P>
<P>
   The change was approved by the FAA's office of aircraft
certification. But the certification office never told the office
that regulates airplane operations. Loeb said that the FAA had told
investigators from the board that there was no requirement for
information to be passed between the two branches.
</P>
<P>
   Embraer told Comair and Comair sent a memorandum to pilots about
a month before the accident mentioning the advice. But the airline
did not make it a rule for pilots. A spokeswoman for the airline,
Meghan Glynn said Thursday that the airline would have no comment
until it had a chance to read the board's report.
</P>
<P>
   Loeb said that under the system now in use, airlines have the
final say on such advice. ``The operator can choose to do what we
wants to with it,'' he said, ``the idea being, you build them, we
fly them, and we know how to fly them better than you because we do
it every day.''
</P>
<P>
   John Goglia, a member of the safety board, complained, ``not to
pass that kind of information on to people, who are operating these
airplanes in these conditions on almost a daily basis, is
unconscionable.'' The board wants the airlines to either adopt the
manufacturers' procedures or demonstrate why they should not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
