<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ECONOMIC WOES IN RUSSIA SEND GLOBAL MARKETS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Investors around the world sold stocks Thursday. In this
country, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 4.19 percent, to
8,165.99, a loss of 357.36 points. The technology-heavy Nasdaq
composite index dropped 4.62 percent, or 81.72 points, to 1,686.41,
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index declined 3.81 percent, or
41.60 points, to 1,042.59. With the Dow average now 12.5 percent
below its July 17 high of 9,337.97, investors are into what Wall
Street calls a correction.
</P>
<P>
   The selloff began in Japan, where the Nikkei index of 225 stocks
declined 3.04 percent. In Europe, key indexes fell 3 percent to 6
percent, with the DAX index in Germany dropping 4.48 percent.
Mexico's main stock index fell 6 percent and Brazil's 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The fall in the ruble has hit Russians hard, pushing up prices.
A woman counts her money as she buys food at a Moscow market. As
the economic crisis deepens, pressure has mounted on the Russian
President, Boris Yeltsin, to cede some of his powers or even step
aside as that country's political leaders negotiated over
fundamental changes in economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   Republic New York, considered one of the nation's most
conservatively managed banks, said its losses in Russia would wipe
out all of its third-quarter earnings. It plans to take a $110
million pretax charge in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   CBS TO SPIN OFF RADIO AND AD UNIT
</P>
<P>
   CBS Corp. said it would spin off up to 20 percent of its radio
and outdoor advertising businesses in a public offering. Shares of
CBS rose $2.0625, to $29.25, on the news.
</P>
<P>
   CHANCELLOR MEDIA ACQUIRING CAPSTAR
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Media announced plans to buy Capstar Broadcasting for
$2.3 billion in stock plus nearly $1.8 billion in assumed debt,
surpassing CBS as the nation's largest chain of radio stations. The
combined company will have 463 stations.
</P>
<P>
   ISIS SHARES RISE ON FDA APPROVAL
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Isis Pharmaceuticals rose 56.25 cents, to $9.8125,
after the Food and Drug Administration approved its drug,
fomivirsen, for treatment of CMV retinitis, a virus that often
causes blindness in AIDS patients. Fomivirsen will be made by Isis
and marketed as Vitravene by Ciba Vision.
</P>
<P>
   NOVARTIS PROFITS INCREASE 14%
</P>
<P>
   Novartis of Switzerland reported a 14 percent gain in first-half
earnings and announced a plan to sell several nutritional brands
and combine its nutrition and over-the-counter drug divisions.
</P>
<P>
   GROWTH SURPASSES ESTIMATE
</P>
<P>
   The economy grew at a faster pace in the second quarter than
previously estimated. The Commerce Department said gross domestic
product rose at a revised 1.6 percent annual rate in the second
quarter, higher than the initial estimate of 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA RAISES MAIN INTEREST RATE
</P>
<P>
   Canada's central bank raised its benchmark interest rate by a
full percentage point in an effort to halt the slide of the
Canadian dollar, which has fallen more than 10 percent against the
United States dollar this year.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA OFFICIALLY IN RECESSION
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia's economy contracted for a second consecutive quarter,
confirming that the country had fallen into recession. Its central
bank reported that the gross domestic product shrank 6.8 percent in
the second quarter as Asian turmoil led to heavy stock sales and
soaring interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH COMPANY BUYING BERG
</P>
<P>
   Berg Electronics agreed to be acquired by Framatome Connectors
International of France for about $1.4 billion in stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
