<HEADLINE>
UNFORTUNATELY FOR RANGERS, ANGELS NOT FOLLOWING SCRIPT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Texas Rangers cleaned out their diapers and bid good
riddance to the mighty Yankees on Sunday, a lady near the New
Yorkers' dugout waved what was supposed to be a prophetic sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yankee Go Home,'' it read. ``And beat the Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what the script was supposed to read, was it not?
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had taken their pinstriped medicine, and now it was
Anaheim's turn to open wide. One week into their tiptoe on the
rough side of the American League tracks, the Rangers had been
mugged in the Bronx and readily surrendered first place.
</P>
<P>
   No worries. The Angels, it was roundly presumed, would soon get
theirs.
</P>
<P>
   So, here the team was in hallowed Yankee Stadium on Wednesday _
fretting, doubting, calling a team meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Except it was the Yankees, not the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're grinders,'' Angels reliever Troy Percival had told
reporters the night before. ``We're going to battle you to the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happened last night, the Angels were assured of
winning the season series from the seemingly record-bound Yanks.
More than that, they were sounding energized, not assaulted and
batteried, by their New York experience.
</P>
<P>
   Even after losing the night end of Wednesday's doubleheader,
Angels manager Terry Collins announced, ``We battled our butts off.
We're going to leave the park tonight feeling great.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that, if you will, to the clenched-throat,
white-knuckled evening the Rangers were experiencing against the
Detroit Tigers. No ground was recouped during the three-game
series. In the end, there was the human lifeboat, John Wetteland,
paddling in to rescue yet another day.
</P>
<P>
   You can compare the lineup cards, if you must. You can argue
whether Darin Erstad is worth more at first base than Will Clark.
You can wonder aloud how flutterballer Steve Sparks could go 0-8 in
the minor leagues, and yet 8-2 for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, it says here, the Rangers are better.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels are tougher. Hungrier. They are, like Percival
said, grinders and battlers.
</P>
<P>
   If they win this American League West race, as they now might,
it'll be because they fought for it harder. The Angels clearly
believe in themselves. The Rangers, on the other hand, seem to look
in the mirror and don't know what to think.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are prolonging innings with costly errors. They are
taking anxious cuts when the situation calls for practicing
patience. They are making stupid base-running mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   They don't deserve to be in first place anymore. Last weekend's
five-error spectacle was a glaring symptom.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, on the other hand, have not been letting ground
balls ripple through their legs and squandering nightly leads. In
their five-game winning streak that ended Wednesday, Anaheim came
from behind in all five.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like a bunch of rats,'' Erstad told writers in New York.
``We just keep grinding at you.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't how the script was supposed to go at all.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Jack McDowell wasn't supposed to come out of four months
on the injured list and give the Angels two dominating starts. Todd
Greene, whose catching career was said to be over, wasn't supposed
to arrive and hit .300 over the final two months.
</P>
<P>
   In New York Tuesday, a 32-year-old rookie named Reggie Williams,
called up after 11 years in the minors, turned the game around for
the Angels with a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   And then, there is pitcher Jeff Juden, renowned loose cannon and
under-achiever, who was the Angels' meek answer to the flurry of
deadline deals that the Rangers pulled off. Against the Yankees
Wednesday, Juden went six-plus innings and held the Yankees to only
three hits.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, for some cash and a player to be named later to
Milwaukee, the Angels have already gotten more from Juden than the
Rangers have from Todd Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   The script lies.
</P>
<P>
   With the combative Collins in charge and with coaches like Larry
Bowa, the Angels are not a placid group. New third baseman Troy
Glaus brought a steel-jawed reputation with him. He once got
knocked cold by a pitch in college. When the Yankees knocked him
down the other night, Glaus got up from the dirt and cracked a
two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some great leaders,'' Collins said. He clicked off the
names of Erstad, Gary DiSarcina, Tim Salmon and Randy Velarde.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are is a testament to the character of the DiSarcinas,
the Salmons and Erstads,'' Collins told the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a lot of guys who care about numbers,'' Erstad
chimed in. ``We just want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, you could argue, it doesn't add up. On paper, the
Rangers have the best catcher, the best slugger, the best left
fielder.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Rangers seem unraveled at the challenge, the
Angels appear inspired.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the script.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0515 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
