u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-COMMODITIES-1S     08-27 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-COMMODITIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO REFUGE IN PLUNGING COMMODITIES PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Edits throughout; tightens and smooths)  (See also: MARKET, MARKET-LOSSES, MARKET-INVESTORS,
MARKET-COMMODITIES, RUSSIA-U.S.-BANKS, RUSSIA-EUROPE-IMPACT,
RUSSIA-EMERGE) 
(JT) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While global stock markets plunged, a major index of
commodity prices, on products from oil to cotton, fell to its
lowest level in 21 years Thursday. And that may be more worrisome
for investors in the long run than Thursday's 4.19 percent decline
in the Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   Each tick down in the price of oil, copper, cotton and gold puts
more economic pressure on the nations where they are produced. And
many of the major producers are the emerging-market countries
experiencing deep financial crisis, like Russia, which is a leading
exporter of oil and precious metals, or countries considered
vulnerable, like Mexico, which is also a big oil producer.
</P>
<P>
   Already, commodity prices have fallen 20 percent in the last
year and heightened concern about the economies and markets of
developing nations that began with Asian currency selloffs in the
second half of 1997. ``It's a flu, it's catching; it's dominoes,''
said William Byers, director of futures research at Bear, Stearns &AMP;
Co. ``Not only is the psychology spreading, but the economic
weakness is spreading.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's drop in commodities came as markets around the world
tumbled and Russia's economic crisis deepened. Millions of
investors, seeking to flee the turmoil, rushed to the relative
safety of U.S. Treasury securities, pushing long-term yields to
their lowest level in 30 years or more.
</P>
<P>
   For the American investor worried about the strength of the
economy, which by all current signs is still strong, and corporate
earnings, which have been weakening, so far the fall in commodity
prices and the drop in interest rates have been good news.
</P>
<P>
   The lower prices for commodities, while tough on emerging-market
and other producing nations, have lowered corporate costs here and
spurred consumer spending. And the damage that had been done to
commodity producers in the United States has not had a big impact
on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The fall in interest rates has also been positive for the
economy, by bolstering housing and capital investment. Thirty-year
mortgage rates have now been below 7 percent for more than two
months. Thursday, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond fell to
5.34 percent, the lowest for long-term yields in three decades. The
10-year note's yield, a benchmark for home mortgage rates, fell to
5.06 percent, its lowest since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   These forces have, so far, have more than offset the drag from
the Asian economic crisis, which has led to a sharp drop in demand
for American exports. And this is one reason the economy has slowed
much less than many economists expected in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   But with the global economic and market turmoil spreading from
Asia to Russia to Latin America, it appears less likely, some
analysts said, that the positives of lower interest rates and low
commodity prices would be sufficient to offset the drag from a
global economic slowdown on American corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Already, many economic forecasters who had bet on the offsetting
effect from lower commodity prices and lower interest rates have
been scaling back their economic forecasts for the second half of
the year. And a steep fall in U.S.  &QL; 
stock prices, which would dampen consumer spending, might force a
further scaling back, which would not be good for corporate
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you correct the problems'' in Asia and Russia, said
Richard Berner, chief economist of Mellon Bank in Pittsburgh, ``the
stimulus will be a minor offset.''
</P>
<P>
   The backwash from the Russian turmoil pushed the Commodity
Research Bureau/Bridge Index of 17 commodities down 1.88 points
Thursday, to 196.24, the lowest since December 1977, a year of
sharp declines in agricultural prices that led to farmer protests.
</P>
<P>
   The impact from the commodity price decline has gone beyond the
emerging economies. In Canada, a major commodity producer, the
currency dropped to another record low, forcing the central bank to
raise its benchmark interest rate a full percentage point, to 6
percent. The increase also helped send the Toronto Stock Exchange
index down more than 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Two forces have been pushing commodity prices lower and will
continue to do so, several analysts said Thursday. One is the
falling demand from Asian nations, which, for example, were major
consumers of copper for new construction. The other is that
countries in deep trouble, like Russia, are expected to sell what
they can to raise money, adding to the supply in an already weak
market.
</P>
<P>
   William O'Neill, director of futures research at Merrill Lynch,
said there had been big sales of platinum and palladium by Russia
in Japan and sales of gold and silver in Zurich and London. The
crisis, he said, ``inspires them to sell as much as possible.'' The
government controls much of the country's precious metals.
</P>
<P>
   The selling by Russia had an odd twist. Gold had been thought of
for years as refuge in the time of political and economic crises,
and a few gold bugs still hold that belief. But Thursday, the price
of gold plunged, dropping to a 19-year low on the spot market in
London at $276.55 an ounce, down $5.70.
</P>
<P>
   Commodity selling is also coming from countries like Australia
whose currency also fell to a record low Thursday. But because most
commodities are priced in dollars, the weaker Australian dollar
means that gold and other commodity sellers can reap nice profits
when the sales are translated back into Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
   This all means that commodity prices _ and the pain that they
are bringing to already troubled economies _ still have a way to go
before they hit bottom. ``I don't think we are there yet,'' Berner
of Mellon Bank said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
