</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kuchar-Garcia showdown is set
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ After two days of cruising around Oak Hill
Country Club, chopping up opponents like some smiling Lawnmower
Man, Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar finally gets thrown into some
deeper rough today in the quarterfinals of the U.S. Amateur
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Two days early, it's the marquee matchup. U.S. Amateur champion
vs. British Amateur champion. Kuchar, 20, vs. Spain's Sergio
Garcia, 18, this morning at 10:15. Two players whose total age
still falls short of 41-year-old Danny Green, whom Garcia defeated
Thursday in the third round, 3 and 2, will provide a look at Ryder
Cup matches of the near future.
</P>
<P>
   But don't blow it all out of proportion. While it's the match
that NBC began to script as soon as the brackets were published,
the winner won't necessarily be hoisting the USGA hardware Sunday
afternoon. Positioned in the other bracket is Kuchar's Tech
teammate, Bryce Molder, who also advanced to the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big match,'' said Kuchar. ``It's the quarterfinals of
the U.S. Amateur. But I don't think I'm going to let down the
United States if I don't win and I don't think he's going to let
down Spain or Europe if he doesn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty special,'' Garcia said, ``because he's the
defending champion and probably the best (amateur) golfer in the
States.''
</P>
<P>
   The two players have met only once before in an official
match-play situation, but under abbreviated and much
less-meaningful conditions. Playing in the rain-shortened Terra
Cotta Invitational in Naples, Fla., last Thanksgiving, Kuchar beat
Garcia 1-up in a 9-hole match that neither player treats too
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Molder, who plays in Kuchar's shadow but is every bit his equal,
advanced to the quarterfinals with a 4 and 3 win over Andy Miller,
son of NBC's Johnny Miller, and will face Hank Kuehne, a 3 and 1
winner over Tech's Mauricio Muniz.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta's Charles Howell, one of the favorites to make the
finals, tripped over UNLV's Bill Lunde Thursday, losing 2 and 1
because of an unfriendly putter. ``I would have been better,'' said
Howell, ``putting with my sand wedge.''
</P>
<P>
   With a tough opponent such as Garcia today,Kuchar might even get
a look at the rest of Oak Hill's superb back nine. In his three
matches thus far, Kuchar has required only 37 holes to close out
his foes. He has won 23 holes, lost only three and has not needed
to journey past the 13th hole. The Tech junior managed two 6-and-5
wins Thursday, ousting Matthew Saglio of Clearwater, Fla., in the
morning and Bert Atkinson, 40, of Charleston, S.C., in the
afternoon. Kuchar is clearly in championship form. Ever since
``something clicked'' on the driving range Sunday, he has been
striking the ball flawlessly and finding recovery shots when
needed. On the 10th hole of his first match he chipped in from 70
feet, demoralizing his opponent. Kuchar also holds a defending
champion's mental edge, fueled by the dominating play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tiger (Woods) might have had a little initimidation
advantage and I may have some of that working, too,'' Kuchar said.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly ...
</P>
<P>
   Colbert's Jedd McLuen of the College of Charleston lost 3 and 2
to Tom McKnight of the University of Virginia. ... Florida
Southern's Andy McLendon lost to Lunde, 4 and 3.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
