<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Game may be DeBerg's last chance
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Atlanta Falcons quarterback Steve DeBerg knows
tonight's final preseason game against Cincinnati might be the last
time he lines up under center. But don't look for the old man to
sweat it, at least not before he stares across the line at the
Bengals' defense.
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg, 44, is trying to resume his career after retiring in
1993 with 17 years in the NFL. He already has lived the good life
in football, so he's not as concerned about his future as some of
the other players.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Falcons must cut seven players to get to the
NFL-mandated 53. The team has spent the past several days looking
at players cut from other teams, particularly quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might be the last time I ever take a snap in a game,''
said DeBerg, who began training camp competing with Tony Graziani
to be Chris Chandler's backup. ``I'm going to enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg is expected to play the second half. He and other Falcons
on the cut bubble are expected to get a good look from the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Right tackle Corey Louchiey, for example, has to prove he's
worth his two-year, $3.5 million contract. He's battling to remain
the starter, a job that coach Dan Reeves said is Louchiey's to
lose.
</P>
<P>
   Louchiey, 26, was in no mood to talk Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to go out and play Friday, and I'll leave it at
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, six-year veteran Todd Kinchen and four-year veteran
Keith Crawford appear to be finalists for one wide receiver spot.
Juran Bolden, rookie Elijah Williams, Lenny McGill and Randy Fuller
are competing for two, maybe only one, spot at cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller, a Columbus native who played the last three seasons with
the Steelers, signed a two-year, $1.25 million contract. But he
injured an ankle and missed 17 practices and three preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm around 85 percent,'' he said. ``It's something I can't
control. This is when teammates learn who they can go into battle
with, a crucial time. It's just unfortunate I've been hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg said he has improved since a rough performance in the
Falcons' 7-3 victory at Detroit two weeks ago. He completed 6-of-11
passes for 39 yards but was slow afoot, slow to get rid of the ball
and didn't throw downfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are starting to come back,'' he said. ``I'm throwing
the ball better; my recognition is faster than it was. I'm on
schedule. Pressure? I'm just going to enjoy it. People say you
should play every game as if it's your last; I'm living it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
