<HEADER>
A6474 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES-COX     08-27 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for turnaround in turnover department
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- This is getting to be redundant, but when the Atlanta
Falcons play the Cincinnati Bengals tonight in their final
preseason game, they'll be looking for a first. The team has yet to
gain a turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta got 18 interceptions and recovered 11 opponents' fumbles
last season, but it's been a bone-dry preseason.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are the only team in the NFL that hasn't gained a
turnover, a dubious distinction they've held for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   They came close Saturday, when cornerback Michael Booker
appeared to intercept Pittsburgh's Kordell Stewart at the Steeler
7-yard line. But Booker was called for holding the receiver, a
questionable call inasmuch as he was jamming the receiver within
the allowable five yards of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Falcons (1-2) have turned the ball over five
times, three times by interceptions, and twice by fumble.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals (1-2) had three interceptions last week, as
defensive backs Ashley Ambrose, Corey Sawyer and Myron Bell had
picks in a 33-19 win over Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a big-play defense against Detroit (including six
sacks), and that's what we have to be,'' said Cincinnati coach
Bruce Coslet. ``The biggest advantage we have over last year (when
the Bengals were 7-9) is our team speed is so much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep an eye on Blake
</P>
<P>
   Falcon coaches will watch Bengals backup quarterback Jeff Blake,
whom the team might be interested in acquiring should he become
available this weekend. Blake lost the starting job to Neil
O'Donnell, and team officials are reluctant to pay his $1.95
million salary this year and $2.65 million salary next.
</P>
<P>
   Blake's agent is talking about renegotiating the player's
contract to one year, but Cincinnati officials are angling for two.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely way Atlanta might acquire the former East
Carolina standout is by signing him as a free agent if Cincinnati
releases him. The Bengals, though, are sure to try to get something
in a trade if they decide to jettison Blake at all. Although
interest in Blake is high (the Bears are said to be keenly
interested), many potential suitors will balk at his contract
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons also will watch the waiver wire Sunday, when rosters
are reduced to 53 around the league.
</P>
<P>
   Reunion time?
</P>
<P>
   Guard Doug Widell, released Tuesday by the Packers, is an
interesting player. The chances of the Falcons being interested are
slim, but it would be intriguing if he were to team up with brother
Dave, a Falcons backup center and guard.
</P>
<P>
   When the Widell brothers played together with Denver (under Dan
Reeves and Falcons general manager Harold Richardson) from
1990-'92, they were just the sixth sibling combination in NFL
history to play for the same team at the same time at the same
position (offensive line).
</P>
<P>
   Doug is one year younger than Dave, 33.
</P>
<P>
   What to look for
</P>
<P>
   Expect to see Falcons rookie linebacker Keith Brooking, the
team's first-round draft choice, on the field with the first-team
nickel defense tonight. He also will perform on multiple special
teams. ... Falcons starters may play into the third quarter
tonight, same as the Bengals. ... After giving up five sacks last
week to the Steelers and their zone-blitz defense, the Falcons
worked extra this week on blitz pickups, often focusing on making
sure a running back is available to help with outside rushes.
Cincinnati plays a very similar defense, and has 12 sacks in three
preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   Schmooze time
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons held their annual kickoff luncheon Thursday, in
connection with the Atlanta Sports Council, on the floor of the
Georgia Dome. With some 1,400 in attendance, left tackle Bob
Whitfield again stole the show. When he was being questioned in
front of the audience, Whitfield showed a lighter side rarely seen.
</P>
<P>
   Upon standing up with the microphone in hand, he said, ``Look,
I'm telling you all, I'm not going to be funny today. I'm tired of
being Bob Joker.'' But he changed tunes. Asked to critique lunch,
he said, ``What was that potato pattie thing? It was like a
sponge.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked to tell the audience something they didn't know about
Reeves, he said, ``He's got the ugliest knees in America. They look
like they got hit by a dump truck. And he's always trying to tan
them at practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Local connections
</P>
<P>
   Falcons defensive line coach Bill Kollar was a first-round
choice of the Bengals in 1974, and played there from '74-76. ...
Falcons running back Harold Green was a second-round Cincinnati
choice in '90, and after playing there through '95 is still third
on team rushing list with 3,727 yards. ... Atlanta secondary coach
Ron Meeks was a Bengals coach from '92-'96. ... Cincinnati
first-round choice Takeo Spikes, a linebacker, is from
Sandersville.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
