<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Safe at any speed?
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Driving a car at speeds as fast as 230 mph can be a
dangerous business, but in Saturday night's Atlanta Classic 500 at
Atlanta Motor Speedway, at least two drivers _ both of whom have
wrecked and suffered injuries _ would rather be on the track than
on I-75.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Boat, who drives the No. 11 Conseco/A.J. Foyt
Dallara/Aurora/Goodyear, and former Atlantan John Paul Jr., pilot
of the No. 10 Byrd/Cunningham Dallara/Aurora/Firestone agree that
going 230 mph in a crowd of professional race car drivers, in
cutting-edge machines designed to protect them in crashes, is the
way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``On I-75, you don't know the guy next to you, if he's sober or
if he has a gun,'' Boat said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed is not a problem,'' Paul agreed. ``I fully trust all the
drivers on the track.''
</P>
<P>
   And neither has to worry about an 18-wheeler in the wrong lane
tailgating a Honda.
</P>
<P>
   Speeds were promising as drivers prepared for today's qualifying
_ especially considering the track temperature for the daytime
session was 130 degrees, which has a big effect on control. Scott
Sharp had the fastest lap during daytime practice at 222.472 mph,
followed closely by Indy 500 winner Eddie Cheever at 222.062.
Paul's best, 217.446, was 14th.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, John Andretti won NASCAR's Primestar 500 pole at
AMS in March with a top speed of 192.956 mph.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Foyt decided to wait until the night practice session to
run Boat and teammate Kenny Brack.
</P>
<P>
   IRL cars are engineered to protect the driver. They are designed
to collapse and break apart, absorbing shock. However, one result
is flying debris, such as the tire that killed spectators in the
stands at Michigan Speedway during a CART race earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   It probably wouldn't have happened at AMS. General manager Ed
Clark pointed out that the safety fence that protects the
grandstands hangs over the track and is reinforced with continuous
strands of cable that would force pieces, or whole cars, back onto
the track.
</P>
<P>
   Shown a photo of the improved grandstand fence at Michigan,
Clark said, ``It looks like ours.''
</P>
<P>
   As a safety precaution, though, the first 15 rows of grandstand
seats will be empty, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Boat and Paul have made major comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   After winning at Texas, Boat suffered a broken leg and pelvis in
the next race at New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   He took only seven weeks to get back in the cockpit, won the
pole at the Radisson 200 at Pike's Peak and was running second with
a lap and a half to go when his car ran out of gas. He finished
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Boat still uses a cane, made of the same carbon fiber as the IRL
cars and light as a feather.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about wrecks and fear: ``When you grow up racing,
you're always aware there's a potential to get hurt. When you move
up, the potential will increase.''
</P>
<P>
   But Boat, 32 years old and 5-foot-7, 140 pounds of grit, did
what the great ones do, including Paul: When you get knocked down,
get back up.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I thought of was, `How can I work harder to get back?' ''
Boat said. ``I was in the gym every day, the first six weeks on
crutches.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul crushed an ankle in the 1997 Indy 500 in a head-on crash.
Nearly the same thing happened in 1983, also at Indy. The lanky
38-year-old is philosophical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a while to get your confidence back,'' Paul admitted,
yet he grinned and quipped that head-on collisions come only ``15
years apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
