<SLUG> BC-RAC-IRLNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMS general manager has eye on numbers
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Southern stock-car fans still look at open-wheeled race cars the
same way they'd regard a chukar if they ran into one on a quail
hunt: ``That's a strange lookin' bird.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans aren't flocking to Southern tracks to watch the Indy Racing
League. Yet the VisionAire 500 in Charlotte drew 50,000-plus, which
would be a good turnout for the Falcons and even the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   And Atlanta Motor Speedway general manager Ed Clark thinks
Saturday's Atlanta 500 Classic will do as well or better than the
VisionAire 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long and short of it is, We will be able to consider it a
success?'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Success, he said, would be 50,000, even though that number won't
resemble a large crowd in a grandstand that holds 60,996. When a
Winston Cup race is on the track, the stands and the infield are
filled, with a total crowd of 135,000 a good estimate.
</P>
<P>
   However, this race doesn't appear to be a one-shot deal. Clark
said the super speedways need more big races for cash flow, and
they apparently are banking on IRL.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark said he hasn't resorted to dropping free tickets from
airplanes. Fans can find discounts, but someone has paid for the
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Pep Boys, the IRL series sponsor, has a block of tickets and is
giving away pairs to customers who purchase $99 in merchandise.
Participants in the Greg LeMond bike ride for the PATH Foundation
will get a ticket. Fans also can find a $20 discount coupon off the
$50 ticket in The Atlanta Journal-Constitution sports pages.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield honorary starter
</P>
<P>
   It probably won't compare with carrying the Olympic torch, but
heavyweight champion Evander Holyfield will wave the green flag as
honorary starter for Saturday's race. ``This is another great event
for the city of Atlanta, and I'm excited about watching the first
lap from the best seat in the house,'' Holyfield said.
</P>
<P>
   ARCA pole
</P>
<P>
   Tim Steele of Coopersville, Mich., won the pole position for
tonight's ARCA Georgia Power 200. His speed of 180.621 mph was only
one mph faster than second-place Jeff Finley of Diamondville, Mich.
Rounding out the top five were Kirk Shelmerdine, winner of the
March ARCA event at AMS, Bill Baird and Andy Hillenberg. Twenty
five cars were on the track Thursday battling for the remaining 18
starting spots. ... Winner, hands-down, of ARCA nickname of the
race, Harris DeVane, the ``Cuthbert Kamikaze.''
</P>
<P>
   In the pits
</P>
<P>
   The IRL is having media events around town. On Wednesday, a
lunchtime crowd at CNN Center saw a pit-stop contest between the
Eddie Cheever team and Scott Goodyear and Panther Racing. Team
Cheever took the best-of-five contest on the fifth pit stop. The
$1,000 prize went to the Kid Stuff Foundation. ... Interesting
comparison: An L-1011 airliner weighs 349,000 pounds and lifts off
at 163 mph. An IRL race car weighs about 1,600 pounds, and no one
is sure how it stays on the ground at 230 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
