<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6477 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-LEMOND-COX     08-27 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-LEMOND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LeMond: `Racing's in my blood'
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Ask Greg LeMond what he'd like to be doing in 10
years, and he'll look you straight in the eye and say something
about fly fishing on the Smith River in central Montana. Don't you
believe him.
</P>
<P>
   LeMond loves fishing. No doubt about that. But LeMond loves
speed and competition even more. And unless he can figure out a way
to fish at 100 mph while competing against a dozen other people,
he's just not going to do it for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing's in my blood,'' LeMond says. ``I'm a very good
competitor. I hate to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that competitive drive that first attracted LeMond to
bicycle racing, where during nearly 20 years he conquered all,
winning three Tour de France competitions and two world
championships.
</P>
<P>
   A rare muscle disease forced him to retire in 1994, but LeMond's
love for speed and competition led him into a new career as a
race-car driver. He's in his second year of U.S. Formula Ford 2000
series racing, and LeMond brings his AutoConnect-sponsored
Indy-type car to Atlanta Motor Speedway for a race Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   While in Atlanta, LeMond also will give a benefit speech tonight
and lead a charity bike ride Saturday morning to benefit the PATH
foundation, which is working to expand Atlanta's network of
greenway trails.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a humbling two years for America's most famous bike
racer, a man used to competing _ and winning _ at the highest
levels.
</P>
<P>
   After a rookie 1997 year in which LeMond never placed higher
than 11th and finished the season in 24th place in a field of 53
competitors, you'd think he would be happy with two third-place and
two seventh-place finishes so far this year. Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm even more unhappy this year,'' LeMond said, bemoaning the
five times in 11 races that he's crashed. ``When I've been able to
race, I've been fairly competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   LeMond knows he still has a long climb from the minor leagues of
racing to the Indianapolis 500, his goal for the year 2000 or 2001.
</P>
<P>
   He's been here before.
</P>
<P>
   As a youngster, he started riding a bike with his father. By age
16 in 1977 he began dominating national junior races. Two years
later, LeMond captured the Junior World Championship road race
title.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it was a dizzying climb to the top: member of the
1980 Olympic squad that did not compete because of the U.S.
boycott; world champion in the 1983 road race; third-place finish
in the 1984 Tour De France, his first attempt at the world's
best-known and toughest bicycle race. LeMond reached the pinnacle
in 1986, when he fought off Bernard Hinault to win the Tour de
France, the first American to do so. But in 1987, LeMond's
brother-in-law accidentally shot him while they hunted turkey in
California. LeMond nearly bled to death and then faced a long and
painful recovery from surgery to remove shotgun pellets from his
liver, kidney and intestines. To this day, he still carries about
30 pellets in his body, some near his heart. Later that year,
LeMond had to undergo an emergency appendectomy.LeMond came back in
1989 to secure his place in sports history by winning his second
Tour de France, a victory he clinched on the last day of the
three-week race by beating Frenchman Laurent Fignon by eight
seconds, the smallest margin of victory in Tour history. That feat
earned LeMond the Sports Illustrated 1989 Sportsman of the Year
award.
</P>
<P>
   LeMond captured his third Tour in 1990 but then started an
inexplicable and frustrating slide. He struggled to a seventh-place
finish in the 1991 race and then failed to complete the 1992 Tour
and did not even start in 1993. In 1994, he again failed to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically,'' LeMond said, ``I did everything I could to
survive the last couple of years of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   After countless visits to doctors, no one could figure out why
LeMond was fading so fast. Finally, a biopsy of a leg muscle in
1994 provided the answer: mitochondrial myopathy, a rare genetic
disease that prevents the body from recovering adequately after
stress. His career was over.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, some friends persuaded LeMond to enroll in Jim
Russell's Racing School in California. Within a half-hour of
strapping into the cockpit and whizzing around the course at 150
mph, he was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I did it,'' LeMond said, ``I realized I love speed.
That's why I got into bike racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he turned pro, racing under the sponsorship of
Manheim Auctions, a subsidiary of Cox Enterprises, which also owns
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. This year, his sponsorship was
picked up by AutoConnect, a Manheim subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel happy about my driving,'' LeMond said. ``It's pretty
consistent. But I've had problems with my qualifying times.''
</P>
<P>
   He likens the learning curve he's going through to his first
three or four years of bike racing. But he realizes that at 37 he
doesn't have many more years to break through. And he's got a wife
and three children to think of.
</P>
<P>
   ``In car racing,'' he said, ``you don't have a long life unless
you make improvements. It costs a lot of money. And I'm not one to
stay in a sport where I'm in the middle of the pack.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, LeMond is back where he thrives _ in the thick
of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having the kind of life I'd like to,'' he said. ``The only
thing I wish I could do is a little more fishing. Now that I'm so
busy, I dream of that. But when I was bike racing, I would dream of
that. I may be always fantasizing about what I can't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wish I had more free time. I like doing things in
life. I like trying new things. I'm a high-energy person who likes
doing different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Different things that go fast. Against some other guy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
