<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYAL GRADUATE MIGHT GET FIRST COLLEGE START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ USC freshman defensive end Ryan Nielsen of
Royal High in Simi Valley could get his first college start Sunday
when the Trojans play Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   An ankle injury has limited starter Lawrence Larry's
availability and USC coach Paul Hackett has not decided if he'll be
healthy enough to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coming along slowly, but (the trainers) are encouraged
he'll be OK for the game,'' Hackett said. ``I don't know if he'll
start.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said Nielsen would probably replace Larry in the lineup,
although he might also go with sophomore Shamsud-Din Abdul-Shaheed.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Mark Cusano said Thursday that he doesn't expect to
start because his pulled hamstring is only 90 percent recovered,
but he will play. Fullback Marvin Powell is also expected to be
available, although he remains bothered by a sore knee.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fletcher's fine: Former Alemany High tailback Miguel Fletcher
has survived his first training camp nicely and he probably
deserves some courage points for telling Hackett he wanted to
remain at tailback even though a position change was pondered.
</P>
<P>
   At least four other players, including quarterbacks Quincy Woods
and John Fox, have switched positions during camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that I made a statement to the coach,'' Fletcher said.
``He said I could play whatever I wanted, and I said I want to stay
a tailback. I knew I could play tailback. Now I just have something
to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher, who will probably redshirt, is working out with the
scout team this week.
</P>
<P>
   __ Crowd count: USC officials are anticipating a crowd of
55,000-60,000 for the Pigskin Classic.
</P>
<P>
   __ Taking it easy: Hackett has tapered practices considerably,
working just 90 minutes the past two days after holding a pair of
three-hour practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be sure we're not going to burn them out,'' he said.
``We worked them very hard when we were down here and we don't want
to mess things up.''
</P>
<P>
   __ All-around athlete: Who's the best athlete on the football
team? Probably safety Ife Ohalete, who won the team's home run
hitting contest and bowling competition Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ohalete outslugged quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst and offensive
lineman Zach Wilson to win the home run derby. He then bowled a 186
to capture that title. Offensive lineman Brent McCaffrey finished
last by bowling a 36.
</P>
<P>
   __ Where's the weight room?: USC's players got a break from
lifting weights on Thursday. The weight equipment was transported
back to Los Angeles, leaving just an empty tent next to the
practice field.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans officially break camp this morning and head back to
Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
