<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Behind Moscow's Drubbing of America's Stock Markets   By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
To Russia, with love.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market got whacked yesterday like a Moscow mobster, as
the Dow Jones industrial average plunged 4.2 percent and the Nasdaq
stock market fell 4.6 percent. We've seen the market take some
terrible tumbles before, but yesterday's hit was a bloody mess.
Fifteen companies reported 52-week highs while 998 firms hit annual
lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was really ugly. There was capitulation and there was
panic,'' says Paul Siegal, president of Hollis Capital Management,
a private investment partnership that manages about $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   The market meltdown was blamed in part on a currency shortage in
Russia. Why a former world power's dilapidated economy would take
the Dow out at its knees, I have no idea. But the financial
community is always looking for a culprit, even if the real factors
behind market swings are far more complex than a single day's
geopolitical machinations. Which is probably the case here.
Besides, Asia's bad-guy role in the recent turbulence was getting
too predictable.
</P>
<P>
   So this time it was Russia's turn. The long and short of it is
that the Russian government is broke. Now that's not
earth-shattering news. But the government has only $17 billion in
reserves to pay off foreign debt. And the trouble is that it has to
make payments of $30 billion in short-term loans in the near
future, says senior portfolio manager Josephine Jimenez of
Montgomery Asset Management in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Greenbacks are nearly impossible to come by in Russia because
the country doesn't have enough U.S. dollars to cover its debts.
Consequently, the government-controlled central bank stopped
selling dollars for the second day in a row yesterday, making it
nearly impossible to determine the value of the country's currency,
the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   When you don't know how much your money is worth, it's pretty
hard to tell if and when you can pay back your debts. This isn't
great news for the world's financial institutions who have lent
money to companies in the former Soviet bloc, including American
banks, says Jimenez, whose fund invests in emerging markets
including Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it good news for American companies that sell goods and
services to Russia. If they don't get paid, their earnings go down.
And if their profits are already hindered because Asian customers
can't pay, then their foreign profits are socked by a double
whammy.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, naturally, if Coca-Cola's profits sink, its stock is
likely to do the same. (Coke stock closed yesterday at $74.75, down
$4.44.)
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies a connection to the U.S. stock market. Not to
mention that a financial meltdown in a nation that possesses
nuclear warheads is also generally upsetting.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, because European stocks have been one of the better
performers this year, their exposure to Russia makes them less
attractive, says Jimenez, whose firm has $1.6 billion invested in
emerging markets but only 1 percent in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe has been one of the brighter spots in the world
economy, and that's where geopolitics comes into play'' regarding
equities markets, Jimenez says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all of the attention placed on Moscow, there are a
lot of reasons why the market is letting off steam. It has been
overpriced. Japanese banks are drowning in nonperforming loans. And
deflation is making it difficult for companies to raise their
prices and earn higher profits.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, these factors have been chipping away at the
strength of the market for some time, says portfolio manager Eric
Flett of Gemmer Asset Management in Walnut Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``The damage had already been done and it started in July,''
says Flett, whose firm manages about $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow is down 12.5 percent from its record high of 9,337.9 on
July 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``So yesterday's 4 percent decline is a drop in the bucket,''
Flett says.
</P>
<P>
   So what are investors to do when it looks like the market is
sinking faster than Leonardo DiCaprio?
</P>
<P>
   You know the mantra. Sit tight, for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good example of where you don't want to sell into a
downdraft,'' says investment adviser Robert Bingham, principal of
Bingham, Osborn &AMP; Scarborough in San Francisco, which manages $425
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors should wait for the volatility to decrease and then
reassess your portfolio,'' Bingham says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But do not react immediately to the panic-driven (sell-off).''
</P>
<P>
   And when you do decide to take action, don't do anything
drastic. If you happen to be so deep into stocks that you can't
sleep at night, you may want to convert some of those holdings into
bonds or cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't time the market, but you can create a cushion`` by
increasing your allocation of fixed-income investments, Bingham
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have these really steep downturns, you'll find there
really are no safe havens,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
