<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Workers To Average 4% Raises   By Ilana DeBare  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
California employees will get raises that average 4 percent this
year _ about the same as in 1997, according to a report released
yesterday by William M. Mercer Inc.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But that 4-percent average masks a growing disparity in raises
and compensation within the state's workforce.
</P>
<P>
   A small minority of very skilled workers will get raises as high
as 50 percent this year, while most California employees will
receive minimal or no pay increases, according to Mercer analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you take that 4 percent average and divvy it up, you're
looking at companies giving most of their employees small increases
or no increases in order to give more to their high performers,''
said Charles King, a senior compensation consultant with Mercer's
San Francisco office.
</P>
<P>
   Mercer _ a nationwide human resources management consulting firm
_ based its 16th annual survey of California compensation trends on
data from 232 large companies such as Bank of America, Chevron and
PG&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   The companies indicated that they plan to give somewhat bigger
raises to high-level employees than to low-level ones. They've
budgeted for raises averaging 4.2 percent for executives, 4 percent
for exempt employees, and 3.9 percent for nonexempt, nonunion
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Mercer analysts said the data show that, despite the current low
unemployment rate, companies are managing to avoid major wage
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay is moving up at about the same level it has for the past
seven or eight years,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   To keep labor costs down, a growing number of companies are
adopting one-time rewards like bonuses that don't become a built-in
part of employees' wage base.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are also increasingly trying to link workers' pay to
their performance.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-four percent of companies said they see merit and
performance as ``very important'' factors in raises, while only 5
percent see the cost of living as very important.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not seeing across-the-board increases like in the
1970s,'' King said. ``The biggest raises are going to employees
whose jobs require specialized or technical knowledge, from
software engineers to attorneys, accountants and human resource
analysts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you add up the impact of (noncash benefits like) stock,
this bipolar compensation model becomes even more dramatic,'' King
added. ``The winners win bigger and bigger, while the losers lose
more and more ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies surveyed were generally optimistic about the
economy and their hiring plans. About half said they plan to add
employees this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the survey was taken between March and May. Since then, a
growing number of companies have reported earnings drops due to
economic problems in Asia and Russia. Some, like Applied Materials,
have imposed layoffs and pay cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have data showing that companies are revising their
compensation budgets down for '98, but they may well be revising
them down for '99,'' King warned.
</P>
<P>
   Along with pay, the Mercer report tracked the different kinds of
benefits offered by California firms.
</P>
<P>
   Among noncash benefits, the fastest-growing single item was
health coverage for employees' domestic partners. Eleven percent of
firms said they had added domestic partner coverage within the past
year. That brought the total share of firms offering domestic
partner coverage to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other fast-growing benefits included individual and group
incentive pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individual incentive pay'' refers to a one-time reward or
bonus based on the performance of an individual employee.
Sixty-four percent of firms offer this to their nonexecutive
employees, including 7 percent who just started offering it within
the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Group incentive pay'' refers to a one-time reward based on the
performance of a work group or team. Thirty-three percent of firms
now offer this, including 5 percent who just started offering it
within the past year.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
