r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     08-27 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEASE, YOUR HONOR, HALT DAVIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Judge Joe Brown? Los Angeles here.
</P>
<P>
   I stand before you, Your Honor, because I'm being stalked by a
man who usually dresses in all white but is never going to be
mistaken for an angel. I'm beseeching you for a restraining order
against this person who has a dark side to match the moon's.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a coincidence that his followers all wear black. I
don't want him within 300 miles of my city limits.
</P>
<P>
   Please help deliver me from the clutches of Al Davis.
</P>
<P>
   You grew up in South Central, so I trust you know our history.
Al and I were close once, that I freely admit. I adored the man and
his band of renegades when he turned to me in 1982 on the rebound
after his relationship with Oakland ended acrimoniously.
</P>
<P>
   He and his football team appealed to my wilder nature. The
Raiders pilloried politeness and pretension. They brought out the
rogue in me. The chrome-and-leather scene was titillating at first,
never more so than during the Raiders' Super Bowl championship
season of 1983. But after a while the goose bumps gave way to
gashes.
</P>
<P>
   The scene turned bad and my reputation took a beating with every
new fracas that broke out in my backyard during Raiders home games.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, it was even worse. I grew so weary of Al's
bullying. He has this compulsion to control. Lest you think I'm
exaggerating, read Marcus Allen's autobiography. Allen was a
running back with the Raiders for 11 years until he escaped to
Kansas City as a free agent after the 1993 season.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Al was gone. He was lured back to Oakland by
the almighty dollar, much to my relief. I wished him good riddance
and was hopeful I had seen the last of him. But now he's making
explicit threats to return.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what exactly he's angling for. I just know he'll
make my life miserable. Honestly, I've been a wreck ever since I
heard he asked the NFL to buy out the dozen years remaining on his
lease in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   If Al leaves Oakland in the lurch, I have no illusions as to
where he'll wind up. It won't be Houston, it won't be Toronto.
It'll be my doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   He acts like he owns me, which is so insulting. The arrogance of
the man is astonishing. Why can't he see there's nothing left of
our relationship to salvage?
</P>
<P>
   I'm so over him. I don't miss his power trips and his
high-maintenance personality.
</P>
<P>
   He's like those other stalkers I've read about who have
delusions that the object of their fixation is in love with them.
An erotomaniac, that's what Al is. People like him take the tiniest
of cues and interpret them to mean the object of their attention is
in love with them. Fine, but if Al thinks a city councilman's
clumsy overtures are a sign of my devotion, he's sadly misguided.
Nate Holden has a voice, but he doesn't speak for me.
</P>
<P>
   I say Al needs his counsel, Joseph Alioto, less than he does
counseling. Only a deluded man would talk as though he left me
three years ago against his will, that league officials sabotaged
his designs on Hollywood Park and, in doing so, forced him out.
</P>
<P>
   For once I wish someone else's will would be done. I don't want
him in my life any more than the other NFL owners do.
</P>
<P>
   This has nothing to do with the fact his sorry team won only
four games last year. The simple truth is, I don't need pro
football to elevate my self-image or fill my leisure time. Unlike
Al, I have many interests, and I'm blessed with the ideal climate
with which to pursue all my hobbies. With the mountains, the sea,
the arts and entertainment such as the Lakers, Clippers and Kings
all at my fingertips, what need do I have for another diversion?
</P>
<P>
   Al doesn't see it that way, of course. He stares right through
me and sees the gateway to the entertainment world and its
corridors of power and a corporate climate that is raining dollars
and a population that's larger than all but seven states.
</P>
<P>
   He can covet me 'till the bikers come home, but he'll never
possess me. If I have to, I'll follow the lead of the former
Raiders assistant coach who decided to put a hex on Al. He wet a
photograph of Al and placed it in the freezer. That was in the fall
of 1995. I'd say the curse has worked pretty well to this point.
But frankly, I'd rather have the vernacular of the law on my side
than voodoo.
</P>
<P>
   So, what do you say, Your Honor, can I have that restraining
order now?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
