<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-EXPLOSION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKET EXPLOSION A BLOW TO BOEING'S SATELLITE LAUNCH BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The explosion of The Boeing Co.'s new Delta III rocket on its
maiden flight Wednesday night is a blow to the U.S. hopes of
wresting more of the commercial satellite launch business from the
French, Chinese and Russians.
</P>
<P>
   And although the direct financial impact on Boeing is likely to
be minimal, the company lost an opportunity to grab early market
share in this increasingly important segment of the space business,
industry experts said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The failure could push the Delta III program back by as much as
six months or more, depending on how quickly an accident
investigation team is able to pinpoint what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing could have really done some damage to Arianespace and
they have missed out on that for now,'' said Marco Caceres, a
rocket and space analysts with the Teal Group, a marketing analysis
firm in Fairfx, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to believe the Europeans are very happy right now
....''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing was hoping to increase its share of the commercial
launch market. This puts everything on hold. It prevents them from
leaping ahead and taking an early market share.''
</P>
<P>
   In a market once dominated by the U.S., the French company
Arianespace now launches more than half the world's communications
satellites _ a business that in a few years is expected to be worth
upwards of $20 billion annually. U.S. companies have about 30
percent of the market with the rest divided between Russia and
China.
</P>
<P>
   Once it proved itself as a reliable launch vehicle, Delta III
was expected to bring a good chunk of the commercial business back
to the U.S., and to Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   But about 55 seconds after lifting off from launch complex 17B
at Cape Canaveral Wednesday evening, the first Delta III began to
veer out of control and a range safety officer pushed a button that
sent an electronic signal to blow up the rocket. By the time the
signal was sent, the 128-foot rocket was already breaking up at an
altitude of about 10 miles. Flaming pieces of the rocket and its
$200 million-plus communications satellite fell into the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Gale Schluter, the vice president of Boeing's expendable launch
systems in Huntington Beach, Calif., where the Delta rockets are
built, said the company considers the Delta III failure ``to be
very serious to our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Quan, an experienced Boeing engineer at Huntington
Beach, was named to lead the accident investigation team. The Air
Force will also participate and the investigation will be monitored
by the Federal Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Quan nor other Boeing officials involved in the Delta
III program were available for comment, but Quan will take
questions about the accident during a teleconference with the media
this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, off Cape Canaveral Thursday, aircraft searched for
floating pieces of the rocket that could help investigators. While
there are no current plans for underwater salvage, the
investigation team will assess that need as more information
becomes available, a Boeing spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   At an early morning news conference Thursday, Brig. Gen. Randall
Starbuck, commander of the 45th Space Wing at Patrick AFB in
Florida, said the flight appeared to be going as expected until the
rocket pitched out of control between 55 and 65 seconds into the
flight.
</P>
<P>
   At 75 seconds, the Air Force sent a destruct signal to the Delta
III. It is not clear if the rocket's self-destruct system had
already been activated by then, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators don't know why the rocket went out of control,
Starbuck said.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks ago, an Air Force Titan 4A built by Lockheed
Martin and carrying a $1 billion spy satellite blew up 40 seconds
after launch from Cape Canaveral.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being punched in the belly,'' Starbuck said of the
back to back launch failures.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the Titan explosion has not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the Delta III accident investigators are certain to
focus on are the 9 solid rocket motors that strap to the sides of
the first stage and help the main engine during the early stages of
flight. Any problem with one of those rockets could have thrown the
vehicle out of control, rocket experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The first stage engine of the Delta II and Delta III are built
by Boeing's Rocketdyne and are nearly identical. The engine is
considered very reliable. But the strap-on solid rockets for Delta
III are new and unproven. They are more powerful than the ones used
on Delta II.
</P>
<P>
   Six of those rockets fire at liftoff and are thrust-vectoring,
meaning the rocket nozzles can be moved to provide additional
control. This is something new for Delta III because it is heavier
than Delta II and needs more control capability than just the main
engine.
</P>
<P>
   The three remaining solid rockets fire at 79 seconds into
flight.
</P>
<P>
   Although cameras at the Cape that tracked the Delta III appeared
to show the solid rockets peeling away moments before the
explosion, that apparently was not the case.
</P>
<P>
   The first set of three solid rockets do not break away from the
first stage until 80.5 seconds into the flight.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rupture in one of the strap-on rockets that resulted in
the explosion of a Delta II 12 seconds after liftoff from Cape
Canaveral in January 1997. That was the last failure of one of
Boeing's Delta rockets, which the company acquired when it bought
McDonnell Douglas last year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said a decision has not been made whether to postpone
next Tuesday's launch of a Delta II from Vandenberg Air Force Base
in California. It will carry several satellites for Motorola's
Iridium worldwide mobile phone network.
</P>
<P>
   And NASA plans to use Delta II rockets to launch its Deep Space
1 technology test bed spacecraft and two probes to Mars in December
and January.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency will closely monitor the progress of Delta III
investigation to determine the possible effect on its upcoming
missions, a NASA spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The accident had little effect on Boeing's stock Thursday. On a
day when the market fell more than 350 points, Boeing's stock fell
less than $1 a share to close at $35.
</P>
<P>
   But the stock of PanAmSat Corp. fell 15 percent after the
company told analysts the loss of its Galaxy X communications
satellite carried by Delta III will mean a loss of about $200
million in revenue this year. The company planned to lease the
satellite to television broadcasters and companies such as MCI.
</P>
<P>
   PanAmSat spokesman Dan Marcus said the satellite was fully
insured. The company contracted with Hughes to build the satellite
and find a launch provider, in this case Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   The Delta III also was insured. That is standard practice in the
risky launch business.
</P>
<P>
   Delta III is the first large launch vehicle ever built entirely
with corporate rather than government money.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing needs Delta III to better compete in the exploding
commercial launch business, in which more powerful rockets are
needed to launch heavy communications satellites into orbits high
above the Earth. Most of that heavy-lift commercial launch business
now goes to France, China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The new Delta III can launch payloads twice as heavy as the
existing Delta II rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has said it is charging customers about $85 million to
launch their satellites on its Delta III, though some industry
analysts believe the actual figure is closer to about $55 million
so Boeing can stay competitive with the French.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has not said how much the three-year Delta III
development project cost, but it was probably at least $1.5
billion, according to Caceres, the rocket and space analyst.
</P>
<P>
   That's how much Hughes agreed to pay then McDonnell Douglas in
1995 to launch a block of 10 satellites, with options to launch 10
more _ the first of which was the Galaxy X. Using that $1.5 billion
commitment from Hughes, Boeing raised other private capitol to
build the more powerful Delta III which would be needed for the
heavier satellite missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That $1.5 billion was probably a good chunk of the development
costs, but I'm not sure of the total amount,'' Caceres said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing had planned a second Delta III launch later this year,
but that will not take place until investigators have learned what
went wrong Wednesday night and the problem is fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Caceres said that even though Delta II has an excellent record,
he was not all that surprised the first Delta III blew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a trend you will see over the next five years as new
launch vehicles are introduced,'' he said. ``Almost every new
launch vehicle in the last few years has failed the first time
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Those first-launch failures include the new Ariane 5 built by
Arianespace. It is far more powerful than the Delta III.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a high risk business,'' Caceres said. ``You are
putting your vehicles out there in front of everyone and if it
blows up, you look real bad.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly what Boeing did not need after suffering
through one of its worst years ever in 1997 because of the highly
publicized production problems with its core product _ commercial
airplanes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
