<SLUG> BC-INTELSIDE1-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Intel Lab Spotlights Association With Microsoft   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Hillsboro, Ore. 
 
The Intel Architecture Labs showcase something beyond cool
technology: the chip giant's love/hate relationship with its main
partner in the personal computer business, software giant
Microsoft.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We work very closely with Microsoft, though we don't always
see things the same way,'' said Craig Kinnie, an Intel vice
president and the director of the labs.
</P>
<P>
   One of those disagreements may mushroom into a factor in the
federal government's antitrust case against Microsoft, according to
reports made public this week.
</P>
<P>
   A dispute erupted several years ago when ``Intel was concerned
that Microsoft wasn't doing enough with multimedia,'' said Linley
Gwennap, editor of Microprocessor Report, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Intel launched its own multimedia initiative at the Oregon lab.
The New York Times reported this week that Microsoft's effort to
squelch Intel's multimedia work is now under scrutiny in the
Justice Department's antitrust case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Intel representatives wouldn't talk about those reports, other
than to confirm that the company has complied with Department of
Justice requests for information.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier interviews, Kinnie said Intel steers clear of
anything that would directly compete with Microsoft's operating
system. Instead, Kinnie said, Intel develops ``technology building
blocks'' that Microsoft incorporates into its operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Intel labs have developed 15 key technologies that are part
of Windows 98, including the application launch accelerator, the
universal serial bus, DVD software and WebTV for Windows, through
which users can watch television over their PC.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  A Microsoft spokesman yesterday said the two companies'
overall relationship remains close. ``We're two independent
companies involved in developing and innovating some very
fast-moving technology,'' said Jim Cullinan. ``When it comes to the
bottom line, we work together as partners to make things easier to
understand. There may be disagreement at times over the
17-year-relationship,'' but the companies generally get along, and
neither one pushes the other around, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel and Microsoft ``have some areas where their interests
overlap and line up, and other areas where they're clearly at cross
purposes,'' said Nathan Brookwood, a chip analyst at Dataquest in
San Jose. ``All in all, the companies share the mantle of
leadership pretty effectively. You see little power struggles here
and there, but they're still locked in a highly symbiotic
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies also differ in their approach to their own
research labs. While Intel's labs stay focused on product
development, Microsoft maintains a research effort that looks far
into the future. Part of that effort includes a nine-person lab in
San Francisco's South of Market neighborhood, headed by computer
industry legends Jim Gray and Gordon Bell.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of Microsoft's research takes place at the
corporation's Redmond, Wash., campus. Former Carnegie Mellon
University professor Rick Rashid, who brought an academic
perspective, leads a team of 300 researchers, expected to double by
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which is headquartered in Santa Clara and had revenues of
$25 billion last year, now employs 500 people in its research labs.
Most of them work in Hillsboro, although about 50 are in California
and Arizona.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-27-98 2300EDT &QL; 
