<SLUG> BC-INTELSIDE2-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Silicon Valley Giant Intel Is Even Bigger in Oregon   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
 Hillsboro, Ore.  
 
Intel is known as a paranoid company, but that's not a new
phenomenon. It was a fear of earthquakes more than 20 years ago
that led Intel to establish its first factory outside of Silicon
Valley, here in a former Oregon cow pasture.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keith Thomson, who was one of the first 100 people hired at
Intel 30 years ago, flew up to Oregon in 1976 at the behest of
Gordon Moore, Intel's chief executive at the time. Someone at
Tektronix, an Oregon electronics manufacturer, had recommended the
state to Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson and a colleague asked a real estate agent, ``Show us
what you have in 30-acre sites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed us two,'' Thomson recalled. ``Everybody was nice.
Tektronix was there. Gordon said, `Let's build there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Today, of course, site selection is ``a huge, involved
process,'' Thomson said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson, 58, retired this month as Intel vice president and
Oregon site manager. Jim B. Johnson is taking his place.
</P>
<P>
   The first facility, Fab 4 _ so named because it was the
company's fourth fabrication plant _ is also entering into its own
retirement after years of upgrades. It's being rehabbed into office
space, and Intel is donating the outdated semiconductor process
equipment to community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Intel runs six major campuses in Oregon, most named for the
former farms they now occupy, and employs 11,000 people there. Not
only is it the largest private employer in the state, but it
employs more people in Oregon than it does anywhere else in the
world _ more than at its Santa Clara headquarters, where 9,000
people work.
</P>
<P>
   So many Intel employees are on the Alaska Airlines early morning
flights between Portland and San Jose that the plane is known as
the ``Nerd Bird.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel occupies 4.2 million square feet in the valley west of
Portland and owns more than 425 acres, with more than enough room
for expansion, Thomson said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel operates two fabs in Oregon, and its Hillsboro facilities
have developed some of the chip giant's most cutting-edge
technology, including the Pentium II microprocessor that now
dominates the personal computing world.
</P>
<P>
   The Hillsboro facilities also handle all design and development
of Intel motherboards and networking cards, as well as many other
facets of chip design.
</P>
<P>
   The chip industry employs one-fourth of Oregon's 70,000
high-tech workers, according to Jim Craven, government affairs
manager for the Oregon Council of the American Engineering
Association. It exports more than $6 billion a year, he said, even
more than the state's vaunted timber industry.
</P>
<P>
   But companies like Hewlett-Packard, LSI Logic, Hyundai and NEC
that have followed Intel to Oregon have changed the landscape.
Traffic now backs up along Highway 26, the Sunset Highway that
leads to Hillsboro.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I graduated from school in 1937, there were 18 of us,''
said Lee Haverstick, 76, a retired mechanic sipping a beer in the
funky Helvetia Tavern three miles from Hillsboro. ``It was all
farmland. It's changed quite a bit since we got Intel and
everybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
