   (NYT11) HUDSON, N.Y. -- Aug. 27, 1998 -- NY-ARTISTS-HOUSES-1,
8-27 -- The magical, magnificent Olana, a Victorian-Moorish fantasy
perched high above the Hudson River, home of the landscape painter
Frederic Edwin Church. Artists homes provide valuable insights into
their inhabitants' quirks, sensibilities and achievements, and
illuminates as well the architecture, taste and living conditions
of their time. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) CAROLINA BEACH, N.C. -- Aug. 27, 1998 --
HURRICANE-BONNIE, 8-27 -- The sign for Atlanta Ave. is just one of
the victims of Hurricane Bonnie. Bonnie was downgraded to a
tropical storm Wednesday as it dragged itself across eastern North
Carolina, pouring up to 10 inches of rain on parts of the coastal
plain. This town suffered suffered some flooding, erosion and
structural damage. (Tyler Hicks/Wilmington Star-News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Aug. 27, 1998 -- GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS, 8-27 --
Grapevines can live hundreds of years, and if there's any variety
that can withstand neglect, it's the Concord grape. These vines in
Carol Stocker's backyard were sprawling on the ground amid with
trunks that were 3 inches thick when she first move into her
home.(Joanne Rathe/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
