<DOCNO> NYT19980827.0535 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6608 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-GIRL-SLAIN-640(2TA     08-27 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-GIRL-SLAIN-640(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J., N.Y.)  
 KILLING SHOWS CONNECTICUT THE LIMITS OF ITS `MEGAN'S LAW' 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIMANTIC, Conn. _ When the Connecticut legislature joined a
national bandwagon and passed a ``Megan's Law'' to notify citizens
about convicted sex offenders who move into their neighborhoods,
lawmakers said they were giving parents a way to know when their
children could be in danger.
</P>
<P>
   But now an 11-year-old papergirl is dead, and a neighbor _ a
convicted sex offender _ has been charged with capital murder.
Bitter parents are complaining that the notification law has failed
them, and lawmakers of both parties are pledging to go back to work
next winter to make the law even stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``A law on the books is a beginning, not an end,'' said state
Sen. Kevin Sullivan, a Democrat who is the president pro tempore.
``People have to be aware of it, police departments have to be
aggressive, and we in the legislature learn the strengths and
weaknesses in the application. This is a terrible way to learn that
you need to do something more.''
</P>
<P>
   In most of the states that have passed versions of the
notification law, including New York and New Jersey, the police
send fliers or registered letters to the neighbors of sex offenders
who are considered likely to act again. But in Connecticut and 14
other states, citizens have to ask the local police for the
information instead of being told.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Willimantic, a blue-collar town of 15,000 in
northeastern Connecticut, the police have a thick black binder with
information about all the registered sex offenders in the area. But
the fat packets of information are sorted alphabetically, not by
address, making it cumbersome to check any particular area. In any
case, Police Chief Milton King said only two people in three years
had ever looked at the list.
</P>
<P>
   After the Aug. 13 killing of the paper carrier, Angelica
Padilla, several residents realized the value of the information
and asked to see it. But King suddenly closed the book, saying that
the sex offenders were now suspects in the case and that the
release of the information could harm his investigation.
</P>
<P>
   So for the 13 days from the killing until the arrest of Jose
Torres, 25, on Wednesday night, parents had no way to narrow their
suspicions, and many kept their children indoors.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the neighbors had been able to look at the list,
Torres might have escaped their notice. The address he had listed
was out of date and more than a mile from where he was living at
the time Angelica was killed. And King said the law was too vague
to force Torres to update his address.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Grahn, 51, who lives one floor below the apartment of
Torres, said she knew all about the notification law but assumed
that the authorities would notify her if she was in danger. ``Isn't
that common sense?'' But Ms. Grahn, a deli supervisor, said she saw
other practical problems with the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had known this type of person _ and I use that loosely _
was in the building, I would move,'' she said. ``But that's not
fair to me. I can see how this brings out vigilantes.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, concerns about vigilante attacks arose earlier this
summer after some a someone in Linden, N.J., fired shots into a
house of a paroled rapist shortly after officials circulated a
flier notifying neighbors that the man had moved into their town.
</P>
<P>
   The police said that Angelica disappeared while delivering
copies of the local newspaper, The Chronicle, around the apartment
complex where she and Torres lived. Her body was discovered later
that night.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say she was attacked in the basement laundry room of
Torres' building. She was struck on the head with a wrench, her
shorts were stripped off and she was dragged 100 feet into the
woods, where she was ``virtually decapitated,'' said the Windham
County state attorney, Mark Solak.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Torres lived with his girlfriend in the same apartment complex
as Angelica and her mother, who lived a few buildings away. He was
living in Willimantic when he was charged in 1996 with seven counts
stemming from an attack on a local woman, including first-degree
sexual assault, burglary and risking injury to a minor. He pleaded
guilty to third-degree sexual assault and unlawful restraint and
served about a year in prison before being released in February
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Torres made a 10-minute appearance Thursday morning in
Connecticut Superior Court in Putnam, where Judge Samuel Sferrazza
set bail at $1 million. An interpreter translated the proceedings
into Spanish for Torres, who said nothing and never looked at the
front bench.
</P>
<P>
   There he would have seen seven of Angelica's relatives _
including her mother, Millie Mercado _ holding hands and wearing
matching white T-shirts bearing a color silk-screen print of their
11-year-old ``angel,'' framed by a black border. Each wore a ribbon
of green, her favorite color.
</P>
<P>
   During the more than 90 minutes they had to wait past the
announced time for the court session, they cradled photos of
Angelica, told stories and alternately laughed, snuffled and cried.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could have prepared them for the gruesome description of
the crime that the prosecutor, Solak, gave while the judge
considered bond. Although investigators have not concluded whether
Angelica was sexually abused, Solak said the crime was ``sexually
motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The evidence suggests this little girl was literally
butchered in the way that a rural farmer butchers a pig.''
</P>
<P>
   The killing has prompted an outpouring of fury and alarm among
the town's residents. For days before his arrest, the Connecticut
police had staked out Torres' apartment. On Wednesday evening,
after the police announced that that they had solved the case,
about 500 people gathered at the apartment complex to await his
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   When he was brought out at 8:40 p.m., the crowd cheered the
police and swore at the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-nine states _ all but New Mexico _ have some type of
community notification law, requiring the registration of sex
offenders and authorizing release of the information to people who
could be affected. Most of them have active notification systems
like that of New Jersey, which passed the first such law in 1994,
after the rape and strangulation of 7-year-old Megan Kanka.
</P>
<P>
   J. Todd Mitchell, the manager of governmental affairs for the
National Center for Missing and Exploited Children, said the
killing pointed to the need for even stronger notification laws.
``No law is going to protect a child,'' he said. ``But by
strengthening these laws, we want to arm parents with information
that will let them warn their children not to go near this house or
that car or individual.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Connecticut, the states with more passive
versions of such laws are: Alaska, Colorado, Hawaii, Idaho, Kansas,
Michigan, Mississippi, Missouri, North Carolina, North Dakota,
South Carolina, South Dakota, Utah and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials in several Connecticut towns said they rarely
received requests to look at their registries of sex offenders,
although a Greenwich official said he had received occasional
inquiries from people considering buying a home in a certain
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the residents who have complained about the law
since Angelica's death, the police have their own concerns.
Sergeant Joseph May of the Norwich Police Department, about 15
miles from Willimantic, said officials have trouble keeping up with
the offenders' current addresses. ``You almost have to trust the
honesty of the individual released from prison,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several Connecticut police chiefs said they planned to lobby the
Legislature to tighten the rules about updating the addresses of
convicted offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Already, several proposals are being floated for this winter's
session. Rep. Angelo Fusco, an assistant Republican leader in the
House of Representatives, has proposed a requirement that the
police notify all residents within half of a mile of a convicted
sex offender.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Connecticut's approach say it is more sensitive to
the civil liberties of recovering sex offenders and prevents
unnecessary panic. But Fusco said Angelica's case was almost sure
to build support for tougher provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Even 24 hours after the arrest, emotions here had not ebbed.
Elaine Beckner and her 14-year-old son drove 30 miles from their
home in Willimantic to see Torres arraigned in Putnam. ``Killer!''
Ms. Beckner, 39, screamed as he was driven away in a white van.
</P>
<P>
   After court, she had one more errand _ one that she admitted she
had postponed for too long. She headed for the Willimantic police
station, to check the list of sex offenders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
