<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6613 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SOLICH-HNS &LR;      08-27 1454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SOLICH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After nearly 20 years preparing for the job, Frank Solich
believed himself ready to shake a few hands and talk Nebraska
football. Few know all things Cornhuskers better. And the joy from
the latest championship is still fresh.
</P>
<P>
   These were his people, fans with deep-enough roots to have known
him as Bob Devaney's first recruit, as an All-Big Eight fullback,
as Tom Osborne's right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Though his celebrity has rocketed since Osborne let college
football in on his and Solich's secret _ announcing last December
that Osborne would step down and Solich up as Nebraska's head coach
_ folks in Nebraska have recognized and appreciated Solich for
years.
</P>
<P>
   No one else could have made more sense to step into Osborne's
shoes. If Osborne failed to mention his choice that afternoon, most
of Nebraska would have assumed it and been ready to slap Solich's
back.
</P>
<P>
   But as head coach, when Solich added the usual circuit of alumni
functions and fund-raisers to his life, he noticed a small
distinction that as an assistant had escaped him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were very supportive,'' he said. ``They said, `You're
going to be great, coach. Everything is going to be great.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But I noticed, at other places they ask you how the team is
going to do. At Nebraska, they tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   At Nebraska, they order the championship as if super-sizing at
the drive-through window.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line loses everybody but one part-time starter,
replacing the All-Americans with sophomores. And it is assumed the
Cornhuskers will maul anything in their path.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers replace a quarterback with a sophomore wingback
and lose one tailback to the NFL and another to a knee injury. They
send their most destructive defenders to the NFL with few
game-breakers stepping in. And they remain a top-five team expected
to contend for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   And Solich, considering all the changes that could keep him
awake at night now that Osborne teaches classes and only
occasionally pokes his head in the football offices to say hello,
knows no one wants to hear the details.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what the expectations are,'' he said. ``Some people may
have 8-3 expectations. I haven't run into any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska has gone 60-3 in the past five seasons, winning three
national championships (it came within a missed field goal of a
fourth in five years). If it falls off its pace, the fingers will
point first to the coach replacing a legend, rather than a team
replacing its best players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be a new coach to be a little nervous,'' he
said. ``We don't have our offensive line returning, our quarterback
returning, our I-back returning. We have a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a short time to get there. Nebraska opens Saturday
against Louisiana Tech. DeAngelo Evans, the tailback heir to Ahman
Green, won't play for two or three weeks after undergoing
arthroscopic knee surgery. Starting safety Clint Finley is also
out. Bobby Newcombe will make his first start at quarterback behind
an offensive line that has struggled in every summer scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   But no change brings the attention that is paid to Solich's role
as Osborne's successor. When Saturday's game begins, Solich will be
Nebraska's third coach since 1962, stepping in where Devaney and
Osborne produced 29 consecutive nine-win seasons, 275 weeks ranked
in the polls, 87 consecutive weeks in the top 10 and five national
championships.
</P>
<P>
   And the history of coaches succeeding legends is far from
glorious. Otherwise-successful coaches have failed to live up to
the standards left them, from Gene Bartow following John Wooden at
UCLA to Ray Perkins stepping into Bear Bryant's shadow at Alabama.
Even Osborne struggled to live up to Devaney and was for a time
decried as second-rate when Oklahoma consistently beat the
Cornhuskers for Big Eight supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   But Osborne was given patience that seems as dated as a rotary
telephone. And as great as Osborne's burden was following Devaney,
Solich arrives with three still-fresh national-championship
trophies to remind what is possible, and expected, in Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of taking it day by day,'' he said of that burden.
``If you look too far down the road, it can be worrisome to you. To
look back to what coach Osborne did and coach Devaney, that can be
awesome. If you look day to day, you can handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has focused on the half-full part of his coaching life.
Though Osborne left him a standard that could be impossible to
match, he also left a program that needs no repairs.
</P>
<P>
   There are changes in personnel that could make the unthinkable
8-3 possible, though remote. But Solich made no changes to the
playbook, style or staff. He often sounds like Osborne, hits on the
same themes. As Osborne had as head coach, Solich will serve as his
own offensive coordinator. He similarly will call the offensive
plays and retain his mentor's devotion to the option.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not out to make my own mark,'' he said. ``I do not have
to separate myself from him. I'm not looking at number of wins or
percentage.''
</P>
<P>
   Said senior fullback Joel Makovicka: ``The transition has been
so smooth between coach Osborne and coach Solich. The team accepted
it and went out and worked hard. It hasn't affected us as much as
everybody might think.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to change style from coach to coach. We have
the same style of coach, the same philosophy, the same type of
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever burden Solich might carry might not be quite as
difficult as the load Osborne dropped before last season. Osborne
had shared his retirement plans with only the smallest circle of
confidants. Solich knew he would inherit the most dominant program
of the time but also knew that before his mentor would step down he
had to help provide a fitting send-off.
</P>
<P>
   And all the while, even as friends and media asked about the day
he might become the Nebraska head coach, he had to keep that vow of
silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had mentioned to me sometime prior to that he would forward
my name when he decided to retire,'' Solich said. ``He was going
strong and never showed signs he would retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Osborne is not one for a lot of flair. This was very
casually done. He knocked on the door and stepped in my office. He
asked if I had a moment. I had a lot of moments when coach showed
up. He said that was going to be it. The only question he had was
when to make the announcement. We discussed that a little bit. I
bet the whole thing didn't take 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said to myself, `This is it.' The thought of running
the program hit me immediately. The responsibility of running the
program hit me. Coach asked me not to mention it to anyone. I knew
how things can spread even if you mention it to a small group. I
mentioned it to my wife and crossed my fingers there. We talked it
through and decided neither one of us would mention it to anyone
else. It was a very exciting moment, but I didn't have anyone to
celebrate it with, so I just sat there.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Osborne rarely asks the Nebraska head coach if he
has a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I see him and have to ask him to come in the
meeting room,'' Solich said.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne has said he will not attend Saturday's game, to avoid
removing attention from the team and his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Solich said he wouldn't have minded had Osborne decided to come
by, certain that he cannot escape that shadow regardless of where
his mentor will spend his Saturdays. And he intends to remain too
busy to worry. As much as his added public responsibilities have
increased, Solich pledged to follow Osborne's lead and still take
on as much hands-on coaching as he can stand, from endless film
study to preparing his game plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life's changed a great deal,'' Solich said. ``I did do many
more interviews. The media attention is much, much greater. Some of
that comes from the program itself. With Tom stepping down, that's
attracted more, and a new coach running the Nebraska program
attracted more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me if you're not careful, that can really dominate
your time. I still want to be a football coach. Not all coaches
want to be football coaches, to be in the offensive and defensive
meetings and call their own plays. If you're not careful, you can
get separated from that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changed a great deal. But there's been no surprises. I
had an idea how it would be being under Tom for 19 years.''
</P>
<P>
   And that would seem the best preparation for the job and the
burden that comes with it. At least that's what the Nebraska
prophets keep reminding him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
