u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-WAKEFOREST-COX     08-27 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WAKEFOREST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deacs sense light at end of tunnel
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. _ Until this year, a phrase containing Wake
Forest and winning football could have been considered an oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   But things seem to be changing for the ACC's perennial doormat.
</P>
<P>
   The Deacons finished last season 5-6, but four of their losses
came in games in which they were leading at halftime. They were, at
least, competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, we could have been 8-3 last year,'' said tight
end Joe Zelenka, who at 6-5, 275, is the lightweight on what is the
league's biggest offensive line. Across the front, Wake goes 310,
310, 301, 328 and 305.
</P>
<P>
   The Deacons also sport one of the best passing combos in the ACC
in senior quarterback Brian Kuklich and wideout Desmond Clark. In
fact, Clark needs 37 receptions to become the conference's all-time
leading receiver; he caught 72 last year.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Clark also is one of the largest split ends in
captivity (6-3, 252) gives him an incredible advantage over
cornerbacks. In '97, Kuklich passed for 2,130 yards in just nine
games, while Clark's 72 catches went for 950 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough around here my first year because we went 1-10,
and although we were just 3-8 my second year, I began to sense
something, I began having the same vision as coach (Jim)
Caldwell,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell's vision seemed to dim with all the losing in his first
five seasons. The 14-41 won-lost mark is the worst in the
conference But Caldwell's persistence seems on the threshold of
paying off. Maybe nothing reflected it more than Sports Illustrated
magazine picking the Deacons as the No. 22 team in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My expectations are higher than that,'' Caldwell said.
````They have always been higher. But we have not reached the
pinnacle by any stretch of the imagination. The proof is in the
pudding, and we still have got to get out there and play.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Caldwell's goals for this season was to shore up what was
an anemic running game in '97 when Wake finished with the
12th-worst rushing attack in the country. ``We'll be better running
the football,'' he predicted, ``but we're not a running football
team. We're a passing team, but a lot of our passes are short,
controlled passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior tailback Morgan Kane has gained 935 yards his first two
years, and with senior Wande Shaw leading the blocking at fullback
behind their mammoth line, Caldwell should be able to order up more
running plays.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, look for Wake to be as good at stopping the run as
it was last season, when the Deacs allowed only 96.1 yards per
game, the 10th best mark in the land. Eight defensive starters come
back to furnish the needed experience. Linebackers Kelvin Moses and
Dustin Lyman are excellent, and the Wake secondary is stable and
quick with Dameon Daniel, DaLawn Parrish and Jeffrey Muyres
returning as starters. Muyres is the brother of Tech wideout Jon
Muyres.
</P>
<P>
   The Deacons' schedule also might help. With games against Air
Force, Navy, Clemson, Appalachian State, Duke and Maryland through
Oct. 17, Wake conceivably could be 6-0 when it plays North Carolina
on Oct. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Wake has not had a winning season since 1992, and, while this
team is better than any other during Caldwell's regime, it still
has to show it on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
