<HEADER>
A6601 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-SFCHRON &LR;      08-27 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Intel's Dream Factory   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
 Hillsboro, Ore.  
 
The research labs at Intel's Oregon headquarters look a lot like
the rest of Intel: long stretches of bland gray cubicles set neatly
atop acres of bland gray carpeting.
<TEXT>
<P>
   All that boring grayness disguises the cutting-edge computing
taking place in these cubicles. Here in the Intel Architecture
Labs, industry standards are born and shaped, video-conferencing
inches closer to becoming an everyday reality and an ambitious
effort is under way to turn the average home into a wired,
thinking, acting computer.
</P>
<P>
   The Intel Architecture Labs, which are content to operate
quietly in the background, vaulted into the news this week when a
report surfaced that research conducted there apparently upset
Microsoft a few years ago _ enough that Microsoft's reportedly
angry rebuke to Intel now is part of the government's antitrust
case against the Redmond, Wash., software giant. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The 450-person lab represents Intel's effort to push computing
forward _ which, though it sounds noble on the surface, is really
about driving demands for more and more of the microprocessors
Intel makes.
</P>
<P>
   Because Intel controls more than 85 percent of the market for
microprocessors _ the brains that run a personal computer _ the
company can't grow by stealing market share from its competitors.
Therefore, the labs' mission is to grow the market by creating new
reasons for people to want PCs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``Intel takes a pretty broad view of the market and
understands their continued success depends on market growth, and
market growth depends on new applications,'' said Nathan Brookwood,
a chip analyst with Dataquest in San Jose. ``It's not leaving
things to chance.''
</P>
<P>
   As things stand, most people don't need an ultrapowerful Intel
chip. People use their PCs for word processing, for crunching
spreadsheets and for surfing the Internet. Most of those functions
can be handled just fine on the chips available in today's
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of the world doesn't have the sense of urgency that
Intel has to buy better PCs,'' said Craig Kinnie, an Intel vice
president and the director of the labs. ``We want people to do
video-conferencing as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In the words of Mike Feibus, principal analyst with Mercury
Research, a market research firm in Scottsdale, Ariz., the question
for the Intel researchers is: ``How will they return us to the days
of the $2,500 PCs?''
</P>
<P>
   About the most futuristic research in the works at Intel's
Oregon facilities is what the company calls the ``Anywhere in the
Home'' initiative, which is looking at ways to wire the house. Even
the wildest components of that program are only about five years
from implementation, said Ed Arrington, the initiative's manager.
</P>
<P>
   In a video that Intel produced to show where things may be
headed, a man tells a panel by his bed, ``Put the house to sleep,''
and doors lock, lights shut off and alarms arm themselves. When the
man's young son breaks a glass during a midnight kitchen raid, mom
sees him on a bedside monitor and tells him to clean it up.
</P>
<P>
   When the man shaves in the morning, sports highlights pop up on
a screen in his bathroom mirror. Mom leaves video messages for the
kids in a refrigerator monitor. When their daughter wants to bake a
birthday cake for grandma, she touches hypertext recipes on a
tabletop panel; when she picks one, the oven turns itself on.
</P>
<P>
   When the little brother spills the batter on the monitor, the
kids only have to run it under the faucet to clean it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that's preventing this is the expense of displays,''
said Arrington. ``So we said, `What would you do in the home
environment if displays were really cheap? You could make the whole
front of the fridge a display design. ... And how practical does it
have to be at home? Can you run it under water and wash it off?'
</P>
<P>
   ``We need things convenient,'' Arrington said. ``We don't want
to change our lifestyles to match the technology. We want to change
the technology to match our lifestyles.''
</P>
<P>
   The ideas don't necessarily start with computer engineers
crunching code and playing with wires. Intel employs a team of
psychologists who study how people lead ordinary lives. They then
brainstorm how computers may be put to use in daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are an anomaly for Intel,'' said Chris Riley, a
psychologist at the lab. ``We are not technologists. We are social
scientists. We study end-user environments _ not computer use, not
technology use, but the way people work and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley, 49, wears jeans and Birkenstocks in the labs' casual
environment. Six of eight people in her group have doctorates;
after earning her Ph.D. at Princeton University, Riley spent 18
years working at Bell Labs in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   She believes that she and her colleagues bring a critical
element to the company. She says they're helping Intel think
``outside the box,'' and while that's become a common cliche among
management consultants, Riley notes that at the company famous for
the slogan ``Intel Inside,'' she means the phrase quite literally.
</P>
<P>
   Riley likens her work to Margaret Mead ``going out and living
with the natives.'' In this case, however, she doesn't have years
to research and report back. ``Intel's not patient enough to send
someone out for two years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she and her colleagues watch children at playgrounds or
interview people in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   That's where ideas like the wired refrigerator originate. ``This
is the information center of the home, not the PC, which is off in
the den,'' Riley said. ``Where do people congregate, do
calendaring, messaging? It's all in the kitchen, and it doesn't
work very well. So we say, `Aha! Computing can work with this real
well.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The engineers sometimes are skeptical of the ethnographers'
work, but often, they can relate. ``Young engineers here say,
`Yeah, when I'm home, that's me,' '' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers work not only with the psychologists, but also
with other companies that ultimately might use Intel's chips.
</P>
<P>
   Mehdi Attaran, 36, a technical marketing engineer, collaborates
with broadcasters and broadcast equipment-makers on creating ways
to bring the PC and the TV set closer together. Attaran works in an
area called ``The Grove,'' a section of cubicles where the
fabricated walls have been removed and banks of televisions,
recorders and other electronic devices are installed in their
place.
</P>
<P>
   The Grove took its name from the tall potted plants that once
decorated the area.
</P>
<P>
   The plants are gone, and it's probably not too outlandish to
think that The Grove should refer to Andy Grove, the Intel chairman
who established the labs in 1991 to respond to ``a vacuum of
leadership in the PC industry,'' according to lab director Kinnie.
</P>
<P>
   The labs were set up in Oregon because most of the engineers
doing related work already were there, said Kinnie, 51, a 23-year
veteran of the company who was tapped to head the project. The labs
are named for the chip architecture that Intel pioneered and still
controls (More information about the labs is on the World Wide Web
at &LR;  developer.intel.com/ial &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Intel anticipates spending $2.8 billion this year on research
and development. Most of that money will go into chip design; Intel
wouldn't release the specific amount spent on the Oregon lab.
</P>
<P>
   Intel built its labs on a different premise than the more-famous
industrial R&AMP;D centers, such as Bell Labs or Xerox PARC in Palo
Alto. While those facilities hired top-notch scientists and gave
them free rein, Intel _ following an industry trend _ has more of a
focus on developing products it can use in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not done until there are products out there,'' Kinnie
said. ``It was frustrating in the early years to get engineers to
think that way. They like to play with technology and then move on
to something else. ... I'm doing what's practical and pragmatic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
