<HEADER>
A6623 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      08-27 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
FOR a starting pitcher, the number is 20 _ as in wins. Closers
shoot for 40 saves. Hitters have their sights set on a .300
average.
<TEXT>
<P>
   None of those individual accomplishments may be as significant
as the number the Astros have to shoot for over the final 28 games,
beginning tonight against the Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice. It's round. And it's reachable for the Astros, who
need 17 more victories to join an elite group of teams that have
won 100 or more games in a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hundred wins pretty much says you've got a team that
deserves a special place in the history of this game,'' general
manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``It's something that doesn't happen
very often. It's a plateau that distinguishes that particular team
as one of the better teams throughout the history of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a great goal to shoot for, and I think this club
has that type of ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering 1998, only 75 teams teams had won 100 games in season
since 1901. Only 12 have done it since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are on pace to finish with exactly 100 wins while the
Yankees, Braves and Padres are on pace to surpass the 100-victory
plateau.
</P>
<P>
   If all keep up the pace, it would mark the first time in
major-league history four teams have won at least 100 games. The
Royals (102), Phillies (101) and Yankees (100) hit the century mark
in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be great,'' Astros left fielder Moises Alou said of
winning 100 games. ``I think we can do it, and I think we're going
to do it. If things keep going the way they're going and if
everyone stays healthy, I think we're going to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got to this team, I never thought we'd win 100
games. What's happening to this team right now is it's just a great
team getting better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, it takes awhile for a team to get used to each
other. Now, we know how to play together.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou is familiar with what it takes to put together a special
season after spending 1997 with the World Series champion Florida
Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the Astros compare to that team, which won 97 games
and entered the postseason as a wild card, Alou said: ``I think
we're just as good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who won the National League Central last season
before being swept in the first round of the playoffs by the
Braves, are just one victory shy of their 1997 total with a month
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker's offseason mission was to make improvements that
would help the Astros reach the next level. On that score, so far,
so good.
</P>
<P>
   Adding Alou and center fielder Carl Everett to the lineup has
given the Astros more offensive weapons than they have ever had.
Acquiring Randy Johnson _ who will start against the Pirates
tonight _ provides a bona fide staff ace, someone who can anchor
the playoff rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one big difference this year is that we're not as
dependent on one or two guys offensively,'' Hunsicker said.
``Because of that, our percentage has gone way up as far as hitting
in the clutch. Last year, we were not a very good team in one-run
games or in terms of coming from behind or scoring runners from
third base with less than two out.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of those are key areas that are critical in putting
together a championship-caliber team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very mediocre in that area last year. This year has
been a different story. We're not dependent on the same people
every day. We have the kind of lineup where if you're an opposing
pitcher, you can't take anything for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are hitting .293 with runners in scoring position
this season compared to .258 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   They have 38 come-from-behind victories, 22 in their last
at-bat. They are 24-15 in one-run games, a major improvement over
last season when they were 19-25 _ second-worst in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always set your goals higher than the year before,''
Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Astros reach 100 wins, they will break the club record
for victories (96 in 1986) and open the debate as to whether this
is the best team in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker has been part of the organization almost
from its inception, making him as qualified as anyone to make that
assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time will tell,'' he said. ``I think we've had better pitching
(in other seasons), but I don't think we've ever had a better
combination of hitting, fielding and baserunning speed. Right now,
that (100 wins) is a possibility, but I don't consider it a goal.
If we get closer to it, I will consider it a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to beat the record of the 1986 team, and 100 would
put the icing on it. To win 100 games takes a lot of consistency.
You have to have a few winning streaks, and you can't afford to
have any losing streaks. I don't think it's as satisfying if you
don't win in the postseason, but I still think it's an
accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' longest losing streak is four games. They have had
winning streaks of eight, seven and five (twice).
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we want to do is win our division,'' first
baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``Secondly, we have a chance to have the
first- or second-best record (in the NL), and if we can do that,
that's obviously going to be beneficial to us because we'll get to
play two home playoff games in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see that more than I'd like to see us win 100
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it would be nice to win 100 games because people
would be saying we're a great team. But we already know we're a
great team in the history of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it takes 100 games to get into first or second place,
that's great. But that's not our first goal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
