<HEADLINE>
YOUTH MARCH ORGANIZER TAUNTS GIULIANI 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Muhammad is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One day after a judge ruled that the rally called the
Million Youth March could proceed next weekend in Harlem, the chief
organizer attacked New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for trying to
block the event, calling him ``an ordinary cracker'' who ``chose to
ignore the law.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Thursday before reporters and about 20 supporters,
organizer Khalid Abdul Muhammad said he wanted young black people
who attended to be courteous and respectful. He said that above
all, the march would be a show of ``love and unity among black
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But Muhammad took every opportunity during his 30-minute speech
to bait Giuliani, who has condemned him for making numerous
anti-Semitic and anti-white remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no need to be afraid of Rudy Giuliani any longer,''
Muhammad said, speaking at Sylvia's restaurant in Harlem. ``This
cracker knows the law, but he chose to ignore the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was uncharacteristically silent after the speech,
refusing to discuss it during an afternoon news conference at City
Hall. But the city pressed on in its battle to stop the march,
asking the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to overturn the
decision of Judge Lewis Kaplan of U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
A three-judge panel will hear arguments on Tuesday, said Florence
Hutner, an assistant corporation counsel for the city.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the city rejected Muhammad's request for a
permit to hold the march in Harlem, scheduled for Sept. 5, saying
the neighborhood could not safely accommodate the thousands
expected. The conflict has since become increasingly bitter, with
each side accusing the other of racism and the organizers finally
suing the city.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad and other organizers have billed the march _ actually a
stationary rally _ as an opportunity for black youth to unite and
hear speeches about issues that affect them, like police brutality,
racism, unemployment and drug abuse. They have invited young black
people from around the country, but they now say attendance will be
nowhere near the million people originally expected.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Thursday, Muhammad praised Kaplan for ruling that
the city's actions had violated the constitutional rights of the
organizers. But he went on to say that he did not believe in the
Constitution, and that it was not ``worth the paper it's printed
on.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He also criticized black politicians who have expressed
reservations about the event. Several, including state Sen. David
Paterson and U.S. Rep. Charles Rangel, have asked why organizers
did not consult Harlem residents before planning the event, and
whether it will be safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stand up, be strong again,'' Muhammad said, addressing black
elected officials who have criticized the march, none of whom
attended the speech. ``Stop flip-flopping on the side of the youth
one day, then against them the next.''
</P>
<P>
   Paterson issued a statement asking march organizers to avoid
making ``bigoted'' remarks and to focus instead on problems facing
black youth.
</P>
<P>
   But Muhammad shrugged off the request, saying he could not make
such a guarantee. ``How are we going to prepare our youth,'' he
said, ``if we don't tell our youth who are our oppressors?''
</P>
<P>
   In one of his attacks, Muhammad said Giuliani ``never would've
told Jewish youth in Crown Heights they couldn't march.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Giuliani would not respond to the speech, he did speak
out against the march earlier Thursday at a news conference in the
Bronx. ``For the life of me, I can't figure out why people would
voluntarily join a hate march,'' he said. ``The person running this
march has said the most hateful things that I have heard in this
city in maybe a couple of decades.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same conference, Police Commissioner Howard Safir said
the march would severely strain police resources, since it falls on
the busy Labor Day weekend. The West Indian Day Parade alone,
scheduled to take place in Brooklyn on Labor Day, will require the
supervision of at least 3,000 officers, he said. Safir said the
department had started planning for the march, but that he did not
yet know how many officers would be needed. Because many officers
are on vacation that weekend, it will be difficult to find enough
to cover two events, even though they are on different days, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
