<HEADLINE>
FTC SAYS MERCK-MEDCO DEAL CUT COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (bl)  
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission said Thursday that Merck &AMP; Co. had
reduced competition in the pharmaceuticals market for a time after
it bought Medco Containment Services, a managed-care drug sales
company, in 1993. Merck announced Wednesday that it had agreed to
antitrust safeguards requested by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC said the new agreement, which would replace the terms
Merck accepted three years ago in settling a civil suit in
California, would insure that Merck and Medco did not revert to
earlier practices. Government regulators said such practices had
threatened to undermine competition. The California settlement
expired earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new agreement, Medco must offer a wide range of
products by all drug makers, on lists selected by independent
committees of doctors and pharmacists. Merck must maintain a fire
wall denying it access to marketing information that Medco gathers
about competing products.
</P>
<P>
   Managed-care units like Medco and similar divisions of Eli Lilly
and SmithKline Beecham buy drugs at discount prices and push
doctors to prescribe them for members of health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Merck said the new agreement merely formalized policies that it
had followed since it bought Medco. A Merck spokesman said the only
change from the 1995 agreement was a provision that the selection
committees would ``give no preference to the products of Merck''
except on ``objective criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   William Baer, director of the FTC's Bureau of Competition, said
the new agreement committed Merck and Medco to maintain the
safeguards and barred any return to the favorable treatment that
the commission said Medco had given to Merck drugs on preferred
drug lists called formularies.
</P>
<P>
   Baer noted that Merck adopted the earlier safeguards in February
1995 in settling a civil suit brought by Bacon-Normandi Corp. on
behalf of pharmacies that objected to the Merck-Medco merger. The
three-year agreement ``was a little bit porous,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Medco spokesman Kevin Colgan said that only 38 of the 533
brand-name drugs on the preferred list had been made by Merck. Of
these, 40 were recommended for substitution as lower priced and as
effective or better than other products. He said only four such
drugs were made by Merck: Zocor, a cholesterol-lowering drug;
Prinivil and Prinzide for cardiovascular problems, and Timoptic XE
for glaucoma.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC's agreement binds Merck to provisions similar to those
accepted by Eli Lilly after it bought PCS Health Systems from
McKesson Corp. The Merck agreement would be for seven years after
formal approval by the FTC. SmithKline Beecham has a smaller market
share and is not considered a threat to competition, antitrust
experts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
