<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: TRAVEL CHANNEL AND CONDE NAST TRAVELER TEAM UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A leading travel magazine is joining forces with a
cable television network devoted to travel for cross-media and
cross-marketing ventures that will include a prime-time travelogue
series.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership is being formed between Conde Nast Traveler, the
monthly travel magazine published by the Conde Nast Publications
unit of Advance Publications in New York, and the Travel Channel,
the travel and tourism TV network now part of the Discovery
Networks unit of Discovery Communications Inc. in Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Marketers are being offered advertising packages by the new
teammates with print, television and Internet components.
</P>
<P>
   The combination is indicative of the growing eagerness among
media giants to link up and then entice advertisers to buy
increased amounts of time and space by promoting the benefits of _
yes, that dreaded word _ synergy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, Conde Nast Traveler and the Travel Channel are
competitors because both are in the business of getting
travel-related companies to be among their advertisers,'' said Jay
Feldman, who joined the Travel Channel as senior vice president and
general manager in January after Discovery acquired 70 percent of
the network from Paxson Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there was also a sense,'' he added, ``that there were
things we might accomplish together.''
</P>
<P>
   And there were already ties on the corporate level between the
magazine and the network. Advance is an owner of Discovery, along
with the Liberty Media Corp. unit of Tele-Communications Inc., Cox
Communications and Discovery chairman John Hendricks.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the first significant news at Conde Nast Traveler
since Thomas Florio returned there as vice president and publisher
in May after being moved out of his job as president of The New
Yorker. Florio served as publisher at Conde Nast Traveler from 1986
until 1993, when he left to join The New Yorker, which, like the
travel monthly, is owned by Advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting in front of more people interested in travel
with Discovery, a gold standard in cable,'' said Florio, who joined
Feldman to discuss the plans for the venture at a dinner at the
trendy Mercer Kitchen restaurant in downtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The rate base for Conde Nast Traveler, the circulation
guaranteed to advertisers, is 750,000. The Travel Channel is
available in 18.5 million American households with cable
television, Feldman said, ``which we expect to grow to 40 to 50
million sometime in the next three years based on my belief in how
good our distribution operation is.''
</P>
<P>
   That reference was to the present availability of Travel Channel
siblings: the Discovery Channel, 74 million households; the
Learning Channel, 65 million households, and Animal Planet, 41
million households.
</P>
<P>
   One result of the collaboration between Conde Nast Traveler and
the Travel Channel will be ``Conde Nast Traveler Presents Amazing
Destinations,'' the travelogue series, which is scheduled to begin
on the network Sept. 28. The hourlong series, to be shown at 10
p.m., Eastern and Pacific times, Monday through Friday, will be
hosted by Thomas Wallace, editor in chief of Conde Nast Traveler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on the cross-marketing packages'' that will
encourage marketers to advertise on the series as well as in Conde
Nast Traveler, Florio said. ``Last week, on the West Coast, as Tom
was filming his segments, we brought 30 advertisers to the set for
lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Another result of the venture will be a 60-minute special on the
Travel Channel based on the annual Conde Nast Traveler Readers'
Choice Awards. That program, to begin running Oct. 15, will promote
the November issue of Conde Nast Traveler, which will present the
11th annual winners of the awards. The awards, based on a poll of
40,000 of the magazine's readers, will also be featured for two
weeks on ``Travel Daily,'' a Travel Channel series.
</P>
<P>
   Among the advertisers that have so far agreed to become print,
television and online sponsors for the awards, Florio said, are:
Hilton Hotels Corp., the Lexus division of Toyota Motor Corp.,
Silversea Cruises, Visa U.S.A. and the tourism promotion
organizations of the British Virgin Islands, the Cayman Islands,
the Dominican Republic and Hong Kong. The combined value of
marketers' commitments is in seven figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the `endemic' advertisers, the travel advertisers,
have tried the Travel Channel,'' Florio said. ``We'll bring them
some nonendemic, new advertisers like Lexus.'' Feldman said he
hoped the special would become an annual event like the awards.
adding, ``This cross-media partnership is really the beginning of
more opportunities to more effectively serve clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio's ebullience at the dinner ran counter to widespread
perceptions that his step back to Conde Nast Traveler was a step
down after The New Yorker, where he wrestled with advertising and
profitability challenges under the fierce scrutiny of the national
media as well as the chattering classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so much fun being back at this magazine,'' he said
when asked about his mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elated would be an understatement,'' he added, also offering
the words ``liberated'' and ``set free.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Florio's appearance was proof of an assertion Feldman
made at dinner, that ``travel is the way to relieve stress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
