<SLUG> BC-NY-ATTORNEY-GENERAL-680-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS IN N.Y. ATTORNEY GENERAL RACE SEEK RECOGNITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ When the political season began, Republican state
Attorney General Dennis Vacco presented an enticing target for
Democrats. His poll ratings were lackluster, critics said he had
dismissed a corps of experienced lawyers in favor of
less-experienced ones with Republican ties, and he had been accused
of not being tough enough on tobacco companies and corporate
polluters.
</P>
<P>
   So it was no surprise that four Democrats immediately leapt into
the race for their party's nomination to unseat Vacco. But now, as
they enter the stretch toward the Sept. 15 primary, the Democrats
find themselves facing a huge obstacle: Few people are paying
attention to the race, and three of the four Democratic candidates
lack the money to mount the kind of aggressive advertising campaign
needed to get voters' attention.
</P>
<P>
   As Eliot Spitzer, one of the Democratic candidates, recently put
it while speaking to about 40 people at a candidates' forum at a
Queens synagogue: ``I've traveled more than 50,000 miles trying to
find a person who understands what the attorney general's office
does. It's amazing. I haven't found that person yet.''
</P>
<P>
   With three weeks to go before the primary, poll numbers indicate
that it could be won by any of the four candidates: Spitzer, a
lawyer in private practice; state Sen. Catherine Abate; former
Attorney General G. Oliver Koppell, or Evan Davis, who was counsel
to Gov. Mario Cuomo. This is apparently because many Democratic
voters do not seem to be paying enough attention to the race to
know who the candidates are, never mind which one they will choose,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sluggishness of the campaign, the stakes in the race
are considerable. The attorney general's office has a budget of
nearly $140 million and a staff of 450 lawyers who defend the state
from hundreds of lawsuits a year ranging from allegations against
government officials to accidents on state-owned properties. The
office is also charged with filing lawsuits on everything from
charities fraud and price fixing to abuses by health insurers.
</P>
<P>
   And yet as they travel around the state, the candidates find
themselves having to stir up interest among voters, and in some
cases even educate them about the office. The other night at the
forum in Queens, Koppell, who has a gentle but tightly wound
manner, was more than a bit pleased that people had bothered to
show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general's race gets virtually no attention,'' he
lamented to the crowd before giving his stump speech on his
accomplishments during his stint as attorney general. ``So we
really appreciate that you're here to listen to us.''
</P>
<P>
   But the seeming lack of interest has not slowed the candidates
down. Davis, the race's firebrand, has become a common sight on the
campaign trail. From his wheelchair (he was stricken with polio at
age 5), Davis rails, taking the same populist message to county
fairs, parades and nursing homes across the state: Politicians have
become too indebted to big donors, instead of to the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a candidate of the establishment,'' he said in a
recent interview. ``The process stinks and it needs to be fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ms. Abate, who has an earnest if sometimes aloof
manner, has given speech after speech before women's groups, gay
organizations, labor unions and other historically Democratic
organizations in an effort to stir up a strong primary turnout.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, most experts say the winner of the primary
will need one crucial thing to challenge Vacco: cash. The
Republican incumbent has already raised more than $3.1 million and
will probably receive more from the state Republican Party should
he need it.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco also has name recognition that the Democrats lack,
although a recent poll showed that more than 40 percent of voters
surveyed had no opinion of him. He has also shown a talent for
getting good publicity on a variety of consumer-related issues. He
may even benefit from the coattails of the popular Republican
governor, George Pataki.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Democratic candidate in the best position to run a
well-financed campaign is Spitzer, a wealthy Manhattan lawyer who
is an intense campaigner with a thundering voice. His campaign has
already raised $3.6 million, $3.1 million of it his own money. By
contrast, Koppell has raised slightly more than $1 million; Ms.
Abate, $713,000, and Davis, $531,000.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's campaign has already spent $2.6 million of his total,
much of it on television advertisements across the state that tout
his accomplishments as a prosecutor and his support for such
popular issues as cleaning up the Hudson River and mandatory AIDS
testing of rapists.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not clear whether Spitzer's advertising will give him
a significant edge. A recent poll by the John Zogby Group of New
Hartford, N.Y., showed that 57 percent of the voters surveyed said
they were still undecided, meaning that it is a wide-open race.
Spitzer had only a slight lead over his rivals, with 16 percent of
likely Democratic voters saying they supported him. Davis received
15 percent; Ms. Abate, 8 percent, and Koppell, 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's spending has emerged as a campaign issue, with his
Democratic rivals accusing him of using his wealth to buy the
election. They have been especially critical about the money he has
pumped into the campaigns of local Democratic leaders in the hopes
of getting their support in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer, 39, has called the accusations absurd, saying the money
is intended to finance a get-out-the-vote effort that will
eventually be needed to mount a serious challenge against
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud to spend my money in support of an ideology that I
believe in deeply,'' he said. ``I'm not beholden to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Spitzer's most vocal critics has been Davis, who has made
campaign finance reform the major theme of his campaign. Davis, who
was Cuomo's counsel from 1985 to 1991, is the only candidate who
has placed voluntary limits on his own fund-raising. He has refused
to take money from unions, corporations and political action
committees. And he has placed limits on the amount he will take
from individual donors _ $2,500 for the primary and $2,500 for the
general election, far less than the state limit of $13,000 for the
primary and $28,000 for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who is 54 and lives in Westchester County, says that he
has chosen to run such an unorthodox campaign so he will not to be
beholden to any interest group. But his campaign has suffered from
the lack of a get-out-the-vote organization and of a strong
fund-raising base.
</P>
<P>
   The other two candidates, for their part, have been stressing
their long records in government. Ms. Abate, who is 50 and lives in
Greenwich Village, has touted her ample experience running large
agencies, including as Commissioner for both the New York City
Probation Department and the New York City Department of
Correction.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, though, she has picked up critical support from
a number of influential unions, including District Council 37, the
largest municipal workers' union in the state, and the Public
Employees Federation, a statewide union of state employees. Her
prospects are also bolstered because her base is in Manhattan,
where primary voter turnout has been traditionally high.
</P>
<P>
   Koppell, who is 57 and lives in the Bronx, points to his 23
years in the Assembly and the year he served as attorney general.
His colleagues in the Legislature chose him to take over as
attorney general in 1993 after Robert Abrams resigned to run for
the U.S. Senate. Koppell ultimately lost the Democratic nomination
for attorney general in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   His message has consistently been that he would use the office
to focus on cracking down on consumer fraud, corporate polluters
and civil rights violations, just as he said he did when he held
the office.
</P>
<P>
   Koppell has picked up considerable support among his former
colleagues in the Assembly. But many political analysts question
the viability of his candidacy for one simple reason: He lost the
last time he tried to get the party's nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
