<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TV-SPORTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN WILL MARIS' RECORD FALL? FOX WOULD REALLY LIKE TO KNOW  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Predicting when Mark McGwire or Sammy Sosa could tie or pass
Roger Maris' home run record of 61 may be a job more suited for a
psychic friend than a TV executive. But on Monday and Tuesday, Ed
Goren, the co-executive producer of Fox Sports, huddled with
baseball executives to estimate when the network might pre-empt its
programming to show McGwire or Sosa swing for 61 or 62.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to be a part of history, everyone wants to say
he saw  &UR; the &LR;  home run,'' Goren said.
</P>
<P>
   But the scheduling is alive with dandy possibilities and no
certainties. ``It's awfully goofy,'' Goren added. ``McGwire went
two weeks without hitting a home run, then hit five or six in a few
days.''
</P>
<P>
   One or both batters could stop in their tracks. Or both sluggers
could hit singles _ there would be suspense but no payoff. But what
if each man is poised to hit No. 61 or 62 on the same day, in games
scheduled for the same time, like on Sept. 20 or 22? Answer: carry
each game simultaneously on Fox, with more of the country getting
the game with the player set to break the record.
</P>
<P>
   Goren offered another scenario: ``Say McGwire gets 60 on a
Thursday. We do the game Friday. Sosa is at 58 and hits two on
Friday. Then McGwire hits one. One guy's at 61, the other's at 60.
The variables keep you up at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Once committed, how long do you stick with the chase and
pre-empt prime time? Two nights? Three? Fox has a network to run
and new episodes to show.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would have happened if Hank Aaron didn't hit his 715th
when he did?'' Goren asked. ``How long would NBC have gone before
they said uncle?''
</P>
<P>
   How often can you set aside commercials sold for entertainment
programming and market baseball spots on the fly to carry potential
history?
</P>
<P>
   So, Goren, Paul Beeston, Major League Baseball's president, and
Leslie Sullivan, baseball's vice president of broadcasting, pored
over schedule printouts. They focused on dates starting Sept. 10,
puzzling over which days were more suitable for Fox than others
(its strong prime-time schedules on Sunday and Monday are nights
the network would not prefer) and who else has broadcast rights to
consider.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday nights on Fox may be preserved for Bart Simpson and the
agents Mulder and Scully, but a potentially crucial Sunday _ when
St. Louis plays Houston on Sept. 13 _ opened up when baseball
wrested three Sunday night games from ESPN because ESPN was going
to shift them to ESPN2 in favor of National Football League games.
The other former ESPN baseball games are on Sept. 6 and 20.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN will remain in the McGwire-Sosa fray. Its West Coast
doubleheader on Sept. 16 should feature the Cubs-Padres game from
San Diego. The only other West Coast game that night is Colorado at
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Fox would love to commandeer any games now scheduled to
be shown by the team's local telecasters. It is likely that if Fox
wants to step in, local stations like the Cubs' WGN or the
Cardinals' KPLR would still carry the game in their markets and Fox
would take it nationally. But WGN would certainly have to black out
its superstation signal across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Prime time doesn't present the only possibilities. Sosa and the
Cubs play six day games at Wrigley Field starting Sept. 10. One, on
Sept. 12, could be added to Fox's Saturday afternoon slate. The
others would require pre-empting children's programming on Fox
stations.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Goren said Fox will not do is follow one player if the
other has broken the record. ``This is already a stretch for a
network to commit to doing something like this,'' he said. ``The
magic number is 62. Once someone reaches it, in all fairness, we
have to back off.''
</P>
<P>
   But ... what if McGwire reaches 62 first, then Sosa ties and
passes him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't deal with that right now,'' Goren said.
</P>
<P>
   And what if Ken Griffey Jr. heats up? More possibilities. More
variables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's make it a trifecta,'' Goren said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
