<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-TRAVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORY GALLOP ADDS WEAPON FOR TRAVERS: FLEET STABLEMATE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Eight horses were entered Thursday for
Saturday's $750,000 Travers Stakes, including one unexpected rabbit
whose role was to wear down Coronado's Quest and set things up for
Victory Gallop.
</P>
<P>
   But while the 3-year-olds were maneuvering for position for
their ``summertime Kentucky Derby,'' another little drama was
unfolding at Saratoga when the marquee star of the steeplechase
world, 10-year-old Lonesome Glory, ran sixth in the New York Turf
Writers Cup in the 41st start of his distinguished career.
</P>
<P>
   The 129th Travers was shaping up as a major test in the rivalry
between Coronado's Quest and Victory Gallop, who ran 1-2 in the
Haskell Invitational at Monmouth Park last month and are battling
for the 3-year-old championship.
</P>
<P>
   Coronado's Quest, who skipped the Triple Crown but has won four
straight races, drew the No. 3 post and was quoted at 8-5 odds in
the early betting line. Victory Gallop, who ran second in the
Kentucky Derby, Preakness and Haskell and first in the Arkansas
Derby and Belmont Stakes, drew the No. 7 post, with his stablemate
Sheila's Flag just to his right on the outside, and was made the
fractional favorite at 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Victory Gallop wins the Travers, he should be the
3-year-old champion,'' said his trainer, Elliott Walden. ``He would
have raced in five Grade I's in a row, never finishing worse than
second. He would have won 4 of 7 starts. And he is still around.''
</P>
<P>
   But Walden was taking no chances. He came up with a surprise
horse to join Victory Gallop as an entry: Sheila's Flag, with the
strict purpose of guaranteeing what Walden called ``plenty of
pace.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference, many racing people believe, could be the
distance: Victory Gallop won the Belmont at a mile and a half,
Coronado's Quest has never won at the Travers distance of a mile
and a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Scotty Schulhofer, the trainer of Deputy Diamond, put it:
``Pace will definitely make this race. If they let Coronado's Quest
get out there and set his own pace, believe me, he'll get the mile
and a quarter. I'm just hoping somebody keeps him honest.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``somebody'' was the rabbit. But Walden, having set up his
strategy, immediately hedged. He said that it had not yet been
decided whether Sheila's Flag would run and that one factor might
be the weather.
</P>
<P>
   James Bond, who won the Travers two years ago with Will's Way
and lost it last year by a nose with Behrens, suggested that
Coronado's Quest was a great horse at a mile and an eighth, ``but
he has never been a mile and a quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' Bond said. ``the million-dollar question for him is, can
he get the distance? And Victory Gallop is a horse that's certainly
tough, but how much did the Triple Crown take out of him?''
</P>
<P>
   On the inner grass stage at Saratoga, meanwhile, the jumpers
played the main event Thursday. And the 5-year-old Hokan not only
repeated the success he scored on opening day but also set a track
record. He ran the two and three-eighths miles in 4 minutes 12
seconds, slicing one-fifth of a second off the mark set by Eskimo
Cove in 1995 and edging Romantic by a neck.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional low came when Lonesome Glory could not crank up
his famous finishing kick, which won him the Eclipse Award four
times for steeplechase racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very big disappointment,'' said Bruce Miller, who
trains Lonesome Glory for Kay Jeffords. ``He got off to a terrible
start and never really got into the race. I see no reason not to
bring him back for the Colonial Cup, but I want to see if he's
fine. If there is a problem, we will have plenty of time to fix
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
