<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATADORS NOW BRADY'S BUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cal State Northridge's quarterback of the future
just became the Matadors' quarterback of the here and now.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Brady, an 18-year-old redshirt freshman from San Diego,
will start CSUN's season opener at Boise State on Sept. 5, head
coach Ron Ponciano said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Brady beat out three others, including junior Josh Fiske, who
opened camp as the No.1 quarterback and is the only one who's
started a game at CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Josh had the experience, he was our No.1 quarterback
coming out of spring (camp),'' Ponciano said, ``but there has been
a swing in these last 15 practices. (Brady) has really taken a grip
of the offense.... He has showed a significant separation from the
other quarterbacks at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   That fact became apparent last Saturday, when Brady outplayed
quarterbacks Fiske, David Lins and Mitch Ryerson in the team's
first full-speed scrimmage. Brady posted far superior ratings in
everything from completion percentage to decision making. He
sustained that level this week to cement his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready,'' said Brady, who turns 19 next month. ``I've
always been ready. This is like a dream come true. This is my
chance. I'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiske, on the other hand, is reassessing his football future.
The backup to Aaron Flowers the past two seasons, and a starter for
three games in 1997, Fiske was upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of boggles my mind a little bit,'' he said. ``After
spring (camp), coach Ponce told me I was the guy and it would be
hard for anybody to beat me out in fall. I would have to really
mess up, which I feel I haven't really done.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they told me and what they're doing now is totally
opposite.... If it was still open after spring, they should have
said that instead of telling me what they did.... They just played
games with my mind, it seemed like.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiske admits he had a poor outing in the first scrimmage,
completing only 33 percent of his passes while Brady hit 83
percent. Fiske improved markedly in Wednesday's scrimmage but
apparently not enough to overtake Brady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I've been thinking the last couple days if I should
stick it out,'' Fiske said. ``I've been here for four years and
I've worked so hard to get to this point ... to become a starting
quarterback. Now that's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano said the decision was based on Brady's clearly superior
performances to date. But he also won't hesitate to change
quarterbacks if Brady struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence in every one of (the four quarterbacks),''
he said. ``Could Josh end up being the No.1 guy? Yeah but not right
now. He lost it to a guy that separated himself from the pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano said he's not concerned about going into the season
with a rookie quarterback. ``Obviously it doesn't make a difference
on the practice field, and that's the only thing we can rate off
of.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady, a former three-sport star at San Diego's Morse High,
succeeds Flowers, an All-American and the Matadors' all-time
leading passer. He inherits an offense that ranked No.1 in the
nation in passing yards last season.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-1, 185-pound Brady is a solid passer but is also the
Matadors' most mobile quarterback and will pose a double threat to
opposing defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to have to prepare for him. He's a weapon,''
CSUN safety Vito Clemente said. ``If he gets out of the pocket,
he's dangerous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
