<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-YOUTH-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW CONCERNS ABOUT THE HARLEM MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Fri., Aug. 28:
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge has ruled that organizers of a Million Youth
March can use the streets of Harlem on Sept. 5. The decision was
unwelcome to the Giuliani administration, but Judge Lewis Kaplan's
decision did appear to reduce the chances of a worrisome
confrontation between police and marchers determined to take to the
streets without a permit. However, there are other safety issues
that still must be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   The Million Youth project posed some sticky political, ethical
and legal issues for New York City. Spearheaded by Khalid Abdul
Muhammad, a freelance demagogue best known for his anti-Semitic
remarks, the project showed no signs of organization beyond a
glitzy web site. Given the fact that Muhammad and his minions said
they were going to attract one million or more young people, some
of them gang members, on the Labor Day weekend, one of the busiest
of the year, City Hall's offer of alternate sites at Randalls
Island or Van Cortlandt Park did not seem unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   When lawyers for Muhammad went to court, they reduced their
crowd estimates to about 175,000. That made it easier to argue that
the city would be violating their constitutional rights by banning
them from the streets. But the planning seemed as fuzzy as ever.
The march organizers have been claiming that famous rap artists
will entertain during the event. In theory, 20 sound trucks and
jumbo screens will broadcast their performances. But there is no
evidence that the screens or trucks exist. Recalling the fatal
stampede at a rap concert at City College a few years ago, state
Sen. David Paterson expressed concern that the same type of tragedy
could occur again.
</P>
<P>
   Paterson and other Harlem leaders who have denounced Muhammad
are nevertheless working hard on public safety issues. The city
must also use its diplomatic skills to insure safety, even if it is
operating under court order. Entertainers whose names have been
linked to the event without permission should tell their fans they
are not really planning to attend. Muhammad's haphazard planning
has put a heavy burden on everyone else to act responsibly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
