<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS KEEPS JETS ON THE MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The tinkering with the New York Jets won't stop with
their final preseason game Friday night. Coach Bill Parcells admits
he remains uncertain about who is starting at three positions.
</P>
<P>
   There are times when Parcells puts on a human face, when he
admits he is stumped or debates openly about what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Was he planning to put rookie Kevin Williams at free safety
against the Chicago Bears just to give him a look?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's a real chance for him,'' Parcells said. ``I don't
know what I've got there.''
</P>
<P>
   What he may have is an extremely quick player with good moves _
on the first day of rookie camp he displaced the highly visible
Scott Frost as a free safety of the future. Each was chosen in the
third round.
</P>
<P>
   Frost, a quarterback for Nebraska, was taken first and was then
converted to safety. But he quickly started practicing at strong
safety when Williams, a cornerback out of Oklahoma State, displayed
classic free-safety technique.
</P>
<P>
   So after having Raymond Austin start the first three preseason
games, Parcells doesn't even plan to use Austin, who has been a
disappointment this summer, against the Bears. Instead, Williams
will share time with last year's starter, Jerome Henderson. But
Williams will get the bulk of the work.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is such a talented athlete, that Parcells said, ``I may
have asked him to do too much.'' It was hard enough for Williams to
absorb the intricacies of football's ``center field'' at free
safety, but the Jets also used him to return a team-high seven
kickoffs, as well as to play on special teams. And there was also a
trial at cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Williams has more quickness but Austin has more size,''
Parcells said. ``Williams doesn't have a year's experience in the
league, so every time we put on a new opponent's film, he doesn't
have any idea what's going on. It's all new to him.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Austin, he was among the second-year players Parcells
admonished to step up to the next level on the first day of camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henderson will play some at free safety _ you know what you're
getting from him,'' Parcells said. ``Sometimes that's a little more
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to believe about a team that went 9-7, but eight
months later, with only a week to go before the Jets open their
season against the 49ers, there are different starters at 12
positions, including the punter and the place-kicker.
</P>
<P>
   This week's shifting could also include Lamont Burns at left
guard instead of Todd Burger, an off-season free-agent pickup from
the Bears. Burger admits he has not always pleased the coach, and
said he has been sent messages, such as not starting.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has confused many people in practice this week by
shifting Burger to right guard, and by moving the backup right
guard, Burns, to the left side.
</P>
<P>
   But Burger was a right guard in Chicago for more than a season,
and could be a valuable back-up to starter Matt O'Dwyer if Burns
can beat Burger on the left side. Parcells has been hoping for two
seasons that Burns could land that spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had an inconsistent camp,'' said Burns, who was a
fifth-round draft pick last year.
</P>
<P>
   The kicking game also continues to vex Parcells. He will give
Brett Conway, who was recently acquired from the Green Bay Packers,
all the kicks this week.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Parcells can decide between Conway and Hall next week,
before going to San Francisco. Parcells dreads having two
place-kickers start a game. In this scenario, Hall would be
employed for kickoffs (29 went for touchbacks a year ago), as well
as field-goal attempts from 50 or more yards.
</P>
<P>
   If Williams makes it, it will be a remarkable coup for the
scouting staff, directed by Dick Haley, as well as for the coaching
staff, because the Jets would have two rookies starting, neither a
high draft pick. Jason Fabini, a fourth-round pick out of
Cincinnati, starts at right tackle. Frost, meanwhile, could be a
year away from making any sort of impact in his new role of safety.
</P>
<P>
   And next week, when the season starts? Who knows. That is why
Parcells plans to employ most of his healthy starters for most of
the Bears' game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes playing the fourth preseason game, but you've got
to play it,'' said center Kevin Mawae. ``It looks like I'll be
playing in it a while. By playing a lot you get in a game mood _
because the next week you go right out there and it's the real
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He just doesn't know who will be on his left side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
