</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IRAQ-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ILLUSORY INSPECTIONS IN IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Fri., Aug. 28:
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Scott Ritter, a top U.S. inspector on the
U.N. team charged with penetrating Iraq's deadly weapons program,
is the latest and most dramatic warning that the Clinton
administration and the United Nations are abandoning a firm
approach toward President Saddam Hussein. Richard Butler, chairman
of the U.N. inspection team, and Mohammed el-Baradei, head of the
International Atomic Energy Agency, have previously warned that the
inspectors could no longer guarantee they had Iraq's weapons
programs adequately policed. Now Ritter charges that the
inspections designed to ferret out hidden weapons have become an
illusion.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has blocked aggressive inspections while it
tries to build a consensus for firm action in the U.N. Security
Council. But prolonged delay is dangerous, giving Iraq precious
time to build biological or chemical weapons without being
detected. Aggressive inspections must be resumed promptly, and if
additional military forces are needed in the gulf region to lend
credible support to the inspectors, they need to be provided.
</P>
<P>
   From 1991 to last year, Washington fought off other nations'
efforts to weaken the inspections. On several occasions when Iraq
balked, America's threats brought it into line again. Now Ritter
charges that U.S. officials sought to stop him and others from
carrying out sensitive missions and that Saddam has found a
``witting partner'' in the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   The administration argues that a drop in political support for
military intervention, both at home and abroad, has forced it to
explore diplomatic options and seek support on the Security Council
before considering the use of military threats and force.
Meanwhile, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has argued that
Saddam is still losing the struggle because the economic sanctions
on Iraq will remain.
</P>
<P>
   But sanctions are not an end in themselves, merely a means to
compel Saddam to cooperate. His willingness to live with sanctions
is a measure of the importance he places on acquiring weapons of
mass destruction. Sanctions and diplomacy cannot work unless backed
by the threat of force _ if necessary, by the United States alone.
</P>
<P>
   The administration must not let its diplomacy drift into
dangerous delay. Even a few more weeks free of inspections might
allow Saddam to revive construction of a biological, chemical or
nuclear weapon. As Washington contemplates an extended war against
terrorism, it cannot give in to a man who specializes in the
unthinkable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
