<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCH FINDS NO TRACE OF MISSING WIDOW
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., N.Y.)  (jw) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investigators probing the disappearance of a wealthy
82-year-old Manhattan woman searched a remote area of high weeds
and dense scrub in northern New Jersey on Thursday, but found no
trace of the woman, Irene Silverman, who vanished nearly eight
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have called her disappearance an apparently deadly con
game to acquire her town house.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on information provided by a Florida man who worked for
the mother and son who are the prime suspects in the case, police
officers with machetes and shovels spent the day and early evening
scouring a large tract just north of St. Peter's Cemetery and just
west of Highway 1-9, in Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   As commuter and freight trains rumbled through the isolated
area, dozens of New York and Jersey City officers moved through
shoulder-high weeds, hacking at scrub and overturning earth.
Shortly before 8 p.m., after 10 hours, the search was suspended
until Friday morning, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Since July 5, when Mrs. Silverman, a widow, disappeared from her
mansion at 20 E. 65th St., authorities have searched unsuccessfully
in parks and dumps, around airports, along highways and in the
Meadowlands of New Jersey, where the suspects were reported to have
spent part of that day.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects _ Sante Kimes, 63, and her son, Kenneth, 23, who
rented a room in Mrs. Silverman's mansion _ were arrested in
Manhattan on the evening of her disappearance on an unrelated Utah
warrant on a bad-check charge. At the time, they held a deed
transferring her home to them for $390,000, about 10 percent of its
value, as well as her identity cards and other financial papers.
</P>
<P>
   While investigators have found no forensic evidence linking the
Kimeses to Mrs. Silverman's disappearance, they have said they
believe she was killed as part of a scheme to swindle her out of
her town house. But the Kimeses have not been charged in her
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they have been held without bail on charges of passing
a bad check to bilk a Utah dealer out of a Lincoln Town Car and of
obtaining a credit card in the name of a Florida man and using it
for dining and shopping in New York. They are also suspects in the
slaying of a California man and the disappearance of a bank
examiner in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses, described by authorities as grifters and drifters,
have refused to speak to investigators, but their lawyers have
repeatedly denied the allegations against them and insisted that
there is no basis for suspecting them in Mrs. Silverman's
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, investigators found a possible witness in the case.
Police said the witness, Jose Antonio Alvarez, 24, of Belle Grande,
Fla., might have been with the Kimeses last spring when they used
bad checks to buy an $80,000 motor home. He also accompanied them
to New York in June, and was seen at Mrs. Silverman's mansion in
the days before she disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez, regarded as a witness and not a suspect, was taken to
New York on Wednesday and has been aiding detectives in the case;
his information, they said, led to Thursday's search.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
