<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-COMMISSIONER-GUILTY-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-MIAMI COMMISSIONER PLEADS GUILTY IN CONSPIRACY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A former Miami city commissioner, Humberto Hernandez,
pleaded guilty Thursday to a federal charge of conspiracy to commit
bank, wire and mail fraud, less than two weeks after a Florida
judge sentenced him to a year in prison for a misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had faced a 28-count indictment involving fraudulent
real estate transactions and the use of a Medicare fraud scheme to
increase his real estate holdings. Federal prosecutors said they
had agreed to drop all of the charges except one, and that they
would recommend that Hernandez serve four years in prison for the
conspiracy charge, which usually carries a maximum penalty of five
years. Sentencing is scheduled for Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humberto Hernandez, after much deliberation, concluded that it
was in his best interests and the best interests of his family to
put this matter to an end,'' Jose Quinon, a lawyer for Hernandez,
said at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez has been in federal custody since late May, when state
prosecutors charged him in an investigation of vote fraud in last
November's citywide elections. On Aug. 14, a jury acquitted him on
charges of obstructing justice and fabricating evidence, but
convicted him on a lesser count of being an accessory to covering
up evidence of fraud. Three days after he was convicted, Hernandez
was officially removed from the Miami City Commission by Gov.
Lawton Chiles.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the U.S. attorney's office said they would agree to
allow Hernandez to serve his federal and state sentences
concurrently. He was indicted along with seven other people, but
does not intend to serve as a witness for prosecutors, Quinon said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's guilty plea contrasted sharply with months of
defiance in which he denied any wrongdoing, and he said on
Spanish-language radio programs that he was a target because of his
Hispanic origins.
</P>
<P>
   Miami has acquired a dubious reputation in recent years as a
city where official corruption is the norm. Hernandez's case was
one of the most prominent in a series that in the last year has led
to charges against top city officials and politicians, including a
former city manager, a state senator and a director of the port
authority.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The state attorney's office for Miami-Dade County said recently
that in the last five years it had charged at least 270 public
employees with crimes that included falsification of records and
embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
   A state investigation into last November's voter fraud ended in
several arrests this year. In March, a civil suit filed by Miami's
current mayor, Joe Carollo, led to the removal of Xavier Suarez as
mayor only four weeks after he took office.
</P>
<P>
   A judge in that case determined that Suarez's election was
invalidated by hundreds of absentee votes fraudulently cast in his
favor. Most of those votes were from Hernandez's Little Havana
district.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
